[
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Introduction"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This work is a continuation of the \"Orlando Innamorato\" of Matteo\nMaria Boiardo, which was left unfinished upon the author's death\nin 1494.  It begins more or less at the point where Boiardo left\nit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This is a brief synopsis of Boiardo's work, omitting most of the\nnumerous digressions and incidental episodes associated with\nthese events:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To the court of King Charlemagne comes Angelica (daughter to the\nking of Cathay, or India and her brother Argalia.  Angelica is )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "the most beautiful woman any of the Peers have ever seen, and all\nwant her.  However, in order to take her as wife they must first\ndefeat Argalia in combat.  The two most stricken by her are\nOrlando and Ranaldo (\"Rinaldo\" in Rose)."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When Argalia falls to the heathen knight Ferrau, Angelica flees\n--- with Orlando and Ranaldo in hot pursuit.  Along the way, both\nAngelica and Ranaldo drink magic waters — Angelica is filled\nwith a burning love for Ranaldo, but Ranaldo is now indifferent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Eventually, Orlando and Ranaldo arrive at Angelica's castle.\nOthers also gather at Angelica's castle, including Agricane, King\nof Tartary; Sacripant, King of Circassia; Agramante, King of\nAfrica and Marfisa (\"Marphisa\" in Rose), an Asian warrior-Queen.\nExcept for Orlando and Ranaldo, all are heathen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile, France is threatened by heathen invaders.  Led by King\nGradasso of Sericana (whose principal reason for going to war is\nto obtain Orlando's sword, Durindana and King Rodomonte of )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Sarzia, a Holy War between Pagans and Christians ensues."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ranaldo leaves Angelica's castle, and Angelica and a very\nlove-sick (but very chaste and proper Orlando, set out for )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "France in search of him.  Again the same waters as before are\ndrunk from, but this time in reverse — Ranaldo now burns for\nAngelica, but Angelica is now indifferent.  Ranaldo and Orlando\nnow begin to fight over her, but King Charlemagne (fearing the\nconsequences if his two best knights kill each other in combat)\nintervenes and promises Angelica to whichever of the two fights\nthe best against the heathen; he leaves her in the care of Duke\nNamus.  Orlando and Ranaldo arrive in Paris just in time to\nrepulse an attack by Agramante."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Namus' camp is overrun by the heathen.  Angelica escapes, with\nRanaldo in pursuit.  Also in pursuit is Ferrau, who (because he\nhad defeated Argalia considers Angelica his.  It is at this )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "point that the poem breaks off."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While the Orlando-Ranaldo-Angelica triangle is going on, the\nstories of other knights and their loves are mixed in.  Most\nimportant of these is that of the female knight Bradamante\n(sister of Ranaldo), who falls in love with a very noble heathen\nknight named Ruggiero (\"Rogero\" in Rose).  Ruggiero, who is said\nto be a descendent of Alexander the Great and Hector, also falls\nin love with Bradamante, but because they are fighting on\nopposite sides it is felt that their love is hopeless.\nNevertheless, it is prophecised that they shall wed and found the\nfamous Este line, who shall rise to become one of the major\nfamilies of Medieval and Renaissance Italy (it is worth noting\nthat the Estes where the patrons of both Boiardo and Ariosto).\nOpposed to this prophecy is Atlantes, an African wizard who seeks\nto derail fate and keep Ruggiero from becoming a Christian.  By\nthe end of the poem, Ruggiero is imprisoned in Atlantes' castle.\nHowever, Bradamante (who has decided to follow her heart is in )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "pursuit of her love, and is not too far away.  It is the\nBradamante-Ruggiero story that eventually takes center stage in\nAriosto's work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Other characters of importance: Astolfo, a Peer and friend of\nOrlando, who is kidnaped by the evil witch Morgana and her sister\nAlcina; Mandricardo, a fierce but hot-headed heathen; and a young\nknight named Brandimarte, who falls in love with (and wins the\nheart of the beautiful Fiordelisa (\"Flordelice\" in Rose).  All )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "play major or semi-major roles in the events of Ariosto's poem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "——DBK"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 1"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Angelica, whom pressing danger frights,\nFlies in disorder through the greenwood shade.\nRinaldo's horse escapes: he, following, fights\nFerrau, the Spaniard, in a forest glade.\nA second oath the haughty paynim plights,\nAnd keeps it better than the first he made.\nKing Sacripant regains his long-lost treasure;\nBut good Rinaldo mars his promised pleasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "OF LOVES and LADIES, KNIGHTS and ARMS, I sing,\nOf COURTESIES, and many a DARING FEAT;\nAnd from those ancient days my story bring,\nWhen Moors from Afric passed in hostile fleet,\nAnd ravaged France, with Agramant their king,\nFlushed with his youthful rage and furious heat,\nWho on king Charles', the Roman emperor's head\nHad vowed due vengeance for Troyano dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the same strain of Roland will I tell\nThings unattempted yet in prose or rhyme,\nOn whom strange madness and rank fury fell,\nA man esteemed so wise in former time;\nIf she, who to like cruel pass has well\nNigh brought my feeble wit which fain would climb\nAnd hourly wastes my sense, concede me skill\nAnd strength my daring promise to fulfil."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Good seed of Hercules, give ear and deign,\nThou that this age's grace and splendour art,\nHippolitus, to smile upon his pain\nWho tenders what he has with humble heart.\nFor though all hope to quit the score were vain,\nMy pen and pages may pay the debt in part;\nThen, with no jealous eye my offering scan,\nNor scorn my gifts who give thee all I can."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And me, amid the worthiest shalt thou hear,\nWhom I with fitting praise prepare to grace,\nRecord the good Rogero, valiant peer,\nThe ancient root of thine illustrious race.\nOf him, if thou wilt lend a willing ear,\nThe worth and warlike feats I shall retrace;\nSo thou thy graver cares some little time\nPostponing, lend thy leisure to my rhyme."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Roland, who long the lady of Catay,\nAngelica, had loved, and with his brand\nRaised countless trophies to that damsel gay,\nIn India, Median, and Tartarian land,\nWestward with her had measured back his way;\nWhere, nigh the Pyrenees, with many a band\nOf Germany and France, King Charlemagne\nHad camped his faithful host upon the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To make King Agramant, for penance, smite\nHis cheek, and rash Marsilius rue the hour;\nThis, when all trained with lance and sword to fight,\nHe led from Africa to swell his power;\nThat other when he pushed, in fell despite,\nAgainst the realm of France Spain's martial flower.\n'Twas thus Orlando came where Charles was tented\nIn evil hour, and soon the deed repented."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For here was seized his dame of peerless charms,\n(How often human judgment wanders wide)!\nWhom in long warfare he had kept from harms,\nFrom western climes to eastern shores her guide\nIn his own land, 'mid friends and kindred arms,\nNow without contest severed from his side.\nFearing the mischief kindled by her eyes,\nFrom him the prudent emperor reft the prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For bold Orlando and his cousin, free\nRinaldo, late contended for the maid,\nEnamored of that beauty rare; since she\nAlike the glowing breast of either swayed.\nBut Charles, who little liked such rivalry,\nAnd drew an omen thence of feebler aid,\nTo abate the cause of quarrel, seized the fair,\nAnd placed her in Bavarian Namus' care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Vowing with her the warrior to content,\nWho in that conflict, on that fatal day,\nWith his good hand most gainful succour lent,\nAnd slew most paynims in the martial fray.\nBut counter to his hopes the battle went,\nAnd his thinned squadrons fled in disarray;\nNamus, with other Christian captains taken,\nAnd his pavilion in the rout forsaken."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There, lodged by Charles, that gentle bonnibel,\nOrdained to be the valiant victor's meed,\nBefore the event had sprung into her sell,\nAnd from the combat turned in time of need;\nPresaging wisely Fortune would rebel\nThat fatal day against the Christian creed:\nAnd, entering a thick wood, discovered near,\nIn a close path, a horseless cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With shield upon his arm, in knightly wise,\nBelted and mailed, his helmet on his head;\nThe knight more lightly through the forest hies\nThan half-clothed churl to win the cloth of red.\nBut not from cruel snake more swiftly flies\nThe timid shepherdess, with startled tread,\nThan poor Angelica the bridle turns\nWhen she the approaching knight on foot discerns."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was that Paladin, good Aymon's seed,\nWho Mount Albano had in his command;\nAnd late Baiardo lost, his gallant steed,\nEscaped by strange adventure from his hand.\nAs soon as seen, the maid who rode at speed\nThe warrior knew, and, while yet distant, scanned\nThe angelic features and the gentle air\nWhich long had held him fast in Cupid's snare."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The affrighted damsel turns her palfrey round,\nAnd shakes the floating bridle in the wind;\nNor in her panic seeks to choose her ground,\nNor open grove prefers to thicket blind.\nBut reckless, pale and trembling, and astound,\nLeaves to her horse the devious way to find.\nHe up and down the forest bore the dame,\nTill to a sylvan river's bank he came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here stood the fierce Ferrau in grisly plight,\nBegrimed with dust, and bathed with sweat and blood\nWho lately had withdrawn him from the fight,\nTo rest and drink at that refreshing flood:\nBut there had tarried in his own despite,\nSince bending from the bank, in hasty mood,\nHe dropped his helmet in the crystal tide,\nAnd vainly to regain the treasure tried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither at speed she drives, and evermore\nIn her wild panic utters fearful cries;\nAnd at the voice, upleaping on the shore,\nThe Saracen her lovely visage spies.\nAnd, pale as is her cheek, and troubled sore,\nArriving, quickly to the warrior's eyes\n(Though many days no news of her had shown)\nThe beautiful Angelica is known."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Courteous, and haply gifted with a breast\nAs warm as either of the cousins two;\nAs bold, as if his brows in steel were dressed,\nThe succour which she sought he lent, and drew\nHis faulchion, and against Rinaldo pressed,\nWho saw with little fear the champion true.\nNot only each to each was known by sight,\nBut each had proved in arms his foeman's might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus, as they are, on foot the warriors vie\nIn cruel strife, and blade to blade oppose;\nNo marvel plate or brittle mail should fly,\nWhen anvils had not stood the deafening blows.\nIt now behoves the palfrey swift to ply\nHis feet; for while the knights in combat close,\nHim vexed to utmost speed, with goading spurs,\nBy waste or wood the frighted damsel stirs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the two had struggled long to throw\nEach other in the strife, and vainly still;\nSince neither valiant warrior was below\nHis opposite in force and knightly skill:\nThe first to parley with his Spanish foe\nWas the good master of Albano's hill\n(As one within whose raging breast was pent\nA reckless fire which struggled for a vent)."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou think'st,\" he said, \"to injure me alone,\nBut know thou wilt thyself as much molest:\nFor if we fight because yon rising sun\nThis raging heat has kindled in thy breast.\nWhat were thy gain, and what the guerdon won,\nThough I should yield my life, or stoop my crest;\nIf she shall never be thy glorious meed,\nWho flies, while vainly we in battle bleed?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then how much better, since our stake's the same,\nThou, loving like myself, should'st mount and stay\nTo wait this battle's end, the lovely dame,\nBefore she fly yet further on her way.\nThe lady taken, we repeat our claim\nWith naked faulchion to that peerless prey:\nElse by long toil I see not what we gain\nBut simple loss and unrequited pain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The peer's proposal pleased the paynim well.\nAnd so their hot contention was foregone;\nAnd such fair truce replaced that discord fell,\nSo mutual wrongs forgot and mischief done;\nThat for departure seated in his sell,\nOn foot the Spaniard left not Aymon's son;\nBut him to mount his courser's crupper prayed;\nAnd both united chased the royal maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh! goodly truth in cavaliers of old!\nRivals they were, to different faith were bred.\nNot yet the weary warriors' wounds were cold —\nStill smarting from those strokes so fell and dread.\nYet they together ride by waste and wold,\nAnd, unsuspecting, devious dingle thread.\nThem, while four spurs infest his foaming sides,\nTheir courser brings to where the way divides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And now the warlike pair at fault, for they\nKnew not by which she might her palfrey goad,\n(Since both, without distinction, there survey\nThe recent print of hoofs on either road),\nCommit the chase to fortune.  By this way\nThe paynim pricked, by that Rinaldo strode.\nBut fierce Ferrau, bewildered in the wood,\nFound himself once again where late he stood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beside the water, where he stoop'd to drink,\nAnd dropt the knightly helmet, — to his cost,\nSunk in the stream; and since he could not think\nHer to retrieve, who late his hopes had crossed.\nHe, where the treasure fell, descends the brink\nOf that swift stream, and seeks the morion lost.\nBut the casque lies so bedded in the sands,\n'Twill ask no light endeavour at his hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A bough he severs from a neighbouring tree,\nAnd shreds and shapes the branch into a pole:\nWith this he sounds the stream, and anxiously\nFathoms, and rakes, and ransacks shelf and hole.\nWhile angered sore at heart, and restless, he\nSo lingered, where the troubled waters roll,\nBreast-high, from the mid river rose upright,\nThe apparition of an angry knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Armed at all points he was, except his head,\nAnd in his better hand a helmet bore:\nThe very casque, which in the river's bed\nFerrau sought vainly, toiling long and sore.\nUpon the Spanish knight he frowned, and said:\n\"Thou traitor to thy word, thou perjured Moor,\nWhy grieve the goodly helmet to resign,\nWhich, due to me long since, is justly mine?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Remember, pagan, when thine arm laid low\nThe brother of Angelica.  That knight\nAm I; — thy word was plighted then to throw\nAfter my other arms his helmet bright.\nIf Fortune now compel thee to forego\nThe prize, and do my will in thy despite,\nGrieve not at this, but rather grieve that thou\nArt found a perjured traitor to thy vow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if thou seek'st a helmet, be thy task\nTo win and wear it more to thy renown.\nA noble prize were good Orlando's casque;\nRinaldo's such, or yet a fairer crown;\nAlmontes', or Mambrino's iron masque:\nMake one of these, by force of arms, thine own.\nAnd this good helm will fitly be bestowed\nWhere (such thy promise it has long been owed.\" )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bristled the paynim's every hair at view\nOf that grim shade, uprising from the tide,\nAnd vanished was his fresh and healthful hue,\nWhile on his lips the half-formed accents died.\nNext hearing Argalia, whom he slew,\n(So was the warrior hight that stream beside, ) \n\nThus his unknightly breach of promise blame,\nHe burned all over, flushed with rage and shame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor having time his falsehood to excuse,\nAnd knowing well how true the phantom's lore,\nStood speechless; such remorse the words infuse.\nThen by Lanfusa's life the warrior swore,\nNever in fight, or foray would he use\nHelmet but that which good Orlando bore\nFrom Aspramont, where bold Almontes paid\nHis life a forfeit to the Christian blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this new vow discharged more faithfully\nThan the vain promise which was whilom plight;\nAnd from the stream departing heavily,\nWas many days sore vexed and grieved in sprite;\nAnd still intent to seek Orlando, he\nRoved wheresoe'er he hoped to find the knight.\nA different lot befel Rinaldo; who\nHad chanced another pathway to pursue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For far the warrior fared not, ere he spied,\nBounding across the path, his gallant steed,\nAnd, \"Stay, Bayardo mine,\" Rinaldo cried,\n\"Too cruel care the loss of thee does breed.\"\nThe horse for this returned not to his side,\nDeaf to his prayer, but flew with better speed.\nFurious, in chase of him, Rinaldo hies.\nBut follow we Angelica, who flies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through dreary woods and dark the damsel fled,\nBy rude unharboured heath and savage height,\nWhile every leaf or spray that rustled, bred\n(Of oak, or elm, or beech), such new affright,\nShe here and there her foaming palfrey sped\nBy strange and crooked paths with furious flight;\nAnd at each shadow, seen in valley blind,\nOr mountain, feared Rinaldo was behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As a young roe or fawn of fallow deer,\nWho, mid the shelter of its native glade,\nHas seen a hungry pard or tiger tear\nThe bosom of its bleeding dam, dismayed,\nBounds, through the forest green in ceaseless fear\nOf the destroying beast, from shade to shade,\nAnd at each sapling touched, amid its pangs,\nBelieves itself between the monster's fangs,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One day and night, and half the following day,\nThe damsel wanders wide, nor whither knows;\nThen enters a deep wood, whose branches play,\nMoved lightly by the freshening breeze which blows.\nThrough this two clear and murmuring rivers stray:\nUpon their banks a fresher herbage grows;\nWhile the twin streams their passage slowly clear,\nMake music with the stones, and please the ear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Weening removed the way by which she wends,\nA thousand miles from loathed Rinaldo's beat,\nTo rest herself a while the maid intends,\nWearied with that long flight and summer's heat.\nShe from her saddle 'mid spring flowers descends\nAnd takes the bridle from her courser fleet.\nAnd loose along the river lets him pass,\nRoving the banks in search of lusty grass."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Behold! at hand a thicket she surveys\nGay with the flowering thorn and vermeil rose:\nThe tuft reflected in the stream which strays\nBeside it, overshadowing oaks enclose.\nHollow within, and safe from vulgar gaze,\nIt seemed a place constructed for repose;\nWith bows so interwoven, that the light\nPierced not the tangled screen, far less the sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within soft moss and herbage form a bed;\nAnd to delay and rest the traveller woo.\n'Twas there her limbs the weary damsel spread,\nHer eye-balls bathed in slumber's balmy dew.\nBut little time had eased her drooping head,\nEre, as she weened, a courser's tramp she knew.\nSoftly she rises, and the river near,\nArmed cap-a-pie, beholds a cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If friend or foe, she nothing comprehends,\n(So hope and fear her doubting bosom tear)\nAnd that adventure's issue mute attends,\nNor even with a sigh disturbs the air.\nThe cavalier upon the bank descends;\nAnd sits so motionless, so lost in care,\n(His visage propt upon his arm to sight ) \n\nChanged into senseless stone appeared the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pensive, above an hour, with drooping head,\nHe rested mute, ere he began his moan;\nAnd then his piteous tale of sorrow said,\nLamenting in so soft and sweet a tone,\nHe in a tiger's breast had pity bred,\nOr with his mournful wailings rent a stone.\nAnd so he sighed and wept; like rivers flowed\nHis tears, his bosom like an Aetna glowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thought which now makes me burn, now freeze with hate,\nWhich gnaws my heart and rankles at its root!\nWhat's left to me,\" he said, \"arrived too late,\nWhile one more favoured bears away the fruit?\nBare words and looks scarce cheered my hopeless state,\nAnd the prime spoils reward another's suit.\nThen since for me nor fruit nor blossom hangs,\nWhy should I longer pine in hopeless pangs?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The virgin has her image in the rose\nSheltered in garden on its native stock,\nWhich there in solitude and safe repose,\nBlooms unapproached by sheperd or by flock.\nFor this earth teems, and freshening water flows,\nAnd breeze and dewy dawn their sweets unlock:\nWith such the wistful youth his bosom dresses.\nWith such the enamored damsel braids her tresses."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But wanton hands no sooner this displace\nFrom the maternal stem, where it was grown,\nThan all is withered; whatsoever grace\nIt found with man or heaven; bloom, beauty, gone.\nThe damsel who should hold in higher place\nThan light or life the flower which is her own,\nSuffering the spoiler's hand to crop the prize,\nForfeits her worth in every other's eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And be she cheap with all except the wight\nOn whom she did so large a boon bestow.\nAh! false and cruel Fortune! foul despite!\nWhile others triumph, I am drown'd in woe.\nAnd can it be that I such treasure slight?\nAnd can I then my very life forego?\nNo! let me die; 'twere happiness above\nA longer life, if I must cease to love.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If any ask who made this sorrowing,\nAnd pour'd into the stream so many tears,\nI answer, it was fair Circassia's king,\nThat Sacripant, oppressed with amorous cares.\nLove is the source from which his troubles spring,\nThe sole occasion of his pains and fears;\nAnd he to her a lover's service paid,\nNow well remembered by the royal maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He for her sake from Orient's farthest reign\nRoved thither, where the sun descends to rest;\nFor he was told in India, to his pain,\nThat she Orlando followed to the west.\nHe after learned in France that Charlemagne\nSecluded from that champion and the rest,\nAs a fit guerdon, mewed her for the knight\nWho should protect the lilies best in fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warrior in the field had been, and viewed,\nShort time before, king Charlemagne's disgrace;\nAnd vainly had Angelica pursued,\nNor of the damsel's footsteps found a trace.\nAnd this is what the weeping monarch rued,\nAnd this he so bewailed in doleful case:\nHence, into words his lamentations run,\nWhich might for pity stop the passing sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While Sacripant laments him in this plight,\nAnd makes a tepid fountain of his eyes;\nAnd, what I deem not needful to recite,\nPours forth yet other plaints and piteous cries;\nPropitious Fortune will his lady bright\nShould hear the youth lament him in such wise:\nAnd thus a moment compassed what, without\nSuch chance, long ages had not brought about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With deep attention, while the warrior weeps,\nShe marks the fashion of the grief and tears\nAnd words of him, whose passion never sleeps;\nNor this the first confession which she hears.\nBut with his plaint her heart no measure keeps,\nCold as the column which the builder rears.\nLike haughty maid, who holds herself above\nThe world, and deems none worthy of her love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But her from harm amid those woods to keep,\nThe damsel weened she might his guidance need;\nFor the poor drowning caitiff, who, chin-deep,\nImplores not help, is obstinate indeed.\nNor will she, if she let the occasion sleep,\nFind escort that will stand her in such stead:\nFor she that king by long experience knew\nAbove all other lovers, kind and true."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But not the more for this the maid intends\nTo heal the mischief which her charms had wrought,\nAnd for past ills to furnish glad amends\nIn that full bliss by pining lover sought.\nTo keep the king in play are all her ends,\nHis help by some device or fiction bought,\nAnd having to her purpose taxed his daring,\nTo reassume as wont her haughty bearing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "An apparition bright and unforeseen,\nShe stood like Venus or Diana fair,\nIn solemn pageant, issuing on the scene\nFrom out of shadowy wood or murky lair.\nAnd \"Peace be with you,\" cried the youthful queen,\n\"And God preserve my honour in his care,\nNor suffer that you blindly entertain\nOpinion of my fame so false and vain!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not with such wonderment a mother eyes,\nWith such excessive bliss the son she mourned\nAs dead, lamented still with tears and sighs,\nSince the thinned files without her boy returned.\n— Not such her rapture as the king's surprise\nAnd ecstasy of joy when he discerned\nThe lofty presence, cheeks of heavenly hue,\nAnd lovely form which broke upon his view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, full of fond and eager passion, pressed\nTowards his Lady, his Divinity;\nAnd she now clasped the warrior to her breast,\nWho in Catay had haply been less free.\nAnd now again the maid her thoughts addressed\nTowards her native land and empery:\nAnd feels, with hope revived, her bosom beat\nShortly to repossess her sumptuous seat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her chances all to him the damsel said,\nSince he was eastward sent to Sericane\nBy her to seek the martial monarch's aid,\nWho swayed the sceptre of that fair domain;\nAnd told how oft Orlando's friendly blade\nHad saved her from dishonour, death, and pain;\nAnd how she so preserved her virgin flower\nPure as it blossomed in her natal hour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Haply the tale was true; yet will not seem\nLikely to one of sober sense possessed:\nBut Sacripant, who waked from worser dream,\nIn all without a cavil acquiesced:\nSince love, who sees without one guiding gleam,\nSpies in broad day but that which likes him best:\nFor one sign of the afflicted man's disease\nIs to give ready faith to things which please."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If good Anglante's lord the prize forbore,\nNor seized the fair occasion when he might,\nThe loss be his, if Fortune never more\nHim to enjoy so fair a prize invite.\nTo imitate that lord of little lore\nI think not,\" said, apart, Circassa's knight.\n\"To quit such proffered good, and, to my shame,\nHave but myself on after-thought to blame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No!  I will pluck the fresh and morning rose,\nWhich, should I tarry, may be overblown.\nTo woman, (this my own experience shows),\nNo deed more sweet or welcome can be done.\nThen, whatsoever scorn the damsel shows,\nThough she awhile may weep and make her moan,\nI will, unchecked by anger, false or true,\nOr sharp repulse, my bold design pursue.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This said, he for the soft assault prepares,\nWhen a loud noise within the greenwood shade\nBeside him, rang in his astounded ears,\nAnd sore against his will the monarch stayed.\nHe donned his helm (his other arms he wears),\nAye wont to rove in steel, with belted blade,\nReplaced the bridle on his courser fleet,\nGrappled his lance, and sprang into his seat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With the bold semblance of a valiant knight,\nBehold a warrior threads the forest hoar.\nThe stranger's mantle was of snowy white,\nAnd white alike the waving plume he wore.\nBalked of his bliss, and full of fell despite,\nThe monarch ill the interruption bore,\nAnd spurred his horse to meet him in mid space,\nWith hate and fury glowing in his face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him he defies to fight, approaching nigh,\nAnd weens to make him stoop his haughty crest:\nThe other knight, whose worth I rate as high,\nHis warlike prowess puts to present test;\nCuts short his haughty threats and angry cry,\nAnd spurs, and lays his levelled lance in rest.\nIn tempest wheels Circassia's valiant peer,\nAnd at his foeman's head each aims his spear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not brindled bulls or tawny lions spring\nTo forest warfare with such deadly will\nAs those two knights, the stranger and the king.\nTheir spears alike the opposing bucklers thrill:\nThe solid ground, at their encountering,\nTrembles from fruitful vale to naked hill:\nAnd well it was the mail in which they dressed\nTheir bodies was of proof, and saved the breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor swerved the chargers from their destined course;\nWho met like rams, and butted head to head.\nThe warlike Saracen's ill-fated horse,\nWell valued while alive, dropt short and dead:\nThe stranger's, too, fell senseless; but perforce\nWas roused by rowel from his grassy bed.\nThat of the paynim king, extended straight,\nLay on his battered lord with all his weight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upright upon his steed, the knight unknown,\nWho at the encounter horse and rider threw,\nDeeming enough was in the conflict done,\nCares not the worthless warfare to renew;\nBut endlong by the readiest path is gone,\nAnd measures, pricking frith and forest through,\nA mile, or little less, in furious heat,\nEre the foiled Saracen regains his feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the bewildered and astonished clown\nWho held the plough (the thunder storm o'erpast)\nThere, where the deafening bolt had beat him down,\nNigh his death-stricken cattle, wakes aghast,\nAnd sees the distant pine without its crown,\nWhich he saw clad in leafy honours last;\nSo rose the paynim knight with troubled face,\nThe maid spectatress of the cruel case."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He sighs and groans, yet not for mischief sore\nEndured in wounded arm or foot which bled;\nBut for mere shame, and never such before\nOr after, dyed his cheek so deep a red,\nAnd if he rued his fall, it grieved him more\nHis dame should lift him from his courser dead.\nHe speechless had remained, I ween, if she\nHad not his prisoned tongue and voice set free."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Grieve not,\" she said, \"sir monarch, for thy fall;\nBut let the blame upon thy courser be!\nTo whom more welcome had been forage, stall,\nAnd rest, than further joust and jeopardy;\nAnd well thy foe the loser may I call,\n(Who shall no glory gain for such is he ) \n\nWho is the first to quit his ground, if aught\nAngelica of fighting fields be taught.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While she so seeks the Saracen to cheer,\nBehold a messenger with pouch and horn,\nOn panting hackney! — man and horse appear\nWith the long journey, weary and forlorn.\nHe questions Sacripant, approaching near,\nHad he seen warrior pass, by whom were borne\nA shield and crest of white; in search of whom\nThrough the wide forest pricked the weary groom."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Sacripant made answer, \"As you see,\nHe threw me here, and went but now his way:\nThen tell the warrior's name, that I may be\nInformed whose valour foiled me in the fray.\"\nTo him the groom, — \"That which you ask of me\nI shall relate to you without delay:\nKnow that you were in combat prostrate laid\nBy the tried valour of a gentle maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Bold is the maid; but fairer yet than bold,\nNor the redoubted virgin's name I veil:\n'Twas Bradamant who marred what praise of old\nYour prowess ever won with sword and mail.\"\nThis said, he spurred again, his story told,\nAnd left him little gladdened by the tale.\nHe recks not what he says or does, for shame,\nAnd his flushed visage kindles into flame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the woeful warrior long had thought\nUpon his cruel case, and still in vain,\nAnd found a woman his defeat had wrought,\nFor thinking but increased the monarch's pain,\nHe climbed the other horse, nor spake he aught;\nBut silently uplifted from the plain,\nUpon the croup bestowed that damsel sweet,\nReserved to gladder use in safer seat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two miles they had not rode before they hear\nThe sweeping woods which spread about them, sound\nWith such loud crash and trample, far and near,\nThe forest seemed to tremble all around;\nAnd shortly after see a steed appear,\nWith housings wrought in gold and richly bound;\nWho clears the bush and stream, with furious force\nAnd whatsoever else impedes his course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Unless the misty air,\" the damsel cries,\n\"And boughs deceive my sight, yon noble steed\nIs, sure, Bayardo, who before us flies,\nAnd parts the wood with such impetuous speed.\n— Yes, 'tis Bayardo's self I recognize.\nHow well the courser understands our need!\nTwo riders ill a foundered jade would bear,\nBut hither speeds the horse to end that care.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The bold Circassian lighted, and applied\nHis hand to seize him by the flowing rein,\nWho, swiftly turning, with his heels replied,\nFor he like lightning wheeled upon the plain.\nWoe to the king! but that he leaps aside,\nFor should he smite, he would not lash in vain.\nSuch are his bone and sinew, that the shock\nOf his good heels had split a metal rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then to the maid he goes submissively,\nWith gentle blandishment and humble mood;\nAs the dog greets his lord with frolic glee,\nWhom, some short season past, he had not viewed.\nFor good Bayardo had in memory\nAlbracca, where her hands prepared his food,\nWhat time the damsel loved Rinaldo bold;\nRinaldo, then ungrateful, stern, and cold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With her left hand she takes him by the bit,\nAnd with the other pats his sides and chest:\nWhile the good steed (so marvellous his wit),\nLamb-like, obeyed the damsel and caressed.\nMeantime the king, who sees the moment fit,\nLeapt up, and with his knees the courser pressed.\nWhile on the palfrey, eased of half his weight,\nThe lady left the croup, and gained the seat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then, as at hazard, she directs her sight,\nSounding in arms a man on foot espies,\nAnd glows with sudden anger and despite;\nFor she in him the son of Aymon eyes.\nHer more than life esteems the youthful knight,\nWhile she from him, like crane from falcon, flies.\nTime was the lady sighed, her passion slighted;\n'Tis now Rinaldo loves, as ill requited."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this effect two different fountains wrought,\nWhose wonderous waters different moods inspire.\nBoth spring in Arden, with rare virtue fraught:\nThis fills the heart with amorous desire:\nWho taste that other fountain are untaught\nTheir love, and change for ice their former fire.\nRinaldo drank the first, and vainly sighs;\nAngelica the last, and hates and flies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Mixed with such secret bane the waters glide,\nWhich amorous care convert to sudden hate;\nThe maid no sooner had Rinaldo spied,\nThan on her laughing eyes deep darkness sate:\nAnd with sad mien and trembling voice she cried\nTo Sacripant, and prayed him not to wait\nThe near approach of the detested knight,\nBut through the wood with her pursue his flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To her the Saracen, with anger hot:\n\"Is knightly worship sunk so low in me,\nThat thou should'st hold my valour cheap, and not\nSufficient to make yonder champion flee?\nAlready are Albracca's fights forgot,\nAnd that dread night I singly stood for thee?\nThat night when I, though naked, was thy shield\nAgainst King Agrican and all his field?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She answers not, and knows not in her fear\nWhat 'tis she does; Rinaldo is too nigh:\nAnd from afar that furious cavalier\nThreats the bold Saracen with angry cry,\nAs soon as the known steed and damsel dear,\nWhose charms such flame had kindled, meet his eye.\nBut what ensued between the haughty pair"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto shall declare.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 2"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A hermit parts, by means of hollow sprite,\nThe two redoubted rivals' dangerous play;\nRinaldo goes where Love and Hope invite,\nBut is dispatched by Charles another way;\nBradamont, seeking her devoted knight,\nThe good Rogero, nigh becomes the prey\nOf Pinabel, who drops the damsel brave\nInto the dungeon of a living grave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Injurious love, why still to mar accord\nBetween desires has been thy favourite feat?\nWhy does it please thee so, perfidious lord,\nTwo hearts should with a different measure beat?\nThou wilt not let me take the certain ford,\nDragging me where the stream is deep and fleet.\nHer I abandon who my love desires,\nWhile she who hates, respect and love inspires."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thou to Rinaldo show'st the damsel fair,\nWhile he seems hideous to that gentle dame;\nAnd he, who when the lady's pride and care,\nPaid back with deepest hate her amorous flame,\nNow pines, himself, the victim of despair,\nScorned in his turn, and his reward the same.\nBy the changed damsel in such sort abhorred,\nShe would choose death before that hated lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He to the Pagan cries: \"Forego thy theft,\nAnd down, false felon, from that pilfer'd steed;\nI am not wont to let my own be reft.\nAnd he who seeks it dearly pays the deed.\nMore — I shall take from thee yon lovely weft;\nTo leave thee such a prize were foul misdeed;\nAnd horse and maid, whose worth outstrips belief,\nWere ill, methinks, relinquished to a thief.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou liest,\" the haughty Saracen retorts,\nAs proud, and burning with as fierce a flame,\n\"A thief thyself, if Fame the truth reports:\nBut let good deeds decide our dubious claim,\nWith whom the steed or damsel fair assorts:\nBest proved by valiant deeds: though, for the dame,\nThat nothing is so precious, I with thee\n(Search the wide world throughout may well agree.\" )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As two fierce dogs will somtimes stand at gaze,\nWhom hate or other springs of strife inspire,\nAnd grind their teeth, while each his foe surveys\nWith sidelong glance and eyes more red than fire,\nThen either falls to bites, and hoarsely bays,\nWhile their stiff bristles stand on end with ire:\nSo from reproach and menace to the sword\nPass Sacripant and Clermont's angry lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus kindling into wrath the knights engage:\nOne is on foot, the other on his horse:\nSmall gain to this; for inexperienced page\nWould better rein his charger in the course.\nFor such Baiardo's sense, he will not wage\nWar with his master, or put out his force.\nFor voice, nor hand, nor manage, will he stir,\nRebellious to the rein or goading spur."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, when the king would urge him, takes the rest,\nOr, when he curbs him, runs in giddy rings;\nAnd drops his head beneath his spreading chest,\nAnd plays his spine, and runs an-end and flings.\nAnd now the furious Saracen distressed,\nSees 'tis no time to tame the beast, and springs,\nWith one hand on the pummel, to the ground;\nClear of the restless courser at a bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as Sacripant, with well-timed leap,\nIs from the fury of Bayardo freed,\nYou may believe the battle does not sleep\nBetween those champions, matched in heart and deed.\nTheir sounding blades such changeful measure keep,\nThe hammer-strokes of Vulcan with less speed\nDescend in that dim cavern, where he heats,\nAnd Jove's red thunders on his anvil beats."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sometimes they lunge, then feign the thrust and parry:\nDeep masters of the desperate game they play;\nOr rise upon the furious stroke, and carry\nTheir swords aloft, or stoop and stand at bay.\nAgain they close, again exhausted tarry;\nNow hide, now show themselves, and now give way,\nAnd where one knight an inch of ground has granted,\nHis foeman's foot upon that inch is planted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When, lo!  Rinaldo, now impatient grown,\nStrikes full at Sacripant with lifted blade;\nAnd he puts forth his buckler made of bone,\nAnd well with strong and stubborn steel inlaid:\nThough passing thick, Fusberta cleaves it: groan\nGreenwood, and covert close, and sunny glade.\nThe paynim's arm rings senseless with the blow,\nAnd steel and bone, like ice, in shivers go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the fair damsel saw, with timid eye,\nSuch ruin follow from the faulchion's sway,\nShe, like the criminal, whose doom is nigh,\nChanged her fair countenance through sore dismay,\nAnd deemed that little time was left to fly\nIf she would not be that Rinaldo's prey,\nRinaldo loathed by her as much, as he\nDoats on the scornful damsel miserably."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So turned her horse into the gloomy chase,\nAnd drove him through rough path and tangled ally\nAnd oftentimes bent back her bloodless face,\nAnd saw Rinaldo from each thicket sally.\nNor flying long had urged the frantic race,\nBefore she met a hermit in a valley.\nDevotion in his aspect was expressed,\nAnd his long beard descended on his breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Wasted he was as much by fasts as age,\nAnd on an ass was mounted, slow and sure;\nHis visage warranted that never sage\nHad conscience more precise or passing pure.\nThough in his arteries time had stilled the rage\nOf blood, and spake him feeble and demure,\nAt sight of the delighted damsel, he\nWas inly stirred for very charity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lady prayed that kindly friar, that he\nWould straight conduct her to some haven near,\nFor that she from the land of France might flee,\nAnd never more of loathed Rinaldo hear.\nThe hermit, who was skilled in sorcery,\nCeased not to soothe the gentle damsel's fear.\nAnd with the promise of deliverance, shook\nHis pocket, and drew forth a secret book."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This opened, quick and mighty marvel wrought;\nFor not a leaf is finished by the sage,\nBefore a spirit, by his bidding brought,\nWaits his command in likeness of a page:\nHe, by the magic writ constrained and taught,\nHastes where the warriors face to face engage,\nIn the cool shade — but not in cool disport —\nAnd steps between, and stops their battle short."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In courtesy,\" he cried, \"let either show\nWhat his foe's death to either can avail,\nAnd what the guerdon conquest will bestow\nOn him who in the battle shall prevail,\nIf Roland, though he has not struck a blow,\nOr snapt in fight a single link of mail,\nTo Paris-town conveys the damsel gay,\nWho has engaged you in this bitter fray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Within an easy mile I saw the peer\nPricking to Paris with that lady bright;\nRiding, in merry mood, with laugh and jeer,\nAnd mocking at your fierce and fruitless fight.\nSure it were better, while they yet are near,\nTo follow peer and damsel in their flight:\nFor should he once in Paris place his prize\nThe lady never more shall meet your eyes.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "You might have seen those angry cavaliers\nChange at the demon's tale for rage and shame;\nAnd curse themselves as wanting eyes and ears,\nTo let their rival cheat them of the dame.\nTowards his horse the good Rinaldo steers,\nBreathing forth piteous sighs which seem of flame;\nAnd, if he joins Orlando — ere they part —\nSwears in his fury he will have his heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So, passing where the prompt Bayardo stood,\nLeaps on his back, and leaves, as swift as wind,\nWithout farewell, his rival in the wood;\nMuch less invites him to a seat behind.\nThe goaded charger, in his heat of blood,\nForces whate'er his eager course confined,\nDitch, river, tangled thorn, or marble block;\nHe swims the river, and he clears the rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let it not, sir, sound strangely in your ear\nRinaldo took the steed thus readily,\nSo long and vainly followed far and near;\nFor he, endued with reasoning faculty,\nHad not in vice lured on the following peer,\nBut fled before his cherished lord, that he\nMight guide him whither went the gentle dame,\nFor whom, as he had heard, he nursed a flame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For when Angelica, in random dread,\nFrom the pavilion winged her rapid flight,\nBayardo marked the damsel as she fled,\nHis saddle lightened of Mount Alban's knight;\nWho then on foot an equal combat sped,\nMatched with a baron of no meaner might;\nAnd chased the maid by woods, and floods, and strands,\nIn hopes to place her in the warrior's hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, with desire to bring him to the maid,\nGallopped before him still with rampant play;\nBut would not let his master mount, afraid\nThat he might make him take another way.\nSo luring on Rinaldo through the shade,\nTwice brought him to his unexpected prey;\nTwice foiled in his endeavour: once by bold\nFerrau; then Sacripant, as lately told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now good Bayardo had believed the tiding\nOf that fair damsel, which produced the accord;\nAnd in the devil's cunning tale confiding,\nRenewed his wonted service to his lord.\nBehold Rinaldo then in fury riding,\nAnd pushing still his courser Paris-ward!\nThough he fly fast, the champion's wishes go\nFaster; and wind itself had seemed too slow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At night Rinaldo rests his steed, with pain\nTo meet Anglante's lord he burned so sore;\nAnd lent such credit to the tidings vain\nOf the false courier of that wizard hoar:\nAnd that day and the next, with flowing rein,\nRode, till the royal city rose before\nHis eyes; where Charlemagne had taken post,\nWith the sad remnant of his broken host."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, for he fears the Afric king's pursuit,\nAnd sap and siege, upon his vassals calls\nTo gather in fresh victual, and recruit\nAnd cleanse their ditches, and repair their walls.\nAnd what may best annoy the foes, and suit\nFor safety, without more delay forestalls;\nAnd plans an embassy to England, thence\nTo gather fresher forces for defence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For he is bent again to try the fate\nOf arms in tented field, though lately shamed;\nAnd send Rinaldo to the neighbouring state\nOf Britain, which was after England named.\nIll liked the Paladin to cross the strait;\nNot that the people or the land he blamed,\nBut that King Charles was sudden; nor a day\nWould grant the valiant envoy for delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo never executed thing\nLess willingly, prevented in his quest\nOf that fair visage he was following,\nWhose charms his heart had ravished from his breast.\nYet, in obediance to the christian king,\nPrepared himself to do the royal hest.\nTo Calais the good envoy wends with speed,\nAnd the same day embarks himself and steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And there, in scorn of cautious pilot's skill\n(Such his impatience to regain his home),\nLaunched on the doubtful sea, which boded ill,\nAnd rolled its heavy billows, white with foam.\nThe wind, enraged that he opposed his will,\nStirred up the waves; and, 'mid the gathering gloom,\nSo the loud storm and tempest's fury grew,\nThat topmast-high the flashing waters flew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The watchful mariners, in wary sort,\nHaul down the mainsail, and attempt to wear;\nAnd would put back in panic to the port,\nWhence, in ill hour, they loosed with little care.\n— \"Not so,\" exclaims the wind, and stops them short,\n\"So poor a penance will not pay the dare.\"\nAnd when they fain would veer, with fiercer roar\nPelts back their reeling prow and blusters more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Starboard and larboard bears the fitful gale,\nAnd never for a thought its ire assuages;\nWhile the strained vessel drives with humble sail\nBefore the billows, as the tempest rages.\nBut I, who still pursue a varying tale,\nMust leave awhile the Paladin, who wages\nA weary warfare with the wind and flood;\nTo follow a fair virgin of his blood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I speak of that famed damsel, by whose spear\nO'erthrown, King Sacripant on earth was flung;\nThe worthy sister of the valiant peer,\nFrom Beatrix and good Duke Aymon sprung.\nBy daring deeds and puissance no less dear\nTo Charlemagne and France: Since proved among\nThe first, her prowess, tried by many a test,\nEqual to good Rinaldo's shone confessed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A cavalier was suitor to the dame,\nWho out of Afric passed with Agramant;\nRogero was his valiant father's name,\nHis mother was the child of Agolant.\nAnd she, who not of bear or lion came,\nDisdained not on the Child her love to plant,\nThough cruel Fortune, ill their wishes meeting,\nHad granted to the pair a single greeting."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Alone thenceforth she sought her lover (he\nWas named of him to whom he owed his birth),\nAnd roved as safe as if in company\nOf thousands, trusting in her single worth.\nShe having made the king of Circassy\nSalute the visage of old mother earth,\nTraversed a wood, and that wood past, a mountain;\nAnd stopt at length beside a lovely fountain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through a delicious mead the fountain-rill,\nBy ancient trees o'ershaded, glides away;\nAnd him whose ear its pleasing murmurs fill,\nInvites to drink, and on its banks to stay;\nOn the left side a cultivated hill\nExcludes the fervors of the middle day.\nAs first the damsel thither turns her eyes,\nA youthful cavalier she seated spies;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A cavalier, who underneath the shade,\nSeems lost, as in a melancholy dream;\nAnd on the bank, which gaudy flowers displayed,\nReposing, overhangs the crystal stream.\nHis horse beneath a spreading beech is laid,\nAnd from a bough the shield and helmet gleam.\nWhile his moist eyes, and sad and downcast air,\nSpeak him the broken victim of despair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Urged by the passion lodged in every breast,\nA restless curiosity to know\nOf others' cares, the gentle maid addressed\nThe knight, and sought the occasion of his woe.\nAnd he to her his secret grief confessed,\nWon by her gentle speech and courteous show,\nAnd by that gallant bearing, which at sight,\nPrepared who saw her for nimble knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Fair sir, a band of horse and foot,\" he said,\n\"I brought to Charlemagne; and thither pressed,\nWhere he an ambush for Marsilius spread,\nDescending from the Pyrenean crest;\nAnd in my company a damsel led,\nWhose charms with fervid love had fired my breast.\nWhen, as we journey by Rhone's current, I\nA rider on a winged courser spy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The robber, whether he were man or shade,\nOr goblin damned to everlasting woe,\nAs soon as he beheld my dear-loved maid,\nLike falcon, who, descending, aims its blow,\nSank in a thought and rose; and soaring, laid\nHands on his prize, and snatched her from below.\nSo quick the rape, that all appeared a dream,\nUntil I heard in air the damsel's scream."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The ravening kite so swoops and plunders, when\nHovering above the shelterd yard, she spies\nA helpless chicken near unwatchful hen,\nWho vainly dins the thief with after cries.\nI cannot reach the mountain-robber's den,\nCompassed with cliffs, or follow one who flies.\nBesides, way-foundered is my weary steed,\nWho 'mid these rocks has wasted wind and speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But I, like one who from his bleeding side\nWould liefer far have seen his heart out-torn,\nLeft my good squadrons masterless, to ride\nAlong the cliffs, and passes least forlorn;\nAnd took the way (love served me for a guide)\nWhere it appeared the ruthless thief had born,\nAscending to his den, the lovely prey,\nWhat time he snatched my hope and peace away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Six days I rode, from morn to setting sun,\nBy horrid cliff, by bottom dark and drear;\nAnd giddy precipice, where path was none,\nNor sign, nor vestiges of man were near.\nAt last a dark and barren vale I won,\nWhere caverned mountains and rude cliffs appear;\nWhere in the middle rose a rugged block,\nWith a fair castle planted on the rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"From far it shone like flame, and seemed not dight\nOf marble or of brick; and in my eye\nMore wonderful the work, more fair to sight\nThe walls appeared, as I approached more nigh.\nI, after, learned that it was built by sprite\nWhom potent fumes had raised and sorcery:\nWho on this rock its towers of steel did fix,\nCase-hardened in the stream and fire of Styx."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Each polished turret shines with such a ray\nThat it defies the mouldering rust and rain:\nThe robber scours the country night and day,\nAnd after harbours in this sure domain.\nNothing is safe which he would bear away;\nPursued with curses and with threats in vain.\nThere (fruitless every hope to foil his art)\nThe felon keeps my love, oh! say my heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alas! what more is left me but to eye\nHer prison on that cliff's aerial crest?\nLike the she-fox, who hears her offspring cry,\nStanding beneath the ravening eagle's nest;\nAnd since she has not wings to rise and fly,\nRuns round the rugged rock with hopeless quest.\nSo inaccessible the wild dominion\nTo whatsoever has not plume and pinion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"While I so lingered where those rocks aspire,\nI saw a dwarf guide two of goodly strain;\nWhose coming added hope to my desire\n(Alas! desire and hope alike were vain)\nBoth barons bold, and fearful in their ire:\nThe one Gradasso, King of Sericane,\nThe next, of youthful vigour, was a knight,\nPrized in the Moorish court, Rogero hight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The dwarf exclaimed, `These champions will assay\nTheir force with him who dwells on yonder steep,\nAnd by such strange and unattempted way\nSpurs the winged courser from his mountain-keep.'\nAnd I to the approaching warriors say,\n`Pity, fair sirs, the cruel loss I weep,\nAnd, as I trust, yon daring spoiler slain,\nGive my lost lady to my arms again.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then how my love was ravished I make known,\nVouching with bitter tears my deep distress.\nThey proffer aid, and down the path of stone\nWhich winds about the craggy mountain, press.\nWhile I, upon the summit left alone,\nLook on, and pray to God for their success.\nBeneath the wily wizard's castle strong\nExtends a little plain, two bow-shots long."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Arrived beneath the craggy keep, the two\nContend which warrior shall begin the fight.\nWhen, whether the first lot Gradasso drew,\nOr young Rogero held the honor light,\nThe King of Sericane his bugle blew,\nAnd the rock rang and fortress on the height;\nAnd, lo! apparelled for the fearful course,\nThe cavalier upon his winged horse!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Upwards, by little and by little, springs\nThe winged courser, as the pilgrim crane\nFinds not at first his balance and his wings,\nRunning and scarcely rising from the plain;\nBut when the flock is launched and scattered, flings\nHis pinions to the wind, and soars amain.\nSo straight the necromancer's upward flight,\nThe eagle scarce attempts so bold a height."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When it seems fit, he wheels his courser round,\nWho shuts his wings, and falling from the sky,\nShoots like a well trained falcon to the ground,\nWho sees the quarry, duck or pigeon, fly:\nSo, through the parting air, with whizzing sound,\nWith rested lance, he darted from on high;\nAnd while Gradasso scarcely marks the foe\nHe hears him swooping near, and feels the blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The wizard on Gradasso breaks his spear,\nHe wounds the empty air, with fury vain.\nThis in the feathered monster breeds no fear;\nWho to a distance shifts, and swoops again.\nWhile that encounter made the Alfana rear,\nThrown back upon her haunches, on the plain.\nThe Alfana that the Indian monarch rode,\nThe fairest was that ever man bestrode."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Up to the starry sphere with swift ascent\nThe wizard soars, then pounces from the sky,\nAnd strikes the young Rogero, who, intent\nUpon Gradasso, deems no danger nigh.\nBeneath the wizard's blow the warrior bent,\nWhich made some deal his generous courser ply;\nAnd when to smite the shifting foe he turned,\nHim in the sky, and out of reach discerned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His blows Rogero, now Gradasso, bruise\nOn forehead, bosom, back, or flanks, between;\nWhile he the warrior's empty blows eschews,\nShifting so quickly that he scarce is seen.\nNow this, now that, the wizard seems to choose,\nThe monster makes such spacious rings and clean,\nWhile the enchanter so deceives the knights,\nThey view him not, and know not whence he smites."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Between the two on earth and him o' the sky,\nUntil that hour the warfare lasted there,\nWhich, spreading wide its veil of dusky dye,\nThroughout the world, discolours all things fair.\nWhat I beheld, I say; I add not, I,\nA tittle to the tale; yet scarcely dare\nTo tell to other what I stood and saw;\nSo strange it seems, so passing Nature's law."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Well covered in a goodly silken case,\nHe, the celestial warrior, bore his shield;\nBut why delayed the mantle to displace\nI know not, and its lucid orb concealed.\nSince this no sooner blazes in his face,\nThan his foe tumbles dazzled on the field;\nAnd while he, like a lifeless body, lies,\nBecomes the necromancer's helpless prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"LIke carbuncle, the magic buckler blazed,\nNo glare was ever seen which shone so bright:\nNor could the warriors choose but fall, amazed\nAnd blinded by the clear and dazzling light.\nI, too, that from a distant mountain gazed,\nFell senseless; and when I regained my sight,\nAfter long time, saw neither knights nor page,\nNor aught beside a dark and empty stage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This while the fell enchanter, I supposed,\nDragged both the warriors to his prison-cell;\nAnd by strange virtue of the shield disclosed,\nI from my hope and they from freedom fell:\nAnd thus I to the turrets, which enclosed\nMy heart, departing, bade a last farewell.\nNow sum my griefs, and say if love combine\nOther distress or grief to match with mine.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The knight relapsed into his first disease,\nAfter his melancholy tale was done.\nThis was Count Pinabel, the Maganzese,\nAnselmo d'Altaripa's faithless son.\nHe, where the blood ran foul through all degrees,\nDisdained to be the only virtuous one;\nNor played a simple part among the base,\nPassing in vice the villains of his race."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With aspect changing still, the beauteous dame\nHears what the mournful Maganzese narrates;\nAnd, at first mention of Rogero's name,\nHer radiant face with eager joy dilates.\nBut, full of pity, kindles into flame\nAs Pinabel his cruel durance states.\nNor finds she, though twice told, the story stale;\nBut makes him oft repeat and piece his tale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, after, when she deemed that all was clear,\nCried to the knight, \"Repose upon my say.\nTo thee may my arrival well be dear,\nAnd thou as fortunate account this day.\nStraight wend me to the keep, sir cavalier,\nWhich holds a jewel of so rich a ray:\nNor shalt thou grudge thy labour and thy care,\nIf envious Fortune do but play me fair.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The knight replied, \"Then nought to me remains\nBut that I yonder mountain-passes show;\nAnd sure 'tis little loss to lose my pains,\nWhere every thing is lost I prize below.\nBut you would climb yon cliffs, and for your gains\nWill find a prison-house, and be it so!\nWhate'er betide you, blame yourself alone;\nYou go forewarned to meet a fate foreshown.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said, the cavalier remounts his horse,\nAnd serves the gallant damsel as a guide;\nWho is prepared Rogero's gaol to force,\nOr to be slain, or in his prison stied.\nWhen lo! a messenger, in furious course,\nCalled to the dame to stay, and rode and cried.\nThis was the post who told Circassa's lord\nWhat valiant hand had stretched him on the sward."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The courier, who so plied his restless heel,\nNews of Narbonne and of Montpelier bore:\nHow both had raised the standard of Castile,\nAll Acquamorta siding with the Moor;\nAnd how Marseilles' disheartened men appeal\nTo her, who should protect her straightened shore;\nAnd how, through him, her citizens demand\nCounsel and comfort at their captain's hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This goodly town, with many miles of plain,\nWhich lie 'twixt Var and Rhone, upon the sea,\nTo her was given by royal Charlemagne:\nSuch trust he placed in her fidelity.\nStill wont with wonder on the tented plain\nThe prowess of that valiant maid to see.\nAnd now the panting courier, as I said,\nRode from Marseilles to ask the lady's aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether or not she should the call obey,\nThe youthful damsel doubts some little space;\nStrong in one balance Fame and Duty weigh,\nBut softer thoughts both Fame and Duty chase:\nAnd she, at length, resolved the emprize to assay,\nAnd free Rogero from the enchanted place:\nOr, should her valour in the adventure fail,\nWould with the cherished lover share his jail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And did with such excuse that post appay,\nHe was contented on her will to wait:\nThen turned the bridle to resume her way\nWith Pinabel, who seemed no whit elate.\nSince of that line he knows the damsel gay,\nHeld in such open and such secret hate;\nAnd future trouble to himself foresees,\nWere he detected as a Maganzese."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For 'twixt Maganza's and old Clermont's line\nThere was an ancient and a deadly feud:\nAnd oft to blows the rival houses came,\nAnd oft in civil blood their hands embrued.\nAnd hence some treason to this gentle dame\nIn his foul heart, the wicked County brewed;\nOr, as the first occasion served, would stray\nOut of the road, and leave her by the way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And so the traitor's troubled fancy rack\nFear, doubt, and his own native, rancorous mood,\nThat unawares he issued from the track,\nAnd found himself within a gloomy wood:\nWhere a rough mountain reared its shaggy back,\nWhose stony peak above the forest stood;\nThe daughter of Dodona's duke behind,\nDogging his footsteps through the thicket blind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, when he saw himself within the brake,\nThought to abandon his unweeting foe;\nAnd to the dame — \" 'Twere better that we make\nFor shelter ere the gathering darkness grow;\nAnd, yonder mountain past, (save I mistake)\nA tower is seated in the vale below.\nDo you expect me then, while from the peak\nI measure the remembered place I seek.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said, he pushed his courser up the height\nOf that lone mountain; in his evil mind\nRevolving, as he went, some scheme or sleight\nTo rid him of the gentle dame behind.\nWhen lo! a rocky cavern met his sight,\nAmid those precipices dark and blind:\nIts sides descended thirty yards and more,\nWorked smooth, and at the bottom was a door."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A void was at the bottom, where a wide\nPortal conducted to an inner room:\nFrom thence a light shone out on every side,\nAs of a torch illumining the gloom.\nFair Bradamant pursued her faithless guide,\nSuspended there, and pondering on her doom:\nAnd came upon the felon where he stood,\nFearing lest she might lose him in the wood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When her approach the County's first intent\nMade vain, the wily traitor sought to mend\nHis toils, and some new stratagem invent\nTo rid her thence, or bring her to her end.\nAnd so to meet the approaching lady went,\nAnd showed the cave, and prayed her to ascend;\nAnd said that in its bottom he had seen\nA gentle damsel of bewitching mien."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who, by her lovely semblance and rich vest,\nAppeared a lady of no mean degree;\nBut melancholy, weeping, and distressed,\nAs one who pined there in captivity:\nAnd that when he towards the entrance pressed,\nTo learn who that unhappy maid might be,\nOne on the melancholy damsel flew,\nAnd her within that inner cavern drew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beauteous Bradamant, who was more bold\nThan wary, gave a ready ear; and, bent\nTo help the maid, imprisoned in that hold,\nSought but the means to try the deep descent.\nThen, looking round, descried an elm-tree old,\nWhich furnished present means for her intent:\nAnd from the tree, with boughs and foliage stored,\nLopt a long branch, and shaped it with her sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The severed end she to the count commended,\nThen, grasping it, hung down that entrance steep.\nWith her feet foremost, by her arms suspended:\nWhen asking if she had the skill to leap,\nThe traitor, with a laugh, his hands extended.\nAnd plunged his helpless prey into the deep.\n\"And thus,\" exclaimed the ruffian, \"might I speed\nWith thee each sucker of thy cursed seed!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But not, as was the will of Pinabel,\nSuch cruel lot fair Bradamant assayed;\nFor striking on the bottom of the cell,\nThe stout elm-bough so long her weight upstayed,\nThat, though it split and splintered where it fell,\nIt broked her fall, and saved the gentle maid.\nSome while astounded there the lady lay,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto will display.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 3"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Restored to sense, the beauteous Bradamant\nFinds sage Melissa in the vaulted tomb,\nAnd hears from her of many a famous plant\nAnd warrior, who shall issue from her womb.\nNext, to release Rogero from the haunt\nOf old Atlantes, learns how from the groom,\nBrunello hight, his virtuous ring to take;\nAnd thus the knight's and others' fetters break."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who will vouchsafe me voice that shall ascend\nAs high as I would raise my noble theme?\nWho will afford befitting words, and lend\nWings to my verse, to soar the pitch I scheme?\nSince fiercer fire for such illustrious end,\nThan what was wont, may well my song beseem.\nFor this fair portion to my lord is due\nWhich sings the sires from whom his lineage grew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Than whose fair line, 'mid those by heavenly grace\nChosen to minister this earth below,\nYou see not, Phoebus, in your daily race,\nOne that in peace or war doth fairer show;\nNor lineage that hath longer kept its place;\nAnd still shall keep it, if the lights which glow\nWithin me, but aright inspire my soul,\nWhile the blue heaven shall turn about the pole."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But should I seek at full its worth to blaze,\nNot mine were needful, but that noble lyre\nWhich sounded at your touch the thunderer's praise,\nWhat time the giants sank in penal fire.\nYet should you instruments, more fit to raise\nThe votive work, bestow, as I desire,\nAll labour and all thought will I combine,\nTo shape and shadow forth the great design."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Till when, this chisel may suffice to scale\nThe stone, and give my lines a right direction;\nAnd haply future study may avail,\nTo bring the stubborn labour to perfection.\nReturn we now to him, to whom the mail\nOf hawberk, shield, and helm, were small protection:\nI speak of Pinabel the Maganzeze,\nWho hopes the damsel's death, whose fall he sees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The wily traitor thought that damsel sweet\nHad perished on the darksome cavern's floor,\nAnd with pale visages hurried his retreat\nFrom that, through him contaminated door.\nAnd, thence returning, clomb into his seat:\nThen, like one who a wicked spirit bore,\nTo add another sin to evil deed,\nBore off with him the warlike virgin's steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leave we sometime the wretch who, while he layed\nSnares for another, wrought his proper doom;\nAnd turn we to the damsel he betrayed,\nWho had nigh found at once her death and tomb.\nShe, after rising from the rock, dismayed\nAt her shrewd fall, and gazing through the gloom,\nBeheld and passed that inner door, which gave\nEntrance to other and more spacious cave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For the first cavern in a second ended,\nFashioned in form of church, and large and square;\nWith roof by cunning architect extended\nOn shafts of alabaster rich and rare.\nThe flame of a clear-burning lamp ascended\nBefore the central altar; and the glare,\nIlluminating all the space about,\nShone through the gate, and lit the cave without."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Touched with the sanctifying thoughts which wait\nOn worthy spirit in a holy place,\nShe prays with eager lips, and heart elate,\nTo the Disposer of all earthly grace:\nAnd, kneeling, hears a secret wicket grate\nIn the opposing wall; whence, face to face,\nA woman issuing forth, the maid addresses,\nBarefoot, ungirt, and with dishevelled tresses."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O generous Bradamant,\" the matron cried,\n\"Know thine arrival in this hallowed hold\nWas not unauthorized of heavenly guide:\nAnd the prophetic ghost of Merlin told,\nThou to this cave shouldst come by path untried,\nWhich covers the renowned magician's mould.\nAnd here have I long time awaited thee,\nTo tell what is the heavens' pronounced decree."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This is the ancient memorable cave\nWhich Merlin, that enchanter sage, did make:\nThou may'st have heard how that magician brave\nWas cheated by the Lady of the Lake.\nBelow, beneath the cavern, is the grave\nWhich holds his bones; where, for that lady's sake,\nHis limbs (for such her will the wizard spread. ) \n\nLiving he laid him there, and lies there dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet lives the spirit of immortal strain;\nLodged in the enchanter's corpse, till to the skies\nThe trumpet call it, or to endless pain,\nAs it with dove or raven's wing shall rise.\nYet lives the voice, and thou shalt hear how plain\nFrom its sepulchral case of marble cries:\nSince this has still the past and future taught\nTo every wight that has its counsel sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Long days have passed since I from distant land\nMy course did to this cemetery steer,\nThat in the solemn mysteries I scanned,\nMerlin to me the truth should better clear;\nAnd having compassed the design I planned,\nA month beyond, for thee, have tarried here;\nSince Merlin, still with certain knowledge summing\nEvents, prefixed this moment for thy coming.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The daughter of Duke Aymon stood aghast,\nAnd silent listened to the speech; while she\nKnew not, sore marvelling at all that passed,\nIf 'twere a dream or a reality.\nAt length, with modest brow, and eyes down cast,\nReplied (like one that was all modesty),\n\"And is this wrought for me? and have I merit\nWorthy the workings of prophetic spirit?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And full of joy the adventure strange pursues,\nMoving with ready haste behind the dame,\nWho brings her to the sepulchre which mews\nThe bones and spirit, erst of Merlin's name.\nThe tomb, of hardest stone which masons use,\nShone smooth and lucid, and as red as flame.\nSo that although no sun-beam pierced the gloom,\nIts splendour lit the subterraneous room."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether it be the native operation\nO certain stones, to shine like torch i' the dark,\nOr whether force of spell or fumigation,\n(A guess that seems to come more near the mark)\nOr sign made under mystic constellation,\nThe blaze that came from the sepulchral ark\nDiscovered sculpture, colour, gems, and gilding,\nAnd whatsoever else adorned the building."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scarcely had Bradamant above the sill\nLifter her foot, and trod the secret cave,\nWhen the live spirit, in clear tones that thrill,\nAddressed the martial virgin from the grave;\n\"May Fortune, chaste and noble maid, fulfil\nThine every wish!\" exclaimed the wizard brave.\n\"Since from thy womb a princely race shall spring,\nWhose name through Italy and earth shall ring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The noble blood derived from ancient Troy,\nMingling in thee its two most glorious streams,\nShall be the ornament, and flower, and joy\nOf every lineage on which Phoebus beams,\nWhere genial stars lend warmth, or cold annoy,\nWhere Indus, Tagus, Nile, or Danube gleams;\nAnd in thy progeny and long drawn line\nShall marquises, counts, dukes and Caesers shine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Captains and cavaliers shall spring from thee,\nWho both by knightly lance and prudent lore,\nShall once again to widowed Italy\nHer ancient praise and fame in arms restore;\nAnd in her realms just lords shall seated be,\n(Such Numa and Augustus were of yore),\nWho with their government, benign and sage,\nShall re-create on earth the golden age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then, that the will of Heaven be duly brought\nTo a fair end through thee, in fitting date,\nWhich from the first to bless thy love has wrought,\nAnd destined young Rogero for thy mate,\nLet nothing interpose to break that thought,\nBut boldly tread the path perscribed by fate;\nNor let aught stay thee till the thief be thrown\nBy thy good lance, who keeps thee from thine own.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here Merlin ceased, that for the solemn feat\nMelissa might prepare with fitting spell,\nTo show bold Bradamant, in aspect meet,\nThe heirs who her illustrious race should swell.\nHence many sprites she chose; but from what seat\nEvoked, I know not, or if called from hell;\nAnd gathered in one place (so bade the dame),\nIn various garb and guise the shadows came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This done, into the church she called the maid,\nWhere she had drawn a magic ring, as wide\nAs might contain the damsel, prostrate laid;\nWith the full measure of a palm beside.\nAnd on her head, lest spirit should invade,\nA pentacle for more assurance tied.\nSo bade her hold her peace, and stand and look,\nThen read, and schooled the demons from her book."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lo! forth of that first cave what countless swarm\nPresses upon the circle's sacred round,\nBut, when they would the magic rampart storm,\nFinds the way barred as if by fosse or mound;\nThen back the rabble turns of various form;\nAnd when it thrice with bending march has wound\nAbout the circle, troops into the cave,\nWhere stands that beauteous urn, the wizard's grave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To tell at large the puissant acts and worth,\nAnd name of each who, figured in a sprite,\nIs present to our eyes before his birth,\"\nSaid sage Melissa to the damsel bright;\n\"To tell the deeds which they shall act on earth,\nWere labour not to finish with the night.\nHence I shall call few worthies of thy line,\nAs time and fair occasion shall combine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"See yonder first-born of thy noble breed,\nWho well reflects thy fair and joyous face;\nHe, first of thine and of Rogero's seed,\nShall plant in Italy thy generous race.\nIn him behold who shall distain the mead,\nAnd his good sword with blood of Pontier base;\nThe mighty wrong chastised, and traitor's guilt,\nBy whom his princely father's blood was spilt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"By him King Desiderius shall be pressed,\nThe valiant leader of the Lombard horde:\nAnd of the fiefs of Calaon and Este;\nFor this imperial Charles shall make him lord.\nHubert, thy grandson, comes behind; the best\nOf Italy, with arms and belted sword:\nWho shall defend the church from barbarous foes,\nAnd more than once assure her safe repose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alberto next, unconquered captain, see,\nWhose trophies shall so many fanes array.\nHugh, the bold son, is with the sire, and he\nShall conquer Milan, and the snakes display.\nAzo, that next approaching form shall be,\nAnd, his good brother dead, the Insubri sway.\nLo!  Albertazo!  by whose rede undone,\nSee Berengarius banished, and his son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With him shall the imperial Otho join\nIn wedlock worthily his daughter fair.\nAnd lo!  another Hugh!  O noble line!\nO!  sire succeeded by an equal heir!\nHe, thwarting with just cause their ill design,\nShall thrash the Romans' pride who overbear;\nShall from their hands the sovereign pontiff take,\nWith the third Otho, and their leaguer break."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"See Fulke, who to his brother will convey\nAll his Italian birth-right, and command\nTo take a mighty dukedom far away\nFrom his fair home, in Almayn's northern land.\nThere he the house of Saxony shall stay,\nAnd prop the ruin with his saving hand;\nThis in his mother's right he shall possess,\nAnd with his progeny maintain and bless."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"More famed for courtesy than warlike deed,\nAzo the second, he who next repairs!\nBertoldo and Albertazo are his seed:\nAnd, lo!  the father walkes between his heirs.\nBy Parma's walls I see the Germans bleed,\nTheir second Henry quelled; such trophy bears\nThe one renowned in story's future page:\nThe next shall wed Matilda, chaste and sage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His virtues shall deserve so fair a flower,\n(And in his age, I wot, no common grace)\nTo hold the half of Italy in dower,\nWith that descendent of first Henry's race.\nRinaldo shall succeed him in his power,\nPledge of Bertoldo's wedded love, and chase\nFierce Frederick Barbarossa's hireling bands,\nSaving the church from his rapacious hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Another Azo rules Verona's town,\nWith its fair fields; and two great chiefs this while\n(One wears the papal, one the imperial crown),\nThe baron, Marquis of Ancona style.\nBut to show all who rear the gonfalon\nOf the consistory, amid that file,\nWere task too long; as long to tell each deed\nAchieved for Rome by thy devoted seed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"See Fulke and Obyson, more Azos, Hughs!\nBoth Henrys! — mark the father and his boy.\nTwo Guelphs: the first fair Umbria's land subdues,\nAnd shall Spoleto's ducal crown enjoy.\nBehold the princely phantom that ensues,\nShall turn fair Italy's long grief to joy;\nI speak of the fifth Azo of thy strain,\nBy whom shall Ezelin be quelled and slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Fierce Ezelin, that most inhuman lord,\nWho shall be deemed by men a child of hell.\nAnd work such evil, thinning with the sword\nWho in Ausonia's wasted cities dwell;\nRome shall no more her Anthony record,\nHer Marius, Sylla, Nero, Cajus fell.\nAnd this fifth Azo shall to scathe and shame\nPut Frederick, second Caeser of the name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, with his better sceptre well contented,\nShall rule the city, seated by the streams,\nWhere Phoebus to his plaintive lyre lamented\nThe son, ill-trusted with the father's beams;\nWhere Cygnus spread his pinions, and the scented\nAmber was wept, as fabling poet dreams.\nTo him such honour shall the church decree;\nFit guerdon of his works, and valour's fee."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But does no laurel for his brother twine,\nAldobrandino, who will carry cheer\nTo Rome (when Otho, with the Ghibelline,\nInto the troubled capital strikes fear),\nAnd make the Umbri and Piceni sign\nTheir shame, and sack the cities far and near;\nThen hopeless to relieve the sacred hold,\nSue to the neighbouring Florentine for gold:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And trust a noble brother to his hands,\nBoasting no dearer pledge, the pact to bind:\nAnd next, victorious o'er the German bands,\nGive his triumphant ensigns to the wind:\nTo the afflicted church restore her lands,\nAnd take due vengeance of Celano's kind.\nThen die, cut off in manhood's early flower,\nBeneath the banners of the Papal power?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, dying, leaves his brother Azo heir\nOf Pesaro and fair Ancona's reign,\nAnd all the cities which 'twixt Tronto are,\nAnd green Isauro's stream, from mount to main;\nWith other heritage, more rich and rare,\nGreatness of mind, and faith without a strain.\nAll else is Fortune's in this mortal state;\nBut Virtue soars beyond her love and hate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In good Rinaldo equal worth shall shine,\n(Such is the promise of his early fire)\nIf such a hope of thine exalted line.\nDark Fate and Fortune wreck not in their ire.\nAlas!  from Naples in this distant shrine,\nNaples, where he is hostage for his sire,\nHis dirge is heard: A stripling of thy race,\nYoung Obyson, shall fill his grandsire's place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This lord to his dominion shall unite\nGay Reggio, joined to Modena's bold land.\nAnd his redoubted valour lend such light,\nThe willing people call him to command.\nSixth of the name, his Azo rears upright\nThe church's banner in his noble hand:\nFair Adria's fief to him in dower shall bring\nThe child of second Charles, Sicilia's king."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Behold in yonder friendly group agreed.\nMany fair princes of illustrious name;\nObyson, Albert famed for pious deed,\nAldobrandino, Nicholas the lame.\nBut we may pass them by, for better speed,\nFaenza conquered, and their feats and fame;\nWith Adria (better held and surer gain)\nWhich gives her title to the neighbouring main:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And that fair town, whose produce is the rose,\nThe rose which gives it name in Grecian speech:\nThat, too, which fishy marshes round enclose,\nAnd Po's two currents threat with double breach;\nWhose townsmen loath the lazy calm's repose,\nAnd pray that stormy waves may lash the beach.\nI pass, mid towns and towers, a countless store,\nArgenta, Lugo, and a thousand more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"See Nicholas, whom in his tender age,\nThe willing people shall elect their lord;\nHe who shall laugh to scorn the civil rage\nOf the rebellious Tideus and his horde;\nWhose infantine delight shall be to wage\nThe mimic fight, and sweat with spear and sword:\nAnd through the discipline such nurture yields,\nShall flourish as the flower of martial fields."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"By him rebellious plans are overthrown,\nAnd turned upon the rash contriver's head;\nAnd so each stratagem of warfare blown,\nThat vainly shall the cunning toils be spread.\nTo the third Otho this too late is known,\nOf Parma and the pleasant Reggio dread;\nWho shall by him be spoiled in sudden strife,\nOf his possessions and his wretched life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And still the fair dominion shall increase,\nAnd without wrong its spreading bounds augment;\nNor its glad subjects violate the peace,\nUnless provoked some outrage to resent,\nAnd hence its wealth and welfare shall not cease;\nAnd the Divine Disposer be content\nTo let it flourish (such his heavenly love!)\nWhile the celestial spheres revolve above."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  Lionel!  lo!  Borse great and kind!\nFirst duke of thy fair race, his realm's delight;\nWho reigns secure, and shall more triumphs find\nIn peace, than warlike princes win in fight.\nWho struggling Fury's hands shall tie behind\nHer back, and prison Mars, removed from sight.\nHis fair endeavours bent to bless and stay\nThe people, that his sovereign rule obey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  Hercules, who may reproach his neighbour,\nWith foot half burnt, and halting gait and slow,\nThat at Budrio, with protecting sabre,\nHe saved his troops from fatal overthrow;\nNot that, for guerdon of his glorious labour,\nHe should distress and vex him as a foe;\nChased into Barco.  It were hard to say,\nIf most he shine in peace or martial fray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lucania, Puglia, and Calabria's strand,\nShall with the rumour of his prowess ring:\nWhere he shall strive in duel, hand to hand,\nAnd gain the praise of Catalonia's king.\nHim, with the wisest captains of the land\nHis worth shall class; such fame his actions bring;\nAnd he the fief shall win like valiant knight,\nWhich thirty years before was his of right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To him his grateful city owes a debt,\nThe greatest subjects to their lord can owe;\nNot that he moves her from a marsh, to set\nHer stones, where Ceres' fruitful treasures grow.\nNor that he shall enlarge her bounds, nor yet\nThat he shall fence her walls against the foe;\nNor that he theatre and dome repairs,\nAnd beautifies her streets and goodly squares;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not that he keeps his lordship well defended\nFrom the winged lions' claws and fierce attacks;\nNor that, when Gallic ravage is extended,\nAnd the invader all Italia sacks,\nHis happy state alone is unoffended;\nUnharassed, and ungalled by toll or tax.\nNot for these blessings I recount, and more\nHis grateful realm shall Hercules adore;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So much as that from him shall spring a pair\nOf brothers, leagued no less by love than blood;\nWho shall be all that Leda's children were;\nThe just Alphonso, Hippolite the good.\nAnd as each twin resigned the vital air\nHis fellow to redeem from Stygian flood,\nSo each of these would gladly spend his breath,\nAnd for his brother brave perpetual death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In these two princes' excellent affection,\nTheir happy lieges more assurance feel,\nThan if their noble town, for its protection,\nWere girded twice by Vulcan's works of steel.\nAnd so Alphonso in his good direction,\nJustice, with knowledge and with love, shall deal,\nAstrea shall appear returned from heaven,\nTo this low earth to varying seasons given."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Well is it that his wisdom shines as bright\nAs his good sire's, nor is his valour less;\nSince here usurping Venice arms for fight,\nAnd her full troops his scanty numbers press,\nThere she (I know not if more justly hight\nMother or stepmother brings new distress; ) \n\nBut, if a mother, scarce to him more mild\nThan Progue or Medea to her child."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This chief, what time soever he shall go\nForth with his faithful crew, by night or day,\nBy water or by land, will shame the foe,\nWith memorable rout and disarray;\nAnd this too late Romagna's sons shall know.\nLed against former friends in bloody fray,\nWho shall bedew the campaign with their blood,\nBy Santern, Po, and Zaniolus' flood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This shall the Spaniard know, to his dismay,\n'Mid the same bounds, whom papal gold shall gain,\nWho shall from him Bastia win and slay,\nWith cruel rage, her hapless Castellain,\nThe city taken; but shall dearly pay;\nHis crime, the town retrieved, and victor slain:\nSince in the rescued city not a groom\nIs left alive, to bear the news to Rome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'Tis he, who with his counsel and his lance,\nShall win the honours of Romagna's plain,\nAnd open to the chivalry of France\nThe victory over Julius, leagued with Spain.\nPaunch-deep in human blood shall steeds advance\nIn that fierce strife, and struggle through the slain,\n'Mid crowded fields, which scarce a grace supply,\nWhere Greek, Italian, Frank, and Spaniard die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  who in priestly vesture clad, is crowned\nWith purple hat, conferred in hallowed dome!\n'Tis he, the wise, the liberal, the renowned\nHippolitus, great cardinal of Rome;\nWhose actions shall in every region sound,\nWhere'er the honoured muse shall find a home:\nTo whose glad era, by indulgent heaven,\nAs to Augustus' is a Maro given."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His deeds adorn his race, as from his car\nThe glorious sun illumes the subject earth\nMore than the silver moon or lesser star;\nSo far all others he transcends in worth.\nI see this captain, ill bested for war,\nGo forth afflicted, and return in mirth:\nBacked by few foot, and fewer cavaliers,\nHe homeward barks, and fifteen gallies steers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Two Sigismonds, the first, the second, see;\nTo these Alphonso's five good sons succeed;\nWhose glories spread o'er seas and land shall be.\nThe first shall wed a maid of France's seed.\nThis is the second Hercules; and he,\n(That you may know their every name and deed),\nHippolitus; who with the light shall shine,\nOf his wise uncle, gilding all his line."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Francis the third comes next; the other two\nAlphonsos both; — but yet again I say,\nThy line through all its branches to pursue,\nFair virgin, would too long protract thy stay;\nAnd Phoebus, many times, to mortal view,\nWould quench and light again the lamp of day.\nThen, with thy leave, 'tis time the pageant cease,\nAnd I dismiss the shades and hold my peace.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So with the lady's leave the volume closed,\nWhose precepts to her will the spirits bent.\nAnd they, where Merlin's ancient bones reposed,\nFrom the first cavern disappearing, went.\nThen Bradamant her eager lips unclosed,\nSince the divine enchantress gave consent;\n\"And who,\" she cried, \"that pair of sorrowing mien,\nAlphonso and Hippolitus between?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sighing, those youths advanced amid the show,\nTheir brows with shame and sorrow overcast,\nWith downward look, and gait subdued and slow:\nI saw the brothers shun them as they passed.\"\nMelissa heard the dame with signs of woe,\nAnd thus, with streaming eyes, exclaim'd at last:\n\"Ah! luckless youths, with vain illusions fed,\nWhither by wicked men's bad counsel led!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O, worthy seed of Hercules the good,\nLet not their guilt beyond thy love prevail;\nAlas!  the wretched pair are of thy blood,\nSo many prevailing pity turn the scale!\"\nAnd in a sad and softer tone pursued,\n\"I will not further press the painful tale.\nChew on fair fancy's food: Nor deem unmeet\nI will not with a bitter chase the sweet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Soon as to-morrow's sun shall gild the skies\nWith his first light, myself the way will show\nTo where the wizard knight Rogero sties;\nAnd built with polished steel the ramparts glow:\nSo long as through deep woods thy journey lies,\nTill, at the sea arrived, I shall bestow\nSuch new instructions for the future way,\nThat thou no more shalt need Melissa's stay.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All night the maid reposes in the cave,\nAnd the best part in talk with Merlin spends;\nWhile with persuasive voice the wizard grave\nTo her Rogero's honest love commends;\nTill from the vault goes forth that virgin brave,\nAs through the sky the rising sun ascends,\nBy path, long space obscure on either side,\nThe weird woman still her faithful guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They gain a hidden glen, which heights inclose,\nAnd mountains inaccessible to man:\nAnd they all day toil on, without repose,\nWhere precipices frowned and torrents ran.\nAnd (what may some diversion interpose)\nSweet subjects of discourse together scan,\nIn conference, which best might make appear\nThe rugged road less dismal and severe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of these the greater portion served to guide\n(Such the wise woman's scope the warlike dame; ) \n\nAnd teach by what device might be untied\nRogero's gyves, if stedfast were her flame.\n\"If thou wert Mars himself, or Pallas,\" cried\nThe sage Melissa, \"though with thee there came\nMore than King Charles or Agramant command,\nAgainst the wizard foe thou could'st not stand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Besides that it is walled about with steel,\nAnd inexpugnable his tower, and high;\nBesides that his swift horse is taught to wheel,\nAnd caracol and gallop in mid sky,\nHe bears a mortal shield of power to seal,\nAs soon as 'tis exposed, the dazzled eye;\nAnd so invades each sense, the splendour shed,\nThat he who sees the blaze remains as dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And lest to shut thine eyes, thou should'st suppose\nMight serve, contending with the wizard knight;\nHow would'st thou know, when both in combat close,\nWhen he strikes home, or when eschews the fight?\nBut to escape the blaze which blinds his foes,\nAnd render vain each necromantic sleight,\nHave here a speedy mean which cannot miss;\nNor can the world afford a way but this."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"King Agramant of Africa a ring.\nThieved from an Indian queen by subtle guiles,\nHas to a baron of his following\nConsigned, who now precedes us by few miles;\nBrunello he.  Who wears the gift shall bring\nTo nought all sorceries and magic wiles.\nIn thefts and cheats Brunello is as well\nInstructed, as the sage in charm and spell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Brunello, he so practised and so sly\nAs now I tell thee, by his king is sent,\nThat he with aid of mother wit may try,\nAnd of this ring, well proved in like event,\nTo take Rogero from the castle high;\nSo has he boasted, by the wizard pent:\nAnd to his lord such promise did impart,\nWho has Rogero's presence most at heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That his escape to thee alone may owe,\nNot to the king, the youthful cavalier,\nHow to release Rogero from his foe\nAnd his enchanted cage, prepare to hear.\nThree days along the shingle shalt thou go,\nBeside the sea, whose waves will soon appear;\nThee the third day shall to a hostel bring,\nWhere he shall come who bears the virtuous ring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That thou may'st recognise the man, in height\nLess than six palms, observe one at this inn\nOf black and curly hair, the dwarfish wight!\nBeard overgrown about the cheek and chin;\nWith shaggy brow, swoln eyes, and cloudy sight,\nA nose close flattened, and a sallow skin;\nTo this, that I may make my sketch complete,\nSuccinctly clad, like courier, goes the cheat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thy conversation with this man shall turn\nUpon enchantment, spell, and mystic pact;\nAnd thou shalt, in thy talk, appear to yearn\nTo prove the wizard's strength, as is the fact.\nBut, lady, let him not thy knowledge learn\nOf his good ring, which mars all magic act:\nHe shall propose to bring thee as a guide\nTo the tall castle, whither thou would'st ride."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Follow him close, and viewing (for a sign),\nNow near, the fortress of the enchanter hoar;\nLet no false pity there thy mind incline\nTo stay the execution of my lore.\nGive him his death; but let him not divine\nThy thought, nor grant him respite; for before\nThine eyes, concealed by it, the caitiff slips\nIf once he place the ring between his lips.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Discoursing thus, they came upon the sea\nWhere Garonne near fair Bordeaux meets the tide;\nHere, fellow travellers no more to be,\nSome natural tears they drop and then divide.\nDuke Aymon's child, who slumbers not till she\nRelease her knight, holds on till even-tide:\n'Twas then the damsel at a hostel rested,\nWhere Sir Brunello was already guested."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The maid Brunello knows as soon as found\n(So was his image on her mind impressed),\nAnd asks him whence he came, and whither bound;\nAnd he replies and lies, as he is pressed.\nThe dame, who is forewarned, and knows her ground,\nFeigns too as well as he, and lies her best:\nAnd changes sex and sect, and name and land,\nAnd her quick eye oft glances at his hand;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oft glances at his resless hand, in fear\nThat he might undetected make some prize;\nNor ever lets the knave approach too near,\nWell knowing his condition: In this guise\nThe couple stand together, when they hear\nA sudden sound:  but what that sound implies\nI, sir, shall tell hereafter with its cause;\nBut first shall break my song with fitting pause."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 4"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The old Atlantes suffers fatal wreck,\nFoiled by the ring, and young Rogero freed,\nWho soars in air till he appears a speck,\nMounted upon the wizard's winged steed.\nObediant to the royal Charles's beck,\nHe who had followed Love's imperious lead,\nRinaldo, disembarks on British land,\nAnd saves Genevra, doomed to stake and brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though an ill mind appear in simulation,\nAnd, for the most, such quality offends;\n'Tis plain that this in many a situation\nIs found to further beneficial ends,\nAnd save from blame, and danger, and vexation;\nSince we converse not always with our friends,\nIn this, less clear than clouded, mortal life,\nBeset with snares, and full of envious strife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If after painful proof we scarcely find\nA real friend, through various chances sought,\nTo whom we may communicate our mind,\nKeeping no watch upon our wandering thought;\nWhat should the young Rogero's lady kind\nDo with Brunello, not sincere, but fraught\nWith treasons manifold, and false and tainted,\nAs by the good enchantress truly painted?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She feigns as well with that deceitful scout;\n(Fitting with him the father of all lies)\nWatches his thievish hands in fear and doubt;\nAnd follows every motion with her eyes.\nWhen lo!  a mighty noise is heard without!\n\"O mighty mother!  king of heaven!\" she cries,\n\"What thing is this I hear?\" and quickly springs\nTowards the place from whence the larum rings,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And sees the host and all his family,\nWhere, one to door, and one to window slips,\nWith eyes upturned and gazing at the sky,\nAs if to witness comet or eclipse.\nAnd there the lady views, with wondering eye,\nWhat she had scarce believed from other's lips,\nA feathered courser, sailing through the rack,\nWho bore an armed knight upon his back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Broad were his pinions, and of various hue;\nSeated between, a knight the saddle pressed,\nClad in steel arms, which wide their radiance threw,\nHis wonderous course directed to the west:\nThere dropt among the mountains lost to view.\nAnd this was, as that host informed his guest,\n(And true the tale a sorcerer, who made ) \n\nNow farther, now more near, his frequent raid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, sometimes towering, soars into the skies;\nThen seems, descending, but to skim the ground:\nAnd of all beauteous women makes a prize,\nWho, to their mischief, in these parts are found.\nHence, whether in their own or other's eyes,\nEsteemed as fair, the wretched damsels round,\n(And all in fact the felon plunders hine; ) \n\nAs fearing of the sun to be descried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A castle on the Pyrenean height\nThe necromancer keeps, the work of spell.\"\n(The host relates \"of steel, so fair and bright, ) \n\nAll nature cannot match the wonderous shell.\nThere many cavaliers, to prove their might,\nHave gone, but none returned the tale to tell.\nSo that I doubt, fair sir, the thief enthralls\nOr slays whoever in the encounter falls.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The watchful maid attends to every thing,\nGlad at her heart, and trusting to complete\n(What she shall compass by the virtuous ring)\nThe downfall of the enchanter and his seat.\nThen to the host — \"A guide I pray thee bring,\nWho better knows than me the thief's retreat.\nSo burns my heart. (nor can I choose but go)\nTo strive in battle with this wizard foe.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"It shall not need,\" exclaimed the dwarfish Moor,\n\"For I, myself, will serve you as a guide;\nWho have the road set down, with other lore,\nSo that you shall rejoice with me to ride.\"\nHe meant the ring, but further hint forbore;\nLest dearly he the avowed should abide.\nAnd she to him — \"Your guidance gives me pleasure.\"\nMeaning by this she hoped to win his treasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What useful was to say, she said, and what\nMight hurt her with the Saracen, concealed.\nWell suited to her ends, the host had got\nA palfrey, fitting for the road or field.\nShe bought the steed, and as Aurora shot\nHer rosy rays, rode forth with spear and shield:\nAnd maid and courier through a valley wind,\nBrunello now before and now behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From wood to wood, from mount to mountain hoar,\nThey clomb a summit, which in cloudless sky\nDiscovers France and Spain, and either shore.\nAs from a peak of Apennine the eye\nMay Tuscan and Sclavonian sea explore,\nThere, whence we journey to Camaldoli.\nThen through a rugged path and painful wended,\nWhich thence into a lowly vale descended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A rock from that deep valley's centre springs;\nBright walls of steel about its summit go:\nAnd this as high that airy summit flings,\nAs it leaves all the neighbouring cliffs below.\nHe may not scale the height who has not wings,\nAnd vainly would each painful toil bestow.\n\"Lo!  where his prisoners!\"  Sir Brunello cries,\n\"Ladies and cavaliers, the enchanter sties.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scarped smooth upon four parts, the mountain bare\nSeemed fashioned with the plumb, by builder's skill\nNor upon any side was path or stair,\nWhich furnished man the means to climb the hill.\nThe castle seemed the very nest and lair\nOf animal, supplied with plume and quill.\nAnd here the damsel knows 'tis time to slay\nThe wily dwarf, and take the ring away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But deems it foul, with blood of man to stain\nUnarmed and of so base a sort, her brand;\nFor well, without his death, she may obtain\nThe costly ring; and so suspends her hand.\nBrunello, off his guard, with little pain,\nShe seized, and strongly bound with girding band:\nThen to a lofty fir made fast the string;\nBut from his finger first withdrew the ring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Neither by tears, nor groans, nor sound of woe,\nTo move the stedfast maid the dwarf had power:\nShe down the rugged hill descended slow,\nUntil she reached the plain beneath the tower.\nThen gave her bugle breath, the keep below,\nTo call the castled wizard to the stower:\nAnd when the sound was finished, threatening cried,\nAnd called him to the combat and defied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not long within his gate the enchanter stayed,\nAfter he heard the voice and bugle ring.\nAgainst the foe, who seemed a man, arrayed\nIn arms, with him the horse is on the wing.\nBut his appearance well consoled the maid,\nWho, with small cause for fear, beheld him bring\nNor mace, nor rested lance, nor bitting sword,\nWherewith the corselet might be bruised or gored."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On his left arm alone his shield he took,\nCovered all o'er with silk of crimson hue;\nIn his right-hand he held an open book,\nWhence, as the enchanter read, strange wonder grew:\nFor often times, to sight, the lance he shook;\nAnd flinching eyelids could not hide the view;\nWith tuck or mace he seemed to smite the foe:\nBut sate aloof and had not struck a blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No empty fiction wrought by magic lore,\nBut natural was the steed the wizard pressed;\nFor him a filly to griffin bore;\nHight hippogryph.  In wings and beak and crest,\nFormed like his sire, as in the feet before;\nBut like the mare, his dam, in all the rest.\nSuch on Riphaean hills, though rarely found,\nAre bred, beyond the frozen ocean's bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Drawn by enchantment from his distant lair,\nThe wizard thought but how to tame the foal;\nAnd, in a month, instructed him to bear\nSaddle and bit, and gallop to the goal;\nAnd execute on earth or in mid air,\nAll shifts of manege, course and caracole;\nHe with such labour wrought.  This only real,\nWhere all the rest was hollow and ideal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This truth by him with fictions was combined,\nWhose sleight passed red for yellow, black for white:\nBut all his vain enchantments could not blind\nThe maid, whose virtuous ring assured her sight:\nYet she her blows discharges at the wind;\nAnd spurring here and there prolongs the fight.\nSo drove or wheeled her steed, and smote at nought,\nAnd practised all she had before been taught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she sometime had fought upon her horse,\nShe from the courser on her feet descends:\nTo compass and more freely put in force,\nAs by the enchantress schooled, her wily ends.\nThe wizard, to display his last resource,\nUnweeting the defence, towards her wends.\nHe bares the shield, secure to blind his foe,\nAnd by the magic light, astonished, throw."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The shield might have been shown at first, nor he\nNeeded to keep the cavaliers at bay;\nBut that he loved some master-stroke to see,\nAchieved by lance or sword in single fray.\nAs with the captive mouse, in sportive glee,\nThe wily cat is sometimes seen to play;\nTill waxing wroth, or weary of her prize,\nShe bites, and at a snap the prisoner dies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To cat and mouse, in battles fought before,\nI liken the magician and his foes;\nBut the comparison holds good no more:\nFor, with the ring, the maid against him goes;\nFirm and attentive still, and watching sore,\nLest upon her the wizard should impose:\nAnd as she sees him bare the wondrous shield,\nCloses her eyes and falls upon the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not that the shining metal could offend,\nAs wont those others, from its cover freed;\nBut so the damsel did, to make descend\nThe vain enchanter from his wondrous steed.\nNor was in ought defeated of her end;\nFor she no sooner on the grassy mead\nHad laid her head, than wheeling widely round,\nThe flying courser pitched upon the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already cased again, the shield was hung,\nBy the magician, at his sadle bow.\nHe lights and seeks her, who like wolf among\nThe bushes, couched in thicket, waits the roe;\nShe without more delay from ambush sprung,\nAs he drew near, and grappled fast the foe.\nThat wretched man, the volume by whose aid\nHe all his battles fought, on earth had laid:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And ran to bind her with a chain, which he,\nGirt round about him for such a purpose, wore;\nBecause he deemed she was no less to be\nMastered and bound than those subdued before.\nHim hath the dame already flung; by me\nExcused with reason, if he strove not more.\nFor fearful were the odds between that bold\nAnd puissant maid, and warrior weak and old!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Intending to behead the fallen foe,\nShe lifts her conquering hand; but in mid space,\nWhen she beholds his visage, stops the blow,\nAs if disdaining a revenge so base.\nShe sees in him, her prowess has laid low,\nA venerable sire, with sorrowing face;\nWhose hair and wrinkles speak him, to her guess,\nOf years six score and ten, or little less."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Kill me, for love of God!\" (afflicted sore,\nThe old enchanter full of wrath did cry).\nBut the victorious damsel was not more\nAverse to kill, than he was bent to die.\nTo know who was the necromancer hoar\nThe gentle lady had desire, and why\nThe tower he in that savage place designed,\nDoing such outrage foul to all mankind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor I, by malice moved, alas!  poor wight,\"\n(The weeping necromancer answer made,)\n\"Built the fair castle on the rocky height,\nNor yet for rapine ply the robber's trade;\nBut only to redeem a gentle knight\nFrom danger sore and death, by love was swayed;\nWho, as the skies foreshow, in little season,\nIs doomed to die a Christian, and by treason."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The sun beholds not 'twixt the poles, a Child\nSo excellent as him, and passing fair;\nWho from his infancy, Rogero styled,\n(Atlantes I was tutored by my care. ) \n\nBy love of fame and evil stars beguiled,\nHe follows into France Troyano's heir.\nHim, in my eyes, than son esteemed more dear,\nI seek to snatch from France and peril near."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I only built the beauteous keep to be\nRogero's dungeon, safely harboured there;\nWho whilom was subdued in fight by me,\nAs I to-day had hoped thyself to snare,\nAnd dames and knights, and more of high degree,\nHave to this tower conveyed, his lot to share,\nThat with such partners of his prison pent,\nHe might the loss of freedom less lament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Save they should seek to break their dungeon's bound,\nI grant my inmates every other pleasure.\nFor whatsoever in the world is found,\nSearch its four quarters, in this keep I treasure;\n(Whatever heart can wish or tongue can sound)\nCates, brave attire, game, sport, or mirthful measure.\nMy field well sown, I well had reaped my grain.\nBut that thy coming makes my labour vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  then unless thy heart less beauteous be\nThan thy sweet face, mar not my pious care;\nTake my steel buckler, this I give to thee,\nAnd take that horse, which flies so fast in air,\nNor meddle with my castle more; or free\nOne or two captive friends, the rest forbear —\nOr (for I crave but this release them all, ) \n\nSo that Rogero but remain my thrall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Or if disposed to take him from my sight,\nBefore the youth be into France conveyed,\nBe pleased to free my miserable sprite\nFrom its now rotted bark, long decayed.\"\n\"Prate as thou wilt, I shall restore the knight\nTo liberty,\"  replied the martial maid,\n\"Nor offer shield and courser to resign,\nWhich are not in thy gift, — already mine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor were they thine to take or to bestow,\nWould it appear that such exchange were wise;\nThou sayest to save him from what stars foreshow,\nAnd cheat an evil influence of the skies\nRogero is confined.  Thou canst not know,\nOr knowing, canst not change his destinies:\nFor, if unknown an ill so near to thee,\nFar less mayest thou another's fate foresee."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Seek not thy death from me; for the petition\nIs made in vain; but if for death thou sigh,\nThough the whole world refused the requisition,\nA soul resolved would find the means to die.\nBut ope thy gates to give thy guests dismission\nBefore thine hand the knot of life untie.\"\nSo spake the scornful dame with angry mock,\nSpeeding her captive still towards the rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Round by the conqueror with the chain he bore,\nAtlantes walked, the damsel following nigh,\nWho trusted not to the magician hoar,\nAlthough he seemed subdued in port and eye.\nNor many paces went the pair, before\nThey at the mountain's foot the cleft espy,\nWith steps by which the rugged hill to round;\nAnd climb, till to the castle-gate they wound:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Atlantes from the threshold, graved by skill,\nWith characters and wondrous signs, upturned\nA virtuous stone, where, underneath the sill,\nPots, with perpetual fire and secret, burned.\nThe enchanter breaks them; and at once the hill\nTo an inhospitable rock is turned.\nNor wall nor tower on any side is seen,\nAs if no castle there had ever been."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then from the lady's toils the wizard clears\nHis limbs, as thrush escapes the fowler's snare;\nWith him as well his castle disappears,\nAnd leaves the prisoned troop in open air;\nFrom their gay lodgings, dames and cavaliers,\nUnhoused upon that desert, bleak and bare.\nAnd many at the freedom felt annoy,\nWhich dispossessed them of such life of joy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There is Gradasso, there is Sacripant,\nThere is Prasildo, noble cavalier,\nWho with Rinaldo came from the Levant;\nIroldo, too, Prasildo's friend sincere.\nAnd there, at last, the lovely Bradamant\nDiscerns Rogero, long desired and dear;\nWho, when assured it was that lady, flew\nWith joyful cheer to greet the damsel true;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As her he prized before his eyes, his heart,\nHis life; from that day cherished when she stood\nUncasqued for him, and from the fight apart;\nAnd hence an arrow drank her virgin blood.\n'Twere long to tell who launched the cruel dart,\nAnd how the lovers wandered in the wood;\nNow guided by the sun, and now benighted,\nHere first since that encounter reunited."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now that the stripling sees her here, and knows\nAlone she freed him from the wizard's nest,\nHe deems, his bosom with such joy overflows,\nThat he is singly fortunate and blest.\nThither, where late the damsel conquered, goes\nThe band, descending from the mountain's crest;\nAnd finds the hippogryph, who bore the shield,\nBut in its case of crimson silk concealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To take him by the rein the lady there\nApproached, and he stood fast till she was nigh,\nThen spread his pinions to the liquid air,\nAnd at short distance lit, half-mountain high:\nAnd, as she follows him with fruitless care,\nNot longer flight nor shorter will he try.\n'Tis thus the raven, on some sandy beach,\nLures on the dog, and flits beyond his reach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gradasso, Sacripant, Rogero, who\nWith all those other knights below were met,\nWhere'er, they hope he may return, pursue\nThe beast, and up and down, each pass beset.\nHe having led those others, as he flew,\nOften to rocky height, and bottom wet,\nAmong the rocks of the moist valley dropt,\nAnd at short distance from Rogero stopt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was Atlantes the enchanter's deed,\nWhose pious wishes still directed were,\nTo see Rogero from his peril freed:\nThis was his only thought, his only care;\nWho for such end dispatched the winged steed,\nHim out of Europe by this sleight to bear.\nRogero took his bridle, but in vain;\nFor he was restive to the guiding rein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now the bold youth from his Frontino flings\n(Frontino was his gentle courser hight)\nThen leaps on him who towers in air, and stings\nAnd goads his haughty heart with rowels bright.\nHe runs a short career; then upward springs.\nAnd through mid ether soars a fairer flight\nThan hawk, from which the falconer plucks away\nIn time the blinding hood, and points her prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When her Rogero the fair dame discerned,\nIn fearful peril, soar so high a strain,\nShe stood long space amazed, ere she returned\nTo her right judgement, and sound wits again:\nAnd what she erst of Ganymede had learned,\nSnatched up to heaven from his paternal reign,\nFeared might befall the stripling, born through air,\nAs gentle as young Ganymede and fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She on Rogero looks with stedfast eyes\nAs long as feeble sight can serve her use;\nAnd in her mind next tracks him through the skies,\nWhen sight in vain the cherished youth pursues.\nAnd still renewing tears, and groans, and sighs,\nWill not afford her sorrow peace or truce.\nAfter the knight had vanished from her view,\nHer eyes she on the good Frontino threw."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And lest the courser should become the prey\nOf the first traveller, who passed the glen,\nHim will not leave; but thence to bear away\nResolves, in trust to see his lord again.\nThe griffin soars, nor can Rogero stay\nThe flying courser; while, beneath his ken,\nEach peak and promontory sinks in guise,\nThat he discerns not flat from mountain-rise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the hippogryph has won such height,\nThat he is lessened to a point, he bends\nHis course for where the sun, with sinking light,\nWhen he goes round the heavenly crab, descends;\nAnd shoots through air, like well-greased bark and light,\nWhich through the sea a wind propitious sends.\nHim leave we on his way, who well shall speed,\nAnd turn we to Rinaldo in his need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Day after day the good Rinaldo fares,\nForced by the wind, the spacious ocean through;\nNow westward borne, and now toward the Bears;\nFor night and day the ceaseless tempest blew.\nScotland at last her dusky coast uprears,\nAnd gives the Caledonian wood to view;\nWhich, through its shadowy groves of ancient oak,\nOft echoes to the champion's sturdy stroke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through this roves many a famous cavalier,\nRenowned for feat in arms, of British strain;\nAnd throng from distant land, or country near,\nFrench, Norse, of German knights, a numerous train.\nLet none, save he be valiant, venture here,\nWhere, seeking glory, death may be his gain.\nHere Arthur, Galahalt, and Gauvaine fought,\nAnd well Sir Launcelot and Tristram wrought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And other worthies of the table round;\n(Of either table, whether old or new)\nWhose trophies yet remain upon the ground;\nProof of their valiant feats, Rinaldo true\nForthwith his armour and Bayardo found,\nAnd landed on the woody coast: The crew\nHe bade, with all the haste they might, repair\nTo Berwick's neighbouring port, and wait him there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Without a guide or company he went\nThrough that wide forest; choosing now this way,\nNow that, now other, as it might present\nHope of adventurous quest or hard assay:\nAnd, ere the first day's circling sun is spent,\nThe peer is guested in an abbey gray:\nWhich spends much wealth in harbouring those who claim\nIts shelter, warlike knight or wandering dame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The monks and abbot to Mount Alban's peer\nA goodly welcome in their house accord;\nWho asked, but not before with savoury cheer\nHe amply had his wearied strength restored,\nIf in that tract, by errant cavalier,\nOften adventurous quest might be explored,\nIn which a man might prove, by dangerous deed,\nIf blame or glory were his fitting meed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They answered, in those woods he might be sure\nMany and strange adventures would be found;\nBut deeds, there wrought, were, like the place, obscure,\nAnd, for the greater part, not bruited round.\n\"Then seek (they said a worthier quest, secure ) \n\nYour works will not be buried underground.\nSo that the glorious act achieved, as due,\nFame may your peril and your pain pursue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if you would your warlike worth assay,\nPrepare the worthiest enterprize to hear,\nThat, e'er in times of old or present day,\nWas undertaken by a cavalier.\nOur monarch's daughter needs some friendly stay,\nNow sore bested, against a puissant peer:\nLurcanio is the doughty baron's name,\nWho would bereave her both of life and fame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her he before her father does pursue,\nPerchance yet more for hatred than for right;\nAnd vouches, to a gallery she updrew\nA lover, seen by him, at dead of night.\nHence death by fire will be the damsel's due,\nSuch is our law, unless some champion fight\nOn her behalf, and, ere a month go by,\n(Nigh spent upon the accuser prove the lie. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Our impious Scottish law, severe and dread,\nWills, that a woman, whether low or high\nHer state, who takes a man into her bed,\nExcept her husband, for the offence shall die.\nNor is there hope of ransom for her head,\nUnless to her defence some warrior hie;\nAnd as her champion true, with spear and shield,\nMaintain her guiltless in the listed field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The king, sore grieving for Geneura bright,\nFor such is his unhappy daughter's name,\nProclaims by town and city, that the knight\nWho shall deliver her from death and shame,\nHe to the royal damsel will unite,\nWith dower, well suited to a royal dame;\nSo that the valiant warrior who has stood\nIn her defence, be come of gentle blood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if within a month no knight appear,\nOr coming, conquer not, the damsel dies.\nA like emrpize were worthier of your spear\nThan wandering through these woods in lowly guise.\nBesides, the eternal trophy you shall rear,\nYou by the deed shall gain a glorious prize,\nThe sweetest flower of all the ladies fair\nThat betwixt Ind and Atlas' pillars are."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And you with wealth and state shall guerdoned be,\nSo that you evermore may live content,\nAnd the king's grace, if through your means he see\nHis honour raised anew, now well-nigh spent.\nBesides, you by the laws of chivalry\nAre bound to venge the damsel foully shent.\nFor she, whose life is by such treason sought,\nIs chaste and spotless in the common thought.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo mused awhile, and then replied,\n\"And must a gentle damsel die by fire,\nBecause she with a lover's wish complied,\nAnd quenched within her arms his fond desire?\nCursed be the law by which the dame is tried!\nCursed he who would permit a doom so dire!\nPerish (such fate were just! who cruel proves! ) \n\nNot she that life bestows on him who loves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Or true or false Geneura's tale of shame;\nIf she her lover blessed I little heed:\nFor this my praise the lady well might claim,\nIf manifest were not that gentle deed.\nMy every thought is turned to aid the dame.\nGrant me but one to guide my steps, and lead\nQuickly to where the foul accuser stands,\nI trust in God to loose Geneura's bands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I will not vouch her guiltless in my thought,\nIn fear to warrant what is false; but I\nBoldly maintain, in such an act is nought\nFor which the damsel should deserve to die;\nAnd ween unjust, or else of wit distraught,\nWho statutes framed of such severity;\nWhich, as iniquitous, should be effaced,\nAnd with a new and better code replaced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If like desire, and if an equal flame\nMove one and the other sex, who warmly press\nTo that soft end of love (their goal the same)\nWhich to the witless crowd seems rank excess;\nSay why shall woman — merit scathe or blame,\nThough lovers, one or more, she may caress;\nWhile man to sin with whom he will is free,\nAnd meets with praise, not mere impunity?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"By this injurious law, unequal still,\nOn woman is inflicted open wrong;\nAnd to demonstrate it a grievous ill,\nI trust in God, which has been borne too long.\"\nTo good Rinaldo's sentence, with one will,\nDeeming their sires unjust, assents the throng,\nTheir sires who such outrageous statute penned,\nAnd king, who might, but does not, this amend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the new dawn, with streaks of red and white,\nBroke in the east, and cleared the hemisphere,\nRinaldo took his steed and armour bright:\nA squire that abbey furnished to the peer.\nWith him, for many leagues and miles, the knight\nPricked through the dismal forest dark and drear;\nWhile they towards the Scottish city ride,\nWhere the poor damsel's cause is to be tried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seeking their way to shorten as they wound,\nThey to the wider track a path preferred;\nWhen echoing through the gloomy forest round,\nLoud lamentations nigh the road were heard.\nTowards a neighbouring vale, whence came the sound,\nThis his Bayardo, that his hackney spurred;\nAnd viewed, between two grisly ruffians there,\nA girl, who seemed at distance passing fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But woe begone and weeping was the maid\nAs ever damsel dame, or wight was seen:\nHard by the barbarous twain prepared the blade,\nTo deluge with that damsel's blood the green.\nShe to delay her death awhile essayed,\nUntil she pity moved with mournful mien.\nThis when Rinaldo near approaching eyes,\nHe thither drives with threats and furious cries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The ruffians turn their backs and take to flight\nAs soon as they the distant succour view,\nAnd squat within a valley out of sight:\nNor cares the good Rinaldo to pursue.\nTo her approaching, sues Mount Alban's knight,\nTo say what on her head such evil drew;\nAnd, to save time, commands his squire to stoop,\nAnd take the damsel on his horse's croup."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And as the lady nearer he surveyed,\nHer wise behaviour marked and beauty's bloom;\nThough her fait countenance was all dismayed,\nAnd by the fear of death o'erspread with gloom.\nAgain to know, the gentle knight essayed,\nWho had prepared for her so fell a doom;\nAnd she began to tell in humble tone"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto I postpone.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 5"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lurcanio, by a false report abused,\nDeemed by Geneura's fault his brother dead,\nWeening the faithless duke, whom she refused,\nWas taken by the damsel to her bed;\nAnd her before the king and peers accused:\nBut to the session Ariodantes led,\nStrives with his brother in disguise.  In season\nRinaldo comes to venge the secret treason."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Among all other animals who prey\nOn earth, or who unite in friendly wise,\nWhether they mix in peace or moody fray,\nNo male offends his mate.  In safety hies\nThe she bear, matched with hers, through forest gray:\nThe lioness beside the lion lies:\nWolves, male and female, live in loving cheer;\nNor gentle heifer dreads the wilful steer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What Fury, what abominable Pest\nSuch poison in the human heart has shed,\nThat still 'twixt man and wife, with rage possessed,\nInjurious words and foul reproach are said?\nAnd blows and outrage hase their peace molest,\nAnd bitter tears still wash the genial bed;\nNot only watered by the tearful flood,\nBut often bathed by senseless ire with blood?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not simply a rank sinner, he appears\nTo outrage nature, and his God to dare,\nWho his foul hand against a woman rears,\nOr of her head would harm a single hair.\nBut who what drug the burning entrail sears,\nOr who for her would knife or noose prepare,\nNo man appears to me, though such to sight\nHe seem, but rather some infernal sprite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such, and no other were those ruffians two,\nWhom good Rinaldo from the damsel scared,\nConducted to these valleys out of view,\nThat none might wot of her so foully snared.\nI ended where the damsel, fair of hue,\nTo tell the occasion of her scathe prepared,\nTo the good Paladin, who brought release;\nAnd in conclusion thus my story piece."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of direr deed than ever yet was done,\"\nThe gentle dame began, \"Sir cavalier,\nIn Thebes, Mycene, Argos, or upon\nOther more savage soil, prepare to hear;\nAnd I believe, that if the circling sun\nTo these our Scottish shores approach less near\nThan other land, 'tis that he would eschew\nA foul ferocious race that shocks his view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"All times have shown that man has still pursued\nWith hair, in every clime, his natural foe;\nBut to deal death to those who seek our good\nDoes from too ill and foul a nature flow.\nNow, that the truth be better understood,\nI shall from first to last the occasion show,\nWhy in my tender years, against all right,\nThose caitiffs would have dome me foul despite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'Tis fitting you should know, that in the spring\nOf life, I to the palace made resort;\nThere served long time the daughter of the king,\nAnd grew with her in growth, well placed in court.\nWhen cruel love, my fortune envying,\nWilled I should be his follower and his sport;\nAnd made, beyond each Scottish lord and knight,\nAlbany's duke find favour in my sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And for he seemed to cherish me above\nAll mean; his love a love as ardent bred.\nWe hear, indeed, and see, but do not prove\nMan's faith, nor is his bosom's purpose read.\nBelieving still, and yielding to my love,\nI ceased not till I took him to my bed;\nNor, of all chambers, in that evil hour,\nMarked I was in Geneura's priviest bower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Where, hoarded, she with careful privacy\nPreserved whatever she esteemed most rare;\nThere many times she slept.  A gallery\nFrom thence projected into the open air.\nHere oft I made my lover climb to me,\nAnd (what he was to mount a hempen stair, ) \n\nWhen him I to my longing arms would call,\nFrom the projecting balcony let fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For here my passion I as often fed\nAs good Geneura's absence made me bold;\nWho with the varying season changed her bed,\nTo shun the burning heat or pinching cold,\nAnd Albany, unseen and safely sped;\nFor, fronting a dismantled street, and old,\nWas built that portion of the palace bright;\nNor any went that way by day or night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So was for many days and months maintained\nBy us, in secrecy, the amorous game;\nStill grew by love, and such new vigour gained,\nI in my inmost bosom felt the flame;\nAnd that he little loved, and deeply feigned\nWeened not, so was I blinded to my shame:\nThough, in a thousand certain signs betrayed,\nThe faithless knight his base deceit bewrayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"After some days, of fair Geneura he\nA suitor showed himself; I cannot say\nIf this began before he sighed for me,\nOr, after, of this love he made assay:\nBut judge, alas!  with what supremacy\nHe ruled my heart, how absolute his sway!\nSince this he owned, and thought no shame to move\nMe to assist him in his second love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Unlike what he bore me, he said, indeed,\nThat was not true which he for her displayed;\nBut so pretending love, he hoped to speed,\nAnd celebrate due spousals with the maid.\nHe with her royal sire might well succeed,\nWere she consenting to the boon he prayed;\nFor after our good king, for wealth and birth\nIn all the realm, was none of equal worth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Me he persuades, if through my ministry\nHe the king's son-in-law elected were,\nFor I must know he next the king would be\nAdvanced as high, as subject could repair,\nThe merit should be mine, and ever he\nSo great a benefit in mind would bear;\nAnd he would cherish me above his bride,\nAnd more than every other dame beside."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I, who to please him was entirely bent,\nWho never could or would gainsay his will,\nUpon those days alone enjoy content,\nWhen I find means his wishes to fulfil:\nAnd snatch at all occasions which present\nA mode, his praise and merits to instil:\nAnd for my lover with all labour strain,\nAnd industry, Geneura's love to gain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With all my heart, in furtherance of his suit,\nI wrought what could be done, God truly knows;\nBut with Geneura this produced no friut,\nNor her to grace my duke could I dispose.\nFor that another love had taken root\nIn her, whose every fond affection flows\nTowards a gentle knight of courteous lore,\nWho sought our Scotland from a distant shore:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And with a brother, then right young, to stay\nIn our king's court, came out of Italy:\nAnd there of knightly arms made such assay,\nWas none in Britain more approved than he;\nPrized by the king, who (no ignoble pay),\nRewarding him like his nobility,\nBestowed upon the youth, with liberal hand,\nBurghs, baronies, and castles, woods and land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Dear to the monarch, to the daughter still\nThis lord was dearer, Ariodantes hight.\nHer with affection might his valour fill;\nBut knowledge of his love brought more delight.\nNor old Vesuvius, nor Sicilia's hill,\nNor Troy-town, ever, with a blaze so bright,\nFlamed, as with all his heart, the damsel learned,\nFor love of her young Ariodantes burned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The passion which she bore the lord, preferred\nAnd loved with perfect truth and all her heart,\nWas the occassion I was still unheard;\nNor hopeful answer would she e'er impart:\nAnd still the more my lover's suit I stirred,\nAnd to obtain his guerdon strove with art,\nHim she would censure still, and ever more\nWas strengthened in the hate she nursed before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My wayward lover often I excite\nSo vain and bootless an emprize to quit;\nNor idly hope to turn her stedfast sprite,\nToo deeply with another passion smit;\nAnd make apparent to the Scottish knight,\nAriodantes such a flame had lit\nIn the young damsel's breast, that seas in flood\nWould not have cooled one whit her boiling blood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This Polinesso many times had heard\nFrom me (for such the Scottish baron's name)\nWell warranted by sight as well as word,\nHow ill his love was cherished by the dame.\nTo see another to himself preferred\nNot only quenched the haughty warrior's flame,\nBut the fond love, which in his bosom burned\nInto despiteful rage and hatred turned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Between Geneura and her faithful knight\nSuch discord and ill will he schemed to shed,\nAnd put betwixt the pair such foul despite.\nNo time should heal the quarrel he had bred;\nBringing such scandal on that damsel bright,\nThe stain should cleave to her, alive or dead:\nNor, bent to wreck her on this fatal shelf,\nCounselled with me, or other but himself."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Dalinda mine,' he said, his project brewed,\n(Dalinda is my name `you needs must know, ) \n\nThat from the root although the trunk be hewed,\nSuccessive suckers many times will grow.\nThus my unhappy passion is renewed,\nTenacious still of life, and buds; although\nCut off by ill success, with new increase:\nNor, till I compass my desire, will cease."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Nor hope of pleasure this so much has wrought,\nAs that to compass my design would please;\nAnd, if not in effect, at least in thought\nTo thrive, would interpose some little ease.\nThen every time your bower by me is sought,\nWhen in her bed Geneura slumbers, seize\nWhat she puts off, and be it still your care\nTo dress yourself in all her daily wear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Dispose your locks and deck yourself as she\nGoes decked; and, as you can, with cunning heed,\nImitate her; then to the gallery\nYou, furnished with the corded stair, shall speed:\nI shall ascend it in the phantasy\nThat you are she, of whom you wear the weed:\nAnd hope, that putting on myself this cheat,\nI in short time shall quench my amorous heat.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So said the knight; and I, who was distraught,\nAnd all beside myself, was not aware\nThat the design, in which he help besought,\nWas manifestly but too foul a snare;\nAnd in Geneura's clothes disguised, as taught,\nLet down (so oft I used the corded stair. ) \n\nNor I the traitor's foul deceit perceived,\nUntil the deadly mischief was achieved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The duke, this while, to Ariodantes' ears\nHad these, or other words like these, addressed;\n(For leagued in friendship were the cavaliers,\nTill, rivals, they pursued this common quest)\n\"I marvel, since you are of all my peers\nHe, whom I must have honoured and caressed,\nAnd held in high regard, and cherished still,\nYou should my benefits repay so ill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I am assured you comprehend and know\nMine and Geneura's love, and old accord;\nAnd, in legitimate espousal, how\nI am about to claim her from my lord:\nThen why disturb my suit, and why bestow\nYour heart on her who offers no reward?\nBy Heaven, I should respect your claim and place,\nWere your condition mine, and mine your case.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And I,' cried Ariodantes, `marvel more'\n(In answer to the Scottish lord `at you, ) \n\nSince I of her enamoured was, before\nThat gentle damsel ever met your view;\nAnd know, you are assured how evermore\nWe two have loved; — was never love more true —\nAre certain she alone would share my lot;\nAnd are as well assured she loves you not."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Why have not I from you the same respect,\nTo which, for friendship past, you would pretend\nFrom me; and I should bear you in effect,\nIf your hope stood more fair to gain its end?\nNo less than you, to wed her I expect;\nAnd if your fortunes here my wealth transcend,\nAs favoured of the king, as you, above\nYou, am I happy in his daughter's love.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Of what a strange mistake,' (to him replied\nThe duke `your foolish passion is the root! ) \n\nYou think yourself beloved; I, on my side,\nBelieve the same; this try we by the fruit.\nYou of your own proceeding nothing hide,\nAnd I will tell the secrets of my suit:\nAnd let the man who proves least favoured, yield,\nProvide himself elsewhere, and quit the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I am prepared, if such your wish, to swear\nNothing of what is told me to reveal;\nAnd will that you assure me, for your share,\nYou shall what I recount as well conceal.'\nUniting in the pact, the rival pair\nTheir solemn vows upon the Bible seal:\nAnd when they had the mutual promise plighted,\nAriodantes first his tale recited."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then plainly, and by simple facts averred,\nHow with Geneura stood his suit, avows;\nAnd how, engaged by writing and by word,\nShe swore she would not be another's spouse.\nHow, if to him the Scottish king demurred,\nVirgin austerity she ever vows;\nAnd other bridal bond for aye eschewed,\nTo pass her days in barren solitude."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then added, how he hoped by worth, which he\nHad more than once avouched, with knightly brand,\nAnd yet might vouch, to the prosperity\nAnd honour of the king, and of his land,\nTo please so well that monarch, as to be\nBy him accounted worthy of the hand\nOf his fair child, espoused with his consent:\nSince he in this her wishes would content."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then so concludes — `I stand upon this ground,\nNor I intruder fear, encroaching nigh;\nNor seek I more; 'tis here my hopes I bound;\nNor, striving for Geneura's love, would I\nSeek surer sign of it than what is found,\nBy God allowed, in wedlock's lawful tie;\nAnd other suit were hopeless, am I sure,\nSo excellent she is, and passing pure.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When Ariodantes had, with honest mind,\nTold what reward he hoped should quit his pain,\nFalse Polinesso, who before designed\nTo make Geneura hateful to her swain,\nBegan — `Alas!  you yet are far behind\nMy hopes, and shall confess your own are vain;\nAnd say, as I the root shall manifest\nOf my good fortune, I alone am blest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `With you Geneura feigns, nor pays nor prizes\nYour passion, which with hopes and words is fed;\nAnd, more than this, your foolish love despises:\nAnd this to me the damsel oft has said,\nOf hers I am assured; of no surmises,\nVain, worthless words, or idle promise bred.\nAnd I to you the fact in trust reveal,\nThough this I should in better faith conceal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `There passes not a month, but in that space\nThree nights, four, six, and often ten, the fair\nReceives me with that joy in her embrace,\nWhich seems to second so the warmth we share.\nThis you may witness, and shall judge the case;\nIf empty hopes can with my bliss compare.\nThen since my happier fortune is above\nYour wishes, yield, and seek another love.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `This will I not believe,' in answer cried\nAriodantes, `well assured you lie,\nAnd that you have this string of falsehoods tied,\nTo scare me from the dear emprize I try.\nBut charge, so passing foul, you shall abide,\nAnd vouch what you have said in arms; for I\nNot only on your tale place no reliance;\nBut as a traitor hurl you my defiance.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To him rejoined the duke, 'I ween 'twere ill\nTo take the battle upon either part,\nSince surer mean our purpose may fulfill;\nAnd if it please, my proof I can impart.'\nAriodantes trembled, and a chill\nWent through his inmost bones; and sick at heart,\nHad he in full believed his rival's boast,\nWould on the spot have yielded up the ghost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With wounded heart, and faltering voice, pale face,\nAnd mouth of gall, he answered, 'When I see\nProofs of thy rare adventure, and the grace\nWith which the fair Geneura honours thee,\nI promise to forego the fruitless chase\nOf one, to thee so kind, so cold to me.\nBut think not that thy story shall avail,\nUnless my very eyes confirm the tale.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `To warn in due time shall be my care.'\n(Said Polinesso and so went his way. ) \n\nTwo nights were scarecly passed, ere his repair\nTo the known bower was fixed for the assay.\nAnd, ready now to spring his secret snare,\nHe sought his rival on the appointed day,\nAnd him to hide, the night ensuing, prayed\nI' the street, which none their habitation made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And to the youth a station over-right\nThe balcony, to which he clambered, shows.\nAriodantes weened, this while, the knight\nWould him to seek that hidden place dispose,\nAs one well suited to his fell despite,\nAnd, bent to take his life, this ambush chose,\nUnder the false pretence to make him see\nWhat seemed a sheer impossibility."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To go the peer resolved, but in such guise,\nHe should not be with vantage overlaid;\nAnd should he be assaulted by surprise,\nHe need not be by fear of death dismay'd.\nHe had a noble brother, bold and wise,\nFirst of the court in arms; and on his aid,\nLurcanio hight, relied with better heart\nThan if ten others fought upon his part."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He called him to his side, and willed him take\nHis arms; and to the place at evening led:\nYet not his secret purpose would be break;\nNor this to him, or other would have read:\nHim a stone's throw removed he placed, and spake:\n` — Come if thou hearest he cry,' the warrior said;\n`But as thou lovest me (whatsoe'er befall)\nCome not and move not, brother, till I call.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Doubt not' (the valiant brother said `but go'; ) \n\nAnd thither went that baron silently,\nAnd hid within the lonely house, and low,\nOver against my secret gallery.\nOn the other side approached the fraudful foe,\nSo pleased to work Geneura's infamy;\nAnd, while I nothing of the cheat divine,\nBeneath my bower renews the wonted sign."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And I in costly robe, in which were set\nFair stripes of gold upon a snowy ground,\nMy tresses gathered in a golden net,\nShaded with tassels of vermillion round,\nMimicking fashions, which were only met\nIn fair Geneura, at the accustomed sound,\nThe gallery mount, constructed in such mode,\nAs upon every side my person showed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This while Lurcanio, either with a view\nTo snares which might beset his brother's feet,\nOr with the common passion to pursue,\nAnd play the spy on other, where the street\nWas darkest, and its deepest shadows threw,\nFollowed him softly to his dim retreat:\nAnd not ten paces from the knight aloof,\nBestowed himself beneath the self same roof."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Suspecting nought, I seek the balcony,\nIn the same habits which I mentioned, dressed;\nAs more than once or twice (still happily)\nI did before; meanwhile the goodly vest\nWas in the moonlight clearly seen, and I,\nIn aspect not unlike her, in the rest\nResembling much Geneura's shape and cheer,\nOne visage well another might appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So much the more, that there was ample space\nBetween the palace and the ruined row:\nHence the two brothers, posted in that place,\nWere lightly cheated by the lying show.\nNow put yourself in his unhappy case,\nAnd figure what the wretched lover's woe,\nWhen Polinesso climbed the stair, which I\nCast down to him, and scaled the gallery."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Arrived, my arms about his neck I throw,\nWeening that we unseen of others meet,\nAnd kiss his lips and face with loving show,\nAs him I hitherto was wont to greet;\nAnd he assayed, with more than wonted glow,\nMe to caress, to mask his hollow cheat.\nLed to the shameful spectacle, aghast,\nThat other, from afar, viewed all that passed,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And fell into such fit of deep despair,\nHe there resolved to die; and, to that end,\nPlanted the pommel of his falchion bare\nI' the ground, its point against his breast to bend.\nLurcanio, who with marvel by that stair,\nSaw Polinesso to my bower ascend,\nBut knew not who the wight, with ready speed\nSprang forward, when he saw his brother's deed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And hindered him in that fell agony\nFrom turning his own hand against his breast.\nHad the good youth been later, or less nigh,\nTo his assistance he had vainly pressed.\nThen, `Wretched brother, what insanity.'\n(He cried `your better sense has dispossessed? ) \n\nDie for a woman!  rather let her kind\nBe scattered like the mist before the wind!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Compass her death!  'tis well deserved; your own\nReserve, as due to more illustrious fate.\n'Twas well to love, before her fraud was shown,\nBut she, once loved, now more deserves your hate:\nSince, witnessed by your eyes, to you is known\nA wanton of what sort you worshipped late.\nHer fault before the Scottish king to attest,\nReserve those arms you turn against your breast.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ariodantes, so surprised, forewent,\nJoined by his brother, the design in show;\nBut resolute to die, in his intent\nWas little shaken: Rising thence to go,\nHe bears away a heart not simply rent,\nBut dead and withered with excess of woe:\nYet better comfort to Lurcanio feigns,\nAs if the rage were spent which fired his veins."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The morn ensuing, without further say\nTo his good brother, or to man beside,\nHe from the city took his reckless way\nWith deadly desperation for his guide;\nNor, save the duke and knight, for many a day\nWas there who knew what moved the youth to ride:\nAnd in the palace, touching this event,\nAnd in the realm, was various sentiment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But eight days past or more, to Scotland's court\nA traveller came, and to Geneura he\nRelated tidings of disastrous sort;\nThat Ariodantes perished in the sea:\nDrowned of his own free will was the report,\nNo wind to blame for the calamity!\nSince from a rock, which over ocean hung,\nInto the raging waves he headlong sprung;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Who said, before he reached that frowning crest,\nTo me, whom he encountered by the way,\nCome with me, that your tongue may manifest,\nAnd what betides me to Geneura say;\nAnd tell her, too, the occasion of the rest,\nWhich you shall witness without more delay;\nIn having seen too much, the occasion lies;\nHappy had I been born without these eyes!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `By chance, upon a promontory we\nWere standing, overright the Irish shore;\nWhen, speaking thus on that high headland, he\nPlunged from a rock amid the watery roar.\nI saw him leap, and left him in the sea;\nAnd, hurrying thence, to you the tidings bore.'\nGeneura stood amazed, her colour fled,\nAnd, at the fearful tale, remained half dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O God!  what said, what did she, when alone,\nShe on her faithful pillow layed her head!\nShe beat her bosom, and she tore her gown,\nAnd in despite her golden tresses shed;\nRepeating often, in bewildered tone,\nThe last sad words which Ariodantes said; —\nThat the sole source of such despair, and such\nDisaster, was that he had seen too much."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Wide was the rumour scattered that the peer\nHad slain himself for grief; nor was the cry\nBy courtly dame, or courtly cavalier,\nOr by the monarch, heard with tearless eye.\nBut, above all the rest, his brother dear\nWas whelmed with sorrow of so deep a dye,\nThat, bent to follow him, he well nigh turned\nHis hand against himself, like him he mourned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And many times repeating in his thought,\nIt was Geneura who his brother slew,\nWho was to self-destruction moved by nought\nBut her ill deed, which he was doomed to view,\nSo on his mind the thirst of vengeance wrought,\nAnd so his grief his season overthrew;\nThat he thought little, graced of each estate,\nTo encounter king and people's common hate;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, when the throng was fullest in the hall,\nStood up before the Scottish king, and said,\n`Of having marred my brother's wits withal,\nSir king, and him to his destruction led,\nYour daughter only can I guilty call:\nFor in his inmost soul such sorrow bred\nThe having seen her little chastity,\nHe loathed existence, and preferred to die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `He was her lover; and for his intent\nWas honest, this I seek not, I, to veil;\nAnd to deserve her by his valour meant\nOf thee, if faithful service might avail;\nBut while he stood aloof, and dared but scent\nThe blossoms, he beheld another scale,\nScale the forbidden tree with happier boot,\nAnd bear away from him the wished-for fruit.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then added, how into the gallery came\nGeneura, and how dropped the corded stair;\nAnd how into the chamber of the dame\nHad climbed a leman of that lady fair;\nWho, for disguise (he knew not hence his name),\nHad changed his habits, and concealed his hair;\nAnd, in conclusion, vowed that every word\nSo said, he would avouch with lance and sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You may divine how grieves the sire, distraught\nWith woe, when he the accusation hears:\nAs well that what he never could have thought,\nHe of his daughter learns with wondering ears,\nAs that he knows, if succour be not brought\nBy cavalier, that in her cause appears,\nWho may upon Lurcanio prove the lie,\nHe cannot choose, but doom the maid to die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I do not think our Scottish law to you\nIs yet unknown, which sentences to fire\nThe miserable dame, or damsel, who\nGrants other than her wedded lord's desire.\nShe dies, unless a champion, good and true,\nArm on her side before a month expire;\nAnd her against the accuser base maintain\nUnmeriting such death, and free from stain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The king has made proclaim by town and tower,\n(For he believes her wronged, his child to free)\nHer he shall have to wife, with ample dower,\nWho saves the royal maid from infamy.\nBut each to the other looks, and to this hour\nNo champion yet, 'tis said, appears: for he,\nLurcanio, is esteemed so fierce in fight,\nIt seems as he were feared of every knight.\n\n\"And evil Fate has willed her brother dear,\nZerbino, is not here the foe to face;\nSince many months has roved the cavalier,\nProving his matchless worth with spear and mace;\nFor if the valiant champion were more near,\n(Such is his courage or in any place, ) \n\nWhither in time the news might be conveyed,\nHe would not fail to bear his sister aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The king, mean time, who would the quest pursue,\nAnd by more certain proof than combat, try\nIf the accuser's tale be false or true,\nAnd she deserve, or merit not, to die,\nArrests some ladies of her retinue,\nThat, as he weens, the fact can verify.\nWhence I foresaw, that if I taken were,\nToo certain risque the duke and I must share."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That very night I from the palace flee,\nAnd to the duke repair, escaped from court;\nAnd, were I taken, make him plainly see\nHow much it either's safety would import:\nHe praised, and bade me of good courage be,\nAnd, for his comfort, prayed me to resort\nTo a strong castle which he held hard by;\nAnd gave me two to bear me company."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With what full proofs, sir stranger, you have heard,\nI of my love assured the Scottish peer;\nAnd clearly can discern, if so preferred,\nThat lord was justly bound to hold me dear.\nMark, in conclusion, what was my reward;\nThe glorious meed of my great merit hear!\nAnd say if woman can expect to earn,\nHowever well she love, her love's return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For this perfidious, foul, ungrateful man,\nAt length suspicious of my faith and zeal,\nAnd apprehending that his wily plan,\nIn course of time, I haply might reveal,\nFeigned that meanwhile the monarch's anger ran\nToo high, he would withdraw me, and conceal\nWithin a fortress of his own, where I\n(Such was his real end was doomed to die. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For secretly the duke enjoined the guide,\nWho with me through the gloomy forest went,\nThe worthy guerdon of a faith so tried,\nTo slay me; and had compassed his intent,\nBut for your ready succour, when I cried.\nBehold!  what wages love's poor slaves content.\"\nThus to Rinaldo did Dalinda say,\nAs they together still pursued their way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above all other fortune, to the knight\nWas welcome to have found the gentle maid,\nWho the whole story of Geneura bright,\nAnd her unblemished innocence displayed;\nAnd, if he hoped, although accused with right,\nTo furnish the afflicted damsel aid,\nPersuaded of the calumny's disproof,\nHe with more courage warred in her behoof."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And for St. Andrew's town, with eager speed,\nWhere was the king with all his family,\nAnd where the single fight, in listed mead,\nUpon his daughter's quarrel, was to be,\nThe good Rinaldo pricked, nor spared his steed,\nUntil, within an easy distance, he\nNow near the city, met a squire who brought\nMore recent tidings than the damsel taught:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That thither had repaired a stranger knight,\nTo combat in Geneura's quarrel bent,\nWith ensigns strange, not known of living wight,\nSince ever close concealed the warrior went;\nNot, since he had been there, had bared to sight\nHis visage, aye within his helmet pent:\nAnd that the very squire who with him came,\nSwore that he knew not what the stranger's name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not far they ride before the walls appear,\nAnd now before the gate their coursers stand.\nTo advance the sad Dalinda was in fear,\nYet followed, trusting in Rinaldo's brand.\nThe gate was shut, and to the porter near,\nWhat this implies Rinaldo makes demand:\nTo him was said, the people, one and all,\nWere trooped to see a fight without the wall:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beyond the city, fought upon accord,\nBetween Lurcanio and a stranger knight;\nWhere, on a spacious meadow's level sward,\nThe pair already had begun the fight.\nThe porter opened to Mount Alban's lord,\nAnd straight behind the peer the portal hight.\nRinaldo through the empty city rode,\nBut in a hostel first the dame bestowed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And will that she (he will not long delay\nTo seek her there till his return repose; ) \n\nAnd quickly to the lists pursued his way,\nWhere the two made that fell exchange of blows,\nAnd strove and struggled yet in bloody fray.\nLurcanio's heart with vengeful hatred glows\nAgainst Geneura; while that other knight\nAs well maintains the quarrel for her right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Six knights on foot within the palisade\nStand covered with the corslet's iron case;\nBeneath the Duke of Albany arrayed,\nBorne on a puissant steed of noble race:\nWho there, as lord high-constable obeyed,\nWas keeper of the field and of the place,\nAnd joyed Geneura's peril to espy\nWith swelling bosom and exulting eye."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo pierces through the parted swarm,\n(So wide is felt the good Bayardo's sway,)\nAnd he who hears the courser come in storm,\nHalts not, in his desire to make him way:\nAbove is seen Rinaldo's lofty form,\nThe flower of those who mix in martial fray.\nHe stops his horse before the monarch's chair,\nWhile all to hear the paladin repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Dread sir,\" to him the good Rinaldo said,\n\"Let not the pair this combat longer ply;\nSince whichsoever of the two falls dead,\nKnow, that you let him perish wrongfully:\nThis thinks that he is right, and is misled,\nVouches the false, and knows not 'tis a lie:\nSince that which brought his brother to his end,\nMoves him in causeless battle contend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That, in pure gentleness, with little care\nIf what he here maintains be wrong or right,\nBecause he would preserve a maid so fair,\nPerils his person in the furious fight.\nTo injured innocence I safety bear,\nAnd to the evil man its opposite.\nBut first, for love of God, the battle stay;\nThen list, sir king, to what I shall display.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So moved the king the grave authority\nOf one who seemed so worthy, by his cheer,\nThat he made sign the battle should not be\nFurther continued then with sword or spear:\nTo whom, together with his chivalry,\nAnd barons of the realm and others near\nRinaldo all the treacherous plot displayed,\nWhich Polinesso for Geneura layed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next that he there in arms would testify\nThe truth of what he vouched, the warrior cried.\nFalse Polinesso, called, with troubled eye,\nStood forth, but daringly the tale denied.\nTo him the good Rinaldo in reply;\n\"By deeds be now the doubtful quarrel tried.\"\nThe field was cleared, and, ready armed, the foes,\nWithout more let, in deadly duel close."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How was the hope to king and people dear,\nThe proof might show Geneura innocent!\nAll trust that God will make the treason clear,\nAnd show she was accused with foul intent:\nFor Polinesso, greedy and severe,\nAnd proud was held, and false and fraudulent.\nSo that none there, of all assembled, deemed\nIt marvel, if the knight such fraud had schemed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "False Polinesso, with a mien distressed,\nA pallid cheek, and heart which thickly beat,\nAt the third trumpet, laid his lance in rest;\nAs well Rinaldo spurred the knight to meet,\nAnd levelled at his evil foeman's breast,\nEager to finish at a single heat.\nNor counter to his wish was the event;\nSince through the warrior half his weapon went."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him, through his breast, impaled upon the spear,\nMore than six yards beyond his horse he bore.\nWith speed alighted Mount Albano's peer,\nAnd, ere he rose, unlaced the helm he wore:\nBut he for mercy prayed with humble cheer,\nUnfit to strive in joust or warfare more:\nAnd, before king and court, with faltering breath,\nConfessed the fraud which brought him to his death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He brings not his confession to a close,\nAnd pangs of death the failing accents drown:\nThe prince, who ended saw his daughter's woes,\nRedeemed from death and scorn, her virtue shown,\nWith more delight and rapture overflows,\nThan if he, having lost his kingly crown,\nThen saw it first upon his head replaced;\nSo that he good Rinaldo singly graced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when, through his uplifted casque displaid,\nFeatures, well known before, the king descried,\nHis thanks to God with lifted hands he paid,\nThat he had deigned such succour to provide.\nThat other cavalier, who bared his blade,\nUnknown of all, upon Geneura's side,\nAnd thither came from far, his aid to impart,\nLooked upon all that passed, and stood apart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him the good king entreated to declare\nHis name, or, at the least, his visage shew;\nThat he might grace him with such guerdon fair,\nAs to his good intent was justly due.\nThe stranger, after long and earnest prayer,\nLifted to covering casque, and bared to view"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto will appear, If you are fain the history to hear.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 6"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ariodantes has, a worthy meed,\nWith his loved bride, the fief of Albany.\nMeantime Rogero, on the flying steed,\nArrives in false Alcina's empery:\nThere from a myrtle-tree her every deed,\nA human myrtle hears, and treachery,\nAnd thence would go; but they who first withdrew\nHim from one strife, engage him in a new."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Wretched that evil man who lives in trust\nHis secret sin is safe in his possession!\nSince, if nought else, the air, the very dust\nIn which the crime is buried, makes confession,\nAnd oftentimes his guilt compels the unjust,\nThough sometime unarraigned in worldly session,\nTo be his own accuser, and bewray,\nSo God has willed, deeds hidden from the day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The unhappy Polinesso hopes had nursed,\nWholly his secret treason to conceal.\nBy taking off Dalinda, who was versed\nIn this, and only could the fact reveal;\nAnd adding thus a second to his first\nOffence, but hurried on the dread appeal,\nWhich haply he had stunned, at least deferred;\nBut he to self-destruction blindly spurred."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And forfeited estate, and life, and love\nOf friends at once, and honour, which was more.\nThe cavalier unknown, I said above,\nLong of the king and court entreated sore,\nAt length the covering helmet did remove,\nAnd showed a visage often seen before,\nThe cherished face of Ariodantes true,\nOf late lamented weeping Scotland through;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ariodantes, whom with tearful eye\nHis brother and Geneura wept as dead,\nAnd king, and people, and nobility:\nSuch light his goodness and his valour shed.\nThe pilgrim therefore might appear to lie\nIn what he of the missing warrior said.\nYet was it true that from a headland, he\nHad seen him plunge into the foaming sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But, as it oft befalls despairing wight,\nWho grisly Death desires till he appear;\nBut loathes what he had sought, on nearer sight;\nSo painful seems the cruel pass and drear.\nThus, in the sea engulphed, the wretched knight,\nRepentant of his deed, was touched with fear;\nAnd, matchless both for spirit and for hand,\nBeat back the billows, and returned to land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, now despising, as of folly bred,\nThe fond desire which did to death impell,\nThence, soaked and dripping wet, his way did tread,\nAnd halted at a hermit's humble cell:\nAnd housed within the holy father's shed,\nThere secretly awhile designed to dwell;\nTill to his ears by rumour should be voiced,\nIf his Geneura sorrowed or rejoiced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At first he heard that, through excess of woe,\nThe miserable damsel well-nigh died:\nFor so abroad the doleful tidings go,\n'Twas talked of in the island, far and wide:\nFar other proof than that deceitful show,\nWhich to his cruel grief he thought he spied!\nAnd next against the fair Geneura heard\nLurcanio to her sire his charge preferred:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor for his brother felt less enmity\nThan was the love he lately bore the maid;\nFor he too foul, and full of cruelty,\nEsteemed the deed, although for him essayed;\nAnd, hearing after, in her jeopardy,\nThat none appeared to lend the damsel aid,\nBecause so puissant was Lurcanio's might,\nAll dreaded an encounter with the knight,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And that who well the youthful champion knew,\nBelieved he was so wary and discreet,\nThat, had what he related been untrue,\nHe never would have risqued so rash a feat,\n— For this the greater part the fight eschew,\nFearing in wrongful cause the knight to meet —\nAriodantes (long his doubts are weighed)\nWill meet his brother in Geneura's aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alas! (he said I cannot bear to see ) \n\nThus by my cause the royal damsel die;\nMy death too bitter and too dread would be,\nDid I, before my own, her death descry;\nFor still my lady, my divinity\nShe is; — the light and comfort of my eye.\nHer, right or wrong, I cannot choose but shield,\nAnd for her safety perish in the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I know I choose the wrong, and be it so!\nAnd in the cause shall die: nor this would move;\nBut that, alas!  my death, as well I know,\nWill such a lovely dame's destruction prove,\nTo death I with one only comfort go,\nThat, if her Polinesso bears her love,\nTo her will manifestly be displayed,\nThat hitherto he moves not in her aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And me, so wronged by her, the maid shall view\nEncounter death in her defence; and he,\nMy brother, who such flames of discord blew,\nShall pay the debt of vengeance due to me.\nFor well I ween to make Lurcanio rue\n(Informed of the event his cruelty, ) \n\nWho will have thought to venge me with his brand,\nAnd will have slain me with his very hand.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, having this concluded in his thought,\nMade new provision of arms, steed, and shield;\nBlack was the vest and buckler which he bought,\nWhere green and yellow striped the sable field:\nBy hazard found, with him a squire he brought,\nA stranger in that country; and, concealed\n(As is already told the unhappy knight, ) \n\nAgainst his brother came, prepared for fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And yielding to his natural inclination,\nAnd at the suit of all his court beside,\nAnd mostly at Rinaldo's instigation,\nAssigned the youth the damsel as his bride.\nAlbany's duchy, now in sequestration,\nLate Polinesso's, who in duel died,\nCould not be forfeited in happier hour;\nSince this the monarch made his daughter's dower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo for Dalinda mercy won;\nWho from her fault's due punishment went free.\nShe, satiate of the world, (and this to shun,\nThe damsel so had vowed to God will flee: ) \n\nAnd hence, in Denmark's land, to live a nun,\nStraight from her native Scotland sailed the sea.\nBut it is time Rogero to pursue,\nWho on his courser posts the welkin through."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Although Rogero is of constant mind,\nNot from his cheek the wonted hues depart.\nI ween that faster than a leaf i' the wind\nFluttered within his breast the stripling's heart.\nAll Europe's region he had left behind\nIn his swift course; and, issuing in that part,\nPassed by a mighty space, the southern sound\nWhere great Alcides fixed the sailor's bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That hippogryph, huge fowl, and strange to sight,\nBears off the warrior with such rapid wing,\nHe would have distanced, in his airy flight,\nThe thunder bearing bird of Aether's king:\nNor other living creature soars such height,\nHim in his mighty swiftness equalling.\nI scarce believe that bolt, or lightning flies,\nOr darts more swiftly from the parted skies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the huge bird his pinions long had plied,\nIn a straight line, without one stoop or bend,\nHe, tired of air, with sweeping wheel and wide,\nBegan upon an island to descend;\nLike that fair region, whither, long unspied\nOf him, her wayward mood did long offend,\nWhilom in vain, through strange and secret sluice,\nPassed under sea the Virgin Arethuse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A more delightful place, wherever hurled\nThrough the whole air, Rogero had not found:\nAnd, had he ranged the universal world,\nWould not have seen a lovelier in his round,\nThan that, where, wheeling wide, the courser furled\nHis spreading wings, and lighted on the ground,\n'Mid cultivated plain, delicious hill,\nMoist meadow, shady bank, and crystal rill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Small thickets, with the scented laurel gay,\nCedar, and orange, full of fruit and flower,\nMyrtle and palm, with interwoven spray,\nPleached in mixed modes, all lovely, form a bower;\nAnd, breaking with their shade the scorching ray,\nMake a cool shelter from the noontide hour.\nAnd nightingales among those branches wing\nTheir flight, and safely amorous descants sing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Amid red roses and white lilies there,\nWhich the soft breezes freshen as they fly,\nSecure the cony haunts, and timid hare,\nAnd stag, with branching forehead broad and high.\nThese, fearless of the hunter's dart or snare,\nFeed at their ease, or ruminating lie:\nWhile, swarming in those wilds, from tuft or steep\nDun deer or nimble goat, disporting, leap."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the hyppogryph above the island hung,\nAnd had approached so nigh that landscape fair,\nThat, if his rider from the saddle sprung,\nHe might the leap with little danger dare,\nRogero lit the grass and flowers among,\nBut held him, lest he should remount the air:\nAnd to a myrtle, nigh the rolling brine,\nMade fast, between a bay-tree and a pine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And there, close-by where rose a bubbling fount,\nBegirt the fertile palm and cedar-tree,\nHe drops the shield, the helmet from his front\nUplifts, and, either hand from gauntlet free,\nNow turning to the beach, and now the mount,\nCatches the gales which blow from hill or sea,\nAnd, with a joyous murmur, lightly stir\nThe lofty top of beech, or feathery fir:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, now, to bathe his burning lips he strains;\nNow dabbles in the crystal wave, to chase\nThe scorching heat which rages in his veins,\nCaught from the heavy corslet's burning case.\nNor is it marvel if the burden pains;\nNo ramble his in square or market-place!\nThree thousand miles, without repose, he went,\nAnd still, at speed, in ponderous armour pent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile the courser by the myrtle's side,\nWhom he left stabled in the cool retreat,\nStarted at something in the wood descried,\nScared by I know not what; and in his heat\nSo made the myrtle shake where he was tied,\nHe brought a shower of leaves about his feet;\nHe made the myrtle shake and foliage fall,\nBut, struggling, could not loose himself withal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in a stick to feed the chimney rent,\nWhere scanty pith ill fills the narrow sheath,\nThe vapour, in its little channel pent,\nStruggles, tormented by the fire beneath;\nAnd, till its prisoned fury find a vent,\nIs heard to hiss and bubble, sing and seethe:\nSo the offended myrtle inly pined,\nGroaned, murmured, and at last unclosed its rind:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And hence a clear, intelligible speech\nThus issued, with a melancholy sound;\n\"If, as thy cheer and gentle presence teach,\nThou courteous art and good, his reign unbound,\nRelease me from this monster, I beseech:\nGriefs of my own inflict sufficient wound:\nNor need I, compassed with such ills about,\nOther new pain to plague me from without.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the first sound, Rogero turns to see\nWhence came the voice, and, in unused surprise,\nStands, when he finds it issues from the tree;\nAnd swiftly to remove the courser hies.\nThen, with a face suffused with crimson, he\nIn answer to the groaning myrtle, cries;\n\"Pardon! and, whatsoe'er thou art, be good,\nSpirit of man, or goddess of the wood!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Unweeting of the wonderous prodigy\nOf spirit, pent beneath the knotty rind,\nTo your fair leaf and living body I\nHave done this scathe and outrage undesigned.\nBut not the less for that, to me reply,\nWhat art thou, who, in rugged case confined,\nDost live and speak?  And so may never hail\nFrom angry heaven your gentle boughs assail!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if I now or ever the despite\nI did thee can repair, or aid impart,\nI, by that lady dear, my promise plight,\nWho in her keeping has my better part,\nTo strive with word and deed, till thou requite\nThe service done with praise and grateful heart.\"\nRogero said; and, as he closed his suit,\nThat gentle myrtle shook from top to root."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next drops were seen to stand upon the bark,\nAs juice is sweated by the sapling-spray,\nNew-severed, when it yields to flame and spark,\nSometime in vain kept back and held at bay.\nAnd next the voice began:  \"My story dark,\nForced by thy courteous deed, I shall display; —\nWhat once I was — by whom, through magic lore,\nChanged to a myrtle on the pleasant shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A peer of France, Astolpho was my name,\nWhilom a paladin, sore feared in fight;\nCousin I was to two of boundless fame,\nOrlando and Rinaldo.  I by right\nLooked to all England's crown; my lawful claim\nAfter my royal father, Otho hight.\nMore dames than one my beauty served to warm,\nAnd in conclusion wrought my single harm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Returning from those isles, whose eastern side\nThe billows of the Indian ocean beat,\nWhere good Rinaldo and more knights beside\nWith me were pent in dark and hollow seat,\nThence, rescued by illustrious Brava's pride,\nWhose prowess freed us from that dark retreat,\nWestward I fared along the sandy shores,\nOn which the stormy north his fury pours."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Pursuing thus our rugged journey, we\nCame (such our evil doom upon the strand, ) \n\nWhere stood a mansion seated by the sea:\nPuissant Alcina owned the house and land.\nWe found her, where, without her dwelling, she\nHad taken on the beach her lonely stand;\nAnd though nor hook nor sweeping net she bore,\nWhat fish she willed, at pleasure drew to shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thither swift dolphins gambol, inly stirred,\nAnd open-mouthed the cumbrous tunnies leap;\nThither the seal or porpus' wallowing herd\nTroop at her bidding, roused from lazy sleep;\nRaven-fish, salmon, salpouth, at her word,\nAnd mullet hurry through the briny deep,\nWith monstrous backs above the water, sail\nOrk, physeter, sea-serpent, shark, and whale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"There we behold a mighty whale, of size\nThe hugest yet in any water seen:\nMore than eleven paces, to our eyes,\nHis back appears above the surface green:\nAnd (for still firm and motionless he lies,\nAnd such the distance his two ends between)\nWe all are cheated by the floating pile,\nAnd idly take the monster for an isle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alcina made the ready fish obey\nBy simple words and by mere magic lore:\nBorn with Morgana — but I cannot say\nIf at one birth, or after or before.\nAs soon as seen, my aspect pleased the fay;\nWho showed it in the countenance she wore:\nThen wrought with art, and compassed her intent,\nTo part me from the friends with whom I went."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She came towards us with a cheerful face,\nWith graceful gestures, and a courteous air,\nAnd said:  'So you my lodging please to grace,\nSir cavalier, and will with me repair,\nYou shall behold the wonders of my chace,\nAnd note the different sorts of fish I snare;\nShaggy or smooth, or clad in scales of light,\nAnd more in number than the stars of night:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'And would you hear a mermaid sing so sweet,\nThat the rude sea grows civil at her song,\nWont at this hour her music to repeat,\n(With that she showed the monster huge and long\n— I said it seemed an island — as her seat)\nPass with me where she sings the shoals among.'\nI, that was always wilful, at her wish,\nI now lament my rashness, climb the fish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To Dudon and Rinaldo's signal blind,\nI go, who warn me to misdoubt the fay.\nWith laughing face Alcina mounts behind,\nLeaving the other two beside the bay.\nThe obedient fish performs the task assigned,\nAnd through the yielding water works his way.\nRepentant of my deed, I curse the snare,\nToo far from land my folly to repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To aid me swam Mount Alban's cavalier,\nAnd was nigh drowned amid the waves that rise;\nFor a south-wind sprang up that, far and near,\nCovered with sudden darkness seas and skies.\nI know not after what befel the peer:\nThis while Alcina to console me tries,\nAnd all that day, and night which followed, me\nDetained upon that monster in mid-sea,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Till to this isle we drifted with the morn,\nOf which Alcina keeps a mighty share;\nBy that usurper from a sister torn,\nWho was her father's universal heir:\nFor that she only was in wedlock born,\nAnd for those other two false sisters were\n(So well-instructed in the story, said\nOne who rehearsed the tale in incest bred. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As these are practised in iniquity,\nAnd full of every vice and evil art;\nSo she, who ever lives in chastity,\nWisely on better things has set her heart.\nHence, leagued against her, in conspiracy,\nThose others are, to drive her from her part:\nAnd more than once their armies have o'errun\nHer realm, and towns above a hundred won."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor at this hour a single span of ground\nWould Logistilla (such her name command, ) \n\nBut that a mountain here, and there a sound,\nProtects the remnant from the invading band.\n'Tis thus the mountain and the river bound\nEngland, and part it from the Scottish land.\nYet will the sisters give their foe no rest,\nTill of her scanty remnant dispossest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Because in wickedness and vice were bred\nThe pair, as chaste and good they loath the dame.\nBut, to return to what I lately said,\nAnd to relate how I a plant became;\nMe, full of love, the kind Alcina fed\nWith full delights; nor I a weaker flame\nFor her, within my burning heart did bear,\nBeholding her so courteous and so fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Clasped in her dainty limbs, and lapt in pleasure,\nI weened that I each separate good had won,\nWhich to mankind is dealt in different measure,\nLittle or more to some, and much to none.\nI evermore contemplated my treasure,\nNor France nor aught beside I thought upon:\nIn her my every fancy, every hope\nCentered and ended as their common scope."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"By her I was as much beloved, or more;\nNor did Alcina now for other care;\nShe left her every lover; for before,\nOthers, in truth, the fairy's love did share:\nI was her close adviser evermore;\nAnd served by her, where they commanded were.\nWith me she counselled, and to me referred;\nNor, night nor day, to other spake a word."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Why touch my wounds, to aggravate my ill,\nAnd that, alas!  without the hope of cure?\nWhy thus the good possessed remember still,\nAmid the cruel penance I endure?\nWhen kindest I believed Alcina's will,\nAnd fondly deemed my happiness secure,\nFrom me the heart she gave, the fay withdrew,\nAnd yielded all her soul to love more new."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Late I discerned her light and fickle bent,\nStill loving and unloving at a heat:\nTwo months, I reigned not more, no sooner spent,\nThan a new paramour assumed my seat;\nAnd me, with scorn, she doomed to banishment,\nFrom her fair grace cast out.  'Tis then I weet\nI share a thousand lovers' fate, whom she\nHad to like pass reduced, all wrongfully."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And these, because they should not scatter bruits,\nRoaming the world, of her lascivious ways,\nShe, up and down the fruitful soil, transmutes\nTo olive, palm, or cedar, firs or bays.\nThese, as you see me changed, Alcina roots;\nWhile this transformed into a monster strays;\nAnother melts into a liquid rill;\nAs suits that haughty fairy's wanton will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou, too, that to this fatal isle art led\nBy way unwonted and till now unknown,\nThat some possessor of the fairy's bed,\nMay be for thee transformed to wave or stone,\nThou shalt, with more than mortal pleasures fed,\nHave from Alcina seigniory and throne;\nBut shalt be sure to join the common flock,\nTransformed to beast or fountain, plant or rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I willingly to thee this truth impart,\nNot that I hope with profit to advise:\nYet 'twill be better, that informed, in part,\nOf her false ways, she harm not by surprise.\nPerhaps, as faces differ, and in art\nAnd wit of man an equal difference lies,\nThou may'st some remedy perchance apply\nTo the ill, which thousand others could not fly.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The good Rogero, who from Fame had learned\nThat he was cousin to the dame he wooed,\nLamented much the sad Astolpho, turned\nFrom his true form, to barren plant and rude:\nAnd for her love, for whom so sore he burned,\nWould gladly serve the stripling if he cou'd:\nBut, witless how to give the wished relief,\nMight but console the unhappy warrior's grief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As best he could, he strove to soothe his pain;\nThen asked him, if to Logistil's retreat\nWere passage, whether over hill or plain;\nThat he might so eschew Alcina's seat.\n— `There was a way', the myrtle said again,\n— `But rough with stones, and rugged to the feet —\nIf he, some little further to the right,\nWould scale the Alpine mountain's very height:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "`But that he must not think he shall pursue\nThe intended journey far; since by the way\nHe will encounter with a frequent crew,\nAnd fierce, who serve as rampart to the fay,\nThat block the road against the stranger, who\nWould break her bounds, and the deserter stay.'\nRogero thanked the tree for all, and taught,\nDeparted thence with full instructions fraught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The courser from the myrtle he untied,\nAnd by the bridle led behind him still;\nNor would he, as before, the horse bestride,\nLest he should bear him off against his will:\nHe mused this while how safely he might find\nA passage to the land of Logistil;\nFirm in his purpose every nerve to strain,\nLest empire over him Alcina gain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He to remount the steed, and through the air\nTo spur him to a new career again\nNow thought; but doubted next, in fear to fare\nWorse on the courser, restive to the rein.\n\"No, I will win by force the mountain stair,\"\nRogero said; (but the resolve was vain)\nNor by the beach two miles his way pursued,\nEre he Alcina's lovely city viewed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A lofty wall at distance meets his eye\nWhich girds a spacious town within its bound;\nIt seems as if its summit touched the sky,\nAnd all appears like gold from top to ground.\nHere some one says it is but alchemy\n— And haply his opinion is unsound —\nAnd haply he more wittily divines:\nFor me, I deem it gold because it shines."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he was nigh the city-walls, so bright,\nThe world has not their equal, he the straight\nAnd spacious way deserts, the way which dight\nAcross the plain, conducted to the gate;\nAnd by that safer road upon the right,\nStrains now against the mountain; but, in wait,\nEncounters soon the crowd of evil foes,\nWho furiously the Child's advance oppose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Was never yet beheld a stranger band,\nOf mien more hideous, or more monstrous shape.\nFormed downwards from neck like men, he scanned\nSome with the head of cat, and some of ape;\nWith hoof of goat that other stamped the sand;\nWhile some seemed centaurs, quick in fight and rape;\nNaked, or mantled in outlandish skin.\nThese doting sires, those striplings bold in sin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This gallops on a horse without a bit;\nThis backs the sluggish ass, or bullock slow;\nThese mounted on the croup of centaur sit:\nThose perched on eagle, crane, or estridge, go.\nSome male, some female, some hermaphrodit,\nThese drain the cup and those the bungle blow.\nOne bore a corded ladder, one a book;\nOne a dull file, or bar of iron shook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The captain of this crew, which blocked the road,\nAppeared, with monstrous paunch and bloated face;\nWho a slow tortoise for a horse bestrode,\nThat passing sluggishly with him did pace:\nDown looked, some here, some there, sustained the load,\nFor he was drunk, and kept him in his place.\nSome wipe his brows and chin from sweat which ran,\nAnd others with their vests his visage fan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One, with a human shape and feet, his crest,\nFashioned like hound, in neck and ears and head,\nBayed at the gallant Child with angry quest,\nTo turn him to the city whence he fled.\n\"That will I never, while of strength possessed\nTo brandish this,\" the good Rogero said:\nWith that his trenchant faulchion he displayed,\nAnd pointed at him full the naked blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That monster would have smote him with a spear,\nBut swiftly at his foe Rogero sprung,\nThrust at his paunch, and drove his faulchion sheer\nThrough his pierced back a palm; his buckler flung\nBefore him, and next sallied there and here:\nBut all too numerous was the wicked throng.\nNow grappled from behind, now punched before,\nHe stands, and plies the crowd with warfare sore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One to the teeth, another to the breast,\nOf that foul race he cleft; since no one steeled\nIn mail, his brows with covering helmet dressed,\nOr fought, secured by corslet or by shield;\nYet is he so upon all quarters pressed,\nThat it would need the Child, to clear the field,\nAnd to keep off the wicked crew which swarms,\nMore than Briareus' hundred hands and arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If he had thought the magic shield to show,\n(I speak of that the necromancer bore,\nWhich dazed the sight of the astonished foe,\nLeft at his saddle by the wizard Moor)\nThat hideous band, in sudden overthrow,\nBlinded by this, had sunk the knight before.\nBut haply he despised such mean as vile,\nAnd would prevail by valour, not by guile."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This as it may: the Child would meet his fate,\nEre by so vile a band be prisoner led;\nWhen, lo!  forth issuing from the city's gate,\nWhose wall appeared like shining gold I said,\nTwo youthful dames, not born in low estate,\nIf measured by their mien and garb, nor bred\nBy swain, in early wants and troubles versed;\nBut amid princely joys in palace nursed!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On unicorn was seated either fair,\nA beast than spotless ermine yet more white;\nSo lovely were the damsels, and so rare\nTheir garb, and with such graceful fashion dight,\nThat he who closely viewed the youthful pair,\nWould need a surer sense than mortal sight,\nTo judge between the two.  With such a mien\nEmbodied Grace and Beauty would be seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Into the mead rode this and the other dame,\nWhere the foul crew opposed the Child's retreat.\nThe rabble scattered as the ladies came,\nWho with extended hand the warrior greet.\nHe, with a kindling visage, red with shame,\nThanked the two damsels for their gentle feat;\nAnd was content upon their will to wait,\nWith them returning to that golden gate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above, a cornice round the gateway goes,\nSomedeal projecting from the colonnade,\nIn which is not a single part but glows,\nWith rarest gems of India overlaid.\nPropp'd at four points, the portal did repose\nOn columns of one solid diamond made.\nWhether what met the eye was false or true,\nWas never sight more fair or glad to view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the sill and through the columns there,\nRan young and wanton girls, in frolic sport;\nWho haply yet would have appeared more fair,\nHad they observed a woman's fitting port.\nAll are arrayed in green, and garlands wear\nOf the fresh leaf.  Him these in courteous sort,\nWith many proffers and fair mien entice,\nAnd welcome to this opening Paradise:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For so with reason I this place may call,\nWhere, it is my belief, that Love had birth;\nWhere life is spent in festive game and ball,\nAnd still the passing moments fleet in mirth.\nHere hoary-headed Thought ne'er comes at all,\nNor finds a place in any bosom.  Dearth,\nNor yet Discomfort, never enter here,\nWhere Plenty fills her horn throughout the year."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here, where with jovial and unclouded brow,\nGlad April seems to wear a constant smile,\nTroop boys and damsels: One, whose fountains flow,\nOn the green margin sings in dulcet style;\nOthers, the hill or tufted tree below,\nIn dance, or no mean sport the hours beguile.\nWhile this, who shuns the revellers' noisy cheer,\nTells his love sorrows in his comrade's ear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above the laurel and pine-tree's height,\nThrough the tall beech and shaggy fir-tree's spray,\nSport little loves, with desultory flight:\nThese, at their conquests made, rejoiced and gay:\nThese, with the well-directed shaft, take sight\nAt hearts, and those spread nets to catch their prey;\nOne wets his arrows in the brook which winds,\nAnd one on whirling stone the weapon grinds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To good Rogero here was brought a steed,\nPuissant and nimble, all of sorel hue;\nWho was caparisoned with costly weed,\nBroidered with gold, and jewels bright to view.\nThat other winged horse, which, at his need,\nObedient to the Moorish wizard flew,\nThe friendly damsels to a youth consigned,\nWho led him at a slower pace behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That kindly pair who, by the wicked band\nOffended fate, had saved the youthful knight;\nThe wicked crew, that did the Child withstand,\nWhen he the road had taken on his right,\nExclaimed, \"Fair sir, your works already scanned\nBy us, who are instructed of your might,\nEmbolden us, in our behalf, to pray\nYou will the prowess of your arm assay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"We soon shall reach a bottom which divides\nThe plain into two parts: A cruel dame\nA bridge maintains, which there a stream bestrides,\nEriphila the savage beldam's name;\nWho cheats, and robs, and scathes, whoever rides\nTo the other shore, a giantess in frame;\nWho has long poisonous teeth her prey to tear,\nAnd scratches with her talons like a bear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Besides that she infests the public way,\nWhich else were free; she often ranging through\nAll this fair garden, puts in disarray\nThis thing or that.  Of the assassin crew,\nThat people who without the portal gay,\nLately with brutal rage assaulted you,\nMany her sons, the whole her followers call,\nAs greedy and inhospitable all.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For you not only her I would assail,\nBut do a hundred battles, well content:\nThen of my person, where it may avail,\nDispose (Rogero said to you intent. ) \n\nSilver and land to conquer, plate or mail\nI swear not, I, in warlike cuirass pent;\nBut to afford my aid to others due;\nAnd, most of all, to beauteous dames like you.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Their grateful thanks the ladies, worthily\nBestowed on such a valiant champion, paid:\nThey talking thus the bridge and river see,\nAnd at her post the haughty dame arraid\n(Sapphire and emerald decked the panoply)\nIn arms of gold: but I awhile delay\nTill other strain the issue of the fray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 7"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, as directed by the pair,\nThe giantess Eriphila o'erthrows.\nThat done, he to Alcina's labyrinth, where\nMore than one knight is tied and prisoned, goes.\nTo him Melissa sage the secret snare,\nAnd remedy for that grave evil shows.\nWhence he, by her advised, with downcast eye,\nAnd full of shame forthwith resolves to fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The traveller, he, whom sea or mountain sunder\nFrom his own country, sees things strange and new;\nThat the misjudging vulgar, which lies under\nThe mist of ignorance, esteems untrue:\nRejecting whatsoever is a wonder,\nUnless 'tis palpable and plain to view:\nHence inexperience, as I know full well,\nWill yield small credence to the tale I tell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But this be great or small, I know not why\nThe rabble's silly judgement I should fear,\nConvinced you will not think the tale a lie,\nIn whom the light of reason shines so clear.\nAnd hence to you it is I only try\nThe fruit of my fatigues to render dear.\nI ended where Eriphila in guard\nOf bridge and stream was seen, the passage barred."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of finest metal was her armour bright,\nWith gems of many colours overspread,\nThe tawny jacinth, yellow chyrsolite,\nThe emerald green of hue, and ruby red.\nMounted, but not on palfrey, for the fight:\nIn place of that, she on a wolf had sped,\nSped on a wolf towards the pass; and rode\nOn sell, that rich beyond all custom showed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No larger wolf, I ween, Apulia roams;\nMore huge than bull, unguided by her hand;\nAlthough upon no bit the monster foams,\nDocile, I know not why, to her command.\nThe accursed Plague, arrayed in surcoat, comes\nAbove her arms, in colour like the sand;\nThat, saving in its dye, was of the sort\nWhich bishops and which prelates wear at court."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The giantess's crest and shield appear,\nFor ensign, decked with swoln and poisonous toad.\nHer the two damsels to the cavalier\nBefore the bridge, prepared for battle, showed,\nThreatening, as wont to some, with levelled spear,\nTo do the warrior scorn and bar the road.\nBidding him turn, she to Rogero cries;\nA lance he takes, and threats her and defies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As quick and daring, the gigantic Pest\nSpurred her wolf, seated well for that dread game:\nIn mid career she laid her lance in rest,\nAnd made earth quake beneath her as she came;\nYet at the encounter fierce the champaign pressed;\nFor underneath the casque, with stedfast aim,\nSo hard Rogero smote her, that he bore\nThe beldam backward six good yards and more:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And came already with his lifted blade,\nDrawn for that end, to take her haughty head;\nTo him an easy task; for she was laid\nAmong the grass and flowers, like one that's dead.\nBut, \" 'Tis enough that she is vanquished,\" said\nThe pair, \"No further press thy vengeance dread.\nSheathe, courteous cavalier, thy sword anew:\nPass we the river, and our way pursue.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Along the path, which through a forest lay,\nRoughish and somedeal ill to beat, they went.\nBesides that strait and stony was the way,\nThis, nigh directly, scaled a hill's ascent.\nBut, when arrived upon the summit, they\nIssued upon a mead of vast extent;\nAnd a more pleasant palace on that green\nBeheld, and brighter than was ever seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To meet the Child, Alcina, fair of hue,\nAdvanced some way beyond the outer gate;\nAnd, girded by a gay and courtly crew,\nRogero there received in lordly state:\nWhile all the rest to him such honour do,\nAnd on the knight with such deep reverence wait,\nThey could not have displayed more zeal and love,\nHad Jove descended from the choirs above."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not so much does the palace, fair to see,\nIn riches other princely domes excel,\nAs that the gentlest, fairest, company\nWhich the whole world contains, within it dwell:\nOf either sex, with small variety\nBetween, in youth and beauty matched as well:\nThe fay alone exceeds the rest as far\nAs the bright sun outshines each lesser star."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her shape is of such perfect symmetry,\nAs best to feign the industrious painter knows,\nWith long and knotted tresses; to the eye\nNot yellow gold with brighter lustre glows.\nUpon her tender cheek the mingled dye\nIs scattered, of the lily and the rose.\nLike ivory smooth, the forehead gay and round\nFills up the space, and forms a fitting bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two black and slender arches rise above\nTwo clear black eyes, say suns of radiant light,\nWhich ever softly beam and slowly move;\nRound these appears to sport in frolic flight,\nHence scattering all his shafts, the little Love,\nAnd seems to plunder hearts in open sight.\nThence, through mid visage, does the nose descend,\nWhere Envy finds not blemish to amend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As if between two vales, which softly curl,\nThe mouth with vermeil tint is seen to glow:\nWithin are strung two rows of orient pearl,\nWhich her delicious lips shut up or show.\nOf force to melt the heart of any churl,\nHowever rude, hence courteous accents flow:\nAnd here that gentle smile receives its birth,\nWhich opes at will a paradise on earth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Like milk the bosom, and the neck of snow;\nRound is the neck, and full and large the breast;\nWhere, fresh and firm, two ivory apples grow,\nWhich rise and fall, as, to the margin pressed\nBy pleasant breeze, the billows come and go.\nNot prying Argus could discern the rest.\nYet might the observing eye of things concealed\nConjecture safely, from the charms revealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To all her arms a just proportion bear,\nAnd a white hand is oftentimes descried,\nWhich narrow is, and somedeal long; and where\nNo knot appears, nor vein is signified.\nFor finish of that stately shape and rare,\nA foot, neat, short, and round, beneath is spied.\nAngelic visions, creatures of the sky,\nConcealed beneath no covering veil can lie."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A springe is planted in Rogero's way,\nOn all sides did she speak, smile, sing, or move;\nNo wonder then the stripling was her prey,\nWho in the fairy saw such show of love.\nWith him the guilt and falsehood little weigh,\nOf which the offended myrtle told above.\nNor will he think that perfidy and guile\nCan be united with so sweet a smile."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No!  he could now believe, by magic art,\nAstolpho well transformed upon the plain,\nFor punishment of foul ungrateful heart,\nAnd haply meriting severer pain.\nAnd, as for all he heard him late impart,\n'Twas prompted by revenge, 'twas false and vain.\nBy hate and malice was the sufferer stung,\nTo blame and wound the fay with slanderous tongue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beauteous lady whom he loved so well\nIs newly banished from his altered breast;\nFor (such the magic of Alcina's spell)\nShe every ancient passion dispossessed;\nAnd in his bosom, there alone to dwell,\nThe image of her love, and self impressed.\nSo witched, Rogero sure some grace deserves,\nIf from his faith his frail affection swerves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At board lyre, lute and harp of tuneful string,\nAnd other sounds, in mixed diversity,\nMade, round about, the joyous palace ring,\nWith glorious concert and sweet harmony.\nNor lacked there well-accorded voice to sing\nOf love, its passion and its ecstasy;\nNor who, with rare inventions, choicely versed,\nDelightful fiction to the guests rehearsed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What table, spread by whatsoever heir\nOf Ninus, though triumphant were the board,\nOr what more famous and more costly, where\nCleopatra feasted with the Latian lord,\nCould with this banquet's matchless joys compare,\nBy the fond fairy for Rogero stored?\nI think not such a feast is spread above,\nWhere Ganymede presents the cup to Jove."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They form a ring, the board and festive cheer\nRemoved, and sitting, play a merry game:\nEach asks, still whispering in a neighbour's ear,\nWhat secret pleases best; to knight and dame\nA fair occasion, without let or fear,\nTheir love, unheard of any, to proclaim.\nAnd in conclusion the two lovers plight\nTheir word, to meet together on that night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Soon, and much sooner than their wont, was ended\nThe game at which the palace inmates play:\nWhen pages on the troop with torches tended,\nAnd with their radiance chased the night away.\nTo seek his bed the paladin ascended,\nGirt with that goodly squadron, in a gay\nAnd airy bower, appointed for his rest,\nMid all the others chosen as the best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when of comfits and of cordial wine\nA fitting proffer has been made anew,\nThe guests their bodies reverently incline,\nAnd to their bowers depart the courtly crew.\nHe upon perfumed sheets, whose texture fine\nSeemed of Arachne's loom, his body threw:\nHearkening this while with still attentive ears,\nIf he the coming of the lady hears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At every movement heard on distant floor,\nHoping 'twas her, Rogero raised his head:\nHe thinks he hears; but it is heard no more,\nThen sighs at his mistake: ofttimes from bed\nHe issued, and undid his chamber door,\nAnd peeped abroad, but still no better sped;\nAnd cursed a thousand times the hour that she\nSo long retarded his felicity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yes, now she comes,\" the stripling often said,\nAnd reckoned up the paces, as he lay,\nWhich from her bower where haply to be made\nTo that where he was waiting for the fay.\nThese thoughts, and other thoughts as vain, he weighed\nBefore she came, and restless at her stay,\nOften believed some hinderance, yet unscanned,\nMight interpose between the fruit and hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At length, when dropping sweets the costly fay\nHad put some end to her perfumery,\nThe time now come she need no more delay,\nSince all was hushed within the palace, she\nStole from her bower alone, through secret way,\nAnd passed towards the chamber silently,\nWhere on his couch the youthful cavalier\nLay, with a heart long torn by Hope and Fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the successor of Astolpho spies\nThose smiling stars above him, at the sight\nA flame, like that of kindled sulphur, flies\nThrough his full veins, as ravished by delight\nOut of himself; and now up to the eyes\nPlunged in a sea of bliss, he swims outright.\nHe leaps from bed and folds her to his breast,\nNor waits until the lady he undressed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though but in a light sendal clad, that she\nWore in the place of farthingale or gown;\nWhich o'er a shift of finest quality,\nAnd white, about her limbs the fay had thrown:\nThe mantle yielded at his touch, as he\nEmbraced her, and that veil remained alone,\nWhich upon every side the damsel shows,\nMore than clear glass the lily or the rose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The plant no closer does the ivy clip,\nWith whose green boughs its stem is interlaced.\nThan those fond lovers, each from either's lip\nThe balmy breath collecting, he embraced:\nRich perfume this, whose like no seed or slip\nBears in sweet Indian or Sabacan waste;\nWhile so to speak their joys is either fixed,\nThat oftentimes those meeting lips are mixed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These things were carried closely by the dame\nAnd youth, or if surmised, were never bruited;\nFor silence seldom was a cause for blame,\nBut oftener as a virtue well reputed.\nBy those shrewd courtiers, conscious of his claim,\nRogero is with proffers fair saluted:\nWorshipped of all those inmates, who fulfil\nIn this the enamoured far, Alcina's will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No pleasure is omitted there; since they\nAlike are prisoners in Love's magic hall.\nThey change their raiment twice or thrice a day,\nNow for this use, and now at other call.\n'Tis often feast, and always holiday;\n'Tis wrestling, tourney, pageant, bath, and ball.\nNow underneath a hill by fountain cast,\nThey read the amorous lays of ages past:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now by glad hill, or through the shady dale,\nThey hunt the fearful hare, and now they flush\nWith busy dog, sagacious of the trail,\nWild pheasant from the stubble-field or bush.\nNow where green junipers perfume the gale,\nSuspend the snare, or lime the fluttering thrush:\nAnd casting now for fish, with net or book,\nDisturb their secret haunts in pleasant brook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero revels there, in like delight,\nWhile Charles and Agramant are troubled sore.\nBut not for him their story will I slight,\nNor Bradamant forget: who evermore,\nMid toilsome pain and care, her cherished knight,\nRavished from her, did many a day deplore;\nWhom by unwonted ways, transported through\nMid air, the damsel saw, nor whither knew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of her I speak before the royal pair,\nWho many days pursued her search in vain;\nBy shadowy wood, or over champaign bare,\nBy farm and city, and by hill and plain;\nBut seeks her cherished friend with fruitless care,\nDivided by such space of land and main:\nOften she goes among the Paynim spears,\nYet never aught of her Rogero hears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of hundreds questioned, upon every side,\nEach day, no answer ever gives content.\nShe roams from post to post, and far and wide\nSearches pavilion, lodging, booth, or rent,\nAnd this, mid foot or horsemen, unespied,\nMay safely do, without impediment,\nThanks to the ring, whose more than mortal aid,\nWhen in her mouth, conceals the vanished maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She cannot, will not, think that he is dead;\nBecause the wreck of such a noble knight\nWould, from Hydaspes' distant waves have spread,\nTo where the sun descends with westering light.\nShe knows not what to think, nor whither sped,\nHe roams in earth or air; yet, hapless wight,\nHim ever seeks, and for attendant train\nHas sobs and sighs, and every bitter pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At length to find the wondrous cave she thought,\nWhere the prophetic homes of Merlin lie,\nAnd there lament herself until she wrought\nUpon the pitying marble to reply;\nFor thence, if yet he lived would she be taught,\nOf this glad life to hard necessity\nHad yielded up; and, when she was possessed\nOf the seer's councils, would pursue the best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With this intention, Bradamant her way\nDirected thither, where in Poictier's wood\nThe vocal tomb, containing Merlin's clay,\nConcealed in Alpine place and savage, stood.\nBut that enchantress sage, who night and day\nThought of the damsel, watchful for her good,\nShe, I repeat, who taught her what should be\nIn that fair grotto her posterity;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She who preserved her with protecting care,\nThat same enchantress, still benign and wise,\nWho, knowing she a matchless race should bear\nOf men, or rather semi-deities,\nSpies daily what her thoughts and actions are,\nAnd lots for her each day, divining, tries; —\nShe all Rogero's fortune knew, how freed;\nThen borne to India by the griffin steed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him on that courser plainly she had eyed,\nWho would not the controlling rein obey;\nWhen, severed by such interval, he hied,\nBorne through the perilous, unwonted way:\nAnd knew that he sport, dance, and banquet plied,\nAnd lapt in idleness and pleasure lay;\nNor memory of his lord nor of the dame,\nOnce loved so well, preserved, not of his fame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And thus such gentle knight ingloriously\nWould have consumed his fairest years and best,\nIn long inaction, afterwards to be,\nBody and soul, destroyed; and that, possessed\nAlone by us in perpetuity.\nThat flower, whose sweets outlive the fragile rest\nWhich quickens man when he in earth is laid,\nWould have been plucked or severed in the blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But that enchantress kind, who with more care\nThan for himself he watched, still kept the knight,\nDesigned to drag him, by rough road and bare,\nTowards true virtue, in his own despite;\nAs often cunning leech will burn and pare\nThe flesh, and poisonous drug employ aright:\nWho, though at first his cruel art offend,\nIs thanked, since he preserves us in the end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, not like old Atlantes, rendered blind\nBy the great love she to the stripling bore,\nSet not on gifting him with life her mind,\nAs was the scope of that enchanter hoar;\nWho, reckless all of fame and praise declined,\nWished length of days to his Rogero more\nThan that, to win a world's applause, the peer\nShould of his joyous life forego one year."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By him he to Alcina's isle had been\nDispatched, that in her palace he might dwell,\nForgetting arms; and, as enchanter seen\nIn magic and the use of every spell,\nThe heart had fastened of that fairy-queen,\nEnamoured of the gentle youth, so well,\nThat she the knot would never disengage,\nThough he should live to more than Nestor's age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Returning now to her that well foreknew\nWhatever was to come to pass, I say\nShe thither did her journey straight pursue,\nWhere she met Aymon's daughter by the way\nForlorn and wandering: Bradamant at view\nOf her enchantress, erst to grief a prey,\nChanges it all to hope: the other tells\nThat with Alcina her Rogero dwells."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nigh dead the maid remains, in piteous guise,\nHearing of him so far removed, and more\nGrieves that she danger to her love descries,\nSave this some strong and speedy cure restore.\nBut her the enchantress comforts, and applies\nA salve where it was needed most, and swore\nThat few short days should pass before anew\nRogero should return to glad her view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Since thou, an antidote to sorcery,\nLady (she said), the virtuous ring dost wear,\nI have no doubt if to yon island I\nThis, where thine every good is hidden, hear,\nTo foil Alcina's wiles and witchery,\nAnd thence to bring thee back thy cherished care.\nThis evening, early, will I hence away,\nAnd be in India by the break of day.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And told to her, the tale continuing,\nThe mode which she was purposing to employ,\nFrom that effeminate, soft realm to bring\nBack into warlike France the cherished boy.\nBradamant from her finger slipt the ring,\nNor this alone would have bestowed with joy;\nBut heart and life would at her feet have laid,\nIf she had deemed they could Rogero aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Giving the ring, her cause she recommends\nTo her, and recommends Rogero more.\nCountless salutes by her the damsel sends,\nThen of Provence, departing seeks the shore.\nThe enchantress to another quarter wends;\nAnd, for the execution of her lore,\nConjures, that eve, a palfrey, by her art,\nWith one foot red, black every other part."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Some Farfarello, or Alchino he,\nI think, whom in that form she raised from hell;\nAnd with loose hair, dishevelled horribly,\nUngirt and barefoot, mounted in the sell.\nBut, with wise caution, from her finger she\nWithdrew the ring, lest it should mar the spell:\nAnd then by him was with such swiftness born,\nShe in Alcina's isle arrived at morn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Herself she changed with wonderful disguise,\nAdding a palm of stature to her height;\nAnd made her limbs of a proportioned size;\nAnd of the very measure seemed to sight,\nAs was she deemed, the necromancer wise,\nWho with such care had reared the youthful knight.\nWith long-descending beard she clothed her chin,\nAnd wrinkled o'er her front and other skin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To imitate his speech, and face, and cheer,\nShe knew so well, that, by the youth descried,\nShe might the sage Atlantes' self appear;\nNext hid, and watched so long, that she espied\nUpon a day (rare chance the cavalier ) \n\nAt length detached from his Alcina's side:\nFor still, in motion or at rest, the fay\nIll bore the youth should be an hour away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Alone she finds him, fitting well her will,\nAs he enjoys the pure and morning air\nBeside a brook, which trickled from a hill,\nStreaming towards a limpid lake and fair.\nHis fine, soft garments, wove with cunning skill,\nAll over, ease and wantonness declare;\nThese with her hand, such subtle toil well taught,\nFor him in silk and gold Alcina wrought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "About the stripling's neck, a splendid string\nOf gems, descending to mid-breast, is wound;\nOn each once manly arm, now glittering\nWith the bright hoop, a bracelet fair is bound.\nPierced with golden wire, in form of ring,\nIs either ear; and from the yellow round\nDepend two precious pearls; not such the coast\nOf Araby or sumptuous India boast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Crisped into comely ringlets was his hair,\nWet with the costliest odours and the best;\nAnd soft and amorous all his gestures were,\nLike one who does Valentian lady's hest.\nIn him, beside his name, was nothing fair,\nAnd more than half corrupted all the rest.\nSo was Rogero found, within that dell,\nChanged from his former self by potent spell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him in the figure of Atlantes sage\nShe fronts, who bore the enchanter's borrowed cheer;\nWith that grave face, and reverend with age,\nWhich he was always wonted to revere;\nAnd with that eye, which in his pupillage,\nBeaming with wrath, he whilom so did fear.\nAnd sternly cries, \"Is this the fruit at last\nWhich pays my tedious pain and labour past?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The marrow of the lion and the bear\nDidst thou for this thine early banquet make,\nAnd, trained by me, by cliff or cavern-lair,\nStrangle with infant hands the crested snake;\nTheir claws from tiger and from panther tear,\nAnd tusks from living boar in tangled brake,\nThat, bred in such a school, in thee should I\nAlcina's Atys or Adonis spy?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Is this the hope that stars, observed by me,\nSigns in conjunction, sacred fibres, bred;\nWith what beside of dream or augury,\nAnd all those lots I but too deeply read,\nWhich, while yet hanging at the breast, of thee,\nWhen these thy years should be accomplished, said,\nThy fears should so be bruited far and near,\nThou justly should be deemed without a peer?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This does, in truth, a fair beginning show;\nA seed which, we may hope, will soon conceive\nA Julius, Alexander, Scipio.\nWho thee Alcina's bondsman could believe;\nAnd (for the world the shameful fact might know)\nThat all should, manifest to sight, perceive\nUpon thy neck and arms the servile chains,\nWherewith she at her will her captive trains?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If thine own single honour move not thee,\nAnd the high deeds which thou art called to do,\nWherefore defraud thy fair posterity\nOf what, was oft predicted, should ensue?\nAlas!  why seal the womb God willed should be\nPregnant by thee with an illustrious crew,\nThat far renowned, and more than human line,\nDestined the sun in glory to outshine?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Forbid not of the noblest souls the birth,\nFormed in the ideas of Eternal Mind,\nDestined, from age to age, to visit earth,\nSprung from thy stock, and clothed in corporal rind;\nThe spring of thousand palms and festal mirth,\nThrough which, to Italy with losses pined\nAnd wounds, thy good descendants shall restore\nThe fame and honours she enjoyed of yore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not only should these many souls have weight\nTo bend thy purpose, holy souls, and bright,\nWhich from thy fruitful tree shall vegetate;\nBut, though alone, a single couple might\nSuffice a nobler feeling to create,\nAlphonso and his brother Hyppolite:\nWhose like was seldom witnessed to this time,\nThrough all the paths whence men to virtue climb."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I was more wont to dwell upon this pair\nThan all the rest, of whom I prophesied;\nAs well that these a greater part should bear\nIn lofty virtues, as that I descried\nThee, listening to my lore with closer care,\nThan to the tale of all thy seed beside.\nI saw thee joy that such a pair would shine\nAmid the heroes of thy noble line."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Say, what has she, thou makest thy fancy's queen,\nMore than what other courtezans possess?\nWho of so many concubine has been;\nHow used her lovers in the end to bless,\nThou truly know'st: but that she may be seen\nWithout disguise, and in her real dress,\nThis ring, returning, on thy finger wear,\nAnd thou shalt see the dame, and mark how fair.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Abashed and mute, Rogero, listening,\nIn vain to her reproof an answer sought:\nWho on his little finger put the ring,\nWhose virtue to himself the warrior brought.\nAnd such remorse and shame within him spring,\nWhen on his altered sense the change is wrought,\nA thousand fathoms deep he fain would lie\nBuried in earth, unseen of any eye."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So speaking, to the natural shape she wore\nBefore his eyes returned the magic dame;\nNor old Atlantes' form was needed more,\nThe good effect obtained for which she came.\nTo tell you that which was not told before,\nMelissa was the sage enchantress' name:\nWho to Rogero now her purpose said,\nAnd told with what design she thither sped:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dispatched by her, who him in anxious pain\nDesires, nor longer can without him be,\nWith the intent to loose him from the chain\nWherewith he was begirt by sorcery;\nAnd had put on, more credence to obtain,\nAtlantes de Carena's form; but she,\nSeeing his health restored, now willed the youth,\nThrough her should hear and see the very truth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That gentle lady who so loves thee, who\nWere well deserving love upon thy part;\nTo whom (unless forgot, thou know'st how true\nThe tale thou debtor for thy freedom art, ) \n\nThis ring, which can each magic spell undo,\nSends for thy succour, and would send her heart,\nIf with such virtue fraught, her heart could bring\nThee safely in thy perils, like the ring.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How Bradamant had loved, and loves, she says,\nContinuing to Rogero her relation;\nTo this, her worth commends with fitting praise,\nTempering in truth and fondness her narration;\nAnd still employs the choicest mode and phrase,\nWhich fits one skilful in negociation,\nAnd on the false Alcina brings such hate,\nAs on things horrible is wont to wait;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Brings hate on that which he so loved before;\nNor let the tale astonish which you hear,\nFor since his love was forced by magic lore,\nThe ring the false enchantment served to clear.\nThis too unmasked the charms Alcina wore,\nAnd made all false, from head to food, appear.\nNone of her own, but borrowed, all he sees,\nAnd the once sparkling cup now drugged with lees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Like boy who somewhere his ripe fruit bestows,\nAnd next forgets the place where it is laid,\nThen, after many days, conducted goes\nBy chance, where he the rich deposit made,\nAnd wonders that the hidden treasure shows,\nNot what it is, but rotten and decayed;\nAnd hates, and scorns, and loathes, with altered eyes,\nAnd throws away what he was used to prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero thus, when by Melissa's lore\nAdvised, he to behold the fay returned,\nAnd that good ring of sovereign virtue wore,\nWhich, on the finger placed, all spells o'erturned;\nFor that fair damsel he had left before,\nTo his surprise, so foul a dame discerned,\nThat in this ample world, examined round,\nA hag so old and hideous is not found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pale, lean, and wrinkled was the face, and white,\nAnd thinly clothed with hair Alcina's head;\nHer stature reached not to six palms in height,\nAnd every tooth was gone; for she had led\nA longer life than ever mortal wight,\nThan Hecuba or she in Cuma bred;\nBut thus by practice, to our age unknown,\nAppeared with youth and beauty not her own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By art she gave herself the lovely look,\nWhich had on many like Rogero wrought;\nBut now the ring interpreted the book,\nWhich secrets, hid for many ages, taught.\nNo wonder then that he the dame forsook,\nAnd banished from his mind all further thought\nOf love for false Alcina, found in guise\nWhich no new means of slippery fraud supplies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But, as Melissa counselled him, he wore\nHis wonted semblance for a time, till he\nWas with his armour, many days before\nLaid by, again accoutred cap-a-pee.\nAnd, lest Alcina should his end explore,\nFeigned to make proof of his agility;\nFeigned to make proof if for his arms he were\nToo gross, long time unwont the mail to bear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next Balisarda to his flank he tied\n(For so Rogero's trenchant sword was hight),\nAnd took the wondrous buckler, which, espied,\nNot only dazzled the beholder's sight,\nBut seemed, when its silk veil was drawn aside,\nAs from the body if exhaled the sprite:\nIn its close cover of red sendal hung,\nThis at his neck the youthful warrior slung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Provided thus, he to the stables came,\nAnd bade with bridle and with saddle dight\nA horse more black than pitch; for so the dame\nCounselled, well-taught how swift the steed and light.\nHim Rabicano those who know him name,\nAnd he the courser was, that with the knight,\nWho stands beside the sea, the breeze's sport,\nThe whale of yore conducted to that port."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The hippogryph he might have had at need,\nWho next below good Rabican was tied,\nBut that the dame had cried to him, \"Take heed,\nThou know'st how ill that courser is to ride\";\nAnd said the following day the winged steed\n'Twas her intention from that realm to guide,\nWhere he should be instructed at his leisure,\nTo rein and run him every where at pleasure:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor, if he took him not, would he suggest\nSuspicion of the intended flight: The peer\nThis while performed Melissa's every hest,\nWho, still invisible, was at his ear.\nSo feigning, from the wanton dome possessed\nBy that old strumpet, rode the cavalier;\nAnd pricking forth drew near unto a gate,\nWhence the road led to Logistilla's state."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Assaulting suddenly the guardian crew,\nHe, sword in hand, the squadron set upon;\nThis one he wounded, and that other slew,\nAnd, point by point made good, the drawbridge won:\nAnd ere of his escape Alcina knew,\nThe gentle youth was far away and gone.\nMy next shall tell his route, and how he gained\nAt last the realm where Logistilla reigned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 8"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero flies; Astolpho with the rest,\nTo their true shape Melissa does restore;\nRinaldo levies knights and squadrons, pressed\nIn aid of Charles assaulted by the Moor:\nAngelica, by ruffians found at rest,\nIs offered to a monster on the shore.\nOrlando, warned in visions of his ill,\nDeparts from Paris sore against his will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How many enchantresses among us!  oh,\nHow many enchanters are there, though unknown!\nWho for their love make man or woman glow,\nChanging them into figures not their own.\nNor this by help of spirits from below,\nNor observation of the stars is done:\nBut these on hearts with fraud and falsehood plot,\nBinding them with indissoluble knot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who with Angelica's, or rather who\nWere fortified with Reason's ring, would see\nEach countenance, exposed to open view,\nUnchanged by art or by hypocrisy.\nThis now seems fair and good, whose borrowed hue\nRemoved, would haply foul and evil be.\nWell was it for Rogero that he wore\nThe virtuous ring which served the truth to explore!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, still dissembling, as I said,\nArmed, to the gate on Rabican did ride;\nFound the guard unprepared, not let his blade,\nAmid that crowd, hang idle at his side:\nHe passed the bridge, and broke the palisade,\nSome slain, some maimed; then t'wards the forest hied;\nBut on that road small space had measured yet,\nWhen he a servant of the fairy met."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He on his fist a ravening falcon bore,\nWhich he made fly for pastime every day;\nNow on the champaign, now upon the shore\nOf neighbouring pool, which teemed with certain prey;\nAnd rode a hack which simple housings wore,\nHis faithful dog, companion of his way.\nHe, marking well the haste with which he hies,\nConjectures truly what Rogero flies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Towards him came the knave, with semblance haught,\nDemanding whither in such haste he sped:\nTo him the good Rogero answers naught.\nHe hence assured more clearly that he fled,\nWithin himself to stop the warrior thought,\nAnd thus, with his left arm extended, said:\n\"What, if I suddenly thy purpose balk,\nAnd thou find no defence against this hawk?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then flies his bird, who works so well his wing,\nRabican cannot distance him in flight:\nThe falconer from his back to ground did spring,\nAnd freed him from the bit which held him tight;\nWho seemed an arrow parted from the string,\nAnd terrible to foe, with kick and bite;\nWhile with such haste behind the servant came,\nHe sped as moved by wind, or rather flame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor will the falconer's dog appear more slow;\nBut hunts Rogero's courser, as in chace\nOf timid hare the pard is wont to go.\nNot to stand fast the warrior deems disgrace,\nAnd turns towards the swiftly-footed foe,\nWhom he sees wield a riding-wand, place\nOf other arms, to make his dog obey.\nRogero scorns his faulchion to display."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The servant made at him, and smote him sore;\nThe dog his left foot worried; while untied\nFrom rein, the lightened horse three times and more\nLashed from the croup, nor missed his better side.\nThe hawk, oft wheeling, with her talons tore\nThe stripling, and his horse so terrified,\nThe courser, by the whizzing sound dismayed,\nLittle the guiding hand or spur obeyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Constrained at length, his sword Rogero drew\nTo clear the rabble, who his course delay;\nAnd in the animals' or villain's view\nDid now its point, and now its edge display.\nBut with more hinderance and vexatious crew\nSwarm here and there, and wholly block the way;\nAnd that dishonour will ensue and loss,\nRogero sees, if him they longer cross."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He knew each little that he longer stayed,\nWould bring the fay and followers on the trail;\nAlready drums were beat, and trumpets brayed,\nAnd larum-bells rang loud in every vale.\nAn act too foul it seemed to use his blade\nOn dog, and knave unfenced with arms or mail:\nA better and shorter way it were\nThe buckler, old Atlantes' work, to bare."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He raised the crimson cloth in which he wore\nThe wondrous shield, enclosed for many a day;\nIts beams, as proved a thousand times before,\nWork as they wont, when on the sight they play;\nSenseless the falconer tumbles on the moor;\nDrop dog and hackney; drop the pinions gay,\nWhich poised in air the bird no longer keep:\nThen glad Rogero leaves a prey to sleep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the mean time, Alcina, who had heard\nHow he had forced the gate, and, in the press,\nSlaughtered a mighty number of her guard,\nRemained nigh dead, o'erwhelmed with her distress;\nShe tore her vesture, and her visage marred,\nAnd cursed her want of wit and wariness.\nThen made forthwith her meiny sound to arms,\nAnd round herself arrayed her martial swarms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Divided next, one squadron by the way\nRogero took, she sent; the bands were two:\nShe at the port embarked the next array,\nAnd straight to sea dispatched the warlike crew.\nWith this good squadron went the desperate fay,\nAnd darked by loosened sails the billows grew;\nFor so desire upon her bosom preyed,\nOf troops she left her city unpurveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Without a guard she left her palace there,\nWhich to Melissa, prompt her time to seize,\nTo loose her vassals that in misery were,\nAfforded all convenience and full ease;\n— To range, at leisure, through the palace fair,\nAnd so examine all her witcheries;\nTo raze the seal, burn images, and loose\nOr cancel hag-knot, rhomb, or magic noose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thence, through the fields, fast hurrying from that dome,\nThe former lovers changed, a mighty train,\nSome into rock or tree, to fountain some,\nOr beast, she made assume their shapes again:\nAnd these, when they anew are free to roam,\nFollow Rogero's footsteps to the reign\nOf Logistilla's sage; and from that bourn\nTo Scythia, Persia, Greece, and Ind return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They to their several homes dispatched, repair,\nBound by a debt which never can be paid:\nThe English duke, above the rest her care,\nOf these, was first in human form arrayed:\nFor much his kindred and the courteous prayer\nOf good Rogero with Melissa weighed.\nBeside his prayers, the ring Rogero gave;\nThat him she by its aid might better save."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus by Rogero's suit the enchantress won,\nTo his first shape transformed the youthful peer;\nBut good Melissa deemed that nought was done\nSave she restored his armour, and that spear\nOf gold, which whensoe'er at tilt he run,\nAt the first touch unseated cavalier;\nOnce Argalia's, next Astolpho's lance,\nAnd source of mighty fame to both in France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The sage Melissa found this spear of gold,\nWhich now Alcina's magic palace graced,\nAnd other armour of the warrior bold,\nOf which he was in that ill dome uncased.\nShe climbed the courser of the wizard old,\nAnd on the croup, at ease, Astolpho placed:\nAnd thus, an hour before Rogero came,\nRepaired to Logistilla, knight and dame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meantime, through rugged rocks, and shagged with thorn,\nRogero wends, to seek the sober fay;\nFrom cliff to cliff, from path to path forlorn,\nA rugged, lone, inhospitable way:\nTill he, with labour huge oppressed and worn,\nIssued at noon upon a beach, that lay\n'Twixt sea and mountain, open to the south,\nDeserted, barren, bare, and parched with drouth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The sunbeams on the neighbouring mountain beat\nAnd glare, reflected from the glowing mass\nSo fiercely, sand and air both boil with heat,\nIn mode that might have more than melted glass.\nThe birds are silent in their dim retreat,\nNor any note is heard in wood or grass,\nSave the bough perched Cicala's wearying cry,\nWhich deafens hill and dale, and sea and sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The heat and thirst and labour which he bore\nBy that drear sandy way beside the sea,\nAlong the unhabited and sunny shore,\nWere to Rogero grievous company:\nBur for I may not still pursue this lore,\nNor should you busied with one matter be,\nRogero I abandon in this heat,\nFor Scotland; to pursue Rinaldo's beat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By king, by daughter, and by all degrees,\nTo Sir Rinaldo was large welcome paid;\nAnd next the warrior, at his better ease,\nThe occasion of his embassy displayed:\nThat he from thence and England, subsidies\nOf men was seeking, for his monarch's aid,\nIn Charles's name; and added, in his care,\nThe justest reasons to support his prayer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king made answer, that `without delay,\nTaxed to the utmost of his powers and might,\nHis means at Charlemagne's disposal lay,\nFor the honour of the empire and the right.\nAnd that, within few days, he in array\nSuch horsemen, as he had in arms, would dight;\nAnd, save that he was now waxed old, would lead\nThe expedition he was prayed to speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "`Nor like consideration would appear\nWorthy to stop him, but that he possessed\nA son, and for such charge that cavalier,\nMeasured by wit and force, was worthiest.\nThough not within the kingdom was the peer,\nIt was his hope (as he assured his guest)\nHe would, while yet preparing was the band,\nReturn, and find it mustered to his hand.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So sent through all his realm, with expedition,\nHis treasures, to levy men and steeds;\nAnd ships prepared, and warlike ammunition,\nAnd money, stores and victual for their needs.\nMeantime the good Rinaldo on his mission,\nLeaving the courteous king, to England speeds;\nHe brought him on his way to Berwick's town,\nAnd was observed to weep when he was gone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The wind sat in the poop; Rinaldo good\nEmbarked and bade farewell to all; the sheet\nStill loosening to the breeze, the skipper stood,\nTill where Thames' waters, waxing bitter, meet\nSalt ocean: wafted thence by tide of flood,\nThrough a sure channel to fair London's seat,\nSafely the mariners their course explore,\nMaking their way, with aid of sail and oar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Emperor Charles, and he, King Otho grave,\nWho was with Charles, by siege in Paris pressed,\nA broad commission to Rinaldo brave,\nWith letters to the Prince of Wales addressed,\nAnd countersigns had given, dispatched to crave\nWhat foot and horse were by the land possessed.\nThe whole to be to Calais' port conveyed;\nThat it to France and Charles might furnish aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The prince I speak of, who on Otho's throne\nSate in his stead, the vacant helm to guide,\nSuch honor did to Aymon's valiant son,\nHe not with such his king had gratified.\nNext, all to good Rinaldo's wish, was done:\nSince for his martial bands on every side,\nIn Britain, or the isles which round her lay,\nTo assemble near the sea he fixed a day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But here, sir, it behoves me shift my ground,\nLike him that makes the sprightly viol ring,\nWho often changes chord and varies sound,\nAnd now a graver strikes, now sharper string:\nThus I: — who did to good Rinaldo bound\nMy tale, Angelica remembering;\nLate left, where saved from him by hasty flight,\nShe had encountered with an anchorite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Awhile I will pursue her story: I\nTold how the maid of him with earnest care,\nEnquired, how she towards the shore might fly:\nWho of the loathed Rinaldo has such fear,\nShe dreads, unless she pass the sea, to die,\nAs insecure in Europe, far or near,\nBut she was by the hermit kept in play,\nBecause he pleasure took with her to stay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His heart with love of that rare beauty glowed,\nAnd to his frozen marrow pierced the heat;\nWho, after, when he saw that she bestowed\nSmall care on him, and thought but of retreat,\nHis sluggish courser stung with many a goad;\nBut with no better speed he plied his feet.\nIll was his walk, and worse his trot; nor spur\nCould that dull beast to quicker motion stir:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And for the flying maid was far before,\nAnd he would soon have ceased to track her steed,\nTo the dark cave recurred the hermit hoar,\nAnd conjured up of fiends a grisly breed:\nOne he selected out of many more,\nAnd first informed the demon of his need;\nThen in the palfrey bade him play his part,\nWho with the lady bore away his heart:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And as sagacious dog on mountain tried\nBefore, accustomed fox and hare to chase,\nIf he behold the quarry choose one side,\nThe other takes, and seems to slight the trace:\nBut at the turn arriving, is espied,\nAlready tearing what he crossed to face;\nSo her the hermit by a different road\nWill meet, wherever she her palfrey goad."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What was the friar's design I well surmise;\nAnd you shall know; but in another page.\nAngelica now slow, now faster, flies,\nNought fearing this: while conjured by the sage,\nThe demon covered in the courser lies;\nAs fire sometimes will hide its smothered rage:\nThen blazes with devouring flame and heat,\nUnquenchable, and scarce allows retreat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the flying maid had shaped her course\nBy the great sea which laves the Gascon shore,\nStill keeping to the rippling waves her horse,\nWhere best the moistened sand the palfrey bore,\nHim, plunged into the brine, the fiend perforce\nDragged, till he swam amid the watery roar.\nNor what to do the timid damsel knew,\nSave that she closer to her saddle grew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She cannot, howsoe'er the rein she ply,\nGovern the horse, who swims the surge to meet:\nHer raiment she collects and holds it high;\nAnd, not to wet them, gathers up her feet.\nHer tresses, which the breeze still wantonly\nAssaults, dishevelled on her shoulders beat.\nThe louder winds are hushed, perchance in duty,\nIntent, like ocean, on such sovereign beauty."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Landward in vain her eyes the damsel bright\nDirects, which water face and breast with tears,\nAnd ever sees, decreasing to her sight,\nThe beach she left, which less and less appears.\nThe courser, who was swimming to the right,\nAfter a mighty sweep, the lady bears\nTo shore, where rock and cavern shag the brink,\nAs night upon the land begins to sink."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When in that desert, which but to descry\nBred fear in the beholder, stood the maid\nAlone, as Phoebus, plunged in ocean, sky\nAnd nether earth had left obscured in shade;\nShe paused in guise, which in uncertainty\nMight leave whoever had the form surveyed,\nIf she were real woman, or some mock\nResemblance, coloured in the living rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, fixed and stupid in her wretchedness,\nStood on the shifting sand, with ruffled hair:\nHer hands were joined, her lips were motionless,\nHer languid eyes upturned, as in despair,\nAccusing Him on high, that to distress\nAnd whelm her, all the fates united were.\nAstound she stood awhile; when grief found vent\nThrough eyes and tongue, in tears and in lament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Fortune what more remains, that thou on me\nShouldst not now satiate thy revengeful thirst?\nWhat more (she said can I bestow on thee ) \n\nThan, what thou seekest not, this life accurst?\nThou wast in haste to snatch me from the sea,\nWhere I had ended its sad days, immersed;\nBecause to torture me with further ill\nBefore I die, is yet thy cruel will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But what worse torment yet remains in store\nBeyond, I am unable to descry:\nBy thee from my fair throne, which nevermore\nI hope to repossess, compelled to fly;\nI, what is worse, my honour lost deplore;\nFor if I sinned not in effect, yet I\nGive matter by my wanderings to be stung\nFor wantonness of every carping tongue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What other good is left to woman, who\nHas lost her honour, in this earthly ball?\nWhat profits it that, whether false or true,\nI am deemed beauteous, and am young withal?\nNo thanks to heaven for such a gift are due,\nWhence on my head does every mischief fall.\nFor this my brother Argalia died;\nTo whom small help enchanted arms supplied:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For this the Tartar king, Sir Agrican,\nSubdued my sire, who Galaphron was hight,\nAnd of Catay in India was great khan;\n'Tis hence I am reduced to such a plight,\nThat wandering evermore, I cannot scan\nAt morn, where I shall lay my head at night.\nIf thou hast ravished what thou couldst, wealth, friends,\nAnd honour; say what more thy wrath intends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If death by drowning in the foaming sea\nWas not enough thy wrath to satiate,\nSend, if thou wilt, some beast to swallow me,\nSo that he keep me not in pain!  Thy hate\nCannot devise a torment, so it be\nMy death, but I shall thank thee for my fate!\"\nThus, with loud sobs, the weeping lady cried,\nWhen she beheld the hermit at her side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From the extremest height the hermit hoar\nOf that high rock above her, had surveyed\nAngelica, arrived upon the shore,\nBeneath the cliff, afflicted and dismayed.\nHe to that place had come six days before;\nFor him by path untrod had fiend conveyed:\nAnd he approached her, feigning such a call\nAs e'er Hilarion might have had, or Paul."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When him, yet unagnized, she saw appear,\nThe lady took some comfort, and laid by,\nEmboldened by degrees, her former fear:\nThough still her visage was of death-like dye.\n\"Misericord!  father,\" when the friar was near\n(She said), \"for brought to evil pass am I.\"\nAnd told, still broke by sobs, in doleful tone,\nThe story, to her hearer not unknown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To comfort her, some reasons full of grace,\nSage and devout the approaching hermit cites:\nAnd, now his hand upon her moistened face,\nIn speaking, now upon her bosom lights:\nAs her, securer, next he would embrace:\nHim, kindling into pretty scorn, she smites\nWith one hand on his breast, and backward throws,\nThen flushed with honest red, all over glows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A pocket at the ancient's side was dight,\nWhere he a cruise of virtuous liquor wore;\nAnd at those puissant eyes, whence flashed the light\nOf the most radiant torch Love ever bore,\nThrew from the flask a little drop, of might\nTo make her sleep: upon the sandy shore\nAlready the recumbent damsel lay,\nThe greedy elder's unresisting prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "(Stanza XLIX untranslated by Rose)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "(Lines 1-2 untranslated by Rose)\nHopeless, at length upon the beach he lies,\nAnd by the maid, exhausted, falls asleep.\nWhen to torment him new misfortunes rise:\nFortune does seldom any measure keep;\nUnused to cut her cruel pastime short,\nIf she with mortal man is pleased to sport."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It here behoves me, from the path I pressed,\nTo turn awhile, ere I this case relate:\nIn the great northern sea, towards the west,\nGreen Ireland past, an isle is situate.\nEbuda is its name, whose shores infest,\n(Its people wasted through the Godhead's hate)\nThe hideous orc, and Proteus' other herd,\nBy him against that race in vengeance stirred."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Old stories, speak they falsely or aright,\nTell how a puissant king this country swayed;\nWho had a daughter fair, so passing bright\nAnd lovely, 'twas no wonder if the maid,\nWhen on the beach she stood in Proteus' sight,\nLeft him to burn amid the waves: surveyed,\nOne day alone, upon that shore in-isled,\nHer he compressed, and quitted great with child."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was sore torment to the sire, severe\nAnd impious more than all mankind; nor he,\nSuch is the force of wrath, was moved to spare\nThe maid, for reason or for piety.\nNor, though he saw her pregnant, would forbear\nTo execute his sentence suddenly;\nBut bade together with the mother kill,\nEre born, his grandchild, who had done no ill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sea-Proteus to his flocks' wide charge preferred\nBy Neptune, of all ocean's rule possessed,\nInflamed with ire, his lady's torment heard,\nAnd, against law and usage, to molest\nThe land (no sluggard in his anger stirred ) \n\nHis monsters, orc and sea-calf, with the rest;\nWho waste not only herds, but human haunts,\nFarm-house and town, with their inhabitants:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And girding them on every side, the rout\nWill often siege to walled cities lay;\nWhere in long weariness and fearful doubt,\nThe townsmen keep their watch by night and day.\nThe fields they have abandoned all about,\nAnd for a remedy, their last assay,\nTo the oracle, demanding counsel, fly,\nWhich to the suppliant's prayer made this reply:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "`That it behoved them find a damsel, who\nA form as beauteous as that other wore,\nTo be to Proteus offered up, in lieu\nOf the fair lady, slain upon the shore:\nHe, if he deems her an atonement due,\nWill keep the damsel, not disturb them more:\nIf not, another they must still present,\nAnd so, till they the deity content.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this it was the cruel usage bred;\nThat of the damsels held most fair of face,\nTo Proteus every day should one be led.\nTill one should in the Godhead's sight find grace.\nThe first and all those others slain, who fed,\nAll a devouring orc, that kept his place\nBeside the port, what time into the main\nThe remnant of the herd retired again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Were the old tale of Proteus' false or true,\n(For this, in sooth, I know not who can read)\nWith such a clause was kept by that foul crew\nThe savage, ancient statute, which decreed\nThat woman's flesh the ravening monster, who\nFor this came every day to land, should feed.\nThough to be woman is a crying ill\nIn every place, 'tis here a greater still."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "O wretched maids!  whom 'mid that barbarous rout\nIll-fortune on that wretched shore has tost!\nWho for the stranger damsel prowl about,\nOf her to make an impious holocaust;\nIn that the more they slaughter from without,\nThey less the number of their own exhaust.\nBut since not always wind and waves convey\nLike plunder, upon every strand they prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With frigate and with galley wont to roam,\nAnd other sort of barks they range the sea,\nAnd, as a solace to their martyrdom,\nFrom far, or from their isle's vicinity,\nBear women off; with open rapine some,\nThese bought by gold, and those by flattery:\nAnd, plundered from the different lands they scower,\nCrowd with their captives dungeon-cell and tower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Keeping that region close aboard, to explore\nThe island's lonely bank, a gallery creeps;\nWhere, amid stubs upon the grassy shore,\nAngelica, unhappy damsel, sleeps.\nTo wood and water there the sailor's moor,\nAnd from the bark, for this, a party leaps;\nAnd there that matchless flower of earthly charms\nDiscovers in the holy father's arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh!  prize too dear, oh!  too illustrious prey!\nTo glut so barbarous and so base a foe!\nOh!  cruel Fortune!  who believed thy sway\nWas of such passing power in things below?\nThat thou shouldst make a hideous monster's prey\nThe beauty, for which Agrican did glow,\nBrought with half Scythia's people from the gates\nOf Caucasus, in Ind, to find their fates."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beauty, by Circassian Sacripant\nPreferred before his honour and his crown,\nThe beauty which made Roland, Brava's vaunt,\nSully his wholesome judgment and renown,\nThe beauty which had moved the wide Levant,\nAnd awed, and turned its kingdom upside down,\nNow has not (thus deserted and unheard)\nOne to assist it even with a word."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oppressed with heavy sleep upon the shore,\nThe lovely virgin, ere awake, they chain:\nWith her, the enchanter friar the pirates bore\nOn board their ship, a sad, afflicted train.\nThis done, they hoisted up their sail once more,\nAnd the bark made the fatal isle again,\nWhere, till the lot shall of their prey dispose,\nHer prisoned in a castle they enclose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But such her matchless beauty's power, the maid\nWas able that fierce crew to mollify,\nWho many days her cruel death delayed,\nPreserved until their last necessity;\nAnd while they damsels from without purveyed,\nSpared such angelic beauty: finally,\nThe damsel to the monstrous orc they bring,\nThe people all behind her sorrowing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who shall relate the anguish, the lament\nAnd outcry which against the welkin knock?\nI marvel that the sea-shore was not rent,\nWhen she was placed upon the rugged block,\nWhere, chained and void of help, the punishment\nOf loathsome death awaits her on the rock.\nThis will not I, so sorrow moves me, say,\nWhich makes me turn my rhymes another way;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To find a verse of less lugubrious strain,\nTill I my wearied spirit shall restore:\nFor not the squalid snake of mottled stain,\nNor wild and whelpless tiger, angered more,\nNor what of venomous, on burning plain,\nCreeps 'twixt the Red and the Atlantic shore,\nCould see the grisly sight, and choose but moan\nThe damsel bound upon the naked stone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh!  if this chance to her Orlando, who\nWas gone to Paris-town to seek the maid,\nHad been reported!  or those other two,\nDuped by a post, dispatched from Stygian shade,\nThey would have tracked her heavenly footsteps through\nA thousand deaths, to bear the damsel aid.\nBut had the warriors of her peril known.\nSo far removed, for what would that have done?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while round Paris-walls the leaguer lay\nOf famed Troyano's son's besieging band,\nReduced to such extremity one day,\nThat it nigh fell into the foeman's hand;\nAnd, but that vows had virtue to allay\nThe wrath of Heaven, whose waters drenched the land,\nThat day had perished by the Moorish lance\nThe holy empire and great name of France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To the just plaint of aged Charlemagne\nThe great Creator turned his eyes, and stayed\nThe conflagration with a sudden rain,\nWhich haply human art had not allayed.\nWise whosoever seeketh, not in vain,\nHis help, than whose there is no better aid!\nWell the religious king, to whom 'twas given,\nKnew that the saving succour was from Heaven."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All night long counsel of his weary bed,\nVexed with a ceaseless care, Orlando sought;\nNow here, now there, the restless fancy sped,\nNow turned, now seized, but never held the thought:\nAs when, from sun or nightly planet shed,\nClear water has the quivering radiance caught,\nThe flashes through the spacious mansion fly,\nWith reaching leap, right, left, and low, and high."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To memory now returned his lady gay,\nShe rather ne'er was banished from his breast;\nAnd fanned the secret fire, which through the day\n(Now kindled into flame had seemed at rest; ) \n\nThat in his escort even from Catay\nOr farthest Ind, had journeyed to the west;\nThere lost: Of whom he had discerned no token\nSince Charles's power near Bordeaux-town was broken."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This in Orlando moved great grief, and he\nLay thinking on his folly past in vain:\n\"My heart,\" he said, \"oh! how unworthily\nI bore myself!  and out, alas!  what pain,\n(When night and day I might have dwelt with thee,\nSince this thou didst not in thy grace disdain.)\nTo have let them place thee in old Namus' hand!\nWitless a wrong so crying to withstand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Might I not have excused myself? — The king\nHad not perchance gainsaid my better right —\nOf if he had gainsaid my reasoning,\nWho would have taken thee in my despite?\nWhy not have armed, and rather let them wring\nMy heart out of my breast?  But not the might\nOf Charles or all his host, had they been tried,\nCould have availed to tear thee from my side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Oh!  had he placed her but in strong repair,\nGuarded in some good fort, or Paris-town!\n— Since he would trust her to Duke Namus' care,\nThat he should lose her in this way, alone\nSorts with my wish. — Who would have kept the fair\nLike me, that would for her to death have gone?\nHave kept her better than my heart or sight:\nWho should and could, yet did not what I might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Without me, my sweet life, beshrew me, where\nArt thou bestowed, so beautiful and young!\nAs some lost lamb, what time the daylight fair\nShuts in, remains the wildering woods among,\nAnd goes about lamenting here and there,\nHoping to warn the shepherd with her tongue;\nTill the wolf hear from far the mournful strain,\nAnd the sad shepherd weep for her in vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My hope, where are thou, where?  In doleful wise\nDost thou, perchance, yet rove thy lonely round?\nArt thou, indeed, to ravening wolf a prize,\nWithout thy faithful Roland's succour found?\nAnd is the flower, which, with the deities,\nMe, in mid heaven had placed, which, not to wound,\n(So reverent was my love thy feelings chaste, ) \n\nI kept untouched, alas!  now plucked and waste?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If this fair flower be plucked, oh, misery!  oh,\nDespair!  what more is left me but to die?\nAlmighty God, with every other woe\nRather than this, thy wretched suppliant try.\nIf this be true, these hands the fatal blow\nShall deal, and doom me to eternity.\"\nMixing his plaint with bitter tears and sighs,\nSo to himself the grieved Orlando cries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already every where, with due repose,\nCreatures restored their weary spirits; laid\nThese upon stones and upon feathers those,\nOr greensward, in the beech or myrtle's shade:\nBut scarcely did thine eyes, Orlando close,\nSo on thy mind tormenting fancies preyed.\nNor would the vexing thoughts which bred annoy,\nLet thee in peace that fleeting sleep enjoy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To good Orlando it appeared as he,\nMid odorous flowers, upon a grassy bed,\nWere gazing on that beauteous ivory,\nWhich Love's own hand had tinged with native red;\nAnd those two stars of pure transparency,\nWith which he in Love's toils his fancy fed:\nOf those bright eyes, and that bright face, I say,\nWhich from his breast had torn his heart away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He with the fullest pleasure overflows,\nThat ever happy lover did content:\nBut, lo!  this time a mighty tempest rose,\nAnd wasted flowers, and trees uptore and rent.\nNot with the rage with which this whirlwind blows,\nJoust warring winds, north, south, and east, unpent.\nIt seemed, as if in search of covering shade,\nHe, vainly wandering, through a desert strayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile the unhappy lover lost the dame\nIn that dim air, nor how he lost her, weets;\nAnd, roving far and near, her beauteous name\nThrough every sounding wood and plain repeats.\nAnd while, \"Oh wretched me!\" is his exclaim,\n\"Who has to poison changed my promised sweets?\"\nHe of his sovereign lady who with tears\nDemands his aid, the lamentation hears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither, whence comes the sound, he swiftly hies,\nAnd toils, now here, now there, with labour sore:\nOh!  what tormenting grief, to think his eyes\nCannot again the lovely rays explore!\n— Lo!  other voice from other quarter cries —\n\"Hope not on earth to enjoy the blessing more.\"\nAt that alarming cry he woke, and found\nHimself in tears of bitter sorrow drowned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not thinking that like images are vain,\nWhen fear, or when desire disturbs our rest,\nThe thought of her, exposed to shame and pain,\nIn such a mode upon his fancy pressed,\nHe, thundering, leaped from bed, and with what chain\nAnd plate behoved, his limbs all over dressed;\nTook Brigliadoro from the stall he filled,\nNor any squire attendant's service willed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And to pass every where, yet not expose\nBy this his dignity to stain or slight,\nThe old and honoured ensign he foregoes,\nHis ancient bearing, quartered red and white.\nAnd in its place a sable ensign shows,\nPerhaps as suited to his mournful plight,\nThat erst he from an Amostantes bore,\nWhom he had slain in fight some time before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At midnight he departed silently,\nNot to his uncle spake, not to his true\nAnd faithful comrade Brandimart, whom he\nSo dearly cherished, even bade adieu;\nBut when, with golden tresses streaming-free,\nThe sun from rich Tithonus' inn withdrew,\nAnd chased the shades, and cleared the humid air,\nThe king perceived Orlando was not there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Charles, to his displeasure, were conveyed\nNews that his nephew had withdrawn at night,\nWhen most he lacked his presence and his aid;\nNor could he curb his choler at the flight,\nBut that with foul reproach he overlaid,\nAnd sorely threatened the departed knight,\nBy him so foul a fault should be repented,\nSave he, returning home, his wrath prevented."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor would Orlando's faithful Brandimart,\nWho loved him as himself, behind him stay;\nWhether to bring him back he in his heart\nHoped, or of him ill brooked injurious say:\nAnd scarce, in his impatience to depart,\nTill fall of eve his sally would delay.\nLest she should hinder his design, of this\nHe nought imparted to his Flordelis:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him this was a lady passing dear,\nAnd from whose side he unwont to stray;\nEndowed with manners, grace, and beauteous cheer,\nWisdom and wit: if now he went away\nAnd took no leave, it was because the peer\nHoped to revisit her that very day.\nBut that befel him after, as he strayed,\nWhich him beyond his own intent delayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She when she has expected him in vain\nWell nigh a month, and nought of him discerns,\nSallies without a guide or faithful train,\nSo with desire of him her bosom yearns:\nAnd many a country seeks for him in vain;\nTo whom the story in due place returns.\nNo more I now shall tell you of these two,\nMore bent Anglantes' champion to pursue;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who having old Almontes' blazonry\nSo changed, drew nigh the gate; and there the peer\nApproached a captain of the guard, when he;\n\"I am the County,\" whispered in his ear,\nAnd (the bridge quickly lowered, and passage free\nAt his commandment by the way most near ) \n\nWent straight towards the foe: but what befell"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto which ensues shall tell.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 9"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So far Orlando wends, he comes to where\nHe of old Proteus' hears the cruel use\nBut feels such pity for Olympia fair,\nWronged by Cymosco, who in prison mews\nHer plighted spouse, that ere he makes repair\nFurther, he gives her hope to venge the abuse:\nHe does so, and departs; and with his spouse\nDeparts Bireno, to repeat his vows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What cannot, when he has a heart possess'd\nThis false and cruel traitor Love?  since he\nCan banish from Orlando's faithful breast\nSuch tried allegiance and due loyalty?\nWise, full of all regards, and of the blest\nAnd glorious church the champion wont to be,\nNow, little for himself or uncle, driven\nBy a vain love, he cares, and less for heaven."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But I excuse him well, rejoiced to know\nI have like partner in my vice: for still\nTo seek my good I too am faint and slow,\nBut sound and nimble in pursuit of ill.\nThe count departs, disguised in sable show,\nNor for so many friends, with froward will,\nDeserted cares; and comes where on the plain\nAre camped the hosts of Afric and of Spain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rather uncamped: for, in less troops or more,\nRains under shed and tree had driven the band.\nHere ten, there twenty, seven or eight, or four,\nNear or further off, Orlando scanned.\nEach sleeps, oppressed with toil and wearied sore;\nThis stretched on earth, that propped upon his hand:\nThey sleep, and many might the count have slain,\nYet never bared his puissant Durindane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So generous is Orlando's heart, he base\nEsteems it were to smite a sleeping foe.\nNow this he seeks, and now that other place;\nYet cannot track his lady, high or low.\nIf he finds any one in waking case,\nSighing, to him he paints her form and show;\nThen prays him that for courtesy, he where\nThe damsel is, will reach him to repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when the day its shining light displayed,\nHe wholly searched the Moorish army through.\nIn that the gentle warrior was arrayed\nIn Arab weeds, he this might safely do;\nAnd of his purpose came alike in aid\nThat other tongues beside the French he knew;\nAnd in the African so well was read,\nHe seemed in Tripoly one born and bred:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He sojourns there three days, the camp to see;\nStill seeking nought beside: next up and down,\nWithin, without, both burgh and city he\nSpies; nor surveys the realm of France alone;\nBut fair Auvergne, and even Gascony\nRevisits, to its farthest little town.\nRoves from Provence to Brittany's domain,\nAnd from the Picards to the bounds of Spain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Between October and November's moon,\nIn that dull season when the leafy vest\nIs stript from trembling plant, whose limbs are shown\nOf all their mantling foliage dispossess'd\nAnd in close flights the swarming birds are flown,\nOrlando enters on his amorous quest:\nThis he pursues the livelong winter through,\nNor quits when gladsome spring returns anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As (such his wont from land to land he goes, ) \n\nA river's side he reaches on a day;\nWhich to the neighbouring sea in quiet flows.\nBretons and Normans parting on its way:\nBut, swoln with mountain rain and melted snows,\nThen thundered, white with foam and flashing-spray:\nAnd with impetuous stream had overtopt\nIts brim, and burst the bridge, and passage stopt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The paladin this bank and the other eyed,\nAlong the river's channel, to explore,\nSince neither fish nor fowl, if from his side\nHe could gain footing on the adverse shore;\nWhen, with a damsel in the poop, he spied\nA ready pinnace that towards him bore:\nShe steered, as if she would approach the strand;\nBut would not let her shallop make the land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Steered not to land; as haply with suspicion\nTo take a lading, in her own despite.\nTo her the good Orlando made petition\nTo put him o'er the stream; and she: \"No knight\nPasses this ferry, but upon condition\nHe shall his faith and promise duly plight,\nThat he will do a battle, at my prayer,\nUpon the justest quarrel and most fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So that if thou on that other shore to land\nDost by my aid, Sir cavalier, desire,\nPromise me, ere the month which is at hand\"\n(The damsel so pursued her speech \"expire, ) \n\nThat thou wilt join the Hibernian monarch's hand,\nWho forms a fair armada, in his ire,\nTo sack Ebuda's isle; of all compress'd\nBy ocean's circling waves, the cruellest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Know, beyond Ireland, in the briny flood,\nAn island, amid many others, lies;\nEbuda is its name; whose people rude\n(Such is their law), in search of plunder hies;\nAnd all the women that it takes, for food\nTo a voracious animal supplies;\nWhich every day to shore for this does speed,\nAnd finds new wife or maid whereon to feed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For of these merchant still and Corsair sell\nA large supply, and most of those most fair.\nReckoning one slain a-day, you thus may well\nCompute what wives and maids have perished there.\nBut if compassion in your bosom dwell,\nNor you to Love an utter rebel are,\nBe you contented with this band to wend,\nUnited for such profitable end.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To hear the whole Orlando scarce could bear,\nEre to be first in that emprize he swore,\nAs one who evil deed misliked to hear,\nAnd with impatience like relation bore:\nHence first induced to think, and next to fear,\nAngelica is captive on that shore:\nSince he so long the missing maid pursues,\nNor of the damsel yet can gather news."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Breaking his every scheme, this phantasy\nThe troubled cavalier did so confound,\nThat will all speed to that fell island he\nResolved to navigate; nor yet the round\nOf a new sun was buried in the sea,\nEre he a vessel at St. Malo's found;\nIn which, embarking on his quest, the count\nPut forth, and cleared that night St. Michael's Mount."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Breac and Landriglier past on the left hand,\nOrlando's vessel skims the Breton shore;\nThen shapes her course towards the chalky strand,\nWhence England's isle the name of Albion bore:\nBut the south wind, which had her canvas fanned,\nShifts to north-west, and freshening, blows so sore,\nThe mariners are fain to strike all sail,\nAnd wear and scud before the boisterous gale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A distance traversed in four days, in one\nBackwards the ceaseless wind the frigate bore;\nThe helmsman kept the sea, lest she should run\nAground, and break like glass upon the shore.\nThe wind upon the fifth day changed its tune,\nSo loud and furious through the other four;\nAnd let, without more strife, the vessel gain\nA port, where Antwerp's river met the main."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as harboured there in shattered plight,\nThe weary mariners their frigate moor,\nOut of a city, seated on the right\nOf that fair stream, descends upon the shore,\nAs his gray hairs may warrant him, a wight\nStricken in years; who, full of courteous lore,\nTurns to the county, after greetings due,\nReputing him the leader of that crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And prays him, on a damsel's part, `that he\nTo her would think not irksome to repair;\nWhom of unequalled affability\nAnd sweetness, he would find, as well as fair;\nOr otherwise would be content, that she\nShould to his bark resort, to seek him there,\nNor prove less pliant than had been before\nAll the knights errant, who had sought that shore:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For hitherto, by land or sea conveyed,\nNo cavalier had journeyed to that place\nThat had refused to parlay with the maid,\nAnd give her counsel in a cruel case.'\nOrlando, hearing this, no more delayed,\nBut issued from the bark with hurried pace,\nAnd, in all kind and courteous usage bred,\nHis way directed where the ancient led."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With him did Roland to the city go,\nAnd at the bottom of a palace-stair,\nConducted by that elder, full of woe\nA lady found, if face may grief declare,\nAnd sable cloth, with which (a mournful show)\nChamber, and hall, and gallery, furnished were;\nWho, after honourable welcome paid,\nSeated the paladin, and sadly said:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The daughter of the Count of Holland,\" (cried\nThe Lady \"know in me, Sir cavalier. ) \n\nThough not his only offspring (for beside\nMyself two brothers were to him so dear, ) \n\nThat, for whatever favour I applied,\nI never met refusal from the peer.\nI living glady in this happy sort,\nA duke by chance was guested at our court;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The Duke of Zealand, meaning for Biscay;\nWith purpose there to war upon the Moor;\nHis youth and beauty, then in manhood's May,\nAnd force of love, unfelt by me before,\nMade me, with little strife, his easy prey:\nPersuaded by his outward cheer yet more,\nI thought, and think, and still shall think, the peer\nLoved me, and loves me yet with heart sincere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Those days, whenas the wind was contrary,\n(Which fair for me, if foul for others blew)\nTo others forty seemed, an hour to me;\nSo upon speedy wings the moments flew.\nThis while, we oftentimes held colloquy,\nWhen, to be given with solemn right and due,\nI promised him, and he to me, his hand,\nOn his return, in wedlock's holy band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Bireno hardly from our court was gone,\nFor such the name my faithful lover bore,\nWhen Friesland's king, whose realm is from our own\nNo further than this stream from Ocean's shore,\nDesigning to bestow me on his son,\nArbantes hight (the monarch had no more),\nTo Holland sent the worthiest of his land,\nMe of the count, my father, to demand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I without power to falsify that vow,\nWhich to my gentle lover I had plight;\nNor though I had the power, would Love allow\nMe so to play the ingrate, if I might,\n(The treaty, well on foot, to overthrow,\nAnd nigh concluded with afflicted sprite, ) \n\nCried to my father, I would rather shed\nMy very life-blood, than in Friesland wed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My gracious father, he who took but pleasure\nIn what pleased me, nor would my will constrain;\nMarking my grief, broke off the intended measure,\nTo give me comfort and relieve my pain.\nAt this proud Friesland's sovereign such displeasure\nConceived, and entertained such high disdain,\nHe entered Holland, and the war began,\nIn which my kin were slaughtered to a man."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Besides, that both his puissance and his might\nAre such, as in our age are matched of few,\nSuch is in evil deeds his cunning sleight,\nHe laughs to scorn what wit and force can do.\nStrange arms he bears, unknown to any wight,\nSave him, of the ancient nations or the new:\nA hollow iron, two yards long, whose small\nChannel he loads with powder and a ball"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, where 'tis closed behind, in the iron round,\nTouches with fire a vent, discerned with pain;\nIn guise that skilful surgeon tries his ground,\nWhere need requires that he should breathe a vein.\nWhence flies the bullet with such deafening sound,\nThat bolt and lightening from the hollow cane\nAppear to dart, and like the passing thunder,\nBurn what they smite, beat-down or rend asunder."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Twice broken, he our armies overthrew\nWith this device, my gentle brethren slain;\nThe first the shot in our first battle slew,\nReaching his heart, through broken plate and chain;\nThe other in the other onset, who\nWas flying from the fatal field in vain.\nThe ball his shoulder from a distance tore\nBehind, and issued from his breast before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My father next, defending on a day\nThe only fortress which he still possessed,\nThe others taken which about it lay,\nWas sent alike to his eternal rest:\nWho going and returning, to purvey\nWhat lacked, as this or that occasion pressed,\nWas aimed at from afar, in privy wise,\nAnd by the traytour struck between the eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And I remaining, sire and brethren dead,\nThe isle of Holland's only heir, the king\nOf Friesland, who by the desire was led\nOf better there his power establishing,\nTo me, and also to my people said,\nI peace and quiet to my state might bring,\nWould I (when I before would not accord)\nNow take his son Arbantes for my lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I, not so much for deadly hate I bear\nTo him and all his kindred, by whose spite\nMy sire and both my brothers slaughtered were,\nMy country sacked and waste, as that the knight\nI would not wrong, to whom I fealty sware,\nAnd had my solemn word already plight\nThat me to wedlock man should woo in vain,\nTill he to Holland should return from Spain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For one ill-born, a hundred yet behind,\nWill bear (replied to hazard all content, ) \n\n— Slain, burnt alive, to let them to the wind\nScatter my ashes, rather than consent. —\nMy people seek to move my stedfast mind,\nBy prayer and by protest, from this intent;\nAnd threat to yield my city up and me,\nLest all be lost through my obduracy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When in my fixt and firm resolve they read,\nThat prayer and protest are alike in vain;\nMy town and me, with Friesland's king agreed,\nSurrendered, as they vowed, my vassal train.\nNot doing by me any shameful deed,\nMe he assured of life and of domain,\nSo I would soften my obdurate mood,\nAnd be to wed with his Arbantes wooed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I who would have consented to forego\nMy life to scape from him, reflection made,\nThat, save I first avenged myself, all woe\nEndured, would be by this regret outweighed.\n— Long time I muse, and to my misery know,\n'Tis only simulation which can aid.\nNot simple willingness, I feign desire,\nTo win his grace, and have him for my sire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"  Mid many in my father's service, I\nSelect two brothers fitted for my view,\nOf valiant heart and great ability\nBut more approved for truth, as followers, who\nBred in my father's court, from infancy\nHad with myself grown up; the brothers two\nSo wholly bound to me, they would have thought\nMy safety with their lives was cheaply bought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To them I tell my project, and the pair\nOf brethren promise me their faithful aid:\nTo Flanders this, a pinnace to prepare,\nI sent, and that with me in Holland stayed.\nNow, while both foreigners and natives were,\nOf Friesland's kingdom, to our nuptials prayed,\nBireno in Biscay (the tidings went)\nFor Holland had equipt an armament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Since on the issue of the earliest fray,\nWhen in the rout one hapless brother fell,\nI had dispatched a courier to Biscay,\nWho the sad news should to Bireno tell:\nWhile he toils sore his squadron to array,\nProud Friesland's arms our wretched remnant quell.\nBireno, who knew nought of this, had weighed,\nAnd with his barks put forth to bring us aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"These tidings told to Friesland's monarch, he\nConfiding to his son the wedding's care,\nTo meet Bireno's squadron puts to sea,\nAnd (so chance willed burns, sinks, or routs them there, ) \n\nLeading him off into captivity; —\nBut none to us as yet the tidings bear.\nThis while I to the amorous youth am wed,\nWho, when the sun sought his, would seek my bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Behind the curtains, I had hid the tried\nAnd faithful follower, of whom I said,\nWho moved not till the bridegroom he descried,\nYet waited not till he in bed was laid:\nBut raised a hatchet, and so well applied\nBehind the stripling's head the ponderous blade,\nOf speech and life it reft him; I, who note\nThe deed, leap lightly up and cut his throat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As falls the bullock upon shamble-sill,\nThus fell the ill-starred stripling, in despite\nOf king Cymosco, worst among the ill;\nSo was the impious king of Friesland hight\nWho did my brothers and my father kill,\nAnd, in my state to found a better right;\nIn wedlock wished to join me with his son,\nHaply to slay me when his end was won."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ere new disturbance interrupt the deed,\nTaking what costliest was and lightest weighed,\nMe my companion by a chord, with speed,\nDrops from a window, where with boat purveyed\nIn Flanders (as related for my need, ) \n\nHis brother, watchful of our motions, stayed:\nWe dip the oar, we loose the sail, and driven\nBy both, escape, as was the will of Heaven."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The daring feat achieved, I cannot say\nIf Friesland's king more sorrowed for his son,\nOr raged at me: he there arrived, the day\nEnsuing, where the dreadful deed was done,\nProud he returned, both he and his array,\nOf the duke taken, and the victory won:\nAnd thought to feast and nuptials he was bound,\nBut in his home all grief and darkness found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His pity for his son, the hate he fed\nTowards me, torment the father day and night;\nBut as lamenting will not raise the dead,\nAnd vengeance is a vent for smothered spite;\nThat portion of his thoughts, which should have led\nThe king, to ease by sighs his troubled sprite,\nNow willingly takes counsel with his hate,\nTo seize me, and his vengeance satiate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"All known or said to by my friends, or who\nWere friends of those that, chosen from my train,\nHad aided me the deadly deed to do,\nTheir goods and chattels burnt, were doomed or slain:\nAnd he had killed Bireno, since he knew\nNo other trouble could inflict such pain;\nBut that he, saving him in malice, thought\nHe had a net wherewith I might be caught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet him a cruel proposition made,\nGranting a year his purpose to complete;\nCondemned to privy death, till then delayed,\nSave in that time, through force or through deceit,\nHe by his friends' and kindred's utmost aid,\nDoing or plotting, me from my retreat\nConveyed into his prisons; so that he\nCan only saved by my destruction be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What for his safety could be done, behold,\nShort of my own destruction, had been tried.\nSix towns I had in Flanders: these I sold,\nAnd (great or small the produce set aside)\nA part of it, to wily persons told,\nThat it to tempt his guards might be applied;\nThe rest of it dispensed to move and arm\nGermans or English, to the miscreant's harm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My agents, whether they their trust betrayed,\nOr that they could in truth perform no more,\nMe with vain words instead of help have paid,\nAnd scorn me, having drained my scanty store:\nAnd now the term is nigh expired, when aid,\nWhether of open force or treasured ore,\nNo longer will arrive in time to save\nMy cherished spouse from torture and the grave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Through him, from me was my dominion rent;\nThrough him, my father and my brethren slain;\nThrough him, the little treasure left me, spent\n(What served alone existence to sustain)\nTo rescue him, in cruel durance pent;\nNor other means to succour him remain;\nSave I, to liberate him from prison, go\nAnd yield myself to such a cruel foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If nothing more be left me then to try,\nNor other way for his escape appear,\nThan his with this my wretched life to buy,\nThis life I gladly will lay down: one fear\nAlone molests me; and it is that I\nCan never my conditions make so clear,\nAs to assure me, that with new deceit,\nMe, when his prey, the tyrant will not cheat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I fear, when I shall be in captive plight,\nAnd he has put all tortures upon me,\nHe may not loose Bireno, and the knight\nHave not to thank me for his liberty:\nLike perjured king, and full of foul despite,\nWho with my murder will not satiate be;\nBut by Bireno neither less nor more\nWill do, than he had done by me before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The occasion now that I confer with you,\nAnd tell my case to all who seek the land,\nBoth lords and knights, is with the single view,\nThat taking counsel of so large a band,\nSome one may indicate assurance due,\nThat when before the cruel king I stand,\nNo longer he Bireno shall detain;\nNor, after I am killed, the duke be slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Warrior to went with me, I in my need,\nWhen I shall be to Friesland given, have prayed;\nBut so he promise, that the exchange agreed\nShall be between us in such manner made,\nThat from his bonds Bireno shall be freed\nWhen I am to the monarch's hands conveyed:\nThus I, when I am slain, shall die content,\nWho to my spouse shall life by death have lent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not to this day have chanced upon a wight\nWho on his faith will give me warranty,\nThat if the king refuse to loose the knight,\nWhen I am offered, from captivity,\nHe will not suffer that in my despite\n(So feared those weapons! I shall taken be. ) \n\nSo feared those weapons, upon every hand!\nWhich, howsoever thick, no plates withstand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Now, if as strong Herculean port and bold\nAppear to vouch, such worth to you belong;\nAnd you believe to give me or withhold\nIs in your power, should he intend me wrong;\nBe with me, when committed to his hold,\nSince I shall fear not, in your convoy strong,\nWhen you are with me, that my lord, though I\nBe after slain, shall by his order die.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here her discourse, wherewith were interposed\nLoud sobs, the lady ceased, and silent stood:\nOrlando, when her lips the damsel closed,\nWhose ready will ne'er halts in doing good,\nBriefly to her replies, as indisposed\nTo idle speeches of his natural mood:\nBut plights his solemn word, that better aid\nShe should from him receive than that she prayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis not his scheme to place her in the hand\nOf her foul foe, to have Bireno freed;\nHe will save both the lovers, if his brand\nAnd wonted valour fail him not at need.\nEmbarked that very day, they put from land\nWith a clear sky and prosperous wind to speed.\nThe county hastes in his impatient heat,\nEager to reach that isle, the monster's seat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through the still deeps, on this or the other side,\nThe skipper veered his canvas to the wind:\nThis isle, and that of Zealand, they descried,\nOne seen before, and one shut in behind.\nThe third day, from the harboured vessel's side,\nIn Holland, Roland disembarks, not joined\nBy the complaining dame; whom to descend\nHe will not till she hear that tyrant's end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Armed at all points, the county passed ashore,\nBorne on a horse 'twixt brown and black, the breed\nOf Denmark, but in Flanders nurtured, more\nEsteemed for weight and puissance than for speed:\nFor when the paladin embarked before,\nIn Brittany he left the gallant steed,\nHis Brigliador; so nimble and so fair,\nThat but Bayardo could with him compare."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando fares to Dordrecht, where he views\nA numerous squadron, which the gate maintain;\nAs well, because suspicion still ensues\nOn the foundation of a new domain;\nAs that before they had received the news,\nThat out of Zealand, backed with armed train,\nWas coming with a fleet of many sail,\nA cousin of the lord here pent in jail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One, good Orlando to the monarch's ear\nBade bear a message, `that an errant knight\nOh him would prove himself, with sword and spear;\nBut would lay down this pact before the fight: —\nThat if the king unhorsed the cavalier,\nHer who Arbantes slew, he, as his right,\nShould have, that, at the cavalier's command,\nWas ready for delivery to his hand;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "`And willed the king should on his side agree,\nIf him the knight in combat overbore,\nForthwith released from his captivity,\nBireno to full freedom to restore.'\nTo him the footman does his embassy;\nBut he, who knightly worth or courteous lore\nHad never known, directs his whole intent\nThe count by treacherous fraud to circumvent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He hopes as well, if he the warrior slay,\nTo have the dame, whom, so aggrieved, he hates,\nIf in the knight's disposal, and the say\nOf that strange knight, the footman well relates.\nHence thirty men dispatched by other way\nThan to the portal led, where Roland waits;\nWho with a long and privy circuit wind,\nAnd come upon the paladin behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He all this while had made his guard delay\nThe knight with words, till horse and foot he spied\nArrived, where he this ambuscade did lay;\nWhen from the gate he with as many hied:\nAs is the practised hunter's wonted way,\nTo circle wood and beasts on every side:\nAs nigh Volana, with his sweeping nets,\nThe wary fisher fish and pool besets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis thus the king bars every path which lies\nFree for the warrior's flight, with armed train:\nHe him alive, and in no other guise,\nWould have, and lightly hopes his end to gain;\nNor for the earthly thunderbolt applies,\nThat had so many and so many slain:\nWhich here he deems would serve his purpose ill,\nWhere he desires to take and not to kill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As wary fowler, bent on greater prey,\nWisely preserves alive the game first caught,\nThat by the call-bird and his cheating play,\nMore may within the circling net be brought;\nSuch cunning art Cymosco would assay:\nBut Roland would not be so lightly bought;\nLike them by the first toil that springs betrayed;\nAnd quickly forced the circle which was made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where he perceives the assailants thickest stand,\nHe rests his lance, and sticks in his career\nFirst one and afterwards another, and\nAnother, and another, who appear\nOf paste; till six he of the circling band\nOf foes impales upon a single spear;\nA seventh left out, who by the push is slain,\nSince the clogged weapon can no more contain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No otherwise, upon the further shore\nOf fosse or of canal, the frogs we spy,\nBy cautious archer, practised in his lore,\nSmote and transfixed the one the other nigh;\nUpon the shaft, until it hold no more,\nFrom barb to feathers full, allowed to lie.\nThe heavy lance Orlando from him flung,\nAnd to close combat with his faulchion sprung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lance now broke, his sword the warrior drew,\nThat sword which never yet was drawn in vain,\nAnd still with cut or thrust some soldier slew;\nNow horse, now footman of the tyrant's train.\nAnd, ever where he dealt a stroke, changed blue,\nYellow, green, white and black, to crimson stain.\nCymosco grieves, when most his need require,\nNot to have now his hollow cane and fire;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And with loud voice and menacing command\nBids these be brought, but ill his followers hear;\nFor those who have found safety of his band,\nTo issue from the city are in fear.\nHe, when he sees them fly on either hand,\nWould fly as well from that dread cavalier;\nMakes for the gate, and would the drawbridge lift,\nBut the pursuing county is too swift."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The monarch turns his back, and leaves the knight\nLord of the drawbridge and of either gate.\nThanks to his swifter steed, the rest in flight\nHe passes: good Orlando will not wait\n(Intent the felon, not his band, to smite)\nUpon the vulgar herd to wreck his hate.\nBut his slow horse seems restive; while the king's,\nMore nimble, flies as if equipt with wings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From street to street, before the count he made;\nAnd vanished clean; but after little stay,\nCame with new arms, with tube and fire purveyed;\nWhich, at his hest, this while his men convey.\nAnd posted at a corner, he waylaid:\nHis foe, as hunter watches for his prey,\nIn forest, with armed dogs and spear, attending\nThe boar in fury from the hill descending,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who rends the branch and overthrows the stone;\nAnd wheresoe'er he turns his haughty front,\nAppears (so loud the deafening crash and groan)\nAs if he were uprending wood and mount,\nIntent to make him his bold deed atone,\nCymosco at the pass expects the count;\nAs soon as he appears, with ready light\nTouches the hole, and fires upon the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Behind, the weapon flames in lightning's guise,\nAnd vents the thunder from before; the ground\nShakes under foot and city wall; the skies\nThe fearful echo all about rebound.\nThe burning bolt with sudden fury flies,\nNot sparing aught which in its course is found.\nHissing and whizzing through the skies it went;\nBut smote not, to the assassin's foul intent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether it was his great desire to kill\nThat baron, or his hurry made him fail,\nOr trembling heart, like leaf which flutters still,\nMade hand and arm together flinch and quail;\nOr that it was not the Creator's will\nThe church so soon her champion should bewail;\nThe glancing stroke his courser's belly tore,\nOutstretched on earth, from thence to rise no more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To earth fall horse and rider: this the knight\nScarce touched; the other thundering pressed the plain:\nFor the first rose so ready and so light,\nHe from the fall seemed breath and force to gain.\nAs African Anteus, in the fight,\nRose from the sand with prouder might and main;\nSo when Orlando touched the ground, to view\nHe rose with doubled force and vigour new."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He who has seen the thunder, from on high,\nDischarged by Jove with such a horrid sound,\nDescend where nitre, coal, and sulphur lie,\nStored up for use in magazine profound,\nWhich scarce has reached — but touched it, ere the sky\nIs in a flame, as well as burning ground,\nFirm walls are split, and solid marbles riven,\nAnd flying stones cast up as high as heaven;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let him imagine, when from earth he sprung,\nSuch was the semblance of the cavalier;\nWho moved in mode to frighten Mars among\nThe Gods, so fierce and horrid was his cheer.\nAt this dismay'd, the King of Friesland stung\nHis horse, and turned his rein, to fly the peer:\nBut fierce Orlando was upon his foe\nFaster than arrow flies from bended bow:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, what before he could not, when possest\nOf his good courser, now afoot will do.\nHis speed outgoes all thought in every breast,\nExceeds all credence, save in those who view.\nThe tyrant shortly joined, he on the crest\nSmote at his head so well, he cleft it through;\nAnd to the neck divided by the blow,\nSent it, to shake its last on earth below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lo!  in the frighted city other sound\nWas heard to rise, and other crash of brands,\nFrom troop, who, thither in his guidance bound,\nFollowed Bireno's cousin from his lands:\nWho, since the unguarded gates he open found,\nInto the city's heart had poured his bands;\nWhere the bold paladin had struck such fear,\nHe without let might scour it far and near."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In rout the people fly, who cannot guess\nWho these may be, or what the foes demand:\nBut, when this man and that by speech and dress\nAs Zealand-men distinguishes the band,\nCarte blanche they proffer, and the chief address,\nBidding him range them under his command;\nAgainst the Frieslanders to lend him aid,\nWho have their duke in loathsome prison stayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Friesland's king that people hatred bore\nWith all his following: who their ancient lord\nHad put to death, and who by them yet more,\nAs evil and rapacious, was abhorred.\nOrlando interposed with kindly lore,\nAs friend of both, the parties to accord:\nBy whom, so joined, no Frieslander was left\nBut was of life or liberty bereft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They would not wait to seek the dungeon-key,\nBut breaking-down the gate, their entrance made;\nBireno to the count with courtesy\nAnd grateful thanks the service done repaid.\nThence they, together with large company,\nWent where Olympia in her vessel stayed:\nFor so was the expecting lady hight,\nTo whom that island's crown belonged of right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She who had thither good Orlando brought,\nNot hoping that he would have thriven so well;\n— Enough for her, if by her misery bought,\nHer spouse were rescued from the tyrant's cell! —\nHer, full of love and loyal homage, sought\nThe people one and all:  Twere long to tell\nHow she caressed Bireno, he the maid, —\nWhat thanks both lovers to the county paid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The people, throned in her paternal reign,\nReplace the injured dame, and fealty swear:\nShe on the duke, to whom in solid chain\nLove with eternal knot had linked the fair,\nThe empire of herself and her domain\nConferred: He, called away by other care,\nLeft in the cousin's guardian care this while\nHis fortresses, and all the subject isle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since he to visit Zealand's duchy planned,\nHis faithful consort in his company;\nAnd thence, upon the king of Friesland's land,\nWould try his fortune (as he said), for he\nA pledge, he rated highly, had in hand,\nWhich seemed of fair success the warranty,\nThe daughter of the king: who here forsaken,\nWith many others had been prisoner taken."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To a younger brother, her, the duke pretends,\nTo be conjoined in wedlock, he conveyed.\nThe Roman senator thence parting wends\nUpon the very day Bireno weighed;\nBut he to nothing else his hand extends\nOf all the many, many prized made,\nSave to that engine, found amid the plunder,\nWhich in all points I said resembled thunder."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not with intent, in his defence to bear\nWhat he had taken, of the prize possest;\nFor he still held it an ungenerous care\nTo go with vantage on whatever quest:\nBut with design to cast the weapon where\nIt never more should living wight molest;\nAnd, what was appertaining to it, all\nBore off as well, the powder and the ball."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And thus, when of the tidesway he was clear,\nAnd in the deepest sea his bark descried,\nSo that no longer distant signs appear\nOf either shore on this or the other side,\nHe seized the tube, and said: \"That cavalier\nMay never vail through thee his knightly pride,\nNor base be rated with a better foe,\nDown with thee to the darkest deep below!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O loathed, O cursed piece of enginery,\nCast in Tartarean bottom, by the hand\nOf Beelzebub, whose foul malignity\nThe ruin of this world through thee has planned!\nTo hell, from whence thou came, I render thee.\"\nSo said, he cast away the weapon: fanned\nMeanwhile, with flowing sheet, his frigate goes,\nBy wind, which for the cruel island blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such was the paladin's desire to explore\nIf in the place his missing lady were;\nWhom he prefers the united world before,\nNor can an hour of life without her bear.\nHe fears, if he set foot on Ireland's shore,\nSome other chance may interrupt him there:\nSo that he after have in vain to say,\n\"Why hasted I no faster on my way?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor he in England nor in Ireland port\nWill make, nor on the coast that's opposite.\nBut let him go, the naked archer's sport,\nSore smitten in the heart! — ere I indite\nYet more of him, to Holland I resort,\nAnd you to hear me company invite.\nFor well I wot that you as well as me\n'Twould grieve that bridal should without us be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sumptuous and fair the bridal there is made;\nBut neither yet so sumptuous nor so fair\nAs it will be in Zealand, it is said:\nBut 'tis not my design you should repair\nThither; since by new accidents delayed\nThe feast will be, of which be it my care,\nIn other strain, the tidings to report;\nIf you to hear that other strain resort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 10"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Another love assails Bireno's breast,\nWho leaves one night Olympia on the shore.\nTo Logistilla's holy realm addressed,\nRogero goes, nor heeds Alcina more:\nHim, of that flying courser repossest,\nThe hippogryph on airy voyage bore:\nWhence he the good Rinaldo's levy sees,\nAnd next Angelica beholds and frees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of all the loves, of all fidelity\nYet proved, of all the constant hearts and true,\nOf all the lovers, in felicity\nOr sorrow faithful found, a famous crew,\nTo Olympia I would give the first degree\nRather than second: if this be not due,\nI well may say that hers no tale is told\nOf truer love, in present times or old."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this she by so many proofs and clear,\nHad made apparent to the Zealand lord,\nNo woman's faith more certain could appear\nTo man, though he her open heart explored:\nAnd if fair truth such spirits should endear,\nAnd they in mutual love deserve reward,\nBireno as himself, nay, he above\nHimself, I say, should kind Olympia love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not only should he nevermore deceive\nHer for another, were that woman she\nWho so made Europe and wide Asia grieve,\nOr fairer yet, if one more fair there be;\nBut rather that quit her the light should leave,\nAnd what is sweet to taste, touch, hear, and see,\nAnd life and fame, and all beside; if aught\nMore precious can in truth be styled, or thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If her Bireno loved, as she had loved\nBireno, if her love he did repay\nWith faith like hers, and still with truth unmoved,\nVeered not his shifting sail another way;\nOr ingrate for such service — cruel proved\nFor such fair love and faith, I now will say;\nAnd you with lips comprest and eye-brows bent,\nShall listen to the tale for wonderment;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when you shall have heard the impiety,\nWhich of such passing goodness was the meed,\nWoman take warning from this perfidy,\nAnd let none make a lover's word her creed.\nMindless that God does all things hear and see,\nThe lover, eager his desires to speed,\nHeaps promises and vows, aye prompt to swear,\nWhich afterwards all winds disperse in air."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The promises and empty vows dispersed\nIn air, by winds all dissipated go,\nAfter these lovers have the greedy thirst\nAppeased, with which their fevered palates glow.\nIn this example which I offer, versed,\nTheir prayers and tears to credit be more slow.\nCheaply, dear ladies mine, is wisdom bought\nBy those who wit at other's cost are taught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of those in the first flower of youth beware,\nWhose visage is so soft and smooth to sight:\nFor past, as soon as bred, their fancies are;\nLike a straw fire their every appetite.\nSo the keen hunter follows up the hare\nIn heat and cold, on shore, or mountain-height;\nNor, when 'tis taken, more esteems the prize;\nAnd only hurries after that which flies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such is the practise of these striplings who,\nWhat time you treat them with austerity,\nLove and revere you, and such homage do,\nAs those who pay their service faithfully;\nBut vaunt no sooner victory, than you\nFrom mistresses shall servants grieve to be;\nAnd mourn to see the fickle love they owed,\nFrom you diverted, and elsewhere bestowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I not for this (for that were wrong opine ) \n\nThat you should cease to love; for you, without\nA lover, like uncultivated vine,\nWould be, that has no prop to wind about.\nBut the first down I pray you to decline,\nTo fly the volatile, inconstant rout;\nTo make your choice the riper fruits among,\nNor yet to gather what too long has hung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A daughter they have found (above was said)\nOf the proud king who ruled the Friesland state;\nThat with Bireno's brother was to wed,\nAs far as rumour tells; but to relate\nThe truth, a longing in Bireno bred\nThe sight of food so passing delicate;\nAnd he to talk his palate deemed would be,\nFor other's sake, a foolish courtesy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The gentle damsel had not past fourteen,\nWas beautiful and fresh, and like a rose,\nWhen this first opening from its bud is seen,\nAnd with the vernal sun expands and grows.\nTo say Bireno loved the youthful queen\nWere little; with less blaze lit tinder glows,\nOr ripened corn, wherever envious hand\nOf foe amid the grain has cast a brand,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Than that which on Bireno's bosom fed,\nAnd to his marrow burned; when, weeping sore\nThe fate of her unhappy father dead,\nHe saw her bathed in ceaseless tears deplore:\nAnd, as cold water, on the cauldron shed,\nShops short the bubbling wave, which boiled before;\nSo was the raging rife Olympia blew\nWithin his breast, extinguished by a new."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor feels Bireno mere satiety;\nHe loathes her so, he ill endures her sight;\nAnd, if his hope he long deferred, will die:\nFor other such his fickle appetite!\nYet till the day prefixed to satisfy\nHis fond desire, so feigns the wary knight,\nOlympia less to love than to adore\nHe seems, and but her pleasure to explore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And if the other he too much caress,\nWho cannot but caress her, there are none\nSee evil in the deed, but rather guess\nIt is in pity, is in goodness done:\nSince to raise up and comfort in distress\nWhom Fortune's wheel beats down in changeful run,\nWas never blamed; with glory oftener paid;\n— So much the more, a young — a harmless maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Almighty God!  how fallible and vain\nIs human judgment, dimmed by clouds obscure!\nBireno's actions, impious and profane,\nBy others are reputed just and pure.\nAlready stooping to their oars, the train\nHave loosed his vessel from the port secure,\nAnd with the duke and his companions steer\nFor Zealand through the deep, with meery cheer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already Holland and its headlands all\nAre left astern, and now descried no more;\nSince to shun Friesland they to larboard hawl.\nAnd keep their course more nigh the Scottish shore:\nWhen they are overtaken by a squall,\nAnd drive three days the open sea before:\nUpon the third, when now, near eventide,\nA barren and unpeopled isle is spied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as they were harboured in a hight,\nOlympia landed and the board was spread;\nShe there contented, with the faithless knight,\nSupt, unsuspecting any cause for dread.\nThence, with Bireno, where a tent was pight\nIn pleasant place, repaired, and went to bed.\nThe others of their train returned abroad,\nAnd rested in their ship, in haven moored."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The fear and late sea sorrow, which had weighed\nSo long upon the dame and broke her rest,\nThe finding herself safe in greenwood shade\nRemoved from noise, and, for her tranquil breast\n(Knowing her lover was beside her laid)\nNo further thoughts, no further cares molest,\nOlympia lap in slumber so profound,\nNo sheltered bear or dormouse sleeps more sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lover false, who, hatching treason lies,\nStole from his bed in silence, when he knew\nShe slept: his clothes he in a bundle ties,\nNor other raiment on his body threw.\nThen issuing forth from the pavilion hies,\nAs if on new-born wings, towards his crew;\nWho, roused, unmoor without a cry, as he\nCommands, and loosen thence and put to sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Behind the land was left; and there to pine\nOlympia, who yet slept the woods among;\nTill from her gilded wheels the frosty rhine\nAurora upon earth beneath had flung;\nAnd the old woe, beside the tumbling brine,\nLamenting, halcyons mournful descant sung;\nWhen she, 'twixt sleep and waking, made a strain\nTo reach her loved Bireno, but in vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She no one found: the dame her arm withdrew;\nShe tried again, yet no one found; she spread\nBoth arms, now here, now there, and sought anew;\nNow either leg; but yet no better sped.\nFear banished sleep; she oped her eyes: in view\nWas nothing: she no more her widowed bed\nWould keep, but from the couch in fury sprung,\nAnd headlong forth from the pavilion flung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And seaward ran, her visage tearing sore,\nPresaging, and now certain of her plight:\nShe beat her bosom, and her tresses tore,\nAnd looked (the moon was shining if she might ) \n\nDiscover any thing beside the shore;\nNor, save the shore, was any thing in sight.\nShe calls Bireno, and the caverns round,\nPitying her grief, Bireno's name rebound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the far shore there rose a rock; below\nScooped by the breaker's beating frequently:\nThe cliff was hollowed underneath, in show\nOf arch, and overhung the foaming sea.\nOlympia (MIND such vigour did bestow)\nSprang up the frowning crest impetuously,\nAnd, at a distance, stretched by favouring gale,\nThence saw her cruel lord's departing sail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Saw it, or seemed to see: for ill her eyes,\nThings through the air, yet dim and hazy, view.\nShe falls, all-trembling, on the ground, and lies\nWith face than snow more cold and white in hue:\nBut when she has again found strength to rise,\nGuiding her voice towards the bark which flew,\nCalling with all her might, the unhappy dame\nCalls often on her cruel consort's name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where unavailing was the feeble note,\nShe wept and clapt her hands in agony.\n\"Without its freight,\" she cried, \"thy ship does float.\n— Where, cruel, dost thou fly so swiftly? — Me\nReceive as well: — small hinderance to thy boat,\nWhich bears my spirit, would my body be.\"\nAnd she her raiment waving in her hand,\nSigned to the frigate to return to land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But the loud wind which, sweeping ocean, bears\nThe faithless stripling's sail across the deep,\nBears off as well the shriek, and moan, and prayers\nOf sad Olympia, sorrowing on the steep.\nThrice, cruel to herself, the dame prepares\nFrom the high rock amid the waves to leap.\nBut from the water lifts at length her sight,\nAnd there returns where she had passed the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stretched on the bed, upon her face she lay,\nBathing it with her tears.  \"Last night in thee\nTogether two found shelter,\" did she say;\n\"Alas!  why two together are not we\nAt rising?  False Bireno!  cursed day\nThat I was born!  What here remains to me\nTo do?  What can be done? — Alone, betrayed —\nWho will console me, who afford me aid?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor man I see, nor see I work, which shows\nThat man inhabits in this isle; nor I\nSee ship, in which (a refuge from my woes),\nEmbarking, I from hence may hope to fly.\nHere shall I starve; nor any one to close\nMy eyes, or give me sepulture, be by,\nSave wolf perchance, who roves this wood, a tomb\nGive me, alas!  in his voracious womb."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I live in terror, and appear to see\nRough bear or lion issue even now,\nOr tiger, from beneath the greenwood tree,\nOr other beast with teeth and claws: but how\nCan ever cruel beast inflict on me,\nO cruel beast, a fouler death than thou?\nEnough for them to slay me once!  while I\nAm made by thee a thousand deaths to die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But grant, e'en now, some skipper hither fare,\nWho may for pity bear me hence away;\nAnd that I so eschew wolf, lion, bear,\nTorture, and dearth, and every horrid way\nOf death; to Holland shall he take me, where\nFor thee is guarded fortilage and bay;\nOr take me to the land where I was born,\nIf this thou hast from me by treachery torn?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou, with pretence, from me my state didst wrest\nOf our connection and of amity;\nAnd quickly of my land thy troops possest,\nTo assure the rule unto thyself.  Shall I\nReturn to Flanders where I sold the rest,\nThough little, upon which I lived, to buy\nThee needful succour and from prison bear?\nWretch, whither shall I go? — I know not where."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Can I to Friesland go, where I to reign\nAs queen was called, and this for thee forewent;\nWhere both my brethren and my sire were slain,\nAnd every other good from me was rent? —\nThee would I not, thou ingrate, with my pain\nReproach, not therefore deal thee punishment:\nAs well as I, the story dost thou know;\nNow, see the meed thou dost for this bestow!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Oh!  may I but escape the wild corsair,\nNor taken be, and after sold for slave!\nRather than this may lion, wolf, or bear,\nTiger, or other beast, if fiercer rave,\nMe with his claws and rushes rend and tear,\nAnd drag my bleeding body to his cave.\"\nSo saying she her golden hair offends,\nAnd lock by lock the scattered tresses rends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She to the shore's extremest verge anew,\nTossing her head, with hair dishevelled, run;\nAnd seemed like maid beside herself, and who\nWas by ten fiends possessed, instead of one;\nOf like the frantic Hecuba, at view\nOf murdered Polydore, her infant son;\nFixed on a stone she gazed upon the sea,\nNor less than real stone seemed stone to be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But let her grieve till my return.  To show\nNow of the Child I wish: his weary way\nRogero, in the noon's intensest glow,\nTakes by the shore: the burning sunbeams play\nUpon the hill and thence rebound; below\nBoils the white sand; while heated with the ray,\nLittle is wanting in that journey dire,\nBut that the arms he wears are all on fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While to the warrior thirst and labour sore,\nStill toiling through that heavy sand, as he\nPursued his path along the sunny shore,\nWere irksome and displeasing company,\nBeneath the shadow of a turret hoar,\nWhich rose beside the beach, amid the sea,\nHe found three ladies of Alcina's court,\nAs such distinguished by their dress and port."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Reclined on Alexandrian carpets rare\nThe ladies joyed the cool in great delight;\nAbout them various wines in vessels were,\nAnd every sort of comfit nicely dight;\nFast by, and sporting with the ripple there,\nLay, waiting on their needs, a pinnace light,\nUntil a breeze should fill her sail anew:\nFor then no breath upon the waters blew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They, who beheld along the shifting sand\nRogero wend, upon his way intent,\nAnd saw thirst figured on his lips, and scanned\nHis troubled visage, all with sweat besprent,\nBegan to pray, `on what he had in hand\nHe would not show his heart so deeply bent,\nBut that he in the cool and grateful shade\nWould rest his weary limbs, beside them laid.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To hold the stirrup one approaching near,\nWould aid him to alight: the other bore\nA cup of chrystal to the cavalier,\nWith foaming wine, which raised his thirst the more;\nBut to the music of their speech no ear\nHe lent, who weened if he his way forbore\nFor anything, each lett would time supply\nTo Alcina to arrive, who now was nigh."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now so saltpetre fine and sulphur pure,\nTouched with the fiery spark, blaze suddenly;\nNot so loud ocean raves, when the obscure\nWhirlwind descends and camps in middle sea,\nAs viewing thus the knight proceed secure\nUpon his journey, and aware that he\nScorns them, who yet believe they beauteous are,\nKindled the third of those three damsels fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As loud as she could raise her voice, she said,\n\"Thou art not gentle, nor art thou a knight;\nAnd hast from other arms and horse conveyed:\nWhich never could be thine by better right.\nSo be thy theft, if well I guess, appaid\nBy death, which this may worthily requite!\nFoul thief, churl, haughty ingrate, may I thee\nBurned, gibbeted, or cut in quarters see!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beside all these and more injurious cries,\nWhich the proud damsel at the warrior throws,\nThough to her taunts Rogero nought replies,\nWho weens small fame from such a contest flows;\nShe with her sisters to the frigate hies,\nWhich waits them, and aboard the tender goes;\nAnd plying fast her oars, pursues the knight\nAlong the sandy beach, still kept in sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On him with threat and curse she ever cried;\nWhose tongue collected still fresh cause for blame.\nMeanwhile, where to the lovelier fairy's side\nThe passage lay across a straight, he came;\nAnd there an ancient ferryman espied\nPut from the other shore with punctual aim,\nAs if forewarned and well prepared, the seer\nWaited the coming of the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The ferryman put forth the Child to meet,\nTo bear him to a better shore rejoicing: he\nAppeared as all benign and all discreet,\nIf of the heart the face is warranty.\nGiving God thanks, Rogero took his seat\nAboard the bark, and passed the quiet sea,\nDiscoursing with that ancient pilot, fraught\nWith wisdom, and by long experience taught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He praised Rogero much, that he had fled\nIn time from false Alcina, and before\nTo him the dame had given the chalice dread,\nHer lover's final guerdon evermore.\nNext that he had to Logistilla sped,\nWhere he should duly witness holy lore,\nAnd beauty infinite and grace enjoy,\nWhich feed and nourish hearts they never cloy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her shall you, struck with wonderment, revere,\"\n(He said), \"when first you shall behold the fay;\nBut better contemplate her lofty cheer,\nAnd you no other treasure shall appay.\nIn this her love from other differs; fear\nAnd hope in other on the bosom prey:\nIn hers Desire demands not aught beside,\nAnd with the blessing seen is satisfied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You shall in nobler studies be professed,\nTutored by her, than bath and costly fare,\nSong, dance, and perfumes; as how fashioned best,\nYour thoughts may tower more high than hawks in air;\nAnd how some of the glory of the blest\nYou here may in the mortal body share.\"\nSo speaking, and yet distant from the shore,\nTo the safe bank approached the pilot hoar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he beholds forth-issuing from the strand,\nA fleet of ships, which all towards him steer.\nWith these came wronged Alcina, with a band\nOf many vassals, gathered far and near;\nTo risk the ruin of herself and land,\nOr repossess the thing she held so dear.\nLove, no light cause, incites the dame aggrieved,\nNor less the bitter injury received."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such choler she had never felt before\nAs that which now upon her bosom fed:\nAnd hence she made her followers ply the oar\nTill the white foam on either bank was shed\nThe deafening noise and din o'er sea and shore,\nBy echo every where repeated, spread,\n\"Now — now, Rogero, bare the magic shield,\nOr in the strife be slain, or basely yield\":"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus Logistilla's pilot; and beside,\nSo saying, seized the pouch, wherein was dight\nThe buckler, and the covering torn aside,\nExposed to open view the shining light.\nThe enchanted splendor, flashing far and wide,\nSo sore offends the adversaries' sight,\nThey from their vessels drop amazed and blind,\nTumbling from prow before, and poop behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One who stood sentry on the citadel\nDescried the navy of the invading dame,\nAnd backwards rang the castle larum-bell,\nWhence speedy succours to the haven came.\nThe artillery rained like storm, whose fury fell\nOn all who would Rogero scathe and shame:\nSo that such aid was brought him in the strife,\nAs saved the warrior's liberty and life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Four ladies are arrived upon the strand,\nThither by Logistilla sped in haste:\nLeagued with the valiant Anrondica stand\nFronesia sage, Dicilla good, and chaste\nSofrosina, who, as she has in had\nMore than the others, 'mid the foremost placed,\nConspicuous flames.  Forth issues from the fort\nA matchless host, and files towards the port."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beneath the castle, safe from wind and swell,\nOf many ships and stout, a squadron lay;\nWhich, in the harbour, at a sound from bell, —\nA word, were fit for action, night or day;\nAnd thus by land and sea was battle, fell\nAnd furious, waged on part of either fay:\nWhence was Alcina's realm turned upside down,\nOf which she had usurped her sister's crown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh!  of how many battles the success\nIs different from what was hoped before!\nNot only failed the dame to repossess,\nAs thought, her lover flying from her shore,\nBut out of ships, even now so numberless,\nThat ample ocean scarce the navy bore,\nFrom all her vessels, to the flames a prey,\nBut with one bark escaped the wretched fay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Alcina flies; and her sad troop around\nRouted and taken, burnt or sunk, remains\nTo have lost Rogero, sorrow more profound\nWakes in her breast than all her other pains;\nAnd she in bitter tears for ever drowned,\nOf the Child's loss by night and day complains;\nAnd bent to end her woes, with many a sigh,\nOften laments her that she cannot die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No fairy dies, or can, while overhead\nThe sun shall burn, or heaven preserve their stile,\nOr Clotho had been moved to cut her thread,\nTouched by such grief; or, as on funeral pile\nFair Dido, she beneath the steel had bled;\nOr, haply, like the gorgeous Queen of Nile,\nIn mortal slumber would have closed her eye:\nBut fairies cannot at their pleasure die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Return we, where eternal fame is due,\nLeaving Alcina in her trouble sore:\nI speak of valorous Rogero, who\nHad disembarked upon the safer shore.\nHe turned his back upon the waters blue,\nGiving God thanks for all with pious lore;\nAnd on dry ground now landed, made repair\nTowards the lofty castle planted there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Than this a stronger or more bright in show\nWas never yet before of mortal sight,\nOr after, viewed; with stones the ramparts glow\nMore rich than carbuncle or diamond bright.\nWe of like gems discourse not here below,\nAnd he who would their nature read aright\nMust thither speed: none such elsewhere, I ween,\nExcept perhaps in heaven above, are seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What gives to them superiority\nO'er every other sort of gem, confessed,\nIs, man in these his very soul may see;\nHis vices and his virtues see expressed.\nHence shall he after heed no flattery,\nNor yet by wrongful censure be depressed.\nHis form he in the lucid mirror eyes,\nAnd by the knowledge of himself grows wise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Their rays, which imitate the sunshine, fill\nAll round about with such a flood of light,\nThat he who has them, Phoebus, may at will\nCreate himself a day, in thy despite.\nNor only marvellous the gems; the skill\nOf the artificer and substance bright\nSo well contend for mastery, of the two,\n'Tis hard to judge where preference is due."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On arches raised, whereon the firmament\nSeemed to repose as props, so fair in show\nAre lovely gardens, and of such extent,\nAs even would be hard to have below.\nClustering 'twixt lucid tower or battlement,\nGreen odoriferous shrubs are seen to grow,\nWhich through the summer and the winter shoot,\nAnd teem with beauteous blossom and ripe fruit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Never in any place such goodly tree\nIs grown, except within these gardens fine;\nOr rose, or violet of like quality,\nLilies, or amaranth, or jessamine.\nElsewhere it seems as if foredoomed to be\nBorn with one sun, to live and to decline,\nUpon its widowed stalk the blossom dies,\nSubject to all the changes of the skies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But here the verdure still is permanent,\nStill permanent the eternal blossoms are;\nNot that kind nature, in her government,\nSo nicely tempers here the genial air,\nBut that, unneeding any influence lent\nBy planet, Logistilla's zeal and care\nEver keep fast (what may appear a thing\nImpossible her own perpetual spring. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That such a gentle lord had sought her rest,\nDid much the prudent Logistilla please,\nAnd she commanded he should be carest,\nAnd all should seek to do him courtesies.\nSometime had Sir Astolpho been her guest,\nWhom with a joyful heart Rogero sees.\nThere in few days resorted all the crew,\nChanged by Melissa to their shapes anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When they a day or more their weariness\nHad eased, Rogero sought the prudent fay;\nWith him the duke Astolpho, who no less\nDesired to measure back his western way.\nMelissa was for both embassadress,\nAnd for the warlike pair, with humble say\nTo favour, warn and help them, prayed the dame;\nSo that they might return from whence they came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I\" (said the fay \"will think upon this need, ) \n\nAnd in two days the pair will expedite.\"\nThen thought how good Rogero she should speed.\nAnd afterwards how aid the English knight.\nShe wills the first shall, on the griffin steed,\nTo the Aquitanian shores direct his flight;\nBut first will fashion for the flying-horse\nA bit, to guide him and restrain his course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She shows him what to do, if he on high\nWould make him soar, or down to earth would bring,\nAnd what, would he in circles make him fly,\nOr swiftly speed, or pause upon the wing.\nAnd all that skilful horsemen use to try\nUpon plain ground, beneath her tutoring,\nRogero learned in air, and gained dominion\nOver the griffin-steed of soaring pinion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When at all points Rogero was prepared,\nHe bade farewell to the protecting fay,\nFor ever to the loving knight endeared,\nAnd issued from her realm upon his way.\nI first of him, who on his journey fared\nIn happy hour, and afterwards shall say\nOf the English knight, who spent more time and pain\nSeeking the friendly court of Charlemagne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero thence departs; but as before\nTakes not the way he took in his despite,\nWhen him above the sea the courser bore,\nAnd seldom was the land beneath in sight.\nBut taught to make him beat his wings and soar,\nHere, there, as liked him best, with docile flight,\nReturning, he another path pursued;\nAs Magi erst, who Herod's snare eschewed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Borne hither, good Rogero, leaving Spain,\nHad sought, in level line, the Indian lands,\nWhere they are watered by the Eastern main;\nWhere the two fairies strove with hostile bands.\nHe now resolved to visit other reign\nThan that where Aeolus his train commands;\nAnd finish so the round he had begun,\nCircling the world beneath him like the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here the Catay, and there he Mangiane,\nPassing the great Quinsay beheld; in air\nAbove Imavus turned, and Sericane\nLeft on the right; and thence did ever bear\nFrom the north Scythians to the Hyrcanian main:\nSo reached Sarmatia's distant land; and, where\nEurope and Asia's parted climes divide,\nRuss, Prussian, he and Pomeranian spied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Although the Child by every wish was pressed\nQuickly to seek his Bradamant, yet he\nWith taste of roving round the world possest,\nWould not desist from it, till Hungary\nHe had seen; and Polacks, Germans, and the rest\nShould in his wide extended circuit see,\nInhabiting that horrid, northern land;\nAnd came at last to England's farthest strand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet think not, sir, that in so long a flight,\nThe warrior is for ever on the wing.\nWho lodges, housed in tavern every night,\nAs best as can, through his capacious ring.\nSo nights and days he passes: such delight\nProspects to him of land and ocean bring.\nArrived one morn nigh London-town, he stopt;\nAnd over Thames the flying courser dropt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where he in meadows to the city nigh\nSaw troops of men at arms, and footmen spread;\nWho, to the drum and trumpet marching by,\nDivided into goodly bands, were led\nBefore Rinaldo, flower of chivalry;\nHe that (if you remember it was said ) \n\nTo have been sent by Charlemagne, and made\nHis envoy to these parts in search of aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero came exactly as the show\nOf that fair host was made without the town,\nAnd of a knight the occasion sought to know;\nBut from the griffin-horse first lighted down:\nAnd he who courteous was, informed him how\nOf kingdoms holding of the British crown,\nEnglish, Scotch, Irish, and the Islands nigh,\nThose many banners were, upreared on high:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And added, having ended this display\nOf arms, the troops would file towards the strand,\nWhere vessels anchored in the harbour lay,\nWaiting to bear them to another land.\n\"The French beseiged, rejoice in this array,\nAnd hope (he said deliverance through the band. ) \n\nBut that I may of all inform you well,\nI of each troop shall separately tell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  where yon mighty banner planted stands,\nWhich pards and flower-de-luces does unfold,\nThat our great captain to the wind expands,\nUnder whose ensign are the rest enrolled:\nThe warrior's name, renowned throughout these lands,\nIs Leonetto, flower of all the bold;\nLancaster's duke, and nephew to the king,\nValiant in war, and wise in counselling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That next the royal gonfalon, which stirred\nBy fluttering wind, is borne towards the mount,\nWhich on green field, three pinions of a bird\nBears agent, speaks Sir Richard, Warwick's count.\nThe Duke of Gloucester's blazon is the third,\nTwo antlers of a stag, and demi-front;\nThe Duke of Clarence shows a torch, and he\nIs Duke of York who bears that verdant tree."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Upon the Duke of Norfolk's gonfalon\nYou see a lance into three pieces broke;\nThe thunder on the Earl of Kent's; upon\nPembroke's a griffin; underneath a yoke;\nIn Essex's, conjoined, two snakes are shown:\nBy yonder lifted balance is bespoke\nThe Duke of Suffolk; and Northumbria's Earl\nA garland does on azure field unfurl."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Arundel's Earl is yonder cavalier,\nWhose banner bears a foundering bark!  In sight\nThe next, is Berkeley's noble Marquis; near\nAre March and Richmond's Earls: the first on white\nShows a cleft mount; a palm the second peer;\nA pine amid the waves the latter knight.\nThe next of Dorset and Southampton's town,\nAre earls; this bears a car, and that a crown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The valiant Raymond, Earl of Devon, bears\nThe hawk, which spreads her wings above her nest;\nWhile or and sable he of Worcester wears:\nDerby's a dog, a bear is Oxford's crest.\nThere, as his badge, a cross of chrystal rears\nBath's wealthy prelate, camped among the rest.\nThe broken seat on dusky field, next scan,\nOf Somerset's good duke, Sir Ariman."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Forty-two thousand muster in array,\nThe men at arms and mounted archers there.\nBy a hundred I misreckon not, or they,\nThe fighting footmen, twice as many are.\nThose ensigns yellow, brown, and green, survey,\nAnd that striped blue and black.  The foot repair\nEach to his separate flag where these are spread;\nBy Godfrey, Henry, Hermant, Edward, led."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The first is the Duke of Buckingham; and he,\nThe next, is Henry, Earl of Salisbury;\nOld Hermant Aberga'nny hold in fee,\nThat Edward is the Earl of Shrewsbury.\nIn those who yonder lodge, the English see\nCamped eastward; and now westward turn your eye,\nWhere you shall thirty thousand Scots, a crew\nLed by their monarch's son, Zerbino, view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The lion 'twixt two unicorns behold\nUpon the standard of the Scottish king!\nWhich has a sword of silver in its hold.\nThere camps his son: of all his following\nIs none so beauteous: nature broke the mould\nIn which she cast him, after fashioning\nHer work: Is none in whom such chivalry\nAnd valour shines.  The Duke of Rothsay he!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Behold the Earl of Huntley's flag display\nUpon an azure field a gilded bar:\nIn that a leopard in the toils survey,\nThe bearing of the noble Duke of Mar.\nWith many birds, and many colours gay,\nSee Alcabrun's, a valiant man in war;\nWho neither duke, nor count, nor marquis hight,\nIs in his savage country first of right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The Duke of Strathforth shows the bird, who strains\nHis daring eyes to keep the sun in view;\nThe Earl Lurcanio, that in Angus reigns,\nA bull, whose flanks are torn by deerhounds two.\nSee there the Duke of Albany, who stains\nHis ensign's field with colours white and blue.\nThe Earl of Buchan next his banner bears,\nIn which a dragon vert a vulture tears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Herman, the lord of Forbes, conducts that band,\nAnd stripes his gonfalon with black and white;\nWith Errol's earl upon his better hand,\nWho on a field of green displays a light.\nNow see the Irish, next the level land,\nInto two squadrons ordered for the fight.\nKildare's redoubted earl commands the first;\nLord Desmond leads the next, in mountains nursed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A burning pine by Kildare is displayed;\nBy Desmond on white field a crimson bend.\nNor only England, Scotland, Ireland, aid\nKing Charlemagne; but to assist him wend\nThe Swede and Norse, and succours are conveyed\nFrom Thule, and the farthest Iceland's end.\nAll lands that round them lie, in fine, increase\nHis host, by nature enemies to peace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Issued from cavern and from forest brown,\nThey sixteen thousand are, or little less;\nVisage, legs, arms, and bosom overgrown\nWith hair, like beasts.  Lo!  yonder, where they press\nAbout a standard white, the level down\nOf lances seems a bristling wilderness.\nSuch Moray's flag, the savage squadron's head,\nWho means with Moorish blood to paint it red.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What time Rogero sees the fair array,\nWhose bands to succour ravaged France prepare,\nAnd notes and talks of ensigns they display,\nAnd names of British lords, to him repair\nOne and another, crowding to survey\nHis courser, single of its kind, or rare:\nAll thither hasten, wondering and astound,\nAnd compassing the warrior, form a round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So that to raise more wonder in the train.\nAnd to make better sport, as him they eyed,\nRogero shook the flying courser's rein,\nAnd lightly with the rowels touched his side:\nHe towards heaven, uprising, soared amain,\nAnd left behind each gazer stupefied.\nHaving from end to end the English force\nSo viewed, he next for Ireland shaped his course;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And saw fabulous Hibernia, where\nThe goodly, sainted elder made the cave,\nIn which men cleansed from all offences are;\nSuch mercy there, it seems, is found to save.\nThence o'er that sea he spurred, through yielding air,\nWhose briny waves the lesser Britain lave;\nAnd, looking down, Angelica descried\nIn passing, to the rock with fetters tied;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bound to the naked rock upon the strand,\nIn the isle of tears; for the isle of tears was hight,\nThat which was peopled by the inhuman band,\nSo passing fierce and full of foul despite;\nWho (as I told above on every hand ) \n\nCruized with their scattered fleet by day or night;\nAnd every beauteous woman bore away,\nDestined to be a monster's evil prey:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There but that morning bound in cruel wise;\nWhere (to devour a living damsel sped)\nThe orc, that measureless sea-monster, hies,\nWhich on abominable food is fed.\nHow on the beach the maid became the prize\nOf the rapacious crew, above was said,\nWho found her sleeping near the enchanter hoar,\nWho her had thither brought by magic lore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The cruel and inhospitable crew\nTo the voracious beast the dame expose\nUpon the sea-beat shore, as bare to view\nAs nature did at first her work compose.\nNot even a veil she had, to shade the hue\nOf the white lily and vermillion rose,\nWhich mingled in her lovely members meet,\nProof to December-snow and July-heat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her would Rogero have some statue deemed\nOf alabaster made, or marble rare,\nWhich to the rugged rock so fastened seemed\nBy the industrious sculptor's cunning care,\nBut that he saw distinct a tear which streamed\nAmid fresh-opening rose and lily fair,\nStand on her budding paps beneath in dew,\nAnd that her golden hair dishevelled flew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And as he fastened his on her fair eyes,\nHis Bradamant he called to mind again.\nPity and love within his bosom rise\nAt once, and ill he can from tears refrain:\nAnd in soft tone he to the damsel cries,\n(When he has checked his flying courser's rein)\n\"O lady, worthy but that chain to wear,\nWith which Love's faithful servants fettered are,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And most unworthy this or other ill,\nWhat wretch has had the cruelty to wound\nAnd gall those snowy hands with livid stain,\nThus painfully with griding fetters bound?\"\nAt this she cannot choose but show like grain,\nOf crimson spreading on an ivory ground;\nKnowing those secret beauties are espied,\nWhich, howsoever lovely, shame would hide;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And gladly with her hands her face would hood,\nWere they not fastened to the rugged stone:\nBut with her tears (for this at least she could)\nBedewed it, and essayed to hold it down.\nSobbing some while the lovely damsel stood;\nThen loosed her tongue and spake in feeble tone;\nBut ended not; arrested in mid-word,\nBy a loud noise which in the sea was heard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lo!  and behold!  the unmeasured-beast appears,\nHalf surging and half hidden, in such sort\nAs sped by roaring wind long carack steers\nFrom north or south, towards her destined port.\nSo the sea monster to his food repairs:\nAnd now the interval between is short.\nHalf dead the lady is through fear endured,\nIll by that other's comfort reassured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero overhand, not in the rest\nCarries his lance, and beats, with downright blow,\nThe monstrous orc.  What this resembled best,\nBut a huge, writhing mass, I do not know;\nWhich wore no form of animal exprest,\nSave in the head, with eyes and teeth of sow.\nHis forehead, 'twixt the eyes, Rogero smites,\nBut as on steel or rock the weapon lights."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he perceives the first of no avail,\nThe knight returns to deal a better blow;\nThe orc, who sees the shifting shadow sail\nOf those huge pinions on the sea below,\nIn furious heat, deserts his sure regale\nOn shore, to follow that deceitful show:\nAnd rolls and reels behind it, as it fleets.\nRogero drops, and oft the stroke repeats."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As eagle, that amid her downward flight,\nSurveys amid the grass a snake unrolled,\nOr where she smoothes upon a sunny height,\nHer ruffled plumage, and her scales of gold,\nAssails it not where prompt with poisonous bite\nTo hiss and creep; but with securer hold\nGripes it behind, and either pinion clangs,\nLest it should turn and wound her with its fangs;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So the fell orc Rogero does not smite\nWith lance or faulchion where the tushes grow,\nBut aims that 'twixt the ears his blow may light;\nNow on the spine, or now on tail below.\nAnd still in time descends or soars upright,\nAnd shifts his course, to cheat the veering foe:\nBut as if beating on a jasper block,\nCan never cleave the hard and rugged rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With suchlike warfare is the mastiff vext\nBy the bold fly in August's time of dust,\nOr in the month before or in the next,\nThis full of yellow spikes and that of must;\nFor ever by the circling plague perplext,\nWhose sting into his eyes or snout is thrust:\nAnd oft the dog's dry teeth are heard to fall;\nBut reaching once the foe, he pays for all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With his huge tail the troubled waves so sore\nThe monster beats, that they ascend heaven-high;\nAnd the knight knows not if he swim, or soar\nUpon his feathered courser in mid sky;\nAnd oft were fain to find himself ashore:\nFor, if long time the spray so thickly fly,\nHe fears it so will bathe his hippogryph,\nThat he shall vainly covet gourd or skiff."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He then new counsel took, and 'twas the best,\nWith other arms the monster to pursue;\nAnd lifting from his shield the covering vest,\nTo dazzle with the light his blasted view.\nLandward towards the rock-chained maid he pressed,\nAnd on her little finger, lest a new\nMischance should follow, slipt the ring, which brought\nThe enchantment of the magic shield to nought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say the ring, which Bradamant, to free\nRogero, from Brunello's hand had rent,\nAnd which, to snatch him from Alcina, she\nHad next to India by Melissa sent.\nMelissa (as before was said by me),\nIn aid of many used the instrument;\nAnd to Rogero this again had born;\nBy whom 'twas ever on his finger worn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He gave it now Angelica; for he\nFeared lest the buckler's light should be impaired,\nAnd willed as well those beauteous eyes should be\nDefended, which had him already snared.\nPressing beneath his paunch full half the sea,\nNow to the shore the monstrous whale repaired:\nFirm stood Rogero, and the veil undone,\nAppeared to give the sky another sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He in the monster's eyes the radiance throws,\nWhich works as it was wont in other time.\nAs trout or grayling to the bottom goes\nIn stream, which mountaineer disturbs with lime;\nSo the enchanted buckler overthrows\nThe orc, reversed among the foam and slime.\nRogero here and there the beast astound\nStill beats, but cannot find the way to wound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while the lady begs him not to bray\nLonger the monster's rugged scale in vain.\n\"For heaven's sake turn and loose me\" (did she say,\nStill weeping \"ere the orc awake again. ) \n\nBear me with thee, and drown me in mid-way.\nLet me not this foul monster's food remain.\"\nBy her just plaint Rogero moved, forebore,\nUntied the maid, and raised her from the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the beach the courser plants his feet,\nAnd goaded by the rowel, towers in air,\nAnd gallops with Rogero in mid seat,\nWhile on the croup behind him sate the fair;\nWho of his banquet so the monster cheat;\nFor him too delicate and dainty fare.\nRogero turns and with thick kisses plies\nThe lady's snowy breast and sparkling eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He kept no more the way, as he before\nProposed, for compassing the whole of Spain:\nBut stopt his courser on the neighbouring shore\nWhere lesser Britain runs into the main.\nUpon the bank there rose an oakwood hoar,\nWhere Philomel for ever seemed to plain;\nI' the middle was a meadow with a fountain,\nAnd, at each end, a solitary mountain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas here the wishful knight first checked the rein,\nAnd dropping in the meadow, made his steed\nFurl, yet not shut so close, his wings again,\nAs he had spread them wide for better speed.\nDown lights Rogero, and forbears with pain\nFrom other leap; but this his arms impede:\nHis arms impede; a bar to his desire,\nAnd he must doff them would he slake the fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now here, now there, confused by different throng,\nRogero did his shining arms undo:\nNever the task appeared to him so long;\nFor where he loosed one knot, he fastened two.\nBut, sir, too long continued is this song,\nAnd haply may as well have wearied you;\nSo that I shall delay to other time,\nWhen it may better please, my tedious rhyme."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 11"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Assisted by the magic ring she wears,\nAngelica evanishes from view.\nNext in a damsel, whom a giant bears\nBeneath his arm, his bride Rogero true\nBeholds.  Orlando to the shore repairs,\nWhere the fell orc so many damsels slew;\nOlympia frees, and spoils the beast of life:\nHer afterwards Oberto takes to wife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Although a feeble rein, in mid career,\nWill oft suffice to stop courageous horse;\n'Tis seldom Reason's bit will serve to steer\nDesire, or turn him from his furious course,\nWhen pleasure is in reach: like headstrong bear,\nWhom from the honeyed meal 'tis ill to force,\nIf once he scent the tempting mess, or sup\nA drop, which hangs upon the luscious cup."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What reason then Rogero shall withhold\nFrom taking with Angelica delight, —\nThat gentle maid, there naked in his hold,\nIn the lone forest, and secure from sight?\nOf Bradamant he thinks not, who controlled\nHis bosom erst: and foolish were the knight,\nIf thinking of that damsel as before,\nBy this he had not set an equal store;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Warmed by whose youthful beauties, the severe\nXenocrates would not have been more chaste.\nThe impatient Child had dropt both shield and spear,\nAnd hurrying now his other arms uncased;\nWhen, casting down her eyes in shame and fear,\nThe virtuous ring upon her finger placed,\nAngelica descried, and which of yore\nFrom her Brunello in Albracca bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This is the ring she carried into France,\nWhen thither first the damsel took her way;\nWith her the brother, bearer of the lance,\nAfter, the paladin, Astolpho's prey.\nWith this she Malagigi's spells and trance\nMade vain by Merlin's stair; and on a day\nOrlando freed, with many knights and good,\nFrom Dragontina's cruel servitude:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With this passed viewless from the turret-cell,\nWhere her that bad old man had mewed; but why\nRecount its different wonders, if as well\nYou know the virtues of the ring as I?\nFrom her this even in her citadel,\nHis monarch Agramant to satisfy,\nBrunello took: since where she had been crost\nBy Fortune, till her native realm was lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now that she this upon her hand surveys,\nShe is so full of pleasure and surprise,\nShe doubts it is a dream, and, in amaze,\nHardly believes her very hand and eyes.\nThen softly to her mouth the hoop conveys,\nAnd, quicker than the flash which cleaves the skies,\nFrom bold Rogero's sight her beauty shrowds,\nAs disappears the sun, concealed in clouds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet still Rogero gazed like wight distraught,\nAnd hurried here and there with fruitless speed:\nBut when he had recalled the ring to thought,\nFoiled and astounded, cursed his little heed.\nAnd now the vanished lady, whom he sought,\nOf that ungrateful and discourteous deed\nAccusing stood, wherewith she had repaid,\n(Unfitting recompense his generous aid. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ungrateful damsel!  and is this the pay\nYou render for the service done?\" (said he)\n\"Why rather would you steal my ring away\nThan have it as a welcome gift from me?\nNot only this, (but use me as you may)\nI, and my shield and courser, yours shall be;\nSo you no more conceal your beauteous cheer.\nCruel, though answering not, I know you hear.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, like one blind, with bootless care,\nFeeling his way about the fount he strayed.\nHow often he embraced the empty air,\nHoping in this to have embraced the maid!\nMeanwhile, now far removed, the flying fair\nHad halted not, till to a cave conveyed.\nFormed in a mountain was that harbour rude;\nSpacious, and for her need supplied with food."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas here an aged herdsman, one who tended\nA numerous troop of mares, had made his won:\nThese, seeking pasture, through the valley wended,\nWhere the green grass was fed by freshening run:\nWhile stalls on either side the cave, defended\nHis charge from the oppressive noon-tide sun;\nAngelica, within, that livelong day,\nUnseen of prying eyes, prolonged her stay;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And about evening, when refreshed with rest\nAnd food, she deemed her course she might renew;\nIn certain rustic weeds her body dressed:\nHow different from those robes of red, or blue,\nGreen, yellow, purple, her accustomed vest,\nSo various in its fashion, shape, and hue!\nYet her not so that habit misbecame,\nBut that she looked the fair and noble dame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then Phillis' and Neaera's praise forbear,\nAnd ye who sing of Amaryllis cease,\nOr flying Galataea, not so fair,\nTityrus and Melibaeus, with your peace!\n'Twas here the beauteous lady took a mare,\nWhich liked her best, of all that herd's increase.\nThen, and then first conceived the thought, again\nTo seek in the Levant her antient reign."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while Rogero, after he had passed\nLong space in hope the maid might re-appear,\nAwakened from his foolish dream at last,\nAnd found she was not nigh, and did not hear.\nThen to remount his griffin-courser cast,\nIn earth and air accustomed to career.\nBut, having slipt his bit, the winged horse\nHad towered and soared in air a freer course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To his first ill addition grave and sore\nWas to have lost the bird of rapid wing,\nWhich he no better than the mockery bore\nPut on him by the maid; but deeper sting\nThan this or that, implants, and pains him more,\nThe thought of having lost the precious ring;\nNot for its power so much, esteemed above\nIts worth, as given him by his lady love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Afflicted beyond measure, he, with shield\nCast on his shoulder, and new-cased in mail,\nLeft the sea-side, and through a grassy field\nPursued his way, towards a spacious vale:\nWhere he beheld a path, by wood concealed,\nThe widest and most beaten in the dale.\nNor far had wound the closest shades within,\nEre on his right he heard a mighty din."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He heard a din, and fearful clashing sound\nOf arms, and hurrying on with eager pace\n'Twixt tree and tree, two furious champions found,\nWaging fierce fight in close and straightened place:\nWho to each other (warring on what ground\nI know not neither showed regard nor grace. ) \n\nThe one a giant was of haughty cheer,\nAnd one a bold and gallant cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Covered with shield and sword, one, leaping, sped\nNow here now there, and thus himself defended,\nLest a two-handed mace upon his head\nShould fall, with which the giant still offended: —\nOn the field lay his horse, already dead.\nRogero paused, and to the strife attended:\nAnd straight his wishes leant towards the knight,\nWhom he would fain see conqueror in the fight:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet not for this would lend the champion aid,\nBut to behold the cruel strife stood nigh.\nLo!  a two-handed stroke the giant made\nUpon the lesser warrior's casque, and by\nThe mighty blow the knight was overlaid:\nThe other, when astound he saw him lie,\nTo deal the foe his death, his helm untied,\nSo that the warrior's face Rogero spied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of his sweet lady, of his passing fair,\nAnd dearest Bradamant Rogero spies\nThe lovely visage of its helmet bare;\nTowards whom, to deal her death, the giant hies:\nSo that, advancing with his sword in air,\nTo sudden battle him the Child defies,\nBut he, who will not wait for new alarm,\nTakes the half-lifeless lady in his arm,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And on his shoulder flings and bears away;\nAs sometimes wolf a little lamb will bear,\nOr eagle in her crooked claws convey\nPigeon, or such-like bird, through liquid air.\nRogero runs with all the speed he may,\nWho sees how needed is his succour there.\nBut with such strides the giant scours the plain,\nHim with his eyes the knight pursues with pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This flying and that following, the two\nKept a close path which widened still, and they\nPiercing that forest, issued forth to view\nOn a wide meadow, which without it lay.\n— No more of this.  Orlando I pursue,\nThat bore Cymosco's thunder-bolt away;\nAnd this had in the deepest bottom drowned,\nThat never more the mischief might be found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But with small boot: for the impious enemy\nOf human nature, taught the bolt to frame,\nAfter the shaft, which darting from the sky\nPierces the cloud and comes to ground in flame,\nWho, when he tempted Eve to eat and die\nWith the apple, hardly wrought more scathe and shame,\nSome deal before, or in our grandsires' day,\nGuided a necromancer where it lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "More than a hundred fathom buried so,\nWhere hidden it had lain a mighty space,\nThe infernal tool by magic from below\nWas fished and born amid the German race;\nWho, by one proof and the other, taught to know\nIts powers, and he who plots for our disgrace,\nThe demon, working on their weaker wit,\nAs last upon its fatal purpose hit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Italy and France, on every hand\nThe cruel art among all people past:\nAnd these the bronze in hollow mould expand,\nFirst in the furnace melted by the blast:\nOthers the iron bore, and small or grand,\nFashion the various tube they pierce or cast.\nAnd bombard, gun, according to its frame,\nOr single cannon this, or double, name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This saker, culverine, or falcon hight,\nI hear (all names the inventor has bestowed);\nWhich splits or shivers steel and stone outright,\nAnd, where the bullet passes, makes a road.\n— Down to the sword, restore thy weapons bright,\nSad soldier, to the forge, a useless load;\nAnd gun or carbine on thy shoulder lay,\nWho without these, I wot, shalt touch no pay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How, foul and pestilent discovery,\nDidst thou find place within the human heart?\nThrough thee is martial glory lost, through thee\nThe trade of arms became a worthless art:\nAnd at such ebb are worth and chivalry,\nThat the base often plays the better part.\nThrough thee no more shall gallantry, no more\nShall valour prove their prowess as of yore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through thee, alas!  are dead, or have to die,\nSo many noble lords and cavaliers\nBefore this war shall end, which, Italy\nAfflicting most, has drowned the world in tears,\nThat, if I said the word, I err not, I,\nSaying he sure the cruellest appears\nAnd worst, of nature's impious and malign,\nWho did this hateful engine first design:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And I shall think, in order to pursue\nThe sin for ever, God has doomed to hell\nThat cursed soul, amid the unhappy crew,\nBeside the accursed Judas there to dwell.\nBut follow we the good Orlando, who\nSo burns to seek Ebuda's island fell,\nWhose foul inhabitants a monster sate\nWith flesh of women, fair and delicate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But no less slow than eager was the knight:\nThe winds appear, which still his course delay;\nWho, whether blowing on the left or right,\nOr poop, so faintly in his canvas play,\nHis bark makes little speed; and, spent outright,\nThe breeze which wafts her sometimes dies away,\nOr blows so foul, that he is fain to steer\nAnother course, or to the leeward veer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It was the will of Heaven that he, before\nThe King of Ireland, should not reach the land,\nThe he with greater ease upon that shore\nMight act what shortly you shall understand.\n\"Make for the isle.  Now\" (said he \"may'st thou moor,\" ) \n\n(Thus issuing to the pilot his command),\n\"And give me for my need the skiff; for I\nWill to the rock without more company."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The biggest cable that thou hast aboard,\nAnd biggest anchor to my hands consign;\nThou shalt perceive why thus my boat is stored,\nIf I but meet that monster of the brine.\"\nHe bade them lower the pinnace overboard,\nWith all things that befitted his design:\nHis arms he left behind, except his blade,\nAnd singly for the rocky island made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Home to his breast the count pulls either oar,\nWith the island at his back, to which he wends,\nIn guise that, crawling up the sandy shore,\nThe crooked crab from sea or marsh ascends.\nIt was the hour Aurora gay before\nThe rising sun her yellow hair extends\n(His orb as yet half-seen, half-hid from sight)\nNot without stirring jealous Tithon's spite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Approaching to the naked rock as near\nAs vigorous hand might serve to cast a stone,\nHe knew not if he heard, or did not hear\nA cry, so faint and feeble was the moan.\nWhen, turning to the left, the cavalier,\nHis level sight along the water thrown,\nNaked as born, bound to a stump, espied\nA dame whose feet were wetted by the tide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Because she distant is, and evermore\nHolds down her face, he ill can her discern:\nBoth sculls he pulls amain, and nears the shore,\nWith keen desire more certain news to learn:\nBut now the winding beach is heard to roar,\nAnd wood and cave the mighty noise return;\nThe billows swell, and, lo!  the beast!  who pressed,\nAnd nigh concealed the sea beneath his breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As cloud from humid vale is seen to rise,\nPregnant with rain and storm, which seems withal\nTo extinguished day, and charged with deeper dyes\nThan night, to spread throughout this earthly ball,\nSo swims the beast, who so much occupies\nOf sea, he may be said to keep it all.\nWaves roar: collected in himself, the peer\nLooks proudly on, unchanged in heart and cheer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, as one well resolved in his intent,\nMoved quickly to perform the feat he planned;\nAnd, for he would the damsel's harm prevent,\nAnd would with that assail the beast at hand,\nBetween her and the orc the boat he sent,\nLeaving within the sheath his idle brand,\nAnchor and cable next he takes in hold,\nAnd waits the foe with constant heart and bold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as him the monster has descried,\nAnd skiff at little interval, his throat\nThe fish, to swallow him, expands so wide,\nThat horse and horseman through his jaws might float.\nHere Roland with the anchor, and beside\n(Unless I am mistaken with the boat ) \n\nPlunged, and engulphed the parted teeth betwixt,\nHis anchor in the tongue and palate fixt;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So that the monster could no longer drop\nOr raise his horrid jaws, which this extends.\n'Tis thus who digs the mine is wont to prop\nThe ground, and where he works the roof suspends,\nLest sudden ruin whelm him from atop,\nWhile he incautiously his task intends.\nRoland (so far apart was either hook)\nBut by a leap could reach the highest crook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The prop so placed, Orlando now secure\nThat the fell beast his mouth no more can close,\nUnsheathes his sword, and, in that cave obscure,\nDeals here and there, now thrusts, now trenchant blows.\nAs well as citadel, whose walls immure\nThe assailants, can defend her from her foes,\nThe monster, harassed by the war within,\nDefends himself against the Paladin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now floats the monstrous beast, o'ercome with pain,\nWhose scaly flanks upon the waves expand;\nAnd now descends into the deepest main,\nScowers at the bottom, and stirs up the sand.\nThe rising flood ill able to sustain,\nThe cavalier swims forth, and makes for land.\nHe leaves the anchor fastened in his tongue,\nAnd grasps the rope which from the anchor hung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So swimming till the island is attained,\nWith this towards the rock Orlando speeds:\nHe hawls the anchor home (a footing gained),\nPricked by whose double fluke, the monster bleeds.\nThe labouring orc to follow is constrained,\nDragged by that force which every force exceeds;\nWhich at a single sally more achieves\nThan at ten turns the circling windlass heaves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As a wild bull, about whose horn is wound\nThe unexpected noose, leaps here and there,\nWhen he has felt the cord, and turns him round,\nAnd rolls and rises, yet slips not the snare;\nSo from his pleasant seat and ancient bound,\nDragged by that arm and rope he cannot tear,\nWith thousands of strange wheels and thousand slides,\nThe monster follows where the cable guides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This the red sea with reason would be hight\nTo-day, such streams of blood have changed its hue;\nAnd where the monster lashed it in his spite,\nThe eye its bottom through the waves might view.\nAnd now he splashed the sky, and dimmed the light\nOf the clear sun, so high the water flew.\nThe noise re-echoing round, the distant shore\nAnd wood and hill rebound the deafening roar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Forth from his grotto aged Proteus hies,\nAnd mounts above the surface at the sound;\nAnd having seen Orlando dive, and rise\nFrom the orc, and drag the monstrous fish to ground,\nHis scattered flock forgot, o'er ocean flies;\nWhile so the din increases, that, astound,\nNeptune bids yoke his dolphins, and that day\nFor distant Aethiopia posts away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With Melicerta on her shoulders, weeping\nIno, and Nereids with dishevelled hair,\nThe Glauci, Tritons, and their fellows, leaping\nThey know not whither, speed, some here, some there.\nOrlando draws to land, the billows sweeping,\nThat horrid fish, but might his labour spare:\nFor, with the torment worn, and travel sore,\nThe brute, exhausted, died, ere dragged ashore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of the islanders had trooped no petty throng,\nTo witness that strange fight, who by a vain\nAnd miserable superstition stung,\nEsteemed such holy deed a work profane;\nAnd said that this would be another wrong\nTo Proteus, and provoke his ire again;\nMake him his herds pour forth upon the strand,\nAnd with the whole old warfare vex the land;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And that it better were to sue for peace,\nFirst from the injured god, lest worse ensue;\nAnd Proteus from his cruel hate would cease,\nIf they into the sea the offender threw.\nAs torch to torch gives fire, and lights increase,\nUntil the flame is spread the country through,\nEven so from heart to heart the fury spread,\nWhich in the waves would doom Orlando dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These, armed with sling or bow, upon the shore,\nAnd these supplied with spear or sword descend;\nAnd on each side, behind him and before,\nDistant and near, as best they can, offend.\nAt such a brutal insult wonders sore\nThe peer, who sees that mischief they intend,\nIn vengeance for the cruel monster slain,\nWhence he had glory hoped, and praise to gain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But as the usage is of surly bear,\nBy sturdy Russ or Lithuanian led,\nLittle to heed the dogs in crowded fair,\nNor even at their yelps to turn his head,\nThe clamour of the churls assembled there\nOrlando witnessed with as little dread;\nWho knew that he the rout which threatened death,\nHad power to scatter at a single breath:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And speedily he made them yield him place,\nWhen turned on them, he grasped his trenchant blade.\nMisjudging of his worth, the foolish race\nDeemed that he would have short resistance made;\nSince him they saw no covering buckler brace,\nUncuirassed, nor in other arms arrayed;\nBut knew not that, from head to foot, a skin\nMore hard than diamond cased the Paladin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What by Orlando others cannot do,\nThe knight by others can; at half a score\nOf blows in all he thirty killed; by few\nHe passed that measure, if the strokes were more:\nAnd had already turned him to undo\nThe naked lady, having cleared the shore,\nWhen other larum sounds, and other cries\nFrom a new quarter of the island rise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While so the Paladin had kept in play\nThe barbarous islanders, upon that hand,\nThe men of Ireland, without let or fray,\nHad poured from many quarters on the strand:\nAnd now, without remorse or pity, slay\nThe inhabitants, through all the wasted land;\nAnd, was it justice moved, or cruel rage,\nSlaughter without regard to sex or age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Little or no defender the island-crew\nAttempt; in part as taken unaware,\nIn part that in the little place are few,\nAnd that those few without a purpose are.\n'Mid sack and fire, the wasted country through,\nThe islanders are slain, and everwhere\nThe walls are upon earth in ruin spread,\nNor in the land is left a living head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As if the mighty tumult which he hears,\nAnd shriek and ruin had concerned him nought,\nThe naked rock the bold Orlando nears,\nWhere she was placed, to feed the monster brought.\nHe looks, and known to him the dame appears,\nAnd more appears, when nigher her he sought:\nOlympia she appears, and is indeed\nOlympia, whose faith reaped so ill a meed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Wretched Olympia; whom, beside the scorn\nWhich Love put on her, Fortune too pursued,\nWho sent the corsairs fell, which her had born\nThat very day to the island of Ebude.\nShe Roland recollects on his return\nLandward; but, for the damsel naked stood,\nNot only nought she to the warrior said,\nBut dared not raise her eyes, and dropt her head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando asks what evil destiny\nHer to that cruel island had conveyed\nFrom where she in as much felicity\nWas with her consort left as could be said:\n\"I know not (cried the weeping dame if I ) \n\nHave thanks to render thee for death delayed,\nOr should lament me that, through means of thee,\nThis day did not my woes concluded see."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I have to thank thee that from death, too dread\nAnd monstrous, thy good arm deliverance gave;\nWhich would have been too monstrous, had I fed\nThe beast, and in his belly found a grave:\nBut cannot thank thee that I am not dead,\nSince death alone can me from misery save,\nWell shall I thank thee for that wished relief,\nWhich can deliver me from every grief.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next she related, with loud sobs and sighs,\nHow her false spouse betrayed her as she lay\nAsleep, and how of pirates made the prize,\nThey bore her from the desert isle away.\nAnd, as she spake, she turned her in the guise\nOf Dian, framed by artists, who pourtray\nHer carved or painted, as in liquid font\nShe threw the water in Actaeon's front."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For, as she can, her waist she hides, and breast,\nMore liberal of flowing flank and reins.\nRoland desires his ship, to find a vest\nTo cover her, delivered from her chains:\nWhile he is all intent upon this quest,\nOberto comes; Oberto, he that reigns\nO'er Ireland's people, who had understood\nHow lifeless lay the monster of the flood;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, swimming, how, amid the watery roar,\nA knight a weighty anchor in his throat\nHad fix'd, and so had dragged him to the shore,\nAs men against the current track a boat.\nThis while Oberto comes; who, if his lore,\nWho told the tale, were true, desires to note;\nWhile his invading army, far and wide,\nEbuda burn and waste on every side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oberto, though the Paladin to sight\nWas dripping, and with water foul and gore;\nWith gore, that from the orc, emerged to light,\nWhom he had entered bodily, he bore,\nHe for the country knew the stranger knight\nAs he perused his face; so much the more,\nThat he had thought when told the tidings, none\nSave Roland could such mighty fear have done;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Knew him, because a page of honour he\nHad been in France, and for the crown, his right\nUpon his father's death, had crossed the sea\nThe year before.  So often he the knight\nHad seen, and had with him held colloquy,\nTheir times of meeting had been infinite.\nHe doffed his casque, with festive welcome pressed\nTowards the count, and clasped him to the breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando is no less rejoined to see\nThe king, than is the king that champion true.\nAfter with friendly cheer and equal glee\nHad once or twice embraced the noble two,\nTo Oberto Roland told the treachery\nWhich had been done the youthful dame, and who\nHad done it, — false Bireno — that among\nAll men should least have sought to do her wrong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him he told the many proofs and clear\nBy which the dame's affection had been tried;\nAnd how she for Bireno kin and geer\nHad lost, and would in fine for him have died.\nAnd how he this could warrant, and appear\nTo vouch for much, as witness on her side.\nWhile thus to him her griefs Orlando showed,\nThe lady's shining eyes with tears o'erflowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her face was such as sometimes in the spring\nWe see a doubtful sky, when on the plain\nA shower descends, and the sun, opening\nHis cloudy veil, looks out amid the rain.\nAnd as the nightingale then loves to sing\nFrom branch of verdant stem her dulcet strain,\nSo in her beauteous tears his pinions bright\nLove bathes, rejoicing in the chrystal light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The stripling heats his golden arrow's head\nAt her bright eyes, then slacks the weapon's glow\nIn streams, which falls between white flowers and red;\nAnd, the shaft tempered, strongly draws his bow,\nAnd roves at him, o'er whom no shield is spread,\nNor iron rind, nor double mail below;\nWho, gazing on her tresses, eyes, and brow,\nFeels that his heart is pierced, he knows not how."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Olympia's beauties are of those most rare,\nNor is the forehead's beauteous curve alone\nExcellent, and her eyes and cheeks and hair,\nMouth, nose, and throat, and shoulders; but, so down\nDescending from the lady's bosom fair,\nParts which are wont to be concealed by gown,\nAre such, as haply should be placed before\nWhate'er this ample world contains in store."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In whiteness they surpassed unsullied snow,\nSmooth ivory to the touch: above were seen\nTwo rounding paps, like new-pressed milk in show,\nFresh-taken from its crate of rushes green;\nThe space betwixt was like the valley low,\nWhich oftentimes we see small hills between,\nSweet in its season, and now such as when\nWinter with snows has newly filled the glen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The swelling hips and haunches' symmetry,\nThe waist more clear than mirror's polished grain,\nAnd members seem of Phidias' turnery,\nOr work of better hand and nicer pain.\nAs well to you of other parts should I\nRelate, which she to hide desired in vain.\nTo sum the beauteous whole, from head to feet,\nIn her all loveliness is found complete."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And had she in the Idaean glen unveiled\nIn ancient days before the Phrygian swain,\nBy how much heavenly Venus had prevailed\nI know not, though her rivals strove in vain.\nNor haply had the youth for Sparta sailed,\nTo violate the hospitable reign;\nBut said:  \"With Menelaus let Helen rest!\nNo other prize I seek, of this possest\";"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Or in Crotona dwelt, where the divine\nZeuxis in days of old his work projected,\nTo be the ornament of Juno's shrine,\nAnd hence so many naked dames collected;\nAnd in one form perfection to combine,\nSome separate charm from this or that selected,\nHe from no other model need have wrought.\nSince joined in her were all the charms he sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I do not think Bireno ever viewed\nNaked that beauteous form; for sure it were\nHe never could have been so stern of mood,\nAs to have left her on that desert lair.\nThat Ireland's king was fired I well conclude,\nNor hid the flame that he within him bare.\nHe strives to comfort her, and hope instill,\nThat future good shall end her present ill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And her to Holland promises to bear,\nAnd vows till she is to her state restored,\nAnd just and memorable vengeance there\nAchieved upon her perjured, traitor lord,\nHe never will unceasing war forbear,\nWaged with all means that Ireland can afford;\nAnd this with all his speed.  He, up and down,\nMeantime bids seek for female vest and gown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now will it need to send in search of vest\nBeyond the savage island's narrow bound,\nSince thither every day in such came dressed,\nSome dame, to feed the beast, from countries round.\nNor long his followers there pursued the quest,\nEre many they of various fashions found.\nSo was Olympia clothed; while sad of mood\nWas he, not so to clothe her as he wou'd."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But never silk so choice or gold so fine\nDid the industrious Florentine prepare,\nNor whosoever broiders gay design,\nThough on his task be spent time, toil, and care,\nNor Lemnos' god, nor Pallas' art divine,\nForm raiment worthy of those limbs so fair,\nThat King Oberto cannot choose but he\nRecalls them at each turn to memory."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To see that love so kindled by the dame,\nOn many grounds Orlando was content;\nWho not alone rejoiced that such a shame\nPut upon her, Bireno should repent;\nBut, that in the design on which he came,\nHe should be freed from grave impediment.\nNot for Olympia thither had he made,\nBut, were his lady there, to lend her aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him, that there she was not, soon was clear,\nBut clear it was not if she had been there,\nOr no; since of those islesmen, far and near,\nOne was not left the tidings to declare.\nThe following day they from the haven steer,\nAnd all united in one squadron fare.\nThe Paladin with them to Ireland hies,\nFrom whence to France the warrior's passage lies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scarcely a day in Ireland's realm he spends:\nAnd for no prayers his purposed end forbore:\nLove, that in quest of his liege-lady sends\nThe knight upon this track, permits no more.\nDeparting, he Olympia recommends\nTo the Irish monarch, who to serve her swore:\nAlthough this needed not; since he was bent\nMore than behoved, her wishes to content:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So levied in few days his warlike band,\nAnd (league with England's kind and Scotland's made)\nIn Holland and in Friesland left no land\nTo the false duke, so rapid was the raid.\nAnd to rebel against that lord's command\nHis Zealand stirred; nor he the war delayed,\nUntil by him Bireno's blood was spilt:\nA punishment that ill atoned his guilt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oberto takes to wife Olympia fair,\nAnd her of countess makes a puissant queen.\nBut be the Paladin again our care,\nWho furrows , night and day, the billows green,\nAnd strikes his sails in the same harbour, where\nThey to the wind erewhile unfurled had been\nAll armed, he on his Brigliadoro leaps,\nAnd leaves behind him winds and briny deeps."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The remnant of the winter, he with shield\nAnd spear achieved things worthy to be shown,\nI ween; but these were then so well concealed,\nIt is no fault of mine they are not blown;\nFor good Orlando was in fighting field,\nPrompter to do, than make his prowess known.\nNor e'er was bruited action of the knight,\nSave when some faithful witness was in sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That winter's remnant he so passed that feat\nOf his was known not to the public ear;\nBut when within that animal discreet\nWhich Phryxus bore, the sun illumed the sphere,\nAnd Zephyrus returning glad and sweet,\nBrought back with him again the blooming year,\nThe wondrous deeds Orlando did in stower,\nAppeared with the new grass and dainty flower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From plain to hill, from champaign flat to shore,\nOppressed with grief and pain the County fares,\nWhen a long cry, entering a forest hoar,\n— A load lamenting smites upon his ears.\nHe grasps his brand and spurs his courser sore,\nAnd swiftly pricks toward the sound he hears.\nBut I shall at another season say\nWhat chanced, and may be heard in future lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 12"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando, full of rage, pursues a knight\nWho bears by force his lady-love away,\nAnd comes where old Atlantes, by his sleight\nHad raised a dome, Rogero there to stay.\nHere too Rogero comes; where getting sight\nOf his lost love, the County strives in fray\nWith fierce Ferrau, and, after slaughter fell\nAmid the paynim host, finds Isabel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ceres, when from the Idaean dame in haste\nReturning to the lonely valley, where\nEnceladus the Aetnaean mountain placed\nOn his bolt-smitten flanks, is doomed to bear,\nHer girl she found not, on that pathless waste,\nBy her late quitted, having rent her hair,\nAnd marked cheeks, eyes, and breast, with livid signs,\nAt the end of her lament tore up two pines,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And lit at Vulcan's fire the double brand,\nAnd gave them virtue never to be spent;\nAnd, afterwards, with one in either hand,\nDrawn by two dragons, in her chariot went,\nSearching the forest, hill, and level land,\nField, valley, running stream, or water pent,\nThe land and sea; and having searched the shell\nOf earth above, descended into hell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Had Roland of Eleusis' deity\nThe sovereign power possessed no less than will,\nHe for Angelica had land and sea\nRansacked, and wood and field, and pool and rill,\nHeaven, and Oblivion's bottom: but since he\nHad not, his pressing purpose to fulfil,\nHer dragon and her car, the unwearied knight\nPursued the missing maid as best he might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through France he sought her, and will seek her through\nThe realms of Italy and of Almayn,\nAnd thence through the Castiles, both old and new,\nSo passing into Libya out of Spain.\nWhile bold Orlando has this plan in view,\nHe hears, or thinks he hears, a voice complain:\nHe forward spurs, and sees on mighty steed\nA warrior trot before him on the mead;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who in his arms a captive damsel bears,\nSore grieving, and across the pommel laid;\nShe weeps and struggles, and the semblance wears\nOf cruel woe, and ever calls for aid\nUpon Anglantes' prince; and now appears\nTo him, as he surveys the youthful maid,\nShe, for whom, night and day, with ceaseless pain,\nInside and out, he France had searched in vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say not is, but that she to the sight\nSeems the Angelica he loves so dear.\nHe who is lady-love and goddess' flight\nBeholds, borne off in such afflicted cheer,\nImpelled by fury foul, and angry spite,\nCalls back with horrid voice the cavalier;\nCalls back the cavalier, and threats in vain,\nAnd Brigliadoro drives with flowing rein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That felon stops not, nor to him replies,\nOn his great gain intent, his glorious prey;\nAnd with such swiftness through the greenwood hies,\nWind would not overtake him on his way.\nThe one pursues while him the other flies,\nAnd with lament resounds the thicket gray.\nThey issue in a spacious mead, on which\nAppears a lofty mansion, rare and rich."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of various marbles, wrought with subtle care,\nIs the proud palace.  He who fast in hold\nBears off upon his arm the damsel fair,\nSore pricking, enters at a gate of gold.\nNor Brigliador is far behind the pair,\nBacked by Orlando, angry knight and bold.\nEntering, around Orlando turns his eyes,\nYet neither cavalier nor damsel spies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He suddenly dismounts, and thundering fares\nThrough the inmost palace, seeking still his foe,\nAnd here and there in restless rage repairs,\nTill he has seen each bower, each galleried row;\nWith the same purpose he ascends the stairs,\nHaving first vainly searched each room below.\nNor spends less labour, on his task intent,\nAbove, than he beneath had vainly spent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here beds are seen adorned with silk and gold;\nNor of partition aught is spied or wall:\nFor these, and floor beneath, throughout that hold,\nAre hid by curtains and by carpets all.\nNow here, now there, returns Orlando bold,\nNor yet can glad his eyes, in bower or hall,\nWith the appearance of the royal maid,\nOr the foul thief by whom she was conveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while, as here and there in fruitless pain\nHe moves, oppressed with thought and trouble sore,\nGradasso, Brandimart, and him of Spain,\nFerrau, he finds, with Sacripant and more;\nWho ever toiling, like himself, in vain\nAbove, that building, and beneath explore,\nAnd as they wander, curse with one accord\nThe malice of the castle's viewless lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All in pursuit of the offender speed,\nAnd upon him some charge of robbery lay:\nOne knight complains that he has stolen his steed,\nOne that he has purloined his lady gay.\nOther accuses him of other deed:\nAnd thus within the enchanted cage they stay,\nNor can depart; while in the palace pent,\nMany have weeks and months together spent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Roland, when he round that strange dome had paced\nFour times or six, still vainly seeking, said\nWithin himself, at last, \"I here might waste\nMy time and trouble, still in vain delayed,\nWhile haply her the robber whom I chased\nHas far away, through other gate conveyed.\"\nSo thinking, from the house he issued out\nInto the mead which girt the dome about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While Roland wanders round the sylvan Hall,\nStill holding close his visage to the ground,\nTo see if recent print or trace withal\nCan, right or left, upon the turf be found,\nHe from a neighbouring window hears a call,\nAnd looks, and thinks he hears that voice's sound,\nAnd thinks he sees the visage by which he\nWas so estranged from what he wont to be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He thinks he hears Angelica, and she\n\"Help, help!\" entreating cries, and weeping sore,\n\"More than for life and soul, alas!  of thee\nProtection for my honour I implore.\nThen shall it in my Roland's presence be\nRavished by this foul robber?  Oh! before\nMe to such miserable fate you leave,\nLet me from your own hand my death receive!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These words repeated once, and yet again,\nMade Roland through each chamber, far and near,\nReturn with passion, and with utmost pain;\nBut tempered with high hope.  Sometimes the peer\nStopt in his search and heard a voice complain,\nWhich seemed to be Angelica's:  if here\nThe restless warrior stand, it sounds from there,\nAnd calls for help he knows not whence nor where,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Returning to Rogero, left, I said,\nWhen through a gloomy path, upon his steed,\nFollowing the giant and the dame who fled,\nHe from the wood had issued on the mead;\nI say that he arrived where Roland dread\nArrived before him, if I rightly read.\nThe giant through the golden portal passed,\nRogero close behind, who followed fast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as he his foot has lifted o'er\nThe threshold, he through court and gallery spies;\nNor sees the giant or the lady more,\nAnd vainly glances here and there his eyes.\nHe up and down returns with labour sore,\nYet not for that his longing satisfies;\nNor can imagine where the felon thief\nHas hid himself and dame in space so brief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After four times or five he so had wound\nAbove, below, through bower and gallery fair,\nHe yet returned, and, having nothing found,\nSearched even to the space beneath the stair.\nAt length, in hope they in the woodlands round\nMight be, he sallied; but the voice, which there\nRoland recalled, did him no less recall,\nAnd made as well return within the Hall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One voice, one shape, which to Anglantes' peer\nSeemed his Angelica, beseeching aid.\nSeemed to Rogero Dordogne's lady dear.\nWho him a truant to himself had made:\nIf with Gradasso, or with other near\nHe spake, of those who through the palace strayed.\nTo all of them the vision, seen apart,\nSeemed that which each had singly most at heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was a new and unwonted spell,\nWhich the renowned Atlantes had composed,\nThat in this toil, this pleasing pain, might dwell\nSo long Rogero, by these walls enclosed,\nFrom him should pass away  the influence fell,\n— Influence which him to early death exposed.\nThough vain his magic tower of steel, and vain\nAlcina's art, Atlantes plots again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not only he, but others who stood high\nFor valour, and in France had greatest fame,\nThat by their hands Rogero might not die,\nBrought here by old Atlantes' magic came:\nWhile these in the enchanted mansion lie,\nThat food be wanting not to knight or dame,\nHe has supplied the dome throughout so well,\nThat all the inmates there in plenty dwell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But to Angelica return we, who\nNow of that ring so wondrous repossessed,\n(Which, in her mouth, concealed the maid from view,\nPreserved from spell when it the finger pressed,)\nWas in the mountain-cavern guided to\nWhatever needed, viands, mare, and vest,\nAnd had conceived the project to pursue\nHer way to her fair Indian realm anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Sacripant, or Roland, willingly\nThe damsel would have taken for her guide;\nNot that, propitious to their wishes, she\n(Averse from both inclined to either side; ) \n\nBut, since her eastern journey was to be\nThrough town and city, scattered far and wide,\nShe needed company, and ill had found\nMore trusty guides than these for such a round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now this, now that she sought with fruitless care,\nBefore she lit on either warrior's trace,\nBy city or by farm, now here, now there,\nIn forest now, and now in other place.\nFortune, at length, where caged with Roland are\nFerrau and Sacripant, directs her chase;\nRogero, with Gradasso fierce, and more,\nNoosed with strange witcheries by Atlantes hoar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She enters, hidden from the enchanter's eyes,\nAnd by the ring concealed, examines all;\nAnd Roland there, and Sacripant espies,\nIntent to seek her vainly through the Hall;\nAnd with her image cheating both, descries\nAtlantes old.  The damsel doubts withal\nWhich of the two to take, and long revolves\nThis in her doubtful thought, nor well resolves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She knows not which with her will best accord,\nThe Count Orlando or Circassia's knight.\nAs of most powers, her would Rogero ward\nIn passage perilous, with better might.\nBut should she make the peer her guide, her lord,\nShe knew not if her champion she could slight,\nIf him she would depress with altered cheer,\nOr into France send back the cavalier:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Sacripant at pleasure could depose,\nThough him she had uplifted to the sky.\nHence him alone she for her escort chose,\nAnd feigned to trust in his fidelity.\nThe ring she from her mouth withdraws, and shows\nHer face, unveiled to the Circassian's eye:\nShe thought to him alone; but fierce Ferrau\nAnd Roland came upon the maid, and saw."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ferrau and Roland came upon the maid;\nFor one and the other champion equally\nWithin the palace and without it strayed\nIn quest of her, who was their deity.\nAnd now, no longer by the enchantment stayed,\nEach ran alike towards the dame, for she\nHad placed the ring upon her hand anew,\nWhich old Atlantes' every scheme o'erthrew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Helm on the head and corselet on the breast\nOf both the knights, of whom I sing, was tied;\nBy night or day, since they into this rest\nHad entered, never doffed and laid aside:\nFor such to wear were easy as a vest,\nTo these, so wont the burden to abide.\nAs well was armed, except with iron masque,\nFerrau, who wore not, nor would wear, a casque."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Till he had that erst wrested by the peer,\nOrlando, from the brother of Troyane;\nFor so had sworn the Spanish cavalier,\nWhat time he Argalia's helm in vain\nSought in the brook; yet though the count was near,\nHas not stretched forth his hand the prize to gain.\nFor so it was, that neither of the pair\nCould recognise the other knight while there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the enchanted dome lay such a spell,\nThat they from one another were concealed;\nThey doffed not, night nor day, the corselet's shell,\nNot sword, nor even put aside the shield.\nSaddled, with bridle hanging at the sell,\nTheir steeds were feeding, ready for the field,\nWithin a chamber, near the palace door,\nWith straw and barley heaped in plenteous store."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor might nor mean in old Atlantes lies\nTo stop the knights from mounting, who repair\nTo their good steeds, to chase the bright black eyes,\nThe fair vermillion cheeks and golden hair\nOf the sweet damsel, who before them flies,\nAnd goads to better speed her panting mare;\nIll pleased the three assembled to discern,\nThough haply she had taken each in turn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when these from the magic palace she\nHad ticed so far, that she no more supposed\nThe warriors to the wicked fallacy\nOf the malign enchanter were exposed,\nThe ring, which more than once from misery\nHad rescued her, she 'twixt her lips enclosed,\nHence from their sight she vanished in a thought,\nAnd left them wondering there, like men distraught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Although she first the scheme had entertained\nRoland or Sacripant to have released,\nTo guide her thither, where her father reigned,\nKing Galaphron, who ruled i' the farthest East,\nThe aid of both she suddenly disdained,\nAnd in an instant from her project ceased;\nAnd deemed, without more debt to count or king,\nIn place of either knight sufficed the ring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In haste, they through the forest, here and there,\nSo scorned of her, still gaze with stupid face;\nLike questing hound which loses sight of hare\nOr fox, of whom he late pursued the trace,\nInto close thicket, ditch, or narrow lair,\nEscaping from the keen pursuer's chase.\nMeantime their ways the wanton Indian queen\nObserves, and at their wonder laughs unseen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the mid wood, where they the maid did lose,\nWas but a single pathway, left or right;\nWhich they believed the damsel could not choose\nBut follow, when she vanished from their sight.\nFerrau halts not, and Roland fast pursues,\nNor Sacripant less plies the rowels bright.\nAngelica, this while, retrains her steed,\nAnd follows the three warriors with less speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When pricking thus they came to where the way\nWas in the forest lost, with wood o'ergrown,\nAnd had begun the herbage to survey\nFor print of recent footsteps, up and down,\nThe fierce Ferrau, who might have borne away\nFrom all that ever proudest were, the crown,\nWith evil countenance, to the other two\nTurned him about, and shouted \"Whence are you?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Turn back or take another road, save here,\nIn truth, you covet to be slain by me.\nNor when I chase or woo my lady dear,\nLet any think I bear with company.\"\nAnd — \"What more could he say, sir cavalier,\"\n(Orlando cried to Sacripant \"if we ) \n\nWere known for the two basest whores that pull\nAnd reel from spindle-staff the matted wool?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then turning to Ferrau,, \"But that thine head,\nThou brutish sot, as I behold, is bare,\nIf thy late words were ill or wisely said,\nThou should'st perceive, before we further fare.\"\nTo him Ferrau:  \"For that which breeds no dread\nIn me, why should'st thou take such sovereign care?\nWhat I have said unhelmed will I prove true,\nHere, single as I am, on both of you.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Oh!\" (to Circassia's king cried Roland dread)\n\"Thy morion for this man let me entreat,\nTill I have driven such folly from his head;\nFor never with like madness did I meet.\"\n— \"Who then would be most fool?\" the monarch said;\n\"But if indeed you deem the suit discreet,\nLend him thine own; nor shall I be less fit\nHaply than thee to school his lack of wit.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"Fools, both of you!\" (the fierce Ferrau replied)\n\"As if, did I to wear a helm delight,\nYou would not be without your casques of pride,\nAlready reft by me in your despite;\nBut know thus much, that I by vow am tied\nTo wear no helm, and thus my promise quite;\nRoaming without, till that fine casque I win\nWorn by Orlando, Charles's paladin.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"Then\" (smiling, to the Spaniard said the count)\n\"With naked head, thou thinkest to repeat\nOn Roland what he did in Aspramont,\nBy Agolant's bold son: but shouldst thou meet\nThe warrior whom thou seekest, front to front,\nI warrant thou wouldst quake from head to feet;\nNor only wouldst forego the casque, but give\nThe knight thine other arms to let thee live.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"So oft have I had Roland on the hip,\nAnd oft,\" (exclaimed the boaster \"heretofore; ) \n\nFrom him it had been easy task to strip\nWhat other arms, beside his helm, he wore;\nAnd if I still have let the occasion slip,\n— We sometimes think of things unwished before:\nSuch wish I had not; I have now; and hope\nTo compass easily my present scope.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The good Orlando could no more forbear,\nAnd cried, \"Foul miscreant, liar, marched with me,\nSay, caitiff, in what country, when and where\nBoast you to have obtained such victory?\nThat paladin am I, o'er whom you dare\nTo vaunt, and whom you distant deemed: now see\nIf you can take my helm, or I have might\nTo take your other arms in your despite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor I o'er you the smallest vantage wou'd.\"\nHe ended, and his temples disarrayed,\nAnd to a beech hung up the helmet good,\nAnd nigh as quickly bared his trenchant blade.\nFerrau stands close, and in such attitude,\n(His courage not for what had chanced dismayed)\nCovered with lifted shield and naked sword,\nAs might best shelter to his head afford."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas thus those warriors two, with faulchions bare,\nTurning their ready steeds, began to wheel;\nAnd where the armour thinnest was, and where\nThe meeting plates were joined, probed steel with steel;\nNor was there in the world another pair\nMore fitted to be matched in fierce appeal:\nEqual their daring, equal was their might,\nAnd safe alike from wound was either knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By you, fair sir, already, I presume,\nThat fierce Ferrau was charmed is understood,\nSave where the child, enclosed within the womb\nOf the full mother, takes its early food;\nAnd hence he ever, till the squalid tomb\nCovered his manly face, wore harness good\n(Such was his wont the doubtful part to guard, ) \n\nOf seven good plates of metal, tempered hard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Alike a charmed life Orlando bore,\nSafe every where, except a single part:\nUnfenced beneath his feet, which evermore\nBy him were guarded with all care and art.\nThe rest than diamond dug from mountain hoar\nMore hard, unless report from truth depart;\nAnd armed to battle either champion went,\nLess for necessity than ornament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Waxing more fierce and fell the combat rages,\nOf fear and horror full, between the twain:\nThe fierce Ferrau such dreadful battle wages,\nThat stroke or thrust is never dealt in vain:\nEach mighty blow from Roland disengages\nAnd loosens, breaks, or shatters, plate and chain.\nAngelica alone, secure from view,\nRegards such fearful sight, and marks the two."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For, during this, the king of Circassy,\nWho deemed Angelica not far before,\nWhen Ferrau and Orlando desperately\nClosing in fight were seen, his horse did gore\nAlong the way by which he deemed that she\nHad disappeared; and so that battle sore\nWas witnessed 'twixt the struggling foes, by none,\nBeside the daughter of king Galaphron."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the damsel had sometime descried\nThis dread and direful combat, standing nigh;\nAnd it appearing that on either side\nWith equal peril both the warriors vie,\nShe, fond of novelty, the helm untied\nDesigns to take; desirous to espy\nWhat they would do when they perceived the wrong;\nBut, without thought to keep her plunder long."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To give it to Orlando was she bent,\nBut first she would upon the warrior play:\nThe helmet she took down with this intent\nAnd in her bosom hid, and marked the fray:\nNext thence, without a word to either went,\nAnd from the scene of strife was far away\nEre either of the two had marked the feat;\nSo were they blinded by their angry heat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Ferrau, who first chanced the loss to see,\nFrom Roland disengaged himself, and cried,\n\"How like unwary men and fools are we\nTreated by him, who late with us did ride!\nWhat meed, which worthiest of the strife might be,\nIf this be stolen, the victor shall abide?\"\nRoland draws back, looks upward, and with ire,\nMissing the noble casque, is all on fire:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And in opinion with Ferrau agreed,\nThat he the knight, who was with them before,\nHad born away the prize: hence turned his steed.\nAnd with the spur admonished Brigliador.\nFerrau, who from the field beheld him speed.\nFollowed him, and when Roland and the Moor\nArrived where tracks upon the herbage green\nOf the Circassian and the maid were seen,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Towards a vale upon the left the count\nWent off, pursuing the Circassian's tread;\nThe Spaniard kept the path more nigh the mount,\nBy which the fair Angelica had fled.\nAngelica, this while, has reached a fount,\nOf pleasant site, and shaded overhead;\nBy whose inviting shades no traveller hasted,\nNor ever left the chrystal wave untasted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Angelica, the sylvan spring beside,\nReposes, unsuspicious of surprise;\nAnd thinking her the sacred ring will hide,\nFears not that evil accident can rise.\nOn her arrival at the fountain's side,\nShe to a branch above the helmet ties;\nThen seeks the fittest sapling for her need,\nWhere, fastened to its trunk, her mare may feed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Spanish cavalier the stream beside\nArrived, who had pursued her traces there:\nAngelica no sooner him espied,\nThan she evanished clean, and spurred her mare:\nThe helm this while had dropt, but lay too wide\nTo be recovered of the flying fair.\nAs soon as sweet Angelica he saw,\nTowards her full of rapture sprang Ferrau."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She disappeared, I say, as forms avaunt\nAt sleep's departure: toiling long and sore\nHe seeks the damsel there, 'twixt plant and plant,\nNow can his wretched eyes behold her more.\nBlaspheming his Mahound and Termagant,\nAnd cursing every master of his lore,\nFerrau returned towards the sylvan fount,\nWhere lay on earth the helmet of the count."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This he soon recognised, for here he read\nLetters upon the margin, written fair,\nWhich how Orlando won the helmet said;\nAnd from what champion took, and when and where.\nWith it the paynim armed his neck and head,\nWho would not for his grief the prize forbear;\nHis grief for loss of her, conveyed from sight,\nAs disappear the phantoms of the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When in this goodly casque he was arrayed,\nHe deemed nought wanting to his full content,\nBut the discovery of the royal maid,\nWho like a flash of lightning came and went:\nFor her he searches every greenwood shade,\nAnd when all hope of finding her is spent,\nHe for the vain pursuit no longer tarries,\nBut to the Spanish camp returns near Paris;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Tempering the grief which glowed within his breast,\nFor such sore disappointment, with the thought\nThat he was with Orlando's morion blest,\nAs sworn.  By good Anglante's count, when taught\nThat the false Saracen the prize possest,\nLong time the Spanish knight was vainly sought;\nNor Roland took the helmet from his head,\nTill he between two bridges laid him dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Angelica thus, viewless and alone,\nSpeeds on her journey, but with troubled front;\nGrieved for the helmet, in her haste foregone\nOn her departure from the grassy fount.\n\"Choosing to do what I should least have done,\"\n(She said \"I took his helmet from the count. ) \n\nThis for his first desert I well bestow;\nA worthy recompense for all I owe!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With good intentions, as God knows, I wrought;\nThough these an ill and different end produce;\nI took the helmet only with the thought\nTo bring that deadly battle to a truce;\nAnd not that this foul Spaniard what he sought\nShould gain, or I to his intent conduce.\"\nSo she, lamenting, took herself to task\nFor having robbed Orlando of his casque."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By what appeared to her the meetest way,\nMoody and ill-content she eastward pressed;\nOfttimes concealed, sometimes in face of day,\nAs seemed most opportune and pleased her best.\nAfter much country seen, a forest gray\nShe reached, where, sorely wounded in mid breast,\nBetween two dead companions on the ground,\nThe royal maid a bleeding stripling found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But of Angelica I now no more\nShall speak, who first have many things to say;\nNor shall to the Circassian or the Moor\nGive for long space a rhyme; thence called away\nBy good Anglante's prince, who wills, before\nI of those others tell, I should display\nThe labours and the troubles he sustained,\nPursuing the great good he never gained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the first city, whither he was brought\n(Because to go concealed he had good care),\nHe a new helmet donned; but took no thought\nWhat was the head-piece he designed to bear.\nSo safe is he in fairy spell, it nought\nImports, if hard or soft its temper were.\nOrlando, covered thus, pursues the quest,\nNor him day, night, or rain, or sun arrest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It was the hour that our of Ocean's bed\nDan Phoebus drew his dripping steeds, and high\nAnd low, still scattering yellow flowers and red,\nAurora stained the heavens with various dye,\nAnd Stars had cast their veils about their head,\nDeparting from their revels in the sky;\nWhen passing on a day fair Paris near,\nOrlando made his mighty worth appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two squadrons he encountered; one an old\nSaracen, Manilardo clept, obeyed;\nKing of Noritia, whilom fierce and bold.\nBut fitter now to counsel than to aid.\nThe next beneath the standard was enrolled\nOr Tremisena's monarch, who was said\n'Mid Africans to be a perfect knight;\nAlzirdo he by those who knew him, hight:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These, with the other Saracen array,\nCantoned throughout the winter months had lain,\nSome near the city, some more far away,\nAll lodged nigh town or hamlet on the plain.\nFor since King Agramant had many a day\nSpent in attacking Paris' walls in vain,\nHe (for no other means remained to try)\nWould lastly with a siege the city ply;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And to do this had people infinite:\nSince he, beside the host that with him came,\nAnd that of Spain which followed to the fight\nThe Spanish King Marsilius' oriflame,\nMany of France did in his pay unite:\nFor all from Paris he to Arles's stream,\nWith part of Gascony, some straggling tower\nExcepted, had reduced beneath his power."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The quivering brook, as warmer breezes blew,\nBeginning now from ice its waves to free,\nAnd the fresh-springing grass and foliage new,\nTo cloathe again the field and greenwood tree,\nAll those King Agramant assembled, who\nHad followed him in his prosperity;\nTo muster in review the armed swarm,\nAnd give to his affairs a better form:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hence did the King of Tremisen' repair,\nWith him who had Noritia in command,\nTo be in time at that full muster, where\nEach squadron, good or bad, was to be scanned\nOrlando thus by chance encountered there,\nAs I have told you, this united hand;\nWho, as his usage was, went seeking her,\nBy whom he had been made Love's prisoner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Alzirdo, as the approaching count he eyes,\nWho in this world for valour has no peer,\nWith such a haughty front, and in such guise,\nThe God of war would less in arms appear,\nThe features known before astounded spies,\nThe fierce, disdainful glance and furious cheer;\nAnd him esteems a knight of prowess high,\nWhich, fondly, he too sore desires to try."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Arrogant, young, and of redoubted force,\nAlzirdo was, and prized for dauntless mind;\nWho bent to joust pricked forth his foaming horse,\nHappier had he remained in line behind!\nMet by Anglante's prince in middle course,\nWho pierced his heart as they encountering joined.\nFrighted, the lightened courser scoured the plain,\nWithout a rider to direct the rein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rises a sudden and a horrid cry,\nAnd air on every side repeats the scream;\nAs his scared band the falling youth descry,\nAnd issuing from his wound so wide a stream:\nDisordered, they the count in fury ply,\nAnd, raised to cut or thrust, their weapons gleam.\nAgainst that flower of knights, their feathered reeds,\nA thicker squadron yet in tempest speeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With sound like that, with which from hill repair,\nOr from the champaign's flat the hurrying swine,\n(If the Wolf, issue from his grot, or Bear,\nDescending to the mountains' lower line,\nSome bristly youngling take away and tear,\nWho with loud squeal and grunt is heard to pine)\nCame driving at the count the barbarous rout;\n\"Upon him!\" and \"upon him!\" still their shout."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At once spears, shafts, and swords, his corslet bore\nBy thousands, and as many pierce his shield.\nThis threatens on one side, and that before,\nAnd those the ponderous mace behind him wield.\nBut he esteems the craven rout no more.\nHe, who did never yet to terror yield,\nThan hungry Wolf in twilight makes account\nTo what the number of the flock may mount."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He held unsheathed that thundering sword in hand,\nWhich with so many foes has heaped the plain,\nThat he who thinks to count the slaughtered band,\nHas undertaken, hard emprize and vain.\nThe road ran red, ensanguined by his brand,\nAnd scarce capacious of the many slain.\nFor neither targe nor head-piece good defends,\nWhere fatal Durindana's blade descends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor safety cotton vest, nor cloths supply,\nIn thousand folds about the temples spread:\nNor only groan and lamentation fly\nThrough air, but shoulder, arm, and severed head,\nDeath roams the field in strange variety\nOf horrid forms, and all inspiring dread;\nAnd says, \"For hundreds of my scythes may stand\nHis Durindana in Orlando's hand.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His ceaseless strokes scarce one the other wait:\nSpeedily all his foemen are in flight.\nAnd when before they came at furious rate,\nThey hoped to swallow quick the single knight.\nNone is there who, in that unhappy straight,\nStops for his comrade, flying from the fight.\nHere one man speeds afoot, one gallops there;\nNone stays to question if the road be fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His mirror Valour bore about, and here\nEach blemish of the soul was seen confest:\nNone looked therein, except an aged peer,\nWhose blood was chilled, but courage unreprest.\nThat death were better deems this cavalier\nThan life in flight, and in disgrace possest:\nI mean Noritia's king, who lays his lance\nIn rest against the paladin of France;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He broke it on the border of the shield\nOf the intrepid count, with stedfast hand,\nWho, by the stroke unshaken, nothing reeled:\nAnd smote the king, in passing, with his brand.\nHim Fortune saved; for as Orlando wheeled\nThe blade, it turned, descending, in his hand.\nAlthough an-edge he guides not still the sword,\nStunned from his saddle reels the paynim lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astounded from his saddle reels the king,\nNor him Orlando turns about to see.\nHe cuts, and cleaves, and slays his following;\nWho all believe him at their backs to be.\nAs through the spacious air, with troubled wing,\nThe starlings from the daring merlin flee;\nSo, of that broken squadron, scattered round,\nSome fly, some dip, and some fall flat to ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He ceased not his ensanguined blade to sway\nTill living wight remained not in his view.\nOrlando doubted to resume his way,\nAlthough the country all about he knew.\nDoes he the right or left-hand road assay,\nHis thoughts still rove from what his steps pursue,\nAnd he to seek the damsel is in dread\nThrough other path than that by which she fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through wood and field his courser did he goad,\nOften inquiring for the royal dame:\nBeside himself, he strayed beside his road,\nAnd to the foot of rising mountain came,\nWhence (it was night-time through a fissure glowed ) \n\nThe distant flicker of a quivering flame.\nOrlando to the rock approached, to spy\nIf there Angelica concealed might lie."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As where low junipers o'er shade her lair,\nOr in the stubble of the open lay,\nWhat time the hunters seek the fearful hare\nThrough traversed woods, and through uncertain way,\n— Lest peradventure she be hidden there,\nThey every bramble, every bush assay;\nEven so, where hope the toiling warrior leads,\nSearching his lady-love, Orlando speeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pricking in haste towards that ray, the count\nArrived where in the wood the light was shed,\nForth-streaming from a crevice in the mount,\nWithin whose womb a spacious grotto spread;\nAnd there, like wall or bank, discerned in front,\nOf thorns and underwood a bristly bed,\nTo hide the grotto's inmates, and defend\nFrom scathe or scorn, which others might intend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By day it had been hidden evermore;\nBut the clear flame betrayed the haunt by night.\nIts use he guessed; but would the place explore,\nAnd better certify himself by sight.\nWhen he without had tied his Brigliador,\nIn silence to the grotto stole the knight;\nThreading the shrubs; nor calling for a guide,\nEntered the passage in the mountain's side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By a long flight of steps was the descent\nInto the cave; where, in the rocky tomb,\nBuried were living folk.  Of wide extent,\nThe grot was chiselled into vaulted room;\nNor was, although its entrance little lent,\nAll daylight wanting to disperse the gloom:\nFor much was furnished by a window dight,\nWithin a natural fissure on the right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the mid cave, beside a fire was seen\nA gentle maid of pleasing look and guise;\nWho seemed to Roland little past fifteen,\nAs far as at first sight he might surmise.\nWith that so fair she made the rugged scene\nSeem in the warrior's sight a paradise.\nAlthough this while her eyes with tears o'erflow,\nClear tokens of a heart oppressed with woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "An aged dame was with her, and the pair\nWrangled, as oftentimes is women's way;\nBut when the County was descending there,\nConcluded the dispute and wordy fray.\nOrlando hastens to salute them fair\n(As still is due to womankind and they ) \n\nTo welcome him rise lightly form their seat,\nAnd with benign return the warrior greet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis true, that when that sudden voice they hear,\nSomedeal confused in look they seem to be,\nAt the same time beholding thus appear\nSo fierce a wight, and harnessed cap-a-pee.\n\"What wight\" (demands Anglantes' cavalier)\nSo barbarous is, and void of courtesy,\nThat he keeps buried, in this rude repair,\nA face so gentle and so passing fair?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With pain the virgin to the count replies,\nAs he inquires of her unhappy doom,\nIn sweet and broken accents, which by sighs\nImpelled, through rows of pearl and coral come:\nAnd between rose and lily, from her eyes\nTears fall so fast, she needs must swallow some.\nIn other canto, sir, be pleased to attend\nThe rest, for here 'tis time my strain should end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 13"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Count Orlando of the damsel bland\nWho loves Zerbino, hears the piteous woes.\nNext puts to death the felons with his hand\nWho pent her there.  Duke Aymon's daughter goes,\nSeeking Rogero, where so large a band\nThe old Atlantes' magic walls enclose.\nHer he impounds, deceived by fictions new.\nAgramant ranks his army for review."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those ancient cavaliers right happy were,\nBorn in an age, when, in the gloomy wood,\nIn valley, and in cave, wherein the bear,\nSerpent, or lion, hid their savage brood,\nThey could find that, which now in palace rare\nIs hardly found by judges proved and good;\nWomen, to wit, who in their freshest days\nOf beauty worthily deserve the praise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above I told you how a gentle maid\nOrlando had discovered under ground,\nAnd asked, by whom she thither was conveyed?\nPursuing now my tale, I tell, how drowned\nIn grief (her speech by many a sob delayed),\nThe damsel fair, in sweet and softest sound,\nSumming them with what brevity she might,\nHer ills recounted to Anglantes' knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Though I am sure,\" she said, \"O cavalier,\nTo suffer punishment for what I say;\nBecause I know, to him who pens me here,\nThis woman quickly will the fact display;\nI would not but thou shouldst the story hear.\n— And let my wretched life the forfeit pay!\nFor what can wait me better than that he,\nMy gaoler, should one day my death decree?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  I am Isabel, who once was styled\nThe daughter of Gallicia's hapless king:\nI said aright who was; but now the child\n(No longer his of care and suffering: ) \n\nThe fault of Love, by whom I was beguiled;\nFor against him alone this charge I bring.\nWho sweetly, at the first, our wish applauds,\nAnd weaves in secret but deceit and frauds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whilom I lived, content in Fortune's smile,\nRich, blameless, fair, and young; to sad reverse\nCondemned, I now am wretched, poor, and vile,\nAnd in worse case, if any yet be worse.\nBut it is fitting, I to thee this while\nFrom their first root my troubles should rehearse.\nAnd it will soothe me, though of thee I borrow\nNo help, that thou compassionate my sorrow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My father in his city of Bayonne,\n(To-day will be twelve months a tourney dight; ) \n\nHence, led by spreading rumour to our town,\nTo joust, from different lands came many a knight;\nMid these (was it his manifest renown,\nOr was it love which so deceived my sight)\nPraise in my eyes alone Zerbino won,\nWho was the mighty king of Scotland's son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When him I after in the field espied,\nPerforming wondrous feats of chivalry,\nI was surprised by Love, ere I descried\nThat freedom in my Love, so rash a guide,\nI lay this unction to my phantasy,\nThat no unseemly place my heart possest,\nFixed on the worthiest in the world and best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In beauty and in valour's boast above\nThose other lords the Scottish prince stood high.\nHe showed me, and, I think, be bore me love,\nAnd left no less an ardent flame than I.\nNor lacked there one who did between us move,\nTo speak our common wishes frequently,\nSo could we still in heart and mind unite,\nAlthough disjoined from one another's sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hence, when concluded was the festal show,\nAnd to his home Zerbino was returned,\nIf thou know'st what is love, thou well may'st know\nHow night and day I for the warrior yearned;\nAnd was assured, no less on him did prey\nThe flame, that in his constant bosom burned.\nHe, save a way to have me with him, nought\nFor solace of his restless passion sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For different faith forbade him (on my side\nI was a saracen, a Christian he)\nTo ask me of my father as a bride,\nBy stealth he purposed to elope with me.\nAmid green fields, our wealthy town beside,\nI had a garden, seated by the sea,\nUpon the pleasant shore; from whence the eye\nMight ocean and the hills about descry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A fitting place to effect what different creed\nAnd law forbade us, he esteemed this site,\nAnd showed the order taken for the deed,\nWhich was to make our future life's delight;\nAnd how, near Santa Martha, for our need,\nA bark was with arm'd men in ambush dight,\nUnder Sir Odoric of Biscay's command;\nA leader he, approved by sea and land!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Unable in his person this to do,\nFor by his father he was forced to wend\nIn succour of the king of France, in lieu\nThis Odoric for the purpose he would send;\nChosen, of all his faithful friends and true,\nAs his most faithful and his truest friend:\nAnd such had been, if benefits could bind\nAnd goodly deeds the friendship of mankind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"At the time fixed to bear me thence away,\nThis chief would anchor on the destined ground.\n— And thus it was arrived the wished for day,\nThen I of them was in my garden found.\nSir Odoric, at night, with fair array\nOf valiant men, by land and sea renowned,\nIn the near river from his bark descends,\nAnd thence in silence to my garden wends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To the pitched bark with me his party sped,\nBefore the city knew what was at hand;\nSome of the house, disarmed and naked, fled,\nAnd some were slain; while of the helpless band,\nWith me, another part was captive led.\nSo was I severed from my native land,\nHoping in brief Zerbino to possess,\nI cannot tell thee with what happiness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Scarcely was Mongia by our galley doubled,\nEre a squall took us on the larboard side,\nWhich round about the clear horizon troubled,\nAnd stirred and tost heaven-high the foaming tide.\nSmote with a north-west wind, next, ocean bubbled,\nWhich on her other beam the vessel plied:\nThis evermore increases, with such force,\nStarboard or larboard, boots not which our course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"It steads not to strike sail, nor lash the mast,\nLowered on the gang-board, nor our castles fell;\nThe bark, in our despite, is hurried fast\nTowards the pointed rocks about Rochelle:\nSave He, above, assist us at the last,\nThe cruel storm will us ashore impel;\nDriven thither by ill wind with mightier speed\nThan ever bow-string gave to whistling reed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Our peril well does the Biscayan note,\nAnd tries what often has an evil end;\nLowers down the galley's skiff, and, when afloat,\nDescends into it, and makes me descend:\nTwo follow, and a troop would throng the boat,\nDid not the first prevent them, and defend\nThe entrance with their naked faulchions; we\nSever the rope forthwith, and put to sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Driven landward, on the shore we safely light\nWho in the skiff embarked; while of our band\nThe rest in the split vessel sink outright;\nOur goods sea-swallowed all.  Upon the strand\nTo Eternal Love, To Goodness Infinite,\nI offer up my thanks, with outstretched hand,\nThat I was doomed not 'mid the watery roar\nTo perish, nor behold Zerbino more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Though I had left on shipboard matters rare,\nAnd precious in their nature, gem and vest,\nSo I might hope Zerbino's lot to share,\nI was content the sea should have the rest.\nNo dwelling on the beach appears, nor there\nIs any pathway seen, by footsteps pressed;\nOnly a hill, whose woody top is beat\nBy ceaseless winds, the waters bathe its feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Here the fell tyrant Love, aye prompt to range,\nAnd faithless to his every promise still,\nWho watches ever how he may derange\nAnd mar our every reasonable will,\nConverts, with woeful and disastrous change,\nMy comfort to despair, my good to ill:\nFor he, in whom Zerbino put his trust,\nCooled in his loyal faith, and burned with lust."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whether he his desire had nursed at sea,\nAnd had not dared exhibit it before;\nOr that it sprung from opportunity,\nSuggested by that solitary shore;\nWithout more pause, in that lone desert, he\nWould sate his greedy passion; but forbore\nTill he of one could rid him, of the twain,\nWho in the boat with us had scaped the main."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A man of Scotland he, Almonio hight,\nWho to Zerbino seemed great faith to bear;\nAnd as a perfect warrior by the knight,\nPraised, when to Odoric given, his trust to share:\nTo him (the Spaniard said it were a slight ) \n\nIf I unto Rochelle afoot should fare;\nAnd prayed, that he before would thither speed,\nAnd forward thence some hackney, for my need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Almonio, who in this suspects no ill,\nForthwith, before our party, wends his way\nTo the town, hidden by the wooded hill,\nAnd which not more than six miles distant lay.\nTo the other finally his wicked will\nSir Odoric took courage to display;\nAs well because he could not rid him thence,\nAs that in him he had great confidence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He that remained with us, of whom I said\nBefore, Corebo was of Bilbao hight,\nWho with him under the same roof was bred\nFrom infancy, and the ungrateful wight\nDeemed that the thought he harboured in his head,\nHe could impart in safety to the knight,\nWho would prefer, neglected of his trust,\nThe pleasure of his friend to what was just."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not without high disdain Corebo heard\n(Who kind and courteous was the Biscayneer, ) \n\nAnd termed him traitor; and by deed and word\nWithstood the purpose of his foul compeer.\nThis mighty wrath in either warrior stirred;\nIn sign whereof their naked brands they rear.\nAt sight of their drawn swords, in panic, I\nTurn shortly through the gloomy wood to fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sir Odoric in war well taught and bred,\nGained in few blows such vantage in the fray,\nHe left Corebo on the field for dead,\nAnd, following in my steps, pursued my way.\nLove lent to him (unless I am misled)\nPinions, that he might overtake his prey;\nAnd many a prayer and glozing flattery taught,\nWherewith I to compliance might be wrought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But all in vain, for I was fixed and bent,\nRather than sate his ill desire, to die.\nWhen menace had by him been vainly spent,\nAnd every prayer and every flattery,\nHe would by open force his will content;\nNor boots it aught that I entreaties try; —\nOf his lord's faith in him the wretch remind,\nAnd how myself I to his hands resigned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When I perceived that fruitless was my prayer,\nAnd that I could not hope for other aid;\nFor he assailed me like a famished bear,\nWith hands and feet I fierce resistance made,\nAs he more brutal waxed, and plucked his hair,\nAnd with my teeth and nails his visage flayed:\nThis while I vent such lamentable cries,\nThe clamour echoes to the starry skies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Were they by chance conducted, or my shriek,\nWhich might have well been heard a league around,\n(Or, was it they were wont the shore to seek,\nWhen any vessel split or ran aground)\nI saw a crowd appear upon the peak,\nWhich, to the sea descending, towards us wound.\nThem the Biscayan say, and at the sight\nAbandoned his design, and turned to flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This rabble, sir, against that treacherous man\nComes to my aid; but in such guise, that I\nThe homely saw, of falling from the pan\nInto the fire beneath, but verify.\n'Tis true so lost I was not, nor that clan\nAccursed with minds of such iniquity,\nThat they to violate my person sought;\nThough nothing good or virtuous on them wrought:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But that they knew, for me preserved a maid,\nAs yet I am, they higher price might crave.\nEight months are past, the ninth arrived, since, stayed\nBy them, alive I languish in this grave.\nAll hope is lost of my Zerbino's aid:\nFor from their speech I gather, as a slave,\nI am bartered to a merchant for his gold;\nBy whom I to the sultan shall be sold.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The gentle damsel so her tale pursues,\nWhile sobs and sighs oft interposing break\nHer soft angelic voice, which might infuse\nCompassion into asp, or venomed snake.\nWhat time she so her piteous grief renews,\nOr haply does her bitter anguish slake,\nSome twenty men the gloomy cavern fill;\nThis armed with hunting-spear, and that with bill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With squinting look and dark, and but one eye,\nThe leader of the troop, of brutish cheer\nWas he, the foremost of the company;\nBy a blow blinded, which from nose to ear\nHad cleft his jaw: when he did so descry\nSeated beside the maid, that cavalier,\nHe turned about and said: \"Lo! in the net\nAnother bird for whom it was not set!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then to the County cried: \"I never knew\nA man more opportune my wants to stead;\nI know not whether any one to you\nPerchance may have announced my pressing need\nOf such fair arms, — or you conjectured true, —\nAs well as of that goodly sable weed.\nYou verily arrived in season are\nMy needs (pursued the losel to repair.\" )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With bitter smile, upstarting on his feet,\nOrlando to the ruffian made reply:\n\"Thou at a price at which no chapman treat,\nUnmarked in merchant's books, these arms shalt buy.\"\nWith that he snatched a brand, which, full of heat\nAnd smoke, was smouldering in the chimney nigh,\nThrew it, and smote by chance the knave half blind,\nWhere with the nose the meeting brows confined."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The brand discharged by him, hit either brow,\nBut most severely on the left did smite;\nFor that ill feature perished by the blow,\nWhich was the thief's sole minister of light.\nNor is the stroke content to blind the foe;\nUnsated, save it register his sprite\nAmong those damned souls, whom Charon keeps,\nWith their companions, plunged in boiling deeps."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A spacious table in mid cavern stood,\nTwo palms in thickness, in its figure square;\nPropt on one huge, ill fashioned food and rude,\nWhich held the thief and all who harboured there.\nEven with such freedom as his dart of wood\nWe mark the nimble Spaniard launch through air,\nThe heavy table Roland seized and threw,\nWhere, crowded close together, stood the crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One had his belly crushed, and one his breast;\nAnother head or arm, or leg and thigh.\nWhence some were slain outright, and maimed the rest,\nWhile he who was least injured sought to fly.\n'Tis so sometimes, with heavy stone oppressed,\nA knot of slimy snakes is seen to lie,\nWith battered heads and loins where, winter done,\nThey lick their scales, rejoicing in the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I could not say what mischiefs these offend;\nOne dies, and one departs without its tail;\nAnother crippled cannot move an-end,\nAnd wriggling wreathes its length without avail:\nWhile this, whom more propitious saints befriend,\nSafe through the grass drags off its slimy trail.\nDire was the stroke; yet should no wonder breed,\nSince good Orlando's arm achieved the deed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those whom the board had little maimed or nought,\n(Turpin says there were seven in craven wise, ) \n\nTheir safety in their feet, yet vainly, sought;\nFor to the cavern's door Orlando hies.\nAnd having them without resistance caught,\nFast with a rope their hands behind them ties;\nA rope, which in the cavern on the ground,\nConvenient for his purpose he had found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He after drags them bound without the cave,\nWhere an old service-tree its shadow throws.\nOrlando lops the branches with his glaive,\nAnd hangs the thieves, a banquet for the crows:\nNor chain and crook for such a deed did crave:\nFor ready hooks the tree itself bestows,\nTo purge the world; where by the chin up-hung,\nThese, on the branches, bold Orlando strung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The ancient woman, the assassin's friend,\nEscapes when she perceives that all are dead,\nAnd, threading that green labyrinth without end,\nLaments, and plucks the hair from off her head,\nBy fear impelled, through paths which sore offend\nHer feet, till she, beside a river's bed,\nEncounters with a warrior: but to say\nWho was the stranger champion I delay;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And turn to her, who to the count applied,\nPraying he would not leave her there alone,\nAnd vowed to follow whither he would guide.\nOrlando her consoles in courteous tone:\nAnd thence, when, with a wreath of roses tied\nAbout her brows, and robed in purple gown,\nOn wonted journey white Aurora starts,\nThe paladin with Isabel departs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Without encountering aught that might appear\nWorthy of note, they wended many a day;\nAnd finally the twain a cavalier,\nAs prisoner led, encountered by the way.\nWho shall be told; but, tale to you as dear\nNow calls me from the beaten path away;\n— Of Aymon's daughter, — whom I left above,\nLanguid and lost in all the pains of love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beauteous lady who desires in vain,\nRogero should not his return delay,\nLies in Marseilles, from whence the paynim train\nShe harasses, nigh each returning day;\n(What time they robbing aye, by hill and plain,\nScower fruitful Languedoc and Provence gay)\nAnd the true duty executes aright\nOf a sage leader and a valiant knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The time long past, she, lying in that place,\nHad hoped that her Rogero would appear,\nShe, not beholding him in all that space,\nOf many evil chances lived in fear.\nOne day, mid others that her woeful case\nThe lady wept alone, to her drew near\nThe dame, who with that healing ring made sound\nThe bosom rankling with Alcina's wound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When her she saw, without her love returned,\n(Such time elapsed, her mission incomplete),\nSore trembling, faint, and pale, her heart so yearned,\nShe scarce had strength to stand upon her feet.\nBut the enchantress kind, when she discerned\nHer fear, advanced with smiles the maid to meet;\nAnd to console her such glad visage wore\nAs messenger who joyful tidings bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Fear not for thy Rogero: he is well\nAnd safe (she cried), and ever worships thee,\nAs wonted; but thy foe, that wizard fell,\nHim yet again deprives of liberty.\nAnd it behoves thee now to climb the sell,\nWould'st thou posses him, and to follow me;\nFor if thou wendest with me, I will lead\nWhither, by thee Rogero shall be freed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And next pursued, relating to her all\nThe frauds and magic of Atlantes hoar,\nThat wearing her fair face, who seemed the thrall\nOf an ill giant, him had through the door\nOf gold, enticed into the enchanted hall,\nAnd after disappeared, the youth before;\nAnd told how dames and cavaliers he cheats\nWho thither make resort, with like deceits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seeing the sage, all think they see a squire,\nCompanion, lady-love, or absent friend;\nWhatever is each several wight's desire:\nSince to our scope our wishes never tend.\nHence searching every where, themselves they tire\nWith labour sore, and frustrate of their end;\nAnd cannot, (so Desire and Hope deceive),\nWithout the missing good, that palace leave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As soon as thou (pursued the dame art near ) \n\nThe place where he has built the magic seat,\nResembling thy Rogero in his cheer\nAnd every look, Atlantes thee shall meet,\nAnd make himself by his ill art appear\nAs suffering from some stronger arm defeat;\nThat thou may'st aid him in the peril feigned,\nAnd thus among those others be detained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To the end thou may'st escape his ambush, where\nSo many and so many, thus betrayed,\nHave fallen; though he Rogero seem, beware\nTo lend him faith, who will demand thine aid:\nNor, when the sage presents himself, forbear\nTo take his worthless life with lifted blade.\nNor think to slay Rogero with the blow,\nBut him who works thee still such cruel woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hard will it seem to slay, full well I know,\nThe wight, in whom Rogero you descry:\nBut, for truth is not in the lying show,\nTrust not to sight where magic blears the eye.\nFix, ere with me you to the forest go,\nTo change not when the traitorous foe is nigh:\nFor never shall with you Rogero wive,\nIf weakly you the wizard leave alive.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The valorous maid with the intent to slay\nThe false enchanter, on her plan decides,\nSnatches her arms, and follows on her way\nMelissa sage, in whom she so confides,\nAnd thus, by fruitful field or forest gray,\nHer by forced journeys that enchantress guides;\nAnd studies to beguile their weary course\nEver, as best she may, with sweet discourse:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And as the fairest topic of all those\nWhich might be grateful to the damsel's ear,\nHer future offspring and Rogero's chose\n(A race of demigods in prince and peer. ) \n\nFor as Melissa all the secrets knows\nOf the eternal gods who rule our sphere,\nThe good enchantress can discover all\nWhich should in many ages hence befall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Oh! my best guide.\" exclaimed the damsel bold\nTo the weird-woman that to aid her came,\n\"As thou hast many years before foretold\nMen who shall glorify my race and name,\nSo now I pray thee, lady, to unfold\nThe praise and virtues of some noble dame,\nIf from my lineage any such shall rise.\"\nTo whom Melissa courteously replies:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Chaste dames of thee descended I survey,\nMothers of those who wear imperial crown,\nAnd mighty kings; the column and the stay\nOf glorious realms and houses of renown.\nAnd as thy sons will shine in arms, so they\nWill no less fame deserve in female gown,\nWith piety and sovereign prudence graced,\nAnd noble hearts, incomparably chaste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if at length, I should relate to thee\nThe praise of all who from thy root ascend,\nToo long my tale would hold, nor do I see\nWhom I could pass, where all to fame pretend.\nBut from a thousand I some two or three\nWill choose, because my tale may have an end.\nWhy was not in the cave thy wish made known,\nWhere I their shadows might as well have shown?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To hear of one of thy famed race prepare,\nWhom liberal studies and good works engage;\nOf whom, I know not well, if she more fair\nMay be entitled, or more chaste and sage;\nThe noble-minded Isabel, who, where\nIt stands on Mincius' bank, in other age\nShall gild the town, of Ocnus' mother hight,\nWith her own glorious rays by day and night;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Where, with her worthiest consort she will strain,\nIn honoured and in splendid rivalry,\nWhich best shall prize the virtues' goodly train,\nAnd widest ope the gates to courtesy.\nIf he by Taro, and in Naples' reign,\n('Tis said), from Gauls delivered Italy,\n'Twill be replied.  Penelope the chaste,\nAs such, was not beneath Ulysses placed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Great things and many thus I sum in few\nOf this brave dame, and others leave behind:\nWhich when I from the vulgar herd withdrew,\nSage Merlin from the hollow stone divined.\nFor I should leave old Typhis out of view,\nIf on such sea I launched before the wind:\nAnd with this finish my prophetic strain,\n— All blessings on her head the skies will rain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With her shall be her sister Beatrice,\nWhose fortunes well shall with her name accord;\nWho, while she lives, not only shall not miss\nWhat good the heavens to those below afford,\nBut make, with her, partaker of her bliss,\nFirst among wealthy dukes, her cherished lord;\nWho shall, when she from hence receives her call,\nInto the lowest depth of misery fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Viscontis' serpents will be held in dread,\nAnd Moro and Sforza, while this dame shall be,\nFrom Hyperborean snows to billows red;\nFrom Ind to hills, which to a double sea\nAfford a passage; and, the lady dead,\nTo the sore mischief of all Italy,\nWill with the Insubri into slavery fall;\nAnd men shall sovereign wisdom fortune call."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Other the same illustrious name will bear,\nAnd who will flourish many years before.\nPannonia's garland one of these shall wear.\nAnother matron on the Ausonian shore,\nWhen she shall be released from earthly care,\nMen will among the blessed saints adore;\nWith incense will approach the dame divine,\nAnd hang with votive images her shrine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The others I shall pass in silence by,\nFor 'twere too much (as said before to sound ) \n\nTheir fame: though each might well deserve, that high\nHeroic trump should in her praise be wound.\nHence the Biancas and Lucretias I\nAnd Constances and more reserve; who found,\nOr else repair, upon Italian land,\nIllustrious houses with supporting hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thy race, which shall all else in this excel,\nIn the rare fortune of its women thrives;\nNor of its daughters' honour more I tell\nThan of the lofty virtue of its wives:\nAnd that thou may'st take note of this as well,\nWhich Merlin said of thy descendents' lives,\n(Haply that I the story might narrate)\nThis I no little covet to relate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of good Richarda first shall be my strain,\nMirror of chastity and fortitude,\nWho, young, remains a widow, in disdain\nOf fortune: (that which oft awaits the good)\nExiles, and cheated of their father's reign,\nShe shall behold the children of her blood\nWandering into the clutches of their foe;\nYet find at last a quittance for her woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor sprung from the ancient root of Aragon,\nI of the gorgeous queen will silent be;\nThan whom more prudent or more chaste is none,\nRenowned in Greek or Latin history;\nNor who so fortunate a course will run,\nAfter that, by divine election, she\nShall with the goodly race of princes swell,\nAlphonso, Hyppolite, and Isabel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The prudent Eleanour is this: a spray\nWhich will be grafted on thy happy tree.\nWhat of the fruitful stepchild shall I say,\nWho in succession next to her I see,\nLucretia Borgia?  who, from day to day,\nShall wax in beauty, virtue, chastity,\nAnd fortune, that like youthful plant will shoot,\nWhich into yielding soil has struck its root."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As tin by silver, brass by gold, as Corn-\nPoppy beside the deeply-crimsoning rose,\nWillow by laurel evergreen, as shorn\nOf light, stained glass by gem that richly glows,\n— So by this dame I honour yet unborn,\nEach hitherto distinguished matron shows;\nFor beauty and for prudence claiming place,\nAnd all praise-worthy excellence and grace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And above every other noble praise,\nWhich shall distinguished her alive or dead,\nIs that by her shall be, through kingly ways,\nHer Hercules and other children led;\nWho thus the seeds of worth in early days,\nTo bloom in council and in camp, will shed.\nFor long wine's savour lingers in the wood\nOf the new vessel, whether bad or good."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor the step-daughter of this noble dame,\nWill I, Renata, hight of France, forget,\nOf Louis born, twelfth monarch of his name,\nAnd Bretagne's pride; all virtues ever yet\nBestowed on woman, since the ruddy flame\nHas warmed, or water had the power to wet,\nOr overhead the circling heavens have rolled,\nUnited in Renata I behold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'Twere long to tell of Alda de Sansogna,\nOr of Celano's countess in this string,\nOr Blanche Maria, stiled of Catalonia;\nOr her, the daughter of Sicilia's king,\nOr of the beauteous Lippa de Bologna,\nOr more, with whose renown the world shall ring,\nTo speak whose separate praise with fitting lore,\nWere to attempt a sea without a shore.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When of the larger portion of her seed\nThe king enchantress at full ease had told,\nAnd oft and oft rehearsed, amid the rede,\nWhat arts Rogero to the wizard's hold\nHad drawn, Melissa halted near the mead\nWhere stood the mansion of Atlantes old,\nNor would approach the magic dome more nigh,\nLest her the false magician should espy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And yet again advised the martial maid,\n(Counsel she had a thousand times bestowed)\nThen left, Nor Bradamant through greenwood shade\nMore than two miles in narrow path had rode,\nBefore, by two fierce giants overlaid,\nShe saw a knight, who like Rogero showed,\nSo closely pressed, and labouring sore for breath,\nThat he appeared well nigh reduced to death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she beheld him in such perilous strait,\nWho of Rogero all the tokens wore,\nShe quickly lost the faith she nourished late,\nQuickly her every fair design forbore.\nShe weens Melissa bears Rogero hate,\nFor some new injury unheard before:\nAnd with unheard of hate and wrong, her foe\nWould by her hand destroy who loves him so."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She cried, \"And is not this Rogero, who\nAye present to my heart, is now to sight?\nIf 'tis not him whom I agnize and view.\nWhom e'er shall I agnize or view aright?\nWhy should I other's judgment deem more true\nThan the belief that's warranted by sight?\nEven without eyes, and by my heart alone,\nIf he were near or distant, would be shown.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While so the damsel thinks, a voice she hears,\nWhich, like Rogero's, seems for aid to cry;\nAt the same time, the worsted knight appears\nTo slack the bridle and the rowels ply:\nWhile at full speed the goaded courser clears\nHis ground, pursued by either enemy.\nNor paused the dame, in following them who sought\nHis life, till to the enchanted palace brought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of which no sooner has she past the door,\nThan she is cheated by the common show.\nEach crooked way or straight her feet explore\nWithin it and without, above, below;\nNor rests she night or day, so strong the lore\nOf the enchanter, who has ordered so,\nShe (though they still encounter and confer)\nKnows not Rogero, nor Rogero her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But leave we Bradamant, nor grieve, O ye\nWho hear, that she is prisoned by the spell,\nSince her in fitting time I shall set free,\nAnd good Rogero, from the dome as well,\nAs taste is quickened by variety,\nSo it appears that, in the things I tell,\nThe wider here and there my story ranges,\nIt will be found less tedious for its changes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meseems that I have many threads to clear\nIn the great web I labour evermore;\nAnd therefore be ye not displeased to hear\nHow, all dislodged, the squadrons of the Moor,\nThreatening the golden lines loud, appear\nIn arms, the royal Agramant before:\nWho bids for a review his army post,\nWilling to know the numbers of his host."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For besides horse and foot, in the campaign\nSore thinned, whose numbers were to be supplied,\nHad many captains, and those good, of Spain,\nOf Libya, and of Aethiopia, died;\nAnd thus the nations, and the various train,\nWandered without a ruler or a guide.\nTo give to each its head and order due,\nThe ample camp is mustered in review."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To fill the squadrons ravaged by the sword,\nIn those fierce battles and those conflicts dread,\nThis to his Spain, to his Africa that lord,\nSent to recruit, where well their files they fed;\nAnd next distributed the paynim horde\nUnder their proper captains, ranged and led.\nI, with your leave, till other strain, delay\nThe order of the muster to display."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 14"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two squadrons lack of those which muster under\nKing Agramant, by single Roland slain;\nHence furious Mandricardo, full of wonder\nAnd envy, seeks the count by hill and plain:\nNext joys himself with Doralice; such plunder,\nAided by heaven, his valiant arms obtain.\nRinaldo comes, with the angel-guide before,\nTo Paris, now assaulted by the Moor."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In many a fierce assault and conflict dread,\n'Twixt Spain and Afric and their Gallic foe,\nCountless had been the slain, whose bodies fed\nThe ravening eagle, wolf, and greedy crow;\nBut though the Franks had worse in warfare sped,\nForced all the champaigne country to forego,\nThis had the paynims purchased at the cost\nOf more good princes and bold barons lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So bloody was the price of victory,\nSmall ground was left them triumphs to prepare;\nAnd if, unconquered Duke Alphonso, we\nMay modern things with ancient deeds compare,\nThe battle, whose illustrious palm may be\nWell worthily assigned to you to wear,\nAt whose remembrance sad Ravenna trembles,\nAnd aye shall weep her loss, this field resembles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the Calesians and the Picards yielding,\nAnd troops of Normandy and Aquitaine,\nYou, with your valiant arms their squadrons shielding,\nStormed the almost victorious flags of Spain;\nAnd those bold youths their trenchant weapons wielding,\nThrough parted squadrons, followed in your train;\nWho on that day deserved you should accord,\nFor honoured gifts, the gilded spur and sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "You, with such glorious hearts, who were not slow\nTo follow, nor far off, the gorgeous oak\nSeized, and shook down the golden acorns so,\nAnd so the red and yellow truncheon broke,\nThat we to you our festive laurels owe,\nAnd the fair lily, rescued from its stroke;\nAnother wreath may round your temples bloom,\nIn that Fabricius you preserved to Rome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rome's mighty column, by your valiant hand\nTaken and kept entire, more praise has shed\nOn you, than if the predatory band\nHad routed by your single valour bled,\nOf all who flocked to fat Ravenna's land,\nOr masterless, without a banner fled,\nOf Arragon, Castile, or of Navarre;\nWhen vain was lance or cannon's thundering car."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This dear-bought victory brought more relief\nThan joy, by its event too much outweighed,\nThe loss of that French captain and our chief,\nWhom dead we on the fatal field surveyed;\nAnd swallowed in one storm, for further grief,\nSo many glorious princes, who, arrayed\nFor safeguard of their own, or neighbouring lands,\nHad poured through, frozen Alps their friendly bands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Our present safety, and life held in fear,\nWe see assured us by this victory,\nThat saved us from the wintry tempest drear,\nWhich would have whelmed us from Jove's angry sky.\nBut ill can we rejoice, while yet the tear\nIs standing in full many a widow's eye,\nWho weeping and attired in sable, vents,\nThroughout all grieving France, her loud laments."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis meet King Lewis should find new supplies\nOf chiefs by whom his troops may be arrayed,\nWho for the lilies' honour shall chastise\nThe hands which so rapaciously have preyed;\nWho brethren, black and white, in shameful wise,\nHave outraged, sister, mother, wife, and maid,\nAnd cast on earth Christ's sacrament divine,\nWith the intent to thieve his silver shrine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hadst thou not made resistance to thy foe,\nBetter, Ravenna, had it been for thee,\nAnd thou been warned by Brescia's fate, than so\nThine should Faenza warn and Rimini.\nO Lewis, bid good old Trivulzio go\nWith thine, and to thy bands example be,\nAnd tell what ills such license still has bred,\nHeaping our ample Italy with dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the illustrious King of France has need\nOf captains to supply his leaders lost,\nSo the two kings who Spain and Afric lead,\nTo give new order to the double host,\nResolve their bands should muster on the mead,\nFrom winter lodgings moved and various post;\nThat they may furnish, as their wants demand,\nA guide and government to every band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marsilius first, and after Agramant,\nPassing it troop by troop their army scan.\nThe Catalonians, who their captain vaunt\nIn Doriphoebus, muster in the van;\nAnd next, without their monarch Fulvirant,\nErst killed by good Rinaldo, comes the clan\nOf bold Navarre; whose guideless band to steer\nThe King of Spain appoints Sir Isolier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With Balugantes Leon's race comes on,\nThe Algarbi governed by Grandonio wheel.\nThe brother of Marsilius, Falsiron,\nBrings up with him the power of Less Castile.\nThey follow Madarasso's gonfalon,\nWho have left Malaga and fair Seville,\n'Twixt fruitful Cordova and Cadiz-bay,\nWhere through green banks the Betis winds its way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stordilane, Tessira, and Baricond,\nAfter each other, next their forces stirred;\nThis in Grenada, that in Lisbon crowned;\nMajorca was obedient to the third.\nLarbino had Lisbon ruled, whose golden round\nWas at his death on Tessira conferred;\nHis kinsman he: Gallicia came in guide\nOr Serpentine, who Mericold supplied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They of Toledo and of Calatrave,\nWho erst with Sinnagon's broad banner spread,\nMarched, and the multitude who drink and lave\nTheir limbs in chrystal Guadiana's bed,\nCame thither, under Matalista brave;\nBeneath Bianzardin, their common head,\nAstorga, Salamanca, Placenza,\nWith Avila, Zamorra, and Palenza."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The household-troops which guard Marsilius' state,\nAnd Saragossa's men, Ferrau commands;\nAnd in this force, well-sheathed in mail and plate,\nBold Malgarine and Balinverno stands;\nMorgant and Malzarise, whom common fate\nHad both condemned to dwell in foreign lands,\nWho, when dethroned, had to Marsilius' court\n(There hospitably harboured made resort. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Follicon, Kind Marsilius' bastard, hies\nWith valiant Doricont; amid this horde,\nBavartes, Analard, and Argalise,\nAnd Archidantes, the Saguntine lord.\nHere, Malagur, in ready cunning wise,\nAnd Ammirant and Langhiran the sword\nUnsheath, and march; of whom I shall endite,\nWhen it is time, their prowess to recite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When so had filed the warlike host of Spain\nIn fair review before King Agramant,\nAppeared King Oran with his martial train,\nWho might almost a giant's stature vaunt;\nNext they who weep their Martasino, slain\nBy the avenging sword of Bradamant,\nKing of the Garamantes, and lament\nThat woman triumphs in their monarch spent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marmonda's men next past the royal Moor,\nWho left Argosto dead on Gascon meads;\nAnd this unguided band, like that before,\nAs well as the fourth troop, a captain needs.\nAlthough King Agramant has little store\nOf chiefs, he feigns a choice, and thinks; next speeds\nBuraldo, Ormida, and Arganio tried,\nWhere needing, the unordered troops to guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He give Arganio charge of Libicane,\nWho wept the sable Dudrinasso dead.\nBrunello guides the men of Tingitane,\nWith cloudy countenance and drooping head;\nWho since he in the wooded mountain-chain\n(Nigh where Atlantes dwelt), to her he led,\nFair Bradamant, had lost the virtuous ring,\nHad lived in the displeasure of his king;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And but that Ferrau's brother Isolier,\nWho fastened to a stem had found him there,\nMade to King Agramant the truth appear,\nHe from the gallows-tree had swung in air:\nAlready fastened was the noose, and near\nThe caitiff's fate, when at the many's prayer\nThe king bade loose him; but reprieving, swore,\nFor his first fault to hang, offending more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus, not without a cause, Brunello pined,\nAnd showed a mournful face, and hung his head.\nNext Farurantes; to whose care consigned,\nMaurina's valiant horse and footmen tread.\nThe new-made king Libanio comes behind,\nBy whom are Constatina's people led:\nSince Agramant the crown and staff of gold,\nOnce Pinador's, had given to him to hold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hesperia's people come with Soridan,\nWith Dorilon the men of Setta ride;\nThe Nasamonians troop with Pulian,\nAnd Agricaltes is Ammonia's guide.\nMalabupherso rules o'er Fezzan's clan,\nAnd Finaduro leads the band supplied\nBy the Canary Islands and Morocco:\nBalastro fills the place of king Tardocco."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next Mulga and Arzilla's legions two.\nThe first beneath their ancient captains wend;\nThe second troop without a leader, who\nAre given to Corineus, the sovereign's friend.\nSo (late Tanphirion's Almonsilla's crew, ) \n\nTo a new monarch in Caichus bend.\nGoetulia is bestowed on Rhimedont,\nAnd Cosca comes in charge of Balinfront."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ruled by Clarindo, Bolga's people go,\nWho fills the valiant Mirabaldo's post:\nHim Baliverso, whom I'd have you know\nFor the worst ribald in that ample host,\nSucceeded next.  I think not, 'mid that show,\nThe bannered camp a firmer troop could boast\nThan that which followed in Sobrino's care;\nNor Saracen than him more wise and ware."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gualciotto dead, Bellamarina's crew,\n(His vassals serve, the sovereign of Algiers, ) \n\nKing Rodomont, of Sarza; that anew\nBrought up a band of foot and cavaliers:\nWhom, when the cloudy sun his rays withdrew\nBeneath the Centaur and the Goat, his spears\nThere to recruit, was sent to the Afric shore\nBy Agramant, returned three days before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There was no Saracen of bolder strain,\nOf all the chiefs who Moorish squadrons led;\nAnd Paris-town (nor is the terror vain)\nMore of the puissant warrior stands in dread\nThan of King Agramant and all the train,\nWhich he, or the renowned Marsilius head;\nAnd amid all that mighty muster, more\nThan others, hatred to our faith he bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Prusion is the Alvaracchia's king: below\nKing Dardinello's flag Zumara's power\nIs ranged.  I wot not, I, if owl or crow,\nOr other bird ill-omened, which from tower\nOr tree croaks future evil, did foreshow\nTo one or to the other, that the hour\nWas fixed in heaven, when on the following day\nEither should perish in this deadly fray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Noritia's men and Tremisene's alone\nWere wanting to complete the paynim host;\nBut in the martial muster sign was none,\nNor tale, nor tiding of the squadrons lost;\nTo wondering Agramant alike unknown,\nWhat kept the slothful warriors from their post,\nWhen of King Tremisene's a squire was brought\nBefore him, who at large the mischief taught;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— Who taught how Manilardo was laid low,\nAlzirdo, and many others, on the plain.\n— \"Sir,\" said the bearer of the news, \"the foe\nWho slew our troop, would all thy camp have slain,\nIf thine assembled host had been more slow\nThan me, who, as it was, escaped with pain.\nThis man slays horse and foot, as in the cote,\nThe wolf makes easy waste of sheep and goat.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where the bold Africans their standards plant,\nA warrior had arrived some days before;\nNor was there in the west, or whole Levant,\nA knight, with heart or prowess gifted more.\nTo him much grace was done by Agramant,\nAs successor of Agrican, who wore\nThe crown of Tartary, a warrior wight;\nThe son the famous Mandricardo hight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Renowned he was for many a glorious quest\nAtchieved, and through the world his fame was blown.\nBut him had glorified above the rest\nWorth in the Syrian fairy's castle shown:\nWhere mail, which cased the Trojan Hector's breast\nA thousand years before, he made his own.\nAnd finished that adventure, strange and fell;\nA story which breeds terror but to tell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the squire told his news amid that show\nOf troops, was present Agrican's bold son,\nWho raised his daring face, resolved to go\nAnd find the warrior who the deed had done;\nBut the design he hatched, forebore to show;\nAs making small account of any one,\nOr fearing lest, should he reveal his thought,\nThe quest by other champion might be sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He of the squire demanded what the vest\nAnd bearings, which the valiant stranger wore;\nWho answered that he went without a crest,\nAnd sable shield and sable surcoat bore.\n— And, sir, 'twas true; for so was Roland drest;\nThe old device renounced he had before:\nFor as he mourned within, so he without,\nThe symbols of his grief would bear about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marsilius had to Mandricardo sped,\nAs gift, a courser of a chestnut stain,\nWhose legs and mane were sable; he was bred\nBetween a Friesland mare and nag of Spain.\nKing Mandricardo, armed from foot to head,\nLeapt on the steed and galloped o'er the plain,\nAnd swore upon the camp to turn his back\nTill he should find the champion clad in black."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king encounters many of the crew\nWhom good Orlando's arm had put to flight;\nAnd some a son, and some a brother rue,\nWho in the rout had perished in their sight;\nAnd in the coward's cheek of pallid hue\nIs yet pourtrayed the sad and craven sprite:\n— Yet, through the fear endured, they far and nigh,\nPallid, and silent, and insensate fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor he long was had rode, ere he descried\nA passing-cruel spectacle and sore;\nBut which the wonderous feats well testified,\nThat were recounted Agramant before.\nNow on this hand, now that, the dead he eyed,\nMeasured their wounds, and turned their bodies o'er;\nMoved by strange envy of the knight whose hand\nHad strown the champaign with the slaughtered band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As wolf or mastiff-dog, who comes the last\nWhere the remains of slaughtered bullock lie,\nAnd finds but horn and bones, where rich repast\nHad fed the ravening hound and vulture night,\nGlares vainly on the scull, unsmacked; so passed\nThe barbarous Tartar king those bodies by;\nAnd grudged, lamenting, like the hungry beast,\nTo have come too late for such a sumptuous feast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That day, and half the next, in search he strayed\nOf him who wore the sable vest and shield.\nWhen lo! he saw a mead, o'ertopt with shade,\nWhere a deep river wound about the field,\nWith narrow space between the turns it made,\nWhere'er from side to side the water wheeled.\nEven such a spot as this with circling waves\nBelow Otricoli the Tyber laves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where this deep stream was fordable, he scanned\nA crowd of cavaliers that armour bore:\nAnd these the paynim questioned who had manned,\nWith such a troop, and to what end, the shore?\nTo him replied the captain of the band,\nMoved by his lordly air, and arms he wore,\nGlittering with gold and jewels, — costly gear,\nWhich showed him an illustrious cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In charge\" (he said \"we of the daughter go ) \n\nOf him our king, who fills Granada's throne,\nEspoused by Rodomont of Sarza, though\nTo fame the tidings are as yet  unknown.\nAnd we, departing when the sun is low,\nAnd the cicala hushed, which now alone\nIs heard, shall bring her where her father keeps\nI' the Spanish camp; meanwhile the lady sleeps.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He who for scorn had daffed the world aside,\nDesigns to see at once, how able were\nThose horsemen to defend the royal bride,\nCommitted by their sovereign to their care.\n\"The maid, by what I hear, is fair\" (he cried).\n\"Fain would I now be certified, how fair:\nThen me to her, or her to me convey,\nFor I must quickly wend another way.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou needs art raving mad,\" replied in few\nThe chief, — nor more.  But with his lance in rest,\nThe Tartar monarch at the speaker flew,\nAnd with the levelled spear transfixed his breast.\nFor the point pierced the yielding corslet through,\nAnd lifeless he, perforce, the champaign prest.\nThe son of Agrican his lance regained,\nWho weaponless without the spear remained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now sword nor club the warlike Tartar bore,\nSince, when the Trojan Hector's plate and chain\nHe gained, because the faulchion lacked, he swore\n(To this obliged), nor swore the king in vain,\nThat save he won the blade Orlando wore,\nHe would no other grasp, — that Durindane.\nHeld in high value by Almontes bold,\nWhich Roland bears, and Hector bore of old."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Great is the Tartar monarch's daring, those\nAt such a disadvantage to assay,\nHe pricks, with levelled lance, among his foes,\nShouting, in fury, — \"Who shall bar my way?\" —\nRound and about him suddenly they close;\nThese draw the faulchion, and those others lay\nThe spear in rest: a multitude he slew,\nBefore his lance was broke upon the crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When this he saw was broke, the truncheon sound\nAnd yet entire, he took, both hands between,\nAnd with so many bodies strewed the ground,\nThat direr havoc never yet was seen:\nAnd as with that jaw bone, by hazard found,\nThe Hebrew Samson slew the Philistine,\nCrushed helm and shield; and often side by side,\nSlain by the truncheon, horse and rider died."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In running to their death the wretches vie,\nNor cease because their comrades perish near:\nYet bitterer in such a mode to die,\nThan death itself, does to the troop appear.\nThey grudge to forfeit precious life, and lie\nCrushed by the fragment of a broken spear;\nAnd think foul scorn beneath the pounding stake\nStrangely to die the death of frog or snake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But after they at their expense had read\nThat it was ill to die in any way,\nAnd near two thirds were now already dead,\nThe rest began to fly in disarray.\nAs if with what was his the vanquished fled,\nThe cruel paynim, cheated of his prey,\nIll bore that any, from the murderous strife\nOf that scared rabble, should escape with life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in the well-dried fen or stubble-land,\nShort time the stalk endures, or stridulous reed,\nAgainst the flames, which careful rustic's hand\nScatters when Boreas blows the fires to feed;\nWhat time they take, and by the north-wind fanned.\nCrackle and snap, and through the furrow speed;\nNo otherwise, with little profit, those\nKing Mandricardo's kindled wrath oppose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When afterwards he marks the entrance free,\nLeft ill-secured, and without sentinel.\nHe, following prints (which had been recently\nMarked on the mead), proceeds, amid the swell\nOf loud laments, Granada's dame to see,\nIf she as beauteous were as what they tell.\nHe wound his way 'mid corpses, where the wave,\nWinding from side to side, a passage gave:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And in the middle of the mead surveyed\nDoralice (such the gentle lady's name),\nWho, at the root of an old ash tree laid,\nBemoaned her: fast her lamentations came.\nAnd tears, like plenteous vein of water, strayed\nInto the beauteous bosom of the dame;\nWho, (so it from her lovely face appeared,)\nFor others mourned, while for herself she feared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her fear increased when she approaching spied\nHim foul with blood, and marked his felon cheer;\nAnd piercing shrieks the very sky divide\nRaised by herself and followers, in their fear.\nFor over and above the troop who guide\nThe fair infanta, squire and cavalier,\nCame ancient men and matrons in her train,\nAnd maids, the fairest of Granada's reign."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When that fair face by him of Tartary\nIs seen, which has no paragon in Spain,\nWhere amid tears (in laughter what were she?)\nIs twisted Love's inextricable chain.\nHe knows not if in heaven or earth he be;\nNor from his victory reaps other gain,\nThan yielding up himself a thrall to her,\n(He knows not why who was his prisoner. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet not so far his courtesy he strained,\nThat he would lose his labour's fruit, although\nThe royal damsel showed, who sorely plained,\nSuch grief as women in despair can show.\nHe, who the hope within him entertained\nTo turn to sovereign joy her present woe,\nWould wholly bear her off; whom having placed\nOn a white jennet, he his way retraced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He dames, maids, ancient men, and others, who\nHad from Granada with the damsel fared,\nKindly dismissed, their journey to pursue;\nSaying, \"My care suffices; I of guard,\nOf guide, of handmaid will the office do,\nTo serve her in her every need prepared.\nFarewell!\" and thus unable to withstand\nThe wrong, with tears and sighs withdrew the band,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Saying, \"How woe-begone will be her sire,\nWhen he the miserable case shall hear!\nWhat grief will be the bridegroom's!  what his ire!\nHow dread the vengeance of that cavalier!\nWhen so the lady's needs such help require.\nAlas! and why is not the champion near,\nTo save the illustrious blood of Stordilane,\nEre the thief bears her farther hence, from stain?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Tartar, joying in the prize possest,\nWhich he by chance and valour won and wore;\nTo find the warrior of the sable vest\nSeemed not to have the haste he had before,\nAnd stopp'd and loitered, where he whilom prest;\nAnd cast about and studied evermore\nTo find some fitting shelter; with desire,\nIn quiet to exhale such amorous fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Doralice he consoled this while, whose eyes\nAnd cheek were wetted with the frequent tear,\nAnd many matters feigned and flattering lies;\n— How, known by fame, he long had held her dear,\nAnd how his country and glad realm, whose size\nShamed others, praised for grandeur far and near,\nHe quitted, not for sight of France or Spain;\nBut to behold that cheek of lovely grain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If a man merits love by loving, I\nYours by my love deserve; if it is won\nBy birth, — who boasts a genealogy\nLike me, the puissant Agricano's son?\nBy riches, — who with me in wealth can vie.\nThat in dominion yield to God alone?\nBy courage, — I to-day (I ween have proved ) \n\nThat I for courage merit to be loved.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These words, and many others on his part,\nLove frames and dictates to the Tartar knight,\nWhich sweetly tend to cheer the afflicted heart\nOf the unhappy maid, disturbed with fright.\nBy these fear first was laid, and next the smart\nSheathed of that woe, which had nigh pierced her sprite;\nAnd with more patience thence the maid began\nTo hear, and her new lover's reasons scan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next much more affable, with courteous lore\nSeasoning her answers to his suit, replies;\nNor looking at the king, sometimes forbore\nTo fix upon his face her pitying eyes.\nThe paynim thence, whom Love had smote before,\nNot hopeful now, but certain, of his prize,\nDeemed that the lovely damsel would not still,\nAs late, be found rebellious to his will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Riding in her glad company a-field,\nWhich so rejoiced his soul, so satisfied;\nAnd being near the time, when to their bield,\nWarned by the chilly night, all creatures hied,\nSeeing the sun now low and half concealed,\nThe warrior 'gan in greater hurry ride;\nUntil he heard reed-pipe and whistle sound,\nAnd next saw farm and cabin smoking round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pastoral lodgings were the dwellings near,\nLess formed for show, than for conveniency;\nAnd the young damsel and the cavalier\nThe herdsman welcomed with such courtesy,\nThat both were pleasured by his kindly cheer.\nFor not alone dwells Hospitality\nIn court and city; but ofttimes we find\nIn loft and cottage men of gentle kind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What afterwards was done at close of day\nBetween the damsel and the Tartar lord,\nI will not take upon myself to say;\nSo leave to each, at pleasure, to award.\nBut as they rose the following morn more gay,\nIt would appear they were of fair accord:\nAnd on the swain who them such honour showed,\nHer thanks at parting Doralice bestowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thence from one place to the other wandering, they\nFind themselves by a river, as they go.\nWhich to the sea in silence winds its way,\nAnd ill could be pronounced to stand or flow,\nSo clear and limpid, that the cheerful day,\nWith nought to intercept it, pierced below.\nUpon its bank, beneath a cooling shade,\nThey found two warriors and a damsel laid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now lofty Fancy, which one course to run\nPermits not, calls me hence in sudden wise;\nAnd thither I return, where paynims stun\nFair France with hosile din and angry cries,\nAbout the tent, wherein Troyano's son\nThey holy empire in his wrath defies,\nAnd boastful Rodomont, with vengeful doom,\nGives Paris to the flames, and levels Rome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Tidings had reached the Moorish sovereign's ear\nThat the English had already passed the sea;\nAnd he bade Garbo's aged king appear,\nMarsilius, and his heads of chivalry:\nWho all advised the monarch to prepare\nFor the assault of Paris.  They may be\nAssured they in the storm will never thrive,\nUnless 'tis made before the aids arrive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Innumerable ladders for the scale\nHad been collected upon every hand,\nAnd plank and beam, and hurdle's twisted mail,\nFor different uses, at the king's command;\nAnd bridge and boat; and, what might more avail\nThan all the rest, a first and second band\nFor the assault (so bids the monarch form; ) \n\nWho will himself go forth with them that storm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The emperor, on the vigil of the day\nOf battle, within Paris, everywhere,\nBy priest and friar of orders black and gray,\nAnd white, bade celebrate mass-rite and prayer;\nAnd those who had confessed, a fair array,\nAnd from the Stygian demons rescued were,\nCommunicated in such fashions, all,\nAs if they were the ensuing day to fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the high church, he, girt with paladine\nAnd preachers of the word, and barons brave,\nWith much devotion at those acts divine\nAssisted, and a fair example gave;\nAnd there with folded hands and face supine,\nExclaimed, \"O Lord! although my sins be grave,\nPermit not, that, in this their utmost need,\nThy people suffer for their king's misdeed!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if that they should suffer is thy will,\nAnd that they should due penance undergo,\nAt least delay thy purpose to fulfil;\nSo that thine enemies deal not the blow.\nFor, when 'tis given him in his wrath to kill\nUs who are deemed thy friends, the paynim foe,\nThat thou art without power to save, will cry,\nBecause thou lett'st thy faithful people die:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, for one faithless found, against thy sway\nA hundred shall throughout the world rebel;\nSo that false Babel's law will have its way,\nAnd thus thy blessed faith put down and quell.\nDefend thy suffering people, who are they\nThat purged thy tomb from heathen hounds and fell.\nAnd many times and oft, by foes offended,\nThy holy church and vicars have defended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That our deserts unfitting are to place\nI' the scale against our mighty debt, I know;\nNor pardon can we hope, if we retrace\nOur sinful lives; but if thou shouldst bestow\nIn aid, the gift of they redeeming grace,\nThe account is quit and balanced, that we owe;\nNor can we of thy succour, Lord, despair,\nWhile we in mind thy saving mercy bear.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So spake the holy emperor aloud,\nIn humbleness of heart and deep contrition;\nAnd added other prayers withal, and vowed\nWhat fitted his great needs and high condition.\nNow was his supplication disallowed;\nFor his good genius hears the king's petition,\nBest of the seraphs he; who spreads his wings,\nAnd to the Saviour's feet this offering brings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Infinite other prayers as well preferred,\nWere, by like couriers, to the Godhead's ear\nSo borne; which when the blessed spirits heard,\nThey all together gazed, with pitying cheer,\nOn their eternal, loving Lord, and, stirred\nWith one desire, besought that he would hear\nThe just petition, to his ears conveyed,\nOf this his Christian people, seeking aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And the ineffable Goodness, who in vain\nWas never sought by faithful heart, an eye,\nFull of compassion, raised; and from the train\nWaved Michael, and to the arch-angel:  \"Hie,\nTo seek the Christian host that crost the main,\nAnd lately furled their sails in Picardy:\nThese so conduct to Paris, that their tramp\nAnd noise be heard not in the hostile camp."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Find Silence first, and bid him, on my part,\nOn this emprize attend thee, at thy side:\nSince he for such a quest, with happiest art\nWill know what is most fitting to provide.\nNext, where she sojourns, instantly impart\nTo Discord my command, that she, supplied\nWith steel and tinder, 'mid the paynims go,\nAnd fire and flame in their encampment blow;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And throughout those among them, who are said\nTo be the mightiest, spread such strife, that they\nTogether may contend, and that some dead\nRemain, some hurt, some taken in the fray;\nAnd some to leave the camp, by wrath, be led;\nSo that they yield their sovereign little stay.\"\nNothing the blessed winged-one replies,\nBut swoops descending from the starry skies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where'er the angel Michael turns his wing,\nThe clouds are scattered and the sky turns bright;\nAbout his person forms a golden ring,\nAs we see summer lightning gleam at night.\nThis while the courier of the heavenly king\nThinks, on his way, where he may best alight,\nWith the intent to find that foe to speech,\nTo whom he first his high behest would teach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the thought the posting angel brooded,\nWhere he, for whom he sought was used to dwell,\nWho after thinking much, at last concluded\nHim he should find in church or convent cell;\nWhere social speech is in such mode excluded,\nThat SILENCE, where the cloistered brethren swell\nTheir anthems, where they sleep, and where they sit\nAt meat; and everywhere in fine is writ."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Weening that he shall find him here, he plies\nWith greater speed his plumes of gilded scale,\nAnd deems as well that Peace, here guested, lies,\nAnd Charity and Quiet, without fail.\nBut finds he is deceived in his surmise,\nAs soon as he has past the cloister's pale.\nHere Silence is not; nor ('tis said is found ) \n\nLonger, except in writing, on this ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor here he Love, nor here he Peace surveys,\nPiety, Quiet, or Humility.\nHere dwelt they once; but 'twas in ancient days;\nChased hence by Avarice, Anger, Gluttony,\nPride, Envy, Sloth, and Cruelty.  In amaze\nThe angel mused upon such novelty:\nHe narrowly the hideous squadron eyed,\nAnd Discord too amid the rest espied;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even her, to whom the eternal Sire as well,\nHaving found Silence, bade him to repair.\nHe had believed he to Avernus' cell,\nWhere she was harboured with the damned, must fare,\nAnd now discerned her in this other hell\n(Who would believe it? amid mass and prayer. ) \n\nStrange Michael thought to see her there enshrined,\nWhom he believed he must go far to find."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her by her party-coloured vest he knew.\nUnequal strips and many formed the gown,\nWhich, opening with her walk, or wind that blew,\nNow showed, now hid her; for they were unsown.\nHer hair appeared to be at strife; in hue\nLike silver and like gold, and black and brown;\nPart in a tress, in riband part comprest,\nSome on her shoulders flowed, some on her breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Examinations, summons, and a store\nOf writs and letters of attorney, she,\nAnd hearings, in her hands and bosom bore,\nAnd consultation, and authority:\nWeapons, from which the substance of the poor\nCan never safe in walled city be.\nBefore, behind her, and about her, wait\nAttorney, notary, and advocate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her Michael calls to him, and give command\nThat she among the strongest paynims go;\nAnd find occasion whence amid the band\nWarfare and memorable scathe may grow.\nHe next from her of Silence makes demand,\nWho of his motions easily might know;\nAs one who from one land to the other hied,\nKindling and scattering fire on either side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I recollect not ever to have viewed\nHim anywhere,\" quoth Discord in reply;\n\"But oft have heard him mentioned, and for shrewd\nGreatly commended by the general cry:\nBut Fraud, who makes one of this multitude,\nAnd who has sometimes kept him company,\nI think, can furnish news of him to thee,\nAnd\" (pointing with her finger \"that is she.\" )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With pleasing mien, grave walk, and decent vest,\nFraud rolled her eye-balls humbly in her head;\nAnd such benign and modest speech possest,\nShe might a Gabriel seem who Ave said.\nFoul was she and deformed, in all the rest;\nBut with a mantle long and widely spread,\nConcealed her hideous parts; and evermore\nBeneath the stole a poisoned dagger wore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of her the good archangel made demand\nWhat way in search of Silence to pursue:\nWho said; \"He with the Virtues once was scanned\nNor dwelt elsewhere; aye guested by the crew\nOf Benedict, or blest Elias' band,\nWhen abbeys and when convent-cells were new;\nAnd whilom in the schools long time did pass,\nWith sage Archytas and Pythagorus."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But those philosophers and saints of yore\nExtinguished, who had been his former stay,\nFrom the good habits he had used before\nHe passed to evil ones; began to stray,\nChanging his life, at night with lovers, bore\nThieves company, and sinned in every way:\nHe oftentimes consorts with Treason; further,\nI even have beheld him leagued with Murther."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With coiners him you oftentimes may see\nHarbour in some obscure and close repair.\nSo oft he changes home and company,\nTo light on him would be a fortune rare:\nYet have I hope to point him out to thee;\nIf to Sleep's house thou wilt at midnight fare,\nHim wilt thou surely find; for to repose\nAt night he ever to that harbour goes.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though Fraud was alway wont to deal in lies,\nSo like the simple truth appears her say,\nThe angel yields the tale belief; and flies\nForth from the monastery without delay,\nTempers his speed, and schemes withal in wise\nTo finish at the appointed time his way,\nThat at the house of Sleep (the mansion blind\nFull well he knew this Silence he may find. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In blest Arabia lies a pleasant vale,\nRemoved from village and from city's reach.\nBy two fair hills o'ershadowed is the dale,\nAnd full of ancient fir and sturdy beech.\nThither the circling sun without avail\nConveys the cheerful daylight: for no breach\nThe rays can make through boughs spread thickly round;\nAnd it is here a cave runs under ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beneath the shadow of this forest deep,\nInto the rock there runs a grotto wide.\nHere widely wandering, ivy-suckers creep,\nAbout the cavern's entrance multiplied.\nHarboured within this grot lies heavy Sleep,\nEase, corpulent and gross, upon this side,\nUpon that, Sloth, on earth has made her seat;\nWho cannot go, and hardly keeps her feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Mindless Oblivion at the gate is found,\nWho lets none enter, and agnizes none;\nNor message hears or bears, and from that ground\nWithout distinction chases every one;\nWhile Silence plays the scout and walks his round,\nEquipt with shoes of felt and mantle brown,\nAnd motions from a distance all who meet\nHim on his circuit, from the dim retreat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The angel him approaches quietly,\nAnd, \" 'Tis God's bidding\" (whispers in his ear)\n\"That thou Rinaldo and his company,\nBrought in his sovereign's aid, to Paris steer:\nBut that thou do the deed so silently,\nThat not a Saracen their cry shall hear;\nSo that their army come upon the foe,\nEre he from Fame of their arrival know.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Silence to him no otherwise replied\nThan signing with his head that he obeyed:\n(And took his post behind the heavenly guide)\nBoth at one flight to Picardy conveyed.\nThe angel moved those bands of valour tried,\nAnd short to them a tedious distance made:\nWhom he to Paris safe transports; while none\nIs conscious that a miracle is done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Silence the advancing troop kept skirting round,\nIn front, and flank, and rear of the array;\nAbove the band he spread a mist profound,\nAnd everywhere beside 'twas lightsome day;\nNor through the impeding fog the shrilling sound\nOf horn was heard, without, or trumpet's bray.\nHe next the hostile paynims went to find,\nAnd with I know not what made deaf and blind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While with such haste his band Rinaldo led,\nThat him an angel well might seem to guide,\nAnd in such silence moved, that nought was said\nOr heard of this upon the paynim side;\nKing Agramant his infantry had spread\nThroughout fair Paris' suburbs, and beside\nThe foss, and underneath the walls; that day\nTo make upon the place his worst assay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He who the Moorish monarch's force would tell,\nWhich Charlemagne this day will have to meet,\nIn wooded Apennine might count as well\nThe trees upon its back, or waves that beat\n(What time the troubled waters highest swell)\nAgainst the Mauritanian Atlas' feet;\nOr watch at midnight with how many eyes\nThe furtive works of lovers Heaven espies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The larum-bells, loud-sounding through the air,\nStricken with frequent blows, the town affray;\nAnd in the crowded temples every where\nMovement of lips and hands upraised to pray\nAre seen: if treasure seemed to God so fair\nAs to our foolish thoughts, upon this day\nThe holy consistory had bid mould\nTheir every statue upon earth in gold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lamenting may be heard the aged just,\nIn that they were reserved for such a woe;\nCalling those happy that in sacred dust\nWere buried many and many a year ago.\nBut the bold youths who, valiant and robust,\nSmall thought upon the approaching ills bestow,\nScorning their elders' counsel, here and there\nHurrying, in fury, to the walls repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here might you paladin and baron ken,\nKing, duke, and marquis, count and chivalry,\nAnd soldier, foreigner or citizen,\nReady for honour and for Christ to die;\nWho, eager to assail the Saracen,\nOn Charlemagne to lower the bridges cry.\nHe witnesses with joy their martial beat,\nBut to permit their sally deems not meet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And them he ordered in convenient post,\nThe advance of the barbarians to impede:\nFor this would ill suffice a numerous host,\nTo that he was content that few should speed.\nSome worked at the machines, some wild-fire tost,\nAll ranged according to the separate need.\nCharles, never in one place, with restless care\nProvides defence and succour every where."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Paris is seated on a spacious plain,\nI' the midst — the heart of France, more justly say.\nA stream flows into it, and forth again;\nBut first, the passing waters, as they stray,\nAn island form, and so secure the main\nAnd better part, dividing on their way.\nThe other two (three separate quarters note).\nWithin the river girds, without the moat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The town, whose walls for miles in circuit run,\nMight well have been attacked from many a side;\nYet, for he would assail it but on one,\nNor willingly his scattered troops divide,\nWestward beyond the stream Troyano's son\nRetired, from thence the assailing bands to guide.\nIn that, he neither city had nor  plain\nBehind, but what was his, as far as Spain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where'er the walls of Paris wound about,\nLarge ammunition had king Charles purveyed;\nStrengthening with dyke each quarter held in doubt;\nAnd had within trench, drain, and casemate made:\nAnd where the river entered and went out,\nHad thickest chains across the channel laid.\nBut most of all, his prudent cares appear\nWhere there is greatest cause for present fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With eyes of Argus, Pepin's valiant son,\nWhere Agramant was bent to storm foresaw,\nAnd every thing forestalled, ere yet begun\nBy the bold followers of Mahound's law.\nWith Isolier, Grandonio, Falsiron,\nSerpentin, Balugantes, and Ferrau,\nAnd what beside he out of Spain had led,\nMarsilius was in arms, their valiant head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With old Sobrino, on the left of Seine,\nPulian and Dardinel d'Almontes meet,\nWith Oran's giant king, to swell the train:\nSix cubits is the prince, from head to feet.\nBut why move I my pen with greater pain\nThan these men move their arms? for in his heat\nKing Rodomont exclaims, blaspheming sore,\nNor can contain his furious spirit more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As swarming to assail the pastoral bowl,\nWith sound of stridulous wing, through summer sky,\nOr relics of a feast, their luscious dole,\nRepair the ready numbers of the fly;\nAs starlings to the vineyard's crimsoning pole\nWith the ripe clusters charged, — heaven's concave high\nFilling, as they advanced, with noise and shout,\nFast hurried to the storm the Moorish rout."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon their walls the Christians in array,\nWith lance, sword, axe, and wild-fire tost,\nThe assaulted city guard without dismay,\nAnd little reck the proud barbarian's boast:\nNor when death snatches this or that away,\nDoes any one in fear refuse his post.\nInto the fosse below the paynim foes\nReturn, amid a storm of strokes and blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor in this was is iron plied alone,\nBut mighty masses and whole bulwarks fall,\nAnd top of tower, huge piece of bastion,\nAnd with much toil disrupted, solid wall;\nWhile streams of boiling water pouring down,\nInsufferably the advancing paynims gall:\nAn ill-resisted rain, which, in despite\nOf helmet, makes its way, and blinds the sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this than iron spear offended more:\nThen how much more the mist of lime-dust fine!\nThen how the emptied vessel, burning sore\nWith nitre, sulphur, pitch, and turpentine!\nNor idle lie the fiery hoops in store,\nWhich, wreathed about with flaming tresses, shine.\nThese at the foemen scaled, upon all hands,\nForm cruel garlands for the paynim bands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile, up to the walls the second crew\nFierce Sarza's king was driven, accompanied\nBy bold Orlando and Buraldo, who\nThe Garamantes and Marmonda guide;\nClarindo and Loridano; nor from view,\nIt seems, will Setta's valiant monarch hide:\nMorocco's king and he of Cosco go\nWith these, that men their martial worth may know."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With crimson Rodomont his banner stains,\nAnd in the vermeil field a lion shows;\nWho, bitted by a maid, to curb and reins\nHis savage mouth disdains not to unclose.\nHimself in the submissive lion feigns\nThe haughty Rodomont, and would suppose\nIn her who curbs him with the bit and string,\nDoralice, daughter to Grenada's king;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whom Mandricardo took, as I before\nRelated, and from whom, and in what wise.\nEven she it was, whom Sarza's monarch more\nLoved than his realm, — beyond his very eyes:\nAnd valour showed for her and courteous lore,\nNot knowing yet she was another's prize.\nIf he had, — then, — then, first, — the story known,\nEven what he did that day, he would have done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At once the foes a thousand ladders rear.\nAgainst the wall by the assailants shored,\nTwo mannered each round; the second, in the rear,\nUrged on by the first; the third the second gored.\nOne mounts the wall through valour, one through fear,\nAnd all attempt perforce the dangerous ford;\nFor cruel Rodomont of Argier slays\nOr smites the wretched laggard who delays."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis thus, 'mid fire and ruin, all assay\nTo mount the wall; but others to assure\nThemselves, some safer passage seek, where they\nWill have least pain and peril to endure.\nRodomont only scorns by any way\nTo wend, except by what is least secure;\nAnd in that desperate case, where others made\nTheir offerings, cursed the god to whom they prayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He in a cuirass, hard and strong, was drest;\nA dragon-skin it was with scaly quilt,\nWhich erst secured the manly back and breast\nOf his bold ancestor, that Babel built;\nWho hoped the rule of heaven from God to wrest,\nAnd him would from his golden dome have split.\nPerfect, and for this end alone, were made\nHelmet and shield as well as trenchant blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor Rodomont to Nimrod yields in might,\nProud and untamed; and who would not forbear\nTo scale the lofty firmament till night,\nCould he in this wide world descry the stair.\nHe stood not, he, to mark the bulwark's plight\nNor if the fosse of certain bottom were.\nHe past, ran, — rather flew across the moat,\nPlunging in filth and water to his throat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dripping and foul with water and with weeds,\n'Mid fire and stone, and arbalests, and bows,\nOn drives the chief; as through the marshy reeds,\nThe wild-swine of our own Mallea goes;\nWho makes large day-light wheresoe'er he speeds,\nParting the sedge with breast and tusk and nose.\nThe paynim, safe in buckler lifted high,\nScorns not the wall alone, but braves the sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont has no sooner gained the shore,\nThan on the wooden bartizan he stands,\nWithin the city walls, a bridge that bore\n(Roomy and large king Charles's Christian bands. ) \n\nHere many a scull is riven, here men take more\nThan monkish tonsure at the warrior's hands:\nHeads fly and arms; and to the ditch a flood\nRuns streaming from the wall of crimson blood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He drops the shield; and with two-handed sway\nWielding his sword, duke Arnulph he offends.\nWho came from whence, into the briny bay,\nThe water of the rapid Rhine descends.\nNo better than the sulphur keeps away\nThe advancing flame, the wretch his life defends.\nHe his last shudder gives, and tumbles dead;\nCleft downwards, a full palm from neck and head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At one back-stroke sir Spineloccio true,\nAnselmo, Prando, and Oldrado fell;\nThe narrow place and thickly-swarming crew\nMake the wide-circling blow so fully tell.\nThe first half Flemings were, the residue\nAre Normans, who the list of slaughter swell.\nOrghetto of Maganza, he from brow\nTo breast divides, and thence to paunch below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Down from the wall Andropono and Moschine\nHe cast into the ditch: a priest the first;\nThe second, but a worshipper of wine,\nDrained, at a draught, whole runlets in his thirst;\nAye wonted simple water to decline,\nLike viper's blood or venom: now immersed\nIn this, he perishes amid that slaughter;\nAnd, what breeds most affliction, dies by water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lewis the Provencal is cleft in two;\nArnold of Thoulouse through the breast before;\nHubert of Tours, sir Dionysius, Hugh,\nAnd Claud, pour forth their ghosts in reeking gore.\nOdo, Ambaldo, Satallon ensue,\nAnd Walter next; of Paris are the four —\nWith others, that by me unmentioned fall,\nWho cannot tell the name and land of all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The crowd, by Rodomont of Sarza led,\nThe ladders lift, and many places scale.\nHere the Parisians make no further head,\nWho find their first defense of small avail\nFull well they know that danger more to dread\nWithin awaits the foemen who assail;\nBecause between the wall and second mound\nA fosse descends, wide, horrid, and profound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Besides, that ours, with those upon the height,\nWar from below, like valiant men and stout,\nNew files succeed to those who fall in fight,\nWhere, on the interior summit, stand the rout,\nWho gall with lances, and a whistling flight\nOf darts, the mighty multitude without;\nMany of whom, I ween, that post would shun,\nIf it were not for royal Ulien's son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But he still heartened some, and chid the rest,\nAnd forced them forward to their sore alarm.\nOne paynim's head he cleft, and other's breast,\nWho turned about to fly; and of the swarm\nSome shoved and pushed and to the encounter prest,\nClose-grappled by the collar, hair, or arm:\nAnd downwards from the wall such numbers threw,\nThe ditch was all to narrow for the crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While so the foes descend, or rather fling\nThemselves into the perilous profound;\nAnd thence by many ladders try to spring\nUpon the summit of the second mound,\nKing Rodomont, as if he had a wing\nUpon his every member, from the ground\nUpraised his weight, and vaulted clean across,\nLoaded with all his arms, the yawning fosse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The moat of thirty feet, not less, he cleared,\nAs dexterously as leaps the greyhound fleet,\nNor at his lighting louder noise was heard\nThan if he had worn felt beneath his feet.\nHe now of this, now that, the mantle sheared;\nAs though of pewter, not of iron beat,\nOr rather of soft rind their arms had been:\nSo matchless was his force and sword so keen!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while, not idle, those of ours had laid\nSnares in the inner moat, a well-charged mine:\nWhere broom and thick fascines, all over paid\nWith swarthy pitch, in plenty intertwine.\nThough they from bank to bank that hollow line,\nFilling the bottom well-nigh to the brink;\nAnd countless vessels the defenders sink."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Charged with salt-petre, oil, or sulphur pale,\nOne and the other, or with such like gear;\nWhile ours, intent the paynims that assail\nThe town, should pay their daring folly dear,\n(Who from the ditch on different parts would scale\nThe inner bulwark's platform when they hear ) \n\nThe appointed signal which their comrades raise,\nSet, at fit points, the wildfire in a blaze."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For that the moat was full from side to side,\nThe scattered flames united into one,\nAnd mounted to such height, they well-nigh dried\nThe watery bosom of the moon; a dun\nAnd dismal cloud above extending wide,\nDimmed every glimpse of light, and hid the sun:\nA fearful crash, with a continued sound,\nLike a long peal of thunder, shook the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A horrid concert, a rude harmony\nOf deep lament, and yell and shriek, which came\nFrom those poor wretches in extremity,\nPerishing through their furious leader's blame,\nWas heard, as in strange concord, to agree\nWith the fierce crackling of the murderous flame.\nNo more of this, no more! — Here, sir, I close\nMy canto, hoarse, and needing short repose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 15"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Round about Paris every where are spread\nThe assailing hosts of Africa and Spain.\nAstolpho home by Logistilla sped,\nBinds first Caligorantes with his chain;\nNext from Orrilo's trunk divides the head;\nWith whom Sir Aquilant had warred in vain,\nAnd Gryphon bold: next Sansonet discerns,\nIll tidings of his lady Gryphon learns."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though Conquest fruit of skill or fortune be,\nTo conquer always is a glorious thing.\n'Tis true, indeed, a bloody victory\nIs to a chief less honour wont to bring;\nAnd that fair field is famed eternally,\nAnd he who wins it merits worshipping,\nWho, saving from all harm his own, without\nLoss to his followers, puts the foe to rout."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "You, sir, earned worthy praise, when you o'erbore\nThe lion of such might by sea, and so\nDid by him, where he guarded either shore\nFrom Francolino to the mouth of Po,\nThat I, though yet again I heard him roar,\nIf you were present, should my fear forego.\nHow fields are fitly won was then made plain;\nFor we were rescued, and your foemen slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was the Paynim little skilled to do,\nWho was but daring to his proper loss;\nAnd to the moat impelled his meiny, who\nOne and all perished in the burning fosse.\nThe mighty gulf had not contained the crew,\nBut that, devouring those who sought to cross,\nThem into dust the flame reduced, that room\nMight be for all within the crowded tomb."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of twenty thousand warriors thither sent,\nDied nineteen thousand in the fiery pit;\nWho to the fosse descended, ill content;\nBut so their leader willed, of little wit:\nExtinguished amid such a blaze, and spent\nBy the devouring flame the Christians lit.\nAnd Rodomont, occasion of their woes,\nExempted from the mighty mischief goes:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For he to the inner bank, by foes possest,\nAcross the ditch had vaulted wonderously:\nHad he within it been, among the rest,\nIt sure had been his last assault.  His eye\nHe turns, and when the wild-fires, which infest\nThe infernal vale, he sees ascend so high,\nAnd hears his people's moan and dying screams,\nWith imprecations dread he Heaven blasphemes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while a band King Agramant had brought,\nTo make a fierce assault upon a gate:\nFor while the cruel battle here was fought,\nWherein so many sufferers met their fate,\nThis haply unprovided had he thought\nWith fitting guard.  Upon the monarch wait\nKing Bambirago, 'mid his knights of price,\nAnd Baliverso, sink of every vice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And Corineus of Mulga, Prusion,\nThe wealthy monarch of the blessed isles;\nMalabuferzo, he who fills the throne\nOf Fez, where a perpetual summer smiles;\nAnd other noble lords, and many a one\nWell-armed and tried; and others 'mid their files,\nNaked, and base, whose hearts in martial fields\nHad found no shelter from a thousand shields."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But all things counter to the hopes ensue\nOf Agramant upon his side; within,\nIn person, girded by a gallant crew,\nIs Charlemagne, with many a paladin:\nOgier the Duke, King Salamon, the two\nGuidos are seen, and either Angelin;\nBavaria's duke, and Ganelon are here,\nAvino, Avolio, Otho, and Berlinghier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And of inferior count withal, a horde\nOf Lombards, French, and Germans, without end;\nWho, every one, in presence of his lord,\nTo rank among the valiantest contend,\nThis will I in another place record;\nWho here a mighty duke perforce attend,\nWho signs to me from far, and prays that I\nWill not omit him in my history."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis time that I should measure back my way\nThither, where I Astolpho left of yore;\nWho, in long exile, loathing more to stay,\nBurnt with desire to tread his native shore;\nAs hopes to him had given the sober fay,\nWho quelled Alcina by her better lore,\nShe with all care would send the warrior back\nBy the securest and the freest track."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And thus by her a barque is fitted out;\n— A better galley never ploughed the sea;\nAnd Logistilla wills, for aye in doubt\nOf hinderance from Alcina's treachery,\nThat good Andronica, with squadron stout,\nAnd chaste Sophrosina, with him shall be,\nTill to the Arabian Sea, beneath their care,\nOr to the Persian Gulf he safe repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By Scyth and Indian she prefers the peer\nShould coast, and by the Nabataean reign;\nContent he, after such a round, should veer\nFor Persian gulf, or Erithraean main,\nRather than for that Boreal palace steer,\nWhere angry winds aye vex the rude domain:\nSo ill, at seasons, favoured by the sun,\nThat there, for months together, light is none."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next, when she all in readiness espied,\nHer license to depart the prudent fay\nAccorded to the duke, first fortified\nWith counsel as to things too long to say;\nAnd that he might no more by charms be stayed\nIn place from whence he could not wend his way,\nHim with a useful book and fair purveyed,\nAnd ever for her love to wear it prayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How man should guard himself from magic cheats\nThe book instructed, which the fay bestowed;\nAt the end or the beginning, where it treats\nOf such, an index and appendix showed.\nAnother gift, which in its goodly feats\nAll other gifts excelled, to her he owed;\nThis was a horn, which made whatever wight\nShould hear its clang betake himself to flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say, the horn is of such horrid sound,\nThat, wheresoe'er 'tis heard, all fly for fear;\nNor in the world is one of heart so sound\nThat would not fly, should he the bugle hear.\nWind, thunder, and the shock which rives the ground,\nCome not, in aught, the hideous clangour near.\nWith thanks did the good Englishman receive\nThe gift, and of the fairy took his leave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Quitting the port and smoother waves, they stand\nTo sea, with favouring wind which blows astern;\nAnd (coasting round the rich and populous land ) \n\nOf odoriferous Ind the vessels turn,\nOpening a thousand isles on either hand,\nScattered about that sea, till they discern\nThe land of Thomas; here the pilot veers\nHis ready tiller, and more northward steers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho, furrowing that ocean hoar,\nMarks, as he coasts, the wealthy land at ease.\nGanges amid the whitening waters roar,\nNigh skirting now the golden Chersonese;\nTaprobana with Cori next, and sees\nThe frith which chafes against its double shore;\nMakes distant Cochin, and with favouring wind\nIssues beyond the boundaries of Ind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scouring at large broad ocean, with a guide\nSo faithful and secure, the cavalier\nQuestions Andronica, if from that side\nNamed from the westering sun, of this our sphere,\nBark, which with oars or canvas stemmed the tide,\nOn eastern sea was wonted to appear;\n— And could a wight, who loosed from Indian strand,\nReach France or Britain, without touching land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Andronica to England's duke replies:\n\"Know that this earth is girt about with seas,\nAnd all to one another yield supplies,\nWhether the circling waters boil or freeze:\nBut, since the Aethiops' land before us lies,\nExtending southward many long degrees.\nAcross his waters, some one has supposed\nA barrier here to Neptune interposed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hence bark from this Levant of Ind is none\nWhich weighs, to shape her course for Europe's shore;\nNor navigates from Europe any one,\nOur Oriental regions to explore;\nFain to retrace alike the course begun\nBy the mid land, extending wide before:\nWeening (its limits of such length appear)\nThat it must join another hemisphere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But in the course of circling years I view\nFrom farthest lands which catch the western ray,\nNew Argonauts put forth, and Tiphys new\nOpening, till now an undiscovered way.\nOthers I see coast Afric, and pursue\nSo far the negroes' burning shore, that they\nPass the far sign, from whence, on his return,\nThe sun moves hither, leaving Capricorn;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And find the limit of this length of land,\nWhich makes a single sea appear as two;\nWho, scouring in their frigates every strand,\nPass Ind and Arab isles, or Persian through:\nOthers I see who leave, on either hand,\nThe banks, which stout Alcides cleft in two,\nAnd in the manner of the circling sun,\nTo seek new lands and new creations run."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The imperial flags and holy cross I know,\nFixed on the verdant shore; see some upon\nThe shattered barks keep guard, and others go\nA-field, by whom new countries will be won;\nTen chase a thousand of the flying foe,\nRealms beyond Ind subdued by Arragon;\nAnd see all, wheresoe'er the warriors wend,\nTo the fifth Charles' triumphant captains bend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That this way should be hidden was God's will\nOf old, and ere 'twas known long time should run;\nNor will he suffer its discovery, till\nThe sixth and seventh century be done.\nAnd he delays his purpose to fulfil,\nIn that he would subject the world to one,\nThe justest and most fraught with prudent lore\nOr emperors, since Augustus, or before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of Arragon and Austria's blood I see\nOn the left bank of Rhine a monarch bred;\nNo sovereign is so famed in history,\nOf all whose goodly deeds are heard or read.\nAstraea reinthroned by him will be, —\nRather restored to life, long seeming dead;\nAnd Virtues with her into exile sent,\nBy him shall be recalled from banishment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For such desert, Heaven's bounty not alone\nDesigns he should the imperial garland bear, —\nAugustus', Trajan's, Mark's, Severus', crown;\nBut that of every farthest land should wear,\nWhich here and there extends, as yet unknown,\nYielding no passage to the sun and year;\nAnd wills that in his time Christ's scattered sheep\nShould be one flock, beneath one Shepherd's keep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And that this be accomplished with more ease,\nWrit in the skies from all eternity,\nCaptains, invincible by lands and seas,\nShall heavenly Providence to him supply.\nI mark Hernando Cortez bring, 'mid these,\nNew cities under Caesar's dynasty,\nAnd kingdoms in the Orient so remote,\nThat we of these in India have no note."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With Prospero Colonna, puissant peer,\nA marquis of Pescara I behold; —\nA youth of Guasto next, who render dear\nHesperia to the flower-de-luce of gold;\nI see prepared to enter the career\nThis third, who shall the laurel win and hold;\nAs a good horse before the rest will dart,\nAnd first attain the goal, though last to start."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I see such faith, such valour in the deeds\nOf young Alphonso (such his name confest, ) \n\nHe in his unripe age, — nor he exceeds\nHis sixth and twentieth year, — at Caesar's hest,\n(A mighty trust the imperial army leads: ) \n\nSaving which, Caesar not alone the rest\nOf his fair empire saves, but may the world\nReduce, with ensigns by this chief unfurled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As with these captains, where the way by land\nIs free, he spreads the ancient empire's sway,\nSo on the sea, which severs Europe's strand\nFrom Afric, open to the southern day,\nWhen with good Doria linked in friendly band,\nVictorious he shall prove in every fray.\nThis is that Andrew Doria who will sweep\nFrom pirates, on all sides, your midland deep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Pompey, though he chased rovers everywhere,\nWas not his peer; for ill the thievish brood\nVanquished by him, in puissance, could compare\nWith the most mighty realm that ever stood.\nBut Doria singly will of the corsair\nWith his own forces purge the briny flood:\nSo that I see each continent and isle\nQuake at his name, from Calpe to the Nile."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Beneath the faith, beneath the warrantry\nOf the redoubted chief, of whom I say,\nI see Charles enter fertile Italy,\nTo which this captain clears the monarch's way;\nBut on his country, not himself, that fee\nShall he bestow, which is his labour's pay;\nAnd beg her freedom, where himself perchance\nAnother would to sovereign rule advance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The pious love he bears his native land\nHonours him more than any battle's gain\nWhich Julius ever won on Afric's strand,\nOr in thine isle, France, Thessaly, or Spain.\nNor great Octavius does more praise command,\nNor Anthony who jousted for the reign,\nWith equal arms: in that the wrong outweighs\n— Done to their native land — their every praise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Let these, and every other wight who tries\nTo subject a free country, blush for shame,\nNor dare in face of man to lift his eyes,\nWhere he hears Andrew Doria's honoured name!\nTo him I see Charles other meed supplies;\nFor he beside his leaders' common claim,\nBestows upon the chief the sumptuous state,\nWhence Norman bands their power in Puglia date."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not only to this captain courtesy\nShall Charles display, still liberal of his store;\nBut to all those who for the empery\nIn his emprizes have not spared their gore.\nHim to bestow a town, — a realm — I see,\nUpon a faithful friend, rejoicing more,\nAnd on all such as have good service done,\nThan in new kingdom and new empire won.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus of the victories, by land and main,\nWhich, when long course of years shall be complete,\nCharles' worthy captains for their lord will gain,\nAndronica did with Astolpho treat.\nThis while, now loosening, tightening now, the rein\nOn the eastern winds, which blow upon their feet,\nMaking this serve or that, her comrade stands;\nWhile the blasts rise or sink as she commands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while they saw, as for their port they made,\nHow wide the Persian sea extends to sight;\nWhence in few days the squadron was conveyed\nNigh the famed gulf from ancient Magi hight;\nHere they found harbourage; and here were stayed\nTheir wandering barks, which stern to shore were dight.\nSecure from danger from Alcina's wrath,\nThe duke by land continued hence his path."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He pricks through many a field and forest blind,\nBy many a vale and many a mountain gray;\nWhere robbers, now before and now behind,\nOft threat the peer by night or open day;\nLion and dragon oft of poisonous kind,\nAnd other savage monsters cross his way:\nBut he no sooner has his bugle wound,\nThan these are scared and scattered by the sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through Araby the blest he fares, where grow\nThickets of myrrh, and gums odorous ooze,\nWhere the sole phoenix makes her nest, although\nThe world is all before her where to choose;\nAnd to the avenging sea which whelmed the foe\nOf Israel, his way the duke pursues;\nIn which King Pharaoh and his host were lost:\nFrom whence he to the land of heroes crost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho along Trajan's channel goes,\nUpon that horse which has no earthly peer,\nAnd moves so lightly, that the soft sand shows\nNo token of the passing cavalier;\nWho prints not grass, prints not the driven snows,\n— Who dry-shod would the briny billows clear,\nAnd strains so nimbly in the course, he wind\nAnd thunderbolt and arrow leaves behind: —"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Erst Argalia's courser, which was born\nFrom a close union of the wind and flame,\nAnd, nourished not by hay or heartening corn,\nFed on pure air, and Rabican his name.\nHis way the bearer of the magic horn\nFollowing, where Nile received that river, came;\nBut ere he at its outlet could arrive,\nTowards him saw a pinnace swiftly drive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A hermit in the poop the bark did guide\nWith snowy beard descending to mid breast;\nWho when from far the Paladin be spied,\nHim to ascend his ready pinnace prest.\n\"My son, unless thou loathest life, (he cried)\nAnd wouldst that Death to-day thy course arrest,\nContent thee in my bark to cross the water;\nFor yonder path conducts thee straight to slaughter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Within six miles, no further, shalt thou light\n(Pursued the hermit on the bloody seat, ) \n\nWhere dwells a giant, horrible to sight,\nExceeding every stature by eight feet.\nFrom him wayfaring man or errant knight\nWould vainly hope with life to make retreat;\nFor some the felon quarters, some he flays,\nAnd some he swallows quick, and some he slays."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, 'mid the cruel horrors he intends,\nTakes pleasure in a net, by cunning hands\nContrived, which near his mansion he extends;\nSo well concealed beneath the crumbling sands,\nThat whoso uninstructed thither wends,\nNought of the subtle mischief understands;\nAnd so the giant scares him with his cries,\nThat he within the toils in terror flies;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whom with loud laughter, to his seat hard by\nHe drags along, enveloped in his snare;\nAnd knight and damsel views with equal eye,\nAnd for his prisoners' worth has little care.\nThen, having sucked their brains and life-blood dry,\nCasts forth their bones upon the desert lair;\nAnd round about his griesly palace pins,\nFor horrid ornament, their bloody skins."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Take this, — my son, oh!  take this other way,\nWhich thee will to the sea in safety guide.\"\n\"I thank thee, holy father, for thy say,\n(To him the fearless cavalier replied)\nBut cannot peril against honour weigh,\nFar dearer than my life.  To the other side\nMe vainly dost thou move to pass the wave;\nRather for this I seek the giant's cave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I with dishonour life to flight may owe;\nBut worse than death loath thus to save my head.\nThe worst that can befall me if I go,\nIs I my blood shall with the others shed:\nBut if on me such mercy God bestow,\nThat I remain alive, the giant dead,\nSecure for thousands shall I make the ways;\nSo that the greater good the risque o'erpays."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I peril but the single life of one\nAgainst safety of the countless rest.\"\n— \"Go then in peace,\" (the other said). \"my son,\nAnd to thy succour, form among the blest,\nMay God dispatch the Archangel Michael down.\"\n— And him, with that, the simple hermit blest.\nAstolpho pricks along Nile's rosy strand,\nMore in his horn confiding than his brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Between the mighty river and the fen,\nA path upon the sandy shore doth lie,\nBarred by the giant's solitary den\nCut off from converse with humanity.\nAbout it heads and naked limbs of men\nWere fixed, the victims of his cruelty.\nWindow or battlements was not, whence strung\nMight not be seen some wretched prisoner hung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in hill-farm or castle, fenced with moat,\nThe hunter, mindful what his dangers were,\nAye fastens on his door the shaggy coat\nAnd horrid paws and monstrous head of bear;\nSo showed the giant those of greatest note,\nWho, thither brought, had perished in his snare.\nThe bones of countless others wide were spread,\nAnd every ditch with human blood was red."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Caligorant was standing at the gate\n(For so was the  despiteous monster hight);\nWho decked his house with corpses, as for state\nSome theirs with cloth of gold and scarlet dight.\nHe scarce contained himself for joy, so great\nHis pleasure, when the duke appeared in sight;\nFor 'twas two months complete, a third was near,\nSince by that road had past a cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Towards the marish, where green rushes grow,\nHe hastes, intending from that covert blind\nTo double on his unsuspecting foe,\nAnd issue on the cavalier behind:\nFor him to drive into the net, below\nThe sand, the griesly giant had designed;\nAs others trapt he had been wont to see,\nBrought thither by their evil destiny."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When him the wary paladin espied,\nHe stopt his courser, not without great heed,\nLest he into the covert snare might tide,\nForewarned of this by the good hermit's rede.\nHere to his horn for succour he applied,\nNor failed its wonted virtue in this need:\nIt smote the giant's heart with such affright,\nThat he turned back, and homeward fled outright."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho blew, still watchful of surprise,\nWeening to see the engine sprung: fast flew\nThe giant, — as if heart as well as eyes\nThe thief had lost, — nor whitherward he knew:\nSuch is his fear, he kens not as he flies,\nHow is own covert mischief to eschew:\nHe runs into the net, which closing round,\nHampers the wretch, and drags him to the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho, who beholds his bulky prey\nFall bodily, drives thither at full speed,\nSecure himself, and, bent — to make him pay\nThe price of slaughtered thousands — quits his steed.\nYet after, deems a helpless wight to slay\nNo valour were, but rather foul misdeed:\nFor him, arms, neck, and feet, so closely tied,\nHe could not shake himself, the warrior spied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With subtle thread of steel had Vulcan wrought\nThe net of old, and with such cunning pain,\nHe, who to break its weakest mesh had sought,\nWould have bestowed his time and toil in vain.\nIt was with this he Mars and Venus caught,\nWho, hands and feet, were fettered by the chain:\nNor did the jealous husband weave the thread\nFor aught, but to surprise that pair in bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Mercury from the smith conveyed the prize,\nWanting to take young Chloris in the snare;\nSweet Chloris, who behind Aurora flies,\nAt rise of sun, through fields of liquid air,\nAnd from her gathered garment, through the skies,\nScatters the violet, rose, and lily fair.\nHe for this nymph his toils so deftly set,\nOne day, in air he took her with the net."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The nymph (it seems was taken as she flew, ) \n\nWhere the great Aethiop river meets the brine:\nThe net was treasured in Canopus, through\nSuccessive ages, in Anubis' shrine.\nAfter three thousand years, Caligorant drew\nThe sacred relict from the palace divine:\nWhence with the net the impious thief returned,\nWho robbed the temple and the city burned,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He fixed it here, beneath the sandy plain,\nIn mode, that all the travellers whom he chased\nRan into it, and the engine was with pain\nTouched, ere it arms, and feet, and neck embraced.\nFrom this the good Astolpho took a chain,\nAnd with the gyve his hands behind him laced:\nHis arms and breast he swaddled in such guise,\nHe could not loose himself; then let him rise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After, his other knots unfastening,\n(For he was turned more gentle than a maid)\nAstolpho, as a show, the thief would bring,\nBy city, borough-town, and farm conveyed;\nThe net as well; than which no quainter thing\nWas ever by the file and hammer made.\nOn him, like sumpter-nag he laid the load,\nIn triumph led, behind him, on his road."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him helm and shield he gives alike to bear,\nAs to a valet; hence proceeds the peer,\nGladdening the fearful pilgrim every where,\nWho joys to think, henceforth his way is clear.\nSo far an end does bold Astolpho fare,\nHe is to Memphis' tombs already near, —\nMemphis renowned for pyramids; in sight,\nHe marks the populous Cairo opposite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ran all the people in tumultuous tide,\nTo see him drag the unmeasured wight along.\n\"How can it be,\" (each to his fellow cried)\n\"That one so weak could master one so strong?\"\nScarce can Astolpho put the press aside,\nSo close from every part their numbers throng;\nWhile all admire him as a cavalier\nOf mighty worth, and make him goodly cheer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then Cairo was not such, as common cry\nPronounces in our age that costly seat;\n— That eighteen thousand districts ill supply\nLodging to those who in her markets meet;\n— And though the houses are three stories high,\nNumbers are forced to sleep in the open street;\nAnd that the soldan has a palace there\nOf wonderous size, and passing rich and fair;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And therein (Christian renegadoes all)\nKeeps fifteen thousand vassals, for his needs,\nBeneath one roof supplied with bower and stall,\nThemselves, and wives, and families, and steeds.\nThe duke desired to see the river's fall,\nAnd how far Nile into the sea proceeds.\nAt Damietta; where wayfaring wight,\nHe heard, was prisoner made or slain outright."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For at Nile's outlet there, beside his bed,\nA sturdy thief was sheltered in a tower,\nAlike the native's and the stranger's dread,\nWont even to Cairo's gate the road to scower.\nHim no one could resist, and, it was said,\nThat man to slay the felon had no power.\nA hundred thousand wounds he had in strife\nReceived, yet none could ever take his life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To see if he could break the thread which tied\nThe felon's life, upon his way the knight\nSet forward, and to Damietta hied,\nTo find Orrilo, so the thief was hight;\nThence to the river's outlet past, and spied\nThe sturdy castle on the margin dight;\nHarboured in which the enchanted demon lay,\nThe fruit of a hobgoblin and a fay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He here Orrilo and two knights in mail\nFound at fierce strife: the two ill held their own\nAgainst him; so Orrilo did assail\nThe warlike pair, although himself alone;\nAnd how much either might in arms avail,\nFame through the universal world had blown.\nOf Oliviero's seed was either plant;\nGryphon the white, and sable Aquilant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The necromancer had this while (to say\nThe truth with vantage on his side, begun ) \n\nThe fight, who brought a monster to the fray,\nFound only in those parts, and wont to won\nAshore or under water, and to prey,\nFor food, on human bodies; feeding on\nPoor mariners and travelling men, who fare,\nOf the impending danger, unaware."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The monster, slaughtered by the brethren two,\nUpon the sand beside the haven lies;\nAnd hence no wrong they to Orrilo do,\nAssailing him together in this guise.\nHim they dismembered often and not slew:\nNow he, — because dismembered, — ever dies;\nFor he replaces leg or hand like wax,\nWhich the good faulchion from his body hacks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon and Aquilant by turns divide,\nNow to the teeth, now breast, the enchanted wight.\nThe fruitless blow Orrilo does deride,\nWhile the two baffled warriors rage for spite.\nLet him who falling silver has espied\n(Which mercury by alchymists is hight)\nScatter, and reunite each broken member,\nHearing my tale, what he has seen remember."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If the thief's head be severed by the pair,\nHe lights and staggers till he finds it; now\nUptaken by the nose or by the hair,\nAnd fastened to the neck, I know not how.\nThis sometimes Gryphon takes, and whirled through air,\nWhelms in the stream; but bootless is the throw:\nFor like a fish can fierce Orrilo swim;\nAnd safely, with the head, regains the brim."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two ladies, meetly clad in fair array,\nOne damsel was in black and one in white,\nAnd who had been the occasion of that fray,\nStood by to gaze upon the cruel fight:\nEither of these was a benignant fay,\nWhose care had nourished one and the other knight,\nOliver's children; when the babes forlorn\nThey from the claws of two huge birds had torn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since, from Gismonda they had these conveyed,\nBorne to a distance from their native sky.\nBut more to say were needless, since displaid\nTo the whole world has been their history.\nThough the author has the father's name mis-said;\nOne for another (how I know not, I)\nMistaking.  Now this fearful strife the pair\nOf warriors waged at both the ladies' prayer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though it was noon in the happy islands, day\nHad vanished in this clime, displaced by night;\nAnd, underneath the moon's uncertain ray,\nAnd ill-discerned, were all things hid from sight;\nWhen to the fort Orrilo took his way.\nSince both the sable sister and the white\nWere pleased the furious battle to defer,\nTill a new sun should in the horizon stir."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke, who by their ensigns, and yet more\nHad by the sight of many a vigorous blow,\nGryphon and Aquilant long time before\nAgnized, to greet the brethren was not slow:\nAnd they, who in the peer, victorious o'er\nThe giant, whom he led a captive, know\nThe BARON OF THE PARD, (so styled at court)\nHim to salute, with no less love resort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The ladies to repose the warriors led\nTo a fair palace near, their sumptuous seat:\nThence issuing courtly squire and damsel sped,\nThem with lit torches in mid-way to meet.\nTheir goodly steeds they quit, there well bested,\nPut off their arms, and in a garden sweet\nDiscern the ready supper duly laid\nFast by, where a refreshing fountain played."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here they bid bind the giant on the green,\nFast-tethered by a strong and weighty chain\nTo a tough oak, whose ancient trunk they ween\nMay well be proof against a single strain;\nWith that, by ten good serjeants overseen,\nLest he by night get loose, and so the train\nAssault and haply harm; while careless they\nWithout a guard and unsuspecting lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the abundant and most sumptuous board,\nWith costly viands (its least pleasure fraught, ) \n\nThe longest topic for discourse afford\nOrrilo's prowess, and the marvel wrought;\nFor head or arm dissevered by the sword,\nThey (who upon the recent wonder thought)\nMight think a dream to see him re-unite,\nAnd but return more furious to the fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho in his book had found exprest\n(That which prescribed a remedy for spell)\nHow he who of one hair deprived the pest\nOnly could him in battle hope to quell:\nBut this plucked out or sheared, he from his breast\nParforce the felon's spirit would expell.\nSo says the volume; but instructs not where,\n'Mid locks so thickly set, to find the hair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke no less with hope of conquest glows\nThan if the palm he has already won;\nAs he that hopes with small expense of blows\nTo pluck the hair, the wizard-wight undone.\nHence does he to the youthful pair propose\nThe burden of that enterprize upon\nHimself to take: Orrilo will he slay,\nIf the two brethren nought the intent gainsay,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But willingly to him these yield the emprize,\nAssured his toil will be bestowed in vain;\nAnd now a new Aurora climbs the skies,\nAnd from his walls Orrilo on the plain\nDrops, — and the strife begins — Orrilo plies\nThe mace, the duke the sword; he 'mid a rain\nOf strokes would from the body at one blow\nDivorce the spirit of the enchanted foe:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Together with the mace he lops the fist;\nAnd now this arm, now the other falls to ground;\nSometimes he cleaves the corslet's iron twist,\nAnd piecemeal shares and maims the felon round.\nOrrilo re-unites the portions missed,\nFound on the champagne, and again is sound:\nAnd, though into a hundred fragments hewed,\nAstolpho sees him, in a thought, renewed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After a thousand blows, Astolpho sped\nOne stroke, above the shoulders and below\nThe chin, which lopt away both helm and head:\nNor lights the duke less swiftly than his foe.\nThen grasps the hair defiled with gore and red,\nSprings in a moment on his horse, and lo!\nUp-stream with it along Nile's margin hies,\nSo that the thief cannot retake the prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That fool, who had not marked the warrior's feat,\nWas searching in the dust to find his head;\nBut when he heard the charger in retreat,\nWho through the forest with the plunder fled,\nLeapt quickly into his own courser's seat,\nAnd in pursuit of bold Astolpho sped.\nFain had Orrilo shouted \"Hola!  stay!\"\nBut that the duke had borne his mouth away:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet pleased Astolpho had not in like guise\nBorne off his heels, pursues with flowing rein.\nHim Rabican, who marvellously flies,\nDistances by a mighty length of plain.\nThis while the wizard's head Astolpho eyes\nFrom poll to front, above the eyebrows twain,\nSearching, in haste, if he the hair can see\nWhich makes Orrilo's immortality."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Amid innumerable locks, no hair\nStraiter or crisper than the rest was seen.\nHow then should good Astolpho, in his care\nTo slay the thief, so many choose between?\n\"To cut them all (he said it better were.\" ) \n\nAnd since he scissors lacked and razor keen,\nHe wanting these, resorted to his glaive,\nWhich cut so well, it might be said to shave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, holding, by the nose, the severed head,\nClose-sheared it all, behind and eke before.\nHe found, among the rest, the fatal thread.\nThen pale became the visage, changing sore,\nTurned up its eyes, and signals sore and dread\nOf the last agony of nature wore;\nAnd the headless body seated in the sell,\nShuddered its last, and from the courser fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke returns where he the champions two\nAnd dames had left, the trophy in his hand,\nWhich manifests of death the tokens true;\nAnd shows the distant body on the sand.\nI know not if they this with pleasure view,\nThough him they welcome with demeanour bland:\nFor the intercepted victory might pain\nPerchance inflict upon the envying twain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor do I think that either gentle fay\nWith pleasure could that battle's issue see:\nSince those kind dames, because they would delay\nThe doleful fate which shortly was to be\nIn France the brethren's lot, had in that fray\nWith fierce Orrilo matched the warriors free;\nAnd so to occupy the pair had cast,\nTill the sad influence of the skies were past."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When to the castellan was certified\nIn Damietta, that the thief was dead,\nHe loosed a carrier pigeon, having tied\nBeneath her wing a letter by a thread.\nShe went to Cairo; and, to scatter wide\nThe news, another from that town was sped\n(Such is the usage there); so, Egypt through,\nIn a few hours the joyful tidings flew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As he had brought the adventure to an end,\nThe duke now sought the noble youths to stir,\n(Though of themselves that way their wishes tend,\nNor they to whet that purpose need the spur)\nThat they the Church from outrage to defend,\nAnd rights of Charles, the Roman Emperor,\nWould cease to war upon that Eastern strand,\nAnd would seek honour in their native land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon and Aquilant thus bid adieu,\nOne and the other, to his lady fair;\nWho, though it sorely troubled them, ill knew\nHow to resist the wishes of the pair.\nThe duke, together with the warlike two,\nTurns to the right, resolved to worship, where\nGod erst incarnate dwelt, the holy places,\nEre he to cherished France his way retraces."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warriors to the left-hand might incline,\nAs plainer and more full of pleasant cheer,\nWhere still along the sea extends their line;\nBut take the right-hand path, abrupt and drear;\nSince the chief city of all Palestine,\nBy six days' journey, is, through this, more near.\nWater there is along this rugged track,\nAnd grass; all other needful matters lack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So that, before they enter on their road,\nAll that is needful they collect, and lay\nUpon the giant's back the bulky load,\nWho could a tower upon his neck convey.\nThe Holy Land a mountain-summit showed,\nAt finishing their rough and salvage way;\nWhere HEAVENLY LOVE a willing offering stood,\nAnd washed away our errors with his blood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They, at the entrance of the city, view\nA gentle stripling; and in him the three\nAgnize Sir Sansonet of Mecca, who\nWas, in youth's flower, for sovereign chivalry,\nFor sovereign goodness, famed the country through,\nAnd wise beyond his years: from paganry\nConverted by Orlando to the truth,\nWho had, with his own hands, baptized the youth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Designing there a fortilage, in front\nOf Egypt's caliph they the warrior found;\nAnd with a wall two miles in length, the mount\nOf Calvary intending to surround.\nReceived with such a countenance, as is wont\nTo be of inward love the surest ground,\nThem he conducted to his royal home,\nAnd, with all comfort, harboured in the dome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As deputy, the sainted land he swayed,\nConferred on him by Charlemagne, in trust,\nTo him the English duke a present made\nOf that so sturdy and unmeasured beast,\nThat it ten draught horse burdens had conveyed;\nSo monstrous was the giant, and next gave\nThe net, in which he took the unwieldy slave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In quittance, Sansonet, his sword to bear,\nGave a rich girdle to Astolpho bold,\nAnd spurs for either heel, a costly pair,\nWith bucklers and with rowels made of gold;\nWhich ('twas believed the warrior's relicts were, ) \n\nWho freed the damsel from that dragon old;\nSpoils, which Sir Sansonet, with many more,\nFrom Joppa, when he took the city, bore"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Cleansed of their errors in a monastery,\nFrom whence the odour of good works upwent,\nThey of Christ's passion every mystery\nContemplating, through all the churches went;\nWhich now, to our eternal infamy,\nFoul Moor usurp; what time on strife intent,\nAll Europe rings with arms and martial deeds,\nAnd war is everywhere but where it needs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While grace the warlike three devoutly sought,\nIntent on pardon and on pious lore,\nA Grecian pilgrim, known to Gryphon, brought\nTidings, which ill the afflicted champion bore,\nFrom his long-cherished vow and former thought,\nToo foreign, too remote; and these so sore\nInflamed his troubled breast, and bred such care,\nThey wholly turned aside his mind from prayer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For his misfortune, one of lovely feature\nSir Gryphon worshipped, Origilla hight.\nOf fairer visage and of better stature,\nNot one among a thousand meets the sight:\nBut faithless, and of such an evil nature,\nThat thou mightst town and city search outright,\nAnd continent and island, far and near,\nYet, never, as I think, wouldst find her peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In Constantine's imperial city, burned\nWith a fierce fever, he had left the fair;\nAnd hoped to find her, to that place returned,\nLovelier than ever; and enjoy her there.\nBut she to Antioch (as the warrior learned)\nHad with another leman made repair;\nThinking, while such fresh youth was yet her own,\n'Twere not a thing to brook — to sleep alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Gryphon, from the time he heard the news\nHad evermore bemoaned him, day or night:\nWhatever pleasure other wight pursues\nSeems but the more to vex his troubled sprite.\nLet each reflect, who to his mischief woos,\nHow keenly tempered are Love's darts of might,\nAnd, heavier than all ills, the torment fell,\nIn that he was ashamed his grief to tell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This: for that Aquilant had oft before\nReproved him for the passion which he nursed,\nAnd sought to banish her from his heart's core;\n— Her, who of all bad women is the worst,\nHe still had censured, in his wiser lore,\nIf by his brother Aquilant accurst,\nHer Gryphon, in his partial love, excuses,\nFor mostly self-conceit our sense abuses."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It therefore is his purpose, without say\nTo Aquilant, alone to take the quest\nAs far as Antioch, and bear her away,\nWho had borne off his heart-core from his breast:\nTo find him, who had made the dame his prey,\nAnd take such vengeance of him, ere he rest,\nAs shall for aye be told.  My next will tell\nHow he effected this, and what befell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 16"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon finds traitorous Origilla nigh\nDamascus city, with Martano vile.\nSlaughtered the Saracens and Christians lie\nBy thousands and by thousands heaped this while;\nAnd if the Moor outside of Paris die,\nWithin the Sarzan so destroys each pile,\nSuch slaughter deals, that greater ill than this\nNever before has been exprest, I wiss."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Love's penalties are manifold and dread:\nOf which I have endured the greater part,\nAnd, to my cost, in these so well am read,\nThat I can speak of them as 'twere my art.\nHence if I say, or if I ever said,\n(Did speech or living page my thoughts impart)\n\"One ill is grievous and another light.\"\nYield me belief, and deem my judgment right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say, I said, and, while I live, will say,\n\"He, who is fettered by a worthy chain,\nThough his desire his lady should gainsay,\nAnd, every way averse, his suit disdain;\nThough Love deprive him of all praised pay,\nAfter long time and trouble spent in vain,\nHe, if his heart be placed well worthily,\nNeeds not lament though he should waste and die.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let him lament, who plays a slavish part,\nWhom two bright eyes and lovely tresses please:\nBeneath which beauties lurks a wanton heart\nWith little that is pure, and much of lees.\nThe wretch would fly; but bears in him a dart,\nLike wounded stag, whichever way he flees;\nDares not confess, yet cannot quench, his flame,\nAnd of himself and worthless love has shame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The youthful Gryphon finds him in this case,\nWho sees the error which he cannot right;\nHe sees how vilely he his heart does place\nOn faithless Origille, his vain delight:\nYet evil use doth sovereign reason chase,\nAnd free will is subdued by appetite.\nThough a foul mind the lady's actions speak,\nHer, wheresoe'er she is, must Gryphon seek."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Resuming the fair history, I say,\nOut of the city he in secret rode;\nNor to his brother would his plan bewray,\nWho oft on him had vain reproof bestowed:\nBut to the left t'wards Ramah shaped his way,\nBy the most level and most easy road.\nHim six days' journey to Damascus brought,\nWhence, setting out anew, he Antioch sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He nigh Damascus met the lover, who\nPerfidious Origilla's heart possest,\nAnd matched in evil customs were the two,\nLike stalk and flower: for that in either's breast\nWas lodged a fickle heart; the dame untrue,\nAnd he a traitor whom she loved the best.\nWhile both the lovers hid their nature base,\nTo others' cost, beneath a courteous face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As I relate to you, the cavalier\nCame on huge courser, trapped with mickle pride;\nWith faithless Origille, in gorgeous gear,\nWith gold embroidered, and with azure dyed.\nTwo ready knaves, who serve the warrior, rear\nThe knightly helm and buckler at his side;\nAs one who with fair pomp and semblance went\nTowards Damascus, to a tournament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Damascus' king a splendid festival\nHad in these days bid solemnly proclaim;\nAnd with what pomp they could, upon his call,\nThither, in shining arms, the champions came.\nAt Gryphon's sight the harlot's spirits fall,\nWho fears that he will work her scathe and shame;\nAnd knows her lover has not force and breath\nTo save her from Sir Gryphon, threatening death;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But like most cunning and audacious quean,\nAlthough she quakes from head to foot with fear,\nHer voice so strengthens, and so shapes her mien,\nThat in her face no signs of dread appear,\nHaving already made her leman ween\nThe trick devised, she feigns a joyous cheer,\nTowards Sir Gryphon goes, and for long space\nHangs on his neck, fast-locked in her embrace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, after suiting with much suavity\nThe action to the word, sore weeping, cried:\n\"Dear lord, is this the guerdon due to me,\nFor love and worship?  that I should abide\nAlone one live long year, deprived of thee,\n— A second near — and, yet upon thy side\nNo grief? — and had I borne for thee to stay,\nI know not if I should have seen that day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When I from Nicosia thee expected\n(When thou wast journeying to the plenar court)\nTo cheer me, — left with fever sore infected,\nAnd in the dread of death, — I heard report\nThat thou wast gone to Syria; and dejected\nBy that ill tiding, suffered in such sort,\nI, all unable to pursue thy quest,\nHad nigh with this right hand transfixt my breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But fortune, by her double bounty, shows\nShe guards me more than thou: me to convey\nShe sent my brother here, who with me goes,\nMy honour safe in his protecting stay;\nAnd this encounter with thee now bestows,\nWhich I above all other blessings weigh,\nAnd in good time; for hadst thou longer stayed,\nMy lord, I should have died of hope delayed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The wicked woman, full of subtlety\n(Worse than a fox in crafty hardihood)\nPursues, and so well shapes her history,\nShe wholly throws the blame on Gryphon good;\nMakes him believe that other not to be\nHer kin alone, but of her flesh and blood,\nGot by one father; — and so puts upon\nThe knight, that he less credits Luke and John."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor he the fraud of her, more false than fair,\nOnly forbore with just reproach to pay;\nNor only did the threatened stranger spare,\nWho was the lover of that lady gay;\nBut deemed to excuse himself sufficient were,\nTurning some portion of the blame away;\nAnd as the real brother she profest,\nUnceasingly the lady's knight carest;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And to Damascus, with the cavalier\nReturned, who to Sir Gryphon made report,\nThat Syria's wealthy king, with sumptuous cheer,\nWithin that place would hold a splendid court;\nAnd who, baptized or infidel, appear\nThere at his tourney (of whatever sort),\nWithin the city and without, assures\nFrom wrong, for all the time the feast endures."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet I of Origilla's treachery\nShall not so steadfastly pursue the lore,\nWho, famed not for one single perfidy,\nThousands and thousands had betrayed before,\nBut that I will return again to see\nTwo hundred thousand wretched men or more\nBurnt by the raging wild-fire, where they spread,\nAbout the walls of Paris, scathe and dread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I left you where king Agramant prepared\nTo storm a gate, and to the assault was gone:\nThis he had hoped to find without a guard;\nAnd work elsewhere to bar the way was none.\nFor there, in person, Charles kept watch and ward\nWith many, practised warriors every one;\nTwo Angelines, two Guidos, Angelier,\nAvino, Avolio, Otho, and Berlinghier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One and the other host its worth, before\nCharles and king Agramant, desire to show,\nWhere praise, where riches are, they think, in store\nFor those that do their duty on the foe.\nBut such were not the atchievements of the Moor\nAs to repair the loss; for, to his woe,\nFull many a Saracen the champaign prest;\nWhose folly was a beacon to the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The frequent darts a storm of hail appear,\nWhich from the city-wall the Christians fling;\nThe deafening clamours put the heavens in fear,\nWhich, from our part, and from that other, ring.\nBut Charles and Agramant must wait; for here\nI of the Mars of Africa will sing,\nKing Rodomont, that fierce and fearful man,\nThat through the middle of the city ran."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I know not, sir, if you the adventure dread\nOf that so daring Moor to mind recall,\nThe leader, who had left his people dead,\nBetween the second work and outer wall;\nUpon those limbs the ravening fire so fed,\nWas never sight more sad! — I told withal,\nHow vaulting o'er that hindrance at a bound,\nHe cleared the moat which girt the city round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he was known the thickening crowd among,\nBy the strange arms he wore and scaly hide,\nThere, where the aged sires and feebler throng.\nListened to each new tale on every side;\nHeaven-high groan, moan, and lamentation rung,\nAnd loud they beat their lifted palms and cried:\nWhile those who had the strength to fly aloof,\nSought safety not from house or temple's roof."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But this the cruel sword concedes to few,\nSo brandished by that Saracen robust;\nAnd here, with half a leg dissevered, flew\nA foot, there head divided from the bust:\nThis cleft across, and that behold him hew,\nFrom head to hips, so strong the blow and just.\nWhile, of the thousands wounded by the Moor,\nIs none that shows an honest scar before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What by weak herd, in fields of Hircany,\nThe tiger does, or Indian Ganges near,\nOr wolf, by lamb or kid, on heights which lie\nOn Typheus' back, the cruel cavalier\nNow executes on those, I will not, I\nCall phalanxes or squadrons, but a mere\nRabble, that I should term a race forlorn,\nWho but deserved to die ere they were born."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of all he cuts, and thrusts, and maims, and bleeds,\nThere is not one who looks him in the face.\nThroughout that street, which in a straight line leads\nUp to St. Michael's bridge, so thronged a space,\nRodomont, terrible and fearful, speeds,\nWhirling his bloody brand, nor grants he grace,\nIn his career, to servant or to lord;\nAnd saint and sinner feel alike the sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Religion cannot for the priest bespeak\nMercy, nor innocence avail the child:\nNor gently beaming eyes, nor vermeil cheek,\nProtect the blooming dame or damsel mild.\nAge smites its breast and flies: while bent to wreak\nVengeance, the Saracen, with gore defiled,\nShows not his valour more than cruel rage,\nHeedless alike of order, sex, and age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor the impious king alone with human blood,\n— Lord of the impious he — his hand distains,\nBut even on walls so sorely vents his mood,\nHe fires fair houses, and polluted fanes.\nThe houses almost all were made of wood,\nThen (as 'tis told and this, by what remains, ) \n\nMay be believed; for yet in Paris we\nSix out of ten no better builded see."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though flames demolish all things far and wide,\nThis ill appears his furious hate to slake:\nWhere'er the paynim has his hands applied,\nHe tumbles down a roof at every shake.\nMy lord, believe, you never yet espied\nBombard in Padua, of so large a make,\nThat it could rend from wall of battered town\nWhat, at a single pull, the king plucked down."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While the accursed man, amid the rout,\nSo warred with fire and sword, if at his post,\nKing Agramant had prest it from without,\nThe ample city had that day been lost.\nBut he was hindered by the warrior stout,\nWho came from England with the advancing host,\nComposed of English and of Scotch allied,\nWith Silence and the Angel for their guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It was God's will, that while through town and tower\nThe furious Rodomont such ruin spread,\nThither arrived Rinaldo, Clermont's flower.\nThree leagues above, he o'er the river's bed\nHad cast a bridge; from whence his English power\nTo the left-hand by crooked ways he led;\nThat, meaning to assail the barbarous foes,\nThe stream no obstacle might interpose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo had, with Edward, sent a force,\nSix thousand strong, of archer infantry,\nAnd sped, with Ariman, two thousand horse\nOf lightest sort; and foot and cavalry\nSought Paris by those roads, which have their course\nDirectly to, and from, the Picard sea;\nThat by St. Martin's and St. Denys' gate,\nThey might convey the aid the burghers wait."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo sent with these the baggage train\nAnd carriages, with which his troops were stored;\nAnd fetching, with the forces that remain,\nA compass, he the upper way explored.\nHe bridge, and boat, and means to pass the Seine,\nHad with him; for it here was ill to ford.\nHe past his army, broke the bridges down,\nAnd rank'd in line the bands of either crown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But having first the peers and captains wheeled\nAbout him in a ring, the cavalier\nMounted the bank which overtopt the field,\nSo much, that all might plainly see and hear;\nAnd cried, \"My lords, you should thanksgiving yield,\nWith lifted hands, to God, who brought you here;\nThrough whom, o'er every nation, you may gain\nEternal glory, bought with little pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Two princes, by your means, will rescued be,\nIf you relieve those city gates from siege;\nHim, your own king, whom you from slavery\nAnd death to save, a subject's vows oblige;\nAnd a famed emperor, of more majesty\nThan ever yet in court was served by liege,\nAnd with them other kings, and dukes, and peers,\nAnd lords of other lands, and cavaliers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So that one city saving, not alone\nWill the Parisians bless your helping hand,\nWho, sadder than for sorrows of their own,\nTimid, afflicted, and disheartened stand;\nAnd their unhappy wives and children moan,\nWhich share in the same peril, and the band\nOr virgins, dedicate to heavenly spouse,\nLest this day frustrate see their holy vows;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"I say, this city saved from deadly wound,\nNot only will Parisians hold you dear;\nBut habitants of all the countries round:\nNor speak I only of the nations near;\nFor city there is none on Christian ground.\nBut what has citizens beleaguered here;\nSo that to you, for vanquishing the foe,\nMore lands than France will obligation owe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If him the ancients with a crown endued,\nWho saved one citizen by worthy deed,\nFor rescuing such a countless multitude,\nWhat recompense shall be your worthy meed?\nBut if, from jealousy or sloth, so good\nAnd holy, enterprise should ill succeed,\nBelieve me, only while these walls endure,\nIs Italy or Almayn's realm secure;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Or any other part, where men adore\nHim, who for us upon the cross was hung;\nNor think that distance saves you from the Moor,\nNor deem your island strong, the waves among.\nFor if, from far Gibraltar's straits of yore,\nAnd old Alcides' pillars, sailed the throng,\nTo bear off plunder from your sea-girt strands,\nWhat will they do when they possess our lands?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, if in this fair enterprise arrayed,\nNo gain, no glory served you as a guide,\nA common debt enjoins you mutual aid,\nMilitant here upon one Church's side.\nMoreover, let not any be afraid,\nOur broken foemen will the assault abide;\nWho seem to me ill-taught in warlike art,\nA feeble rabble without arms or heart.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such reasons, and yet better for, that need\nMight good Rinaldo in his speech infer;\nAnd with quick phrase and voice, to valiant deed\nThe high-minded barons and bold army stir;\nAnd this was but to goad a willing steed\n(As the old proverb says who lacks no spur. ) \n\nHe moved the squadrons, having closed his speech,\nSoftly, beneath their separate banners, each."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, without clamour, without any noise.\nSo moves his triple host, their flags below.\nZerbino, marching by the stream, enjoys\nThe honour first to assail the barbarous foe;\nThe paladin the Irishmen employs\nMore inland, with a wider wheel to go.\nThus England's horse and foot, the two between,\nLed by the Duke of Lancaster, are seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The paladin rode on, along the shore,\nWhen he had put the warriors in their way,\nAnd, passing by their squadrons, pricked before\nValiant Zerbino and his whole array,\nUntil he reached the quarters of the Moor,\nWhere Oran's king, and king Sobrino lay;\nWho, half-a-mile removed from those of Spain,\nPosted upon that side, observed the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With such a faithful escort fortified\nAnd sure, the Christians who had thither wound,\nWith Silence and the Angel for their guide,\nNo longer could stand mute or keep their ground:\nBut hearing now the foe, with shouts defied\nTheir host, and made the shrilling trumpets sound;\nAnd with loud clamours, which Heaven's concave fill,\nSent through the paynim's bones a deadly chill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo spurs before the troops combined\nHis foaming courser, and his weapon rests;\nAnd a full bow-shot leaves the Scots behind:\nSo all delay the impatient peer molests.\nAs oftentimes an eddying gust of winds\nIssues, ere yet the horrid storm infests,\nSo sallying swiftly from the following herd,\nRinaldo forth upon Baiardo spurred."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the aspect of the paladin of France,\nThe wavering Moorish files betray their fear;\nAnd, trembling in their hands, is seen the lance,\nTheir thighs and stirrups quivering, like the spear.\nKing Pulian only marks the knight's advance,\nKnowing Rinaldo not, unchanged in cheer;\nNor thinking such a cruel shock to meet,\nGallops against him on his courser fleet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He stoops upon the weapon which he strains,\nWhole and collected for the martial game:\nThen to his horse abandoning the reins,\nAnd goading with both spurs the courser, came.\nUpon the other side no valour feigns,\nBut shows, by doings, what he is in name;\n— With what rare grace and matchless art he wars,\nThe son of Aymon, rather son of Mars."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Well-matched in skill, they aimed their cruel blows,\nWith lances at each other's heads addrest;\nIll matched, in arms and valour, were the foes,\nFor this past on, and that the champaigne prest.\nMore certain proof of worth, when warriors close,\nThere needs than knightly lance, well placed in rest;\nBut Fortune even more than Valour needs,\nWhich ill, without her saving succour, speeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With the good spear new levelled in his fist,\nAt Oran's king behold Rinaldo dart.\nOf bulk, and bone, and sinew, to resist\nThe monarch was, but ill supplied with heart.\nAnd his might pass for a fair stroke in list,\nThough planted in the buckler's nether part.\nLet those excuse it who refuse to admire,\nSince the good paladin could reach no higher."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor did the buckler so the weapon stay,\nThough made of palm within, and steel without,\nBut that it pierced the paunch, and made a way\nTo let that mean and ill matched spirit out.\nThe courser, who had deemed that all the day\nHe must so huge a burden bear about,\nThanked in his heart the warrior, who well met,\nHad thus preserved him from so sore a sweat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo, having broke his rested spear,\nSo wheels his horse, he seems equipt with wings;\nWho, turning swiftly with the cavalier,\nAmid the closest crowd, impetuous springs.\nComposed of brittle glass the arms appear\nWhere Sir Rinaldo red Fusberta swings.\nNor tempered steel is there, nor corslet thick,\nWhich keeps the sword from biting to the quick."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet few the tempered plates or iron pins\nWith which encounters that descending brand;\nBut targets, some of oak and some of skins,\nAnd quilted vest and turban's twisted band.\nLightly such drapery good Rinaldo thins,\nAnd cleaves, and bores, and shears, on either hand;\nNor better from his sword escapes the swarm,\nThan grass from sweeping scythe, or grain from storm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The foremost squadron had been put to flight,\nWhen thither the vanguard Zerbino led.\nForth pricking from the following crowd, in sight\nAppeared, with levelled lance, their youthful head:\nWith no less fury those who trooped to fight\nBeneath his banner, to the combat sped;\nLike lions, like so many wolves, who leap\nIn fury to the assault of goat or sheep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Both spurred their coursers on, with rested lance,\nWhen either warrior to his foe was near;\nAnd that short interval, that small expanse,\nOf plain, between, was seen to disappear.\nWas never witnessed yet a stranger dance!\nFor the Scots only ply the murderous spear;\nOnly the scattered paynims slaughtered lie,\nAs if conducted thither but to die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It seemed as if each coward paynim grew\nMore cold than ice, each Scot more fierce than flame.\nThe Moors believed that with Rinaldo's thew\nAnd muscle fortified, each Christian came.\nSobrino quickly moved his ordered crew,\nNor stayed till herald should his call proclaim:\nBetter were they than those which went before,\nFor captain, armour, and for martial lore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Less worthless men of Africa were they,\nThough ill had they been deemed of much avail.\nIll harnessed, and worse trained to martial fray,\nForthwith King Dardinel, the foe to assail,\nMoved up his host, himself in helmet gay,\nAnd sheathing all his limbs in plate and mail.\nThe fourth division I believe was best,\nWhich, under Isolier, to battle prest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thraso, this while, the valiant Duke of Mar,\nGlad in the tumult, for the cavaliers\nWho muster in his train, uplifts the bar,\nAnd to the lists of fame his following chears,\nWhen Isolier, with horsemen of Navarre,\nEntered in that fierce fray he sees and hears.\nNext Ariodantes moved his chivalry,\nWho was of late made Duke of Albany."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The deep sonorous trumpet's bellowing,\nAnd sound of drum, and barbarous instrument,\nCombined with twang of bow, and whiz of sling,\nWheel and machine, and stone from engine sent,\nAnd (what more loud than these appeared to ring)\nTumult, and shriek, and groan, and loud lament,\nComposed a direr whole than what offends\nThe neighbouring tribes where deafening Nile descends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The arrows' double shower the ample sky\nWith wide-extended shade is seen to shrowd;\nBreath, smoke of sweat and dust ascend on high,\nAnd seem to stamp in air a murky cloud.\nBy turns each host gives way, and you might spy,\nNow chasing, now in flight, the self-same crowd;\nAnd here some wight, beside his foeman slain,\nOr little distant, prostrate on the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When, harassed with fatigue, a wearied crew\nWithdraw, fresh files their fellows reinforce:\nMen, here and there, the wasted ranks renew;\nHere march supplies of foot, and there of horse:\nHer mantle green for robe of crimson hue\nEarth shifts, ensanguined where the warriors course:\nAnd there were azure flowers and yellow sprung,\nNow slaughtered men lie stretched their steeds among."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino was more wonders seen to do\nThan ever stripling of his age, he strowed\nThe ground with heaps of dead, and overthrew\nThe paynim numbers which about him flowed.\nThe valiant Ariodantes to his new-\nEntrusted squadron mighty prowess showed;\nFilling with dread and wonder, near and far,\nThe squadrons of Castile and of Navarre."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Chelindo and Mosco (bastards were the twain\nOf Calabrun, late king of Arragon),\nAnd one esteemed among the valiant train,\nCalamidor, of Barcellona's town,\nLeaving their standards, in the hope to gain,\nBy young Zerbino's death, a glorious force,\nAnd wounded in his flanks the prince's horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pierced by three lances lay the courser strong,\nBut bold Zerbino quickly rose anew;\nAnd, eager to avenge his charger's wrong,\nThe assailants, where he sees them, will pursue.\nZerbino at Mosco first, that overhung\nHim, in the hope to make him prisoner, flew,\nAnd pierced him in the flank; who from his sell,\nPallid and cold, upon the champaign fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When him so killed, as 'twere by stealthy blow,\nChelindo viewed, to avenge his brother slain,\nHe charged, intent the prince to overthrow;\nBut he seized fast his courser by the rein,\nAnd, thence to rise not, laid the charger low,\nDestined no more to feed on hay or grain;\nFor at one stroke, so matchless was his force,\nZerbino cleft the rider and his horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When that fell blow Calamidor espied,\nHe turned the bridle short to speed away,\nBut him with downright cut Zerbino plied\nBehind, and cried withal, \"Stay, traitor, stay.\"\nNor from its aim the sword-stroke wandered wide,\nThough from the mark it went somedeal astray;\nThe falchion missed the rider as he fled,\nBut reached the horse's croup, and stretched him dead,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He quits the horse, and thence for safety crawls;\nBut he with little boot escapes his foe;\nFor him Duke Thraso's horse o'erturns and mawls,\nOpprest the ponderous courser's weight below.\nWhere the huge crowd upon Zerbino falls,\nAriodantes and Lurcanio go;\nAnd with them many a cavalier and count,\nWho do their best Zerbino to remount."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then Artalico and Margano knew\nThe force of Ariodantes' circling brand:\nWhile Casimir and Enearco rue\nMore deeply yet the puissance of his hand.\nSmote by the knight, escaped the former two;\nThe others were left dead upon the strand.\nLurcanio shows what are his force and breath;\nWho charges, smites, o'erturns, and puts to death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir, think not that more inland on the plain\nThe warfare is less mortal than along\nThe stream, nor that the troops behind remain\nWhich to the duke of Lancaster belong.\nHe valiantly assailed the flags of Spain,\nAnd long in even scale the battle hung.\nFor Horse and Foot, and Captains of those bands,\nOn either side, could deftly ply their hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Forward Sir Oldrad pricks and Fieramont;\nThis Glocester's duke, and York's the other knight;\nWith them conjoined is Richard, Warwick's count,\nAnd the bold duke of Clarence, Henry hight.\nThese Follicon and Matalista front,\nAnd Baricond, with all they lead to fight.\nAlmeria this, and that Granada guides,\nAnd o'er Marjorca Baricond presides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Well matched awhile the Christian and the Moor\nAppeared, without advantage in the fray.\nNot this, now that gave ground, like corn before\nThe light and fickle breeze which blows in May:\nOr as the sea which ripples on the shore,\nStill comes and goes, nor keeps one certain way,\nWhen hollow Fortune thus had sported long,\nShe proved disastrous to the paynim throng."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke of Glocester Matalista bold\nAssailed this while, and hurtled from his sell;\nFieramont Follicon o'erturned and rolled,\nIn the right shoulder smit, on earth as well.\nThe advancing English either paynim hold,\nAnd bear their prisoners off to dungeon cell.\nThis while, Sir Baricond is, in the strife,\nBy Clarence's bold duke deprived of life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hence 'tis among the Moors amazement all,\nWhile hence the Christians take such heart and pride,\nThe bands do nought but quit their ground and fall,\nAnd break their order on the Paynim side,\nWhat time the Christian troops come on, and gall\nTheir flying rants, which nowhere will abide:\nAnd had not one arrived to aid their host.\nThe Paynim camp had on that side been lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Ferrau, who till this time ever nigh\nMarsilius, scarce had quitted him that day,\nWhen half destroyed he marked his chivalry,\nAnd saw that baffled banner born away,\nPricked his good courser forth, in time to spy,\n(Where mid those squadrons hottest waxed the fray)\nWith his head severed in a griesly wound,\nOlympio de la Serra fall to ground:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A stripling he, who such sweet musick vented,\nAccorded to the horned lyre's soft tone;\nThat at the dulcet melody relented\nThe hearer's heart, though harder than a stone.\nHappy!  if, with such excellence contented,\nHe had pursued so fair a fame alone,\nAnd loathed shield, quiver, helmet, sword and lance;\nDestined by these to die a youth in France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When bold French beheld his cruel plight,\nFor whom he love and much esteem profest,\nHe felt more pity at the doleful sight\nThan, 'mid those thousands slain, for all the rest.\nAnd smote the foe who slew him with such might,\nThat he his helm divided from the crest;\nCut front, eyes, visage, and mid bosom through,\nAnd cast him down amid the slaughtered crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor stops he here, nor leaves a corslet whole,\nNor helm unbroken, where his sword is plied,\nOf this the front or cheek, of that the poll,\nThe arm of other foe his strokes divide;\nAnd he, of these divorcing body and soul,\nRestores the wavering battle on that side;\nWhence the disheartened and ignoble throng\nAre scattered wide, and broke, and driven along."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Into the medley pricks King Agramant,\nDesirous there his bloody course to run;\nWith him King Baliverzo, Farurant,\nSoridan, Bambirago, Prusion;\nAnd next so many more of little vaunt,\nWhose blood will form a lake ere day be done,\nThat I could count each leaf with greater ease\nWhen autumn of their mantle strips the trees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant from the wall a numerous band\nOf horse and foot withdraws, and sends the array\nBeneath the king of Fez, with a command\nBehind the Moorish tents to make his way,\nAnd those of Ireland in their march withstand,\nWhom he sees hurrying with what haste they may,\nAnd with wide wheel and spacious compass wind,\nTo fall upon the paynim camp behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king of Fez upon this service prest;\nFor all delay might sore his work impede.\nThis while King Agramant unites the rest,\nAnd parts the troops who to the battle speed.\nHe sought himself the river, where he guessed\nThe Moorish host might most his presence need;\nAnd, from that quarter, had a courier prayed,\nBy King Sobrino sent, the monarch's aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He more than half his camp behind him led,\nIn one deep phalanx.  At the mighty sound\nAlone, the Scotsmen trembled, and in dread\nAbandoned honour, order, and their ground:\nLurcanio, Ariodantes, and their head,\nZerbino, there alone the torrent bound;\nAnd haply he, who was afoot, had died,\nBut that in time his need Rinaldo spied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Elsewhere the paladin was making fly\nA hundred banners: while the cavalier\nSo chased the quailing Saracens, the cry\nOf young Zerbino's peril smote the ear;\nFor, single and afoot, his chivalry\nAmid the Africans had left the peer.\nRinaldo turned about and took his way\nWhere he beheld the Scots in disarray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He plants his courser, where their squadrons yield\nTo the fierce paynims, and exclaims:  \"Where go\nYour bands, and why so basely quit the field,\nYielding so vilely to so vile a foe?\nBehold the promised trophies, spear and shield,\nSpoils which your loaded churches ought to show!\nWhat praise!  what glory!  that alone, and reft\nOf his good horse, your monarch's son is left!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He from a squire receives a lance, and spies\nKing Prusion little distant, sovereign\nOf the Alvaracchiae, and against him hies;\nWhom he unhorses, dead upon the plain.\nSo Agricalt, so Bambirago dies;\nAnd next sore wounded is Sir Soridane;\nWho had been slain as well amid the throng,\nIf good Rinaldo's lance had proved more strong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That weapon broken, he Fusberta rears,\nAnd smites Sir Serpentine, him of the star.\nThough charmed from mischief are the cavalier's\nGood arms, he falls astounded by the jar,\nAnd thus Rinaldo round Zerbino clears\nThe field so widely, where those champions war,\nThat without more dispute he takes a horse\nOf those, who masterless, at random, course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That he in time remounted it was well,\nWho haply would not, if he more delayed:\nFor Agramant at once, and Dardinel,\nSobrino, and Balastro thither made;\nBut he, who had in time regained the sell,\nWheeled, here and there his horse, with brandished blade,\nDispatching into hell the mixt array,\nThat how men live above their ghosts might say."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The good Rinaldo, who to overthrow\nThe strongest of the foeman covets still,\nAt Agramant directs a deadly blow,\n— Who seems too passing-proud, and greater ill\nWorks there, than thousand others of the foe —\nAnd spurs his horse, the Moorish chief to spill.\nHe smote the monarch, broadside charged the steed,\nAnd man and horse reversed upon the mead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What time, without, in such destructive frays\nHate, Rage, and Fury, all offend by turns,\nIn Paris Rodomont the people slays,\nAnd costly house, and holy temple burns:\nWhile Charles elsewhere anther duty stays,\nWho nothing hears of this, nor aught discerns.\nHe, in the town, receives the British band,\nWhich Edward and Sir Ariman command."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him a squire approached, who pale with dread,\nScarce drew his breath, and cried: \"Oh, well away!\nAlas!  alas!\"  (and thus he often said,\nEre he could utter aught beside).  \"To-day,\nTo-day, sire, is the Roman empire sped,\nAnd Christ to the heathen makes his flock a prey.\nA fiend from air to-day has dropt, that none\nHenceforth may in this city make their won."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Satan (in sooth, it can no other be)\nDestroys and ruins the unhappy town.\nTurn, and the curling wreaths of vapour see,\nFrom the red flames which wander up and down;\nList to those groans, and be they warrantry\nOf the sad news thy servant now makes known!\nOne the fair city wastes with sword and fire,\nBefore whose vengeful fury all retire.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even such as he, who hears the tumult wide,\nAnd clatter of church-bells, ere he espy\nThe raging fire, concealed from none beside\nHimself, to him most dangerous, and most nigh;\nSuch was King Charles; who heard, and then descried\nThe new disaster with his very eye.\nHence he the choicest of his meiny steers\nThither, where he the cry and tumult hears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With many peers and chiefs, who worthiest are,\nSummoned about him, Charlemagne is gone:\nHe bids direct his standards to the square\nWhither the paynim had repaired; hears groan\nAnd tumult, spies the horrid tokens there\nOf cruelty, sees human members strown.\n— No more — Let him return another time,\nWho willingly will listen to this rhyme."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 17"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Charles goes, with his, against King Rodomont.\nGryphon in Norandino's tournament\nDoes mighty deeds; Martano turns his front,\nShowing how recreant is his natural bent;\nAnd next, on Gryphon to bring down affront,\nStole from the knight the arms in which he went;\nHence by the kindly monarch much esteemed,\nAnd Gryphon scorned, whom he Martano deemed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "God, outraged by our rank iniquity,\nWhenever crimes have past remission's bound,\nThat mercy may with justice mingled be,\nHas monstrous and destructive tyrants crowned;\nAnd gifted them with force and subtlety,\nA sinful world to punish and confound.\nMarius and Sylla to this end were nursed,\nRome with two Neros and a Caius cursed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Domitian and the latter Antonine;\nAnd, lifted from the lowest rabble's lees,\nTo imperial place and puissance, Maximine:\nHence Thebes to cruel Creon bent her knees,\nMezentius ruled the subject Agiline,\nFattening his fields with blood.  To pests like these\nOur Italy was given in later day,\nTo Lombard, Goth, and Hun a bleeding prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What shall I of fierce Attila, what say\nOf wicked Ezzeline, and hundreds more?\nWhom, because men still trod the crooked way,\nGod sent them for their pain and torment sore.\nOf this ourselves have made a clear assay,\nAs well as those who lived in days of yore;\nConsigned to ravening wolves, ordained to keep\nUs, his ill-nurturing and unuseful sheep;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who, as if having more than served to fill\nTheir hungry maw, invite from foreign wood\nBeyond the mountain, wolves of greedier will,\nWith them to be partakers of their food.\nThe bones which Thrasymene and Trebbia fill,\nAnd Cannae, seem but few to what are strewed\nOn fattened field and bank, where on their way\nAdda and Mella, Ronco and Tarro stray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now God permits that we should feel the spite\nOf people, who are haply worse than we,\nFor errors multiplied and infinite,\nAnd foul and pestilent iniquity.\nThe time will come we may such ill requite\nUpon their shores, if we shall better be,\nAnd their transgressions ever prove above\nThe long endurance of AETERNAL LOVE."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Christian people then God's placid front\nMust have disturbed with their excesses sore;\nSince them with slaughter, rape, and rapine hunt,\nThrough all their quarters, plundering Turk and Moor:\nBut the unsparing rage of Rodomont\nProves worse than all the ills endured before.\nI said that Charlemagne had made repair\nIn search of him towards the city square."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Charles, by the way, his people's butchery\nBeholds — burnt palaces and ruined fanes —\nAnd sees large portion of the city lie\nIn unexampled wreck. — \"Ye coward trains,\nWhither in heartless panic would ye fly?\nWill none his loss contemplate?  what remains\nTo you, — what place of refuge, say, is left,\nIf this from you so shamefully be reft?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then shall one man alone, a prisoned foe,\nWho cannot scale the walls which round him spread,\nUnscathed, unquestioned, from your city go,\nWhen all are by his vengeful arm laid dead?\"\nThus Charlemagne, whose veins with anger glow,\nAnd shame, too strong to brook, in fury said;\nAnd to the spacious square made good his way,\nWhere he beheld the foe his people slay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither large portion of the populace,\nClimbing the palace roof, had made resort;\nFor strongly walled, and furnished was the place\nWith ammunition, for their long support.\nRodomont, mad with pride, had, in his chace\nOf the scared burghers, singly cleared the court,\nHe with one daring hand, which scorned the world,\nBrandished the sword; — his other wildfire hurled;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And smote and thundered, 'mid a fearful shower,\nAt the sublime and royal house's gate.\nTo their life's peril, crumbling roof and tower\nIs tost by them that on the summit wait:\nNor any fears to ruin hall or bower;\nBut wood and stone endure one common fate,\nAnd marbled column, slab, and gilded beam,\nBy sire and grandsire held in high esteem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont stands before the portal, bright\nWith steel, his head and bust secured in mail,\nLike to a serpent, issued into light,\nHaving cast off his slough, diseased and stale:\nWho more than ever joying in his might,\nRenewed in youth, and proud of polished scale,\nDarts his three tongues, fire flashing from his eyes;\nWhile every frighted beast before him flies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor bulwark, stone, nor arbalest, nor bow,\nNor what upon the paynim smote beside,\nSufficed to arrest the sanguinary foe;\nWho broke and hewed, and shook that portal wide,\nAnd in his fury let such day-light through,\n'Twas easy to espy — and might be spied —\nIn visages o'ercast in death-like sort,\nThat full of people was the palace court."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through those fair chambers echoed shouts of dread,\nAnd feminine lament from dame distrest;\nAnd grieving, through the house, pale women fled,\nWho wept, afflicted sore, and beat their breast.\nAnd hugged the door-post and the genial bed,\nToo soon to be by stranger lords possest.\nThe matter in this state of peril hung\nWhen thither came the king, his peers among."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Charles turned him round to  these, of vigorous hand,\nWhom he had found in former peril true.\n\"Are you not those that erst with me did stand\n'Gainst Agolant in Aspramont?  In you\nIs vigour now so spent, (he said), the band,\nWho him, Troyano, and Almontes slew,\nWith hundreds more, that you now fear to face\nOne of that very blood, that very race?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Why should I now in contest with the foe\nLess strength in you behold than them?  Your might\nUpon this hound (pursued the monarch show; ) \n\nThis hound who preys on man. — A generous sprite\nThe thought of death — approach he fast or slow —\nSo that he dies but well, holds cheap and light.\nBut where you are, I doubt my fortune ill,\nFor by your succour, have I conquered still.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This said, he spurred his courser, couched his spear,\nAnd charged the paynim; nor of life less free,\nSir Ogier joined the king in his career;\nNamus and Oliver; and, with the three,\nAvino, Avolio, Otho, and Berlinghier:\n(For one without the rest I never see)\nAnd on the bosom, flanks, and on the front,\nAll smote together at King Rodomont."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But let us, sir, for love of Heaven, forego\nOf anger and of death the noisome lore;\nAnd be it deemed that I have said enow,\nFor this while, of that Saracen, not more\nCruel than strong; 'tis time in trace to go\nOf Gryphon, left with Origille, before\nDamascus' gate, and him who with her came,\nThe adulterer, not the brother of the dame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of all the cities under eastern skies,\nMost wealthy, populous, and fairly dight,\n'Tis said, Damascus is; which distant lies\nFrom Salem seven days' journey; its fair site,\nA fertile plain, abundant fruits supplies,\nWinter and summer, sojourn of delight.\nShading the city from the dawning day,\nA mountain intercepts its early ray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two crystal streams the wealthy city scower;\nWhose currents, parted into many a rill,\nInfinite gardens, never bare of flower,\nOr stript of leaf, with grateful murmur fill:\n'Tis said the perfumed waters are of power\n(So plenteously they swell to turn a mill; ) \n\nAnd that whoever wander through the streets,\nScent, issuing from each home, a cloud of sweets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then the high-street gay signs of triumph wore,\nCovered with showy cloths of different dye,\nWhich deck the walls, while sylvan leaves in store,\nAnd scented herbs upon the pavement lie.\nAdorned is every window, every door,\nWith carpeting and finest drapery;\nBut more with ladies fair, and richly drest,\nIn costly jewels and in gorgeous vest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within the city gates in frolic sport,\nMany are seen to ply the festive dance;\nAnd here the burghers of the better sort\nUpon their gay and well-trapt coursers prance.\nA fairer show remains; the sumptuous court\nOf barons bold and vassals, who advance,\nGarnished with what could be procured, of ore\nAnd pearl, from Ind and Erythraean shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Forward Sir Gryphon pricked, with his array,\nSurveying, here and there, the whole at ease;\nWhen them a knight arrested by the way,\nAnd (such his wont and natural courtesies)\nObliged beneath his palace-roof to stay;\nWhere he let nought be wanting which might please;\nAnd chearfully the guests, with bath restored,\nNext welcomed at his costly supper-board;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And told how he, who, Norandino hight,\nDamascus and all Syria's kingdom swayed,\nNative and foreigner had bade invite,\nOn whom the sword of knighthood had been laid,\nTo a fair joust, which at the morrow's light,\nEnsuing, in the square was to be made.\nWhere they might show, and without further faring,\nIf they had valour equal to their bearing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon, though he came not that joust to see,\nAccepts the challenge of the cavalier;\nFor when occasion serves, it cannot be\nAn evil use to make our worth appear:\nThen questioned more of that solemnity;\n— If 'twere a wonted feast, held every year,\nOr new emprise; by which, in martial course,\nThe monarch would assay his warriors' force. —"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The gorgeous feast our monarch will display\nEach fourth succeeding moon,\" the baron said;\n\"This is the first that you will now survey;\nNone have been held beside.  The cause which bred\nThe solemn usage is, that on such day\nThe king from sovereign peril saved his head,\nAfter four months, consumed in doleful wise,\n'Mid tears and groans, with death before his eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Our monarch, who is named king Norandine\n(Fully to you the matter to recite),\nThrough many and many a year for her did pine,\nAbove all other damsels fair and bright,\nThe king of Cyprus' daughter; whom, in fine,\nEspoused, he, with his bride, and dame, and knight,\nTo wait upon her home, a fair array,\nTowards his Syrian realm had shaped his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But as we scoured the fell Carpathian sea,\nWith flowing sheet, at distance from the shore,\nA storm assailed us, of such cruelty,\nThe tempest even scared our pilot hoar.\nDrifting three days and nights at random, we\nOur devious course 'mid threatening waves explore;\nThen, wet and weary, land 'mid verdant hills,\nBetween well-shaded and refreshing rills."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"We our pavilions pitch, and, 'mid those groves,\nJoyfully strain our awnings overhead;\nAnd kitchens there construct, and rustic stoves,\nAnd carpets for the intended banquet spread.\nMeanwhile through neighbouring vale the monarch roves,\nAnd secret wood, scarce pervious to the tread,\nSeeking red deer, goat, fallow-buck, and doe;\nAnd, following him, two servants bear his bow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"While, with much solace, seated in a round,\nWe from the chace expect our lord's return,\nApproaching us along the shore, astound,\nThe orc, that fearful monster, we discern.\nGod grant, fair sir, he never may confound\nYour eyesight with his semblance foul and stern!\nBetter it is of him by fame to hear,\nThan to behold him by approaching near."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To calculate the griesly monster's height,\n(So measureless is he exceeds all skill; ) \n\nOf fungus-hue, in place of orbs of sight,\nTheir sockets two small bones like berries fill.\nTowards us, as I say, he speeds outright\nAlong the shore, and seems a moving hill.\nTusks jutting out like savage swine he shows,\nA breast with drivel foul, and pointed nose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Running, the monster comes, and bears his snout\nIn guise of brach, who enters on the trail.\nWe who behold him fly (a helpless rout),\nWherever terror drives, with visage pale.\n'Tis little comfort, that he is without\nEye-sight, who winds his plunder in the gale,\nBetter than aught possest of scent and sight:\nAnd wing and plume were needed for our flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Some here, some there make off, but little gain\nBy flying him; for swifter is the pest\nThan the south wind.  Of forty, ten, with pain,\nSwimming aboard the bark in safety rest.\nUnder his arm some wretches of our train\nHe packed, nor empty left his lap or breast:\nAnd loaded a capacious scrip beside,\nWhich, like a shepherd's, to his waist was tied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Us to his den the sightless monster carried,\nHollowed within a rock, upon the shore;\nOf snowy marble was that cavern quarried,\nAs white as leaf, unstained by inky score.\nWith him within the cave a matron tarried,\nWho marked by grief and pain a visage wore.\nWith her were wife and maid, a numerous court,\nBoth fair and foul, of every age and sort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Large as the other, and that grotto near,\nAlmost upon the summit of the rock,\nAnother cavern was contrived, to rear,\nAnd from the weather fend his woolly flock,\nWhich he still herded through the changeful year;\nSo numerous, it were hard to count his stock:\nWont in due season these to pen or loose,\nAnd play the shepherd more for sport than use."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The flesh of man he savoured more than sheep,\nAnd this, before he reached the cave, was seen.\nThree youths of ours, ere yet he climbed the steep,\nHe are alive, or rather swallowed clean;\nThen moved the stone, which closed that cavern deep,\nAnd lodged us there.  With that, to pasture green\nHis flock he led, as wont, the meads among,\nSounding the pipe which at his neck was hung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Our lord, meanwhile, returning to the strand,\nThe loss which he had suffered comprehends;\nFor in deep silence, upon every hand,\nThrough empty tent and hut the monarch wends:\nNor who has robbed him can be understand;\nAnd full of terror to the beach descends;\nWhence he his sailors in the offing sees\nUnmoor and spread their canvas to the breeze."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As soon as Norandino was in view,\nThey launched and sent their pinnace to convey\nThe monarch thence: but he no sooner knew\nOf the fell orc, and those he made his prey,\nThen he, without more thought, would him pursue\nAnd follow, wheresoe'er he bent his way.\nTo lose Lucina is such cruel pain,\nThat life is loathsome save he her regain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When on the newly printed sand his eyes\nNorandine fixt, he with the swiftness sped\nWith which the rage of love a man supplies,\nUntil he reached the cave of which I said,\nWhere we, enduring greater agonies\nThan e'er were suffered, there await in dread\nThe orc, and deem at every sound we hear,\nThe famished brute about to re-appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The monarch to the cave did Fortune guide,\nWhen the orc's wife alone was in the lair.\nSeeing the king: `Fly! — Woe to thee!' (she cried)\n`Should the orc take thee!' — `Woeful every where\nI cannot choose but be,' (the king replied)\n`Whether be take or miss me, kill or spare.\nNot hither I by chance have wandered, I\nCome with desire beside my wife to die.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He afterwards the dame for tidings pressed\nOf those the orc had taken on the shore;\nAnd of Lucina above all the rest;\nIf slain or prisoner kept.  With kindly lore,\nShe Norandino, in return, addressed;\nAnd said Lucina lived, nor need he more\nHave of her future safety any dread,\nFor the orc on flesh of woman never fed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Of this you may behold the proof in me,\nAnd all these other dames who with me dwell;\nNor me, nor them the orc offends, so we\nDepart not ever from this caverned cell.\nBut vainly who would from her prison flee,\nHopes peace or pardon from our tyrant fell:\nBuried alive, or bound with griding band,\nOf, in the sun, stript naked on the sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `When hither he to-day conveyed your crew,\nThe females from the males he severed not;\nBut, as he took them, in confusion threw\nAll he had captive made, into that grot.\nHe will scent out their sex; not tremble, you,\nLest he the women slay: the others' lot\nIs fixt; and, of four men or six a-day,\nBe sure the greedy orc will make his prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I have no counsel for you how to free\nThe lady; but content thyself to hear,\nShe in no danger of her life will be,\nWho will our lot, in good or evil, share.\nBut go, for love of Heaven, my son, lest thee\nThe monster smell, and on thy body fare;\nFor when arrived, he sniffs about the house,\nAnd, such his subtle scent, can wind a mouse.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To her the amorous monarch made reply,\nThat he the cave would not abandon, ere\nHe saw Lucina, and near her to die,\nThan to live far from her, esteemed more dear.\n— Seeing that she can nothing more supply\nFitted to shake the purpose of the peer,\nUpon a new design the matron hits.\nPursued with all her pains, with all her wits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With slaughtered sheep and goat was evermore\nThe cavern filled, the numerous flock's increase,\nWhich served her and her household as a store;\nAnd from the ceiling dangled many a fleece.\nThe dame made Norandino from a hoar\nAnd huge he-goat's fat bowels take the grease,\nAnd with the suet all his members pay,\nUntil he drove his natural scent away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And when she thought he had imbibed the smell\nWhich the rank goat exhales, she took the hide,\nAnd made him creep into the shaggy fell;\nWho was well covered by that mantle wide.\nHim in this strange disguise she from the cell\nCrawling (for such was her command did guide, ) \n\nWhere, prisoned by a stone, in her retreat,\nWas hid his beauteous lady's visage sweet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Kin Norandine, as bid, took up his ground\nBefore the cavern, on the greensward laid,\nThat he might enter with the flock who wound\nHomeward; and longing sore, till evening stayed.\nAt eve he hears the hollow elder's sound,\nUpon whose pipes the wonted tune was played,\nCalling his sheep from pasture to their rock,\nBy the fell swain who stalked behind his flock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Think if his heart is trembling at its core,\nWhen Norandino hears the approaching strains;\nAnd now advancing to the cavern door,\nThe sight of that terrific face sustains!\nBut if fear shook him, pity moved him more:\nYou see if he loves well or only feigns!\nThe orc removed the stone, unbarred the cote,\nAnd the king entered, amid sheep and goat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His flock so housed, to us the orc descended,\nBut first had care the cavern door to close:\nThen scented all about, and having ended\nHis quest, two wretches for his supper chose.\nSo is remembrance by this meal offended,\nIt makes me tremble yet: this done, he goes;\nAnd being gone, the king his goatish vest\nCasts off, and folds his lady to his breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whereas she him with pleasure should descry,\nShe, seeing him, but suffers grief and pain.\nShe sees him thither but arrived to die,\nWho cannot hinder her from being slain.\n` \"Twas no small joy 'mid all the woes, that.'\nTo him exclaimed Lucina, 'here sustain.\nThat thou wert not among us found to-day,\nWhen hither I was brought, the monster's prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `For though to find myself about to leave\nThis life be bitter and afflict me sore,\nSuch is our common instinct, I should grieve\nBut for myself; but whether thee, before\nOf after me, the orc of life bereave,\nAssure thyself thy death will pain me more\nThan mine.'  And thus the dame persists to moan\nMore Norandino's danger than her own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"  `A hope conducts me here,' the monarch said,\n`To save thee and thy followers every one;\nAnd, if I cannot, I were better dead,\nThan living without light of thee, my sun!\nI trust to scape, as hither I have spied;\nAs ye shall all, if, as ourselves have done,\nTo compass our design, you do not shrink\nTo imbue your bodies with the loathsome stink.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The trick he told, wherewith the monster's smell\nTo cheat, as first to him the wife had told:\nIn any case to cloathe us in the fell,\nThat he may feel is issueing from the fold.\nAs many men as women in the cell,\nWe slay (persuaded by the monarch bold)\nAs many goats as with our number square,\nOf those which stink the most and oldest are."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"We smeared our bodies with the fruitful grease\nWhich round about the fat intestines lay,\nAnd cloathed our bodies with the shaggy fleece:\nThis while from golden dwelling broke the day.\nAnd now, his flock returning to release,\nWe viewed the shepherd, with the dawning ray;\nWho, giving breath to the sonorous reeds,\nPiped forth his prisoned flock to hill and meads."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He held his hand before the opened lair,\nLest with the herd we issued from the den,\nAnd stopt us short; but feeling wool or hair\nUpon our bodies, let us go again.\nBy such a strange device we rescued were,\nCloathed in our shaggy fleeces, dames and men:\nNor any issuing thence the monster kept,\nTill thither, sore alarmed, Lucina crept."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lucina — whether she abhorred the scent,\nAnd, like us others, loathed herself to smear,\n— Or whether with a slower gait she went\nThan might like the pretended beast's appear,\n— Or whether, when the orc her body hent,\nHer dread so mastered her, she screamed for fear,\n— Or that her hair escaped from neck or brow,\nWas known; nor can I well inform you how."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So were we all intent on our own case,\nWe for another's danger had no eyes:\nHim, turning at the scream.  I saw uncase\nAlready her whom he had made his prize,\nAnd force her to the cavern to retrace\nHer steps: we, couching in our quaint disguise,\nWend with the flock, where us the shepherd leads,\nThrough verdant mountains, into pleasant meads."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"There we awaited, till beneath the shade\nSecure, we saw the beaked orc asleep;\nWhen one along the shore of ocean made,\nAnd one betook him to the mountain steep.\nKing Norandine his love alone delayed;\nWho would return disguised among the sheep,\nNor from the place depart, while life remained,\nUnless his faithful consort he regained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For when before, on the flock issuing out,\nHe saw her prisoned in the cave alone,\nInto the orc's wide throat he was about\nTo spring; so grief had reason overthrown,\nAnd he advanced even to the monster's snout,\nAnd, but by little, scaped the grinding stone:\nYet him the hope detained amid the flock,\nTrusting to bear Lucina from the rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The orc, at eve, when to the cave again\nHe brings the herd, nor finds us in the stall,\nAnd knows that he must supperless remain,\nLucina guilty of the whole does call,\nCondemned to stand, fast girded with a chain,\nIn open air, upon the summit tall.\nThe king who caused her woes, with pitying eye\nLooks on, and pines, — and only cannot die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Morning and evening, her, lamenting sore,\nEver the unhappy lover might survey;\nWhat time he grieving went afield before\nThe issuing flock, or homeward took his way.\nShe, with sad face, and suppliant evermore,\nSigned that for love of Heaven he would not stay;\nSince there he tarried at great risk of life.\nNor could in any thing assist his wife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So the orc's wife, as well upon her side,\nImplored him to depart, but moved him nought;\nTo go without Lucina he denied,\nAnd but remained more constant in his thought.\nIn this sad servitude he long was tried,\nBy Love and Pity bound: till Fortune brought\nA pair of warriors to the rocky won,\nGradasso, and Agrican's redoubted son:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Where, with their arms so wrought the champions brave,\nThey freed Lucina from the chains she wore,\n(Though he Wit less than Fortune served in save)\nAnd running to the sea their burden bore:\nHer to her father, who was there, they gave.\nThis was at morn, when in the cavern hoar,\nMixt with the goats, king Norandino stood,\nWhich ruminating, chewed their grassy food:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But when, at day-light, 'twas unbarred, and now\nHe was instructed that his wife was gone;\nFor the orc's consort told the tale, and how,\nIn every point, the thing rehearsed was done;\nHe thanked his God, and begged, with promised vow,\nThat, since 'twas granted her such ill to shun,\nHe would direct his wife to some repair,\nWhence he might free her, by arms, gold, or prayer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Together with the flat-nosed herd his way\nHe took, and for green meads rejoicing made.\nHe here expected, till the monster lay\nExtended, underneath the gloomy shade:\nThen journeyed all the night and all the day;\nTill, of the cruel orc no more afraid,\nHe climbed a bark on Satalia's strand,\nAnd, three days past, arrived on Syrian land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In Cyprus, and in Rhodes, by tower and town,\nWhich in near Egypt, Turkey, or Afric lay,\nThe king bade seek Lucina up and down,\nNor could hear news of her till the other day.\nThe other day, his father-in-law made known\nHe had her safe with him.  What caused her stay\nIn Nicosia was a cruel gale\nWhich had long time been adverse to her sail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The king, for pleasure of the tidings true,\nPrepares the costly feast in solemn state;\nAnd will on each fourth moon that shall ensue\nMake one, resembling this we celebrate.\nPleased of that time the memory to renew,\nThat he, in the orc's cavern, had to wait,\n— For four months and a day — which is to-morrow;\nWhen he was rescued from such cruel sorrow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The things related I in part descried,\nAnd from him, present at the whole, heard more;\nFrom Norandine, through calend and through ide,\nPent, till he changed to smiles his anguish sore:\nAnd if from other you hear aught beside,\nSay, he is ill instructed in his lore.\"\nThe Syrian gentleman did thus display\nThe occasion of that feast and fair array."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Large portion of the night, in like discourse,\nWas by those cavaliers together spent,\nWho deemed that Love and Pity's mickle force\nWas proved in that so dread experiment;\nThen rising, when the supper's sumptuous course\nWas cleared, to good and pleasant lodgings went;\nAnd, as the ensuing morning fairly broke,\nTo sounds of triumph and rejoicing woke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The circling drums' and trumpets' echoing strain\nAssemble all the town within the square;\nAnd now, when mixt with sound of horse and wain,\nLoud outcries through the streets repeated are,\nSir Gryphon dons his glittering arms again,\nA panoply of those esteemed most rare;\nWhose mail, impassable by spear or brand,\nShe, the white fay, had tempered with her hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The man of Antioch in his company,\nArmed him (a recreant worse than he was none),\nProvided by their landlord's courtesy\nWith sturdy spears and good, the course to run;\nWho with his kindred, a fair chivalry,\nTo bring the warriors to the square is gone;\nWith squires afoot and mounted upon steeds,\nWhom he bestowed, as aptest for their needs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They in the square arrived and stood aside,\nNor of themselves awhile would make display;\nBetter to see the martial gallants ride\nBy twos and threes, or singly, to the fray.\nOne told, by colours cunningly allied,\nHis joy or sorrow to his lady gay;\nOne, with a painted Love on crest or shield,\nIf she were cruel or were kind, revealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It was the Syrians' practise in that age\nTo arm them in this fashion of the west.\nHaply this sprung out of their vicinage\nAnd constant commerce with the Franks, possest\nIn those days of the sacred heritage,\nThat God incarnate with his presence blest;\nWhich now, to them abandoned by the train\nOf wretched Christians, heathen hounds profane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "God's worshippers, where they should couch the lance,\nFor furtherance of his holy faith and true,\nAgainst each other's breast the spear advance,\nTo the destruction of the faithful few.\nYou men of Spain, and you, ye men of France,\nAnd Switzers, turn your steps elsewhere , and you,\nYe Germans, worthier empire to acquire;\nFor that is won for Christ, which you desire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If verily most Christian you would be,\n— I speak to you, that catholic are hight —\nWhy slain by you Christ's people do I see?\nWherefore are they despoiled of their right?\nWhy seek you not Jerusalem to free\nFrom renegades?  By Turkish Moslemite\nImpure, why is Byzantium, with the best\nAnd fairest portion of the world, possest?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thou Spain, hast thou not fruitful Afric nigh?\nAnd has she not in sooth offended more\nThan Italy?  yet her to scathe, that high,\nAnd noble, enterprize wilt thou give o'er.\nAlas!  thou sleepest, drunken Italy,\nOf every vice and crime the fetid sewer!\nNor grievest, as a hand-maid, to obey,\nIn turn, the nations that have owned thy sway."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If fear of famishing within thy cave,\nSwitzer, does thee to Lombardy convey,\nAnd thou, among our people, dost but crave\nA hand to give thee daily bread, or slay, —\nThe Turk has ready wealth; across the wave,\nDrive him from Europe or from Greece away:\nSo shalt thou in those parts have wherewithal\nTo feed thy hunger, or more nobly fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I to the German neighbour of thy lair\nSay what I say to thee; the wealth o' the west,\nWhich Constantine brought off from Rome, is there —\nBrought off the choicest, gave away the rest —\nThere golden Hermus and Pactolus are,\nMygdonia and Lydia: nor that country blest,\nWhich many tales for many praises note,\nIf thou wouldst thither wend, is too remote."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thou mighty Lion, that art charged to keep\nThe keys of Paradise, a weighty care,\nOh!  let not Italy lie plunged in sleep,\nIf thy strong hand is planted in her hair.\nTo thee, his shepherd, God, to guide his sheep,\nHas given that wand and furious name to bear;\nThat thou may'st roar, and wide thine arms extend,\nAnd so from greedy wolves thy flock defend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But whither have I roved!  who evermore\nSo from one topic to the other stray?\nYet think not I the road I kept before\nTo have missed so far, but I can find my way.\nI said, the Syrians then observed the lore\nOr arming like the Christians of that day.\nSo that Damascus' crowded square was bright\nWith corslet, plate, and helm of belted knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lovely ladies from their scaffolds throw\nUpon the jousters yellow flowers and red;\nWhile these, as loud the brazen trumpets blow,\nMake their steeds leap and wheel and proudly tread.\nEach, rode he well or ill, his art would show,\nAnd with the goring spur his courser bled.\nHence this good cavalier earns fame and praise,\nWhile others scornful hoots and laughter raise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A suit of arms was prize of the assay,\nPresented to the king some days before;\nWhich late a merchant found upon the way\nReturning from Armenia; this the more\nTo grace, a vest, with noblest tissue gay,\nThe Syrian king subjoined, so powdered o'er\nWith jewels, gold, and pearls in rich device,\nThey made the meed a thing of passing price."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If the good king had known the panoply,\nThis he had held above all others dear;\nNor this had given, as full of courtesy,\nTo be contented for with sword and spear.\n'Twere long to tell who so unworthily\nHad erst mistreated thus the goodly gear,\nThat lay the way the harness had been strowed,\nA prey to whosoever past the road."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of this you more in other place shall hear.\nOf Gryphon now I tell, who at the just\nArrived, saw broken many a knightly spear,\nAnd more than one good stroke and one good thrust.\nEight were there who made league together, dear\nTo Norandine, and held in sovereign trust;\nYouths quick in arms and practised in the shock:\nAll lords, or scions of illustrious stock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At open barriers, one by one, the place\nThey kept against all comers for a day;\nAt first with lance, and next with sword or mace,\nWhile them the king delighted to survey.\nOfttimes they pierce the corslet's iron case,\nAnd every thing in fine perform in play,\nWhich foemen do that deadly weapons measure,\nSave that the king may part them at his pleasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That witless Antiochite, who, worthily,\nBy name was cowardly Martano hight,\nThinking, because his comrade, he must be\nPartaker of the noble Gryphon's might,\nInto the martial press rides valiantly,\nThen stops; and the issue of a furious fight,\nWhich had begun between two cavaliers,\nTo wait, retiring from the strife, appears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seleucia's lord, of those companions one,\nCombined in that emprize to keep the place,\nWho then a course with bold Ombruno run,\nWounded the unhappy warrior in mid-face,\nSo that he slew him; mourned by every one,\nWho as a worthy knight the warrior grace,\nAnd over and above his worth, before\nAll others, hold him for his courteous lore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When vile Martano from his place discerned\nThe fate which might be his with fearful eye,\nInto his craven nature be returned,\nAnd straight began to think how he might fly:\nBut him from flight the watchful Gryphon turned,\nAnd, after much ado, with act and cry,\nUrged him against a knight upon the ground,\nAs at the ravening wolf men slip the hound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who will pursue the brindled beast for ten,\nOr twenty yards, and, after, stop to bay;\nWhen he beholds his flashing eyes, and when\nHe sees the griesly beast his teeth display.\n'Twas thus, before those valiant gentlemen\nAnd princes, present there in fair array,\nFearful Martano, seized with panic dread,\nTurned to the right his courser's rein and head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet he who would excuse the sudden wheel,\nUpon his courser might the blame bestow:\nBut, after, he so ill his strokes did deal,\nDemosthenes his cause might well forego.\nWith paper armed he seems, and not with steel,\nSo shrinks he at the wind of every blow:\nAt length he breaks the ordered champions through,\nAmid loud laughter from the circling crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Clapping of hands, and cries, at every turn,\nWere heard from all that rubble widely spread.\nAs a wolf sorely hunted makes return\nTo earth, to his retreat Martano fled.\nGryphon remained, and sullied with the scorn\nEsteemed himself, which on his mate was shed;\nAnd rather than be there, he, in his ire,\nWould gladly find himself i' the midst of fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With burning heart, and visage red with shame,\nHe thinks the knight's disgrace is all his own,\nBecause by deeds like his with whom he came,\nHe weens the mob expects to see him known.\nSo that it now behoves his valour flame\nMore clear than light, or they, to censure prone,\n— Errs he a finger's breadth — an inch — will swell\nHis fault, and of that inch will make an ell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already he the lance upon his thigh\nHas rested, little used to miss the foe:\nThen makes with flowing rein his courser fly,\nAnd next, somedeal advanced, directs the blow;\nAnd, smiting, puts to the last agony\nSidonia's youthful lord, by him laid low.\nO'ercome with wonder each assistant rises,\nWhom sore the unexpected deed surprises."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon returned, and did the weapon wield.\nWhole and recovered, which he couched before,\nAnd in three pieces broke it on the shield\nWhich bold Laodicea's baron bore.\nThrice of four times about to press the field\nHe seemed, and lay along the crupper, sore\nAstound; yet rose at length, unsheathed his blade,\nWheeled his good courser, and at Gryphon made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon, who in his saddle sees the peer\nAdvancing towards him, nor unseated by\nThe encounter, says: \"The failure of the spear\nIn a few strokes the sabre shall supply;\"\nAnd on his temples smote a stroke so shear,\nIt seemed that it descended from the sky;\nAnd matched it with another, and again\nAnother, till he stretched him on the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here two good brothers of Apamia were,\nIn tourney wont to have the upper hand:\nCorimbo named and Thyrsis was the pair;\nBoth overturned by Gryphon on the land.\nOne at the encounter left his saddle bare,\nOn the other Gryphon used his trenchant brand:\nThis valiant knight, was, in the common trust,\nSure to obtain the honours of the just."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bold Salinterno, mid the warlike train,\nWas in the lists, vizier and marshal hight,\nWho had the government of all that reign,\nAnd was, withal, a puissant man of might:\nThe tourney's prize he sees, with much disdain,\nAbout to be borne off by foreign knight.\nA lance he snatches, and to Gryphon cries,\nAnd him with many menaces defies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But he makes answer with a massy spear,\nOut of ten others chosen as the best;\nAnd levelling at the buckler of the peer,\nFor greater surety, pierces plate and breast.\n'Twixt rib and rib, it bored the cavalier,\nIssuing a palm behind.  To all the rest,\nThe king excepted, welcome was the blow:\nFor each was greedy Salinterno's foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two of Damascus next Sir Gryphon sped,\nHermophilo and Carmondo.  This, arraid\nUnder his flag, the king's militia led;\nThat was as lord high admiral obeyed.\nThis lightly at the shock on earth was shed,\nAnd that, reversed, upon the ground o'erlaid\nBy his weak horse, too feeble to withstand\nSir Gryphon's mighty push and puissant hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet in the field remained Seleucia's knight,\nThe best of all the other seven at need;\nAnd one who well accompanied his might\nWith perfect armour and a gallant steed.\nBoth at the helmet, where it locks, take sight,\nAnd with their spears to the encounter speed:\nBut Gryphon hardest smote, whose paynim foe\nLost his left stirrup, staggered by the blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They cast the truncheons down, their coursers wheel,\nAnd, full of daring, with drawn falchions close.\nSir Gryphon was the first a stroke to deal,\nWhich might have split an anvil; at the blow's\nDescent, the shield is splintered — bone and steel —\nThis had its lord mid thousand others chose;\nAnd, but 'twas double, and the coat as well,\nThe sword had cleft the thigh on which it fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He of Seleucia at Sir Gryphon's casque,\nAt the same time, so fell a blow addrest,\nIt would have rent and torn the iron mask,\nHad it not been enchanted like the rest.\nThe paynim's labour is a fruitless task,\nOf arms so hard Sir Gryphon is possest;\nWho has the foe's already cleft and broke\nIn many parts, nor thrown away a stroke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Each one might see how much Seleucia's lord\nWas overmatched by Gryphon, and that day,\nThe worsted men had perished by the sword,\nHad not the monarch quickly stopt the fray.\nTo his guard king Norandino spake the word,\nAnd bade them enter, and the duel stay:\nThey part the knight, whom they asunder bear,\nAnd much the king is lauded for his care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The eight, who had to keep the field pretended\nFrom all the world, nor yet their part had done\nOn a sole knight, — their quarrel ill defended, —\nHad vanished from the tilt-yard one by one.\nThe others, who with them should have contended,\nStood idle; for to answer them was none.\nSince Gryphon had forestalled, in the debate,\nWhat they should all have done against those eight;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, for such little time endured the play,\nLess than an hour sufficed to finish all.\nBut Norandine, the pastime to delay,\nAnd to continue it till even-fall,\nDescending from his place, bade clear the way;\nAnd the huge squad divided, at his call,\nInto two troops, whom, ranked by blood and might,\nThe monarch formed, and marched for other fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Gryphon, during this, had made return\nHomeward, with anger and with fury stung;\nLess thinking of his honours that the scorn\nWhich on the vile Martano had been flung.\nHence, from himself the opprobrious shame to turn,\nMartano now employs his lying tongue;\nAnd she, the false and cunning courtezan,\nAssists him in his scheme as best she can."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether the youth believed the tale or no,\nHe the excuse received, like one discreet;\nAnd deemed it best for them at once to go,\nAnd secretly and silently retreat,\nFor fear, that if the populace should know\nMartano base, they him might ill entreat.\nSo, by short ways and close, they quit the abode,\nAnd issue from the gates upon their road."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Gryphon, was he or his horse foredone\nWith toil, or was it sleep his eyes down weighed,\nEre yet the troop beyond two miles had gone,\nAt the first inn upon the highway stayed.\nHe doffed his armour all, and morion,\nAnd had the steeds of trappings disarrayed;\nAnd next alone he to a chamber sped,\nLocked himself in, undrest, and went to bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner he his head had rested there,\nThan, with deep sleep opprest, he closed his eye:\nSo heavily, no badgers in their lair,\nOr dormice, overcome with slumber, lie.\nMartano and Origille, to take the air,\nEntered this while a garden which was nigh;\nAnd there the strangest fraud together bred,\nWhich ever entered into mortal head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Martano schemed to take away the steed\nAnd gear, in which Sir Gryphon had been dight,\nAnd stand before the monarch, in the weed\nOf him who had in joust so proved his might.\nAs he had shaped in thought, he did the deed:\nHe took away the warrior's horse, more white\nThan milk, his buckler, surcoat, arms, and crest;\nIn all Sir Gryphon's knightly ensigns drest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, who was clad in trappings not his own,\nLike the ass mantled in the lion's hide,\nAs he expected, to the king, unknown,\nWas called in place of Gryphon: when descried\nOr Norandine, he rising from his throne,\nEmbraced and kissed, and placed him by his side:\nNor deems enough to praise and hold him dear,\nBut wills that all around his praise should hear:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And bids them the sonorous metal blow,\nProclaiming him the conqueror of that day:\nAnd round about loud voices, high and low,\nThe unworthy name throughout the lists convey.\nHe wills that, side by side, with him shall go\nThe knight, when homeward he shall take his way;\nAnd him such favour shows, intent to please,\nAs might have honoured Mars or Hercules."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him lodgings fair he gave, wherein to dwell\nAt court; and she who with the peer did ride\nWas honoured by the courteous king as well,\n— False Origille, — with knight and page supplied.\nBut it is time that I of Gryphon tell;\nWho unsuspecting, she, or wight beside,\nHim would with treacherous stratagem deceive,\nHad fallen asleep, nor ever waked till eve."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he how late it was, awaking, knew,\nWith speed he from the chamber did withdraw;\nAnd hastened where he, with the other crew,\nLeft Origille and her false brother-in-law:\nAnd when, nor these, nor, upon better view,\nHis armour nor his wonted clothes he saw,\nSuspicious waxed; and more suspicion bred\nThe ensigns of his comrade left instead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The host, arriving, him at full possest\nOf every thing, — and how, in white array,\nThat warrior, with the lady and the rest,\nHad to the city measured back their way.\nBy little and by little, Gryphon guessed\nWhat love from him had hidden till that day;\nAnd knew, to his great sorrow, in the other\nOrigille's paramour, and not her brother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now he lamenting for his folly stood,\nThat having heard the truths the pilgrim said,\nHe should have let her story change his mood,\nWho him before so often had betrayed.\nHe might have venged himself, nor did: — now wou'd,\nToo late, inflict the punishment delaid;\nConstrained (a crying error! in his need ) \n\nTo take that wily treachour's arms and steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He better would have gone like naked man,\nThan braced the unworthy cuirass on his breast;\nOr hastened the detested shield to span,\nOr place upon his helm the scorned crest.\nBut of the lover, and that courtezan,\nHe, passion mastering reason, took the quest:\nAnd bending to Damascus' gate his way,\nArrived an hour before the close of day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the left hand a castle richly dight\nStood nigh the gate, to which Sir Gryphon rode.\nBesides, that it was strong and armed for fight,\nFilled with rare chambers was the rich abode.\nThe first of Syria, king, and lord, and knight,\nAnd lady, in a gentle group bestowed,\nThere in an open gallery fairly met,\nWere at their glad and costly supper set."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With the high tower the beauteous gallery, clear\nBeyond the city-wall, projected out,\nFrom whence might be discovered, far and near,\nThe spacious fields and different roads about.\nWhen Gryphon now, in his opprobrious gear,\nAnd arms, dishonoured by the rabble's flout,\nMakes, by ill fortune, to the gate resort,\nHe by the king is seen, and all his court;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, taken for the man whose crest he wears,\nIn dame and knight moves laughter, through the ring.\nThe vile Martano, as a man who shares\nThe royal grace, sits next below the king;\nAnd next, she, whom her love so fitly pairs;\nWhom Norandino gaily questioning.\nDemands of them, who is the coward knight,\nThat of his honour makes so passing light;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who, after feat so base and foul, anew\nApproaches, with such front and shameless cheer,\n— And cries, \"It seems a thing unheard, that you,\nAn excellent and worthy cavalier,\nShould take this man for your companion, who\nHas not in all our wide Levant his peer.\nDid you with him for contrast-sake combine,\nThat so your valour might more brightly shine?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"— But did not love for you my will restrain,\nBy the eternal gods, I truly swear,\nHe should endure such ignominious stain,\nAs I am wont to make his fellows share:\nHim would I make of my long-nursed disdain\nOf cowardice perpetual record bear.\nTo you, by whom he hither was conveyed,\nIf now unpunished, let his thanks be paid.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That vessel of all filthy vices, he,\nMade answer: \"Mighty sir, I cannot say\nWho is the stranger, that fell in with me\nJourneying from Antioch hither, by the way:\nBut him I worthy of my company\nDeemed, by his warlike semblance led astray.\nI nothing of his deeds have heard or seen,\nSave what ill feats to-day have witnessed been;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Which moved me so, it little lacked but I,\nFor punishment of his unworthy fear,\nHad put him out of case again to ply,\nIn martial tournament, the sword or spear;\nAnd, but in reverence to your majesty\nAnd presence, I forbore by hand to rear,\nNot for his sake: — nor by thy mercy showed\nOn him, as my companion on the road;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whose former fellowship appears a stain;\nAnd ever 'twill sit heavy at my heart,\nIf I, uninjured, see the wretch again\n'Scape, to the scandal of the warlike art.\n'Twere better he from tower, a worthy pain,\nWere gibbeted, than suffered to depart:\nHung as a beacon for the coward's gaze.\nSuch were a princely deed, and worthy praise.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A voucher he in Origilla had,\nWho well, without a sign, his purpose read.\n\"I deem not,\" cried the king, \"his works so bad,\nThat they should cost the stranger knight his head:\nEnough that he again the people glad,\nFor penance of his weighty sin.\"  This said,\nHe quickly called a baron of his crew,\nAnd him enjoined the deed he was to do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With many armed men that baron fares,\nAnd to the city-gate descending, here\nCollects his troop, and for the attempt prepares,\nWaiting the coming of the cavalier;\nAnd him surprises so at unawares,\nHe, softly, 'twixt two bridges, takes the peer;\nAnd him detains, with mockery and scorn,\nIn a dark chamber, till returning morn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The early sun had scarce his golden hair\nUplifted from his ancient nurse's breast,\nBeginning, upon Alpine regions bare,\nTo chase the shades and gild the mountain-crest,\nWhen Martan', fearing Gryphon might declare\nHis wrong, and to the king the truth attest,\nRetorting upon him the slander cast,\nTook leave, and thence upon his journey past."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His ready wit a fit excuse supplies\nWhy he stays not, to see the recreant shown.\nHe is with other gifts, beside the prize,\nRewarded for the victory, not his own,\nAnd letters patent, drawn in ample wise,\nWherein his lofty honours wide are blown.\nLet him depart; I promise he shall meet\nA guerdon worthy of his treacherous feat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon is brought with shame into the square,\nWhen it is fully thronged with gazing wight,\nWhom they of cuirass and of helmet bare,\nAnd leave in simple cassock, meanly dight;\nAnd, as to slaughter he conducted were,\nPlace on a wain, conspicuous to the sight;\nHarnessed to which two sluggish cows are seen,\nWeary and weak, and with long hunger lean."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thronging about the ignoble car, appear\nBrazen-faced boy and girl of evil fame,\nWho, each in turn, will play the charioteer,\nAnd all assail the knight with bitter blame.\nThe boys might be a cause of greater fear,\nFor, joined to mocks and mows, and words of shame,\nThe warrior they with volleyed stones would slay,\nBut that the wiser few their fury stay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That which of his disgrace had been the ground,\nThough no true evidence of guilt, his mail\nAnd plate, are dragged in due dishonour round,\nSuspended at the shameful waggon's tail.\nThe wain is stopt, and to the trumpet's sound,\nHeralds, in front of a tribunal's pale,\nHis shame, before his eyes, amid the crowd,\n(Another's evil deed proclaim aloud. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They take their prisoner thence, and so repair\nIn front of temple, dwelling-house, and store;\nNor any cruel name of mockery spare,\nNor leave unsaid a word of filthy lore;\nAnd him at last without the city bear:\nThe foolish rabble, trusting evermore\nTheir thrall to banish to the sound of blows,\nWho passing little of its prisoner knows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warrior's gyves no sooner they undo,\nAnd from their manacles free either hand,\nThan Gryphon seizes shield and sword, and, through\nThe rabble, makes long furrows with his brand.\nWith pike and spear unfurnished was the crew,\nWho without weapons came, a witless band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto I suspend,\nFor, sir, 'tis time this song should have an end.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 18"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon is venged.  Sir Mandricardo goes\nIn search of Argier's king.  Charles wins the fight.\nMarphisa Norandino's men o'erthrows.\nDue pains Martano's cowardice requite.\nA favouring wind Marphisa's gallery blows,\nFor France with Gryphon bound and many a knight.\nThe field Medoro and Cloridano tread,\nAnd find their monarch Dardinello dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "High minded lord!  your actions evermore\nI have with reason lauded, and still laud;\nThough I with style inapt, and rustic lore,\nYou of large portion of your praise defraud:\nBut, of your many virtues, one before\nAll others I with heart and tongue applaud,\n— That, if each man a gracious audience finds,\nNo easy faith your equal judgment blinds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Often, to shield the absent one from blame,\nI hear you this, or other, thing adduce;\nOr him you let, at least, an audience claim,\nWhere still one ear is open to excuse:\nAnd before dooming men to scaith and shame,\nTo see and hear them ever is your use;\nAnd ere you judge another, many a day,\nAnd month, and year, your sentence to delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Had Norandine been with your care endued,\nWhat he by Gryphon did, he had not done.\nProfit and fame have from your rule accrued:\nA stain more black than pitch he cast upon\nHis name: through him, his people were pursued\nAnd put to death by Olivero's son;\nWho at ten cuts or thrusts, in fury made,\nSome thirty dead about the waggon laid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whither fear drives, in rout, the others all,\nSome scattered here, some there, on every side,\nFill road and field; to gain the city-wall\nSome strive, and smothered in the mighty tide,\nOne on another, in the gateway fall.\nGryphon, all thought of pity laid aside,\nThreats not nor speaks, but whirls his sword about,\nWell venging on the crowd their every flout."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of those who to the portal foremost fleed,\nThe readiest of the crowd their feet to ply,\nPart, more intent upon their proper need\nThan their friends' peril, raise the draw-bridge high:\nPart, weeping and with deathlike visage, speed,\nNor turn their eyes behind them as they fly:\nWhile, through the ample city, outcry loud,\nAnd noise, and tumult rises from the crowd."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two nimble Gryphon seizes, mid the train,\nWhen to their woe the bridge is raised; of one,\nUpon the field the warrior strews the brain,\nWhich he bears out on a hard grinding stone;\nSeized by the breast, the other of the twain\nOver the city-wall by him is thrown,\nFear chills the townsmen's marrow, when they spy\nThe luckless wretch descending from the sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Many there were who feared in their alarms,\nLest o'er the wall Sir Gryphon would have vaulted;\nNor greater panic seized upon those swarms,\nThan if the soldan had the town assaulted.\nThe sound of running up and down, of arms,\nOf cry of Muezzins, on high exalted;\nOf drums and trumpets, heaven, 'twould seem, rebounded,\nAnd, that the world was by the noise confounded."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But I will to another time delay,\nWhat chanced on this occasion, to recount.\n'Tis meet I follow Charles upon his way,\nHurrying in search of furious Rodomont,\nWho did the monarch's suffering people slay.\nI said, with him, the danger to affront,\nWent Namus, Oliver, the Danish peer,\nAvino, Avolio, Otho and Berlinghier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Eight lances' shock, that eight such warriors guide,\nWhich all at once against the king they rest,\nEndured the stout and scaly serpent's hide,\nIn which the cruel Moor his limbs had drest.\nAs a barque rights itself, — the sheet untied,\nWhich held its sail, — by growing wind opprest;\nSo speedily Sir Rodomont arose,\nThough a hill had been uprooted by the blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rainier and Guido, Richard, Salomon,\nIvan, Ughetto, Turpin, and the twain —\nAngiolin, Angelier — false Ganellon,\nAnd Mark and Matthew from St. Michael's plain,\nWith the eight of whom I spake, all set upon\nThe foe, with Edward and Sir Arimane;\nWho leading succours from the English shore,\nHad lodged them in the town short time before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not so, well-keyed into the solid stone,\nGroans upon Alpine height the castle good,\nWhen by rude Boreas' rage or Eurus' strown,\nUptorn are ash and fir in mountain wood,\nAs groans Sir Rodomont, with pride o'erblown,\nInflamed with anger and with thirst of blood:\nAnd, as the thunder and the lightning's fire\nFly coupled, such his vengeance and his ire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He at his head took aim who stood most nigh;\nUghetto was the miserable wight,\nWhom to the teeth he clove, and left to die;\nThough of good temper was his helmet bright.\nAs well the others many strokes let fly\nAt him, himself; which all the warrior smite,\nBut harm (so hard the dragon's hide no more, ) \n\nThan needle can the solid anvil score."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All the defences, round, abandoned are,\nThe unpeopled city is abandoned all;\nFor, where the danger is the greater, there\nThe many give their aid, at Charles' call:\nThrough every street they hurry to the square,\nSince flying nought avails, from work and wall.\nTheir bosoms so the monarch's presence warms,\nThat each again takes courage, each takes arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As when within the closely-fastened cage\nOf an old lioness, well used to fight,\nAn untamed bull is prisoned, to engage\nThe savage monster, for the mob's delight;\nThe cubs, who see him cresting in his rage,\nAnd round the den loud-bellowing, to the sight\nOf the huge beast's enormous horns unused,\nCower at a distance, timid and confused;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But if the mother spring at him, and hang,\nFixing her cruel tusks into his ear,\nHer whelps as well will blood their greedy fang,\nAnd, bold in her defence, assail the steer:\nOne bites his paunch, and one his back: so sprang\nThat band upon the paynim cavalier.\nFrom roof and window, and from place more nigh,\nPoured in a ceaseless shower, the weapons fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of cavaliers and footmen such the squeeze,\nThat hardly can the place the press contain:\nThey cluster there as thick as swarming bees,\nWho thither from each passage troop amain.\nSo that, were they unarmed, and with more ease\nThan stalks or turnips he could cleave the train,\nIll Rodomont in twenty days would clear\nThe gathering crowd, united far and near."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Unknowing how himself from thence to free,\nThe paynim by this game is angered sore,\nWho little thins the gathering rabblery,\nStaining the ground with thousands slain or more;\nAnd all the while, in his extremity,\nFinds that his breath comes thicker than before;\nAnd sees he cannot pierce the hostile round,\nUnless he thence escape while strong and sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The monarch rolls about his horrid eyes,\nAnd sees that foes all outlets barricade;\nBut, at the cost of countless enemies,\nA path shall quickly by his hand be made.\nWhere Fury calls him, lo!  the felon hies,\nAnd brandishes on high his trenchant blade,\nTo assail the newly entered British band,\nWhich Edward and Sir Ariman command."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He who has seen the fence, in well-thonged square,\n(Against whose stakes the eddying crowd is born)\nBy wild bull broken, that has had to bear,\nThrough the long day, dogs, blows, and ceaseless scorn;\nWho hunts the scattered people here and there,\nAnd this, or that, now hoists upon his horn;\nLet him as such, or fiercer yet, account,\nWhen he breaks forth, the cruel Rodomont."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At one cross-blow fifteen or twenty foes\nHe hews, as many leaves without a bead,\nAt cross or downright-stroke; as if he rows\nTrashes in vineyard or in willow-bed,\nAt last all smeared with blood the paynim goes,\nSafe from the place, which he has heaped with dead;\nAnd wheresoe'er he turns his steps, are left\nHeads, arms, and other members, maimed and cleft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He from the square retires in such a mode,\nNone can perceive that danger him appals;\nBut, during this, what were the safest road,\nBy which to sally, he to thought recals.\nHe comes at last to where the river flowed\nBelow the isle, and past without the walls.\nIn daring men at arms and mob increase,\nWho press him sore, nor let him part in peace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the high-couraged beast, whom hunters start\nIn the wild Nomade or Massilian chace,\nWho, even in flying, shows his noble heart,\nAnd threatening seeks his lair with sluggish pace;\nFrom that strange wood of sword, and spear, and dart,\nTurns Rodomont, with action nothing base;\nAnd still impeded by the galling foe,\nMakes for the river with long steps and slow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He turned upon the rabble-rout who bayed\nBehind him, thrice or more, by anger driven,\nAnd stained anew his falchion, by whose blade\nMore than a hundred deadly wounds were given.\nBut reason, finally, his fury stayed\nBefore the bloody carnage stank to heaven;\nAnd he, with better counsel, from the side\nCast himself down into Seine's foaming tide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Athwart the current swam, with arms and all,\nAs if by corks upborn, the cavalier.\nThough thou Antaeus bred'st, and Hannibal,\nO Africa!  thou never bred'st his peer! —\nWhen now across the stream, without the wall,\nHe turned, and saw the royal town appear,\n— To have traversed all the city moved his ire,\nLeaving it undestroyed by sword or fire;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And him so sorely anger stung and pride,\nThither he thought a second time to go;\nAnd from his inmost bosom groaned and sighed,\nNor would depart until he laid it low.\nBut he saw one along the river-side\nApproach, who made him rage and hate forego;\nStrait shall you hear who 'twas, approached the king,\nBut first I have to say of other thing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I have of haughty Discord now to say,\nTo whom the archangel Michael gave command,\nTo heat to enmity and fierce affray\nThe best of Agramant's besieging band.\nShe went that evening from the abbey gray,\nHer task committing to another's hand;\n— Left it to Fraud to feed, till her return,\nThe war, and make the fires she kindled burn;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And she believed, that she with greater power\nShould go, did Pride with her as well repair;\nAnd she (for all were guested in one bower)\nIn search of her had little way to fare.\nPride went with her; but, that in hall or tower,\nA vicar too her charge might duly bear,\nShe for those days she absent thought to be,\nFor her lieutenant left Hypocrisy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The implacable Discord went, and with the dame,\n(Companion of the enterprise, was Pride)\nUpon her road; and found that, by the same,\nWas journeying to the paynim camp, beside,\nComfortless Jealousy, with whom there came\nA little dwarf, attending as a guide;\nWho erst had been sent forward with advice\nTo Sarza's king, by beauteous Doralice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she fell into Mandricardo's hand,\n(I have before recounted when and where)\nShe had in secret given the dwarf command,\nHe to the king should with the tidings fare;\nBy whom she hoped not vainly would be scanned\nThe tale her messenger was charged to bear,\nBut wonderous deeds be done for her relief,\nWith sad and signal vengeance on the thief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Jealousy had that little dwarf espied,\nAnd kenned the reason of his mission too,\nAnd joined him, journeying with him side by side,\nDeeming that she therein a part might do.\nDiscord, with pleasure, Jealousy decried,\nBut with more joy, when she the occasion knew\nWhich thither brought the dame, who much (she wist)\nMight in the task she had in hand assist."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of means to embroil the Sarzan and the son\nOf Agrican, she deems herself possest.\nA certain mode to enrage these two is won;\nAnd other means may work upon the rest.\nShe thither with the dwarfish page is gone,\nWhere the fierce Pagan in his clutch had prest\nProud Paris, and they reached the river strand,\nExactly as the felon swam to land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as the redoubted Rodomont\nKnew in the dwarf the courier of his dame,\nHe all his rage extinguished, cleared his front,\nAnd felt his courage brighten into flame.\nAll else he deems the courier may recount,\nSave that a wight had wrought him scaith and shame,\nAnd cries (encountering him with chearful brow)\n\"How fares our lady?  wither sent art thou?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor mine nor thine that lady will I say,\nWho is another's thrall,\" the dwarf replied.\n\"We, on our road, encountered yesterday\nA knight, who seized and bore away the bride.\"\nJealousy, upon this, took up the play,\nAnd, cold as asp, embraced the king: her guide\nPursued his tale, relating how the train,\nTheir mistress taken, by one man were slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her flint and steel, fell Discord, as he said,\nTook forth, and somewhile hammered on the stone.\nPride, underneath, the ready tinder spread,\nAnd the quick fire was in a moment blown:\nThis on the paynim's soul so fiercely fed,\nHe could not find a resting place: 'mid groan\nAnd sob he storms, with horrid face and eye,\nWhich threat the elements and ample sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As tiger rages, who in vain descends\nInto her den, and finds herself alone,\nAnd, circling all the cavern, comprehends,\nAt last, that her beloved young are gone;\nTo ire, to rage like hers his wrath extends:\nNor night the king regards, nor rock, nor stone,\nNor stream: — Nor length of way nor storm arrest\nThe speed with which he on the plunderer prest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So raging, to the pigmy dwarf who bore\nThe news, exclaimed the king, \"Now hence away!\"\nNor horse he waits, nor carriage, nor, before\nDeparting, deigns to his a word to say.\nHe hurries with such speed, that not with more\nThe lizard darts at noon across the way.\nHorse had he none, but be he whose he might,\nWould make his own the first which came in sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Discord at this, who read his secret thought,\nExclaimed, as she looked smilingly on Pride,\nThrough her he to a courser should be brought,\nBy which new cause of strife should be supplied;\nAnd, that by him no other might be caught,\nShe from his path would keep all steeds beside;\nAnd knew already where the prize to seek.\n— But her I leave, again of Charles to speak."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When, on the Saracen's departure, spent,\nAbout King Charles, was the consuming flame,\nHe ranged his troops anew: some warriors went\nTo strengthen feeble posts which succours claim;\nThe rest against the Saracens are sent,\nTo give the foe checkmate and end the game;\nAnd from St. German's to Saint Victor's gates,\nHe pours the host, which on his signal waits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He these at Saint Marcellus' gate, where lay,\nOutstretched a large circumference of plain,\nBade one another wait, in one array,\nTo reunite against the paynim train.\nInflaming every one to smite and slay,\nIn guise, that for a record should remain,\nHe made the various troops fall in below\nTheir banners, and the battle-signal blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant has remounted in his sell,\nWhile this is doing in his foe's despite,\nAnd with the stripling who loved Isabel,\nIs waging perilous and fearful fight.\nLurcanio with Sobrino strives as well;\nRinaldo a troop encounters, whom the knight,\nWith Valour and with Fortune for his guide,\nCharges, and breaks, and routs on every side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While so the battle stands, king Charlemagne\nFalls on the rear guard of the paynim foe,\nWhere bold Marsilius halts the flower of Spain,\nAnd forms the host, his royal flag below.\nOn these king Charlemagne impels his train,\nWho, foot with horse to flank, against them go.\nWhile so the deafening drum and trumpet sounds,\n'Twould seem the spacious world the din rebounds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Saracenic squadrons had begun\nTo bend, and all the army of the Moor\nHad turned, disordered, broken, and undone,\nNever to be arrayed or rallied more,\nBut that Grandonio stood, and Falsiron,\nTried oftentimes in greater ill before,\nWith Serpentine and Balugantes proud,\nAnd the renowned Ferrau, who cried aloud:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O valiant men,\" he — \"O companions,\" cries,\n\"O brethren, stand, and yet your place maintain;\nLike cobweb-threads our cruel enemies\nWill find their works, if we our part sustain.\nWhat this day Fortune offers to our eyes,\nIf now we conquer, see the praise, the gain! —\nIf conquered, see the utter loss and shame\nWhich will for ever wait upon your name!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He in this time a mighty lance had spanned,\nAnd spurred at once against Sir Berlinghier,\nWho Argaliffa guided with his hand,\nAnd broke his helmet's frontal with the spear,\nCast him on earth, and with the cruel brand\nUnhorsed perhaps eight other warriors near.\nHis mighty strokes discharging, at each blow,\nHe ever laid at least one horseman low."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In other part, Rinaldo, in his mood,\nHas slain more enemies than I can say,\nBefore the warlike knight no order stood;\nYou might have seen the ample camp give way.\nNo less Zerbino and Lurcanio good\nDo deeds, which will be told in every day;\nThis, with a thrust, has bold Balastro slain,\nThat Finaduro's helm has cleft in twain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The first was of the Alzerban army head,\nRuled by Tardocco some short time before;\nThe other one the valiant squadrons led\nOf Saphi, and Morocco, and Zamor.\n\"Where, 'mid the paynims,\" might to me be said,\n\"Is knight whose sword can cleave or lance can gore?\"\nBut step by step I go, and as I wind\nMy way, leave none who merits praise behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zumara's king is not forgotten here,\nDardinel, who Sir Dulphin of the mount,\nClaude of the wood, and Hubert, with the spear,\n(Of Mirford he and Elio did dismount, ) \n\nAnd, with the faulchion, Stamford's cavalier,\nSir Anselm, Raymond and Sir Pinnamont\nFrom London-town; though valiant were the twain;\nTwo stunned, one wounded, the four others slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet will his squadron not so firmly stand,\nMaugre the valour which his deeds display,\nSo firmly, as to wait the Christian band,\nIn number less, but steadier in array,\nMore used to joust and manage of the brand,\nAnd all things appertaining to the gray.\nSetta and Morocco turned, and, seized with dread,\nZumara and Canaries' islesmen fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But faster than the rest Alzerba flies,\nWhom Dardinel opposed, and now with sore\nReproach, and now with prayer he moves, and tries\nWhat best he deems their courage may restore.\n\"If good Almontes has deserved,\" he cries,\n\"That you should by his memory set such store,\nNow shall be seen — be seen, if you will me,\nHis son, abandon in such jeopardy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For sake of my green youth, I pray you stand,\nThat youth whereon your hopes were wont to feed,\nAnd suffer not that, scattered by the brand,\nTo Africa be lost our noble seed.\nSave you united go, be sure the land\nIs shut against you, wheresoe'er you speed.\nToo high a wall to climb is mountain-steep,\nThe yawning sea a ditch too wide to leap."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Far better 'tis to perish than to be\nTorn by these dogs, or lie at their control.\nSince vain is every other remedy,\nWait, friends, for love of Heaven, the advancing shoal:\nThey are not gifted with more lives than we;\nHave but one pair of hands, have but one soul.\"\nSo saying, the bold youth, amid the crew\nOf enemies, the Earl of Huntley slew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Almontes' memory, through the Moorish bands,\nMakes every bosom with such ardour glow,\nThey deem 'tis better to use arms and hands\nIn fight, than turn their backs upon the foe.\nTaller than all William of Burnwich stands,\nAn Englishman, whom Dardinel brings low,\nAnd equals with the rest; then smites upon,\nAnd cleaves, the head of Cornish Aramon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Down fell this Aramon, and to afford\nHim succour, thitherward his brother made;\nBut from the shoulder him Zumara's lord\nCleft to the fork, with his descending blade;\nNext Bogio de Vergalla's belly gored,\nAnd from his debt absolved (the forfeit paid)\nWho to return within six months, if life\nWere granted him, had promised to his wife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lurcanio next met Dardinello's eye;\nHe upon earth Dorchino had laid low,\nPierced through the throat, and hapless Gardo nigh\nCleft to the teeth; at him, as all too slow,\nHe from Altheus vainly seeks to fly,\nWhom as his heart Lurcanio loves, a blow\nUpon his head behind the Scotchman speeds;\nAnd. slaughtered by the stroke, the warrior bleeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dardinel, to avenge him, took a spear,\nAnd, should he lay the fierce Lurcanio dead,\nVowed to his Mahomet, if he could hear,\nThe mosque should have his empty arms; this said,\nRanging the field in haste, that cavalier\nHe in the flank, with thrust so full and dread,\nEncountered, that it went through either side:\nAnd he to his to strip the baron cried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From me it sure were needless to demand,\nIf Ariodantes, when his brother fell,\nWas grieved; if he with his avenging hand\nAmong the damned would send Sir Dardinell;\nBut all access the circling troops withstand\nAnd bar, no less baptized than infidel:\nYet would he venge himself, and with his blade,\nNow here, now there, an open passage made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He charges, chases, breaks, and overthrows\nWhoever cross him on the crowded plain;\nAnd Dardinello, who his object knows,\nWould fain the wish content; but him the train\nImpedes as well, which round about him flows,\nAnd renders aye his every purpose vain.\nIf one on all sides thins the Moorish rank,\nThe other slays Scot, Englishman, and Frank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fortune still blocked their path throughout the day,\nSo that they met not, 'mid that chivalry,\nAnd kept one as a mightier champion's prey;\nFor rarely man escapes his destiny.\nBehold the good Rinaldo turns that way!\nThat, for this one no refuge there might be.\nLo!  good Rinaldo comes: him Fortune guides,\nAnd for his sword King Dardinel provides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But here enough for this one while is shown\nOf their illustrious doings in the west;\n'Tis time I seek Sir Gryphon, and make known\nHow he, with fury burning in his breast,\nThat rabble-rout had broke and overthrown,\nStruck with more fear than ever men possest.\nThither speeds Norandine on that alarm,\nAnd for his guard above a thousand arm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Norandine, girt with peer and knight,\nSeeing on every side the people fly,\nRides to the gates, with squadron duly dight,\nAnd at his hest the portals open fly.\nMeanwhile Sir Gryphon, having put to flight\nThe weak and worthless rabble far and nigh,\nThe scorned arms (to keep him from that train),\nSuch as they were, took up and donned again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And nigh a temple strongly walled, and round\nWhose base a moat for its protection goes,\nUpon a little bridge takes up his ground,\nThat him his enemies may not enclose.\nLo!  loudly shouting, and with threatening sound,\nA mighty squadron through the gateway flows.\nThe valiant Gryphon changes not his place,\nAnd shows how small his fear by act and face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But when, approaching near, he saw the band,\nHe sallied forth to meet them by the way;\nAnd wielding still his sword in either hand,\nMade cruel havoc in the close array.\nThen on the narrow bridge resumed his stand,\nNor there his hunters only held at bay:\nAnew he sallied, and returned anew,\nAye leaving bloody signs when he withdrew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fore-stroke and back he deals, and on the ground\nHorsemen and foot o'erthrows on every side:\nThis while the ample mob the knight surround,\nAnd more and more the warfare rages wide.\nAt length Sir Gryphon fears he shall be drowned,\n(So waxed their numbers in the increasing tide; ) \n\nAnd hurt in the left shoulder, through his mail,\nAnd thigh, his wind as well begins to fail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Valour, who so oft befriends her own,\nMakes him find grace in Norandino's eyes;\nWho, while alarmed, he hurries there, o'erthrown\nSo many men, such heaps of dead espies,\nWhile he views wounds, which Hector's hand alone\nHe weens could deal, — to him all testifies\nThat he had put an undeserved shame\nUpon a cavalier of mighty name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next seeing him more near, whose falchion's sweep\nHad dealt such deaths amid his chivalry,\nAnd raised about himself that horrid heap,\nAnd stained the water with that bloody dye,\nHe thought that he beheld Horatius keep,\nSingly, the bridge against all Tuscany;\nAnd vext, and anxious to remove the stain,\nRecalled his men, and that with little pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, lifting his bare hand, in sign affied,\nFrom ancient times, of treaty and of truce,\nRepenting him, he to Sir Gryphon cried,\n\"It grieves me sorely, and I cannot choose\nBut own my sin: let counsels which misguide,\nAnd my own little wit, such fault excuse.\nWhat by the vilest knight I thought to do,\nI to the best on earth have done in you."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And though the bitter injuries and shame\nThat have to thee through ignorance been done,\nAre equalled, and all cancelled by thy fame,\nAnd merged, in truth, in glory thou hast won;\nWhatever satisfaction thou canst claim,\nWithin my power or knowledge, count upon,\nWhen I know how atonement may be made,\nBy city, castle, or by money paid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Demand of me this kingdom's moiety,\nAnd from this day thou its possessor art,\nSince not alone thy worth deserves this fee,\nBut merits, I with this should give my heart;\nThen, pledge of faith and lasting love, to me,\nIn the meanwhile, thy friendly hand impart.\"\nSo saying, from his horse the king descended,\nAnd towards Gryphon his right-hand extended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he beheld the monarch's altered cheer,\nWho bent to clasp his neck, towards him paced,\nHis sword and rancour laid aside, the peer\nHim humbly underneath the hips embraced.\nKing Norandine, who saw the sanguine smear\nOf his two wounds, bade seek a leech in haste;\nAnd bade them softly with the knight resort\nTowards the town, and lodge him in his court."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here, wounded, he remained some days before\nHe could bear arms: but him, in the design\nOf seeking out Sir Aquilant once more,\nAnd good Astolpho, left in Palestine,\nI quit; they vainly did his path explore,\nAfter Sir Gryphon left the holy shrine,\nThrough Solyma in every place of note,\nAnd many, from the Holy Land remote."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One and the other are alike to seek\nIn the inquiry where the knight may use;\nBut they encounter with the pilgrim-Greek,\nWho of false Origilla gives them news;\nRelating, as of her he haps to speak,\nThat towards Antioch she her way pursues,\nBy a new leman of that city charmed,\nWho her with fierce and sudden flame had warmed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Aquilant asked him, if he had possest\nSir Gryphon of the news to them conveyed,\nWho, hearing that he had, surmised the rest, —\nWhere he was gone, and by what motive swayed:\nHe followed Origille, was manifest,\nAnd had in quest of her for Antioch made,\nTo take her from his rival, and with view\nOn him some memorable scathe to do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Aquilant brooked not Gryphon such a feat,\nWithout him, and alone, should thus assay,\nAnd took his armour and pursued his beat;\nBut first besought the duke he would delay\nTo visit France and his paternal seat,\nTill he from Antioch measured back his way.\nAt Joppa he embarks, who deems by sea\nThe better and securer way to be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From the south-east up-sprung so strong a breeze,\nAnd which for Gryphon's galley blew so right,\nThat the third day he Tyre's famed city sees,\nAnd lesser Joppa quick succeeds to sight.\nBy Zibellotto and Baruti flees,\n(Cyprus to larboard left the galley light; ) \n\nFrom Tripoli to Tortosa shapes her way,\nAnd so to Lizza and Lajazzo's bay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From thence, towards the east the pilot veered\nHer ready tiller, prompt his course to scan;\nAnd straightway for the wide Orontes steered,\nAnd watched his time, and for the harbour ran.\nAquilant, when his bark the margin neared,\nBade lower the bridge, and issued, horse and man,\nIt armour, and along the river wended,\nUp-stream, till he his way at Antioch ended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To inform himself of that Martano bent;\nAnd heard that he to Antioch was addrest,\nWith Origilla, where a tournament\nWas to be solemnized by royal hest.\nTo track whom Aquilant was so intent,\nAssured that Gryphon had pursued his quest,\nHe Antioch left again that very day,\nBut not by sea again would take his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He towards Lidia and Larissa goes,\n— At rich Aleppo makes a longer stay.\nGod, to make plain that he, even here, bestows\nOn evil and on good their fitting pay,\nAt a league's distance from Mamuga, throws\nMartano in the avenging brother's way,\nMartano travelling with the tourney's prize,\nDisplayed before his horse in showy wise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Aquilant believed, at the first show,\nHis brother he in vile Martano spied.\nFor arms and vest, more white than virgin snow,\nThe coward in the warrior's sight belied,\nAnd sprang towards him, with that joyful \"Oh!\"\nBy which delight is ever signified;\nBut changed his look and tone, when, nearer brought\nHe sees that he is not the wight he sought:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And through that evil woman's treachery,\nDeemed Gryphon murdered by the cavalier;\nAnd, \"Tell me,\" he exclaimed, \"thou, who must be\nTraitor and thief — both written in thy cheer —\nWhence are these arms?  and wherefore do I thee\nView on the courser of my brother dear?\nSay is my brother slaughtered or alive?\nHow didst thou him of horse and arms deprive?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Origille hears him, in affright\nShe turns her palfrey, and for flight prepares:\nBut Aquilant, more quick, in her despite,\nArrests the traitress, ere she further fares.\nAt the loud threats of that all furious knight,\nBy whom he so was taken unawares,\nMartan' turns pale and trembles like a leaf,\nNor how to act or answer knows the thief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Aquilant thundered still, and, to his dread,\nA falchion, pointed at his gullet, shewed,\nAnd swore with angry menaces, the head\nFrom him and Origille should be hewed,\nSave in all points the very truth be said.\nAwhile on this ill-starred Martano chewed,\nRevolving still what pretext he might try\nTo lessen his grave fault, then made reply:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Know, sir, you see my sister in this dame,\nAnd one of good and virtuous parents born,\nThough she has lately led a life of shame,\nAnd been by Gryphon foully brought to scorn;\nAnd, for I loathed such blot upon our name,\nYet weened that she could ill by force be torn\nFrom such a puissant wight, I laid a scheme\nHer by address and cunning to redeem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With her I planned the means, who in her breast\nNursed the desire a better life to prove,\nThat she, when Gryphon was retired to rest,\nIn silence from the warrior should remove.\nThis done: lest he should follow on our quest,\nAnd so undo the web we vainly wove,\nHim we deprived of horse and arm, and we\nAre hither come together, as you see.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His cunning might have proved of good avail,\nFor Aquilant believed him easily;\nAnd, save in taking Gryphon's horse and mail,\nHe to the knight had done no injury;\nBut that he wrought so high the specious tale,\nAs manifested plainly, 'twas a lie.\nIn all 'twas perfect, save that he the dame\nHad for his sister vouched with whom he came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Aquilant had in Antioch chanced to know\nShe was his concubine, — well certified\nOf this by many, — and in furious glow\nExclaimed; \"Thou falsest robber, thou hast lied!\"\nAnd dealt, with that, the recreant such a blow,\nHe drove two grinders down his throat; then tied\n(Not sought Martano with his foe to cope)\nThe caitiff's arms behind him with a rope."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, though she for excuse tried many wiles,\nDid thus as well by Origille untrue;\nAnd till he reached Damascus' lofty piles,\nThem by town, street, or farm, behind him drew:\nAnd will a thousand times a thousand miles,\nWith sorrow and with suffering, drag the two,\nTill he his brother find; who, at his pleasure,\nMay vengeance to the guilty couple measure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Aquilant made squires and beasts as well\nReturn with him, and to Damascus came;\nAnd heard Renown, throughout the city, swell,\nPlying her ample wings, Sir Gryphon's name.\nHere, great and little — every one, could tell\n'Twas he that in the tourney won such fame,\nAnd had, by one that ill deserved his trust,\nBeen cheated of the honours of the just."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pointing him out to one another's sight,\nThe hostile people all Martano bayed;\n\"And is not this (they cried that ribald wight ) \n\nWho in another's spoils himself arrayed,\nAnd who the valour of a sleeping knight,\nWith his own shame and infamy o'erlaid?\nAnd this the woman of ungrateful mood,\nWho aids the wicked and betrays the good?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Others exclaimed, \"How fittingly combined,\nMarked with one stamp, and of one race are they!\"\nSome loudly cursed them, and some raved behind,\nWhile others shouted, \"Hang, burn, quarter, slay!\"\nThe throng to view them prest, with fury blind,\nAnd to the square before them made its way.\nThe monarch of the tidings was advised,\nAnd these above another kingdom prized."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Attended with few squires the Syrian king,\nAs then he chanced to be, came forth with speed,\nAnd with Sir Aquilant encountering,\nWho Gryphon had avenged with worthy deed,\nHim honoured with fair cheer, and home would bring,\nAnd in his palace lodged, as fitting meed;\nHaving the prisoned pair, with his consent,\nFirst in the bottom of a turret pent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither they go, where Gryphon from his bed\nHas not as yet, since he was wounded, stirred;\nWho at his brother's coming waxes red,\nSurmising well he of his case has heard:\nAnd after Aquilant his say had said,\nAnd him somedeal reproached, the three conferred\nAs to what penance to the wicked two,\nSo fallen into their hands, was justly due."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis Aquilant's, 'tis Norandino's will\nA thousand tortures shall their guerdon be:\nBut Gryphon, who the dame alone can ill\nExcuse, entreats for both impunity;\nAnd many matters urges with much skill.\nBut well is answered: and 'tis ruled, to flea\nMartano's body with the hangman's scourge,\nAnd only short of death his penance urge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bound is the wretch, but not 'mid grass and flower,\nWhose limbs beneath the hangman's lashes burn\nAll the next morn: they prison in the tower\nOrigille, till Lucina shall return;\nTo whom the counselling lords reserve the power\nTo speak the woman's sentence, mild or stern.\nHarboured, till Gryphon can bear arms, at court,\nAquilant fleets the time in fair disport."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The valiant Norandino could not choose\n(Made by such error temperate and wise),\nBut full of penitence and sorrow, muse,\nWith downcast spirit, and in mournful guise,\nOn having bid his men a knight misuse,\nWhom all should worthily reward and prize;\nSo that he, night and morning, in his thought,\nHow to content the injured warrior sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And he determined, in the public sight\nO' the city, guilty of that injury,\nWith all such honour as to perfect knight\nCould by a puissant monarch rendered be,\nHim with the glorious guerdon to requite,\nWhich had been ravished by such treachery:\nAnd hence, within a month, proclaimed the intent\nTo hold another solemn tournament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For which he made what stately preparation\nWas possible to make by sceptered king.\nHence Fame divulged the royal proclamation\nThroughout all Syria's land, with nimble wing,\nPhoenicia and Palestine; till the relation\nOf this in good Astolpho's ears did ring;\nWho, with the lord who ruled that land in trust,\nResolved he would be present at the just."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For a renowned and valiant cavalier\nHas the true history vaunted, Sansonnet,\nBy Roland christened, Charles (I said), the peer\nOver the Holy Land as ruler set:\nHe with the duke takes up his load, to steer\nThither, where Rumour speaks the champions met.\nSo that his ears, on all sides in the journey,\nAre filled with tidings of Damascus' tourney."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither the twain their way those countries through,\nBy easy stages and by slow, addrest,\nThat fresh upon the day of joust the two\nMight in Damascus-town set up their rest.\nWhen at the meeting of cross-ways they view\nA person, who, in movement and in vest,\nAppears to be a man, but is a maid;\nAnd marvellously fierce, in martial raid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa was the warlike virgin's name,\nAnd such her worth, she oft with naked brand\nHad pressed Orlando sore in martial game,\nAnd him who had Mount Alban in command;\nAnd ever, night and day, the armed dame\nScowered, here and there, by hill and plain, the land;\nHoping with errant cavalier to meet,\nAnd win immortal fame by glorious feat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Sansonnetto and the English knight\nShe sees approaching her, in warlike weed,\nWho seem two valiant warriors in her sight,\nAs of large bone, and nerved for doughty deed,\nOn them she fain would prove her martial might,\nAnd to defy the pair has moved her steed.\nWhen, eyeing the two warriors, now more near,\nMarphisa recognized the duke and peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His pleasing ways she did in mind retrace,\nWhen arms in far Catay with her he bore\nCalled him by name, nor would in iron case;\nRetain her hand, upraised the casque she wore,\nAnd him, advanced, to meet with glad embrace,\nThough, of all living dames and those of yore,\nThe proudest, she; nor with less courteous mien\nThe paladin salutes the martial queen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They questioned one another of their way;\nAnd when the duke has said (who first replied)\nThat he Damascus seeks, where to assay\nTheir virtuous deeds, all knights of valour tried\nThe Syrian king invites, in martial play, —\nThe bold Marphisa, at his hearing cried,\n(Ever to prove her warlike prowess bent)\n\"I will be with you at this tournament.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To have such a comrade either cavalier\nIs much rejoiced.  They to Damascus go,\nAnd in a suburb, of the city clear,\nAre lodged, upon the day before the show;\nAnd, till her aged lover, once so dear,\nAurora roused, their humble roof below,\nIn greater ease the weary warriors rested\nThan had they been in costly palace guested."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when the clear and lucid sun again\nIts shining glories all abroad had spread,\nThe beauteous lady armed, and warriors twain,\nHaving first couriers to the city sped,\nWho, when 'twas time, reported to the train,\nThat, to see truncheons split in contest dread,\nKing Norandine had come into the square\nIn which the cruel games appointed were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Straight to the city ride the martial band,\nAnd, through the high-street, to the crowded place;\nWhere, waiting for the royal signal, stand,\nRanged here and there, the knights of gentle race.\nThe guerdons destined to the conqueror's hand,\nIn that day's tourney, were a tuck and mace\nRichly adorned, and, with them, such a steed\nAs to the winning lord were fitting meed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Norandine, sure that, in the martial game,\nBoth prizes destined for the conquering knight,\nAs well as one and the other tourney's fame,\nMust be obtained by Gryphon, named the white,\nTo give him all that valiant man could claim,\nNor could he give the warrior less, with right,\nThe armour, guerdon of this final course\nPlaced with the tuck and mace and noble horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The arms which in the former joust the due\nOf valiant Gryphon were, who all had gained,\n(With evil profit, by the wretch untrue,\nMartan' usurped, who Gryphon's bearing feigned)\nTo be hung up on high in public view\nWith the rich-flourished tuck, the king ordained,\nAnd fastened at the saddle of the steed\nThe mace, that Gryphon might win either meed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But from effecting what he had intended\nHe was prevented by the warlike maid;\nWho late into the crowded square had wended,\nWith Sansonnet and England's duke arrayed,\nSeeing the arms of which I spoke suspended,\nShe straight agnized the harness she surveyed,\nOnce hers, and dear to her; as matters are\nEsteemed by us as excellent and rare;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though, as a hindrance, she upon the road\nHad left the arms, when, to retrieve her sword,\nShe from her shoulders slipt the ponderous load,\nAnd chased Brunello, worthy of the cord.\nMore to relate were labour ill bestowed,\nI deem, nor further of the tale record.\nEnough for me, by you 'tis understood,\nHow here she found anew her armour good."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "You shall take with you, when by manifest\nAnd certain tokens they by her were known,\nShe, for no earthly thing, the iron vest\nAnd weapons for a day would have foregone.\nShe thinks not if this mode or that be best\nTo have them, anxious to regain her own;\nBut t'wards the arms with hand extended hies,\nAnd without more regard takes down the prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And throwing some on earth, it chanced that more\nThan was her own she in her hurry took.\nThe Syrian king, who was offended sore,\nRaised war against her with a single look.\nFor ill the wrong his angered people bore,\nAnd, to avenge him, lance and falchion shook;\nRemembering not, on other day, how dear\nThey paid for scathing errant cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No wishful child more joyfully, 'mid all\nThe flowers of spring-tide, yellow, blue, and red,\nFinds itself, nor at concert or at ball\nDame beauteous and adorned, than 'mid the tread\nOf warlike steeds, and din of arms, and fall\nOf darts, and push of spears. — where blood is shed,\nAnd death is dealt, in the tumultuous throng, —\nSHE finds herself beyond all credence strong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She spurred her courser, and with lance in rest,\nImperious at the foolish rabble made,\nAnd — through the neck impaled or through the breast, —\nSome pierced, some prostrate at the encounter layed.\nNext this or that she with the falchion prest;\nThe head from one she severed with the blade,\nAnd from that other cleft: another sank,\nShort of right arm or left, or pierced in flank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bold Sansonnetto and Astolpho near,\nWho had, with her, their limbs in harness dight,\nThough they for other end in arms appear,\nSeeing the maid and crowd engaged in fight,\nFirst lower the helmet's vizor, next the spear,\nAnd with their lances charge the mob outright:\nThen bare their falchions, and, amid the crew,\nA passage with the trenchant weapons hew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The errant cavaliers who to that stage,\nTo joust, from different lands had made resort,\nSeeing them warfare with such fury wage,\nAnd into mourning changed the expected sport,\nBecause all knew not what had moved the rage\nOf the infuriate people in that sort,\nNor what the insult offered to the king,\nSuspended stood in doubt and wondering."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of these, some will the crowded rabble's band\n(Too late repentant of the feat befriend: ) \n\nThose, favouring not the natives of the land\nMore than the foreigners, to part them wend.\nOthers more wary, with their reins in hand,\nSit watching how the mischief is to end.\nGryphon and Aquilant are of the throng\nWhich hurry forward to avenge the wrong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The pair of warlike brethren witnessing\nThe monarch's drunken eyes with venom fraught,\nAnd having heard from many in the ring\nThe occasion which the furious strife had wrought,\nHimself no whit less injured than the king\nOf Syria's land, offended Gryphon thought.\nEach knight, in haste, supplied himself with spear,\nAnd thundering vengeance drove in full career."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On Rabican, pricked forth before his hand,\nValiant Astolpho, from the other bound,\nWith the enchanted lance of gold in hand,\nWhich at the first encounter bore to ground\nWhat knights he smote with it; and on the sand\nLaid Gryphon first; next Aquilant he found,\nAnd scarcely touched the border of his shield,\nEre he reversed the warrior on the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From lofty saddle Sansonnet o'erthrew,\nFamous for price and prowess, many a knight.\nTo the outlet of the square the mob withdrew;\nThe monarch raged with anger and despite.\nMeanwhile, of the first cuirass and the new\nPossest, as well as either helmet bright,\nMarphisa, when she all in flight discerned,\nConqueror towards her suburb-inn returned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sansonnet and Astolpho are not slow\nIn following t'wards the gate the martial maid,\n(The mob dividing all to let them go)\nAnd halt when they have reached the barricade.\nGryphon and Aquilant, who saw with woe\nThemselves on earth at one encounter laid,\nTheir drooping heads, opprest with shame, decline,\nNor dare appear before King Norandine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seizing their steeds and mounting, either son\nOf Oliver to seek their foemen went:\nWith many of his vassals too is gone\nThe king; on death or vengeance all intent.\nThe foolish rabble cry, \"Lay on, lay on.\"\nAnd stand at distance and await the event.\nGryphon arrived where the three friends had gained\nA bridge, and facing round the post maintained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, at the first approach, Astolpho knew,\nFor still the same device had been his wear,\nEven from the day he charmed Orrilo slew,\nHis horse, his arms the same: him not with care\nSir Gryphon had remarked, nor stedfast view,\nWhen late he jousted with him in the square:\nHe knows him here and greets; next prays him show\nWho the companions are that with him go;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And why they had those arms, without the fear\nOf Syria's king, pulled down, and to his slight.\nOf his champions England's cavalier,\nSir Gryphon courteously informed aright.\nBut little of those arms, pursued the peer,\nHe knew, which were the occasion of the fight;\nBut (for he thither with Marphisa came\nAnd Sansonnet had armed to aid the dame. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While he and Gryphon stood in colloquy,\nAquilant came, and knew Astolpho good,\nWhom he heard speaking with his brother nigh,\nAnd, though of evil purpose, changed his mood.\nOf Norandine's trooped many, these to spy;\nBut came not nigh the warriors where they stood:\nAnd seeing them in conference, stood clear,\nListening, in silence, and intent to hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Some one who hears Marphisa hold is there,\nFamed, through the world, for matchless bravery,\nHis courser turns, and bids the king have care,\nSave he would lose his Syrian chivalry,\nTo snatch his court, before all slaughtered are,\nFrom the hand of Death and of Tisiphone:\nFor that 'twas verily Marphisa, who\nHad borne away the arms in public view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As Norandine is told that name of dread,\nThrough the Levant so feared on every side,\nWhose mention made the hair on many a head\nBristle, though she was often distant wide.\nHe fears the ill may happen which is said,\nUnless against the mischief he provide;\nAnd hence his meiny, who have changed their ire\nAlready into fear, he bids retire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The sons of Oliver, on the other hand,\nWith Sansonnetto and the English knight,\nSo supplicate Marphisa, she her brand\nPuts up, and terminates the cruel fight;\nAnd to the monarch next, amid his brand,\nCries, proudly, \"Sir, I know not by what right\nThou wouldst this armour, not thine own, present\nTo him who conquers in thy tournament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Mine are these arms, which I, upon a day,\nLeft on the road which leads from Armeny,\nBecause, parforce a-foot, I sought to stay\nA robber, who had sore offended me.\nThe truth of this my ensign may display.\nWhich here is seen, if it be known to thee.\"\nWith that she on the plate which sheathed the breast\n(Cleft in three places showed a crown imprest. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To me this an Armenian merchant gave,\n'Tis true,\" replied the king, \"some days ago;\nAnd had you raised your voice, the arms to crave,\nYou should have had them, whether yours or no.\nFor, notwithstanding I to Gryphon gave\nThe armour, I so well his nature know,\nHe freely would resign the gift he earned,\nThat it by me to you might be returned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Your allegation needs not to persuade\nThese arms are yours — that they your impress bear;\nYour word suffices me, by me more weighed\nThan all that other witness could declare.\nTo grant them yours is but a tribute paid\nTo Virtue, worthy better prize to wear.\nNow have the arms, and let us make accord;\nAnd let some fairer gift the knight reward.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gryphon, who little had those arms at heart,\nBut much to satisfy the king was bent,\nReplied: \"You recompense enough impart,\nTeaching me how your wishes to content.\"\n— \"Here is my honour all at sake,\" apart,\n\"Meseemeth,\" said Marphisa, and forewent\nHer claim for Gryphon's sake, with courteous cheer;\nAnd, as his gift, in fine received the gear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To the city, their rejoicings to renew,\nIn love and peace they measured back their way.\nNext came the joust, of which the honour due,\nAnd prize was Sansonnet's; since from the fray\nAbstained Astolpho and the brethren two,\nAnd bold Marphisa, best of that array,\nLike faithful friends and good companions; fain\nThat Sansonnet the tourney's meed should gain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Eight days or ten in joy and triumph dwell\nThe knights with Norandine; but with such strong\nDesire of France the warriors' bosoms swell,\nWhich will not let them thence be absent long,\nThey take their leave.  Marphisa, who as well\nThither would go, departs the troop among.\nMarphisa had long time, with sword and lance,\nDesired to prove the paladins of France;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And make experiment, if they indeed\nSuch worth as is by Rumour voiced display.\nSansonnet leaves another, in his stead,\nThe city of Jerusalem to sway,\nAnd now these five, in chosen squadron speed,\nWho have few peers in prowess, on their way.\nDismist by Norandine, to Tripoli\nThey wend, and to the neighbouring haven hie."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And there a carack find, about to steer\nFor western countries, taking in her store:\nThey, with the patron, for themselves and gear,\nAnd horses, make accord; a seaman hoar\nOf Luna he: the heavens, on all sides clear,\nVouch many days' fair weather.  From the shore\nThey loose, with sky serene, and every sail\nOf the yare vessel stretched by favouring gale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The island of the amorous deity\nBreathed upon them an air, in her first port,\nWhich not alone to man does injury,\nBut moulders iron, and here life is short;\n— A marsh the cause, — and Nature certainly\nWrongs Famagosta, poisoning, in such sort,\nThat city with Constantia's fen malign,\nTo all the rest of Cyprus so benign."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The noxious scents that from the marish spring,\nAfter short sojourn there, compel their flight.\nThe barque to a south-easter every wing\nExtends, and circles Cyprus to the right,\nMakes Paphos' island next, and, anchoring,\nThe crew and warriors on the beach alight;\nThose to ship merchandize, and these, at leisure,\nTo view the laughing land of Love and Pleasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Inland six miles or seven from thence, a way\nScales, with an easy rise, a pleasant hill;\nWhich myrtle, orange, cedar-tree, and bay,\nAnd other perfumed plants by thousands fill;\nThyme, marjoram, crocus, rose, and lily gay\nFrom odoriferous leaf such sweets distill,\nThat they who sail the sea the fragrance bland,\nScent in each genial gale which blows from land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A fruitful rill, by limpid fountain fed,\nWaters, all round about, the fertile space.\nThe land of Venus truly may be said\nThat passing joyous and delightful place:\nFor every maid and wife, who there is bred,\nIs through the world beside, unmatched in grace:\nAnd Venus wills, till their last hour be tolled,\nThat Love should warm their bosoms, young and old."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas here they heard the same which they before\nOf the orc and of Lucina, erst had heard\nIn Syria; how she to return once more\nIn Nicosia, to her lord prepared.\nThence (a fair wind now blowing from the shore)\nHis bark for sea the ready Patron cleared,\nHawled up his anchor, westward turned the head\nOf the good ship, and all his canvas spread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To the north wind, which blew upon their right,\nStretching to seaward, they their sails untie:\nWhen lo! a south-south-wester, which seemed light,\nIn the beginning, while the sun was high,\nAnd afterwards increased in force t'wards night,\nRaised up the sea against them mountains high;\nWith such dread flashes, and loud peals of thunder,\nAs Heaven, to swallow all in fire, would sunder."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The clouds their gloomy veil above them strain,\nNor suffer sun or star to cheer the view.\nAbove the welkin roared, beneath the main;\nOn every side the wind and tempest grew;\nWhich, with sharp piercing cold and blinding rain,\nAfflicted sore the miserable crew.\nWhile aye descending night, with deeper shade,\nThe vext and fearful billows overlayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The sailors, in this war of wind and flood,\nWere prompt to manifest their vaunted art.\nOne blowing through the shrilling whistle stood,\nAnd with the signal taught the rest their part.\nOne clears the best bower anchor: one is good\nTo lower, this other to hawl home or start\nThe braces; one from deck the lumber cast,\nAnd this secured the tiller, that the mast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The cruel wind increased throughout the night,\nWhich grew more dismal and more dark than hell.\nThe wary Patron stood to sea outright,\nWhere he believed less broken was the swell;\nAnd turned his prow to meet, with ready sleight,\nThe buffets of the dreadful waves which fell;\nNever without some hope, that at day-break\nThe storm might lull, or else its fury slake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It lulls not, nor its fury slakes, but grown\nWilder, shows worse by day, — if this be day,\nWhich but by reckoning of the hours is known,\nAnd not by any cheering light or ray.\nNow, with more fear (his weaker hope o'erthrown).\nThe sorrowing Patron to the wind gives way,\nHe veers his barque before the cruel gale,\nAnd scowers the foaming sea with humble sail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While Fortune on the sea annoys this crew,\nShe grants those others small repose by land,\nThose left in France, who one another slew, —\nThe men of England and the paynim band.\nThese bold Rinaldo broke and overthrew;\nNor troops nor banners spread before him stand:\nI speak of him, who his Baiardo fleet\nHad spurred the gallant Dardinel to meet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The shield, of which Almontes' son was vain,\nThat of the quarters, good Rinaldo spied;\nAnd deemed him bold, and of a valiant strain,\nWho with Orlando's ensign dared to ride.\nApproaching nearer, this appeared more plain,\nWhen heaps of slaughtered men he round him eyed.\n\"Better it were,\" he cried, \"to overthrow\nThis evil plant, before it shoot and grow.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Each to retreat betook him, where the peer\nHis face directed, and large passage made.\nNor less the Saracens than faithful, clear\nThe way, so reverenced is Fusberta's blade.\nSave Dardinel, Mount Alban's cavalier,\nSaw none, nor he to chase his prey delayed.\nTo whom, \"He cast upon thee mickle care,\nPoor child, who of that buckler left thee heir."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I seek thee out to prove (if thou attend\nMy coming how thou keep'st the red and white, ) \n\nFor thou, save this from me thou canst defend,\nCanst ill defend it from Orlando's might.\"\nTo him the king: \"Now clearly comprehend,\nI what I bear, as well defend in fight;\nAnd I more honour hope than trouble dread\nFrom my paternal quartering, white and red."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Have thou no hope to make me fly, or yield\nTo thee my quarters, though a child I be;\nMy life shalt thou take from me, if my shield;\nBut I, in God, well hope the contrary.\n— This as it may! — shall none, in fighting field,\nSay that I ever shamed my ancestry.\"\nSo said, and grasping in his hand the sword,\nThe youthful king assailed Mount Alban's lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon all parts, a freezing fear goes through\nThe heart blood of each trembling paynim nigh,\nWhen they amazed the fierce Rinaldo view;\nWho charged the monarch with such enmity,\nAs might a lion, which a bullock, new\nTo stings of love, should in a meadow spy.\nThe Moor smote first, but fruitless was his task,\nWho beat in vain upon Mambrino's casque."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo smiled, and said: \"I'd have thee know\nIf I am better skilled to find the vein.\"\nHe spurs, and lets with that the bridle go,\nAnd a thrust pushes with such might and main,\n— A thrust against the bosom of his foe,\nThat at his back the blade appears again.\nForth issued blood and soul, and from his sell\nLifeless and cold the reeling body fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As languishes the flower of purple hue,\nWhich levelled by the passing ploughshare lies;\nOr as the poppy, overcharged with dew,\nIn garden droops its head in piteous wise:\nFrom life the leader of Zumara's crew\nSo past, his visage losing all its dyes;\nSo passed from life; and perished with their king,\nThe heart and hope of all his following."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As waters will sometime their course delay,\nStagnant, and penned in pool by human skill,\nWhich, when the opposing dyke is broke away,\nFall, and with mighty noise the country fill:\n'Twas so the Africans, who had some stay,\nWhile Dardinello valour did instil,\nFled here and there, dismayed on every side,\nWhen they him hurtling form his sell descried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Letting the flyers fly, of those who stand\nFirm in their place, Rinaldo breaks the array;\nAriodantes kills on every hand;\nWho ranks well nigh Rinaldo on that day.\nThese Leonetto's, those Zerbino's brand\nO'erturns, all rivals in the glorious fray.\nWell Charles and Oliver their parts have done,\nTurpin and Ogier, Guido and Salomon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In peril were the Moors, that none again\nShould visit Heatheness, that day opprest:\nBut that the wise and wary king of Spain,\nGathered, and from the field bore off the rest:\nTo sit down with his loss he better gain\nEsteemed, that here to hazard purse and vest:\nBetter some remnant of the host to save,\nThan bid whole squadrons stand and find a grave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He bids forthwith the Moorish ensigns be\nBorne to the camp, which fosse and rampart span.\nWith the bold monarch of Andology,\nThe valiant Portuguese, and Stordilan.\nHe sends to pray the king of Barbary,\nTo endeavour to retire, as best be can;\nWho will no little praise that day deserve,\nIf he his person and his place preserve."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That king, who deemed himself in desperate case,\nNor ever more Biserta hoped to see;\nFor, with so horrible and foul a face\nHe never Fortune had beheld, with glee\nHeard that Marsilius had contrived to place\nPart of his host in full security;\nAnd faced about his banners and bade beat\nThroughout his broken squadrons a retreat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But the best portion neither signal knew,\nNor listened to the drum or trumpet's sound.\nSo scared, so crowded is the wretched crew,\nThat many in Seine's neighbouring stream are drowned,\nAgramant, who would form the band anew,\n(With him Sobrino scowers the squadrons round; ) \n\nAnd with them every leader good combines\nTo bring the routed host within their lines."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But nought by sovereign or Sobrino done,\nWho, toiling, them with prayer or menace stirred,\nTo march, where their ill-followed flags are gone.\nCan bring (I say not all not even a third. ) \n\nSlaughtered or put to flight are two for one\nWho 'scapes, — nor he unharmed: among that herd,\nWounded is this behind, and that before,\nAnd wearied, one and all, and harassed sore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And even within their lines, in panic sore,\nThey by the Christian bands are held in chase;\nAnd of all needful matters little store\nWas made there, for provisioning the place.\nCharlemagne wisely by the lock before\nWould grapple Fortune, when she turned her face,\nBut that dark night upon the field descended,\nAnd hushed all earthly matters and suspended:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By the Creator haply hastened, who\nWas moved to pity for the works he made.\nThe blood in torrents ran the country through,\nFlooding the roads: while on the champaign laid\nWere eighty thousand of the paynim crew,\nCut off that day by the destroying blade:\nLast trooped from caverns, at the midnight hour,\nVillain and wolf to spoil them and devour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Charles returns no more within the town,\nBut camps without the city, opposite\nThe Moor's cantonments, and bids up and down,\nAnd round, high-piled and frequent watch-fires light.\nThe paynim fashions ditch and bastion,\nRampart and mine, and all things requisite;\nVisits his outposts and his guards alarms,\nNor all the livelong night puts off his arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That livelong night the foes, throughout their tents,\nAs insecure and with their scathe deprest,\nPoured tears, and uttered murmurs and laments;\nBut, as they could, their sounds of woe supprest.\nOne grief for slaughtered friends or kindred vents;\nSome are by sorrows of their own distrest,\nAs wounded or as ill at ease; but more\nTremble at mischief which they deem in store."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two Moors amid the paynim army were,\nFrom stock obscure in Ptolomita grown;\nOf whom the story, an example rare\nOf constant love, is worthy to be known:\nMedoro and Cloridan were named the pair;\nWho, whether Fortune pleased to smile or frown,\nServed Dardinello with fidelity,\nAnd late with him to France had crost the sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of nimble frame and strong was Cloridane,\nThroughout his life a follower of the chase.\nA cheek of white, suffused with crimson grain,\nMedoro had, in youth a pleasing grace.\nNor bound on that emprize, 'mid all the train,\nWas there a fairer or more jocund face.\nCrisp hair he had of gold, and jet-black eyes:\nAnd seemed an angel lighted from the skies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These two were posted on a rampart's height,\nWith more to guard the encampment from surprise,\nWhen 'mid the equal intervals, at night,\nMedoro gazed on heaven with sleepy eyes.\nIn all his talk, the stripling, woful wight,\nHere cannot choose, but of his lord devise,\nThe royal Dardinel; and evermore\nHim, left unhonoured on the field, deplore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then, turning to his mate, cries: \"Cloridane,\nI cannot tell thee what a cause of woe\nIt is to me, my lord upon the plain\nShould lie, unworthy food for wolf or crow!\nThinking how still to me he was humane,\nMeseems, if in his honour I forego\nThis life of mine, for favours so immense\nI shall but make a feeble recompense."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That he may lack not sepulture, will I\nGo forth, and seek him out among the slain;\nAnd haply God may will that none shall spy\nWhere Charles's camp lies hushed.  Do thou remain;\nThat, if my death be written in the sky,\nThou may'st the deed be able to explain.\nSo that if Fortune foil so fear a feat,\nThe world, through Fame, my loving heart may weet.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Amazed was Cloridan a child should show\nSuch heart, such love, and such fair loyalty;\nAnd fain would make the youth his though forego,\nWhom he held passing dear; but fruitlessly\nWould move his stedfast purpose; for such woe\nWill neither comforted nor altered be.\nMedoro is disposed to meet his doom,\nOr to enclose his master in the tomb."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seeing that nought would bend him, nought would move,\n\"I too will go,\" was Cloridan's reply,\n\"In such a glorious act myself will prove;\nAs well such famous death I cover, I:\nWhat other thing is left me, here above,\nDeprived of thee, Medoro mine?  To die\nWith thee in arms is better, on the plain,\nThan afterwards of grief, should'st thou be slain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And thus resolved, disposing in their place\nTheir guard's relief, depart the youthful pair,\nLeave fosse and palisade, and, in small space,\nAre among ours, who watch with little care:\nWho, for they little fear the paynim race,\nSlumber with fires extinguished everywhere.\n'Mid carriages and arms, they lie supine\nUp to the eyes, immersed in sleep and wine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A moment Cloridano stopt and cried:\n\"Not to be lost are opportunities.\nThis troop, by whom my master's blood was shed,\nMedoro, ought not I to sacrifice?\nDo thou, lest any one this way be led,\nWatch everywhere about, with ears and eyes.\nFor a wide way, amid the hostile horde,\nI offer here to make thee with my sword.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said he, and his talk cut quickly short,\nComing where learned Alpheus slumbered nigh;\nWho had the year before sought Charles's court,\nIn medicine, magic, and astrology\nWell versed; but now in art found small-support,\nOr rather found that it was all a lie.\nHe had foreseen, that he his long-drawn life\nShould finish in the bosom of his wife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And now the Saracen with wary view\nHas pierced his weasand with the pointed sword.\nFour others he neat that Diviner, slew,\nNor gave the wretches time to say a word.\nSir Turpin in his story tells not who,\nAnd Time had of their names effaced record.\nPalidon of Moncalier next he speeds;\nOne who securely sleeps between two steeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next came the warrior where, with limbs outspread,\nPillowed on barrel, lay the wretched Gryll:\nThis he had drained, and undisturbed by dread,\nHoped to enjoy a peaceful sleep and still.\nThe daring Saracen lopt off his head,\nBlood issues from the tap-hole, with a rill\nOf wine; and he, well drenched with many a can,\nDreams that he drinks, dispatched by Cloridan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next Gryll, Andropono and Conrad hight,\nA Greek and German, at two thrusts he gored,\nWho in the air had past large part of night\nWith dice and goblet; blest it at that board\nThey still had watched, till, clothed in amber light,\nThe radiant sun had traversed Indus' ford!\nBut mortals Destiny would set at nought\nIf every wight futurity were taught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As, in full fold, a lion long unfed,\nWhom wasting famine had made lean and spare,\nDevours and rends, and swallows, and lays dead\nThe feeble flock, which at his mercy are;\nSo, in their sleep, the cruel paynim bled\nOur host, and made wide slaughter everywhere:\nNor blunted was the young Medoro's sword,\nBut he disdained to smite the ignoble horde."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He to Labretto's duke, leaving those dead,\nHad come, who slumbered with a gentle mate,\nEach clasping each so closely in their bed,\nThat air between them could not penetrate.\nFrom both Medoro cleanly lopt the head.\nOh!  blessed way of death!  oh!  happy fate!\nFor 'tis my trust, that as their bodies, so\nTheir souls embracing to their bourne shall go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Malindo, with Andalico, he slew,\nHis brother, sons to the earl of Flanders they:\nTo whom has bearings (each to arms was new)\nCharles had the lilies given; because that day\nThe monarch had beheld the valiant two\nWith crimsoned staves, returning from the fray;\nAnd them with lands in Flanders vowed to glad;\nAnd would, but that Medoro this forbad."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rearing the insidious blade, the pair are near\nThe place, where round King Charles' pavilion\nAre tented warlike paladin and peer,\nGuarding the side that each is camped upon.\nWhen in good time the paynims backward steer,\nAnd sheathe their swords, the impious slaughter done;\nDeeming impossible, in such a number,\nBut they must light on one who does not slumber."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And though they might escape well charged with prey,\nTo save themselves they think sufficient gain.\nThither by what he deems the safest way\n(Medoro following him went Cloridane ) \n\nWhere, in the field, 'mid bow and falchion, lay,\nAnd shield and spear, in pool of purple stain,\nWealthy and poor, the king and vassal's corse,\nAnd overthrown the rider and his horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The horrid mixture of the bodies there\nWhich heaped the plain where roved these comrades sworn,\nMight well have rendered vain their faithful care\nAmid the mighty piles, till break of morn,\nHad not the moon, at young Medoro's prayer,\nOut of a gloomy cloud put forth her horn.\nMedoro to the heavens upturns his eyes\nTowards the moon, and thus devoutly cries:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O holy goddess!  whom our fathers well\nHave styled as of a triple form, and who\nThy sovereign beauty dost in heaven, and hell,\nAnd earth, in many forms reveal; and through\nThe greenwood holt, of beast and monster fell,\n— A huntress bold — the flying steps pursue,\nShow where my king, amid so many lies,\nWho did, alive, thy holy studies prize.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the youth's prayer from parted cloud outshone\n(Were it the work of faith or accident)\nThe moon, as fair, as when Endymion\nShe circled in her naked arms: with tent,\nChristian or Saracen, was Paris-town\nSeen in that gleam, and hill and plain's extent.\nWith these Mount Martyr and Mount Levy's height,\nThis on the left, and that upon the right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The silvery splendor glistened yet more clear,\nThere where renowned Almontes' son lay dead.\nFaithful Medoro mourned his master dear,\nWho well agnized the quartering white and red,\nWith visage bathed in many a bitter tear\n(For he a rill from either eyelid shed),\nAnd piteous act and moan, that might have whist\nThe winds, his melancholy plaint to list;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But with a voice supprest: not that he aught\nRegards if any one the noise should hear,\nBecause he of his life takes any thought;\nOf which loathed burden he would fain be clear;\nBut, lest his being heard should bring to nought\nThe pious purpose which has brought them here.\nThe youths the king upon their shoulders stowed;\nAnd so between themselves divide the load."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hurrying their steps, they hastened, as they might,\nUnder the cherished burden they conveyed;\nAnd now approaching was the lord of light,\nTo sweep from heaven the stars, from earth the shade.\nWhen good Zerbino, he, whose valiant sprite\nWas ne'er in time of need by sleep down-weighed,\nFrom chasing Moors all night, his homeward way\nWas taking to the camp at dawn of day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He has with him some horsemen in his train,\nThat from afar the two companions spy.\nExpecting thus some spoil or prize to gain,\nThey, every one, towards that quarter hie.\n\"Brother, behoves us,\" cried young Cloridane,\n\"To cast away the load we bear, and fly:\nFor 'twere a foolish thought (might well be said)\nTo lose two living men, to save one dead:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And dropt the burden, weening his Medore\nHad done the same by it, upon his side:\nBut that poor boy, who loved his master more,\nHis shoulders to the weight, alone, applied;\nCloridan hurrying with all haste before,\nDeeming him close behind him or beside;\nWho, did he know his danger, him to save\nA thousand deaths, instead of one, would brave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those horsemen, with intent to make the two\nYield themselves prisoners to their band, or die,\nSome here, some there, disperse the champaign through,\nAnd every pass and outlet occupy.\nThe captain, little distant from his crew,\nIs keener than the rest the chase to ply;\nAnd, when he sees them hurrying in such guise,\nIs certain that the twain are enemies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of old an ancient forest clothed that lair,\nOf trees and underwood a tangled maze;\nOf salvage beasts alone the wild repair,\nAnd, like a labyrinth, full of narrow ways:\nHere from the boughs such shelter hope the pair\nAs may conceal them well from hostile gaze.\nBut him I shall expect who loves the rhyme,\nTo listen to my tale some other time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 19"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Medoro, by Angelica's quaint hand,\nIs healed, and weds, and bears her to Catay.\nAt length Marphisa, with the chosen band,\nAfter long suffering, makes Laiazzi's bay.\nGuido the savage, bondsman in the land,\nWhich impious women rule with civil sway,\nWith Marphisa strives in single fight,\nAnd lodges her and hers at full of night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By whom he is beloved can no one know,\nWho on the top of Fortune's wheel is seated;\nSince he, by true and faithless friends, with show\nOf equal faith, in glad estate is greeted.\nBut, should felicity be changed to woe,\nThe flattering multitude is turned and fleeted!\nWhile he who loves his master from his heart,\nEven after death performs his faithful part."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Were the heart seen as is the outward cheer,\nHe who at court is held in sovereign grace,\nAnd he that to his lord is little dear,\nWith parts reversed, would fill each other's place;\nThe humble man the greater would appear,\nAnd he, now first, be hindmost in the race.\nBut be Medoro's faithful story said,\nThe youth who loved his lord, alive or dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The closest path, amid the forest gray,\nTo save himself, pursued the youth forlorn;\nBut all his schemes were marred by the delay\nOf that sore weight upon his shoulders born.\nThe place he knew not, and mistook the way,\nAnd hid himself again in sheltering thorn.\nSecure and distant was his mate, that through\nThe greenwood shade with lighter shoulders flew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So far was Cloridan advanced before,\nHe heard the boy no longer in the wind;\nBut when he marked the absence of Medore,\nIt seemed as if his heart was left behind.\n\"Ah!  how was I so negligent,\" (the Moor\nExclaimed \"so far beside myself, and blind, ) \n\nThat I, Medoro, should without thee fare,\nNor know when I deserted thee or where?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, in the wood he disappears,\nPlunging into the maze with hurried pace;\nAnd thither, whence he lately issued, steers,\nAnd, desperate, of death returns in trace.\nCries and the tread of steeds this while he hears,\nAnd word and the tread of foemen, as in chase:\nLastly Medoro by his voice is known,\nDisarmed, on foot, 'mid many horse, alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A hundred horsemen who the youth surround,\nZerbino leads, and bids his followers seize\nThe stripling: like a top, the boy turns round\nAnd keeps him as he can: among the trees,\nBehind oak, elm, beech, ash, he takes his ground,\nNor from the cherished load his shoulders frees.\nWearied, at length, the burden he bestowed\nUpon the grass, and stalked about his load."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in her rocky cavern the she-bear,\nWith whom close warfare Alpine hunters wage,\nUncertain hangs about her shaggy care,\nAnd growls in mingled sound of love and rage,\nTo unsheath her claws, and blood her tushes bare,\nWould natural hate and wrath the beast engage;\nLove softens her, and bids from strife retire,\nAnd for her offspring watch, amid her ire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Cloridan who to aid him knows not how,\nAnd with Medoro willingly would die,\nBut who would not for death this being forego,\nUntil more foes than one should lifeless lie,\nAmbushed, his sharpest arrow to his bow\nFits, and directs it with so true an eye,\nThe feathered weapon bores a Scotchman's brain,\nAnd lays the warrior dead upon the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Together, all the others of the band\nTurned thither, whence was shot the murderous reed;\nMeanwhile he launched another from his stand,\nThat a new foe might by the weapon bleed,\nWhom (while he made of this and that demand,\nAnd loudly questioned who had done the deed)\nThe arrow reached — transfixed the wretch's throat,\nAnd cut his question short in middle note."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino, captain of those horse, no more\nCan at the piteous sight his wrath refrain;\nIn furious heat, he springs upon Medore,\nExclaiming, \"Thou of this shalt bear the pain.\"\nOne hand he in his locks of golden ore\nEnwreaths, and drags him to himself amain;\nBut, as his eyes that beauteous face survey,\nTakes pity on the boy, and does not slay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him the stripling turns, with suppliant cry,\nAnd, \"By thy God, sir knight,\" exclaims, \"I pray,\nBe not so passing cruel, nor deny\nThat I in earth my honoured king may lay:\nNo other grace I supplicate, nor I\nThis for the love of life, believe me, say.\nSo much, no longer, space of life I crave.\nAs may suffice to give my lord a grave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if you needs must feed the beast and bird,\nLike Theban Creon, let their worst be done\nUpon these limbs; so that by me interred\nIn earth be those of good Almontes' son.\"\nMedoro thus his suit, with grace, preferred,\nAnd words — to move a mountain, and so won\nUpon Zerbino's mood, to kindness turned,\nWith love and pity he all over burned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while, a churlish horseman of the band,\nWho little deference for his lord confest,\nHis lance uplifting, wounded overhand\nThe unhappy suppliant in his dainty breast.\nZerbino, who the cruel action scanned,\nWas deeply stirred, the rather that, opprest\nAnd livid with the blow the churl had sped,\nMedoro fell as he was wholly dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So grieved Zerbino, with such wrath was stung,\n\"Not unavenged shalt thou remain,\" he cries;\nThen full of evil will in fury sprung\nUpon the author of the foul emprize.\nBut he his vantage marks, and, from among\nThe warriors, in a moment slips and flies.\nCloridan who beholds the deed, at sight\nOf young Medoro's fall, springs forth to fight;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And casts away his bow, and, 'mid the band\nOf foemen, whirls his falchion, in desire\nRather of death, than hoping that his hand\nMay snatch a vengeance equal to his ire.\nAmid so many blades, he views the sand\nTinged with his blood, and ready to expire,\nAnd feeling he the sword no more can guide,\nLets himself drop by his Medoro's side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Scots pursue their chief, who pricks before,\nThrough the deep wood, inspired by high disdain,\nWhen he has left the one and the other Moor,\nThis dead, that scarce alive, upon the plain.\nThere for a mighty space lay young Medore,\nSpouting his life-blood from so large a vein,\nHe would have perished, but that thither made\nA stranger, as it chanced, who lent him aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By chance arrived a damsel at the place,\nWho was (though mean and rustic was her wear)\nOf royal presence and of beauteous face,\nAnd lofty manners, sagely debonair:\nHer have I left unsung so long a space,\nThat you will hardly recognise the fair.\nAngelica, in her (if known not scan, ) \n\nThe lofty daughter of Catay's great khan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Angelica, when she had won again\nThe ring Brunello had from her conveyed,\nSo waxed in stubborn pride and haught disdain,\nShe seemed to scorn this ample world, and strayed\nAlone, and held as cheap each living swain,\nAlthough, amid the best, by Fame arrayed:\nNor brooked she to remember a galant\nIn Count Orlando or king Sacripant;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And above every other deed repented,\nThat good Rinaldo she had loved of yore;\nAnd that to look so low she had consented,\n(As by such choice dishonoured grieved her sore. ) \n\nLove, hearing this, such arrogance resented,\nAnd would the damsel's pride endure no more.\nWhere young Medoro lay he took his stand,\nAnd waited her, with bow and shaft in hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When fair Angelica the stripling spies,\nNigh hurt to death in that disastrous fray,\nWho for his king, that there unsheltered lies,\nMore sad than for his own misfortune lay,\nShe feels new pity in her bosom rise,\nWhich makes its entry in unwonted way.\nTouched was her haughty heart, once hard and curst,\nAnd more when he his piteous tale rehearsed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And calling back to memory her art,\nFor she in Ind had learned chirurgery,\n(Since it appears such studies in that part\nWorthy of praise and fame are held to be,\nAnd, as an heir-loom, sires to sons impart,\nWith little aid of books, the mystery)\nDisposed herself to work with simples' juice,\nTill she in him should healthier life produce;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And recollects a herb had caught her sight\nIn passing hither, on a pleasant plain,\nWhat (whether dittany or pancy hight)\nI know not; fraught with virtue to restrain\nThe crimson blood forth-welling, and of might\nTo sheathe each perilous and piercing pain,\nShe found it near, and having pulled the weed,\nReturned to seek Medoro on the mead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Returning, she upon a swain did light,\nWho was on horseback passing through the wood.\nStrayed from the lowing herd, the rustic wight\nA heifer, missing for two days, pursued.\nHim she with her conducted, where the might\nOf the faint youth was ebbing with his blood:\nWhich had the ground about so deeply dyed,\nLife was nigh wasted with the gushing tide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Angelica alights upon the ground,\nAnd he her rustic comrade, at her hest.\nShe hastened 'twixt two stones the herb to pound,\nThen took it, and the healing juice exprest:\nWith this did she foment the stripling's wound,\nAnd, even to the hips, his waist and breast;\nAnd (with such virtue was the salve endued)\nIt stanched his life-blood, and his strength renewed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And into him infused such force again,\nThat he could mount the horse the swain conveyed;\nBut good Medoro would not leave the plain\nTill he in earth had seen his master laid.\nHe, with the monarch, buried Cloridane,\nAnd after followed whither pleased the maid,\nWho was to stay with him, by pity led,\nBeneath the courteous shepherd's humble shed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor would the damsel quit the lowly pile\n(So she esteemed the youth till he was sound; ) \n\nSuch pity first she felt, when him erewhile\nShe saw outstretched and bleeding on the ground.\nTouched by his mien and manners next, a file\nShe felt corrode her heart with secret wound;\nShe felt corrode her heart, and with desire,\nBy little and by little warmed, took fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The shepherd dwelt, between two mountains hoar,\nIn goodly cabin, in the greenwood shade,\nWith wife and children; and, short time before,\nThe brent-new shed had builded in the glade.\nHere of his griesly wound the youthful Moor\nWas briefly healed by the Catayan maid;\nBut who in briefer space, a sorer smart\nThan young Medoro's, suffered at her heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A wound far wider and which deeper lies,\nNow in her heart she feels, from viewless bow;\nWhich from the boy's fair hair and beauteous eyes\nHad the winged archer dealt: a sudden glow\nShe feels, and still the flames increasing rise;\nYet less she heeds her own than other's woe:\n— Heeds not herself, and only to content\nThe author of her cruel ill is bent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her ill but festered and increased the more\nThe stripling's wounds were seen to heal and close:\nThe youth grew lusty, while she suffered sore,\nAnd, with new fever parched, now burnt, now froze:\nFrom day to day in beauty waxed Medore:\nShe miserably wasted; like the snow's\nUnseasonable flake, which melts away\nExposed, in sunny place, to scorching ray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, if of vain desire will not die,\nMust help herself, nor yet delay the aid.\nAnd she in truth, her will to satisfy,\nDeemed 'twas no time to wait till she was prayed.\nAnd next of shame renouncing every tye,\nWith tongue as bold as eyes, petition made,\nAnd begged him, haply an unwitting foe,\nTo sheathe the suffering of that cruel blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "O Count Orlando, O king of Circassy,\nSay what your valour has availed to you!\nSay what your honour boots, what goodly fee\nRemunerates ye both, for service true!\nSirs, show me but a single courtesy,\nWith which she ever graced ye, — old or new, —\nAs some poor recompense, desert, or guerdon,\nFor having born so long so sore a burden!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh! couldst thou yet again to life return,\nHow hard would this appear, O Agricane!\nIn that she whilom thee was wont to spurn,\nWith sharp repulse and insolent disdain.\nO Ferrau, O ye thousand more, forlorn,\nUnsung, who wrought a thousand feats in vain\nFor this ungrateful fair, what pain 'twould be\nCould you within his arms the damsel see!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To pluck, as yet untouched, the virgin rose,\nAngelica permits the young Medore.\nWas none so blest as in that garden's close\nYet to have set his venturous foot before.\nThey holy ceremonies interpose,\nSomedeal to veil — to gild — the matter o'er.\nYoung Love was bridesman there the tie to bless,\nAnd for brideswoman stood the shepherdess."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the low shed, with all solemnities,\nThe couple made their wedding as they might;\nAnd there above a month, in tranquil guise,\nThe happy lovers rested in delight.\nSave for the youth the lady has no eyes,\nNor with his looks can satisfy her sight.\nNor yet of hanging on his neck can tire,\nOf feel she can content her fond desire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beauteous boy is with her night and day,\nDoes she untent herself, or keep the shed.\nMorning or eve they to some meadow stray,\nNow to this bank, and to that other led:\nHaply, in cavern harboured, at mid-day,\nGrateful as that to which Aeneas fled\nWith Dido, when the tempest raged above,\nThe faithful witness to their secret love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Amid such pleasures, where, with tree o'ergrown,\nRan stream, or bubbling fountain's wave did spin,\nOn bark or rock, if yielding were the stone,\nThe knife was straight at work or ready pin.\nAnd there, without, in thousand places lone,\nAnd in as many places graved, within,\nMEDORO and ANGELICA were traced,\nIn divers cyphers quaintly interlaced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she believed they had prolonged their stay\nMore than enow, the damsel made design\nIn India to revisit her Catay,\nAnd with its crown Medoro's head entwine.\nShe had upon her wrist an armlet, gay\nWith costly gems, in witness and in sign\nOf love to her by Count Orlando borne,\nAnd which the damsel for long time had worn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On Ziliantes, hid beneath the wave,\nThis Morgue bestowed; and from captivity\nThe youth (restored to Monodantes grave,\nHis ancient sire, through Roland's chivalry)\nTo Roland in return the bracelet gave:\nRoland, a lover, deigned the gorgeous fee\nTo wear, with the intention to convey\nThe present to his queen, of whom I say."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No love which to the paladin she bears,\nBut that it costly is and wrought with care,\nThis to Angelica so much endears,\nThat never more esteemed was matter rare:\nThis she was suffered, in THE ISLE OF TEARS,\nI know not by what privilege, to wear,\nWhen, naked, to the whale exposed for food\nBy that inhospitable race and rude."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, not possessing wherewithal to pay\nThe kindly couple's hospitality,\nServed by them in their cabin, from the day\nShe there was lodged, with such fidelity,\nUnfastened from her arm the bracelet gay,\nAnd bade them keep it for her memory.\nDeparting hence the lovers climb the side\nOf hills, which fertile France from Spain divide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within Valencia or Barcelona's town\nThe couple thought a little to remain,\nUntil some goodly ship should make her boun\nTo loose for the Levant: as so the twain\nJourney, beneath Gerona, — coming down\nThose mountains — they behold the subject main;\nAnd keeping on their left the beach below,\nBy beaten track to Barcelona go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But, ere they there arrive, a crazed wight\nThey find, extended on the outer shore;\nWho is bedaubed like swine, in filthy plight,\nAnd smeared with mud, face, reins, and bosom o'er'\nHe comes upon them, as a dog in spite\nSwiftly assails the stranger at the door;\nAnd is about to do the lovers scorn,\nBut to the bold Marphisa I return —"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa, Astolpho, Gryphon, Aquilant.\nOf these and of the others will I tell:\nWho, death before their eyes, the vext Levant\nTraverse, and ill resist the boisterous swell.\nWhile aye more passing proud and arrogant,\nWaxes in rage and threat the tempest fell.\nAnd now three days the angry gale has blown,\nNor signal of abatement yet has shown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Waves lifted by the waxing tempest start\nCastle and flooring, and, if yet there be\nAught standing left in any other part,\n'Tis cut away and cast into the sea.\nHere, pricking out their course upon the chart,\nOne by a lantern does his ministry,\nUpon a sea-chest propt; another wight\nIs busied in the well by torch's light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This one beneath the poop, beneath the prow\nThat other, stands to watch the ebbing sand;\nAnd (each half-glass run out returns to know ) \n\nWhat way the ship has made, and towards what land.\nThence all to speak their different thoughts, below,\nTo midships make resort, with chart in hand;\nThere where the mariners, assembled all,\nAre met in council, at the master's call."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One says: \"Abreast of Limisso are we\nAmong the shoals\" — and by his reckoning, nigh\nThe rocks of Tripoli and bark must be,\nWhere shipwrecked, for the most part, vessels lie.\nAnother: \"We are lost on Sataly,\nWhose coast makes many patrons weep and sigh.\"\nAccording to their judgment, all suggest\nTheir treasons, each with equal dread opprest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "More spitefully the wind on the third day\nBlows, and the sea more yeasty billows rears:\nThe fore-mast by the first is borne away,\nThe rudder by the last, with him who steers.\nBetter than steel that man will bide the assay,\n— Of marble breast — who has not now his fears.\nMarphisa, erst so confident 'mid harms,\nDenied not but that day she felt alarms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A pilgrimage is vowed to Sinai,\nTo Cyprus and Gallicia, and to Rome,\nEttino, and other place of sanctity,\nIf such is named, and to the holy tomb.\nMeanwhile, above the sea and near the sky,\nThe bark is tost, with shattered plank and boom;\nFrom which the crew had cut, in her distress,\nThe mizenmast, to make her labour less."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They bale and chest and all their heavy lumber\nCast overboard, from poop, and prow, and side;\nAnd every birth and cabin disencumber\nOf merchandize, to feed the greedy tide.\nWater to water others of the number\nRendered, by whom the spouting pumps were plied.\nThis in the hold bestirs himself, where'er\nPlanks opened by the beating sea appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They in this trouble, in this woe, remained\nFor full four days; and helpless was their plight,\nAnd a full victory the sea had gained,\nIf yet a little had endured its spite:\nBut them with hope of clearer sky sustained\nThe wished appearance of St. Elmo's light,\nWhich (every spar was gone descending glowed ) \n\nUpon a boat, which in the prow was stowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When, flaming, they the beauteous light surveyed,\nAll those aboard kneeled down in humble guise,\nAnd Heaven for peace and for smooth water prayed,\nWith trembling voices and with watery eyes.\nNor longer waxed the storm, which had dismayed,\nTill then enduring in such cruel wise.\nNorth-wester or cross-wind no longer reigns;\nBut tyrant of the sea the south remains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This on the sea remained so passing strong,\nAnd from its sable mouth so fiercely blew,\nAnd bore with it so swift a stream and strong\nOf the vext waters, that it hurried through\nTheir tumbling waves the shattered bark along,\nFaster than gentle falcon ever flew;\nAnd sore the patron feared, to the world's brink\nIt would transport his bark, or wreck or sink."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For this the master finds a remedy,\nWho bids them cast out spars, and veer away\nA line which holds this float, and as they flee,\nSo, by two-thirds, their furious course delay.\nThis counsel boots, and more the augury\nFrom him whose lights upon the gunwale play.\nThis saves the vessel, haply else undone;\nAnd makes her through the sea securely run."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They, driven on Syria, in Laiazzo's bay\nA mighty city rise; so nigh at hand,\nThat they can from the vessel's deck survey\nTwo castles, which the port within command.\nPale turns the patron's visage with dismay,\nWhen he perceives what  is the neighbouring land,\nWho will not to the port for shelter hie,\nNor yet can keep the open sea, nor fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They cannot fly, nor yet can keep the sea;\nFor mast and yards are gone, and by the stroke\nOf the huge billows beating frequently,\nLoosened is plank, and beam and timber broke:\nAnd certain death to make the port would be,\nOr to be doomed to a perpetual yoke.\nFor each is made a slave, or sentenced dead,\nThither by evil Chance or Error led."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sore dangerous 'twas to doubt; lest hostile band\nShould sally from the puissant town in sight,\nWith armed barks, and upon theirs lay hand,\nIn evil case for sea, and worse for fight.\nWhat time the patron knows not what command\nTo give, of him inquires the English knight\nWhat kept his mind suspended in that sort,\nAnd why at first he had not made the port."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him relates the patron how a crew\nOf murderous women tenanted that shore,\nWhich, by their ancient law, enslave or slew\nAll those whom Fortune to this kingdom bore;\nAnd that he only could such for eschew\nThat in the lists ten champions overbore,\nAnd having this achieved, the following night\nIn bed should with ten damsels take delight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And if he brings to end the former feat,\nBut afterwards the next unfinished leaves,\nThey kill him, and as slaves his following treat,\nCondemned to delve their land or keep their beeves.\n— If for the first and second labour meet —\nHe liberty for all his band achieves,\nNot for himself; who there must stay and wed\nTen wives by him selected for his bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So strange a custom of the neighbouring strand\nWithout a laugh Astolpho cannot hear;\nSansonet and Marphisa, near at hand,\nNext Aquilant, and he, his brother dear,\nArrive: to them the patron who from land\nAye keeps aloof, explains the cause of fear,\nAnd cries: \"I liefer in the sea would choke,\nThan here of servitude endure the yoke.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The sailors by the patron's rede abide,\nAnd all the passengers affrighted sore;\nSave that Marphisa took the other side\nWith hers, who deemed that safer was the shore\nThan sea, which raging round them, far and wide,\nThan a hundred thousand swords dismayed them more.\nThem little this, or other place alarms,\nSo that they have but power to wield their arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warriors are impatient all to land:\nBut boldest is of these the English peer;\nKnowing how soon his horn will clear the strand,\nWhen the scared foe its pealing sound shall hear.\nTo put into the neighbouring port this band\nDesires, and are at strife with those who fear.\nAnd they who are the strongest, in such sort\nCompel the patron, that he makes the port."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already when their bark was first espied\nAt sea, within the cruel city's view,\nThey had observed a galley, well supplied\nWith practised mariners and numerous crew\n(While them uncertain counsels did divide)\nMake for their wretched ship, the billows through:\nHer lofty prow to their short stern and low\nThese lash, and into port the vessel tow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They thitherward were worked with warp and oar,\nRather than with assistance of the sail;\nSince to lay starboard course or larboard more,\nNo means were left them by the cruel gale.\nAgain their rugged rhind the champions wore,\nGirding the faithful falchion with the mail,\nAnd with unceasing hope of comfort fed\nMaster and mariners opprest with dread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Like a half-moon, projected from the beach,\nMore than four miles about, the city's port;\nSix hundred paces deep; and crowning each\nHorn of the circling haven, was a fort;\nOn every side, secure from storm or breach,\n(Save only from the south, a safe resort)\nIn guise of theatre the town extended\nAbout it, and a hill behind ascended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner there the harboured ship was seen\n(The news had spread already through the land)\nThan thitherward, with martial garb and mien,\nSix thousand women trooped, with bow in hand;\nAnd, to remove all hope of flight, between\nOne castle and the other, drew a band;\nAnd with strong chains and barks the port enclosed;\nWhich ever, for that use, they kept disposed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A dame, as the Cumean sybil gray,\nOr Hector's ancient mother of renown,\nMade call the patron out, and bade him say,\nIf they their lives were willing to lay down;\nOr were content beneath the yoke to stay,\nAccording to the custom of the town,\n— One of two evils they must choose, — be slain,\nOr captives, one and all, must there remain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'Tis true, if one so bold and of such might\nBe found amid your crew,\" (the matron said),\n\"That he ten men of ours engage in fight,\nAnd can in cruel battle lay them dead,\nAnd, after, with ten women, in one night,\nSuffice to play the husband's part in bed,\nHe shall remain our sovereign, and shall sway\nThe land, and you may homeward wend your way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And at your choice to stay shall also be,\nWhether a part or all, but with this pact,\nThat he who here would stay and would be free,\nCan with ten dames the husband's part enact.\nBut if your chosen warrior fall or flee,\nBy his ten enemies at once attacked,\nOr for the second function have not breath,\nTo slavery you we doom, and him to death.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At what she deemed the cavaliers would start,\nThe beldam found them bold; for to compete\nWith those they should engage, and play their part\nThe champions hoped alike in either feat.\nNor failed renowned Marphisa's valiant heart,\nAlbeit for the second dance unmeet;\nSecure, where nature had her aid denied,\nThe want should with the falchion be supplied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The patron is commanded their reply\nResolved in common council to unfold;\nThe dames at pleasure may their prowess try,\nAnd shall in lists and bed allow them bold.\nThe lashings from the vessels they untie,\nThe skipper heaves the warp, and bids lay hold,\nAnd lowers the bridge; o'er which, in warlike weed,\nThe expectant cavaliers their coursers lead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These through the middle of the city go,\nAnd see the damsels, as they forward fare,\nRide through the streets, succinct, in haughty show,\nAnd arm, in guise of warriors, in the square.\nNor to gird sword, nor fasten spur below,\nIs man allowed, nor any arm to wear;\nExcepting, as I said, the ten; to follow\nThe ancient usage which those women hallow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All others of the manly sex they seat,\nTo ply the distaff, broider, card and sow,\nIn female gown descending to the feet,\nWhich renders them effeminate and slow;\nSome chained, another labour to complete,\nAre tasked, to keep their cattle, or to plough.\nFew are the males; and scarce the warriors ken,\nAmid a thousand dames, a hundred men."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The knights determining by lot to try\nWho in their common cause on listed ground,\nShould slay the ten, with whom they were to vie,\nAnd in the other field ten others wound,\nDesigned to pass the bold Marphisa by,\nBelieving she unfitting would be found;\nAnd would be, in the second joust at eve,\nIll-qualified the victory to achieve."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But with the others she, the martial maid,\nWill run her risque; and 'tis her destiny.\n\"I will lay down this life,\" the damsel said,\n\"Rather than you lay down your liberty.\nBut this\" — with that she pointed to the blade\nWhich she had girt — \"is your security,\nI will all tangles in such manner loose,\nAs Alexander did the Gordian noose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I will not henceforth stranger shall complain,\nSo long as the world lasts, of this repair.\"\nSo said the maid, nor could the friendly train\nTake from her what had fallen to her share.\nThen, — either every thing to lose, or gain\nTheir liberty, — to her they leave the care.\nWith stubborn plate and mail all over steeled,\nReady for cruel fight, she takes the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "High up the spacious city is place,\nWith steps, which serve as seats in rising rows;\nWhich for nought else is used, except the chase,\nTourney, or wrestling match, or such-like shows.\nFour gates of solid bronze the rabble flows\nIn troubled tide; and to Marphisa bold,\nThat she may enter, afterwards is told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On pieballed horse Marphisa entered, — spread\nWere circles dappling all about his hair, —\nOf a bold countenance and little head,\nAnd beauteous points, and haughty gait and air.\nOut of a thousand coursers which he fed,\nHim, as the best, and biggest, and most rare,\nKing Norandino chose, and, decked with brave\nAnd costly trappings, to Marphisa gave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through the south gate, from the mid-day, the plain\nMarphisa entered, nor expected long,\nBefore she heard approaching trumpet-strain\nPeal through the lists in shrilling notes and strong;\nAnd, looking next towards the northern wain,\nSaw her ten opposites appear: among\nThese, as their leader, pricked a cavalier,\nExcelling all the rest in goodly cheer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On a large courser came the leading foe,\nWhich was, excepting the near foot behind\nAnd forehead, darker than was ever crow:\nHis foot and forehead with some white were signed.\nThe horseman did his horse's colours show\nIn his own dress; and hence might be divined,\nHe, as the mournful hue o'erpowered the clear,\nWas less inclined to smile, than mournful tear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At once their spears in rest nine warriors laid,\nWhen the trump sounded, in the hostile train,\nBut he in black no sign of jousting made,\nAs if he held such vantage in disdain:\nBetter he deemed the law were disobeyed,\nThan that his courtesy should suffer stain.\nThe knight retires apart, and sits to view\nWhat against nine one single lance can do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of smooth and balanced pace, the damsel's horse\nTo the encounter her with swiftness bore;\nWho poised a lance so massive in the course,\nIt would have been an overweight for four.\nShe, disembarking, as of greatest force,\nThe boom had chosen out of many more.\nAt her fierce semblance when in motion, quail\nA thousand hearts, a thousand looks grow pale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The bosom of the first she opens so,\nAs might surprise, if naked were the breast:\nShe pierced the cuirass and the mail below;\nBut first a buckler, solid and well prest,\nA yard behind the shoulders of the foe\nWas seen the steel, so well was it addrest.\nSpeared on her lance she left him on the plain,\nAnd at the others drove with flowing rein;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And so she shocked the second of the crew,\nAnd dealt the third so terrible a blow,\nFrom sell and life, with broken spine, the two\nShe drove at once.  So fell the overthrow,\nAnd with such weight she charged the warriors through!\nSo serried was the battle of the foe! —\nI have seen bombard open in such mode\nThe squadrons, as that band Marphisa strowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Many good spears were broken on the dame,\nWho was as little moved as solid wall,\nWhen revellers play the chace's merry game,\nIs ever moved by stroke of heavy ball.\nSo hard the temper of her corslet's mail,\nThe strokes aye harmless on the breast-plate fall,\nWhose steel was heated in the fires of hell,\nAnd in Avernus' water slaked by spell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the end of the career, she checked her steed,\nWheeled him about, and for a little stayed;\nAnd then against the others drove at speed,\nBroke them, and to the handle dyed her blade.\nHere shorn of arms, and there of head, they bleed;\nAnd other in such manner cleft the maid,\nThat breast, and head, and arms together fell,\nBelly and legs remaining in the sell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With such just measure him she cleaves, I say,\nWhere the two haunches and the ribs confine:\nAnd leaves him a half figure, in such way\nAs what we before images divine,\nOf silver, oftener made of wax, survey;\nWhich supplicants from far and near enshrine,\nIn thanks for mercy shown, and to bestow\nA pious quittance for accepted vow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa next made after one that flew,\nAnd overtook the wretch, and cleft (before\nHe the mid square had won his collar through, ) \n\nSo clean, no surgeon ever pieced it more.\nOne after other, all in fine she slew,\nOr wounded every one she smote so sore,\nShe was secure, that never more would foe\nArise anew from earth, to work her woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The cavalier this while had stood aside,\nWho had the ten conducted to the place,\nSince, with so many against one to ride,\nHad seemed to him advantage four and base;\nWho, now he by a single hand espied\nSo speedily his whole array displaced,\nPricked forth against the martial maid, to show\n'Twas courtesy, not fear, had made him slow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, signing with his right hand, made appear\nThat he would speak ere their career was run,\nNor thinking that beneath such manly cheer\nA gentle virgin was concealed, begun:\n\"I wot thou needs must be, sir cavalier,\nSore wearied with such mighty slaughter done;\nAnd if I were disposed to weary thee\nMore than thou art, it were discourtesy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To thee, to rest until to-morrow's light,\nThen to renew the battle, I concede.\nNo honour 'twere to-day to prove my might\nOn thee, whom weak and overwrought I read.\"\n— \"Arms are not new to me, nor listed fight;\nNor does fatigue so short a toil succeed,\"\nAnswered Marphisa, \"and I, at my post,\nHope to prove this upon thee, to thy cost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I thank thee for thy offer of delay,\nBut need not what thy courtesy agrees;\nAnd yet remains so large a space of day\n'Twere very shame to spend it all in ease.\"\n— \"Oh!  were I (he replied so sure to appay ) \n\nMy heart with everything which best would please,\nAs thine I shall appay in this! — but see,\nThat ere thou thinkest, daylight fail not thee.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said he, and obedient to his hest\nTwo spears, say rather heavy booms, they bear.\nHe to Marphisa bids consigns the best,\nAnd the other takes himself: the martial pair\nAlready, with their lances in the rest,\nWait but till other blast the joust declare.\nLo!  earth and air and sea the noise rebound,\nAs they prick forth, at the first trumpet's sound!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No mouth was opened and no eyelid fell,\nNor breath was drawn, amid the observant crew:\nSo sore intent was every one to spell\nWhich should be conqueror of the warlike two.\nMarphisa the black champion from his sell,\nSo to o'erthrow he shall not rise anew,\nLevels her lance; and the black champion, bent\nTo slay Marphisa, spurs with like intent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Both lances, made of willow thin and dry,\nRather than stout and stubborn oak, appeared;\nSo splintered even to the rest, they fly:\nWhile with such force the encountering steeds careered,\nIt seemed, as with a scythe-blade equally\nThe hams of either courser had been sheared.\nAlike both fall; but voiding quick the seat,\nThe nimble riders start upon their feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa in her life, with certain wound,\nA thousand cavaliers on earth had laid;\nAnd never had herself been borne to ground;\nYet quitted now the saddle, as was said.\nNot only at the accident astound,\nBut nigh beside herself, remained the maid.\nStrange to the sable cavalier withal,\nUnwont to be unhorsed, appeared his fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They scarcely touch the ground before they gain\nTheir feet, and now the fierce assault renew,\nWith cut and thrust; which now with shield the twain\nOr blade ward off, and now by leaps eschew.\nWhether the foes strike home, or smite in vain,\nBlows ring, and echo parted aether through.\nMore force those shields, those helms, those breast-plates show\nThan anvils underneath the sounding blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If heavy falls the savage damsel's blade,\nThat falls not lightly of her warlike foe.\nEqual the measure one the other paid;\nAnd both receive as much as they bestow.\nHe who would see two daring spirits weighed,\nTo seek two fiercer need no further go.\nNor to seek more dexterity or might;\nFor greater could not be in mortal wight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The women who have sate long time, to view\nThe champions with such horrid strokes offend,\nNor sign of trouble in the warriors true\nBehold, nor yet of weariness, commend\nThem with just praises, as the worthiest two\nThat are, where'er the sea's wide arms extend.\nThey deem these of mere toil and labour long\nMust die, save they be strongest of the strong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Communing with herself, Marphisa said,\n\"That he moved not before was well for me!\nWho risqued to have been numbered with the dead,\nIf he at first had joined his company.\nSince, as it is, I hardly can make head\nAgainst his deadly blows.\"  This colloquy\nShe with herself maintained, and while she spoke,\nCeased not to ply her sword with circling stroke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'Twas well for me,\" the other cried again,\n\"That to repose I did not leave the knight.\nI now from him defend myself with pain,\nWho is o'erwearied with the former fight:\nWhat had he been, renewed in might and main,\nIf he had rested till to-morrow's light?\nRight fortunate was I, as man could be,\nThat he refused my proffered courtesy!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Till eve they strove, nor did it yet appear\nWhich had the vantage of the doubtful fray:\nNor, without light, could either foe see clear\nNow to avoid the furious blows; when day\nWas done, again the courteous cavalier\nTo his illustrious opposite 'gan say;\n\"What shall we do, since ill-timed shades descend,\nWhile we with equal fortune thus contend?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Meseems, at least, that till to-morrow's morn\n'Twere better thou prolonged thy life: no right\nHave I thy doom, sir warrior, to adjourn\nBeyond the limits of one little night.\nNor will I that by me the blame be born\nThat thou no longer shalt enjoy the light.\nWith reason to the sex's charge, by whom\nThis place is governed, lay thy cruel doom.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If I lament thee and thy company,\nHE knows, by whom all hidden things are spied.\nThou and thy comrades may repose with me,\nFor whom there is no safe abode beside:\nSince leagued against you in conspiracy\nAre all those husbands by thy hand have died.\nFor every valiant warrior of the men\nSlain in the tourney, consort was of ten."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The scathe they have to-day received from thee,\nWould ninety women wreak with vengeful spite;\nAnd, save thou take my hospitality,\nExcept by them to be assailed this night.\"\n— \"I take thy proffer in security,\"\n(Replied Marphisa), \"that the faith so plight,\nAnd goodness of thy heart, will prove no less,\nThan are thy corporal strength and hardiness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if, as having to kill me, thou grieve,\nThou well mayst grieve, for reasons opposite;\nNor hast thou cause to laugh, as I conceive,\nNor hitherto has found me worst in fight.\nWhether thou wouldst defer the fray, or leave,\nOr prosecute by this or other light,\nBehold me prompt thy wishes to fulfil;\nWhere and whenever it shall be thy will!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So by consent the combatants divided,\nTill the dawn broke from Ganges' stream anew;\nAnd so remained the question undecided,\nWhich was the better champion of the two,\nTo both the brothers and the rest who sided\nUpon that part, the liberal lord did sue\nWith courteous prayer, that till the coming day\nThey would be pleased beneath his roof to stay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They unsuspecting with the prayer complied,\nAnd by the cheerful blaze of torches white\nA royal dome ascended, with their guide,\nDivided into many bowers and bright.\nThe combatants remain as stupified,\nOn lifting up their vizors, at the sight\nOne of the other; for (by what appears)\nThe warrior hardly numbers eighteen years."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much marvels with herself the gentle dame,\nThat one so young so well should do and dare.\nMuch marvels he (his wonderment the same)\nWhen he her sex agnizes by her hair.\nQuestioning one another of their name,\nAs speedily reply the youthful pair.\nBut how was hight the youthful cavalier,\nAwait till the ensuing strain to hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 20"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guido and his from that foul haunt retire,\nWhile all Astolpho chases with his horn,\nWho to all quarters of the town sets fire,\nThen roving singly round the world is borne.\nMarphisa, for Gabrina's cause, in ire\nPuts upon young Zerbino scathe and scorn,\nAnd makes him guardian of Gabrina fell,\nFrom whom he first learns news of Isabel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Great fears the women of antiquity\nIn arms and hallowed arts as well have done,\nAnd of their worthy works the memory\nAnd lustre through this ample world has shone.\nPraised is Camilla, with Harpalice,\nFor the fair course which they in battle run.\nCorinna and Sappho, famous for their lore,\nShine two illustrious light, to set no more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Women have reached the pinnacle of glory,\nIn every art by them professed, well seen;\nAnd whosoever turns the leaf of story,\nFinds record of them, neither dim nor mean.\nThe evil influence will be transitory,\nIf long deprived of such the world had been;\nAnd envious men, and those that never knew\nTheir worth, have haply hid their honours due."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To me it plainly seems, in this our age\nOf women such is the celebrity,\nThat it may furnish matter to the page,\nWhence this dispersed to future years shall be;\nAnd you, ye evil tongues which foully rage,\nBe tied to your eternal infamy,\nAnd women's praises so resplendent show,\nThey shall, by much, Marphisa's worth outgo."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To her returning yet again; the dame\nTo him who showed to her such courteous lore,\nRefused not to disclose her martial name,\nSince he agreed to tell the style be bore.\nShe quickly satisfied the warrior's claim;\nTo learn his title she desired so sore.\n\"I am Marphisa,\" the virago cried:\nAll else was known, as bruited far and wide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The other, since 'twas his to speak, begun\nWith longer preamble: \"Amid your train,\nSirs, it is my belief that there is none\nBut has heard mention of my race and strain.\nNot Pontus, Aethiopia, Ind alone,\nWith all their neighbouring realms, but France and Spain\nWot well of Clermont, from whose loins the knight\nIssued who killed Almontes bold in fight,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And Chiareillo and Mambrino slew,\nAnd sacked the realm whose royal crown they wore.\nCome of this blood, where Danube's waters, through\nEight horns or ten to meet the Euxine pour,\nMe to the far-renowned Duke Aymon, who\nThither a stranger roved, my mother bore.\nAnd 'tis a twelvemonth now since her, in quest\nOf my French kin, I left with grief opprest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But reached not France, for southern tempest's spite\nImpelled me hither; lodged in royal bower\nTen months or more; for — miserable wight! —\nI reckon every day and every hour.\nGuido the Savage I by name am hight,\nIll known and scarcely proved in warlike stower.\nHere Argilon of Meliboea I\nSlew with ten warriors in his company."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Conqueror as well in other field confessed,\nTen ladies are the partners of my bed:\nSelected at my choice, who are the best\nAnd fairest damsels in this kingdom bred:\nThese I command, as well as all the rest,\nWho of their female band have made me head;\nAnd so would make another who in fight,\nLike me, ten opposites to death would smite.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Guido is besought of them to say\nWhy there appear so few of the male race,\nAnd to declare if women there bear sway\nO'er men, as men o'er them in other place.\nHe: \"Since my fortune has been here to stay,\nI oftentimes have heard relate the case;\nAnd now (according to the story told)\nWill, since it pleases you, the cause unfold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When, after twenty years, the Grecian host\nReturned from Troy (ten years hostility\nThe town endured, ten weary years were tost\nThe Greeks, detained by adverse winds at sea),\nThey found their women had, for comforts lost,\nAnd pangs of absence, learned a remedy;\nAnd, that they might not freeze alone in bed,\nChosen young lovers in their husbands' stead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With others' children filled the Grecian crew\nTheir houses found, and by consent was past\nA pardon to their women; for they knew\nHow ill they could endure so long a fast.\nBut the adulterous issue, as their due,\nTo seek their fortunes on the world were cast:\nBecause the husbands would not suffer more\nThe striplings should be nourished from their store."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Some are exposed, and others underhand\nTheir kindly mothers shelter and maintain:\nWhile the adults, in many a various band,\nSome here, some there dispersed, their living gain.\nArms are the trade of some, by some are scanned\nLetters and arts; another tills the plain:\nOne serves in court, by other guided go\nThe herd as pleases her who rules below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A boy departed with they youthful peers,\nWho was of cruel Clytemnestra born;\nLike lily fresh (he numbered eighteen years)\nOr blooming rose, new-gathered from the thorn.\nHe having armed a bark, his pinnace steers\nIn search of plunder, o'er the billows borne.\nWith him a hundred other youths engage,\nPicked from all Greece, and of their leader's age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The Cretans, who had banished in that day\nIdomeneus the tyrant of their land,\nAnd their new state to strengthen and upstay,\nWere gathering arms and levying martial band,\nPhalantus' service by their goodly pay\nPurchased (so hight the youth who sought that strand),\nAnd all those others that his fortune run,\nWho the Dictaean city garrison."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Amid the hundred cities of old Crete,\nWas the Dictaean the most rich and bright;\nOf fair and amorous dames the joyous seat,\nJoyous with festive sports from morn to night:\nAnd (as her townsmen aye were wont to greet\nThe stranger with such hospitable rite ) \n\nThey welcomed these, it little lacked but they\nGranted them o'er their households sovereign sway."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Youthful and passing fair were all the crew,\nThe flower of Greece, who bold Phalantus led;\nSo that with those fair ladies at first view,\nStealing their hearts, full well the striplings sped.\nSince, fair in deed as show, they good and true\nLovers evinced themselves and bold in bed.\nAnd in few days to them so grateful proved,\nAbove all dearest things they were beloved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"After the war was ended on accord,\nFor which were hired Phalantus and his train,\nAnd pay withdrawn, nor longer by the sword\nWas aught which the adventurous youth can gain,\nAnd they, for this, anew would go aboard,\nThe unhappy Cretan women more complain,\nAnd fuller tears on this occasion shed,\nThat if their fathers lay before them dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Long time and sorely all the striplings bold\nWere, each apart, by them implored to stay:\nWho since the fleeting youths they cannot hold,\nLeave brother, sire, and son, with these to stray,\nOf jewels and of weighty sums of gold\nSpoiling their households ere they wend their way,\nFor so well was the plot concealed, no wight\nThroughout all Crete was privy to their flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So happy was the hour, so fair the wind,\nWhen young Phalantus chose his time to flee,\nThey many miles had left the isle behind,\nEre Crete lamented her calamity.\nNext, uninhabited by human kind,\nThis shore received them wandering o'er the sea.\n'Twas here they settled, with the plunder reft,\nAnd better weighed the issue of their theft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With amorous pleasures teemed this place of rest,\nFor ten days, to that roving company:\nBut, as oft happens that in youthful breast\nAbundance brings with it satiety,\nTo quit their women, with one wish possest,\nThe band resolved to win their liberty;\nFor never burden does so sore oppress\nAs woman, when her love breeds weariness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"They, who are covetous of spoil and gain,\nAnd ill-bested withal in stipend, know\nThat better means are wanted to maintain\nSo many paramours, than shaft and bow;\nAnd leaving thus alone the wretched train,\nThence, with their riches charged the adventurers go\nFor Puglia's pleasant land: there founded near\nThe sea, Tarentum's city, as I hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The women when they find themselves betrayed\nOf lovers by whose faith they set most store,\nFor many days remain so sore dismayed,\nThat they seem lifeless statues on the shore.\nBut seeing lamentations nothing aid,\nAnd fruitless are the many tears they pour,\nBegin to meditate, amid their pains,\nWhat remedy for such an ill remains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Some laying their opinions now before\nThe others, deem that to return to Crete\nIs in their sad estate the wiser lore,\nThrowing themselves at sire and husband's feet,\nThan in those wilds, and on that desert shore,\nTo pine of want.  Another troop repeat,\nThey should esteem it were a worthier notion\nTo cast themselves into the neighbouring ocean;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And lighter ill, if they as harlots went\nAbout the world, — beggars or slaves to be,\nThan offer up themselves for punishment,\nWell merited by their iniquity.\nSuch and like schemes the unhappy dames present,\nEach harder than the other.  Finally,\nOne Orontea amid these upstood,\nWho drew her origin from Minos' blood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Youngest and fairest of the crew betrayed\nShe was, and wariest, and who least had erred,\nWho to Phalantus' arms had come a maid,\nAnd left for him her father: she in word,\nAs well as in a kindling face, displayed\nHow much with generous wrath her heart was stirred;\nThen, reprobating all advised before,\nSpake; and adopted saw her better lore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She would not leave the land they were upon,\nWhose soil was fruitful, and whose air was sane,\nThroughout which many limpid rivers ran,\nShaded with woods, and for the most part plain;\nWith creek and port, where stranger bark could shun\nFoul wind or storm, which vexed the neighbouring main,\nThat might from Afric or from Egypt bring\nVictual or other necessary thing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For vengeance (she opined they there should stay ) \n\nUpon man's sex, which had so sore offended.\nShe willed each bark and crew which to that bay\nFor shelter from the angry tempest wended,\nThey should, without remorse, burn, sack, and slay,\nNor mercy be to any one extended.\nSuch was the lady's motion, such the course\nAdopted; and the statute put in force."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The women, when they see the changing heaven\nTurbid with tempest, hurry to the strand,\nWith savage Orontea, by whom given\nWas the fell law, the ruler of the land;\nAnd of all barks into their haven driven\nMake havoc dread with fire and murderous brand,\nLeaving no man alive, who may diffuse\nUpon this side or that the dismal news."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'Twas thus with the male sex at enmity,\nSome years the lonely women lived forlorn:\nThen found that hurtful to themselves would be\nThe scheme, save changed; for if from them were born\nNone to perpetuate their empery,\nThe idle law would soon be held in scorn,\nAnd fail together with the fruitful reign,\nWhich they had hoped eternal should remain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So that some deal its rigour they allay,\nAnd in four years, of all who made repair\nThither, by chance conducted to this bay,\nChose out ten vigorous cavaliers and fair;\nThat for endurance in the amorous play\nAgainst those hundred dames good champions were:\nA hundred they; and, of the chosen men,\nA husband was assigned to every ten."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ere this, too feeble to abide the test,\nMany a one on scaffold lost his head.\nNow these ten warriors so approved the best,\nWere made partakers of their rule and bed;\nFirst swearing at the sovereign ladies' hest,\nThat they, if others to that port are led,\nNo mercy shall to any one afford,\nBut one and all will put them to the sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To swell, and next to child, and thence to fear\nThe women turned to teeming wives began\nLest they in time so many males should bear\nAs might invade the sovereignty they plan,\nAnd that the government they hold so dear\nMight finally from them revert to man.\nAnd so, while these are children yet, take measure,\nThey never shall rebel against their pleasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That the male sex may not usurp the sway,\nIt is enacted by the statute fell,\nEach mother should one boy preserve, and slay\nThe others, or abroad exchange or sell.\nFor this, they these to various parts convey,\nAnd to the bearers of the children tell,\nTo truck the girls for boys in foreign lands,\nOr not, at least, return with empty hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor by the women one preserved would be,\nIf they without them could the race maintain.\nSuch all their mercy, all the clemency\nThe law accords for theirs, not others' gain.\nThe dames all others sentence equally;\nAnd temper but in this their statute's pain,\nThat, not as was their former practice, they\nAll in their rage promiscuously slay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Did ten or twenty persons, or yet more,\nArrive, they were imprisoned and put by;\nAnd every day one only from the store\nOf victims was brought out by lot to die,\nIn fane by Orontea built, before\nAn altar raised to Vengeance; and to ply\nAs headsman, and dispatched the unhappy men,\nOne was by lot selected from the ten."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To that foul murderous shore by chance did fare,\nAfter long years elapsed, a youthful wight,\nWhose fathers sprung from good Alcides were,\nAnd he, of proof in arms, Elbanio hight;\nThere was he seized, of peril scarce aware,\nAs unsuspecting such a foul despite:\nAnd, closely guarded, into prison flung,\nKept for like cruel use the rest among."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Adorned with every fair accomplishment,\nOf pleasing face and manners was the peer,\nAnd of a speech so sweet and eloquent,\nHim the deaf adder might have stopt to hear;\nSo that of him to Alexandria went\nTidings as of a precious thing and rare.\nShe was the daughter of that matron bold,\nQueen Orontea, that yet lived, though old."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet Orontea lived, while of that shore\nThe other settlers all were dead and gone;\nAnd now ten times as many such or more\nHad into strength and greater credit grown.\nNor for ten forges, often closed, in store\nHave the ill-furnished band more files than one;\nAnd the ten champions have as well the care\nTo welcome shrewdly all who thither fare."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Young Alexandria, who the blooming peer\nBurned to behold so praised on every part,\nThe special pleasure him to see and hear,\nWon from her mother; and, about to part\nFrom him, discovers that the cavalier\nRemains the master of her tortured heart;\nFinds herself bound, and that 'tis vain to stir,\n— A captive made by her own prisoner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I pity,' (said Elbanio 'lady fair, ) \n\nWas in this cruel region known, as through\nAll other countries near or distant, where\nThe wandering sun sheds light and colouring hue,\nI by your beauty's kindly charms should dare\n(Which make each gentle spirit bound to you)\nTo beg my life; which always, at your will,\nShould I be ready for your love to spill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `But since deprived of all humanity\nAre human bosoms in this cruel land,\nI shall not now request my life of thee,\n(For fruitless would, I know, be the demand)\nBut, whether a good knight or bad I be,\nAsk but like such to die with arms in hand,\nAnd not as one condemned to penal pain;\nOr like brute beast in sacrifice be slain.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The gentle maid, her eye bedimmed with tear,\nIn pity for the hapless youth, replied:\n`Though this land be more cruel and severe\nThan any other country, far and wide,\nEach woman is not a Medaea here\nAs thou wouldst make her; and, if all beside\nWere of such evil kind, in me alone\nShould an exception to the rest be known."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And though I, like so many here, of yore\nWas full of evil deeds and cruelty,\nI can well say, I never had before\nA fitting subject for my clemency.\nBut fiercer were I than a tiger, more\nHard were my heart than diamonds, if in me\nAll hardness did not vanish and give place\nBefore your courage, gentleness, and grace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Ah!  were the cruel statute less severe\nAgainst the stranger to these shores conveyed!\nSo should I not esteem my death too dear\nA ransom for thy worthier life were paid.\nBut none is here so great, sir cavalier,\nNor of such puissance as to lend thee aid;\nAnd what thou askest, though a scanty grace,\nWere difficult to compass in this place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And yet will I endeavour to obtain\nFor thee, before thou perish, this content;\nThough much, I fear, 'twill but augment thy pain.\nAnd thee protracted death but more torment.'\n`So I the ten encounter,' (said again\nElbanio), `I at heart, am confident\nMyself to save, and enemies to slay;\nThough made of iron were the whole array.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To this the youthful Alexandria nought\nMade answer, saving with a piteous sigh;\nAnd from the conference a bosom brought,\nGored with deep wounds, beyond all remedy.\nTo Orontea she repaired, and wrought\nOn her to will the stripling should not die,\nShould he display such courage and such skill\nAs with his single hand the ten to kill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Queen Orontea straightway bade unite\nHer council, and bespoke the assembled band:\n`It still behoves us place the prowest wight\nWhom we can find, to guard our ports and strand.\nAnd, to discover whom to take or slight,\n'Tis fitting that we prove the warrior's hand;\nLest, to our loss, the election made be wrong,\nAnd we enthrone the weak and slay the strong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I deem it fit, if you the counsel shown\nDeem fit as well, in future to ordain,\nThat each upon our coast by Fortune thrown,\nBefore he in the temple shall be slain,\nShall have the choice, instead of this, alone\nBattle against ten others to maintain;\nAnd if he conquer, shall the port defend\nWith other comrades, pardoned to that end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I say this, since to strive against our ten,\nIt seems, that one imprisoned here will dare:\nWho, if he stands against so many men,\nBy Heaven, deserves that we should hear his prayer;\nBut if he rashly boasts himself, again\nAs worthily due the punishment should bear.'\nHere Orontea ceased; on the other side,\nTo her the oldest of the dames replied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `The leading cause, for which to entertain\nThis intercourse with men we first agreed,\nWas not because we, to defend this reign,\nOf their assistance stood in any need;\nFor we have skill and courage to maintain\nThis of ourselves, and force, withal, to speed.\nWould that we could in all as well avail\nWithout their succour, nor succession fail!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `But since this may not be, we some have made\n(These few partakers of our company; ) \n\nThat, ten to one, we be not overlaid;\nNor they possess them of the sovereignty.\nNot that we for protection need their aid,\nBut simply to increase and multiply.\nThan be their powers to this sole fear addressed,\nAnd be they sluggards, idle for the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `To keep among us such a puissant wight\nOur first design would render wholly vain.\nIf one can singly slay ten men in fight,\nHow many women can he not restrain?\nIf our ten champions had possessed such might,\nThey the first day would have usurped the reign.\nTo arm a hand more powerful than your own\nIs an ill method to maintain the throne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Reflect withal, that if your prisoner speed\nSo that he kill ten champions in the fray,\nA hundred women's cry, whose lords will bleed\nBeneath his falchion, shall your ears dismay.\nLet him not 'scape by such a murderous deed;\nBut, if he would, propound some other way.\n— Yet if he of those ten supply the place,\nAnd please a hundred women, grant him grace.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This was severe Artemia's sentiment,\n(So was she named and had her counsel weighed, ) \n\nElbanio to the temple had been sent,\nTo perish by the sacrificial blade.\nBut Orontea, willing to content\nHer daughter, to the matron answer made;\nAnd urged so many reasons, and so wrought,\nThe yielding senate granted what she ought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Elbanio's beauty (for so fair to view\nNever was any cavalier beside)\nSo strongly works upon the youthful crew,\nWhich in that council sit the state to guide,\nThat the opinion of the older few\nThat like Artemia think, is set aside;\nAnd little lacks but that the assembled race\nAbsolve Elbanio by especial grace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To pardon him in fine the dames agreed:\nBut, after slaying his half-score, and when\nHe in the next assault as well should speech,\nNot with a hundred women, but with ten;\nAnd, furnished to his wish with arms and steed,\nNext day he was released from dungeon-den,\nAnd singly with ten warriors matched in plain,\nWho by his arm successively were slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He to new proof was put the following night,\nAgainst ten damsels naked and alone;\nWhen so successful was the stripling's might,\nHe took the 'say of all the troop, and won\nSuch grace with Orontea, that the knight\nWas by the dame adopted for her son;\nAnd from her Alexandria had to wife,\nWith those whom he had proved in amorous strife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And him she left with Alexandria, heir\nTo this famed city, which from her was hight,\nSo he and all who his successors were,\nShould guard the law which willed, whatever wight,\nConducted hither by his cruel star,\nUpon this miserable land did light,\nShould have his choice to perish by the knife,\nOr singly with ten foes contend to strife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if he should dispatch the men by day,\nAt night should prove him with the female crew;\nAnd if so fortunate that in this play\nHe proved again the conqueror, he, as due,\nThe female band, as prince and guide, should sway,\nAnd his ten consorts at his choice renew:\nAnd reign with them, till other should arrive\nOf stouter hand, and him of life deprive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"They for two thousand years nigh past away\nThis usage have maintained, and yet maintain\nThe impious rite; and rarely passes day\nBut stranger wight is slaughtered in the fane.\nIf he, Elbanio-like, ten foes assay,\n(And such sometimes is found he oft is slain ) \n\nIn the first charge: nor, in a thousand, one\nThe other feat, of which I spake, has done,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet some there are have done it, though so few,\nThey may be numbered on the fingers; one\nOf the victorious cavaliers, but who\nReigned with his ten short time, was Argilon:\nFor, smote by me, whom ill wind hither blew,\nThe knight to his eternal rest is gone.\nWould I with him that day had filled a grave,\nRather than in such scorn survive a slave!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For amorous pleasures, laughter, game, and play,\nWhich evermore delight the youthful breast;\nThe gem, the purple garment, rich array,\nAnd in his city place before the rest.\nLittle, by Heaven, the wretched man appay\nWho of his liberty is dispossest:\nAnd not to have the power to leave this shore\nTo me seems shameful servitude and sore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To know I wear away life's glorious spring\nIn such effeminate and slothful leisure\nIs to my troubled heart a constant sting,\nAnd takes away the taste of every pleasure.\nFame bears my kindred's praise on outstretched wing,\nEven to the skies; and haply equal measure\nI of the glories of my blood might share\nIf I united with my brethren were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Methinks my fate does such injurious deed\nBy me, condemned to servitude so base,\nAs he who turns to grass the generous steed\nTo run amid the herd of meaner race,\nBecause unfit for war or worthier meed,\nThrough blemish, or disease of sight or pace.\nNor hoping but by death, alas!  to fly\nSo vile a service, I desire to die.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here Guido ceased to address the martial peers,\nAnd cursed withal the day, in high disdain,\nThat he achieved o'er dames and cavaliers\nThe double victory which bestowed that reign.\nAstolpho hides his name, and silent hears,\nUntil to him by many a sign is plain\nThat this Sir Guido is, as he had said,\nThe issue of his kinsman Aymon's bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then cried: \"The English duke, Astolpho, I\nThy cousin am,\" and clipt him round the waist,\nAnd in a kindly act of courtesy,\nNot without weeping, kist him and embraced.\nThen, \"Kinsman dear, thy birth to certify\nNo better sign thy mother could have placed\nAbout thy neck.  Enough!  that sword of thine,\nAnd courage, vouch thee of our valiant line.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guido, who gladly would in other place\nSo near a kin have welcomed, in dismay\nBeholds him here and with a mournful face;\nKnowing, if he himself survives the fray,\nAstolpho will be doomed to slavery base,\nHis fate deferred but till the following day;\nAnd he shall perish, if the duke is free:\nSo that one's good the other's ill shall be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He grieves, as well, the other cavaliers\nShould through his means for ever captive be;\nNor, that he should, if slain, those martial peers\nDeliver by his death from slavery.\nSince if Marphisa from one quicksand clears\nThe troop, yet these from other fails to free,\nShe will have won the victory in vain;\nFor they will be enslaved, and she be slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the other hand, the stripling's age, in May\nOf youth, with courtesy and valour fraught,\nUpon the maid and comrades with such sway,\nTouching their breasts with love and pity, wrought\nThat they of freedom, for which he must pay\nThe forfeit of his life, nigh loathed the thought;\nAnd if Marphisa him perforce must kill,\nShe is resolved as well herself to spill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Join thou with us,\" she to Sir Guido cried,\n\"And we from hence will sally.\" — \"From within\nThese walls to sally\" — Guido on his side\nAnswered, \"Ne'er hope: With me you lose or win.\"\n\"— I fear not, I,\" the martial maid replied,\n\"To execute whatever I begin;\nNor know what can securer path afford\nThan that which I shall open with my sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Such proof of thy fair prowess have I made,\nWith thee I every enterprise would dare.\nTo-morrow when about the palisade\nThe crowds assembled in the circus are,\nLet us on every side the mob invade,\nWhether they fly or for defence prepare;\nThen give the town to fire, and on their bed\nOf earth to wolf and vulture leave the dead.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He: \"Ready shalt thou find me in the strife\nTo follow thee or perish at thy side:\nBut let us hope not to escape with life.\nEnough, is vengeance somedeal satisfied\nEre death; for oft ten thousand, maid and wife,\nI in the place have witnessed; and, outside,\nAs many castle, wall and port, defend.\nNor know I certain way from hence to wend.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And were there more (Marphisa made reply)\nThan Xerxes led, our squadrons to oppose,\nMore than those rebel spirits from the sky\nCast out to dwell amid perpetual woes,\nAll in one day should by this weapon die,\nWert thou with me, at least, not with my foes.\"\nTo her again, \"No project but must fail,\n(Sir Guido said I know, save this avail.\" )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This only us can save, should it succeed;\nThis, which but now remembered I shall teach.\nTo dames alone our laws the right concede\nTo sally, or set foot upon the beach,\nAnd hence to one of mine in this our need\nMust I commit myself, and aid beseech;\nWhose love for me, by perfect friendship tied,\nHas oft by better proof than this been tried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No less than me would she desire that I\nShould 'scape from slavery, so she went with me;\nAnd that, without her rival's company,\nShe of my lot should sole partaker be.\nShe bark or pinnace, in the harbour nigh,\nShall bid, while yet 'tis dark, prepare for sea;\nWhich shall await your sailors, rigged and yare\nFor sailing, when they thither shall repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Behind me, in a solid band comprest,\nYe merchants, mariners and warriors, who,\nDriven to this city, have set up your rest\nBeneath this roof (for which my thanks are due)\n— You have to force your way with stedfast breast,\nIf adversaries interrupt our crew.\n'Tis thus I hope, by succour of the sword,\nTo clear a passage through the cruel horde.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Do as thou wilt,\" Marphisa made reply,\n\"I of escape am confident withal:\nAnd likelier 'twere that by my hand should die\nThe martial race, encompassed by this wall,\nThan any one should ever see me fly,\nOr guess by other sign that fears appall.\nI would my passage force in open day,\nAnd shameful in my sight were other way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I wot if I were for a woman known,\nHonour and place from women I might claim,\nHere gladly entertained, and classed as one\nHaply among their chiefs of highest fame:\nBut privilege or favour will I none\nUnshared by those with whom I hither came.\nToo base it were, did I depart or free\nRemain, to leave the rest in slavery.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These speeches by Marphisa made, and more,\nShowed that what only had restrained her arm\nWas the respect she to the safety bore\nOf the companions whom her wrath might harm;\nBy this alone withheld form taking sore\nAnd signal vengeance on the female swarm.\nAnd hence she left in Guido's care to shape\nWhat seemed the fittest means for their escape."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Guido speaks that night with Alery\n(So the most faithful of his wives was hight)\nNor needs long prayer to make the dame agree,\nDisposed already to obey the knight.\nShe takes a ship and arms the bark for sea,\nStowed with her richest chattels for their flight;\nFeigning design, as soon as dawn ensues,\nTo sail with her companions on a cruise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She into Guido's palace had before\nBid sword and spear and shield and cuirass bear;\nWith the intent to furnish from this store,\nMerchants and sailors that half naked were.\nSome watch, and some repose upon the floor,\nAnd rest and guard among each other share;\nOft marking, still with harness on their backs,\nIf ruddy yet with light the orient wax."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not yet from earth's hard visage has the sun\nLifted her veil of dim and dingy dye;\nScarcely Lycaon's child, her furrow done,\nHas turned about her ploughshare in the sky;\nWhen to the theatre the women run\nWho would the fearful battle's end espy,\nAs swarming bees upon their threshold cluster,\nWho bent on change of realm in springtide muster."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With warlike trumpet, drum, and sound of horn,\nThe people make the land and welkin roar;\nSummoning thus their chieftain to return,\nAnd end of unfinished warfare.  Covered o'er\nWith arms stand Aquilant and Gryphon stern,\nAnd the redoubted duke from England's shore.\nMarphisa, Dudo, Sansonet, and all\nThe knights or footmen harboured in that hall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hence to descend towards the sea or port\nThe way across the place of combat lies;\nNor was there other passage, long or short.\nSir Guido so to his companions cries:\nAnd having ceased his comrades to exhort,\nTo do their best set forth in silent wise,\nAnd in the place appeared, amid the throng,\nHead of a squad above a hundred strong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Toward the other gate Sir Guido went,\nHurrying his band, but, gathered far and nigh\nThe mighty multitude, for aye intent\nTo smite, and clad in arms, when they descry\nThe comrades whom he leads, perceive his bent,\nAnd truly deem he is about to fly.\nAll in a thought betake them to their bows,\nAnd at the portal part the knight oppose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Guido and the cavaliers who go\nBeneath that champion's guidance, and before\nThe others bold Marphisa, were not slow\nTo strike, and laboured hard to force the door.\nBut such a storm of darts from ready bow,\nDealing on all sides death or wounding sore,\nWas rained in fury on the troop forlorn,\nThey feared at last to encounter skaith and scorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of proof the corslet was each warrior wore,\nWho without this would have had worse to fear:\nSansonnet's horse was slain, and that which bore\nMarphisa: to himself the English peer\nExclaimed, \"Why wait I longer?  As if more\nMy horn could ever succour me than here.\nSince the sword steads not, I will make assay\nIf with my bugle I can clear the way.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As he was customed in extremity,\nHe to his mouth applied the bugle's round;\nThe wide world seemed to tremble, earth and sky,\nAs he in air discharged the horrid sound.\nSuch terror smote the dames, that bent to fly,\nWhen in their ears the deafening horn was wound,\nNot only they the gate unguarded left,\nBut from the circus reeled, of wit bereft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As family, awaked in sudden wise,\nLeaps from the windows and from lofty height,\nPeriling life and limb, when in surprise\nThey see, now near, the fire's encircling light,\nWhich had, while slumber sealed their heavy eyes,\nBy little and by little waxed at night:\nReckless of life, thus each, impelled by dread,\nAt sound of that appalling bugle fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above, below, and here and there, the rout\nRise in confusion and attempt to fly.\nAt once, above a thousand swarm about\nEach entrance, to each other's lett, and lie\nIn heaps: from window these, or stage without,\nLeap headlong; in the press these smothered die.\nBroken is many an arm, and many a head;\nAnd one lies crippled, and another dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Amid the mighty ruin which ensued,\nCries pierce the very heavens on every part.\nWhere'er the sound is heard, the multitude,\nIn panic at the deafening echo, start.\nWhen you are told that without hardihood\nAppear the rabble, and of feeble heart,\nThis need not more your marvel; for by nature\nThe hare is evermore a timid creature."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But of Marphisa what will be your thought,\nAnd Guido late so furious? — of the two\nYoung sons of Olivier, that lately wrought\nSuch deeds in honour of their lineage?  who\nLately a hundred thousand held as nought,\nAnd now, deprived of courage, basely flew,\nAs ring-doves flutter and as coneys fly,\nWho hear some mighty noise resounding nigh."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For so to friend as stranger, noxious are\nThe powers that in the enchanted horn reside.\nSansonet, Guido, follow, with the pair\nOr brethren bold, Marphisa terrified.\nNor flying, can they to such distance fare,\nBut that their ears are dinned.  On every side\nAstolpho, on his foaming courser borne,\nLends louder breath to his enchanted horn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One sought the sea, and one the mountain-top,\nOne fled the hide herself in forest hoar;\nAnd this, who turned not once nor made a stop,\nNot for ten days her headlong flight forbore:\nThese from the bridge in that dread moment drop,\nNever to climb the river's margin more.\nSo temple, house and square and street were drained,\nThat nigh unpeopled the wide town remained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa, Guido, and the brethren two,\nWith Sansonetto, pale and trembling, hie\nTowards the sea, and behind these the crew\nOf frighted mariners and merchants fly;\nAnd 'twixt the forts, in bark, prepared with view\nTo their escape, discover Alery;\nWho in sore haste receives the warriors pale,\nAnd bids them ply their oars and make all sail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke within and out the town had bear\nFrom the surrounding hills to the sea-side,\nAnd of its people emptied every street.\nAll fly before the deafening sound, and hide:\nMany in panic, seeking a retreat,\nLurk, in some place obscure and filthy stied;\nMany, not knowing whither to repair,\nPlunge in the neighbouring sea, and perish there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke arrives, seeking the friendly band,\nWhom he had hoped to find upon the quay;\nHe turns and gazes round the desert strand,\nAnd none is there — directs along the bay\nHis eyes, and now, far distant from the land,\nBeholds the parting frigate under way.\nSo that the paladin, for his escape —\nThe vessel gone — must other project shape."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let him depart!  nor let it trouble you\nThat he so long a road must beat alone;\nWhere, never without fear, man journeys through\nWild paynim countries: danger is there none,\nBut what he with his bugle may eschew,\nWhose dread effect the English duke has shown;\nAnd let his late companions be our care,\nWho trembling to the beach had made repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They from that cruel and ensanguined ground\nTo seaward, under all their canvas, bore;\nAnd having gained such offing, that the sound\nOf that alarming horn was heard no more,\nUnwonted shame inflicted such a wound,\nThat all a face of burning crimson wore.\nOne dares not eye the other, and they stand\nWith downcast looks, a mute and mournful band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fixed on his course, the pilot passes by\nCyprus and Rhodes, and ploughs the Aegean sea:\nBeholds a hundred islands from him fly,\nAnd Malea's fearful headland; fanned by free\nAnd constant wind, sees vanish from the eye\nThe Greek Morea; rounding Sicily,\nInto the Tuscan sea his frigate veers,\nAnd, coasting Italy's fair region, steers:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Last rises Luna, where his family\nIs waiting his return, the patron hoar\nGives thanks to God at having passed the sea\nWithout more harm, and makes the well-known shore.\nHere, offering passage to their company,\nThey find a master, ready to unmoor\nFor France, and that same day his pinnace climb;\nThence wafted to Marseilles in little time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There was not Bradamant, who used to sway\nThe land, and had that city in her care,\nAnd who (if present there to make some stay ) \n\nWould have compelled them by her courteous prayer.\nThey disembarked; and that same hour away\nDid bold Marphisa at a venture fare;\nBidding adieu to salvage Guido's wife,\nAnd to the four, her comrades in the strife:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Saying she deems unfitting for a knight\nTo fare in like great fellowship; that so\nThe starlings and the doves in flock unite,\nAnd every beast who fears — the stag and doe;\nBut hawk and eagle, that in other's might\nPut not their trust, for ever singly go;\nAnd lion, bear, and tyger, roam alone,\nWho fear no prowess greater than their own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But none with her opine, and, in the lack\nOf a companion, singly must she fare,\nSo then, alone and friendless, she a track\nUncouth pursues, and through a wooded lair.\nGryphon the white and Aquilant the black\nTake road more beaten with the other pair;\nAnd on the following day a castle see,\nWithin which they are harboured courteously."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Courteously I, in outward show, would say;\nFor soon the contrary was made appear.\nSince he, the castellain, who with display\nOf kindness sheltered them and courteous cheer,\nThe night ensuing took them as they lay\nCouched in their beds, secure and void of fear.\nNor from the snare would he his prisoners loose,\nTill they had sworn to observe an evil use."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But I will first pursue the martial maid,\nEre more of these, fair sir, I shall proclaim.\nBeyond the Durence, Rhone, and Saone she strayed,\nAnd to the foot of sunny mountain came;\nAnd there approaching in black gown arrayed,\nBeside a torrent, saw an ancient dame;\nWho with long journey weak, and wearied sore,\nAppeared, but pined by melancholy more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was the beldam who had wont to ply\nServing the robbers in the caverned mount;\nWhither stern Justice sent (that they might die\nBy that good paladin Anglante's count. ) \n\nThe aged harridan, for cause which I\nTo you shall in another place recount,\nNow many days by path obscure had flown,\nStill fearing lest her visage should be known."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The semblance now of foreign cavalier\nShe in Marphisa saw, in arms and vest;\nAnd hence she flies not her, though wont to fear,\n(As being natives of that land the rest; ) \n\n— Nay, with security and open cheer,\nStops at the ford the damsel to arrest:\nStops at the ford — where that old beldam meets\nMarphisa, and with fair encounter greets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And next implored the maid, she of her grace\nWould bear her on the croupe to the other shore.\nMarphisa, who was come of gentle race,\nThe hag with her across the torrent bore;\nAnd is content to bear, till she can place\nIn a securer road the beldam hoar,\nClear of a spacious marish: as its end\nThey see a cavalier towards them wend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In shining armour and in fair array,\nThe warrior rode on saddle richly wrought\nTowards the river, and upon his way\nWith him a single squire and damsel brought.\nOf passing beauty was the lady gay,\nBut little pleasing was her semblance haught;\nAll overblown with insolence and pride,\nWorthy the cavalier who was her guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He of Maganza was a count, who bore\nThe lady with him (Pinabello hight):\nThe same who Bradamant, some months before,\nHad plunged into a hollow cave in spite.\nThose many sobs, those burning sighs and sore,\nThose tears which had nigh quenched the warrior's sight, —\nAll for the damsel were, now at his side;\nAnd then by that false necromancer stied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But when the magic tower upon the hill\nWas razed, the dwelling of Atlantes hoar,\nAnd every one was free to rove at will,\nThrough Bradamant's good deed and virtuous lore,\nThe damsel, who had been compliant still\nWith the desires of Pinabel before,\nRejoined him, and now journeying in a round\nWith him, from castle was to castle bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As wanton and ill-customed, when she spies\nMarphisa's aged charge approaching near,\nShe cannot rein her saucy tongue, but plies\nHere, in her petulance, with laugh and jeer.\nMarphisa haught, unwont in any wise\nOutrage from whatsoever part to hear,\nMakes answer to the dame, in angry tone,\nThat handsomer than her she deems the crone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And that she this would prove upon her knight\nWith pact that she might strip the bonnibell\nOf gown and palfrey, if, o'erthrown in fight,\nHer champion from his goodly courser fell.\n— In silence to have overpast the slight\nWould have been sin and shame in Pinabel,\nWho for short answer seized his shield and spear,\nAnd wheeled, and drove at her in fierce career."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa grasped a mighty lance, and thrust,\nEncountering him, at Pinabello's eyes;\nAnd stretched him so astounded in the dust,\nThat motionless an hour the warrior lies.\nMarphisa, now victorious in the just,\nGave orders to strip off the glorious guise\nAnd ornaments wherewith the maid was drest,\nAnd with the spoils her ancient crone invest;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And willed that she should don the youthful weed,\nBedizened at the haughty damsel's cost;\nAnd took away as well the goodly steed\nWhich her had thither borne, and — bent to post\nOn her old track — with her the hag will speed,\nWho seems most hideous when adorned the most.\nThree days the tedious road the couple beat,\nWithout adventure needful to repeat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the fourth day they met a cavalier,\nWho came in fury galloping alone.\nIf you the stranger's name desire to hear,\nI tell you 'twas Zerbino, a king's son,\nOf beauty and of worth example rare,\nNow grieved and angered, as unvenged of one,\nWho a great act of courtesy, which fain\nThe warrior would have done, had rendered vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Vainly the young Zerbino, through the glade,\nHad chased that man of his, who this despite\nHad done him, who himself so well conveyed\nAway and took such 'vantage in his flight,\nSo hid by wood and mist, which overlaid\nThe horizon and bedimmed the morning-light,\nThat he escaped Zerbino's grasp, and lay\nConcealed until his wrath was past away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino laughed parforce, when he descried\nThat beldam's face, though he was full of rage;\nFor too ill-sorted seemed her vest of pride\nWith her foul visage, more deformed by age;\nAnd to the proud Marphisa, at her side\nThe prince, exclaimed, \"Sir warrior, you are sage,\nIn having chosen damsel of a sort,\nWhom none, I ween, will grudge you should escort.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Older than Sibyl seemed the beldam hoar,\n(As far as from her wrinkles one might guess),\nAnd in the youthful ornaments she wore,\nLooked like an ape which men in mockery dress;\nAnd now appears more foul, as angered sore,\nWhile rage and wrath her kindled eyes express.\nFor none can do a woman worse despite\nThan to proclaim her old and foul to sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To have sport of him — as she had — an air\nOf wrath the maid assumed upon her part,\nAnd to the prince, \"By Heaven, more passing fair\nIs this my lady than thou courteous art,\"\nExclaimed in answer; \"though I am aware\nWhat thou hast uttered comes not from thy heart.\nThou wilt not own her beauty; a device\nPut on to masque thy sovereign cowardice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And of what stamp would be that cavalier\nWho found such fair and youthful dame alone,\nWithout protection, in the forest drear,\nNor sought to make the lovely weft his own?\"\n— \"So well she sorts with thee,\" replied the peer,\n\" `Twere ill that she were claimed by any one:\nNor I of her would thee in any wise\nDeprive; God rest thee merry with thy prize!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But would thou prove what is my chivalry,\nOn other ground I to thy wish incline;\nYet deem me not of such perversity\nAs to tilt with thee for this prize of thine.\nOr fair or foul, let her remain thy fee;\nI would not, I, such amity disjoin.\nWell are ye paired, and safely would I swear\nThat thou as valiant art as she is fair.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him Marphisa, \"Thou in thy despite\nShalt try to bear from me the dame away.\nI will not suffer that so fair a sight\nThou shouldst behold, nor seek to gain the prey.\"\nTo her the prince, \"I know not wherefore wight\nShould suffer pain and peril in affray,\nStriving for victory, where, for his pains,\nThe victor losses, and the vanquished gains.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If this condition please not, other course\nWhich ill thou canst refuse, I offer thee,\"\n(Marphisa cried):  \"If thou shalt me unhorse\nIn this our tourney, she remains with me:\nBut if I win, I give her thee parforce.\nThen prove we now who shall without her be.\nPremised, if loser, thou shalt be her guide,\nWherever it may please the dame to ride.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And be it so,\" Zerbino cried, and wheeled\nSwiftly his foaming courser for the shock,\nAnd rising in his stirrups scowered the field,\nFirm in his seat, and smote, with levelled stock,\nFor surer aim, the damsel in mid-shield;\nBut she sate stedfast as a metal rock,\nAnd at the warrior's morion thrust so well,\nShe clean out-bore him senseless from the sell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much grieved the prince, to whom in other fray\nThe like misfortune had not chanced before,\nWho had unhorsed some thousands in his day:\nNow shamed, he thought for ever.  Troubled sore,\nAnd mute long space upon the ground he lay,\nAnd, when 'twas recollected, grieved the more,\nThat he had promised, and that he was bound,\nTo accompany the hag where'er she wound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Turning about to him the victoress cried,\nLaughing, \"This lady I to thee present,\nAnd the more beauty is in her descried,\nThe more that she is thine I am content,\nNow in my place her champion and her guide.\nBut do not thou thy plighted faith repent,\nSo that thou fail, as promised, to attend\nThe dame, wherever she may please to wend.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Without awaiting answer, to career\nShe spurred her horse, and vanished in the wood.\nZerbino, deeming her a cavalier,\nCried to the crone, \"By whom am I subdued?\"\nAnd, knowing 'twould be poison to his ear,\nAnd that it would inflame his angered blood,\nShe in reply, \"It was a damsel's blow\nWhich from thy lofty saddle laid thee low."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She, for her matchless force, deservedly\nUsurps from cavalier the sword and lance;\nAnd even from the east is come to try\nHer strength against the paladins of France.\"\nNot only was his cheek of crimson dye,\nSuch shame Zerbino felt as his mischance,\nLittle was wanting (so his blushes spread)\nBut all the arms he wore had glowed as red."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He mounts, and blames himself in angry wise,\nIn that he had no better kept his seat.\nWithin herself the beldam laughs, and tries\nThe Scottish warrior more to sting and heat.\nTo him for promised convoy she applies;\nAnd he, who knows that there is no retreat,\nStands like tired courser, who in pensive fit,\nHangs down his ears, controlled by spur and bit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, sighing deeply, cries, in his despair,\n\"Fell Fortune, with what change dost thou repay\nMy loss!  she who was fairest of the fair,\nWho should be mine, by thee is snatched away!\nAnd thinkest thou the evil to repair\nWith her whom thou hast given to me this day?\nRather than make like ill exchange, less cross\nIt were to undergo a total loss."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her, who for virtue and for beauteous form\nWas never equalled, nor will ever be,\nThou on the rocks hast wrecked, in wintry storm,\nAs food for fowls and fishes of the sea;\nAnd her who should have fed the earth-bred worm\nPreserved beyond her date, some ten or score\nOf years, to harass and torment me more.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So spake Zerbino, and like grief displaid,\nIn his despairing words and woful mien,\nFor such an odious acquisition made,\nAs he had suffered when he lost his queen.\nThe aged woman now, from what he said,\nThough she before Zerbino had not seen,\nPerceived 'twas him of whom, in the thieves' hold,\nIsabel of Gallicia erst had told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If you remember what was said before,\nThis was the hag who 'scaped out of the cave,\nWhere Isabella, who had wounded sore\nZerbino's heart, was long detained a slave;\nWho oft had told how she her native shore\nHad left, and, launching upon ocean's wave\nHer frigate, had been wrecked by wind and swell\nUpon the rocky shallows near Rochelle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And she to her Zerbino's goodly cheer\nAnd gentle features had pourtrayed so well,\nThat the hag hearing him, and now more near,\nLetter her eyes upon his visage dwell,\nDiscerned it was the youth for whom, whilere,\nHad grieved at heart the prisoned Isabel;\nWhose loss she in the cavern more deplored,\nThan being captive to the murderous horde."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beldam, hearing what in rage and grief\nZerbino vents, perceives the youth to be\nDeceived, and cheated by the false belief\nThat Isabel had perished in the sea;\nAnd though she might have given the prince relief,\nKnowing the truth, in her perversity\nWhat would have made him joyful she concealed,\nAnd only what would cause him grief revealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hear, you that are so proud,\" (the hag pursues)\n\"And flout me with such insolence and scorn,\nYou would entreat me fair to have the news\nI know of her whose timeless death you mourn;\nBut to be strangled would I rather choose,\nAnd be into a thousand pieces torn.\nWhereas if you had made me kinder cheer,\nHaply from me the secret might you hear.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the dog's rage is quickly overblown,\nWho flies the approaching robber to arrest,\nIf the thief proffer piece of bread or bone,\nOf offer other lure which likes him best;\nAs readily Zerbino to the crone\nHumbled himself, and burned to know the rest;\nWho, in the hints of the old woman, read\nThat she had news of her he mourned as dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And with more winning mien to her applied,\nAnd her did supplicate, entreat, conjure,\nBy men and gods, the truth no more to hide,\nDid she benign or evil lot endure.\nThe hard and pertinacious crone replied,\n\"Nought shalt thou hear, thy comfort to assure.\nIsabel has not yielded up her breath,\nBut lives a life she would exchange for death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She, since thou heardest of her destiny,\nWithin few days, has fallen into the power\nOf more than twenty.  If restored to thee,\nThink now, if thou hast hope to crop her flower.\"\n— \"Curst hag, how well thou shapest thy history,\nYet knowest it is false!  Her virgin dower\nSecure from brutal wrong, would none invade,\nThough in the power of twenty were the maid.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Questioning of the maid, he when and where\nShe saw her, vainly asked the beldam hoar,\nWho, ever restive to Zerbino's prayer,\nTo what she had rehearsed would add no more.\nThe prince in the beginning spoke her fair,\nAnd next to cut her throat in fury swore.\nBut prayers and menaces alike were weak;\nNor could he make the hideous beldam speak."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At length Zerbino to his tongue gave rest,\nSince speaking to the woman booted nought;\nScarcely his heart found room within his breast,\nSuch dread suspicion had her story wrought.\nHe to find Isabella was so pressed,\nHer in the midst of fire he would have sought;\nBut could not hurry more than was allowed\nBy her his convoy, since he so had vowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They hence, by strange and solitary way,\nRove, as the beldam does her will betoken,\nNor climbing, nor descending hill, survey\nEach other's face, nor any word is spoken.\nBut when the sun upon the middle day\nHad turned his back, their silence first was broken\nBy cavalier encountered in their way:\nWhat followed the ensuing strain will say."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 21"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino for Gabrina, who a heart\nOf asp appears to bear, contends.  O'erthrown,\nThe Fleming falls upon the other part,\nThrough cause of that despised and odious crone,\nHe wounded sore, and writhing with the smart,\nThe beldam's treason to the prince makes known,\nWhose scorn and hatred hence derive new force.\nTowards loud cries Zerbino spurs his horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No cord I well believe is wound so tight\nRound chest, nor nails the plank so fastly hold,\nAs Faith enwraps an honourable sprite\nIn its secure, inextricable, fold;\nNor holy Faith, it seems, except in white\nWas mantled over in the days of old;\nSo by the ancient limner ever painted,\nAs by one speck, one single blemish tainted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Faith should be kept unbroken evermore,\nWith one or with a thousand men united;\nAs well if given in grot or forest hoar,\nRemote from town and hamlet, as if plighted\nAmid a crowd of witnesses, before\nTribunal, and in act and deed recited:\nNor needs the solemn sanction of an oath:\nIt is sufficient that we pledge our troth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this maintains as it maintained should be,\nIn each emprize the Scottish cavalier,\nAnd gives good proof of his fidelity,\nQuitting his road with that old crone to steer;\nAlthough this breeds the youth such misery,\nAs 'twould to have Disease itself as near,\nOr even Death; but with him heavier weighed\nThat his desire the promise he had made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of him I told who felt at heart such load,\nReflecting she beneath his charge must go,\nHe spake no word; and thus in silent mode\nBoth fared: so sullen was Zerbino's woe.\nI said how vexed their silence, as they rode,\nWas broke, when Sol his hindmost wheels did show,\nBy an adventurous errant cavalier,\nWho in mid pathway met the crone and peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The hag, who the approaching warrior knew,\n(Hermonides of Holland he was hight)\nThat bore upon a field of sable hue\nA bar of vermeil tint, transversely dight,\nDid humbly now to good Zerbino sue,\n— Her pride abased, and look of haught despite —\nAnd him reminded of the promise made,\nWhen her Marphisa to his care conveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Because as foe to her and hers she knew\nThe knight they were encountering, who had slain\nHer only brother and her father true;\nAnd was advised, the traitor would be fain\nBy her, the remnant of her race, to do\nWhat he had perpetrated on the twain.\n\"Woman, while guarded by my arm (he said)\nI will not thou shouldst any danger dread.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As nearer now, the stranger knight espied\nThat face, which was so hateful in his sight,\nWith menacing and savage voice he cried,\n\"Either with me prepare thyself to fight,\nOr arm thee not on that old woman's side,\nWho by my hand shall perish, as is right.\nIf thou contendest for her, thou art slain;\nFor such their portion is who wrong maintain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him young Zerbino answered courteously,\nTwas sign of evil and ungenerous will,\nAnd corresponded not with chivalry,\nThat he a woman should desire to kill;\nYet if the knight persists, he will not flee —\nBut bids him well consider first how ill\n'Twould sound, that he, a gentle knight and good,\nShould wish to dip his hand in woman's blood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This and yet more he vainly says; nor stand\nThey idle long; from word they pass to deed;\nAnd having compassed on the level land\nEnough of ground, encounter on the mead.\nNot fired in some rejoicing, from the hand\nDischarged, so fast the whistling rockets speed,\nAs the two coursers bear the cavaliers\nTo hurtle in mid space with rested spears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hermonides of Holland levelled low,\nAnd for the youth's left flank the stroke intended;\nBut his weak lance was shivered by the blow,\nAnd little the opposing Scot offended:\nBut vain was not the spear-thrust of his foe,\nWho bored his opposite's good shield, and rended\nHis shoulder, by the lance pierced through and through,\nAnd good Hermonides on earth o'erthrew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thinking him slain who only lay amazed,\nBy pity prest, Zerbino leapt to ground,\nAnd from his deathlike face the vizor raised;\nAnd he, as wakened out of sleep profound,\nIn silence, hard upon Zerbino gazed;\nThen cried, \"It does not me, in truth, confound,\nTo think that I am overthrown by thee,\nWho seem'st the flower of errant chivalry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But it with reason grieves me this is done\nUpon account of a false woman's spite;\nWhose wicked cause I know not why you own,\nAn office ill according with your might:\nAnd when to you the occasion shall be known\nWhich urges me her wickedness to quite,\nWhene'er you think on it, you will repent\nHow she by you was saved, and I was shent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if enough of breath, although I fear\nThe contrary, is left me to expound\nHer evil actions, I shall make appear\nShe in all guilt transgresses every bound.\nI had a brother once: the youthful peer\nSet out from Holland's isle, our natal ground,\nTo serve Heraclius, 'mid his knights arrayed,\nWho then the Grecian empire's sceptre swayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Brother in arms and bosom-friend installed\nHere was he by a baron of that court,\nWho, in a pleasant site, and strongly walled,\nOn Servia's distant frontier had a fort.\nArgaeus he of whom I tell was called,\nHusband of that ill hag, whom in such sort\nHe loved, as passed all mean, and misbecame\nOne of his worth and honourable fame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But she, more volatile than leaf, when breeze\nOf autumn most its natural moisture dries,\nAnd strips the fluttering foliage from the trees,\nWhich, blown about, before its fury flies,\nChanges her humour, and her husband sees,\nWhom she some time had loved, with other eyes,\nAnd in her every wish and every thought\nSchemes how my brother's love may best be bought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But not Acroceraunus fronts the brine,\n— Ill-famed — against whose base the billow heaves,\nNor against Boreas stands the mountain pine,\nThat has a hundred times renewed its leaves,\nAnd towering high on Alp or Apennine,\nWith its fast root the rock as deeply cleaves,\nSo firmly as the youth resists the will\nOf that foul woman, sink of every ill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Now, as it oft befalls a cavalier\nWho seeks and finds adventure, high and low,\nIt happened that my gentle brother near\nHis comrade's fort was wounded by a foe;\nWhere often, uninvited by the peer,\nHe guested, was his host with him or no;\nAnd thither he resorted from the field,\nThere to repose until his wounds were healed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"While there he wounded lay, upon some need\nIt chanced Argaeus was compelled to ride.\nQuickly that wanton, from his presence freed,\nAs was her use, my brother's fealty tried.\nBut he, as one unstained in thought and deed,\nSo fell a goad no longer would abide;\nAnd to preserve his faith, as lures increased,\nOf many evils chose what seemed the least."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To break communion with the cavalier,\nTo him — of many — seemed the lightest ill,\nAnd go so far, that wanton should not hear\nMore of his name: this purpose to fulfil\nWas honester (though quitting one so dear\nWas hard than to content her evil will, ) \n\nOf her foul wishes to her lord impart,\nWho cherished her as fondly as his heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And though yet smarting with his wounds and pined,\nHe dons his arms, and from the tower departs;\nAnd wanders thence with firm and constant mind,\nNe'er to return again into those parts.\nBut nought availed the purpose he designed;\nHis projects Fortune baffled with new arts.\nThis while, behold!  the castellain returned,\nAnd bathed in bitter tears the wife discerned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And with flushed face, and hair in disarray,\nHe asks of her what had disturbed her mood;\nWho, ere she in reply a word will say,\nIs vainly more than once to answer wooed;\nAnd all the while is thinking in what way\nThe knight can best with vengeance be pursued.\nAnd well it suited with her fickle vein,\nLightly to change her love into disdain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Ah!  why should I conceal (in fine she cried)\nThe fault committed while you were away?\nFor though I it from all the world should hide,\nThis would my conscience to myself bewray.\nThe soul, which is with secret evil dyed,\nDoes with such penitence its fault appay,\nAs every corporal sufferance exceeds\nThat thou couldst deal me for my evil deeds;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `If evil be the deed, when done parforce.\nBut, be it what it may, the mischief know;\nThen, with my sword from this polluted corse,\nDelivered, let my spotless spirit go;\nAnd quench these wretched eyes, which in remorse,\nI, if I lived, on earth must ever throw,\nAs the least penance of so foul a blame,\nAnd, look on whom they may, must blush for shame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `My honour has been ruined by thy mate,\nWho to this body violence has done,\nAnd fearing lest I all to thee relate,\nWithout farewell the graceless churl is gone.'\nShe by this story made her husband hate\nThe youth, than whom before was dearer none.\nArgaeus credits all, without delay\nArms him, and, breathing vengeance, posts away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In knowledge of that country not to seek,\nHe overtook the knight in little space;\nFor my poor brother, yet diseased and weak,\nRode, unsuspicious, at an easy pace;\nArgaeus, eager his revenge to wreak,\nAssailed him straight in a sequestered place.\nMy brother would excuse him if he might,\nBut his indignant host insists on fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This one was sound and full of new disdain,\nThat weak and friendly, as aye wont to be:\nMy brother was ill fitted to sustain\nHis altered comrade's new-born enmity.\nPhilander, then unmeriting such pain,\n(So was the stripling named, described by me)\nNot gifted with the power to undergo\nSuch fierce assault, was taken by the foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Forbid it, Heaven!  I should be led astray\nSo by just wrath and thy iniquity,\n(To him Argaeus cried as thee to slay, ) \n\nWho loved thee once, and certes thou lovedst me,\nThough in the end thou ill didst this display,\nI yet desire this ample world may see\nThat, measured by my deeds, I rank above\nThyself in hate as highly as in love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `In other mode shall I chastise the deed,\nThan spilling more of thine ill blood.'  The peer,\nThis said, commands his followers, on a steed,\nOf verdant boughs composed to place a bier,\nAnd with the knight half-lifeless homeward speed,\nAnd in a tower enclose the cavalier;\nThere dooms the guiltless stripling to remain,\nAnd suffer prisonment's perpetual pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet nothing but his former liberty\nThence to depart was wanting to the knight;\nIn all the rest, as one at large and free,\nHe ordered, and was still obeyed aright.\nBut that ill dame her former phantasy\nPursuing ever with unwearied sprite,\nHaving the keys, repaired nigh every day\nTo the close turret where the prisoner lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And evermore my brother she assailed,\nAnd with more boldness prest her former suit.\n`Mark what to thee fidelity availed!'\n(She cries `which all mere perfidy repute. ) \n\nWith what triumphant joy shalt thou be hailed!\nWhat noble spoils are thine, what happy fruit!\nOh what a worthy guerdon is thy meed!\nBranded by all men for a traitor's deed!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `How well thou mightst have given, and without stain\nOf thine own honour, what I sought of thee!\nNow of so rigorous mood the worthy gain\nHave and enjoy.  In close captivity\nThou art; nor ever hope to break thy chain,\nUnless thou soften thy obduracy.\nBut, if compliant, I a mean can frame\nTo render thee thy liberty and fame.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `No, no; have thou no hope,' (replied the knight,)\n`That my true faith shall ever change, although\nIt thus should happen that, against all right,\nI should so hard a sentence undergo.\nLet the world blame.  Enough that in HIS sight\n— Who sees and judges every thing below,\nAnd in HIS grace divine my fame can clear —\nMy innocence unsullied shall appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Does not Argaeus deem enough to sty\nMe in his prison, let him take away\nThis noisome life.  Nor yet may Heaven deny\nIts meed, though ill the world my work appay.\nAnd yet he who condemns me may, when I\nAm parted from this tenement of clay,\nPerceive that he has wronged me in the end,\nAnd shall bewail when dead his faithful friend.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thus oftentimes that shameless woman prest\nThe good Philander, but obtained no fruit.\nNursing her blind desires, which knew not rest\nIn seeking what her wicked love may boot,\nShe her old vices, in her inmost breast,\nRansacks for what may best the occasion suit,\nAnd sifts them all: then, having overrun\nA thousand evil thoughts, resolved on one."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Six months she waited ere again she sought\nThe prisoner's tower, as she was wont before:\nFrom which the sad Philander hoped and thought\nThat love to him the dame no longer bore.\nLo!  Fortune for her an occasion wrought,\n(To evil deed propitious evermore)\nTo give effect, with memorable ill,\nTo her irrational and evil will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The husband had an ancient feud with one\nWho was by name Morando hight the fair;\nWho even within the fort would often run\nIn its lord's absence; but the knight's repair\nAt the wide distance of ten miles would shun,\nWas he assured the castellain was there:\nWho now, to lure him thither, bruited how\nHe for Jerusalem was bound by vow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Said he would go; and went.  Thus each who spies\nHis outset, of his journey spreads the fame:\nNor he, who only on his wife relies,\nTrusts any with his purpose but the dame,\nAnd home returned when dusky waxed the skies;\nNor ever, save at evening, thither came;\nAnd with changed ensigns, at the dawn of day,\nUnseen of any, always went his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He now on this side, now on the other side,\nRoved round his castle but to ascertain\nIf credulous Morando, who to ride\nThither was wonted, would return again.\nAll day he in the forest used to hide,\nAnd, when he saw the sun beneath the main,\nCame to the tower, and, through a secret gate,\nWas there admitted by his faithless mate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thus every one, except his consort ill,\nArgaeus many miles away suppose:\nShe, when 'tis time her errand to fulfil,\nHatching new mischief, to my brother goes.\nOf tears she has a ready shower at will,\nWhich from her eyes into her bosom flows,\n` — Where shall I succour find, now needed most,\nSo that my honour be not wholly lost,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And, with my own, my wedded lord's?' (she cries;)\n`I should feel no alarm, if he were here.\nThou knowst Morando, know if deities\nOr men he in Argaeus' absence fear.\nHe at this time tries all extremities;\nNor servant have I but by threat or prayer\nHe him to further his desire has swayed;\nNor know I whither to recur for aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Of my lord's absence hearing the report,\nAnd that he would not quickly homeward fare,\nHe had the insolence within my court,\nUpon no other pretext to repair;\nWho, were my absent lord within his fort,\nSo bold a deer not only would not dare,\nBut would not deem himself secure withal,\nBy Heaven!  at three miles' distance from his wall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And what he erst by messenger had sought,\nFrom me to-day has sued for face to face;\nAnd in such manner that long time I thought\nDishonour must have followed and disgrace;\nAnd if I had not humbly him besought,\nAnd feigned to yield to him with ready grace,\nHe haply would have ravished that by force,\nWhich he expects to win by milder course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I promise, not designing to comply,\nFor void is contract made in fear; alone\nFrom his ill purpose would I put him by,\nAnd what he then parforce would else have done.\nSo stands the case: the single remedy\nLies in yourself: my honour else is gone,\nAnd that of my Argaeus; which as dear,\nOr more so, than your own you vowed whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `If you refuse me, I shall say, you show\nThat you have not the faith which you pretended,\nBut that in cruelty you said me no,\nWhen vainly were my tears on you expended,\nAnd no wise for Argaeus' sake, although\nWith this pretext you have yourself defended.\nOur loves bad been concealed and free from blame;\nBut here I stand exposed to certain shame.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `To me such preface needs not (said anew\nThe good Philander), bound by amity\nTo my Argaeus still; thy pleasure shew:\nI what I ever was will be, and I,\nAlthough from him I bear such ill undue,\nAccuse him not; for him would I defy\nEven death itself; and let the world, allied\nWith my ill destiny, against me side!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The impious woman answered, ` 'Tis my will\nThou slay him who would do us foul despite;\nNor apprehend to encounter any ill:\nFor I the certain mean will tell aright.\nHe will return, his purpose to fulfil,\nAt the third hour, when darkest is the night;\nAnd, at a preconcerted signal made,\nBe without noise by me within conveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Let it not irk thee to await the peer\nWithin my chamber, where no light will be;\nTill I shall make him doff his warlike gear,\nAnd, almost naked, yield him up to thee.'\nSo did his wife into that quicksand steer\nHer hapless husband (it appears to me)\nIf wife she rightly could be called; more fell\nAnd cruel than a fury sprung from hell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She drew my brother forth, that guilty night,\nWith his good arms in hand, and him again\nSecreted in the chamber without light,\nTill thither came the wretched castellain.\nAs it was ordered, all fell out aright,\nFor seldom ill design is schemed in vain.\nSo fell Argaeus by Philander's sword,\nWho for Morando took the castle's lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"One blow divided head and neck; for nought\nWas there of helm, the warrior to defend.\nWithout a struggle was Argaeus brought\nTo his unhappy life's disastrous end,\nAnd he who slew him never had such thought,\nNor this would have believed: to aid his friend\nIntent, (strange chance! he wrought him in that blow ) \n\nThe worst that could be done by mortal foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When now, unknown, on earth Argaeus lay,\nMy brother to Gabrina gave the blade,\n(So was she named who lived but to betray. ) \n\nShe, who discovery had till then delayed,\nWills that Philander with a light survey\nThe man whom he on earth has lifeless laid,\nAnd she, with the assistance of the light,\nShows him Argaeus in the murdered wight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And threatens, save he with desires comply\nTo which her bosom had been long a prey,\nWhat he would be unable to deny\nShe to the assembled household will display,\nAnd he like traitor and assassin die,\nUpon her tale, in ignominious way:\nAnd minds him fame is not to be despised,\nAlbeit so little life by him be prized."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Philander stood oppressed with grief and fear,\nWhen his mistake to him the woman showed,\nAnd to have slain her in his wrath went near,\nAnd long be doubted, so his choler glowed;\nAnd, but that Reason whispered in his ear\nThat he was in an enemy's abode,\nFor lack of faulchion in his empty sheath,\nHe would have torn her piece-meal with his teeth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As sometimes vessel by two winds which blow\nFrom different points is vext upon the main,\nAnd now one speeds the bark an-end, and now\nAnother squall impels her back again;\nStill on her poop assailed, or on her prow,\nTill she before the strongest flies amain:\nPhilander, so distraught by two designs,\nTakes what he pregnant with least ill opines."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Reason demonstrates with what peril fraught\nHis case, not more with death than lasting stain,\nIf in the castle were that murder taught;\nNor any time has he to sift his brain.\nWill he or nill he, in conclusion nought\nIs left him but the bitter cup to drain.\nThus in his troubled heart prevailing more,\nHis fear his resolution overbore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The fear of shameful punishment's pursuit\nMade him with many protestations swear\nTo grant in every thing Gabrina's suit,\nIf from the fortilage they safely fare.\nSo plucks that impious dame, parforce, the fruit\nOf her desires, and thence retreat the pair.\nThus home again the young Philander came,\nLeaving behind him a polluted name;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And deeply graven in his bosom bore\nThe image of his friend so rashly slain;\nBy this to purchase, to his torment sore,\nA Progne, a Medea; impious gain!\n— And but his knightly faith, and oaths he swore,\nWere to his fury as a curbing rein,\nFrom him when safe she would have met her fate;\nBut lived subjected to his bitterest hate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thenceforth he nevermore was seen to smile:\nAll his discourse was sad, and still ensued\nSobs from his breast; afflicted in the style\nOf vext Orestes, when he in his mood\nHad slain his mother and Aegysthus vile;\nBy vengeful furies for the deed pursued.\nTill broken by the ceaseless grief he fed,\nHe sickened and betook himself to bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Now in the harlot, when she had discerned\nThis other set by her so little store,\nThe former amorous flame was quickly turned\nInto despiteous rage and hatred sore;\nNor with less wrath she towards my brother burned\nThan for Argaeus she had felt before;\nAnd she disposed herself, in treasons versed,\nTo slay her second husband like the first."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of a deceitful leech she made assay,\nWell fitted for the work she had in hand,\nWho better knew what deadly poisons slay\nThan he the force of healing syrup scanned;\nAnd promised him his service to repay\nWith a reward exceeding his demand,\nWhen he should, with some drink of deadly might,\nOf her detested husband rid her sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In presence of myself and more beside,\nThe wicked elder, with his deadly dole,\nApproaching my unhappy brother, cried,\n`It was a sovereign drink to make him whole.'\nBut here a new device Gabrina tried,\nAnd, ere the sickly man could taste the bowl,\nTo rid her of accomplice in the deed,\nOr to defraud him of his promised meed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Seized on his hand, the instant he presented\nThe poison to my brother.  `Ill my fear,\n(Exclaimed the dame by you would be resented, ) \n\nExcited for a spouse I hold so dear.\nI, that the beverage has not been fermented\nWith evil drug and poisonous, will be clear;\nNor deem it meet that you to him convey\nThe proffered bowl, unless you take the say.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In what condition think you, sir, remained\nThe wretched elder by his fears opprest?\nThus by the woman's suddenness constrained,\nHe had no time for thinking what were best.\nHe, lest more doubt of him be entertained,\nTastes of the chalice, at Gabrina's hest;\nAnd the sick man, emboldened so, drinks up\nAll the remainder of the poisoned cup."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As the trained hawk of crooked talon who\nClutches the partridge, when about to eat,\nIs by the dog, she deems her comrade true,\nO'ertaken and defrauded of the meat;\nSo on ill gain intent, the leech, in lieu\nOf the expected aid, received defeat.\nHear, thus, what sovereign wickedness will dare,\nAnd be like fate each greedy miscreant's share!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This past and done, the leech would homeward speed,\nThat he, to counteract the pest he bore\nWithin his bowels, in this fearful need,\nMight use some secret of his cunning lore;\nBut this the wicked dame would not concede,\nForbidding him to issue thence before\nHis patient's stomach should the juice digest,\nAnd its restoring power be manifest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No prayer will move, nor offered price will buy\nThe woman's leave to let him thence depart.\nThe desperate man who saw that death was nigh,\nAnd sure to follow, quickly changed his part;\nAnd told the story to the standers-by;\nNor could she cover it with all her art.\nThus what he wont to do by many a one,\nThat goodly doctor by himself has done;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And follows with his soul my brother true,\nThat hence, already freed, was gone before.\nWe, the assistants, that the matter knew\nFrom the old man who lingered little more,\nTook that abominable monster, who\nMore cruel was than beast in forest hoar,\nAnd, prisoned in a darksome place, reserved\nTo perish in the fire, as she deserved.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said Hermonides, and had pursued\nHis tale, and told how she from prison fled;\nBut suffered from his wound a pang so shrewd,\nHe fell reversed upon his grassy bed.\nMeanwhile two squires, who served him in the wood,\nA rustic bier of sturdy branches spread.\nTheir master upon this the servants lay,\nWho could not thence be borne in other way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino, in excuse, assured the peer,\nHe grieved so good a knight to have offended;\nBut, as was still the use of cavalier,\nHad guarded her who in his guidance wended;\nNor had he else preserved his honour clear:\nFor when the dame was to his care commended,\nHer to defend his promise he had plight\nFrom all men, to the utmost of his might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, if he might, is any thing beside,\nWould readily assist him in his need.\n— His only wish, (the cavalier replied,)\nWas, he might be from ill Gabrina freed,\nEre him some mighty mischief should betide,\nOf future penitence the bitter seed.\nGabrina keeps on earth her downcast eye;\nFor ill the simple truth admits reply."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino thence, upon the promised way,\nWith the old woman in his escort, went,\nAnd inly cursed her all the livelong day,\nThat in her cause that baron he had shent.\nAnd having heard the knight her guilt display,\nWho was instructed in her evil bent,\nHe — if before he had her at despite —\nSo loathed her, she was poison to his sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Well read in young Zerbino's hate, the dame\nWould not by him in malice be outdone,\nNor bated him an inch, but in that game\nOf deadly hatred set him two for one.\nHer face was with the venom in a flame\nWherewith her swelling bosom overrun.\n'Twas thus in such concord as I say,\nThese through the ancient wood pursued their way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When, lo!  as it is now nigh eventide,\nThey a mixt sound of blows and outcries hear,\nWhich seem a sign of battle fiercely plied,\nAnd (as the deafening noise demonstrates near. ) \n\nTo mark what this might be, towards that side\nWhence came the tumult, moved the Scottish peer;\nNor is in following him Gabrina slow:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto you shall know.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 22"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Atlantes' magic towers Astolpho wight\nDestroys, and frees his thralls from prison-cell.\nBradamant finds Rogero, who in fight\nO'erthrows four barons from the warlike sell,\nWhen on their way to save an errant knight\nDoomed to devouring fire: the four who fell\nFor impious Pinnabel maintained the strife,\nWhom, after, Bradamant deprives of life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ye courteous dames, and to your lovers dear,\nYou that are with one single love content;\nThough, 'mid so many and many, it is clear\nRight few of you are of such constant bent;\nBe not displeased at what I said whilere,\nWhen I so bitterly Gabrina shent,\nNor if I yet expend some other verse\nIn censure of the beldam's mind perverse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such was she; and I hide not what is true;\nSo was enjoined me for a task by one\nWhose will is law; therefore is honour due\nTo constant heart throughout my story done.\nHe who betrayed his master to the Jew\nFor thirty pence, nor Peter wronged, nor John,\nNor less renowned is Hypermnestra's fame,\nFor her so many wicked sisters' shame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For one I dare to censure in my lays,\nFor so the story wills which I recite,\nOn the other hand, a hundred will I praise,\nAnd make their virtue dim the sun's fair light;\nBut turning to the various pile I raise,\n(Gramercy!  dear to many of the knight ) \n\nOf Scotland I was telling, who hard-by\nHad heard, as was rehearsed, a piercing cry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He entered, 'twixt two hills, a narrow way,\nFrom whence was heard the cry; nor far had hied,\nEre to a vale he came shut out from day,\nWhere he before him a dead knight espied.\nWho I shall tell; but first I must away\nFrom France, in the Levant to wander wide,\nTill I the paladin Astolpho find,\nWho westward had his course from thence inclined."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I in the cruel city left the peer,\nWhence, with the formidable bugle's roar,\nHe had chased the unfaithful people in their fear,\nAnd has preserved himself from peril sore;\nAnd with the sound had made his comrades rear\nThen sail, and fly with noted scorn that shore.\nNow following him, I say, the warrior took\nThe Armenian road, and so that land forsook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, after some few days, in Natoly\nFinds himself, and towards Brusa goes his ways;\nHence wending, on the hither side o' the sea,\nMakes Thrace; through Hungary by the Danube lays\nHis course, and as his horse had wings to flee,\nTraverses in less time than twenty days\nBoth the Moravian and Bohemian line;\nThreaded Franconia next, and crost the Rhine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Aix-la-Chapelle thence, through Arden's wood,\nCame and embarked upon the Flemish strand.\nTo sea, with southern breeze his vessel stood;\nAnd, so the favouring wind her canvas fanned,\nThat he, at little distance, Albion viewed\nBy noon, and disembarked upon her land.\nHe backed his horse, and so the rowels plied,\nIn London he arrived by even-tide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here, learning afterwards that Otho old\nHas lain for many months in Paris-town,\nAnd that anew nigh every baron bold\nHas after his renowned example done,\nHe straightway does for France his sails unfold,\nAnd to the mouth of Thames again is gone.\nWhence issuing forth, with all his canvas spread,\nFor Calais he directs the galley's head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A breeze which, from the starboard blowing light,\nHad tempted forth Astolpho's bark to sea,\nBy little and by little, waxed in might,\nAnd so at last obtains the mastery,\nThe pilot is constrained to veer outright,\nLest by the billows swampt his frigate be,\nAnd he, departing from his first design,\nKeeps the bark straight before the cresting brine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now to the right, now to the other hand,\nSped by the tempest, through the foaming main,\nThe vessel ran; she took the happy land\nAt last nigh Rouen; and forthwith, in chain\nAnd plate Astolpho cased, and girt with brand,\nBade put the saddle upon Rabicane;\nDeparted thence, and (what availed him more\nThan thousands armed with him his bugle bore; )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And traversing a forest, at the feet\nOf a fair hill, arrived beside a font,\nWhat time the sheep foregoes his grassy meat,\nPenned in the cabin or the hollow mount;\nAnd, overcome by feverish thirst and heat,\nLifted the weighty morion from his front;\nTethered his courser in the thickest wood,\nAnd, with intent to drink, approached the flood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His lips he had not wetted in its bed\nBefore a youthful rustic, ambushed near,\nSprang from a copse, backed Rabican, and fled\nWith the good courser of the cavalier.\nAstolpho hears the noise and lifts his head,\nAnd, when he sees his mighty loss so clear,\nSatiate, although he had not drunk, upstarts,\nAnd after the young churl in fury darts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That robber did not let the courser strain\nAt speed, or he had from the warrior shot;\nBut loosening now and tightening now the rein,\nFled at a gallop or a steady trot.\nFrom the deep forest issued forth the twain,\nAfter long round, and reached in fine the spot\nWhere so many illustrious lords were shent:\nWorse prisoners they than if in prison pent!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On Rabican, who with the wind might race,\nThe villain sped, within the enchanter's won.\nImpeded by his shield and iron case,\nParforce Astolpho far behind him run;\nYet there arrives as well, but every trace\nOf what the warrior had pursued is gone.\nHe neither Rabican nor thief can meet,\nAnd vainly rolls his eyes and plies his feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He plies his feet, and searches still in vain\nThroughout the house, hall, bower, or galleried rows:\nYet labours evermore, with fruitless pain\nAnd care, to find the treacherous churl; nor knows\nWhere he can have secreted Rabicane,\nWho every other animal outgoes:\nAnd vainly searches all day the dome about,\nAbove, below, within it, and without."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, wearied and confused with wandering wide,\nPerceived the place was by enchantment wrought,\nAnd of the book he carried at his side,\nBy Logistilla given in India, thought;\nBestowed, should new enchantment him betide,\nThat needful succour might therein be sought.\nHe to the index turns, and quickly sees\nWhat pages show the proper remedies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I' the book, of that enchanted house at large\nWas written, and in this was taught the way\nTo foil the enchanter, and to set at large\nThe different prisoners, subject to his sway.\nOf these illusions and these frauds in charge,\nA spirit pent beneath the threshold lay;\nAnd the stone raised which kept him fast below,\nWith him the palace into smoke would go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho with desire to bring to end\nAn enterprise so passing fair, delays\nNo more, but to the task his force does bend,\nAnd prove how much the heavy marble weighs.\nAs old Atlantes sees the knight intend\nTo bring to scorn his art and evil ways,\nSuspicious of the ill which may ensue,\nHe moves to assail him with enchantments new."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, with his spells and shapes of devilish kind,\nMakes the duke different from his wont appear;\nTo one a giant, and to one a hind,\nTo other an ill-visaged cavalier;\nEach, in the form which in the thicket blind\nThe false enchanter wore, beholds the peer.\nSo that they all, with purpose to have back\nWhat the magician took, the duke attack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Child, Gradasso, Iroldo, Bradamant,\nPrasildo, Brandimart, and many more,\nAll, cheated by this new illusion, pant\nTo slay the English baron, angered sore;\nBut he abased their pride and haughty vaunt,\nWho straight bethought him of the horn be bore.\nBut for the succour of its echo dread,\nThey, without fail, had laid Astolpho dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But he no sooner has the bugle wound\nAnd poured a horrid larum, than in guise\nOf pigeons at the musquet's scaring sound,\nThe troop of cavaliers affrighted flies.\nNo less the necromancer starts astound,\nNo less he from his den in panic hies;\nTroubled and pale, and hurrying evermore\nTill out of hearing of the horrid roar"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warder fled; with him his prisoned train,\nAnd many steeds as well are fled and gone;\n(These more than rope is needed to restrain)\nWho after their astounded masters run,\nScared by the sound; nor cat nor mouse remain,\nWho seem to hear in it, \"Lay on, lay on.\"\nRabican with the rest had broke his bands,\nBut that he fell into Astolpho's hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, having chased the enchanter Moor away,\nUpraised the heavy threshold from the ground;\nBeneath which, figures and more matters lay,\nThat I omit; desirous to confound\nThe spell which did the magic dome upstay,\nThe duke made havock of whate'er he found,\nAs him the book he carried taught to do:\nAnd into mist and smoke all past from view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There he found fastened by a golden chain\nRogero's famous courser, him I say\nGiven by the wizard, that to the domain\nOf false Alcina him he might convey:\nOn which, equipt with Logistilla's rein,\nTo France Rogero had retraced his way,\nAnd had from Ind to England rounded all\nThe right-hand side of the terrestrial ball."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I know not if you recollect how tied\nTo a tree Rogero left his rein, the day\nGalaphron's naked daughter from his side\nVanished, and him did with that scorn appay.\nThe courser, to his wonder who espied,\nReturned to him whom he was used to obey;\nBeneath the old enchanter's care to dwell,\nAnd stayed with him till broken was the spell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At nought Astolpho could more joyous be\nThan this; of all things fortunate the best:\nIn that the hippogryph so happily\nOffered himself; that he might scower the rest,\n(As much he coveted of land and sea, ) \n\nAnd in few days the ample world invest.\nHim well he knew, how fit for his behoof;\nFor of his feats he had elsewhere made proof."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him he that day in India proved, when sped\nHe was by sage Melissa, from the reign\nOf that ill woman who him, sore bested,\nHad changed from man to myrtle on the plain;\nHad marked and noted how his giddy head\nWas formed by Logistilla to the rein;\nAnd saw how well instructed by her care\nRogero was, to guide him every where."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Minded to take the hippogryph, he flung\nThe saddle on him, which lay near, and bitted\nThe steed, by choosing, all the reins among,\nThis part or that, until his mouth was fitted:\nFor in that place were many bridles hung,\nBelonging to the coursers which flitted.\nAnd now alone, intent upon his flight,\nThe thought of Rabicane detained the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Good cause he had to love that Rabicane,\nFor better horse was not to run with lance,\nAnd him had he from the remotest reign\nOf India ridden even into France:\nAfter much thought, he to some friend would fain\nPresent him, rather than so, left to chance,\nAbandon there the courser, as a prey,\nTo the first stranger who should pass that way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He stood upon the watch if he could view\nSome hunter in the forest, or some hind,\nTo whom he might commit the charge, and who\nMight to some city lead the horse behind.\nHe waited all that day and till the new\nHad dawned, when, while the twilight yet was blind,\nHe thought he saw, as he expecting stood,\nA cavalier approaching through the wood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But it behoves that, ere the rest I say,\nI Bradamant and good Rogero find.\nAfter the horn had ceased, and, far away,\nThe beauteous pair had left the dome behind,\nRogero looked, and knew what till that day\nHe had seen not, by Atlantes rendered blind.\nAtlantes had effected by his power,\nThey should not know each other till that hour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero looks on Bradamant, and she\nLooks on Rogero in profound surprise\nThat for so many days that witchery\nHad so obscurred her altered mind and eyes.\nRejoiced, Rogero clasps his lady free,\nCrimsoning with deeper than the rose's dyes,\nAnd his fair love's first blossoms, while he clips\nThe gentle damsel, gathers from her lips."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A thousand times they their embrace renew,\nAnd closely each is by the other prest;\nWhile so delighted are those lovers two,\nTheir joys are ill contained within their breast.\nDeluded by enchantments, much they rue\nThat while they were within the wizard's rest,\nThey should not e'er have one another known,\nAnd have so many happy days foregone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The gentle Bradamant, who was i' the vein\nTo grant whatever prudent virgin might,\nTo solace her desiring lover's pain,\nSo that her honour should receive no slight;\n— If the last fruits he of her love would gain,\nNor find her ever stubborn, bade the knight,\nHer of Duke Aymon through fair mean demand;\nBut be baptized before he claimed her hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero good, who not alone to be\nA Christian for the love of her were fain,\nAs his good sire had been, and anciently\nHis grandsire and his whole illustrious strain,\nBut for her pleasure would immediately\nResign whatever did of life remain,\nSays, \"I not only, if 'tis thy desire,\nWill be baptized by water, but by fire.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then on his way to be baptized he hied,\nThat he might next espouse the martial may,\nWith Bradamant; who served him as a guide\nTo Vallombrosa's fane, an abbey gray,\nRich, fair, nor less religious, and beside,\nCourteous to whosoever passed that way;\nAnd they encountered, issuing from the chase,\nA woman, with a passing woful face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, as still courteous, still humane\nTo all, but woman most, when he discerned\nHer dainty visage furrowed by a rain\nOf lovely tears, sore pitied her, and burned\nWith the desire to know her grievous pain;\nAnd having to the mournful lady turned,\nBesought her, after fair salute, to show\nWhat cause had made her eyes thus overflow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And she, uplifting their moist rays and bright,\nMost kindly to the inquiring Child replied;\nAnd of the cause of her unhappy plight,\nHim, since he sought it, fully satisfied.\n\"Thou hast to understand, O gentle knight,\nMy visage is so bathed with tears,\" she cried,\n\"In pity to a youth condemned to die\nThis very day, within a town hard by."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Loving a gentle lady and a gay,\nThe daughter of Marsilius, king of Spain,\nAnd feigning, veiled in feminine array,\nThe modest roll of eye and girlish strain,\nWith her each night the amorous stripling lay,\nNor any had suspicion of the twain:\nBut nought so hidden is, but searching eye\nIn the long run the secret will espy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"One first perceived it, and then spoke with two,\nThose two with more, till to the king 'twas said;\nOf whom but yesterday a follower true\nGave order to surprise the pair in bed,\nAnd in the citadel the prisoners new,\nTo separate dungeons in that fortress led;\nNor think I that enough of day remains\nTo save the lover from his cruel pains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I fled, not to behold such cruelty,\nFor they alive the wretched youth will burn;\nNor think I aught could more afflicting be\nThan such fair stripling's torment to discern,\nOr that hereafter thing can pleasure me\nSo much, but that it will to trouble turn,\nIf memory retrace the cruel flame\nWhich preyed upon his fair and dainty frame.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Touched deeply, Bradamant his danger hears,\nIn heart sore troubled at the story shown;\nAs anxious for the lover, it appears,\nAs if he were a brother of her own:\nNor certes wholly causeless are her fears,\nAs in an after verse will be made known,\nThen, to Rogero: \"Him to keep from harms,\nMeseems we worthily should turn our arms.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And to that melancholy damsel said:\n\"Place us but once within the walls, and I,\nSo that the youth be not already dead,\nWill be your warrant that he shall not die.\"\nRogero, who the kindly bosom read\nOf Bradamant, still full of piety,\nFelt himself but all over with desire\nTo snatch the unhappy stripling from the fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And to the maid, whose troubled face apears\nBathed with a briny flood, \"Why wait we? — need\nIs here of speedy succour, not of tears.\nDo you but where the youth is prisoned lead;\nHim from a thousand swords, a thousand spears,\nWe vow to save; so it be done with speed.\nBut haste you, lest too tardy be our aid,\nAnd he be burnt, which succour is delayed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The haughty semblance and the lofty say\nOf these, who with such wondrous daring glowed,\nThat hope, which long had ceased to be her stay,\nAgain upon the grieving dame bestowed:\nBut, for she less the distance of the way\nDreaded, than interruption of the road,\nLest they, through this, should take that path in vain,\nThe damsel stood suspended and in pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then said: \"If to the place our journey lay\nBy the highroad, which is both straight and plain,\nThat we in time might reach it, I should say,\nBefore the fire was lit; but we must strain\nBy path so foul and crooked, that a day\nTo reach the city would suffice with pain;\nAnd when, alas!  we thither shall have sped,\nI fear that we shall find the stripling dead.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And wherefore take we not the way most near?\"\nRogero answers; and the dame replies,\n\"Because fast by where we our course should steer,\nA castle of the Count of Poictiers lies:\nWhere Pinnabel for dame and cavalier\nDid, three days past, a shameful law devise;\nThan whom more worthless living wight is none,\nThe Count Anselmo d'Altaripa's son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No cavalier or lady by that rest\nWithout some noted scorn and injury goes;\nBoth of their coursers here are dispossest,\nAnd knight his arms and dame her gown foregoes.\nNo better cavaliers lay lance in rest,\nNor have for years in France against their foes,\nThan four, who for Sir Pinnabel have plight\nTheir promise to maintain the castle's right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whence first arose the usage, which began\nBut three days since, you now, sir knight, shall hear;\nAnd shall the cause, if right or evil, scan,\nWhich moved the banded cavaliers to swear.\nSo ill a lady has the Castellan,\nSo wayward, that she is without a peer:\nWho, on a day, as with the count she went,\nI know not whither, by a knight was shent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This knight, as flouted by that bonnibel,\nFor carrying on his croup an ancient dame,\nEncountered with her champion Pinnabel,\nOf overweening pride and little fame:\nHim he o'erturned, made alight as well,\nAnd put her to the proof, if sound or lame;\n— Left her on foot, and had that woman old\nIn the dismounted damsel's garment stoled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She, who remained on foot, in fell despite,\nGreedy of vengeance, and athirst for ill,\nLeagued with the faithless Pinnabel, a wight\nAll evil prompt to further and fulfil,\nSays she shall never rest by day nor night,\nNor ever know a happy hour, until\nA thousand knights and dames are dispossest\nOf courser, and of armour, and of vest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Four puissant knights arrived that very day\nIt happened, at a place of his, and who\nHad all of them from regions far away\nCome lately to those parts: so many true\nAnd valiant warriors, skilled in martial play,\nOur age has seen not.  These the goodly crew:\nGuido the savage, but a stripling yet,\nGryphon, and Aquilant, and Sansonet!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Them at the fortilage, of which I told,\nSir Pinnabel received with semblance fair,\nNext seized the ensuing night the warriors bold\nIn bed, nor loosed, till he had made them swear\nThat (he such period fixt they in his hold ) \n\nShould be his faithful champions for a year\nAnd month; and of his horse and arms deprive\nWhatever cavalier should there arrive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And any damsel whom the stranger bore\nWith him, dismount, and strip her of her vest.\nSo, thus surprised, the warlike prisoners swore;\nSo were constrained to observe the cruel hest,\nThough grieved and troubled: nor against the four,\nIt seems, can any joust, but vails his crest.\nKnight infinite have come, but one and all,\nAfoot and without arms have left that Hall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Their order is, who from the castle hies,\nThe first by lot, shall meet the foe alone,\nBut if he find a champion of such guise\nAs keeps the sell, while he himself is thrown,\nThe rest must undertake the enterprise,\nEven to the death, against that single one,\nRanged in a band.  If such each single knight,\nImagine the assembled warriors' might!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor stands it with our haste, which all delay,\nAll let forbids, that you beside that tower\nBe forced to stop and mingle in the fray:\nFor grant that you be conquerors in the stower,\n(And as your presence warrants well, you may,)\n'Tis not a thing concluded in an hour.\nAnd if all day he wait our succour, I\nMuch fear the stripling in the fire will die.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Regard we not this hindrance of our quest,\"\nRogero cried, \"But do we what we may!\nLet HIM who rules the heavens ordain the rest,\nOr Fortune, if he leave it in her sway;\nTo you shall by this joust be manifest\nIf we can aid the youth; for whom to-day\nThey on a ground so causeless and so slight,\nAs you to us rehearsed, the fire will light.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero ceased; and in the nearest way\nThe damsel put the pair without reply:\nNor these beyond three miles had fared, when they\nReached bridge and gate, the place of forfeitry,\nOf horse and arms and feminine array,\nWith peril sore of life.  On turret high,\nUpon first sight of them, a sentinel\nBeat twice upon the castle's larum-bell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And lo, in eager hurry from the gate\nAn elder trotting on hackney made!\nAnd he approaching cried, \"Await, await!\n— Hola!  halt, sirs, for here a fine is paid:\nAnd I to you the usage shall relate,\nIf this has not to you before been said.\"\nAnd to the three forthwith began to tell\nThe use established there by Pinnabel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He next proceeds, as he had wont before\nTo counsel other errant cavalier.\n\"Unrobe the lady,\" (said the elder hoar,)\n\"My sons, and leave your steeds and martial geer;\nNor put yourselves in peril, and with four\nSuch matchless champions hazard the career.\nClothes, arms, and coursers every where are rife;\nBut not to be repaired is loss of life.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" — No more!\"  (Rogero said  \"No more!  for I ) \n\nAm well informed of all, and hither speed\nWith the intention, here by proof to try\nIf, what my heart has vouched, I am in deed.\nFor sign or threat I yield not panoply,\nIf nought beside I hear, nor vest nor steed.\nAnd this my comrade, I as surely know,\nThese for mere words as little will forego."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But let me face to face, by Heaven, espy\nThose who would take my horse and arms away;\nFor we have yet beyond that hill to hie,\nAnd little time can here afford to stay.\"\n\"Behold the man,\" that ancient made reply,\n\"Clear of the bridge!\" — Nor did in this missay;\nFor thence a warrior pricked, who, powdered o'er\nWith snowy flowers, a crimson surcoat wore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant for long time with earnest prayer,\nFor courtesy the good Rogero prest,\nTo let her from his sell the warrior bear,\nWho with white flowers had purfled o'er his vest.\nBut moved him not; and to Rogero's share\nMust leave, and do herself, what liked him best.\nHe willed the whole emprize his own should be,\nAnd Bradamant should stand apart to see."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Child demanded of that elder, who\nWas he that from the gate first took his way,\nAnd he, \" 'Tis Sansonet; of crimson hue,\nI know his surcoat, with white flowers gay.\"\nWithout a word exchanged, the warlike two\nDivide the ground, and short is the delay.\nFor they against each other, levelling low\nTheir spears, and hurrying sore their coursers, go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while had issued from the fortress near,\nWith many footmen girt, Sir Pinnabel,\nAll ready to despoil the cavalier,\nWho in the warlike joust should void is sell.\nAt one another spurred in bold career\nThe knights, with their huge lances rested well.\nUp to the points nigh equal was each stick,\nOf stubborn native oak, and two palms thick."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sansonet, of such staves, above five pair\nHad made them sever from the living stock,\nIn neighboring wood, and bade his followers bear\nTwo of them hither, destined for that shock:\nSuch truncheons to withstand, well needed-were\nA shield and cuirass of the diamond rock.\nOne he had made them give his foe, and one\nHe kept himself, the present course to run."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With these which might the solid anvil bore,\n(So well their ends were pointed there and here, ) \n\nEach aiming at the shield his foeman wore,\nThe puissant warriors shocked in mid career.\nThat of Rogero, wrought with magic lore,\nBy fiends, had little from the stroke to fear:\nI of the buckler speak Atlantes made,\nOf whose rare virtues I whilere have said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I have already said, the enchanted light\nStrikes with such force on the beholder's eyes,\nThat, at the shield's discovery, every wight\nIs blinded, or on earth half lifeless lies.\nWherefore, well mantled with a veil, the knight\nKeeps it, unless some passing need surprise:\nImpassive is the shield as well believed,\nSince it no damage in the shock received."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The other by less skilful artist wrought,\nDid not so well that weightless blow abide,\nBut, as if smit by thunder, in a thought,\nGave way before the steel, and opened wide;\nGave way before the griding steel, which sought\nThe arm beneath, by this ill fortified:\nSo that Sir Sansonet was smote, and reeled,\nIn his departure, unhorsed upon the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this was the first comrade of the train\nThat of the tower maintained the usage fell,\nWho there had failed another's spoil to gain,\nAnd voided in the joust his knightly sell.\nWho laughs, as well will sometimes have to plain,\nAnd find that Fortune will by fits rebel.\nAnew the warder on his larum beats,\nAnd to the other knights the sign repeats."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while Sir Pinnabello had drawn near\nTo Bradamant, and prayed that she would shew\nWhat warrior had his knight in the career\nSmith with such prowess.  That the guerdon due\nTo his ill deeds might wait the cavalier,\nGod's justice that ill-doer thither drew\nOn the same courser, which before the Cheat\nFrom Bradamant had taken by deceit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas now exactly the eighth month was ended,\nSince, if you recollect, upon his way,\nThe faithless Maganzese, with whom she wended,\nCast into Merlin's tomb the martial may;\nWhen her a bough, which fell with her, defended\nFrom death, or her good Fortune, rather say;\nAnd Pinnabel bore off her courser brave,\nDeeming the damsel buried in the cave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The courser, and, through him, the cavalier,\nBradamant knew to be the wicked Count,\nAnd, having heard him, and perused him near,\nWith more attentive eye and front to front —\n\"This is the man,\" (the damsel said \" 'tis clear, ) \n\nWho erst designed me outrage and affront.\nLo!  him the traitor's sin doth hither speed,\nOf all his treasons to receive the meed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To threaten him with vengeance, and to lay\nHands on her sword and charge him now, was done\nAll in a thought; but first she barred the way\nBy which he might his fortilage have won.\nTo earth himself like fox, in his dismay,\nSir Pinnabel has every hope foregone.\nHe screaming loud, nor ever making head\nAgainst the damsel, through the forest fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pale and dismayed his spurs the caitiff plied\nWhose last hope of escape in flight was found;\nWhile with her ready sword, Dordona's pride\nWas at his flank, and prest him in his round,\nHunting him close and ever fast beside:\nLoud is the uproar, and the woods resound.\nNothing of this is at the castle kenned,\nFor only to Rogero all attend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The other three, who from the fortress came,\nThis while had issued forth upon their way,\nAnd brought with them the ill-accustomed dame,\nWho made wayfarers that ill use obey.\nIn all (who rather than prolong with blame\nTheir life, would choose to perish in the fray),\nThe kindling visage burns, and heart is woe,\nThat to assail one man so many go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The cruel courtezan by whom was made,\nAnd by whose hest maintained, that evil rite,\nReminds the warriors that they are arrayed\nBy oath and pact, to avenge her in the fight.\n\"If with this lance alone thy foes are laid\nOn earth, why should I band with other knight?\"\n(Guido the savage said \"and, if I lie, ) \n\nOff with my head, for I consent to die.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So Aquilant, so Gryphon.  For the twain\nSingly against a single foe would run;\nAnd rather would be taken, rather slain,\nThan he should be assailed by more than one.\nTo them exclaimed the woman: \"Why in vain\nWaste you so many words, where fruit is none?\nI brought you here that champion's arms to take,\nNot other laws and other pacts to make."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You should have offered, when in prison-cell,\nThis your excuse; which now too late is made.\n'Tis yours the law's observance to compel,\nAnd not with lying tongue your oath evade.\"\n\" — Behold!  the arms; behold, with a new sell\nAnd cloth, the goodly steed!\"  Rogero said,\n\"Behold with these, as well, the damsel's vest!\nIf these you covet, why your course arrest?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She of the castle presses on this side,\nOn that Rogero rates, and calls them on;\nTill they parforce, t'wards him, together hied:\nBut red with shame, are to the encounter gone.\nForemost appeared 'mid those three knights of pride,\nOf Burgundy's good marquis either son.\nBut Guido, who was borne on heavier steed,\nCame at some interval, with tardier speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With the same lance with which he overbore\nSir Sansonet, Rogero came to fight;\nWell-covered with the shield which heretofore\nAtlantes used on Pyrenean height;\nI say the enchanted buckler, which, too sore\nFor human sufferance, dazed the astonished sight:\nTo which Rogero, as a last resource,\nIn the most pressing peril had recourse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Although three times alone the Child was fain\n(And, certes sore bested this to display; ) \n\nTwice when he from the wanton Fairy's reign\nWas to that soberer region on his way!\nLast, when the unsated Orc upon the main,\nBy this astounded, 'mid the sea-foam lay;\nWhich would have fed upon the naked maid,\nSo cruel to the Child who brought her aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Save these three times, he has preserved the shield\nBeneath its veil, but covered in such wise\nThat it may quickly be to sight revealed,\nIf he in need of its good succour lies.\nWith this, as said before, he came a-field\nAs boldly, as if those three enemies,\nWho were arrayed before him, had appeared\nYet less than little children to be feared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero shocked the valiant Gryphon, where\nThe border of the buckler joined the sight,\nWho seemed as he would fall, now here, now there,\nAnd, from his courser far, last fell outright.\nHe at the shield had aimed, but smote not fair\nThe mark; and (for Rogero's orb was bright\nAnd smooth the hissing weapon slipt, and wrought ) \n\nOther effect than was in Gryphon's thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It rent and tore the veil which served to hide\nThe lightning's fearful and enchanted rays;\nWhich, without blinded eyes, can none abide\nUpright, nor refuge is for them who gaze.\nAquilant, who was at his brother's side,\nTore off the rest, and made the buckler blaze:\nThe splendour struck the valiant brothers blind,\nAnd Guido in their rear, who spurred behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These here, or there, to earth astonished reel;\nNor eyes alone are dazzled by the light,\nBut every sense astounds the flaming steel.\nUnconscious of the issue of the fight,\nRogero turned his horse, and, in the wheel,\nHandled his sword, so good to thrust and smite;\nAnd none descried his fury to oppose;\nFor in the charge dismounted were his foes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The knights, together with the footmen all,\nAnd women, who had from the castle hied,\nNor less the coursers panting with their fall,\nAs if about to die, the warrior spied.\nHe wondered first, and next perceived the pall\nOf silk was handing down on the left side;\nI say the pall, in which he used to lap\nHis shield, the evil cause of that mishap."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He quickly turns, and, turning, rolls his eyes,\nIn hopes to view his well-loved martial maid;\nAnd thitherward, without delay, he hies\nWhere, when the joust began, the damsel stayed.\nNot finding her, it is the Child's surmise\nThat she is gone to bear the stripling aid;\nFearing he may be burnt, while they their journey\nSo long delay, retarded by that tourney."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He saw the damsel, stretched among the rest\nWho him had thither guided: as she lay,\nHe took and placed her, yet with sleep opprest,\nBefore him, and, sore troubled, rode away.\nHe with a mantle, which above her vest\nShe wore, concealed the enchanted buckler's ray:\nAnd to the maid restored, when 'twas concealed,\nHer senses, which were ravished by the shield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Away Rogero posted with the dame,\nAnd did not date his crimsoned visage raise;\nSince every one, it seemed to him, might blame\nWith right that victory, worthy little praise.\n\"By what amends can I of such a shame\n(The blushing warrior said the stain eraze? ) \n\nFor 'twill be bruited, all my deeds by sleight\nOf magic have been done, and not by might.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As, thinking thus, he journeyed on his way,\nRogero stumbled upon what he sought;\nFor, in the middle of the track, there lay\nA well, within the ground profoundly wrought:\nWhither the thirsty herd, at noon of day,\nRepaired, their paunches with green forage fraught.\nRogero said, \" 'Tis now, must I provide,\nI shame from thee, O shield, no more abide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thee will I keep no more, and this shall be\nEven the last shame which so on me is thrown:\"\nThe Child, so ending his self-colloquy,\nDismounting, takes a large and heavy stone;\nWhich to the shield he ties, and bodily\nBoth to the bottom of the well are gone.\n\"Lie buried there for ever, from all eyes,\nAnd with thee hidden be my shame!\" he cries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Filled to the brim with water was the well;\nHeavy the stone, and heavy was the shield;\nNor stopt they till they to the bottom fell,\nBy the light, liquid element concealed.\nFame was not slow the noble act to swell,\nBut, wandering wide, the deed in brief revealed,\nAnd voicing it abroad, with trumpet-sound,\nTold France and Spain and all the countries round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When that so strange adventure to the rest\nOf the wide world, from mouth to mouth was blown,\nKnights out of number undertook the quest,\nFrom neighbouring parts and distant; but unknown\nTo all remained the forest which possessed\nThe spring wherein the virtuous shield was thrown:\nFor she who told the action, would not say\nWhere was the well, nor in what land it lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon Rogero's parting thence, where fell\nThe four good champions of that evil law,\nMade by the castle's lord Sir Pinnabel,\nBy him discomfited like men of straw,\n— The shield withdrawn — he had removed as well\nThe light, which quelled their sight and minds who saw;\nAnd those, who, like dead men, on earth had lain,\nHad risen, full of wonderment, again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor any thing throughout that livelong day\nThey 'mid themselves but that strange case relate;\nAnd how it was in that disastrous fray\nEach by the horrid light was quelled, debate.\nWhile these, discoursing, of the adventure say,\nTidings are brought of Pinnabello's fate.\nThat Pinnabel is dead the warriors hear,\nBut learn not who had slain the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant in close pass, this while, had staid\nThe faithless Pinnabel, and sorely prest;\nAnd many times had buried half her blade\nWithin bleeding flanks and heaving breast.\nWhen of his crimes the forfeit had been paid\nBy him, the infected country's curse and pest,\nShe from the conscious forest turned away\nWith that good steed the thief had made his prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She would return where she had left the knight,\nBut never could make out the road anew;\nAnd now by valley, now by mountain-height,\nWandered well-nigh the ample country through.\nYet could she never (such her fortune's spite)\nFind out the way to join Rogero true."
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto I attend\nWho loves the tale, to hear my story's end.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 23"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho soars in air.  Upon account\nOf Pinnabel is prisoned Scotland's heir:\nBy Roland freed, Frontino Rodomont\nTakes from Hippalca, trusted to her care.\nWith Mandricardo strives Anglantes' count:\nWho, next, offended by his lady fair,\nInto the fury falls, so strange and fell,\nWhich in the world has not a parallel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let each assist the other in his need;\nSeldom good actions go without their due;\nAnd if their just reward should not succeed,\nAt least, nor death, nor shame, nor loss ensue.\nWho wrongs another, the remembered meed\nAs well shall have, and soon or later rue.\nThat mountains never meet, but that men may,\nAnd oft encounter, is an ancient say."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now mark what chanced to Pinnabel, the event\nOf having borne himself so wickedly:\nHe at the last received due punishment,\nDue and deserved by his iniquity.\nAnd God, who for the most is ill content\nTo see the righteous suffer wrongfully,\nSecured the maid from harm, and will secure\nAll who from every wickedness are pure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pinnabel deemed he to an end had brought,\nAnd buried deep in earth, the martial maid;\nNor weening to behold her more, less thought\nTo her his treason's forfeit to have paid.\nNor profits it the wily traitor ought\nTo be among the forts his father swayed.\nFor Altaripa here its summit rears,\nAmid rude hills, confining on Poictiers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Anselm in Altaripa held command,\nThe count from whom was sprung this evil seed:\nWho, to escape from angry Clermont's hand,\nOf friends and of assistance stood in need.\nAt a hill's foot, with her avenging brand,\nBradamant made the worthless traitor bleed;\nWho found no better succour in the strife\nThan piteous cry and fruitless prayer for life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she has put to death the treacherous peer,\nWho to put her to death had erst intent,\nTo seek Rogero she again would steer,\nBut that her cruel fate would not consent;\nWhich, where the wood was loneliest and most drear,\nTo wander by close path the lady sent,\nUntil the western sun withdrew his light,\nAbandoning the world above to night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor knowing where for shelter she should rove,\nBradamant in that place resolves to stay,\nCouched on the verdant herbage of the grove;\nAnd, sleeping, now awaits the dawn of day,\nNow watching Saturn, Venus, Mars, and Jove,\nAnd the other wandering gods upon their way:\nBut, whether waking or to sleep resigned,\nHas aye Rogero present to her mind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With sorrow and repentance oft assailed,\nShe from her inmost heart profoundly sighed,\nThat Anger over Love should have prevailed.\n\"Anger has torn me from my love,\" (she cried,)\n\"Oh!  had I made some note, which had availed,\nThither, whence I set out, my steps to guide,\nWhen I departed on my ill emprize!\nSure I was lorn of memory and of eyes!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These words and others she in mournful strain\nUtters, and broods within her heart on more.\nMeanwhile a wind of sighs, and plenteous rain\nOf tears, are tokens of her anguish sore.\nIn the east, at last, expected long in vain,\nThe wished for twilight streaked the horizon o'er;\nAnd she her courser took, which on the ley\nWas feeding, and rode forth to meet the day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor far had rode, ere from the greenwood-trees\nShe issued, where the dome was erst displayed;\nAnd many days her with such witcheries\nThe evil-minded wizard had delayed.\nHere she Astolpho found, who at full ease\nA bridle for the Hippogryph had made,\nAnd here was standing, thoughtful and in pain\nTo whom he should deliver Rabicane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By chance she found him, as the cavalier\nHad from the helm uncased his head to view;\nSo that when of the dingy forest clear,\nFair Bradamant her gentle cousin knew.\nHim from afar she hailed with joyful cheer,\nAnd now more nigh, to embrace the warrior flew;\nAnd named herself, and raised her vizor high,\nAnd let him plainly who she was espy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "None could Astolpho have found any where\nWith whom to leave his horse with more content,\nAs knowing she would guard the steed with care,\nAnd to his lord on his return present;\nAnd he believed that Heaven had, in its care,\nDuke Aymon's daughter for this pleasure sent.\nHer was he wont with pleasure aye to see,\nBut now with more in his necessity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Embracing twice or thrice the cousins stand,\nFraternally, each other's neck, and they\nHad of each other's welfare made demand\nWith much affection, ere the duke 'gan say;\n\"Would I now see the winged people's land,\nHere upon earth I make too long delay.\"\nAnd opening to the dame the thought he brewed,\nTo her the flying horse Astolpho shewed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But she scarce marvelled when above the plain\nShe saw the rising steed his wings unfold;\nSince upon former time, with mastering rein.\nOn him had charged the dame that wizard old;\nAnd made her eye and eyelid sorely strain,\nSo hard she gazed, his movements to behold;\nThe day that he bore off, with wonderous range,\nRogero on his journey, long and strange."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho says on her he will bestow\nHis Rabican; so passing swift of kind,\nThat, if the courser started when a bow\nWas drawn, he left the feathered shaft behind;\nAnd will as well his panoply forego,\nThat it may to Mount Alban be consigned:\nAnd she for him preserve the martial weed;\nSince of his arms he has no present need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bent, since a course in air was to be flown,\nThat he, as best he can, will make him light.\nYet keeps the sword and horn; although alone\nThe horn from every risque might shield the knight:\nBut he the lance abandons, which the son\nOf Galaphron was wont to bear in flight;\nThe lance, by which whoever in the course\nWas touched, fell headlong hurtling from his horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Backed by Astolpho, and ascending slow,\nThe hippogryph through yielding aether flew;\nAnd next the rider stirred the courser so,\nThat in a thought he vanished out of view.\nThus with his pilot does the patron go,\nFearing the gale and rock, till he is through\nThe reefs; then, having left the shore behind,\nHoists every sail, and shoots before the wind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant, when departed was the peer,\nRemained distressed in mind; since in what way\nShe knew not her good kinsman's warlike gear\nAnd courser to Mount Alban to convey.\nFor on her heart, which they inflame and tear,\nThe warm desire and greedy will yet prey\nTo see the Child; whom she to find once more\nAt Vallombrosa thought, if not before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here standing in suspense, by chance she spied\nA churl, that came towards her on the plain,\nWho, at her best, Astolpho's armour tied,\nAs best he might, and laid on Rabicane;\nShe next behind her bade the peasant guide\n(One courser loaded and one loose the twain. ) \n\nTwo were the steeds; for she had that before,\nOn which his horse from Pinnabel she bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Vallombrosa to direct her way\nShe thought, in hopes to find Rogero there:\nBut, fearing evermore to go astray,\nKnew not how thither she might best repair.\nThe churl had of the country small assay,\nAnd, sure to be bewildered, wend the pair:\nYet at a venture thitherward she hies,\nWhere she believes the place of meeting lies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She here and there, as she her way pursued,\nTurned, but found none to question of the road;\nShe saw at mid-day, issuing from the wood,\nA fort, nor far removed was the abode,\nWhich on the summit of a mountain stood,\nAnd to the lady like Mount Alban showed;\nAnd was Mount Alban sure; in which repair\nOne of her brothers and her mother were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, when she recognized the place, became\nSadder at heart than I have power to say.\nIf she delays, discovered is the dame,\nNor thence will be allowed to wend her way:\nIf thence she wends not, of the amorous flame\nWhich so consumes her, she will be the prey,\nNor see Rogero more, nor compass aught\nWhich was at Vallombrosa to be wrought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Some deal she doubted: then to turn her steed,\nResolved upon Mount Alban's castle near;\nAnd, for she thence her way could deftly read,\nHer course anew towards the abbey steer.\nBut Fortune, good or evil, had decreed\nThe maid, before she of the vale was clear,\nOf one of her good brethren should be spied,\nAlardo named, ere she had time to hide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He came from billeting the bands which lay\nDispersed about that province, foot and horse;\nFor the surrounding district, to obey\nKing Charlemagne, had raised another force.\nEmbraces brotherly and friendly say,\nSalutes and kindly cheer, ensue of course;\nAnd next into Mount Alban, side by side,\nThey, communing of many matters, ride."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant enters Montalbano's seat,\nWhom Beatrice had mourned, and vainly sought\nThrough spacious France: 'Tis here all welcome sweet,\nThe kiss and clasp of hand, she holds at nought,\nWhile her a mother and a brother greet,\nAs the enamoured maid compares in thought\nThese with the loved Rogero's fond embrace;\nWhich time will never from her mind efface."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Because she could not go, one in her stead\nTo send to Vallombrosa she devised,\nWho thither in the damsel's name should speed;\nBy whom should young Rogero be apprised\nWhat kept her thence; and prayed, if prayer should need,\nThat there he for love would be baptised;\nAnd next, as was concerned, would intend\nWhat might their bridal bring to happy end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She purposed the same messenger should bear\nAs well to her Rogero his good steed;\nWhich he was ever wonted to hold dear,\nWorthily dear; for sure so stout at need\nAnd beauteous was no courser, far or near,\nIn land of Christian or of Paynim creed,\nIn occupation of the Gaul or Moor;\nExcept Baiardo good and Brigliador."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Valiant Rogero, when too bold of sprite\nHe backed the hippogryph and soared in air,\nFrontino left (Frontino he was hight),\nWhom Bradamant then took into her care,\nAnd to Mount Alban sent; and had him dight,\nAnd nourished, at large cost, with plenteous fare;\nNor let be rode except at easy pace,\nHence was he ne'er so sleek or well in case."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Each damsel and each dame who her obeyed,\nShe tasked, together with herself, to sew,\nWith subtle toil; and with fine gold o'erlaid\nA piece of silk of white and sable hue:\nWith this she trapt the horse; then chose a maid,\nOld Callitrephia's daughter, from the crew;\nWhose mother whilom Bradamant had nursed;\nA damsel she in all her secrets versed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How graven in her heart Rogero lies,\nA thousand times to her she had confessed;\nAnd had extolled above the deities\nThe manners, worth, and beauty be possessed.\n\"No better messenger could I devise,\"\n(She said, and called the damsel from the rest,)\n\"Nor have I one, Hippalca mine, more sage\nAnd sure than three, to do my embassage.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hippalca was the attendant damsel hight.\n\"Go,\" (says her lady, and describes the way)\nAnd afterwards informs the maid aright\nOf all which to Rogero she should say;\nAnd why she at the abbey failed the knight,\nWho must not to bad faith ascribe her stay,\nBut this to Fortune charge, that so decides,\nWho, more than we ourselves, our conduct guides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She made the damsel mount upon a pad,\nAnd put into her hand Frontino's rein;\nAnd, if she met with one so rude or mad,\nWho to deprive her of the steed were fain,\nHer to proclaim who was his owner, bade,\nAs that which might suffice to make him sane.\nFor she believed there was no cavalier,\nBut that Rogero's name would make him fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of many and many things, whereof to treat\nWith good Rogero, in her stead, she showed;\nOf which instructed well, her palfrey fleet\nHippalca stirred, nor longer there abode.\nThrough highway, field, and wood, a gloomy beat,\nMore than ten weary miles the damsel rode,\nEre any crossed her path on mischief bent,\nOr even questioned witherward she went."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At noon of day, descending from a mount,\nShe in a streight and ill declivity,\nLed by a dwarf, encountered Rodomont,\nWho was afoot and harnessed cap-a-pee.\nThe Moor towards her raised his haughty front,\nAnd straight blasphemed the eternal Hierarchy,\nThat horse, so richly trapped and passing fair,\nHe had not found in a knight-errant's care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the first courser he should find, the knight\nHad sworn a solemn oath his hands to lay:\nThis was the first, nor he on steed could light\nFairer or fitter; yet to take away\nThe charger from a maid were foul despite.\nDoubtful he stands, but covets sore the prey;\nEyes and surveys him, and says often, \"Why\nIs not as well the courser's master by?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  would be were!\" to him the maid replied,\n\"For haply he would make thee change thy thought.\nA better knight than thee the horse doth ride,\nAnd vainly would his match on earth be sought.\"\n— \"Who tramples thus on other's fame?\" — he cried;\nAnd she — \"Rogero\" — said, as she was taught.\nThen Rodomont — \"The steed I may my own;\nSince him a champion rides of such renown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If he, as you relate, be of such force,\nThat he surprises all beside in might,\nI needs must pay the hire as well as horse;\nAnd be this at the pleasure of the knight!\nThat I am Rodomont, to him discourse;\nAnd, if indeed with me he lists to fight,\nMe shall to find; in that I shine confest,\nBy my own light, in motion or at rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I leave such vestige wheresoe'er I tread,\nThe volleyed thunder leaves not worse below.\"\nHe had thrown back, over Frontino's head,\nThe courser's gilded reins, in saying so,\nBacked him, and left Hippalca sore bested;\nWho, bathed in tears, and goaded by her woe,\nCries shame on him, and threats the king with ill:\nRodomont hearkens not, and climbs the hill:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whither the dwarf conducts him on the trace\nOf Doralice and Mandricardo bold.\nBehind, Hippalca him in ceaseless chase,\nPursues with taunt and curses manifold.\nWhat came of this is said in other place.\nTurpin, by whom this history is told,\nHere makes digression, and returns again\nThither, where faithless Pinnabel was slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Duke Aymon's daughter scarce had turned away\nFrom thence, who on her track in haste had gone,\nEre thither by another path, astray,\nZerbino came, with that deceitful crone,\nAnd saw the bleeding body where it lay:\nAnd, though the warrior was to him unknown,\nAs good and courteous, felt his bosom swell,\nWith pity at that cruel sight and fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dead lay Sir Pinnabel, and bathed in gore;\nFrom whom such streams of blood profusely flow,\nAs were a cause for wonderment, had more\nSwords than a hundred joined to lay him low.\nA print of recent footsteps to explore\nThe cavalier of Scotland was not slow;\nWho took the adventure, in the hope to read\nWho was the doer of the murderous deed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The hag to wait was ordered by the peer,\nWho would return to her in little space.\nShe to the body of the count drew near,\nAnd with fixt eye examined every place;\nWho willed not aught, that in her sight was dear,\nThe body of the dead should vainly grace;\nAs one who, soiled with every other vice,\nSurpassed all womankind in avarice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If she in any manner could have thought,\nOr hoped to have concealed the intended theft,\nThe bleeding warrior's surcoat, richly wrought,\nShe would, together with his arms, have reft;\nBut at what might be safely hidden, caught,\nAnd, grieved at heart, forewent the glorious weft.\nHim of a beauteous girdle she undrest,\nAnd this secured between a double vest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino after some short space came back,\nWho vainly Bradamant had thence pursued\nThrough the green holt; because the beaten track\nWas lost in many others in the wood;\nAnd he (for daylight now began to lack)\nFeared night should catch him 'mid those mountains rude,\nAnd with the impious woman thence, in quest\nOf inn, from the disastrous valley prest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A spacious town, which Altaripa hight,\nJourneying the twain, at two miles' distance spy:\nThere stopt the pair, and halted for the night,\nWhich, at full soar, even now went up the sky:\nNor long had rested there ere, left and right,\nThey from the people heard a mournful cry;\nAnd saw fast tears from every eyelid fall,\nAs if some cause of sorrow touched them all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino asked the occasion, and 'twas said\nTidings had been to Count Anselmo brought,\nThat Pinnabel, his son, was lying dead\nIn a streight way between two mountains wrought.\nZerbino feigned surprise, and hung his head,\nIn fear lest he the assassin should be thought;\nBut well divined this was the wight he found\nUpon his journey, lifeless on the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After some little time, the funeral bier\nArrives, 'mid torch and flambeau, where the cries\nAre yet more thick, and to the starry sphere\nLament and noise of smitten hands arise;\nAnd faster and from fuller vein the tear\nWaters all cheeks, descending from the eyes;\nBut in a cloud more dismal than the rest,\nIs the unhappy father's visage drest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While solemn preparation so was made\nFor the grand obsequies, with reverence due,\nAccording to old use and honours paid,\nIn former age, corrupted by each new;\nA proclamation of their lord allayed\nQuickly the noise of the lamenting crew;\nPromising any one a mighty gain\nThat should denounce by whom his son was slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From voice to voice, from one to other ear,\nThe loud proclaim they through the town declare;\nTill this the wicked woman chanced to hear,\nWho past in rage the tyger or the bear;\nAnd hence the ruin of the Scottish peer,\nEither in hatred, would the crone prepare,\nOr were it she alone might boast to be,\nIn human form, without humanity;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Or were it but to gain the promised prize; —\nShe to seek out the grieving county flew,\nAnd, prefacing her tale in likely wise,\nSaid that Zerbino did the deed; and drew\nThe girdle forth, to witness to her lies;\nWhich straight the miserable father knew;\nAnd on the woman's tale and token built\nA clear assurance of Zerbino's guilt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, weeping, with raised hands, was heard to say,\nHe for his murdered son would have amends.\nTo block the hostel where Zerbino lay,\nFor all the town is risen, the father sends.\nThe prince, who deems his enemies away,\nAnd no such injury as this attends,\nIn his first sleep is seized by Anselm's throng,\nWho thinks he has endured so foul a wrong."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That night in prison, fettered with a pair\nOf heavy letters, is Zerbino chained.\nFor before yet the skies illuminated are,\nThe wrongful execution is ordained;\nAnd in the place will he be quartered, where\nThe deed was done for which he is arraigned.\nNo other inquest is on this received;\nIt is enough that so their lord believed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When, the next morn, Aurora stains with dye\nRed, white, and yellow, the clear horizon,\nThe people rise, to punish (\"Death!\"  their cry)\nZerbino for the crime he has not done:\nThey without order him accompany,\nA lawless multitude, some ride, some run.\nI' the midst the Scottish prince, with drooping head,\nIs, bound upon a little hackney, led."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But HE who with the innocent oft sides,\nNor those abandons who make him their stay,\nFor prince Zerbino such defence provides,\nThere is no fear that he will die to-day;\nGod thitherward renowned Orlando guides;\nWhose coming for his safety paves the way:\nOrlando sees beneath him on a plain\nThe youth to death conducted by the train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With him was wended she, that in the cell,\nPrisoned, Orlando found; that royal maid,\nChild of Gallicia's king, fair Isabel,\nWhom chance into the ruffians' power conveyed,\nWhat time her ship she quitted, by the swell\nOf the wild sea and tempest overlaid:\nThe damsel, who, yet nearer her heart-core\nThan her own vital being, Zerbino wore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She had beneath Orlando's convoy strayed,\nSince rescued from the cave.  When on the plain\nThe damsel saw the motley troop arrayed,\nShe asked Orlando what might be the train?\n\"I know not,\" said the Count; and left the maid\nUpon the height, and hurried towards the plain.\nHe marked Zerbino, and at the first sight\nA baron of high worth esteemed the knight,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And asked him why and wherefore him they led\nThus captive, to Zerbino drawing near:\nAt this the doleful prince upraised his head,\nAnd, having better heard the cavalier,\nRehearsed the truth; and this so well he said,\nThat he deserved the succour of the peer.\nWell Sir Orlando him, by his reply,\nDeemed innocent, and wrongly doomed to die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, after he had heard 'twas at the hest\nOf Anselm, Count of Altaripa, done,\nWas certain 'twas and outrage manifest,\nSince nought but ill could spring from him; and one,\nMoreover, was the other's foe profest,\nFrom ancient hate and enmity, which run\nIn Clermont and Maganza's blood; a feud\nWith injuries, and death and shame pursued."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando to the rabble cried, \"Untie\nThe cavalier, unless you would be slain.\"\n— \"Who deals such mighty blows?\" — one made reply,\nThat would be thought the truest of the train;\n\"Were he of fire who makes such bold defy,\nWe wax or straw, too haughty were the strain\":\nAnd charged with that the paladin of France.\nOrlando at the losel couched his lance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The shining armour which the chief had rent\nFrom young Zerbino but the night before,\nAnd clothed himself withal, poor succour lent\nAgainst Orlando in that combat sore.\nAgainst the churl's right cheek the weapon went:\nIt failed indeed his tempered helm to bore,\nBut such a shock he suffered in the strife,\nAs broke his neck, and stretched him void of life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All at one course, of other of the band,\nWith lance unmoved, he pierced the bosom through;\nLeft it; on Durindana laid his hand,\nAnd broke into the thicket of the crew:\nOne head in twain he severed with the brand,\n(While, from the shoulders lopt, another flew)\nOf many pierced the throat; and in a breath\nAbove a hundred broke and put to death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above a third he killed, and chased the rest,\nAnd smote, and pierced, and cleft, as he pursued.\nHimself of helm or shield one dispossest;\nOne with spontoon or bill the champaign strewed\nThis one along the road, across it prest\nA fourth; this squats in cavern or in wood.\nOrlando, without pity, on that day\nLets none escape whom he has power to slay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of a hundred men and twenty, in that crew,\n(So Turpin sums them eighty died at least. ) \n\nThither Orlando finally withdrew,\nWhere, with a heart sore trembling in his breast,\nZerbino sat; how he at Roland's view\nRejoiced, in verse can hardly be exprest:\nWho, but that he was on the hackney bound,\nWould at his feet have cast himself to ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While Roland, after he had loosed the knight,\nHelped him to don his shining arms again;\nStript from those serjeants' captain, who had dight\nHimself with the good harness, to his pain;\nThe prince on Isabella turned his sight,\nWho had halted on the hill above the plain:\nAnd, after she perceived the strife was o'er,\nNearer the field of fight her beauties bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When young Zerbino at his side surveyed\nThe lady, who by him was held so dear;\nThe beauteous lady, whom false tongue had said\nWas drowned, so often wept with many a tear,\nAs if ice at his heart-core had been laid,\nWaxed cold, and some deal shook the cavalier;\nBut the chill quickly past, and he, instead,\nWas flushed with amorous fire, from foot to head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From quickly clipping her in his embrace,\nHim reverence for Anglantes' sovereign stayed;\nBecause he thought, and held for certain case,\nThat Roland was a lover of the maid;\nSo past from pain to pain; and little space\nEndured the joy which he at first assayed.\nAnd worse he bore she should another's be,\nThan hearing that the maid was drowned at sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And worse he grieved, that she was with a knight\nTo whom he owed so much: because to wrest\nThe lady from his hand, was neither right,\nNor yet perhaps would prove an easy quest.\nHe, without quarrel, had no other wight\nSuffered to part, of such a prize possest;\nBut would endure, Orlando (such his debt)\nA foot upon his prostrate neck should set."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The three in silence journey to a font,\nWhere they alight, and halt beside the well;\nHis helmet here undid the weary Count,\nAnd made the prince too quit the iron shell.\nThe youth unhelmed, she sees her lover's front,\nAnd pale with sudden joy grows Isabel:\nThen, changing, brightened like a humid flower,\nWhen the warm sun succeeds to drenching shower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And without more delay or scruple, prest\nTo cast her arms about her lover dear;\nAnd not a word could draw-forth from her breast,\nBut bathed his neck and face with briny tear.\nOrlando, who remarked the love exprest,\nNeeding no more to make the matter clear,\nCould not but, by these certain tokens, see\nThe could no other but Zerbino be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When speech returned, ere yet the maiden well\nHad dried her cheeks from the descending tear,\nShe only of the courtesy could tell\nLate shown her by Anglantes' cavalier.\nThe prince, who in one scale weighed Isabel,\nTogether with his life, esteemed as dear, —\nFell at Orlando's feet and him adored,\nAs to two lives at once by him restored."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Proffers and thanks had followed, with a round\nOf courtesies between the warlike pair,\nHad they not heard the covered paths resound,\nWhich overgrown with gloomy foliage were.\nUpon their heads the helmet, late unbound,\nThey quickly place, and to their steeds repair;\nAnd, lo!  a knight and maid arrive, ere well\nThe cavaliers are seated in the sell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was the Tartar Mandricardo, who\nIn haste behind the paladin had sped,\nTo venge Alzirdo and Manilard, the two\nWhom good Orlando's valour had laid dead:\nThough afterwards less eager to pursue,\nSince he with him fair Doralice had led;\nWhom from a hundred men, in plate and chain,\nHe, with a single staff of oak, had ta'en."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet knew not that it was Anglantes' peer\nThis while, of whom he had pursued the beat;\nThough that he was a puissant cavalier\nBy certain signals was he taught to weet.\nMore than Zerbino him he eyed, and, near,\nPerused the paladin from head to feet;\nThen finding all the tokens coincide,\n\"Thou art the man I seek,\" the paynim cried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" 'Tis now ten days,\" to him the Tartar said,\n\"That thee I still have followed; so the fame\nHad stung me, and in me such longing bred,\nWhich of thee to our camp of Paris came:\nWhen, amid thousands by thy hand laid dead,\nScarce one alive fled thither, to proclaim\nThe mighty havoc made by thy good hand,\n'Mid Tremisena's and Noritia's band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I was not, as I knew, in following slow\nBoth to behold thee, and to prove thy might;\nAnd by the surcoat o'er thine arms I know,\n(Instructed of thy vest thou art the knight: ) \n\nAnd if such cognizance thou didst not show,\nAnd, 'mid a hundred, wert concealed from sight,\nFor what thou art thou plainly wouldst appear,\nThy worth conspicuous in thy haughty cheer.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No one can say,\" to him Orlando cried,\n\"But that a valiant cavalier thou art:\nFor such a brave desire can ill reside,\n'Tis my assurance, in a humble heart.\nSince thou wouldst see me, would that thou inside,\nCouldst as without, behold me!  I apart\nWill lay me helm, that in all points thy will\nAnd purpose of thy quest I may fulfil."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But when thou well hast scanned me with thine eye,\nTo that thine other wish as well attend:\nIt yet remains for thee to satisfy\nThe want, which leads thee after me to wend;\nThat thou mayest mark if, in my valour, I\nAgree with that bold cheer thou so commend.\"\n— \"And now,\" (exclaimed the Tartar), \"for the rest!\nFor my first want is thoroughly redrest.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando, all this while, from head to feet,\nSearches the paynim with inquiring eyes:\nBoth sides, and next the pommel of his seat\nSurveys, yet neither mace nor tuck espies;\nAnd asks how he the combat will repeat,\nIf his good lance at the encounter flies.\n— \"Take thou no care for that,\" replied the peer;\n\"Thus into many have I stricken fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I have an oath in Heaven to gird no blade,\nTill Durindana from the count be won.\nPursuing whom, I through each road here strayed,\nWith him to reckon for more posts than one.\nIf thou wilt please to hear, my oath I made\nWhen on my head I placed this morion:\nWhich casque, with all the other arms I bear,\nA thousand years ago great Hector's were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To these good arms nought lacks beside the sword;\nHow it was stolen, to you I cannot say:\nThis now, it seems, is borne by Brava's lord,\nAnd hence is he so daring in affray.\nYet well I trust, if I the warrior board,\nTo make him render his ill-gotten prey.\nYet more; I seek the champion with desire\nTo avenge the famous Agrican, my sire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Him this Orlando slew by treachery,\nI wot, nor could have slain in other wise.\"\nThe count could bear no more, and, \" 'Tis a lie!\"\n(Exclaims), \"and whosoever says so, lies:\nHim fairly did I slay; Orlando, I.\nBut what thou seekest Fortune here supplies;\nAnd this the faulchion is, which thou has sought,\nWhich shall be thine if by thy valour bought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Although mine is the faulchion, rightfully,\nLet us for it in courtesy contend;\nNor will I in this battle, that it be\nMore mine than thine, but to a tree suspend:\nBear off the weapon freely hence, if me\nThou kill or conquer.\"  As he made an end,\nHe Durindana from his belt unslung,\nAnd in mid-field upon a sapling hung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already distant half the range of bow\nIs from his opposite each puissant knight,\nAnd pricks against the other, nothing slow\nTo slack the reins or ply the rowels bright.\nAlready dealt is either mighty blow,\nWhere the helm yields a passage to the sight.\nAs if of ice, the shattered lances fly,\nBroke in a thousand pieces, to the sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One and the other lance parforce must split,\nIn that the cavaliers refuse to bend;\nThe cavaliers, who in the saddle sit,\nReturning with the staff's unbroken end.\nThe warriors, who with steed had ever smit,\nNow, as a pair of hinds in rage contend\nFor the mead's boundary or river's right,\nArmed with two clubs, maintain a cruel fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The truncheons which the valiant champions bear,\nFail in the combat, and few blows resist;\nBoth rage with mightier fury, here and there,\nLeft without other weapon than the fist;\nWith this the desperate foes engage, and, where\nThe hand can grapple, plate and mail untwist.\nLet none desire, to guard himself from wrongs,\nA heavier hammer or more holding tongs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How can the Saracen conclude the fray\nWith honour, which he haughtily had sought?\n'Twere forty to waste time in an assay\nWhere to himself more harm the smiter wrought\nThan to the smitten: in conclusion, they\nClosed, and the paynim king Orlando caught,\nAnd strained against his bosom; what Jove's son\nDid by Antaeus, thinking to have done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him griped athwart, he, in impetuous mood,\nWould now push from him, now would closely strain;\nAnd waxed so wroth that, in his heat of blood,\nThe Tartar little thought about his rein.\nFirm in his stirrups self-collected stood\nRoland, and watched his vantage to obtain;\nHe to the other courser's forehead slipt\nHis wary hand, and thence the bridle stript."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Saracen assays with all his might\nTo choak, and from the sell his foeman tear:\nWith either knee Orlando grasps it tight,\nNor can the Tartar more him, here or there.\nBut with the straining of the paynim knight,\nThe girts which hold his saddle broken are.\nScarce conscious of his fall, Orlando lies,\nWith feet i' the stirrups, tightening yet his thighs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As falls a sack of armour, with such sound\nTumbled Orlando, when he prest the plain.\nKing Mandricardo's courser, when he found\nHis head delivered from the guiding rein,\nMade off with him, unheeding what the ground,\nStumbling through woodland, or by pathway plain,\nHither and tither, blinded by his fear;\nAnd bore with him the Tartar cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beauteous Doralice, who sees her guide\nSo quit the field, — dismayed at his retreat,\nAnd wonted in his succour to confide,\nHer hackney drives behind his courser fleet:\nThe paynim rates the charger, in his pride,\nAnd smites him oftentimes with hands and feet;\nThreatening, as if he understood his lore;\nAnd where he'd stop the courser, chafes him more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not looking to his feet, by high or low,\nThe beast of craven kind, with headlong force\nThree miles in rings had gone, and more would go,\nBut that into a fosse which stopt their course,\nNot lined with featherbed or quilt below,\nTumble, reversed, the rider and his horse.\nOn the hard ground was Mandricardo thrown,\nYet neither spoiled himself, nor broke a bone:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here stopt the horse; but him he could not guide,\nLeft without bit his motions to restrain.\nBrimfull of rage and choler, at his side,\nThe Tartar held him, grappled by the mane.\n\"Put upon him\" (to Mandricardo cried\nHis lady, Doralice \"my hackney's rein, ) \n\nSince for the bridle I have little use;\nFor gentle is my palfrey, reined or loose.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The paynim deems it were discourtesy\nTo accept the proffer by the damsel made.\nBut his through other means a rein will be;\nSince Fortune, who his wishes well appaid,\nMade thitherward the false Gabrina flee,\nAfter she young Zerbino had betrayed:\nWho like a she-wolf fled, which, as she hies,\nAt distance hears the hounds and hunters' cries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She had upon her back the gallant gear,\nAnd the same youthful ornaments and vest,\nStript from the ill-taught damsel for her jeer,\nThat in her spoils the beldam might be drest,\nAnd rode the horse that damsel backed whilere;\nWho was among the choicest and the best.\nEre yet aware of her, the ancient dame\nOn Doralice and Mandricardo came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stordilane's daughter and the Tartar king\nLaugh at the vest of youthful show and shape,\nUpon that ancient woman, figuring\nLike monkey, rather say, like grandam ape.\nFrom her the Saracen designs to wring\nThe rein, and does the deed: upon the rape\nOf the crone's bridle, he, with angry cry,\nThreatens and scares her horse, and makes him fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He flies and hurries through the forest gray\nThat ancient woman, almost dead with fear,\nBy hill and dale, by straight and crooked way,\nBy fosse and cliff, at hazard, there and here.\nBut it imports me not so much to say\nOf her, that I should leave Anglantes' peer;\nWho, from annoyance of a foe released,\nThe broken saddle at his ease re-pieced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He mounts his horse, and watches long, before\nDeparting, if the foe will re-appear;\nNor seeing puissant Mandricardo more,\nAt last resolves in search of him to steer.\nBut, as one nurtured well in courtly lore,\nFrom thence departed not the cavalier,\nTill he with kind salutes, in friendly strain,\nFair leaves had taken of the loving twain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At his departure waxed Zerbino woe,\nAnd Isabella wept for sorrow: they\nHad wended with him, but the count, although\nTheir company was fair and good, said nay;\nUrging for reason, nought so ill could show\nIn cavalier, as, when upon his way\nTo seek his foeman out, to take a friend,\nWho him with arms might succour or defend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next, if they met the Saracen, before\nThey should encounter him, besought them say,\nThat he, Orlando, would for three days more.\nWaiting him, in that territory stay:\nBut, after that, would seek the flags which bore\nThe golden lilies, and King Charles' array.\nThat Mandricardo through their means might know,\nIf such his pleasure, where to find his foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lovers promised willingly to do\nThis, and whatever else he should command.\nBy different ways the cavaliers withdrew,\nOne on the right, and one on the left hand.\nThe count, ere other path he would pursue,\nTook from the sapling, and replaced, his brand.\nAnd, where he weened he might the paynim best\nEncounter, thitherward his steed addrest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The course in pathless woods, which, without rein,\nThe Tartar's charger had pursued astray,\nMade Roland for two days, with fruitless pain,\nFollow him, without tidings of his way.\nOrlando reached a rill of crystal vein,\nOn either bank of which a meadow lay;\nWhich, stained with native hues and rich, he sees,\nAnd dotted o'er with fair and many trees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The mid-day fervour made the shelter sweet\nTo hardy herd as well as naked swain;\nSo that Orlando, well beneath the heat\nSome deal might wince, opprest with plate and chain.\nHe entered, for repose, the cool retreat,\nAnd found it the abode of grief and pain;\nAnd place of sojourn more accursed and fell,\nOn that unhappy day, than tongue can tell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Turning him round, he there, on many a tree,\nBeheld engraved, upon the woody shore,\nWhat as the writing of his deity\nHe knew, as soon as he had marked the lore.\nThis was a place of those described by me,\nWhither ofttimes, attended by Medore,\nFrom the near shepherd's cot had wont to stray\nThe beauteous lady, sovereign of Catay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In a hundred knots, amid those green abodes,\nIn a hundred parts, their cyphered names are dight;\nWhose many letters are so many goads,\nWhich Love has in his bleeding hear-core pight.\nHe would discredit in a thousand modes,\nThat which he credits in his own despite;\nAnd would parforce persuade himself, that rhind\nOther Angelica than his had signed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And yet I know these characters,\" he cried,\n\"Of which I have so many read and seen;\nBy her may this Medoro be belied,\nAnd me, she, figured in the name, may mean.\"\nFeeding on such like phantasies, beside\nThe real truth, did sad Orlando lean\nUpon the empty hope, though ill contented,\nWhich he by self-illusions had fomented."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But stirred and aye rekindled it, the more\nThat he to quench the ill suspicion wrought,\nLike the incautious bird, by fowler's lore,\nHampered in net or line; which, in the thought\nTo free its tangled pinions and to soar,\nBy struggling, is but more securely caught.\nOrlando passes thither, where a mountain\nO'erhangs in guise of arch the crystal fountain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Splay-footed ivy, with its mantling spray,\nAnd gadding vine, the cavern's entry case;\nWhere often in the hottest noon of day\nThe pair had rested, locked in fond embrace.\nWithin the grotto, and without it, they\nHad oftener than in any other place\nWith charcoal or with chalk their names pourtrayed,\nOr flourished with the knife's indenting blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here from his horse the sorrowing County lit,\nAnd at the entrance of the grot surveyed\nA cloud of words, which seemed but newly writ,\nAnd which the young Medoro's hand had made.\nOn the great pleasure he had known in it,\nThe sentence he in verses had arrayed;\nWhich in his tongue, I deem, might make pretence\nTo polished phrase; and such in ours the sense."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Gay plants, green herbage, rill of limpid vein,\nAnd, grateful with cool shade, thou gloomy cave,\nWhere oft, by many wooed with fruitless pain,\nBeauteous Angelica, the child of grave\nKing Galaphron, within my arms has lain;\nFor the convenient harbourage you gave,\nI, poor Medoro, can but in my lays,\nAs recompence, for ever sing your praise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And any loving lord devoutly pray,\nDamsel and cavalier, and every one,\nWhom choice or fortune hither shall convey,\nStranger or native, — to this crystal run,\nShade, caverned rock, and grass, and plants, to say,\nBenignant be to you the fostering sun\nAnd moon, and may the choir of nymphs provide,\nThat never swain his flock may hither guide!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In Arabic was writ the blessing said,\nKnown to Orlando like the Latin tongue,\nWho, versed in many languages, best read\nWas in this speech; which oftentimes from wrong,\nAnd injury, and shame, had saved his head,\nWhat time he roved the Saracens among.\nBut let him boast not of its former boot,\nO'erbalanced by the present bitter fruit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Three times, and four, and six, the lines imprest\nUpon the stone that wretch perused, in vain\nSeeking another sense than was exprest,\nAnd ever saw the thing more clear and plain;\nAnd all the while, within his troubled breast,\nHe felt an icy hand his heart-core strain.\nWith mind and eyes close fastened on the block,\nAt length he stood, not differing from the rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then well-nigh lost all feeling; so a prey\nWholly was he to that o'ermastering woe.\nThis is a pang, believe the experienced say\nOf him who speaks, which does all griefs outgo.\nHis pride had from his forehead passed away,\nHis chin had fallen upon his breast below;\nNor found he, so grief barred each natural vent,\nMoisture for tears, or utterance for lament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stiffed within, the impetuous sorrow stays,\nWhich would too quickly issue; so to abide\nWater is seen, imprisoned in the vase,\nWhose neck is narrow and whose swell is wide;\nWhat time, when one turns up the inverted base,\nTowards the mouth, so hastes the hurrying tide,\nAnd in the streight encounters such a stop,\nIt scarcely works a passage, drop by drop."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He somewhat to himself returned, and thought\nHow possibly the thing might be untrue:\nThe some one (so he hoped, desired, and sought\nTo think his lady would with shame pursue; ) \n\nOr with such weight of jealously had wrought\nTo whelm his reason, as should him undo;\nAnd that he, whosoe'er the thing had planned,\nHad counterfeited passing well her hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With such vain hope he sought himself to cheat,\nAnd manned some deal his spirits and awoke;\nThen prest the faithful Brigliadoro's seat,\nAs on the sun's retreat his sister broke.\nNor far the warrior had pursued his beat,\nEre eddying from a roof he saw the smoke;\nHeard noise of dog and kine, a farm espied,\nAnd thitherward in quest of lodging hied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Languid, he lit, and left his Brigliador\nTo a discreet attendant: one undrest\nHis limbs, one doffed the golden spurs he wore,\nAnd one bore off, to clean, his iron vest.\nThis was the homestead where the young Medore\nLay wounded, and was here supremely blest.\nOrlando here, with other food unfed,\nHaving supt full of sorrow, sought his bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The more the wretched sufferer seeks for ease,\nHe finds but so much more distress and pain;\nWho every where the loathed hand-writing sees,\nOn wall, and door, and window: he would fain\nQuestion his host of this, but holds his peace,\nBecause, in sooth, he dreads too clear, too plain\nTo make the thing, and this would rather shrowd,\nThat it may less offend him, with a cloud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Little availed the count his self-deceit;\nFor there was one who spake of it unsought;\nThe sheperd-swain, who to allay the heat,\nWith which he saw his guest so troubled, thought:\nThe tale which he was wonted to repeat\n— Of the two lovers — to each listener taught,\nA history which many loved to hear,\nHe now, without reserve, 'gan tell the peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How at Angelica's persuasive prayer,\nHe to his farm had carried young Medore,\nGrievously wounded with an arrow; where,\nIn little space she healed the angry sore.\nBut while she exercised this pious care,\nLove in her heart the lady wounded more,\nAnd kindled from small spark so fierce a fire,\nShe burnt all over, restless with desire:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor thinking she of mightiest king was born,\nWho ruled in the east, nor of her heritage,\nForced by too puissant love, had thought no scorn\nTo be the consort of a poor foot-page.\n— His story done, to them in proof was borne\nThe gem, which, in reward for harbourage,\nTo her extended in that kind abode,\nAngelica, at parting, had bestowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A deadly axe was this unhappy close,\nWhich, at a single stroke, lopt off the head;\nWhen, satiate with innumerable blows,\nThat cruel hangman Love his hate had fed.\nOrlando studied to conceal his woes;\nAnd yet the mischief gathered force and spread,\nAnd would break out parforce in tears and sighs,\nWould he, or would be not, from mouth and eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he can give the rein to raging woe,\nAlone, by other's presence unreprest,\nFrom his full eyes the tears descending flow,\nIn a wide stream, and flood his troubled breast.\n'Mid sob and groan, he tosses to and fro\nAbout his weary bed, in search of rest;\nAnd vainly shifting, harder than a rock\nAnd sharper than a nettle found its flock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Amid the pressure of such cruel pain,\nIt past into the wretched sufferer's head,\nThat oft the ungrateful lady must have lain,\nTogether with her leman, on that bed:\nNor less he loathed the couch in his disdain,\nNor from the down upstarted with less dread,\nThan churl, who, when about to close his eyes,\nSprings from the turf, if he a serpent spies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In him, forthwith, such deadly hatred breed\nThat bed, that house, that swain, he will not stay\nTill the morn break, or till the dawn succeed,\nWhose twilight goes before approaching day.\nIn haste, Orlando takes his arms and steed,\nAnd to the deepest greenwood wends his way.\nAnd, when assured that he is there alone,\nGives utterance to his grief in shriek and groan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Never from tears, never from sorrowing,\nHe paused; nor found he peace by night and day:\nHe fled from town, in forest harbouring,\nAnd in the open air on hard earth lay.\nHe marvelled at himself, how such a spring\nOf water from his eyes could stream away,\nAnd breath was for so many sobs supplied;\nAnd thus ofttimes, amid his mourning, cried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"These are no longer real tears which rise,\nAnd which I scatter from so full a vein.\nOf tears my ceaseless sorrow lacked supplies;\nThey stopt when to mid-height scarce rose my pain.\nThe vital moisture rushing to my eyes,\nDriven by the fire within me, now would gain\nA vent; and it is this which I expend,\nAnd which my sorrows and my life will end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No; these, which are the index of my woes,\nThese are not sighs, nor sighs are such; they fail\nAt times, and have their season of repose:\nI feel, my breast can never less exhale\nIts sorrow: Love, who with his pinions blows\nThe fire about my heart, creates this gale.\nLove, by what miracle does thou contrive,\nIt wastes not in the fire thou keep'st alive?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I am not — am not what I seem to sight:\nWhat Roland was is dead and under ground,\nSlain by that most ungrateful lady's spite,\nWhose faithlessness inflicted such a wound.\nDivided from the flesh, I am his sprite,\nWhich in this hell, tormented, walks its round,\nTo be, but in its shadow left above,\nA warning to all such as thrust in love.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All night about the forest roved the count,\nAnd, at the break of daily light, was brought\nBy his unhappy fortune to the fount,\nWhere his inscription young Medoro wrought.\nTo see his wrongs inscribed upon that mount,\nInflamed his fury so, in him was nought\nBut turned to hatred, phrensy, rage, and spite;\nNor paused he more, but bared his faulchion bright;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Cleft through the writing; and the solid block,\nInto the sky, in tiny fragments sped.\nWo worth each sapling and the caverned rock,\nWhere Medore and Angelica were read!\nSo scathed, that they to shepherd or to flock\nThenceforth shall never furnish shade or bed.\nAnd that sweet fountain, late so clear and pure,\nFrom such tempestuous wrath was ill secure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For he turf, stone, and trunk, and shoot, and lop,\nCast without cease into the beauteous source;\nTill, turbid from the bottom to the top,\nNever again was clear the troubled course.\nAt length, for lack of breath, compelled to stop,\n(When he is bathed in sweat, and wasted force,\nServes not his fury more he falls, and lies ) \n\nUpon the mead, and, gazing upward, sighs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Wearied and woe-begone, he fell to ground,\nAnd turned his eyes toward heaven; nor spake he aught.\nNor ate, nor slept, till in his daily round\nThe golden sun had broken thrice, and sought\nHis rest anew; nor ever ceased his wound\nTo rankle, till it marred his sober thought.\nAt length, impelled by phrensy, the fourth day,\nHe from his limbs tore plate and mail away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here was his helmet, there his shield bestowed;\nHis arms far off; and, farther than the rest,\nHis cuirass; through the greenwood wide was strowed\nAll his good gear, in fine; and next his vest\nHe rent; and, in his fury, naked showed\nHis shaggy paunch, and all his back and breast.\nAnd 'gan that phrensy act, so passing dread,\nOf stranger folly never shall be said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So fierce his rage, so fierce his fury grew,\nThat all obscured remained the warrior's sprite;\nNor, for forgetfulness, his sword he drew,\nOr wonderous deeds, I trow, had wrought the knight:\nBut neither this, nor bill, nor axe to hew,\nWas needed by Orlando's peerless might.\nHe of his prowess gave high proofs and full,\nWho a tall pine uprooted at a pull."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He many others, with as little let\nAs fennel, wall-wort-stem, or dill, up-tore;\nAnd ilex, knotted oak, and fir upset,\nAnd beech, and mountain-ash, and elm-tree hoar.\nHe did what fowler, ere he spreads his net,\nDoes, to prepare the champaigne for his lore,\nBy stubble, rush, and nettle-stalk; and broke,\nLike these, old sturdy trees and stems of oak."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The shepherd swains, who hear the tumult nigh,\nLeaving their flocks beneath the greenwood tree,\nSome here some there across the forest hie,\nAnd hurry thither, all, the cause to see.\n— But I have reached such point, my history,\nIf I o'erpass this bound, may irksome be;\nAnd I my story will delay to end,\nRather than by my tediousness offend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 24"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Odorico's and Gabrina's guilt repaid,\nYouthful Zerbino sets at large the train;\nHe in defence of good Orlando's blade,\nIs afterwards by Mandricardo slain.\nIsabel weeps; by Rodomont is made\nWar on the Tartar king, and truce again,\nTo succour Agramant and his array;\nWho to the lilies are well-nigh a prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let him make haste his feet to disengage,\nNor lime his wings, whom Love has made a prize;\nFor love, in fine, is nought but phrensied rage,\nBy universal suffrage of the wise:\nAnd albeit some may show themselves more sage\nThan Roland, they but sin in other guise.\nFor, what proves folly more than on this shelf,\nThus, for another, to destroy oneself?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Various are love's effects; but from one source\nAll issue, though they lead a different way.\nHe is, as 'twere, a forest, where parforce\nWho enter its recess go astray;\nAnd here and there pursue their devious course:\nIn sum, to you I, for conclusion, say;\nHe who grows old in love, besides all pain\nWhich waits such passion, well deserves a chain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One here may well reproach me: \"Brother, thou\nSeest not thy faults, while thou dost others fit.\"\n— I answer that I see mine plain enow,\nIn this my lucid interval of wit;\nAnd strive and hope withal I shall forego\nThis dance of folly; but yet cannot quit,\nAs quickly as I would, the faults I own;\nFor my disease has reached the very bone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Canto said before,\nOrlando, furious and insensate wight,\nHaving torn off the arms and vest he wore,\nAnd cast away from him his faulchion bright,\nAnd up-torn trees, and made the forest hoar\nAnd hollow cave resound, and rocky height,\nTowards the noise some shepherds, on that side,\nTheir heavy sins or evil planets guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Viewing the madman's wonderous feats more near,\nThe frighted band of rustics turned and fled;\nBut they, in their disorder, knew not where,\nAs happens oftentimes in sudden dread.\nThe madman in a thought is in their rear,\nSeizes a shepherd, and plucks off his head;\nAnd this as easily as one might take\nApple from tree, or blossom from the brake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He by one leg the heavy trunk in air\nUpheaved, and made a mace the rest to bray.\nAstounded, upon earth he stretched one pair,\nWho haply may awake at the last day.\nThe rest, who well awake at the last day.\nThe rest, who well advised and nimble are,\nAt once desert the field and scour away:\nNor had the madman their pursuit deferred,\nHad he not turned already on their herd."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By such examples warned, the rustic crew\nAbandoned in the fields pick, scythe, and plough,\nAnd to the roof of house and temple flew,\n(For ill secure was elm or willow's bough,)\nFrom hence the maniac's horrid rage they view;\nWho, dealing kick, and bite, and scratch, and blow,\nHorses and oxen slew, his helpless prey;\nAnd well the courser ran who 'scaped that day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already might'st thou hear how loudly ring\nThe hubbub and the din, from neighbouring farms,\nOutcry and horn, and rustic trumpeting;\nAnd faster sound of bells; with various arms\nBy thousands, with spontoon, bow, spit, and sling.\nLo!  from the hills the rough militia swarms.\nAs many peasants from the vale below,\nTo make rude war upon the madman go,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As beats the wave upon the salt-sea shore,\nSportive at first, which southern wind has stirred,\nWhen the next, bigger than what went before,\nAnd bigger than the second, breaks the third;\nAnd the vext water waxes evermore,\nAnd louder on the beach the surf is heard:\nThe crowd, increasing so, the count assail,\nAnd drop from mountain and ascend from dale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Twice he ten peasants slaughtered in his mood,\nWho, charging him in disarray, were slain;\nAnd this experiment right clearly showed\nTo stand aloof was safest for the train.\nWas none who from his body could draw blood;\nFor iron smote the impassive skin in vain.\nSo had heaven's King preserved the count from scathe,\nTo make him guardian of his holy faith."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He would have been in peril on that day,\nHad he been made of vulnerable mould;\nAnd might have learned was 'twas to cast away\nHis sword, and, weaponless, so play the bold.\nThe rustic troop retreated from the fray,\nSeeing no stroke upon the madman told.\nSince him no other enemy attends,\nOrlando to a neighbouring township wends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since every one had left the place for dread,\nNo wight he found within it, small or great:\nBut here was homely food in plenty spread,\nVictual, well sorting with the pastoral state.\nHere, acorns undistinguishing from bread,\nBy tedious fast and fury driven to sate\nHis hunger, he employed his hand and jaw\nOn what he first discovered, cooked or raw."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thence, repossest with the desire to rove,\nHe, through the land, did man and beast pursue;\nAnd scowering, in his phrensy, wood and grove,\nTook sometimes goat or doe of dappled hue:\nOften with bear and with wild boar he strove,\nAnd with his naked hand the brutes o'erthrew;\nAnd gorging oftentimes the savage fare,\nSwallowed the prey with all its skin and hair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now right, now left, he wandered, far and wide,\nThroughout all France, and reached a bridge one day;\nBeneath which ran an ample water's tide,\nOf steep and broken banks: a turret gray\nWas builded by the spacious river's side,\nDiscerned, from far and near, and every way.\nWhat here he did I shall relate elsewhere,\nWho first must make the Scottish prince my care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Roland had departed on his quest,\nZerbino paused some deal; then, in his rear,\nSlowly his steed by the same path addrest,\nWhich had been taken by Anglantes' peer;\nNor two miles on his way, I think, had prest,\nWhen he beheld a captive cavalier,\nUpon a sorry, little, hackney tied,\nAnd by armed horseman watched on either side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino speedily the prisoner knew,\nAnd Isabel, as soon, when nigh surveyed.\nThis was Sir Odoric, the Biscayan, who,\nLike wolf, the guardian of a lamb was made:\nTo whom, of all his friends esteemed most true,\nZerbino Isabella had conveyed;\nHoping, one hitherto by him found just,\nWould now, as ever, have approved his trust."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even then how all had chanced, with punctual lore,\nWas Isabel relating to the knight;\nHow in the pinnace she was saved, before\nThe broken vessel sank at sea outright;\nOdoric's assault; and next, how bandits bore\nHer to the cavern, in a mountain dight.\nNor Isabella yet her tale has told,\nWhen bound the malefactor they behold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The two that had Sir Odoric in their ward,\nThe royal damsel Isabella knew;\nAnd deemed he was her lover and her lord,\nThat pricked beside the lady, fair of hue.\nMore; that the bearings on his shield record\nThe honours of the stem from which he grew;\nAnd found, as better they observed his cheer,\nThey had judged rightly of the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lighting, with open arms and hurried pace,\nThey make towards Zerbino eagerly,\nAnd, kneeling, with bare head, the prince embrace,\nWhere lord is clipt by one of less degree.\nZerbino, looking either in the face,\nKnows one Corebo of Biscay to be,\nAnd Sir Almonio, his co-mate; the pair\nCharged, under Odoric, with the galley's care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Almonio cried, \"Since God is pleased in the end,\nGrammercy!  Isabel should be with you;\nMy lord, I very clearly comprehend\nI should deliver tidings, nothing new,\nIf I should now inform you why I wend\nWith this offender, whom with me you view.\nSince she, who at his hands has suffered worst,\nThe story of his crimes will have rehearsed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"How me that traitour duped thou hast not to learn,\nWhat time he rid himself of me, nor how\nCorebo, who would have avenged the scorn,\nIntended to the damsel, was laid low;\nBut that which followed, upon my return,\nBy her unseen or heard, she cannot know,\nSo as to thee the story to have told;\nThe sequel of it then will I unfold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I seaward from the city, with a store\nOf nags, collected in a hurry, fare;\nAye watchful, if the trace I can explore\nOf those left far behind me; I repair\nThitherward; I arrive upon the shore,\nThe place where they were left; look everywhere;\nNor sign of them perceive upon that strand,\nExcept some steps, new-printed on the sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The steps I traced into the forest drear;\nNor far within the greenwood had I wound,\nWhen guided by a noise which smote my ear,\nI saw my comrade bleeding on the ground:\nOf Isabel I asked the cavalier,\nOf Odoric, and what hand had dealt his wound;\nAnd thence departed, when the thing I knew,\nSeeking the wretch these precipices through."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Wide circling still I go, and through that day\nI find no other sign of him that fled;\nAt length return to where Corebo lay,\nWho had the ground about him dyed so red,\nThat he, had I made little more delay,\nA grave would have required, and, more than bed\nAnd succour of the leech, to make him sound,\nCraved priest and friar to lay him in the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I had him to the neighbouring city brought,\nAnd boarded with a friendly host; and there\nCorebo's cure in little time was wrought,\nBeneath an old chirurgeon's skilful care.\nThis finished, having arms and horses brought,\nWe thence together to the court repair\nOf King Alphonso of Biscay; where I\nFind out the traitor, and to fight defy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The monarch's justice, who fair field and free\nAllowed us for the duel, and my right,\nAnd Destiny to boot (for Destiny\nOftener makes conquest where she listeth, light)\nSo backed my arms, that felon was by me\nWorsted, and made a prisoner in the fight.\nAlphonso, having heard his guilt confessed,\nBade me dispose of him as liked me best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Him would I neither loose, nor yet have slain,\nBut, as thou seest, in bonds to thee convey:\nThat whether he should be condemned to pain,\nOr death, it should be thine his doom to say.\nI, hearing thou wert with King Charlemagne,\nThither, in hope to find thee, took my way.\nI thank my God, that thee upon this ground,\nWhere I least hoped to meet thee, I have found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As well I render thanks, that Isabel\nI see restored to thee, I know not how,\nOf whom, by reason of that traitor fell,\nI deemed thou never more should'st tidings know.\"\nIn silence prince Zerbino hears him tell\nHis story, gazing upon Odoric's brow,\nIn pity, more than hate, as he perpends\nHow foully such a goodly friendship ends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After Almonio had his tale suspended,\nAstounded for a while the prince stood by;\nWondering, that he who least should have offended,\nHad him requited with such treachery:\nBut, his long fit of admiration ended,\nWaking from his amazement with a sigh,\nQuestioned the prisoner in the horsemen's hold,\nIt that was true the cavalier had told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The faithless man alighted, and down fell\nUpon his bended knees, and answered: \"Sir,\nAll people that on middle earth do dwell,\nThrough weakness of their nature, sin and err.\nOne thing alone distinguishes the well\nAnd evil doer; this, at every stir\nOf least desire, submits, without a blow;\nThat arms, but yields as well to stronger foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Had I been charged some castle to maintain,\nAnd, without contest, on the first assault,\nHoisted the banners of the hostile train,\n— For cowardice, or treason, fouler fault —\nUpon my eyes (a well deserved pain)\nThou might'st have justly closed the darksome vault;\nBut, yielding to superior force, I read\nI should not merit blame, but praise and meed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The stronger is the enemy, the more\nEasily is the vanquished side excused:\nI could but faith maintain as, girded sore,\nThe leaguered fort to keep her faith is used;\nEven so, with all the sense, with all the lore\nBy sovereign wisdom into me infused,\nThis I essayed to keep; but in the end,\nTo o'ermastering assault was forced to bend.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said Sir Odoric; and after showed\n(Though 'twere too tedious to recount his suit)\nHim no light cause had stirred, but puissant goad.\n— If ever earnestness of prayer could boot\nTo melt a heart that with resentment glowed,\n— If e'er humility produced good fruit,\nIt well might here avail; since all that best\nMoves a hard heart, Sir Odoric now exprest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether or no to venge such infamy,\nYouthful Zerbino doubted: the review\nOf faithless Odorico's treachery\nMoved him to death the felon to pursue;\nThe recollection of the amity\nSo long maintained between them, with the dew\nOf pity cooled the fury in his mind,\nAnd him to mercy towards the wretch inclined."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While Scotland's prince is doubting in such wise\nTo keep him captive, or to loose his chain;\nOr to remove him from before his eyes,\nBy dooming him to die, or live in pain;\nLoud neighing, thitherward the palfrey hies\nFrom which the Tartar king had stript the rein;\nAnd the old harridan, who had before\nNigh caused Zerbino's death, among them bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The horse, that had the others of that band\nHeard at a distance, thither her conveyed.\nSore weeping came the old woman, and demand\nFor succour, in her trouble, vainly made.\nZerbino, when he saw her, raised his hand\nTo heaven, that had to him such grace displayed,\nGiving him to decide that couple's fate;\nThe only two that had deserved his hate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The wicked hag is kept, so bids the peer,\nUntil he is determined what to do:\nHe to cut off her nose and either ear\nNow thought, and her as an example shew.\nNext, 'twere far better, deemed the cavalier,\nIf to the vultures he her carcase threw:\nHe diverse punishments awhile revolved,\nAnd thus the warrior finally resolved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He to his comrades turned him round, and said:\n\"To let the traitour live I am content,\nWho, if full grace he has not merited,\nYet merits not to be so foully shent.\nI, as I find his fault of Love was bred,\nTo give him life and liberty consent;\nAnd easily we all excuses own,\nWhen on commanding Love the blame is thrown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Often has Love turned upside down a brain\nOf sounder wit than that to him assigned,\nAnd led to mischief of far deeper stain,\nThan has so outraged us.  Let Odoric find\nPardon his offences; I the pain\nOf these should justly suffer, who was blind;\nBlind when I gave him such a trust, nor saw\nHow easily the fire consumes the straw.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then gazing upon Odoric, 'gan say:\n\"This is the penance I enjoin to thee;\nThat thou a year shalt with the beldam stay,\nNor ever leave this while her company;\nBut, roving or at rest, by night or day,\nShalt never for an hour without her be;\nAnd her shall even unto death maintain\nAgainst whoever threatens her with pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I will, if so this woman shall command,\nWith whosoe'er he be, thou battle do.\nI will this while that thou all France's land,\nFrom city shalt to city, wander through.\"\nSo says he: for as Odoric at his hand\nWell merits death, for his foul trespass due,\nThis is a pitfall for his feet to shape,\nWhich it will be rare fortune if he 'scape."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So many women, many men betrayed,\nAnd wronged by her, have been so many more,\nNot without strife by knight shall he be stayed,\nWho was beneath his care the beldam hoar.\nSo, for their crimes, shall both alike be paid;\nShe for her evil actions done before,\nAnd he who wrongfully shall her defraud;\nNor far can go before he finds an end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To keep the pact Zerbino makes him swear\nA mighty oath, under this penalty,\nThat should he break his faith, and anywhere\nInto his presence led by fortune be,\nWithout more mercy, without time for prayer,\nA cruel death shall wait him, as his fee.\nNext by his comrades (so their lord commands)\nSir Odoric is unpinioned from his bands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Corebo frees the traitor in the end,\nAlmonio yielding, yet as ill content:\nFor much Zerbino's mercies both offend,\nWhich thus their so desired revenge prevent.\nThence, he disloyal to his prince and friend,\nIn company with that curst woman went.\nWhat these befel Sir Turpin has not said,\nBut more I once in other author read."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This author vouches (I declare not who)\nThat hence they had not one day's journey wended,\nWhen Odoric, to all pact, all faith, untrue,\nFor riddance of the pest to him commended,\nAbout Gabrina's neck a halter threw,\nAnd left her to a neighbouring elm suspended;\nAnd in a year (the place he does not name)\nAlmonio by the traitor did the same."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino, who the Paladin pursues,\nAnd loath would be to lose the cavalier,\nTo his Scottish squadron of himself sends news,\nWhich for its captain well might stand in fear;\nAlmonio sends, and many matters shews,\nToo long at full to be recited here;\nAlmonio sends, Corebo next; nor stayed\nOther with him, besides the royal maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So mighty is the love Zerbino bore,\nNor less than his the love which Isabel\nNursed for the valorous Paladin, so sore\nHe longed to know if that bold infidel\nThe Count had found, who in the duel tore\nHim from his horse, together with the sell,\nThat he to Charles's camp, till the third day\nBe ended, will not measure back his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was the term for which Orlando said\nHe should wait him, who yet no faulchion wears;\nNor is there place the Count has visited,\nBut thither in his search Zerbino fares.\nLast to those trees, upon whose bark was read\nThe ungrateful lady's writing, he repairs,\nLittle beside the road; and there finds all\nIn strange disorder, rock and water-fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Far off, he saw that something shining lay,\nAnd spied Orlando's corslet on the ground;\nAnd next his helm; but not that head-piece gay\nWhich whilom African Almontes crowned:\nHe in the thicket heard a courser neigh,\nAnd, lifting up his visage at the sound,\nSaw Brigliadoro the green herbage browze,\nWith rein yet hanging at his saddle-bows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For Durindane, he sought the greenwood, round,\nWhich separate from the scabbard met his view;\nAnd next the surcoat, but in tatters, found;\nThat, in a hundred rags, the champaign strew.\nZerbino and Isabel, in grief profound,\nStood looking on, nor what to think they knew:\nThey of all matters else might think, besides\nThe fury which the wretched Count misguides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Had but the lovers seen a drop of blood,\nThey might have well believed Orlando dead:\nThis while the pair, beside the neighbouring flood,\nBeheld a shepherd coming, pale with dread.\nHe just before, as on a rock he stood,\nHad seen the wretch's fury; how he shed\nHis arms about the forest, tore his clothes,\nSlew hinds, and caused a thousand other woes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Questioned by good Zerbino, him the swain\nOf all which there had chanced, informed aright.\nZerbino marvelled, and believed with pain,\nAlthough the proofs were clear:  This as it might,\nHe from his horse dismounted on the plain,\nFull of compassion, in afflicted plight;\nAnd went about, collecting from the ground\nThe various relics which were scattered round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Isabel lights as well; and, where they lie\nDispersed, the various arms uniting goes.\nLo!  them a damsel joins, who frequent sigh\nHeaves from her heart, and doleful visage shows.\nIf any ask me who the dame, and why\nShe mourns, and with such sorrow overflows;\nI say 'twas Flordelice, who, bound in trace\nOf her lost lover's footsteps, sought that place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her Brandimart had left disconsolate\nWithout farewell, i' the court of Charlemagne:\nWho there expected him six months or eight; —\nAnd lastly, since he came not there again,\nFrom sea to sea, had sought her absent mate,\nThrough Alpine and through Pyrenean chain:\nIn every place had sought the warrior, save\nWithin the palace of Atlantes' grave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If she had been in that enchanted hold,\nShe might before have seen the cavalier\nWandering with Bradamant, Rogero bold,\nGradasso and Ferrau and Brava's peer.\nBut, when Astolpho chased the wizard old,\nWith the loud bugle, horrible to hear,\nTo Paris he returned; but nought of this\nAs yet was known to faithful Flordelice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Flordelice were known the arms and sword\n(Who, as I say, by chance so joined the twain),\nAnd Brigliadoro, left without his lord,\nYet bearing at the saddle-bow his rein:\nShe with her eyes the unhappy signs explored,\nAnd she had heard the tidings of the swain,\nWho had alike related, how he viewed\nOrlando running frantic, in his mood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here prince Zerbino all the arms unites,\nAnd hangs, like a fair trophy, on a pine.\nAnd, to preserve them safe from errant knights,\nNatives or foreigners, in one short line\nUpon the sapling's verdant surface writes,\nORLANDO'S ARMS, KING CHARLES'S PALADINE.\nAs he would say, `Let none this harness move,\nWho cannot with its lord his prowess prove!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino having done the pious deed,\nIs bowning him to climb his horse; when, lo!\nThe Tartar king arrives upon the mead.\nHe, at the trophied pine-tree's gorgeous show,\nBeseeches him the cause of this to read;\nWho lets him (as rehearsed the story know. ) \n\nWhen, without further pause, the paynim lord\nHastes gladly to the pine, and takes the sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"None can (he said the action reprehend, ) \n\nNor first I make the faulchion mine today;\nAnd to its just possession I pretend\nWhere'er I find it, be it where it may.\nOrlando, this not daring to defend,\nHas feigned him mad, and cast the sword away;\nBut if the champion so excuse his shame,\nThis is no cause I should forego my claim."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Take it not thence,\" to him Zerbino cried,\n\"Nor think to make it thine without a fight:\nIf so thou tookest Hector's arms of pride,\nBy theft thou hadst them, rather than by right.\"\nWithout more parley spurred upon each side.\nWell matched in soul and valour, either knight.\nAlready echoed are a thousand blows;\nNor yet well entered are the encountering foes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In scaping Durindane, a flame in show\n(He shifts so quickly is the Scottish lord. ) \n\nHe leaps about his courser like a doe,\nWhere'er the road best footing does afford.\nAnd well it is that he should not forego\nAn inch of vantage; who, if once that sword\nSmite him, will join the enamoured ghosts, which rove\nAmid the mazes of the myrtle grove."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the swift-footed dog, who does espy\nSwine severed from his fellows, hunts him hard,\nAnd circles round about; but he lies by\nTill once the restless foe neglect his guard;\nSo, while the sword descends, or hangs on high,\nZerbino stands, attentive how to ward,\nHow to save life and honour from surprise;\nAnd keeps a wary eye, and smites and flies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the other side, where'er the foe is seen\nTo threaten stroke in vain, or make good,\nHe seems an Alpine wind, two hills between,\nThat in the month of March shakes leafy wood;\nWhich to the ground now bends the forest green.\nNow whirls the broken boughs, at random strewed.\nAlthough the prince wards many, in the end\nOne mighty stroke he cannot scape or fend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the end he cannot scape one downright blow,\nWhich enters, between sword and shield, his breast,\nAs perfect was the plate and corslet, so\nThick was the steel wherein his paunch was drest:\nBut the destructive weapon, falling low,\nEqually opened either iron vest;\nAnd cleft whate'er it swept in its descent,\nAnd to the saddle-bow, through cuirass, went."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, but that somewhat short the blow descends,\nIt would Zerbino like a cane divide;\nBut him so little in the quick offends,\nThis scarce beyond the skin is scarified.\nMore than a span in length the wound extends;\nOf little depth: of blood a tepid tide\nTo his feet descending, with a crimson line,\nStains the bright arms which on the warrior shine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis so, I sometimes have been wont to view\nA hand, more white than alabaster, part\nThe silver cloth, with ribbon red of hue;\nA hand I often feel divide my heart.\nHere little vantage young Zerbino drew\nFrom strength and greater daring, and from art;\nFor in the temper of his arms and might,\nToo much the Tartar king excelled the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The fearful stroke was mightier in show,\nThan in effect, by which the Prince was prest;\nSo that poor Isabel, distraught with woe,\nFelt her heart severed in her frozen breast.\nThe Scottish prince, all over in a glow,\nWith anger and resentment was possest,\nAnd putting all his strength in either hand,\nSmote full the Tartar's helmet with his brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Almost on his steed's neck the Tartar fell,\nBent by the weighty blow Zerbino sped;\nAnd, had the helmet been unfenced by spell,\nThe biting faulchion would have cleft his head.\nThe king, without delay, avenged him well,\n\"Nor I for you till other season,\" said,\n\"Will keep this gift\"; and levelled at his crest,\nHoping to part Zerbino to the chest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino, on the watch, whose eager eye\nWaits on his wit, wheels quickly to the right;\nBut not withal so quickly, as to fly\nThe trenchant sword, which smote the shield outright,\nAnd cleft from top to bottom equally;\nShearing the sleeve beneath it, and the knight\nSmote on his arm; and next the harness rended,\nAnd even to the champion's thigh descended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Zerbino, here and there, seeks every way\nBy which to wound, nor yet his end obtains;\nFor, while he smites upon that armour gay,\nNot even a feeble dint the coat retains.\nOn the other hand, the Tartar in the fray\nSuch vantage o'er the Scottish prince obtains,\nHim he has wounded in seven parts or eight,\nAnd reft his shield and half his helmet's plate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He ever wastes his blood; his energies\nFail, though he feels it not, as 't would appear;\nUnharmed, the vigorous heart new force supplies\nTo the weak body of the cavalier.\nHis lady, during this, whose crimson dyes\nWhere chased by dread, to Doralice drew near,\nAnd for the love of Heaven, the damsel wooed\nTo stop that evil and disastrous feud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Doralice, who as courteous was as fair,\nAnd ill-assured withal, how it would end,\nWillingly granted Isabella's prayer,\nAnd straight to truce and peace disposed her friend,\nAs well Zerbino, by the other's care,\nWas brought his vengeful anger to suspend;\nAnd, wending where she willed, the Scottish lord\nLeft unachieved the adventure of the sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fair Flordelice, who ill maintained descries\nThe goodly sword of the unhappy count,\nIn secret garden, and so laments the prize\nForegone, she weeps for rage, and smite her front:\nShe would move Brandimart to this emprize;\nAnd, should she find him, and the fact recount,\nWeens, for short season will the Tartar foe\nExulting in the ravished faulchion go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seeking him morn and evening, but in vain,\nFlordelice after Brandimart did fare;\nAnd widely wandered from him, who again\nAlready had to Paris made repair.\nSo far the damsel pricked by hill and plain,\nShe reached the passage of a river, where\nShe saw the wretched count; but what befel\nThe Scottish prince, Zerbino, let me tell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For to leave Durindana such misdeed\nTo him appeared, it past all other woes;\nThough he could hardly sit upon his steed,\nThough mighty loss of life-blood, which yet flows.\nNow, when his anger and his heat secede,\nAfter short interval, his anguish grows;\nHis anguish grows, with such impetuous pains,\nHe feels that life is ebbing from his veins."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For weakness can the prince no further hie,\nAnd so beside a fount is forced to stay:\nHim to assist the pitying maid would try,\nBut knows not what to do, not what to say.\nFor lack of comfort she beholds him die;\nSince every city is too far away,\nWhere in this need she could resort to leech,\nWhose succour she might purchase or beseech."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, blaming Fortune, and the cruel sky,\nCan only utter fond complaints and vain.\n\"Why sank I not in ocean, (was her cry,)\nWhen first I reared my sail upon the main?\"\nZerbino, who on her his languid eye\nHad fixt, as she bemoaned her, felt more pain\nThan that enduring and strong anguish bred,\nThrough which the suffering youth was well-nigh dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So be thou pleased, my heart,\" (Zerbino cried,)\n\"To love me yet, when I am dead and gone,\nAs to abandon thee without a guide,\nAnd not to die, distresses me alone.\nFor did it me in place secure betide\nTo end my days, this earthly journey done,\nI cheerful, and content, and fully blest\nWould die, since I should die upon thy breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But since to abandon thee, to whom a prize\nI know not, my sad fate compels, I swear,\nMy Isabella, by that mouth, those eyes,\nBy what enchained me first, that lovely hair;\nMy spirit, troubled and despairing, hies\nInto hell's deep and gloomy bottom; where\nTo think, thou wert abandoned so by me,\nOf all its woes the heaviest pain will be.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At this the sorrowing Isabel, declining\nHer mournful face, which with her tears o'erflows,\nTowards the sufferer, and her mouth conjoining\nTo her Zerbino's, languid as a rose;\nRose gathered out of season, and which, pining\nFades where it on the shadowy hedgerow grows,\nExclaims, \"Without me think not so, my heart,\nOn this your last, long, journey to depart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of this, my heart, conceive not any fear,\nFor I will follow thee to heaven or hell;\nIt fits our souls together quit this sphere,\nTogether go, for aye together dwell.\nNo sooner closed thine eyelids shall appear\nThan either me internal grief will quell,\nOr, has it not such power, I here protest,\nI with this sword to-day will pierce my breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I of our bodies cherish hope not light,\nThat they shall have a happier fate when dead:\nTogether to entomb them, may some wight,\nHaply by pity moved, be hither led.\"\nShe the poor remnants of his vital sprite\nWent on collecting, as these words she said;\nAnd while yet aught remains, with mournful lips,\nThe last faint breath of life devoutly sips."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas here his feeble voice Zerbino manned,\nCrying.  \"My deity, I beg and pray,\nBy that love witnessed, when thy father's land\nThou quittedst for my sake; and, if I may\nIn any thing command thee, I command,\nThat, with God's pleasure, thou live-out thy day;\nNor ever banish from thy memory,\nThat, well as man can love, have I loved thee."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"God haply will provide thee with good aid,\nTo free thee from each churlish deed I fear;\nAs, when in the dark cavern thou wast stayed,\nHe sent, to rescue thee, Anglante's peer;\nSo he (grammercy! succoured thee dismaid ) \n\nAt sea, and from the wicked Biscayneer.\nAnd, if thou must choose death, in place of worse,\nThen only choose it, as a lesser curse.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I think not these last words of Scotland's knight\nWere so exprest, that he was understood:\nWith these, he finished, like a feeble light,\nWhich needs supply of was, or other food.\n— Who is there, that has power to tell aright\nThe gentle Isabella's doleful mood?\nWhen stiff, her loved Zerbino, with pale face,\nAnd cold as ice, remained in her embrace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the ensanguined corse, in sorrow drowned,\nThe damsel throws herself, in her despair,\nAnd shrieks so lout that wood and plain resound\nFor many miles about; nor does she spare\nBosom or cheek; but still, with cruel wound,\nOne and the other smites the afflicted fair;\nAnd wrongs her curling lock of golden grain,\nAye calling on the well-loved youth in vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She with such rage, such fury, was possest,\nThat, in her transport, she Zerbino's glaive\nWould easily have turned against her breast,\nIll keeping the command her lover gave;\nBut that a hermit, from his neighbouring rest,\nAccustomed oft to seek the fountain-wave,\nHis flagon at the cooling stream to fill,\nOpposed him to the damsel's evil will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The reverend father, who with natural sense\nAbundant goodness happily combined,\nAnd, with ensamples fraught and eloquence,\nWas full of charity towards mankind,\nWith efficacious reasons her did fence,\nAnd to endurance Isabel inclined;\nPlacing, from ancient Testament and new,\nWomen, as in a mirror, for her view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The holy man next made the damsel see,\nThat save in God there was no true content,\nAnd proved all other hope was transitory,\nFleeting, of little worth, and quickly spent;\nAnd urged withal so earnestly his plea,\nHe changed her ill and obstinate intent;\nAnd made her, for the rest of life, desire\nTo live devoted to her heavenly sire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not that she would her mighty love forbear,\nFor her dead lord, nor yet his relics slight;\nThese, did she halt or journey, every where\nWould Isabel have with her, day and night.\nThe hermit therefore seconding her care,\nWho, for his age, was sound and full of might,\nThey on his mournful horse Zerbino placed,\nAnd traversed many a day that woodland waste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The cautious elder would not bear away\nThus all alone with him that damsel bland\nThither, where in a cave, concealed from day,\nHis solitary cell hard by did stand:\nWithin himself exclaiming:  \"I convey\nWith peril fire and fuel in one hand.\"\nNor in such bold experiments the sage\nWisely would trust to prudence or to age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He thought to bear her to Provence, where, near\nThe city of Marseilles a borough stood,\nWhich had a sumptuous monastery; here\nOf ladies was a holy sisterhood;\nAnd, hither to transport the cavalier,\nThey stowed his body in a chest of wood,\nMade in a town by the way-side; and which\nWas long and roomy, and well closed with pitch."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So, compassing a mighty round, they fare\nThrough wildest parts, for many and many a day;\nBecause, the war extending every where,\nThey seek to hide themselves as best they may:\nAt length a cavalier arrests the pair,\nThat with foul scorn and outrage bars their way;\nOf whom you more in fitting time shall learn,\nBut to the Tartar king I now return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the fight between the two was done,\nAlready told by me, the king withdrew\nTo a cooling shade and river from the sun,\nHis horse's reins and saddle to undo;\nLetting the courser at his pleasure run,\nBrowsing the tender grass the pasture through:\nBut he reposed short time ere he descried\nAn errant knight descend the mountain's side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him Doralice, as soon as he his front\nUplifted, knew; and showed him to her knight:\nSaying: \"Behold!  the haughty Rodomont,\nUnless the distance has deceived my sight.\nTo combat with thee, he descends the mount:\nNow it behoves thee put forth all thy might.\nTo lose me, his betrothed, a mighty cross\nThe monarch deems, and comes to venge his loss.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As a good hawk, who duck or woodcock shy,\nPartridge or pigeon, or such other prey,\nSeeing towards her from a distance fly,\nRaises her head, and shows her blithe and gay;\nSo Mandricardo, in security\nOf crushing Rodomont in that affray,\nGladly his courser seized, bestrode the seat,\nReined him, and in the stirrups fixt his feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the two hostile warriors were so near,\nThat words could be exchanged between the twain,\nLoudly began the monarch of Argier\nTo threat with head and hand, in haughty strain,\nThat to repentance he will bring the peer\nWho lightly for a pleasure, rash and vain,\nHad scrupled not his anger to excite\nWho dearly will the offered scorn requite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Mandricardo:  \"He but vainly tries\nTo fright, who threatens me — by words unscared.\nWoman, or child, or him he terrifies,\nWitless of warfare; not me, who regard\nWith more delight than rest, which others prize,\nThe stirring battle; and who am prepared\nMy foeman in the lists or field to meet;\nArmed or unarmed, on horse or on my feet.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They pass to outrage, shout, and ire, unsheath\nThe brand; and loudly smites each cruel foe;\nLike winds, which scarce at first appear to breathe,\nNext shake the oak and ash-tree as they blow;\nThen to the skies upwhirl the dusty wreath,\nThen level forests, and lay houses low,\nAnd bear the storm abroad, o'er land and main,\nBy which the flocks in greenwood-holt are slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of those two infidels, unmatched in worth,\nThe valiant heart and strength, which thus exceed,\nTo such a warfare and such blows give birth,\nAs suits with warrior of so bold a seed.\nAt the loud sound and horrid, trembles earth,\nWhen the swords cross; and to the stroke succeed\nQuick sparks; or rather, flashing to the sky,\nBright flames by thousands and by thousands fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Without once gathering breath, without repose,\nThe champions one another still assail;\nStriving, now here, now there, with deadly blows,\nTo rive the plate, or penetrate the mail.\nNor this one gains, nor the other ground foregoes;\nBut, as if girded in by fosse or pale,\nOr, as too dearly sold they deem an inch,\nNe'er from their close and narrow circle flinch."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Mid thousand blows, so, with two-handed swing,\nOn his foe's forehead smote the Tartar knight,\nHe made him see, revolving in a ring,\nMyriads of fiery balls and sparks of light.\nThe croupe, with head reversed, the Sarzan king\nNow smote, as if deprived of all his might,\nThe stirrups lost; and in her sight, so well\nBeloved, appeared about to quit the sell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But as steel arbalest that's loaded sore,\nBy how much is the engine charged and strained,\nBy lever or by crane, with so much more\nFury returns, its ancient bent regained,\nAnd, in discharging its destructive store,\nInflicts worse evil than itself sustained;\nSo rose that African with ready blade,\nAnd straight with double force the stroke repaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont smites, and in the very place\nWhere he was smit, the Tartar in return;\nBut cannot wound the Sarzan in the face,\nBecause his Trojan arms the weapon turn;\nYes so astounds, he leaves him not in case,\nIf it be morn or evening to discern.\nRodomont stopt not, but in fury sped\nA second blow, still aiming at his head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Mandricardo's courser, who abhorred\nThe whistling of the steel which round him flew,\nSaved, with sore mischief to himself, his lord;\nIn that he backed the faulchion to eschew:\nAimed at his master, not at him, the sword\nSmote him across the head, and cleft it through.\nNo Trojan helm defends the wretched horse,\nLike Mandricardo, and he dies parforce."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He falls, and Mandricardo on the plain\nNo more astound, slides down upon his feet,\nAnd whirls his sword; to see his courser slain\nHe storms all over fired with angry heat.\nAt him the Sarzan monarch drives amain;\nWho stands as firm as rock which billows beat.\nAnd so it happened, that the courser good\nFell in the charge, while fast the footman stood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The African, who feels his horse give way,\nThe stirrups quits, and lightly from the sell\nIs freed, and springs on earth: for the assay\nHence matched anew, stands either infidel.\nWorse than before the battle boils, while they\nWith pride and anger, and with hatred swell,\nAbout to close; but that, with flowing rein,\nA messenger arrives to part the twain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A messenger arrives, that from the Moor,\nWith many others, news through France conveyed;\nWho word to simple knight and captain bore,\nTo join the troops, beneath their flags arrayed.\nFor he, the emperor, who the lilies wore,\nSiege to their quarters had already laid;\nAnd, save quick succour thither was addrest,\nHe read, their army's scathe was manifest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Moorish messenger not only knows,\nBy ensigns and by vest, the warlike pair,\nBut by the circling blades, and furious blows,\nWith which no other hands could wound the air;\nHence dared not 'twixt champions interpose,\nNor deemed his orders an assurance were\nFrom such impetuous fury, nor the saw,\nWhich says embassadors are safe by law:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But to fair Doralice approached, and said\nMarsilius, Agramant, and Stordilane,\nWithin weak works, with scanty troops to aid,\nWere close beleaguered by the Christian train.\nAnd, having told his tale, the damsel prayed,\nThat this she to the warriors would explain;\nAnd would accord the pair, and to their post\nDispatch, for rescue of the Moorish host."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lady, with bold heart, 'twixt either foe\nThrew herself, and exclaimed:  \"I you command,\nBy the large love you hear me, as I know,\nThat you to better use reserve the brand;\nAnd that you instantly in succour go\nOf our host, menaced by the Christian band;\nWhich now, besieged within its camp, attends\nRuin or speedy succour from its friends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The messenger rehearsed, when she had done,\nFully the peril of the paynim train;\nAnd said that he bore letters to the son\nOf Ulien, from the son of King Troyane.\nThe message ended, every grudge foregone,\n'Twas finally resolved between the twain,\nThey should conclude a truce, and till the day\nThe Moorish siege was raised, their strife delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Intending, when from siege their Chivalry\nShall be relieved — the one and the other knight —\nNo longer to remain in company,\nBut bandy cruel war was with fell despite,\nUntil determined by their arms shall be\nTo whom the royal dame belongs of right.\nAnd she, between whose hands their solemn troth\nThey plighted, was security for both."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "DISCORD, at hearing this, impatient grew;\nWith any truce or treaty ill content:\nAnd that such fair agreement should ensue,\nPRIDE, who was present, could as ill consent:\nBut LOVE was there, more puissant than the two,\nEqualled of none in lofty hardiment;\nAnd launching from his bow his shafts of proof,\nWith these, made PRIDE and DISCORD stand aloof."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To keep the truce the rival warriors swore;\nSince so it pleased her well, who either swayed.\nOne of their coursers lacked: for on the moor\nLifeless King Mandricardo's had been laid:\nHence, thither, in good time, came Brigliador,\nWho, feeding, by the river's margin strayed.\nBut here I find me at my canto's end;\nSo, with your licence, shall the tale suspend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 25"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero Richardetto from the pains\nOf fire preserves, doomed by Marsilius dead:\nHe to Rogero afterwards explains\nFully the cause while he to death was led.\nThem mournful Aldigier next entertains,\nAnd with them the ensuing morning sped,\nVivian and Malagigi to set free;\nTo Bertolagi sold for hire and fee."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh!  mighty springs of war in youthful breast,\nImpetuous force of love, and thirst of praise!\nNor yet which most avails is known aright:\nFor each by turns its opposite outweighs.\nWithin the bosom here of either knight,\nHonour, be sure, and duty strongly sways:\nFor the amorous strife between them is delayed,\nTill to the Moorish camp they furnish aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet love sways more; for, save that the command\nWas laid upon them by their lady gay,\nNeither would in that battle sheathe the brand,\nTill he was crowned with the victorious bay;\nAnd Agramant might vainly with his band,\nFor either knight's expected succour, stay.\nThen Love is not of evil nature still;\n— He can at times do good, if often ill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas now, suspending all their hostile rage,\nOne and the other paynim cavalier,\nThe Moorish host from siege to disengage,\nFor Paris, with the gentle lady, steer;\nAnd with them goes as well that dwarfish page,\nWho tracked the footsteps of the Tartar peer,\nTill he had brought the warrior front to front,\nIn presence with the jealous Rodomont."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They at a mead arrived, where, in disport,\nKnights were reposing by a stream, one pair\nDisarmed, another casqued in martial sort;\nAnd with them was a dame of visage fair.\nOf these in other place I shall report,\nNot now; for first Rogero is my care,\nThat good Rogero, who, as I have shown,\nInto a well the magic shield had thrown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He from that well a mile is hardly gone\nEre he a courier sees arrive at speed,\nOf those dispatched by King Troyano's son\nTo knights whom he awaited in his need;\nFrom him Rogero hears that so foredone\nBy Charles are those who hold the paynim creed,\nThey will, save quickly succoured in the strife,\nAs quickly forfeit liberty and life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero stood awhile in pensive case,\nWhom many warring thoughts at once opprest;\nBut neither fitted was the time nor place\nTo make his choice, or judge what promised best.\nThe courier he dismist, and turned his face\nWhither he with the damsel was addrest;\nWhom aye the Child so hurried on her way,\nHe left her not a moment for delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Pursuing thence their ancient road again,\nThey reached a city, with the westering sun;\nWhich, in the midst of France, from Charlemagne\nMarsilius had in that long warfare won:\nNor them to interrupt or to detain,\nAt drawbridge or at gate, was any one:\nThough in the fosse, and round the palisade,\nStood many men, and piles of arms were laid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Because the troop about that fortress see\nAccompanying him, the well-known dame,\nThey to Rogero leave the passage free,\nNor even question him from whence he came.\nReaching the square, of evil company\nHe finds it full, and bright with ruddy flame;\nAnd, in the midst, is manifest to view\nThe youth condemned, with face of pallid hue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As on the stripling's face he turns his eyes,\nWhich hangs declined and wet with frequent tear,\nRogero thinks he Bradamant descries;\nSo much the youth resembles her in cheer:\nMore sure the more intently he espies\nHer face and shape: when thus the cavalier:\n\"Or this is Bradamant, or I no more\nAm the Rogero which I was before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She hath adventured with too daring will,\nIn rescue of the youth condemned to die;\nAnd, for the enterprise had ended ill,\nHath there been taken, as I see.  Ah!  why\nWas she so hot her purpose to fulfil,\nThat she must hither unattended hie!\n— But I thank Heaven, that hither have I made:\nSince I am yet in time to lend her aid.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He drew his falchion without more delay,\n(His lance was broken at the other town),\nAnd, though the unarmed people making way,\nWounding flank, paunch, and bosom, bore them down.\nHe whirled his weapon, and, amid the array,\nSmote some across the gullet, cheek, or crown.\nScreaming, the dissipated rabble fled;\nThe most with cloven limbs or broken head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As while at feed, in full security,\nA troop of fowl along the marish wend,\nIf suddenly a falcon from the sky\nSwoop mid the crowd, and one surprise and rend,\nThe rest dispersing, leave their mate to die,\nAnd only to their own escape attend;\nSo scattering hadst thou seen the frighted throng,\nWhen young Rogero pricked that crowd among."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero smites the head from six or four,\nWho in escaping from the field are slow.\nHe to the breast divides as many more,\nAnd countless to the eyes and teeth below.\nI grant no helmets on their heads they wore,\nBut there were shining iron caps enow;\nAnd, if fine helmets did their temples press,\nHis sword would cut as deep, or little less."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such good Rogero's force and valour are,\nAs never now-a-days in warrior dwell;\nNor yet in rampant lion, nor in bear,\nNor (whether home or foreign beast more fell. ) \n\nHaply with him the earthquake might compare,\nOr haply the great devil — not he of hell —\nBut he who is my lord's, who moves in fire,\nAnd parts heaven, earth, and ocean in his ire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At every stroke he never less o'erthrew\nThan one, and oftener two, upon the plain;\nAnd four, at once, and even five he slew;\nSo that a hundred in a thought were slain.\nThe sword Rogero from his girdle drew\nAs knife cuts curd, divides their plate and chain.\nFalerina in Orgagna's garden made,\nTo deal Orlando death, that cruel blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But to have forged that falchion sorely rued,\nWho saw her garden wasted by the brand.\nWhat wreck, what ruin then must have ensued,\nFrom this when wielded by such warrior's hand?\nIf e'er Rogero force, e'er fury shewed,\nIf e'er his mighty valour well was scanned,\n'Twas here; 'twas here employed; 'twas here displayed;\nIn the desire to give his lady aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As hare from hound unslipt, that helpless train\nDefends itself against the cavalier.\nMany lay dead upon the cumbered plain,\nAnd numberless were they who fled in fear.\nMeanwhile the damsel had unloosed the chain\nFrom the youth's hands, and him in martial gear\nWas hastening, with what speed she might, to deck,\nWith sword in hand and shield about his neck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, who was angered sore, as best he cou'd,\nSought to avenge him of that evil crew;\nAnd gave such signal proofs of hardihood,\nAs stamped him for a warrior good and true.\nThe sun already in the western flood\nHad dipt his gilded wheels, what time the two,\nValiant Rogero and his young compeer,\nVictorious issued, of the city clear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When now Rogero and the stranger knight,\nClear of the city-gates, the champaigne reach,\nThe youth repays, with praises infinite,\nRogero in kind mode and cunning speech,\nWho him, although unknown, had sought to right,\nAt risk of life, and prays his name to teach\nThat he may know to whom his thanks he owed\nFor such a mighty benefit bestowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The visage of Bradamant I see,\nThe beauteous features and the beauteous cheer.\"\nRogero said; \"and yet the suavity\nI of her well-known accents do not hear:\nNor such return of thanks appears to be\nIn place towards her faithful cavalier.\nAnd if in very sooth it is the same,\nHow has the maid so soon forgot my name?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In wary wise, intent the truth to find,\nRogero said, \"You have I seen elsewhere;\nAnd have again, and yet again, divined,\nYet know I not, nor can remember where.\nSay it, yourself, if it returns to mind,\nAnd, I beseech, your name as well declare:\nWhich I would gladly hear, in the desire\nTo know whom I have rescued from the fire.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" — Me, it is possible you may have seen,\nI know not when nor where (the youth replied);\nFor I too range the world, in armour sheen,\nSeeking adventure strange on every side;\nOr haply it a sister may have been,\nWho to her waist the knightly sword has tied;\nBorn with me at a birth; so like to view,\nThe family discerns not who is who."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You not first, second, or even fourth will be,\nWho have in this their error had to learn;\nNor father, brother, nor even mother me\nFrom her (such our resemblance can discern. ) \n\n'Tis true, this hair, which short and loose you see,\nIn many guise, and hers, with many a turn,\nAnd in long tresses wound about her brow,\nWide difference made between us two till now."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But since the day, that, wounded by a Moor\nIn the head (a story tedious to recite)\nA holy man, to heal the damsel's sore,\nCut short to the mid-ear her tresses bright,\nExcepting sex and name, there is no more\nOne from the other to distinguish; hight\nI Richardetto am, Bradamant she;\nRinaldo's brother and his sister we."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And to displease you were I not afraid,\nYou with a wonder would I entertain,\nWhich chanced from my resemblance to the maid;\nBegun in pleasure, finishing in pain.\"\nHe to whom nought more pleasing could be said,\nAnd to whose ears there was no sweeter strain\nThat what in some sort on his lady ran,\nBesought the stripling so, that he began."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"It so fell out, that as my sister through\nThe neighbouring wood pursued her path, a wound\nWas dealt the damsel by a paynim crew,\nWhich her by chance without a helmet found.\nAnd she was fain to trim the locks which grew\nClustering about the gash, to maker her sound\nOf that ill cut which in her head she bore:\nHence, shorn, she wandered through the forest hoar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ranging, she wandered to a shady font;\nWhere, worn and troubled, she, in weary wise,\nLit from her courser and disarmed her front,\nAnd, couched upon the greenwood, closed her eyes.\nA tale more pleasing than what I recount\nIn story there is none, I well surmise:\nThither repaired young Flordespine of Spain,\nWho in that wood was hunting with her train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, when she found my sister in the shade,\nCovered, except her face, with martial gear,\n— In place of spindle, furnished with the blade —\nBelieved that she beheld a cavalier:\nThe face and manly semblance she surveyed,\nTill conquered was her heart: with courteous cheer\nShe wooed the maid to hunt with her, and past\nWith her alone into that hold at last."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When now she had her, fearless of surprise,\nSafe in a solitary place, that dame,\nBy slow degrees, in words and amorous wise,\nShowed her deep-wounded heart; with sighs of flame,\nBreathed from her inmost breast, with burning eyes,\nShe spake her soul sick with desire; became\nNow pale, now red; nor longer self-controlled,\nRavished a kiss, she waxed so passing bold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My sister was assured the huntress maid\nFalsely conceited her a man to be;\nNor in that need could she afford her aid;\nAnd found herself in sore perplexity.\n` 'Tis better that I now dispel (she said)\nThe foolish thought she feeds, and that in me\nThe damsel should a gentle woman scan,\nRather than take me for a craven man.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And she said well: for cravenhood it were\nBefitting man of straw, not warrior true,\nWith whom so bright a lady deigned to pair,\nSo wonderous sweet and full of nectarous dew,\nTo clack like a poor cuckow to the fair,\nHanging his coward wing, when he should woo,\nShaping her speech to this in wary mode,\nMy sister that she was a damsel, showed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That, like Camilla and like Hyppolite,\nSought fame in battle-field, and near the sea,\nIn Afric, in Arzilla, saw the light;\nTo shield and spear enured from infancy.\nA spark this quenched not; nor yet burned less bright\nThe enamoured damsel's kindled phantasy.\nToo tardy came the salve to ease the smart:\nSo deep had Love already driven his dart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor yet less fair to her my sister's face\nAppeared, less fair her ways, less fair her guise;\nNor yet the heart returned into its place,\nWhich joyed itself within those dear-loved eyes.\nFlordespine deems the damsel's iron case\nTo her desire some hope of  ease supplies;\nAnd when she thinks she is indeed a maid,\nLaments and sobs, with mighty woe downweighed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He who had marked her sorrow and lament,\nThat day, himself had sorrowed with the fair.\n`What pains (she said did ever wight torment, ) \n\nSo cruel, but that mine more cruel were?\nI need not to accomplish my intent,\nIn other love, impure or pure, despair;\nThe rose I well might gather from the thorn:\nMy longing only is of hope forlorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `It 'twas thy pleasure, Love, to have me shent,\nBecause by glad estate thine anger stirred,\nThou with some torture might'st have been content\nOn other lovers used; but never word\nHave I found written of a female bent\nOn love of female, mid mankind or herd.\nWoman to woman's beauty still is blind;\nNor ewe delights in ewe, nor hind in hind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Tis only I, on earth, in air, or sea,\nWho suffer at thy hands such cruel pain;\nAnd this thou hast ordained, that I may be\nThe first and last example in thy reign.\nFoully did Ninus' wife and impiously\nFor her own son a passion entertain;\nLoved was Pasiphae's bull and Myrrha's sire;\nBut mine is madder than their worst desire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Here female upon male had set her will;\nHad hope; and, as I hear, was satisfied.\nPasiphae the wooden cow did fill:\nOthers, in other mode, their want supplied.\nBut, had he flown to me, — with all his skill,\nDan Daedalus had not the noose untied:\nFor one too diligent hath wreathed these strings;\nEven Nature's self, the puissantest of things.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So grieves the maid, so goads herself and wears,\nAnd shows no haste her sorrowing to forego;\nSometimes her face, sometimes her tresses tears,\nAnd levels at herself the vengeful blow.\nIn pity, Bradamant the sorrow shares,\nAnd is constrained to hear the tale of woe,\nShe studies to divert, with fruitless pain,\nThe strange and mad desire; but speaks in vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She, who requires assistance, not support,\nStill more laments herself, with grief opprest.\nBy this the waning day was growing short,\nFor the low sun was crimsoning the west;\nA fitting hour for those to seek a port,\nWho would not in the wood set up their rest.\nWhen to this city, near her sylvan haunt,\nYoung Flordespine invited Bradament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My sister the request could ill deny;\nAnd so they came together to the place,\nWhere, but for you, by that ill squadron I\nHad been compelled the cruel flame to face:\nThere Flordespina made her family\nCaress and do my sister no small grace;\nAnd, having in a female robe arraid,\nPast her on all beholders for a maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Because perceiving vantage there was none\nIn the male cheer by which she was misled,\nThe damsel held it wise, reproach to shun,\nWhich might by any carping tongue be said.\nAnd this the rather: that the ill, which one\nOf the two garments in her mind had bred,\nNow with the other which revealed the cheat,\nShe would assay to drive from her conceit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The ladies share one common bed that night,\nTheir bed the same, but different their repose.\nOne sleeps, one groans and weeps in piteous plight,\nBecause her wild desire more fiercely glows;\nAnd on her wearied eyes should slumber light,\nAll is deceitful that brief slumber shows.\nTo her it seems, as if relenting Heaven\nA better sex to Bradamant is given."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As the sick man with burning thirst distrest,\nIf he should sleep, — ere he that wish fulfil, —\nAye in his troubled, interrupted rest,\nRemembers him of every once-seen rill:\nSo is the damsel's fancy still possest,\nIn sleep, with images which glad her will.\nThen from the empty dreams which crowd her brain,\nShe wakes, and, waking, finds the vision vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What vows she vowed, how oft that night she prayed,\nTo all her gods and Mahound, in despair!\n— That they, by open miracle, the maid\nWould change, and give her other sex to wear.\nBut all the lady's vows were ill appaid,\nAnd haply Heaven as well might mock the prayer;\nNight fades, and Phoebus raises from the main\nHis yellow head, and lights the world again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"On issueing from their bed when day is broken,\nThe wretched Flordespina's woes augment:\nFor of departing Bradamant had spoken,\nAnxious to scape from that embarrassment.\nThe princess a prime jennet, as a token,\nForced on my parting sister, when she went;\nAnd gilded housings, and a surcoat brave,\nWhich her own hand had richly broidered, gave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her Flordespine accompanied some way,\nThen, weeping, to her castle made return.\nSo fast my sister pricked, she reached that day\nMount Alban; we who for her absence mourn,\nMother and brother, greet the martial may,\nAnd her arrival with much joy discern:\nFor hearing nought, we feared that she was dead,\nAnd had remained in cruel doubt and dread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Unhelmed, we wondered at her hair, which passed\nIn braids about her brow, she whilom wore;\nNor less we wondered at the foreign cast\nOf the embroidered surcoat which she wore:\nAnd she to us rehearsed, from first to last,\nThe story I was telling you before;\nHow she was wounded in the wood, and how,\nFor cure, were shorn the tresses from her brow;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And next how came on her, with labour spent,\n— As by the stream she slept — that huntress bright;\nAnd how, with all her false semblance well content,\nShe from the train withdrew her out of sight.\nNor left she any thing of her lament\nUntold; which touched with pity every wight;\nTold how the maid had harboured her, and all\nWhich past, till she revisited her Hall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of Flordespine I knew: and I had seen\nIn Saragossa and in France the maid;\nTo whose bewitching eyes and lovely mien\nMy youthful appetite had often strayed:\nYet her I would not make my fancy's queen;\nFor hopeless love is but a dream and shade:\nNow I this proffered in such substance view,\nStraitway the ancient flame breaks forth anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Love, with this hope, constructs his subtle ties;\nWho other threads for me would vainly weave.\n'Tis thus he took me, and explained the guise\nIn which I might the long-sought boon achieve.\nEasy it were the damsel to surprise;\nFor as the likeness others could deceive,\nWhich I to Bradamant, my sister, bear,\nThis haply might as well the maid ensnare."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whether I speed or no, I hold it wise,\nAye to pursue whatever give delight.\nI with no other of my plan devise,\nNor any seek to counsel me aright.\nWell knowing where the suit of armour lies\nMy sister doffed, I thither go at night;\nHer armour and her steed to boot I take,\nNor stand expecting until daylight break."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I rode all night — Love served me as a guide —\nTo seek the home of beauteous Flordespine;\nAnd there arrived, before in ocean's tide\nThe western sun had hid his orbit sheen.\nA happy man was he who fastest hied\nTo tell my coming to the youthful queen;\nExpecting from that lady, for his pain,\nFavour and goodly guerdon to obtain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For Bradamant the guests mistake me all,\n— As you yourself but now — so much the more,\nThat I have both the courser and the pall\nWith which she left them but the day before.\nFlordespine comes at little interval,\nWith such festivity and courteous lore,\nAnd with a face, so jocund and so gay,\nShe could not, for her life, more joy display."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her beauteous arms about my neck she throws,\nAnd fondly clasping me, my mouth she kist.\nIf to my inmost heart the arrow goes,\nWhich Love directs, may well by you be wist.\nShe leads me to her chamber of repose\nIn haste, not suffers others to assist\nIn taking off my panoply of steel;\nDisarming me herself from head to heel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then, ordering from her store a costly vest,\nShe spread it, and — as I a woman were —\nThe lady me in that rich garment drest,\nAnd in a golden net confined my hair.\nI gravely moved my eye-balls, nor confest,\nBy gesture or by look, the sex I bear.\nMy voice, which might discover the deceit,\nI tuned so well that none perceived the cheat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Next to the hall, where dame and cavalier\nIn crowds are gathered, we united go;\nWho make to us such court and goodly cheer,\nAs men to queen or high-born lady show.\nHere oft I laughed at some, with secret jeer,\nWho, knowing not the sex concealed below\nMy flowing robe of feminine array,\nWooed me with wishful eyes in wanton way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When more advanced in now the festive night,\nAnd the rich board — board plenteously purveyed\nWith what in season was most exquisite —\nHas been some time removed, the royal maid\nExpects not till I of myself recite\nThe cause, which thither me anew conveyed:\nBy her own courtesy and kindness led,\nThat lady prays me to partake her bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Damsels and dames withdrawn — with all the rest —\nPages and chamberlains, when now we lay,\nOne and the other, in our bed undrest,\nWith kindled torches, counterfeiting day;\n`Marvel not, lady,' (her I thus addrest,)\n`That I return after such short delay;\nFor, haply, thou imagined, that again\nThou shouldst not see me until Heaven knows when."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `The reason I departed from thy side,\nAnd next of my return, explained shall be.\nCould I unto thy fever have applied,\nBy longer sojourn here, a remedy,\nI in thy service would have lived and died,\nNor would have been an hour away from thee:\nBut seeing how my stay increased thy woe,\nI, who could do no better, fixed to go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Into the middle of a wood profound\nBy chance I from the beaten pathway strayed:\nWhere near me plaintive cries I hear resound,\nAs of a woman who intreated aid.\nTo a lake of crystal I pursue the sound,\nAnd, there, amid the waves, a naked maid\nCaught on the fish-hook of a Faun, survey,\nWho would devour alive his helpless prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Upon the losel, sword in hand, I ran,\nAnd, for I could not aid in other wise,\nBereft of life that evil fisherman.\nShe in an instant to the water flies.\n— `Me hast thou helped not vainly,' (she began)\nAnd well shalt be rewarded — with what prize\nThou canst demand — for know I am a nymph,\nAnd have my dwelling in this crystal lymph;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And power is mine to work portentous ends;\nNature and Elements I force: thy prayer\nShape to the scope to which my strength extends,\nAnd leave its satisfaction to my care.\nCharmed by my song the moon from Heaven descends;\nFire can I freeze, and harden liquid air;\nAnd I at times have stopt the sun, and stirred\nThis earth beneath me by a simple word.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Treasure I covet not, nor yet aspire\nO'er land or people to hold sovereign sway;\nNor greater strength nor valour would acquire,\nNor fame in every warfare bear away;\nBut only to accomplish thy desire,\nEntreat the damsel she will show some way.\nNor one nor other method I forestall;\nBut to her choice refer me, all in all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Scarce my demand was made, before mine eye\nBeneath the lymph engulphed that lady viewed:\nNor answered she my prayer, but, for reply,\nMe with the enchanted element bedewed;\nWhich has no sooner touched my face than I,\nI know not how, am utterly transmewed:\nI see, I feel — yet doubting what I scan —\nFeel, I am changed from woman into man.\n\nLXV - LXIX\n(Stazas LXV - LXIX untranslated by Rose)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The thing remained concealed between us two;\nSo that our bliss endured some months; at last\nWe were espied; and, as I sorely rue,\nThe tidings to the Spanish monarch past.\nThou that whilere preserved'st me from the crew,\nWhich me into the flames designed to cast,\nBy this mayst fully comprehend the rest;\nBut God alone can read my sorrowing breast.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So Richardetto spake, and by his say\nMade the dark path they trod less irksome be.\nUp a small height this while their journey lay,\nGirded with cliff and cavern, drear to see.\nBristling with rocks, a steep and narrow way\nWas to that rugged hill the stubborn key;\nA town, called Agrismonte, crowned the steep,\nWhich Aldigier of Clermont had in keep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bastard of Buovo, brother to the pair,\nSir Vivian and Sir Malagigi hight:\nWho him Gerardo's lawful son declare,\nAre witnesses of little worth and light.\n— This, as it may! — strong, valiant, wise, and ware,\nLiberal, humane, and courteous was the knight;\nAnd on the fortress of its absent lord,\nBy night and day, kept faithful watch and ward."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His cousin Richardetto, as behoved,\nWas courteously received by Aldigier;\nWho him as dearly as a brother loved,\nAnd made Rogero for his sake good cheer;\nBut not with wonted welcome; — inly moved —\nHe even wore a visage sad and drear:\nFor he, that day, ill-tidings had received,\nAnd hence in heart and face the warrior grieved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Richardetto he exclaims, instead\nOf greeting: \"Evil news are hither blown.\nBy a sure messenger, to-day I read\nThat faithless Bertolagi of Bayonne,\nWith barbarous Lanfusa has agreed,\nAnd costly spoils makes over to that crone;\nWho will consign to him the brethren twain,\nThy Malagigi and thy Viviane;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"These she, since Ferrau took them, aye has stayed\nImprisoned in a dark and evil cell;\nTill the discourteous and foul pact was made\nWith that false Maganzese of whom I tell;\nAnd them to-morrow, to a place conveyed\n'Twixt Bayonne and a town of his, will sell\nTo him, who will be present, to advance\nThe price of the most precious blood in France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"One, at a gallop, even now, to report\nTidings to our Rinaldo of the wrong,\nI sent; bur fear that he can ill resort\nTo him in time, the journey is so long.\nMen have I not to sally from my fort;\nAnd my power halts where my desire is strong.\nThe traitor will the knights, if rendered, slay;\nNor know I what to do nor what to say.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Richardetto the ill news displease,\nAnd (as they him displease in equal wise ) \n\nRogero; who, when silent both he sees,\nNor able any counsel to devise,\nExclaims with mickle daring: \"Be at ease;\nI challenge for myself the whole emprize;\nAnd, to set free your brethren, in my hand\nMore than a thousand shall avail this brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I ask not men, I ask not aid; my spear\nIs, I believe, sufficient to the feat.\nI only ask of you a guide to steer\nMe to the place where for the exchange they meet:\nI even in this place will make you hear\nTheir cries, who for that evil bargain threat.\"\nHe said; nor to one listener of the twain,\nThat had helped his actions, spake in vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The other heard him not, or heard at most\nAs we great talkers hear, who little do:\nBut Richardetto took aside their host\nAnd told how him he from the fire withdrew;\nAnd how he was assured, beyond his boast,\nHe would in time and place his prowess shew.\n'Twas now that better audience than before\nAldigier lent, and set by him great store;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And at the feast, where Plenty for the three\nEmptied her horn, him honoured as his lord.\nHere they conclude they can the brethren free\nWithout more succour from their gaoler's ward.\nThis while Sleep seized on lord and family,\nSave young Rogero: no repose afford\nTo him the thoughts, which evermore molest,\nAnd, rankling in his bosom, banish rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The siege of Agramant, to him that day\nTold by the messenger, he has at heart.\nHe well discerns that every least delay\nWill he dishonour.  What a ceaseless smart\nWill scorn inflict, what shame will him appay,\nIf he against his sovereign lord take part?\nOh!  what foul cowardice, how foul a crime\nHis baptism will appear at such a time!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That true religion had the stripling swayed\nMen might at any other time conceive:\nBut now, when needed was the warrior's aid\nFrom siege the Moorish monarch to relieve,\nThat Fear and Baseness had more largely weighed,\nIn his designs, would every one believe,\nThat any preference of a better creed:\nThis thought makes good Rogero's bosom bleed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor less to quit his Queen, her leave unsought,\nDid with Rogero's other griefs combine:\nNow this and now that care upon him wrought;\nWhich diversely his doubtful heart incline:\nThe unhappy lover fruitlessly had thought\nTo find her at the abode of Flordespine;\nWhither together went (as told whilere)\nTo succour Richardetto, maid and peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He next bethinks him of the promise plight\nTo meet at Vallombrosa's sanctuary,\nDeems her gone thither, and that 'twill excite\nHer wonderment himself not there to see.\nCould he at least a message send or write,\nThat he with reason might not censured be,\nBecause not only he had disobeyed,\nBut was departing hence, and nothing said!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, having thought on many things, in the end\nResolves on writing what behoves; and, though\nHe knows not how his letter he shall send,\nIn the assurance it will safely go,\nThis hinders not; he thinks that, as they wend,\nChance in his way some faithful Post may throw;\nNor more delays: up leaps the restless knight,\nAnd calls for pen and paper, ink and light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That which is needed, in obedience meet,\nAldigier's valets bring, a careful band,\nThe youth begins to write; and, first, to greet\nThe maid, as wonted courtesies demand;\nNext tells how Agramant has sent to entreat,\nIn his dispatches, succour at his hand;\nAnd, save he quickly to his comfort goes,\nMust needs be slain or taken by his foes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then adds, his sovereign being so bested,\nAnd praying him for succour in his pain,\nShe must perceive what blame upon his head\nWould light, if Agramant applied in vain;\nAnd, since with her he is about to wed,\n'Tis fitting he should keep him with stain;\nFor ill he deems a union could endure\nBetween aught foul and her to passing pure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And if he erst a name, renowned and clear,\nHad laboured to procure by actions fair,\nAnd having gained it thus, he held it dear,\n— If this had sought to keep — with greater care\nHe kept it now, — and with a miser's fear\nGuarded the treasure she with him would share;\nWho, though distinct in body and in limb,\nWhen wedded, ought to be one soul with him;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, as he erst by word, he now explained\nAnew by writing, that the period o'er,\nFor which he was to serve his king constrained,\nUnless it were his lot to die before,\nHe would in deed a Christian be ordained,\nAs in resolve he had been evermore;\nAnd of her kin, Rinaldo and her sire,\nHer afterwards in wedlock would require."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I would,\" he said, \"relieve, with your good will,\nMy king, besieged by Charlemagne's array,\nThat the misjudging rabble, prone to ill,\nMight never, to my shame and scandal, say:\nRogero, in fair wind and weather, still\nWaited upon his sovereign, night and day,\nAnd now that Fortune to King Charles is fled,\nHas with that conquering lord his ensign spread.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I fifteen days or twenty ask, that I\nYet once again may to our army speed;\nSo that, by me from leaguering enemy\nThe African cantonments may be freed:\nI will some fit and just occasion spy,\nMeanwhile, to justify my change of creed,\nI for my honour make this sole request;\nThen wholly yours for life, in all things, rest.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero is such words his thoughts exposed,\nWhich never could by me be fully showed;\nAnd added more, nor from his task reposed,\nUntil the crowded paper overflowed:\nHe next the letter folded and enclosed,\nAnd sealed it, and within his bosom stowed;\nIn hopes to meet next morning by the way\nOne who might covertly that writ convey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he had closed the sheet, that amorous knight\nHis eyelids closed as well, and rest ensued:\nFor Slumber came and steeped his wearied might\nIn balmy moisture, from a branch imbued\nWith Lethe's water; and he slept till — white\nAnd red — a rain of flowers the horizon strewed,\nPainting the joyous east with colours gay;\nWhen from her golden dwelling broke the day:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when the greenwood birds 'gan, far and wide,\nGreet the returning light with gladsome strain,\nSir Aldigier (who wished to be the guide,\nUpon that journey, of the warlike twain,\nWho would in succour of those brethren ride,\nTo rescue them from Bertolagi's chain)\nWas first upon his feet; and either peer\nIssues as well from bed, when him they hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When clad and thoroughly in arms arrayed —\nRogero with the cousins took his way,\nHaving that pair already warmly prayed\nThe adventure on himself alone to lay:\nBut these, by love for those two brethren swayed,\nAnd deeming it discourtesy to obey,\nStood out against his prayer, more stiff than stone,\nNor would consent that he should wend alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "True to the time and place of change, they hie\nWhither Sir Aldigier's advices teach;\nAnd there survey an ample band who lie\nExposed to fierce Apollo's heat; in reach,\nNor myrtle-tree nor laurel they descry,\nNor tapering cypress, ash, nor spreading beech:\nBut naked gravel with low shrubs discerned,\nUndelved by mattock and by share unturned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those three adventurous warriors halted where\nA path went through the uncultivated plain,\nAnd saw a knight arrive upon the lair,\nWho, flourished o'er with gold, wore plate and chain,\nAnd on green field that beauteous bird and rare,\nWhich longer than an age extends its reign.\nNo more, my lord: for at my canto's close\nI find myself arrived, and crave repose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 26"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of mighty matters, sculptured in a font,\nDoes Malagigi to his comrades tell:\nOn them come Mandricardo and Rodomont,\nAnd forthwith battle follows fierce and fell.\nDiscord goes scattering quarrel and affront\nAmid the crew: but whither, forced by spell,\nFair Doralice upon her palfrey speeds,\nThe Tartar king, and Sarzan, turn their steeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In former ages courteous ladies were,\nWho worshipt virtue, and not worldly gear.\nWomen in this degenerate age are rare,\nTo whom aught else but sordid gain is dear;\nBut they who real goodness make their care,\nNor with the avaricious many steer,\nIn this frail life are worthy to be blest,\n— Held glorious and immortal when at rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant well would deathless praise inherit,\nWho nor in wealth nor empire took delight;\nBut in Rogero's worth, excelling spirit,\nIn his unbounded gentlesse; and aright\nFor this did good Duke Aymon's daughter merit\nTo be beloved of such a valorous knight;\nWho, what might be for miracles received,\nIn future ages, for her sake achieved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, with those two of Clermont, as whilere\nCanto said,\nI say with Richardet and Aldigier,\nWas gone, to give the prisoned brethren aid:\nI told, as well how they a cavalier\nOf haughty look approaching had surveyed,\nWho bore that noble bird, by fiery birth\nRenewed, and ever single upon earth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When those three of that warrior were espied,\nPoised on the wing, as if about to smite,\nHe fain by proof their prowess would have tried,\nAnd if their semblance tallied with their might.\n\"Is there, among you, one,\" the stranger cried,\n\"Will prove upon me, which is best in fight,\nWith lance or sword, till one to ground be cast,\nWhile in the sell his foe is seated fast?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" — I, at your choice,\" said Aldigier, \"were fain\nTo flourish faulchion, or to tilt with spear;\nBut this with feat, which, if you here remain,\nYourself may witness, so would interfere,\nThat for the present parley time with pain\nSuffices, and yet less for the career.\nSix hundred men, or more, we here attend,\nWith whom we must to-day in arms contend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Two of our own to rescue from their foes,\nAnd free from chains, us Love and Pity sway.\"\nHe to that stranger next the reason shows\nWhy thus in steel their bodies they array.\n\"So just is the excuse which you oppose,\"\n— He answered — \"that I ill should this gainsay,\nAnd hold you surely for three cavaliers\nThat seldom upon earth will find their peers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With you a lance or two I would have crost\nTo prove how great your prowess in the field;\nBut, since 'tis shown me at another's cost,\nForego the joust, and to your reasons yield.\nWarmly I pray your leave against that host,\nTo join with your good arms this helm and shield;\nAnd hope, if suffered of your band to be,\nNo worthless comrade shall you find in me.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Some one, meseems, may crave the stranger's name,\nWho thus the champions on their road delayed,\nAnd so to partnership in arms laid claim\nWith those three warriors, for the strife arrayed:\nSHE — style no more a man that martial dame —\nMarphisa was; that on Zerbino laid\nThe task to bear about, against his will,\nRibald Gabrina, prone to every ill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The two of Clermont and their bold compeer\nGladly received her succour in their cause,\nWhom certes they believed a cavalier,\nAnd not a damsel, and not what she was.\nA banner was espied by Aldigier\nAnd shown the others, after little pause,\nWhich by the wavering wind was blown about,\nAnd round about it ranged a numerous rout."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when, now nearer, the advancing crew\nWere better marked in Moorish habit stoled,\nFor Saracens the stranger band they knew;\nAnd they upon two sorry jades behold,\nI' the middle of that troop, the prisoners, who\nWere to the false Maganza to be sold.\nMarphisa cries, \"Why is the feast delayed,\nWhen lo!  the guests are here, for whom we stayed?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"Not all,\" Rogero said, \"Of the array\nInvited, lacks as yet a numerous part:\nA solemn festival is held to-day,\nAnd we. to grace it more, use every art:\nYet they can now but little more delay.\"\nWhile thus they parley, they from other part\nDescry the treacherous Maganzese advance;\nSo all was ready to begin the dance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They of Maganza from one quarter steer,\nAnd laden mules beneath their convoy go,\nBearing vest, gold, and other costly gear.\nOn the other side, mid faulchion, spear, and bow,\nApproached the captive two with doleful cheer,\nWho found themselves awaited by the foe;\nAnd false and impious Bertolagi heard,\nAs with the Moorish captain he conferred."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor Buovo's nor Duke Aymon's valiant son\nCan hold, when that false Maganzese they view;\nAgainst him both with rested lances run:\nHe falls the victim of those furious two,\nThrough belly and through pummel pierced by one,\nAnd by the other, in mid visage, through\nHis bleeding cheeks: may like disastrous fate\nO'erwhelm all evil doers, soon or late!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa with Rogero moved her horse\nAt this, nor waited other trumpet-strain;\nNor broke her lance in her impetuous course,\nTill in succession three had prest the plain.\nA mark well worthy fierce Rogero's force,\nThe paynim leader in a thought is slain;\nAnd with him, pierced by the same weapon, go\nTwo others to the gloomy realms below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas hence a foul mistake the assaulted made;\nIt caused their utter loss, and ruined all:\nThey of Maganza deemed themselves betrayed\nBy the infidels, upon their leader's fall:\nOn the other side, so charged with hostile blade,\nThe Moors those Maganzese assassins call;\nAnd, with fierce slaughter, either angry horde\n'Gan bend bow, and brandish lance and sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, charging this, or the other band,\nSlays ten or twenty, shifting his career;\nNo fewer by the warlike damsel's hand\nAre slaughtered and extinguished, there and here:\nAs many men as feel the murderous brand\nAre from the saddle seen to disappear:\nBefore it vanish cuirass, helms and shields,\nAs the dry wood to fire in forest yields."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If ever you remember to have viewed,\nOr heard, — what time the wasps divided are,\nAnd all the winged college is at feud,\nMustering their swarms for mischief in mid air, —\nThe greedy swallow swoop amid that brood,\nTo mangle and devour, and kill, and tear,\nYou must imagine so, on either part\nThe bold Rogero and Marphisa dart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not so Sir Richardet and Aldigier,\nVaried the dance between those squadrons twain;\nFor, heedless of the Moors, each cavalier\nHad but an eye to false Maganza's train.\nThe brother of Rinaldo, Charles's peer,\nMuch courage added to much might and main;\nAnd these were now redoubled by the spite,\nWhich against false Maganza warmed the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This cause made him who in his fury shared,\nGood Buovo's bastard, seems a lion fell;\nHe, without pause, each trusty helmet pared\nWith his good blade, or crushed it like the shell\nOf brittle egg: and who would not have dared —\nWould not have shown a Hector's worth as well,\nHaving two such companions in the stower,\nOf warlike wights the very choice and flower?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa, waging all the while the fight,\nOn her companions often turned to gaze,\nAnd as she marked their rivalry in might,\nAdmiring, upon all bestowed her praise;\nBut when she on Rogero fixed her sight,\nDeemed him unparalleled; and in amaze,\nAt times believed that Paladin was Mars,\nWho left his heaven to mix in mortal wars."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She marvels at the champion's horrid blows;\nShe marvels how in vain they never fell.\nThe iron, smit by Balisarda shows\nLike paper, not like stubborn plate and shell.\nTo pieces helm and solid corslet goes,\nAnd men are severed, even to the sell;\nWhom into equal parts those strokes divide,\nHalf dropt on this, and half on the other side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With the same downright stroke, he overbore\nThe horse and rider, bleeding in the dust;\nThe heads of others from their shoulders bore,\nAnd parted from the hips the bleeding bust.\nHe often at a blow cleft five and more;\nAnd — but I doubt who hears me might distrust\nWhat of a seeming falsehood bears the impress —\nI would say more; but I parforce say less."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Good Turpin, he who knows that he tells true,\nAnd leaves men to believe what they think right,\nSays of Rogero wondrous things, which you\nHearing related, would as falsehoods slight.\nThus, with Marphisa matched, that hostile crew\nAppears like ice, and she like burning light.\nNor her Rogero with less marvel eyes,\nThat she had marked his valour with surprise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As she had Mars in bold Rogero seen,\nPerhaps Bellona he had deemed the maid,\nIf for a woman he had known that queen,\nWho seemed the contrary, in arms arrayed;\nAnd haply emulation had between\nThe pair ensued, by whom with cruel blade\nMost deadly signs of prowess should be shown,\nMid that vile herd, on sinew, flesh and bone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To rout each hostile squadron, filled with dread,\nSufficed the soul and valour of the four;\nNor better arms remained for them who fled\nThan the sharp goads which on their heels they wore.\nHappy was he with courser well bested!\nBy trot or amble they set little store;\nAnd he who had no steed, here learned, dismayed,\nHow wretched is the poor foot-soldier's trade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The conqueror's prize remained both field and prey;\nNor was there footman left nor muleteer;\nThe Moor took this, Maganza took that way;\nOne leaves the prisoners, and one leaves the gear.\nWith visage glad, and yet with heart more gay,\nThe four united each captive cavalier;\nNor were less diligent to free from chains\nThe prisoned pages, and unload the wains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Besides good quantity of silver fine,\nWrought into different vessels, with a store\nOf feminine array, of fair design,\nEmbroidered round about with choicest lore,\nAnd suit of Flemish tapestry, framed to line\nRoyal apartments, wrought with silk and ore —\n— They, 'mid more costly things in plenty spread —\nDiscovered flasks of wine, and meat and bread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When now the conquering troop their temples bare,\nAll see they have received a damsel's aid,\nKnown by her curling locks of golden hair,\nAnd delicate and beauteous face displayed:\nHer the knights honoured much, and to declare\nHer name, so well deserving glory, prayed;\nNor she, that ever was of courteous mood\nAmong her friends, their instances withstood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With viewing her they cannot sate their eyes,\nWho in the battle such had her espied,\nShe speaks but with the Child, but him descries;\nNone prizes, values none, 'twould seem, beside.\nMeanwhile that ready spread a banquet lies,\nTo them is by the servants notified.\nThis they had served about a neighbouring fountain,\nScreened from the sun by an o'ershadowing mountain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This spring was one of those four fountains rare,\nOf those in France produced by Merlin's sleight;\nEncompassed round about with marble fair,\nShining and polished, and then milk more white.\nThere in the stone choice figures chisseled were,\nBy that magician's godlike labour dight;\nSave voice was wanting, these you might have thought\nWere living and with nerve and spirit fraught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here, to appearance, from the forest prest\nA cruel Beast and hideous to the eye,\nWith teeth of wolf, an ass's head and crest,\nA carcass with long famine lean and dry,\nAnd lion's claws; a fox in all the rest:\nWhich seemed to ravage France and Italy,\nAnd Spain and England's desolated strands,\nEurope and Asia, and in fine all lands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beast the low and those of proudest port\nHad slain or maimed throughout this earthly ball;\nYea, fiercest seemed on those of noble sort,\nSovereign and satrap, prince and peer, to fall;\nAnd made most havoc in the Roman court;\nFor it had slaughtered Pope and Cardinal:\nHad filled St. Peter's beauteous seat with scathe,\nAnd brought foul scandal on the HOLY FAITH."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whate'er she touches, wall or rampire steep,\nGoes to the ground' where'er the monster wends,\nEach fortress opens; neither castle-keep,\nNor city from her rage its wealth defends.\nHonours divine as well that Beast would reap,\nIt seems (while the besotted rabble bends)\nAnd claim withal, as to its keeping given,\nThe sacred keys which open Hell and Heaven."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Approaching next, is seen a cavalier,\nHis temples circled with imperial bay;\nThree youths with him in company appear,\nWith golden lilies wrought in their array:\nA lion seems against that monster drear\nTo issue, with the same device as they:\nThe name of these are on the marble read,\nSome on their skirt, some written overhead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of those who so against Beast advance,\nOne to the hilt has in his life-blood dyed\nHis faulchion, Francis styled the first of France;\nWith Austrian Maximilian at his side:\nIn one, who gores his gullet with the lance,\nThe emperor Charles the fifth is signified:\nHenry the eighth of England is he hight,\nWho in the monster's breast a dart has pight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The TENTH, in writing, on his back displayed\nThe Lion, who that Beast is seen to hold\nBy both his ears, and him so well has bayed,\nThat thither troop assistants manifold.\n'Twould seem the world all fear aside has laid;\nAnd, in amendment of their errors old,\nThitherward nobles troop, but these are few;\nAnd so that hideous Beast those hunters slew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In wonder stood long time that warlike train,\nDesirous, as the storied work they traced,\nTo know by hands of whom that Beast was slain,\nWhich had so many smiling lands defaced,\nThe names unknown to them, though figured plain\nUpon the marble which that fountain cased:\nThey one another prayed, if any guessed\nThat story, he would tell it to the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Vivian on Malagigi turned his eyes,\nWho listening stood this while, yet spake he nought.\n\"With thee,\" he cried, \"to tell the meaning lies,\nWho are they, by whose darts and lances dies\nThat shouldst by what I see in this be taught:\nThe hideous monster, that to bay is brought?\"\n— And Malagigi — \"Hitherto their glory\nNo author has consigned to living story."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The chiefs whose names are graved upon the stone,\nNot yet have moved upon this worldly stage;\nBut will within seven hundred years be known,\nTo the great honour of a future age.\nWhat time king Arthur filled the British throne,\nThis fountain Merlin made, enchanter sage;\nWho things to come upon the marble fair\nMade sculpture by a cunning artist's care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This Beast, when weights and measures first were found,\nCame out of nether hell; when on the plain,\nCommon before, men fixed the landmark's bound,\nAnd fashioned written pacts with jealous pain;\nYet walked not every where, at first, her round:\nUnvisited she left yet many a reign:\nThrough diverse places in our time she wends;\nBut the vile rabble and the crowd offends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"From the beginning even to our day,\nAye has that monster grown, and aye will grow;\nAnd till much time be past will grow alway:\nWas never mightier, nor worse cause of woe.\nThat Python, oft the theme of ancient lay,\nSo passing wonderful and fierce in show,\nCame not by half this loathsome monster nigh,\nIn all its foulness and deformity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Dread desolation shall it make; nor place\nWill unpolluted or untainted be;\nAnd you in the mysterious sculptured trace\nBut little of its foul iniquity.\nThe world, when weary of imploring grace,\nThose worthy peers (whose names you sculptured see,\nAnd which shall blazing carbuncle outshine),\nTo succour in its utmost need combine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No one shall more that cruel beast molest\nThan Francis, who the realm of France will steer,\nWho justly shall be forward in this quest,\nWhom none shall go beyond, whom few shall peer\nSince he in splendour, as in all the rest,\nWanting in worth, will many make appear\nWho whilom perfect seemed; so fade and yield\nAll lesser glories to the sun revealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In the first year of his successful reign,\nThe crown yet ill secure upon his front,\nHe threads the Alps, and makes their labour vain,\nWho would against his arms maintain the Mount.\nImpelled by generous and by just disdain,\nThe unavenged as yet is that affront,\nWhich a French army suffered from their rage,\nWho poured from beast-cote, field, and pasturage:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And thence shall into the rich Lombard plain\nDescend, with all the flower of France, and so\nShall break the Switzer, that henceforth in vain\nWould he uplift his horn against the foe.\nTo the sore scandal of the Church and Spain,\nAnd to the Florentine's much scathe and woe,\nBy him that famous castle shall be quelled,\nWhich inexpugnable whilere was held."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In quelling it his honoured faulchion, more\nThan other arms, availing shall be found;\nWhich first that cruel Beast to death will gore,\nThe foul destroyer of each country round:\nParforce will every standard fly before\nThat conquering faulchion, or be cast to ground:\nNor, stormed by it, will rampart, fosse, or wall,\nSecure the city, they surround, from fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Imbued with every generous quality,\nWhich can in great commander be combined,\n— Prudence like his who won Thrasymenae\nAnd Trebbia's field, with Caesar's daring mind,\nAnd Alexander's fortune, him I see;\nWithout which all designs are mist and wind;\nWithal, so passing liberal, I in none\nMark his example or his parragon.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So Malagigi to his comrades said,\nAnd moved in them desire some name to hear\nOf others, who had laid that monster dead,\nWhich to slay others had been used whilere.\nAmong the first Bernardo's name was read,\nMuch vaunted in the writing of the Seer:\nWho said, \"Through him as known as Bibbiena\nAs her own neighbour Florence and Siena."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"More forward in this chase shall no one show\nThan Sigismond, than Lewis, and than John;\nEach to that hideous beast a cruel foe;\nOne a Gonzaga, one of Arragon,\nAnd one a Salviati: with them go\nFrancis Gonzaga and Frederick his son:\nBrother and son-in-law, their aid afford;\nOne chief Ferrara's, one Urbino's lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of one of these the son, Sir Guidobald,\nWill not by sire, or other, distanced be:\nWith Ottobon de Flisco, Sinibald\nChases the Beast, both striving equally:\nLewis de Gazolo its neck has galled\nWith one of those keen darts, Apollo's fee,\nGiven with his bow, what time as well his glaive,\nThe god of war, to gird that warrior, gave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Two Hercules and two Hippolyti\nOf Este, a Hercules and Hippolyte\nOf the Gonzagas' and the Medici,\nHunt and fatigue the monster in his flight:\nNor Julian lets his good son pass him by;\nNor bold Ferrant his brother; nor less wight\nIs Andrew Doria; nor by any one\nIs Francis Sforza in the chase outdone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of good Avalo's glorious lineage bred,\nTwo chiefs that mountain for their bearing show,\nWhich, hiding him, from dragon-feet to head,\nThe wicked Typheus seems to keep below.\n'Mid those combined, to lay the monster dead,\nShall none more forward than this couple go:\nHim Francis of Pescara names the text;\nAlphonso, hight of Guasto, is the next."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But where leave I Gonsalvo Ferrant, who\nIs held in such esteem, the pride of Spain?\nSo praised by Malagigi, that him few\nEqual among the worthies of that train.\nWilliam, surnamed of Monferrato, view\n'Mid those that have the hideous monster slain:\nBut these are few compared with numbers round,\nWhom that despiteous Beast shall kill or wound.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To converse gay the friends themselves addrest,\nAnd seemly pastimes, when their meal was done,\nThrough the hot noontide, and fine carpets prest,\n'Mid shrubs, by which the limpid river run.\nVivian and Malagigi, that the rest\nMight be more tranquil, watched with armour on;\nWhen unaccompanied they saw a dame,\nWho quickly towards their place of shelter came;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hippalca she; from whom was torn away\nFrontino, that good horse, by Rodomont:\nHim had she long pursued the former day,\nAnd now with prayer, now followed with affront.\nWhich booting nought, she had retraced her way,\nTo seek Rogero out in Agrismont;\nAnd, how I know not, heard upon her round,\nHe here with Richardetto would be found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, for to her well known was that repair,\nUsed by her often, she herself addrest\nTowards the fount, and in that quarter fair\nFound him, and in what manner, was exprest;\nBut like embassadress, who — wise and ware —\nBetter than was enjoined performs a hest,\nWhen Richardetto she beheld, made show\nAs if she good Rogero did not know."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She turned her wholly to Sir Richardet,\nAs bound direct to him; and, on his side,\nHe who well knew her, straight uprose and met,\nAnd asked that damsel whitherward she hied.\nHippalca, with her eyes yet red and wet\nFrom her long weeping, sighing deeply, cried,\nBut cried aloud, that young Rogero, near\nThe warrior she addrest, her tale might hear:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I from Mount Alban with a courser sped;\n(So your good sister had commanded me)\nA horse much loved by her, and highly bred;\nFrontino is yclept that charger free;\nAnd him I more than thirty miles had led\nTowards Marseilles, where she designed to be\nWithin few days; by her enjoined to wend\nThither, and her arrival there attend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I in the sure belief pursued my course,\nWas none so stout of heart, if I should say\nHow Sir Rinaldo's sister owned the horse,\nHe would presume to take that steed away.\nBut vain was my design; for him parforce\nA Saracen took from me yesterday:\nNor, when to him his master's name I read,\nWill that bold robber render back the steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Him I to-day and all the day before\nHave prayed, and prayer and menace proving vain,\nAye cursing him and execrating sore,\nHave left at little distance; where, with pain,\nBoth to his courser and himself, the Moor,\nAs best he can, a combat does maintain\nAgainst a knight, who him so hard has prest,\nI trust my injury shall be redrest.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At this Rogero, leaping on his feet,\nWho scarcely had endured the whole to hear,\nTo Richardetto turned; and, as a meet\nGuerdon for his good deed, the cavalier\nDid, with beseechings infinite, entreat\nTo let him singly with that damsel steer,\nUntil she showed the paynim, who by force\nHad wrested from her hands that goodly horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Richardet (though it seems discourtesy\nTo yield to other champion that emprize,\nWhich by himself should terminated be)\nYet with Rogero's earnest suit complies;\nWho takes farewell of that good company,\nAnd with the damsel on her journey hies.\nAnd leaves those others, whom his feats confound,\nNot merely lost in wonder, but astoud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him Hippalca said, when she apart\nHad drawn him to some distance from the rest,\nShe was dispatched by her that in her heart\nBore of his worth the image so imprest;\n— And added, without using farther art,\nAll that her lady had to him addrest;\nAnd if she told another tale whilere,\nOf Richardetto she was then in fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She added how the author of that deed\nHad also said to her with mickle pride;\n\"Because I know Rogero owns the steed,\nMore willingly I take him from his guide.\nIf he would repossess the courser, read\nTo him what I have no desire to hide,\nI am that Rodomont, whose martial worth\nScatters its splendour through this ample earth.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Listening, the visage of the youthful knight\nShowed with what rage his heart was in a flame,\nAs well as that the horse was his delight;\nAs well upon account of whence it came;\nAnd also that 'twas reft in his despite;\nHe sees dishonour will ensue and blame,\nSave he from Rodomont redeems the prey,\nAnd with a due revenge that wrong repay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With him, without repose, the damsel rides,\nWho with his foe would bring him front to front;\nAnd thither journies where the road divides,\nAnd one branch cuts the plain, one climbs the mount,\nAnd either pathway to that valley guides,\nWhere she had newly left King Rodomont,\nThe mountain track was short, but trod with pain;\nThat other longer far, but smooth and plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hippalca's ardour to retrieve the prey,\nAnd upon Rodomont's avenge the wrong,\nIncites that maid the mountain to assay;\nBy which (as said the journey was less long: ) \n\nWhile Mandricardo, Rodomont, and they\nOf whom I erst made mention in my song,\nThat easier track across the level hold;\nAnd thus encounter not Rogero bold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Until King Agramant shall succoured be,\nSuspended is their quarrel (in what wise\nYou know), and in the champions' company\nDoralice, cause of all their discord, hies.\nNow hear the upshot of this history!\nTheir way directly by that fountain lies,\nBeside whose margin are in pastime met\nMarphisa and Aldigier and Richardet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa had, at her companions' prayer,\nCloathed her in female ornaments and vest,\nOf those, which by Maganza's traitour were\nLate to Lanfusa, in full trust, addrest;\nAnd, though the appearance of that maid was rare\nWithout her corslet, casque and all the rest,\n— At their entreaty, these for once laid down —\nShe deigned to seem a maid and donned the gown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as Mandricardo saw her face,\nIn trust that, could he win her in affray,\nHe would that maid, in recompense and place\nOf Doralice, to Rodomont convey;\nAs if Love trafficked in such contracts base,\nAnd lover could his lady change away,\nNor yet with reason at the event be pained,\nIf he in losing one another gained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hence with a damsel to provide the peer,\nThat he himself the other may retain;\nDeeming her worthy any cavalier,\nHe would by force of arms the maid obtain;\nAnd, as if he could suddenly hold dear\nThis maid as that, on him bestow the gain;\nAnd all of those, whom he about her spied,\nForthwith to joust and single fight defied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Vivian and Malagigi (who were dight\nIn arms, as guard and surety for the rest,)\nOne and the other champion — prompt for fight,\nRose lightly from the herbage which they prest,\nDeeming they had to joust with either knight;\nBut Rodomont, who came not on this quest,\nNo motion made as he a course would run;\nSo that they had to tourney but with one."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Vivian is the first who moves his horse,\nWith mighty heart, and lays his weapon low;\nAnd he, that Tartar king, renowned for force,\nWith greater puissance meets the coming foe.\nHis lance each warrior levels in the course\nWhere he bests trusts to plant the furious blow.\nVainly Sir Vivian's spear the casque offends;\nNor throws that paynim knight, nor even bends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That Tartar's harder weapon makes the shield\nOf Vivian, at their onset, fly like grass;\nAnd, tumbling from his saddle on the field,\nExtends the champion amid flowers and grass.\nTo run his chance Sir Malagigi, steeled,\nDid to his brother's succour quickly pass;\nBut (such that warrior's hurry to be near)\nRather accompanied, than venged the peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The other of those brethren armed before\nHis cousin, and had backed his courser wight;\nAnd, having first defied, encountered sore,\nSpurring with flowing rein, the stranger knight.\nAgainst the tempered helm that pagan wore\nSounded the blow, an inch below the sight:\nHeaven-high the truncheon flew, in fragments broke,\nBut the stout pagan winced not for the stroke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him on the left side smote that paynim peer,\nAnd (for the blow was with huge force designed)\nLittle his shield, and less his iron gear,\nAvailed, which opened like the yielding rhind:\nThe weapon pierced his shoulder; Aldigier\nNow right now left upon his horse inclined;\nThen him, 'mid grass and flowers, his comrades view,\nWith arms of crimson, face of pallid, hue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next Richardetto comes, and for the blow\nIntended, levels such a mighty lance,\nHe showed himself, as he was wont to show,\nWorthy to be a paladin of France;\nAnd has stamped signs of this upon the foe.\nIf he had warred on him with equal chance;\nBut prostrate rolled, encumbered by his steed;\nNor fell the courser through his lord's misdeed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When knight appeared not on the other side,\nWho should in joust the paynim king affront,\nHe thought the damsel was his prize, and hied\nThither, where she was seated by the fount.\nAnd — \"Lady, you are mine,\" the Tartar cried,\n\"Save other champion in your succour mount;\nNor can you make denial or excuse,\nSince such the right of war and common use.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa raised her face with haughty cheer,\nAnd answered him:  \"Thy judgment wanders far;\nI will concede thy sentence would be clear,\nConcluding I am thine by right of war,\nIf either were my lord or cavalier\nOf those, by thee unhorsed in bloody jar:\nNor theirs am I, nor other's, but my own,\nWho wins me, wins me from myself alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I too with lance and sword do doughty deed,\nAnd more than one good knight on earth have laid.\n— Give me,\" she cried, \"my armour and my steed.\"\nAnd readily her squires that hest obeyed:\nThen in her waistcoat stood, of flowing weed\nDespoiled, with well-knit from and charms displayed;\nAnd in all points (such strength she shewed and grace)\nResembled heavenly Mars, except her face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The damsel donned her sword, when armed all o'er,\nAnd on her courser leapt with nimble spring;\nAnd, right and left, she made him, thrice or more\nPoised on his haunches, turn in narrow ring.\nAnd, levelling the sturdy lance she bore,\nDefied, and next assailed, the Tartar king.\nSo combating with Peleus' son, of yore,\nPenthesilaea warred on Trojan shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Like brittle crystal, in that proud career,\nThe weapons at the rest to pieces went;\nYet neither of those warriors, 'twould appear,\nBackwards one inch at their encounter bent.\nMarphisa, who would willingly be clear\nWhat of a closer fight would be the event,\nFor a new combat with the paynim lord,\nWheeled, to attack that warrior with the sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That Tartar cursed the elements and sky,\nWhen her he saw remaining in her sell;\nAnd she, who thought to make his buckler fly,\nCursed heaven as loudly as that infidel.\nAlready were their faulchions raised on high,\nWhich on the enchanted arms like hammers fell:\nEnchanted arms both combatants enclose,\nNever more needed by those deadly foes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So perfect are the champions' plate and chain,\nThey thrust or cut of spear or faulchion stay;\nSo that the two the battle might maintain,\nThroughout this and throughout another day:\nBut Rodomont leaps in between the twain,\nAnd taxes Mandricardo with delay;\nCrying, \"If battle here is to be done,\nFinish we that which we to-day begun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"We made a truce, thou knowest, upon pact\nOf furnishing our baffled forces aid;\nNor foe in joust or fight can be attacked\nBy us with justice till this debt be paid.\"\nThen to Marphisa he in reverent act\nAddressed himself, and of that courier said;\nAnd next recounted to the martial dame,\nHow seeking aid for Agramant he came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next prays not only with that Tartar knight\nShe will abandon or defer the fray;\nBut that, Troyano's valiant son to right,\nShe will, together with them, wend her way;\nBy which her warlike fame a higher flight,\nMore easily may, even to heaven, assay,\nThan in a quarrel of such paltry guise,\nWhich offers hindrance to such fair emprize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa, who had evermore in thought\nTo prove the paladins of Charles, and who\nTo France was over land and ocean brought,\nFrom clime so distant, with no other view,\nThan by her own experience to be taught\nIf their far-spread renown were false or true,\nResolved together with the troop to speed,\nAs soon as she had heard their monarch's need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile Rogero, with that guiding may,\nHad vainly by the rugged pathway sped;\nWho that king Rodomont another way\nHad taken, when he reached the mountain, read;\nAnd thinking, that he was not far away,\nAnd the road straight towards that fountain led,\nTrotting in haste behind the Sarzan hied,\nWhere he new prints upon the path espied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hippalca he to Mont Albano prayed,\nTo wend, which distant one day's journey lies;\nBecause to seek anew that fountain-glade,\nWould be to wander in too wide a guise.\nAnd that she need not doubt withal, he said,\nBut that he would retrieve the ravished prize.\nAnd, were she in Mount Alban — or where'er —\nVowed she the tidings speedily should hear,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And gave the letter to that maid to bear,\nWhich, writ by him, he in his bosom wore,\nAnd added many matters, with the prayer,\nShe would excuse him by her friendly lore.\nHippalca in her memory fixt, with care,\nThe whole; took leave, and turned her horse once more:\nNor ceased that faithful messenger to ride\nTill she Mount Alban reached at evening-tide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero followed fast the paynim knight,\nTracked o'er the level by those footsteps new,\nBut overtook him not, till he got sight,\nBeside the fount, of Mandricardo too.\nAlready either had his promise plight,\nHe nought unknown to his compeer would do,\nTill they had succour to that host conveyed,\nOn which King Charles his yoke had nearly laid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Arrived, Rogero knew Frontino gay,\nAnd, through that courser, knew the knight astride;\nAnd on his lance with bending shoulder lay,\nAnd in fierce tone the African defied.\nJob was outdone by Rodomont that day,\nIn that the king subdued his haughty pride,\nAnd the fell fight which he had ever used\nTo seek with every instance, he refused."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The first day this and last, that e'er in fight\nKing Rodomont refused his part to bear!\nBut his desire appeared to him so right,\nIn succour of his sovereign to repair;\nThat if he had believed he clutched the knight\nFaster than nimble leopard gripes the hare,\nHe not so far his purpose would forego,\nAs on his prey to waste a passing blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Add, that he knows Rogero is the peer\nWho him for good Frontino now assails;\n— So famous, that no other cavalier\nLike him such eminence of glory scales;\n— The man, of whom he gladly would be clear,\nBy proof, how much in battle he avails:\nYet shuns the combat, proffered on his part;\nSo much his monarch's siege has he at heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Three hundred miles, a thousand, would he ride,\n— Were it not so — to purchase such affray;\nBut he, if him Achilles had defied,\nHad done no otherwise than as I say;\nSo deeply did the covering ashes hide\nThat fire beneath, whose fury stifled lay:\nHe told why he refused the strife; and prayed,\nAs well Rogero the design to aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Adding that he, in doing so, would do\nWhat to his lord a faithful vassal owes;\nStill, when the siege was raised, might they renew\nAnd terminate their deadly strife by blows.\nTo him Rogero cried, \"The fight with you\nI freely will defer, till from his foes\nKing Agramant be rescued by the sword;\nProvided first Frontino be restored."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Would you that I delay to prove by deed,\nThat you have acted in unworthy sort,\n— Nor did, like valiant man, to take my steed\nThus from a woman — till we meet at court,\nRender me my Frontino back, or read,\nUpon no other ground, will I support\nThat battle shall not be between us two;\nNor will accord an hour of truce to you.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While of that African he so demands\nFrontino, or him threats with instant fray;\nAnd either still the other's claim withstands,\nNor this the steed will grant, nor that delay;\nKing Mandricardo stirs, on the other hand,\nAnother strife; who sees that ensign gay\nRogero on his shield was wont to wear,\nThe bird which reigns o'er other fowls of air."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He bore on azure field that eagle white,\nThe beauteous ensign of the Trojan throng:\nSuch glorious bearing showed that youthful knight,\nBecause he drew his line from Hector strong.\nBut Mandricardo knew not of this right,\nNor would endure — and deemed a crying wrong,\nThat any other but himself should wield\nFamed Hector's argent eagle on his shield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Mandricardo is like blazon wore\nThe bird of Ide, which bore off Ganymede:\nHow in the castle perilous of yore,\nHe gained that noble ensign for his meed,\n— That enterprize I ween, with matter more,\nYou bear in mind, and how, for his good deed,\nThe fairy gave it him with all the gear,\nErst given by Vulcan to the Trojan peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Tartar and Rogero had before\nEngaged in battle, only on this quest,\nDivided by what accident, my lore\nRecites not, as already manifest:\nNor had till now those knights encountered more:\nWhen Mandricardo sees that bird imprest\nOn the Child's shield, he shouts with threatening cry\nTo young Rogero: \"Take my proud defy!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Audacious man, mine ensign do'st thou wear,\nNor this to-day for the first time, is said;\nAnd think'st thou, madman, I will thee forbear,\nBecause for once to spare thee I was led?\nBut since nor menace nor yet counsel are\nOf force to drive this folly from thy head,\nIt shall appear how much it had been best\nFor thee forthwith to have obeyed my hest.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As fire, whereon dry, heated wood is strown,\nRoused by a little puff, at once ascends,\nSo burns Rogero's wrath, to fury blown,\nBy the first word with which that king offends.\n\"Thou thinkest,\" he exclaims, \"to bear me down,\nBecause his knight as well with me contends:\nBut learn that I can win in fighting field\nFrom him the horse, from thee good Hector's shield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet once before — nor is it long ago —\nTwixt us in battle was this question tried:\nBut I that day restrained the murderous blow,\nBecause thou hadst no faulchion at thy side.\nThese shall be deeds, that strife was but a show;\nAnd ill this argent bird shall thee betide;\nThis is the ancient bearing of my line;\nTis thou usurpest what by right is mine.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"Say rather, thou usurpest mine from me\";\nCried Mandricardo; and that faulchion drew,\nWhich lately, underneath the greenwood tree,\nOrlando from his hand in fury threw.\nThe Child, who could not aught but courteous be,\n(Such was his gentle nature at the view ) \n\nOf Mandricardo, with his faulchion drawn,\nLet fall his ready lance upon the lawn;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And at the same time, strained his goodly sword;\nAnd better braced the covering shield he wore:\nBut 'twixt those combatants leapt Argier's lord,\nAnd quick Marphisa spurred the pair before;\nAnd one this foe, the other that implored,\nAnd both besought, that they would strive no more.\nKing Rodomont complains the Tartar knight\nHas violated twice the compact plight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "First, in belief he should Marphisa gain,\nHe more than once had jousted for that fair;\nNow to bear off Rogero's ensign fain,\nHe for king Agramant shows little care.\n— \"If thus\" (said Rodomont \"you faith maintain, ) \n\nTo finish our own combat better were,\nA cause of strife more fitting and more due\nThan either of the pleas maintained by you."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"On this condition was the treaty plight,\nAnd the accord between us now in force;\nWhen I with thee shall have performed the fight,\nI next shall answer him about the horse:\nYou then with him, if you survive, your right\nShall to the shield maintain in warlike course.\nBut I such work shall give you, I conceive,\nAs will small labour for Rogero leave.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"The bargain which thou hopest thou shalt not have,\"\n(King Mandricardo answered Rodomont)\n\"I will accord thee more than thou do'st crave,\nAnd trust to make thee sweat from feet to front.\nAnd to bestow on others, much shall save,\nAs water never fails in plenteous font;\nAnd for Rogero and a thousand more,\nAnd all the world beside reserve a store.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Their fury waxed, and angrier words ensued,\nNow upon this and now upon that side.\nWith Rodomont and with the Child at feud,\nFierce Mandricardo both at once defied.\nRogero, not endowed with suffering mood,\nWould hear no more of peace, but vengeance cried.\nNow here Marphisa hurried, and now there,\nBut could not singly such an ill repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As peasant, when a river saps its mounds,\nAnd seeking vent the oozing waters drop,\nHastening to shut the stream within its bounds,\nAnd save his pastures and expected crop,\nDams right and left; yet him the stream confounds:\nFor, if he here the sinking ruin prop,\nThere he beholds the rotten dyke give out,\nAnd from thick seams the restless water spout,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So, while the Tartar and Rogero rage,\nAnd Rodomont, in hurly-burly fray,\nFor each of these would fiercest battle wage,\nAnd would outgo his fears in that assay,\nMarphisa seeks their fury to assuage,\nAnd strives, and time and trouble throws away;\nFor as she makes one knight from strife retire,\nShe sees the others re-engage with ire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa, to appease the warriors bent,\nExclaimed, \"Sirs, listen to my better lore;\nA good remembrance 'tis, all argument\nTo leave until we Agramant restore.\nIf each is on his own design intent,\nWith Mandricardo will I strive once more;\nAnd fain would see, according to his word,\nIf he can conquer me with spear and sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if, to aid our sovereign, duty call,\nHim let us aid, nor civil discord breed.\"\n— \"To ground, through me, such project shall not fall,\"\nRogero said, \"so he restore my steed.\nLet him resign that horse, or — once for all.\nI say again — to his defence take heed.\nI either here my parting breath will yield,\nOr on my courser will return afield.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"Twere not so easy to obtain this quest\nAs 'twere that other,\" Rodomont replied;\nAnd thus pursued: \"I unto thee protest,\nIf any evil shall our king betide,\nThine is the fault not mine; for I am prest\nTo do whate'er is fitting, on my side.\"\nSmall heed to that protest Rogero paid,\nAnd stung by fury, griped his trenchant blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On Argier's king he sprang, like savage boar,\nEncountering him with shoulder and with shield;\nAnd him disordered and distrest so sore,\nThat with one stirrup's loss, the monarch reeled.\n— \"Rogero,\" Mandricardo cried, \"give o'er,\nOr else with me divide the battle-field\";\nAnd struck, this said, with worse than felon spite,\nUpon the morion of that youthful knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even to his courser's neck Rogero bends;\nNor, when he would, himself can rear;\nBecause the sword of Ulien's son descends\nAs well upon the youthful cavalier;\nAnd, but that adamant his face defends,\nAcross the cheeks his tempered helm would sheer.\nThe Child, in anguish, opens either hand;\nAnd this the bridle drops and that the brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him o'er the field his courser bears away;\nOn earth the faulchion lies, which he let go:\nMarphisa (with Rogero's through that day,\nComrade in arms appeared like fire to glow, ) \n\nEnraged, that two one knight should overlay;\nAnd, as magnanimous and stout, for foe\nSingled King Mandricardo out, and sped,\nWith all her might, stroke upon his head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont o'er the plain pursues his man.\n— Another stroke, and he has lost the horse!\nBut Richardetto drives, and Vivian,\nBetween the Child and paynim in that course.\nThis warrior at the king of Argier ran,\nAnd from Rogero severed him by force;\nThat (it was Vivian in Rogero's hand, ) \n\nNow from the blow recovered, placed his brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as to himself the Child returns,\nAnd is by Vivian armed with sword again,\nTo venge the injury that stripling burns,\nAnd runs at Rodomont with flowing rein,\nLike lion, whom a bull upon his horns\nHas lifted, though he feels this while no pain,\nSo him his heat of blood, disdain, and ire,\nTo venge that cruel outrage goad and fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero storms upon the paynim's crest;\nAnd, could that knight recover his own brand,\nWhich by foul felony (as erst exprest)\nWas ravished from the youthful warrior's hand,\nI well believe that the descending pest\nRodomont's iron casque will ill withstand;\nThat casque which Babel's king bade forge, who sought\nTo war on Heaven in his presumptuous thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Discord, believing nothing could ensue\nBut stir, and strife, and combat on that head;\nAnd that there was no place, amid the crew,\nFor truce or treaty, to her sister said,\nThat she, her well-beloved monks to view,\nMight now again with her securely tread.\nLet them depart; and mark we where in front\nRogero has sore wounded Rodomont."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero's blow was levelled with such spite,\nThat this upon Frontino's crupper made\nThe helmet and the shell of iron smite,\nIn which that Saracen his limbs arrayed;\nAnd he, three times or four, to left and right,\n— As if about to fall — head-foremost, swayed;\nAnd would have lost withal his trusty brand,\nBut that the hilt was fastened to his hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa has king Mandricardo prest\nMeanwhile, and makes him sweat breast, front, and face;\nAnd he Marphisa has as sore distrest:\nBut such good plates each valiant bosom case,\nImpassable is either iron vest;\nAnd both have hitherto maintained their place.\nBut, at a turn her martial courser made,\nMarphisa needed young Rogero's aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa's martial steed, in turning short,\nWhere a firm footing that soft mead denied,\nOn the moist surface slipt, and in such sort,\nThat he fell, helpless, on his better side;\nAnd, as he rose in haste and lacked support,\nAthwart by furious Brigliador was plied;\nOn which the paynim, little courteous, came;\nSo that he fell anew beneath the dame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, when Marphisa on the ground\nHe saw unhorsed, deferred no more his aid;\nWho for that deed had leisure; since, astound,\nRodomont far away had been conveyed:\nHe smote the morion which that Tartar crowned;\nAnd, cleft like stalk, his head on earth had laid,\nHad he his trusty Balisarda born,\nOr Mandricardo other helmet worn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont, of his senses repossest,\nTurned round this while, and Richardetto spied;\nAnd recollecting how, when late distrest,\nHe to Rogero succour had supplied,\nQuickly against that youthful warrior prest;\nWho an ill guerdon would from him abide,\nDid Malagigi not his malice thwart\nWith other magic and with mickle art."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sage Malagigi versed in every sleight\nWhich by the wisest wizard can be done;\nAlthough his book he has not, by whose might,\nHe in his course can stop the passing sun;\nThe conjuration recollects and rite,\nBy which he tames the rebel fiends; and one\nBids enter into Doralice's steed,\nWhom he to fury stings and headlong speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Into that gentle palfrey's form, who bore\nThe beauteous daughter of King Stordilane,\nSir Vivian's brother, simply by his lore,\nMade pass an angel of the dark domain;\nAnd the good horse, who never moved before,\nExcept in due obedience to the rein,\nNow took a leap, possest by that ill sprite,\nThirty feet long and sixteen feet in height."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It was a mighty leap, yet not so wide\nAs to make any rider void the sell.\nSeeing herself so high in air, loud cried,\n(Yielding herself for dead that bonnibel. ) \n\nHer palfrey, with the Daemon for his guide,\nAfter his leap, runs, goaded by the spell\n(The maid still screaming such a furious course, ) \n\nAn arrow had not reached the flying horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the first hearing of that voice, the son\nOf Ulien, on his part, the strife suspended;\nAnd thither, where the furious palfrey run,\nSwiftly in succour of the lady wended.\nNo less was by the Tartar monarch done;\nWho neither Child nor damsel more offended;\nBut without craving time, or truce, or peace,\nPursued King Rodomont and Doralice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa rose meanwhile, to fury stirred;\nAnd, with disdain all over in a glow,\nThought to accomplish her revenge, and erred:\nFor at too great a distance was the foe.\nRogero, who beheld the war deferred,\nRather like lion roared than sighed: well know\nThose two their coursers they should vainly gore,\nFollowing Frontino and good Brigliador."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero will not halt till he renew\nAnd end the unfinished combat for the horse;\nMarphisa will not quit that Tartar, who\nWill to her satisfaction prove his force.\nTo leave their quarrel in such guise the two\nEsteem foul scandal; as their better course,\nIn chase of those offending knights to fare,\nIs the conclusion of that valiant pair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They in the paynim camp will find each foe,\nIf them before they find not on their way;\nWhom thither bound, to raise the siege they know,\nEre Charlemagne bring all beneath his sway.\nSo thitherward the twain directly go\nWhere these, they deem, will be their certain prey.\nYet not so rudely thence Rogero broke,\nBut that he first with his companion spoke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither returns Rogero, where apart\nIs he, the brother of his lady fair;\nAnd vows himself his friend, with generous heart,\nIn good or evil fortune, everywhere.\nHim he implores — and frames his speech with art —\nHe his salutes will to his sister bear;\nAnd this so well, he moves by that request\nNo doubt in him, nor any of the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of Malagigi he and Viviane\nNext takes farewell and wounded Aldigier;\nTheir services no less that kindly twain\nProffer, as ever debtors to the peer.\nMarphisa to seek Paris is so fain,\nThat parting she forgets her friends to cheer;\nBut Malagigi and Vivian, in pursuit,\nFollow, and from afar that maid salute;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And so Sir Richardet as well: but low\nOn earth lies Aldigier, and there must rest.\nThe two first champions towards Paris go,\nAnd the two others next pursue that quest.\nIn other canto, Sir, I hope to show\nOf wondrous and of superhuman gest,\nWrought to the damage of the Christian king,\nBy those two couples of whose worth I sing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 27"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By good Rogero and those paynims three\nDefeated, Charlemagne to Paris flies.\nAlready all, throughout their chivalry,\nAre mad with spite and hatred; jars arise,\nAnd strife; and means to still their enmity\nTheir sovereign is unable to devise.\nFrom him departs the monarch of Argier,\nWho is rejected of his lady dear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A woman for the most part reasons best\nUpon a sudden motion, and untaught;\nFor with that special grace the sex is blest,\n'Mid those so many gifts, wherewith 'tis fraught;\nBut man, of a less nimble wit possest,\nIs ill at counsel, save, with sober thought,\nHe ruminates thereon, content to spend\nCare, time and trouble to mature his end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That seemed good counsel, but was ill indeed\nOf Malagigi's, as before was said;\nAlbeit he so rescued in his need\nHis cousin Richardet, with odds o'erlaid,\nWhen from the paynim monarchs him he freed\nBy ready demon, who his hest obeyed;\nFor sure he never deemed they should be borne,\nWhere they would work the Christian army scorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Had he some little prize for counsel stayed,\n(We with the same success may well suppose)\nHe to his cousin might have furnished aid,\nYet brought not on the Christian host their foes:\nThat evil sprite he might as well have made,\nHim, who embodied in the palfrey goes,\nEastward or west, so far that lady bear,\nThat France should hear no further of the pair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So the two lovers, following her who flies,\nTo other place than Paris might be brought:\nBut this calamity was a surprise\nOn Malagigi, through his little thought;\nAnd fiendish malice, banished from the skies,\nWhich ever blood and fire and ravage sought,\nGuided them by that way to Charles' disaster;\nLeft to his choice by him, the wizard master."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The wayward fiend who makes that palfrey ramp\nBears off the frighted Doralice amain;\nNor river nor yet yawning ditch, or swamp,\nWood, rock, or rugged cliff, the steed restrain;\nTill, traversing the French and English camp,\nAnd other squadrons of the mingled train,\nBeneath the holy flag of Christ arraid,\nHe to Granada's king the fair conveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Sarzan and the Tartar the first day\nThat royal damsel a long while pursue;\nBecause her distant form they yet survey;\nBut finally they lose that lady's view;\nWhen, like a lyme-dog, whom the hunters lay\nOn hare or roebuck's trail, the valiant two\nFollow upon her track, nor halt, till told\nThat she is harboured in her father's hold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guard thyself, Charles: for, lo! against thee blown\nIs such a storm, that I no refuge see:\nNor these redoubted monarchs come alone,\nBut those of Sericane and Circassy;\nWhile Fortune, who would probe thee to the bone,\nHas taken those two shining stars from thee,\nWho kept thee by their wisdom and their light;\nAnd thou remainest blind and wrapt in night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis of the valiant cousins I would speak:\nOf these, Orlando of his wit bereft,\nNaked, in sun or shower, by plain or peak,\nWanders about the world, a helpless weft;\nAnd he, in wisdom little less to seek,\nRinaldo, in thy peril thee has left;\nAnd, for in Paris-town she is not found,\nIn search of his Angelica is bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A cunning, old enchanter him deceived,\nAs in the outlet of my tale was said:\nDeluded by a phantom, he believed\nAngelica was with Orlando fled;\nAnd hence with jealousy, at heart, aggrieved\n(Lover ne'er suffered worse to Paris sped; ) \n\nWhence he, as soon as he appeared at court,\nBy chance, was named to Britain to resort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now, the field won, wherein with mickle fame\nHe drove King Agramant his works behind,\nTo Paris yet again the warrior came,\nSearched convent, tower, and house, and, save confined\n'Twixt solid walls or columns be the dame,\nHer will the restless lover surely find:\nNor her nor yet Orlando he descries,\nSo forth in the desire to seek them hies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her to Anglantes or to Brava brought,\nHe deemed the Count enjoyed in mirth and play;\nAnd vainly, here and there, that damsel sought,\nNor here nor there, descried the long-sought prey.\nTo Paris he repaired again, in thought\nThe paladin returning to waylay;\nBecause he deemed he could not rove at large\nWithout that Town, but on some special charge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within he takes a day or two's repose;\nAnd, when he finds Orlando comes not there,\nAgain to Brava and Anglantes goes\nInquiring tidings of the royal fair;\nNor, whether morning dawns or noontide glows,\n— Nor night nor day — his weary steed does spare;\nNor once — but twice a hundred times — has run\nThe selfsame course, by light of moon or sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But the ancient foe, deluded by whose say,\nTo the forbidden fruit Eve raised her hand,\nTurned his wan eyes on Charlemagne one day,\nWhen he the good Rinaldo absent scanned;\nAnd seeing what foul rout and disarray\nMight at that time be given to Charles's band,\nOf all the Saracens the choice and flower\nMarshalled in arms against the Christian power."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Sacripant and King Gradasso (who\nWhilere companionship in war had made,\nWhen from Atlantes' palace fled the two)\nTogether to unite their arms, in aid\nOf royal Agramant's beleaguered crew,\nAnd where through unknown lands the warriors hied,\nMade smooth the way, and served them as a guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither another fiend that ruthless foe\nBade Rodomont and Mandricardo bear\nThrough ways, by which his comrade was not slow\nWith the affrighted Doralice to fare:\nA third, lest they their enterprize forego,\nRogero and Marphisa has in care:\nBut their conductor journeys not so fast;\nAnd hence that martial pair arrives the last."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Later by half an hour, against their foes,\nSo matched, Rogero and Marphisa speed;\nBecause the sable angel, who his blows\nAimed at the bands that held the Christian creed,\nProvided, that the contest which arose\nAbout that horse, his work should not impede;\nWhich had again been kindled, had the twain,\nRodomont and Rogero, met again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The first four ride until themselves they find\nWhere the besiegers and besieged they view;\nAnd see the banners shaking in the wind,\nAnd the cantonments of those armies two.\nHere they short counsel took, and next opined,\nIn spite of Charlemagne's beleaguering crew,\nTo carry speedy succour to their liege,\nAnd rescue royal Agramant from siege."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where thickest camped lay Charles's host, they spurred,\nClosing their files against the Christian foe.\n\"Afric and Spain!\" is the assailants' word,\nWhom at all points the Franks for paynims know.\n— \"To arms, to arms!\" throughout their camp is heard:\nBut first is felt the Moorish sabre's blow:\nEven on the rear-guard falls the vengeful stroke,\nNot charged alone, but routed, beat and broke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Christian host throughout is overthrown,\nAnd how they know not, in tumultuous wise;\nAnd that it is a wonted insult done\nBy Switzer or by Gascon, some surmise;\nBut — since the reason is to most unknown —\nEach several nation to its standard flies,\nThis to the drum, that to the trumpet's sound,\nAnd shriek and shout from earth to heaven redound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All armed is Charlemagne, except his head,\nAnd, girt with paladins, his faithful stay,\nArrived demanding what alarm has bred\nDisorder in his host and disarray;\nAnd stopt with menace this or that who fled,\nAnd many fugitives, upon their way,\nSome with maimed face, breast, arm, or hand, espied,\nAnd some with head or throat with life-blood dyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Advancing, he on earth saw many more,\nOr rather in a lake of crimson laid,\nHorribly weltering in their own dark gore,\nBeyond the leech's and magician's aid;\nAnd busts dissevered from the heads they bore,\nAnd legs and arms — a cruel show — surveyed;\nAnd, from the first cantonments to the last,\nSaw slaughtered men on all sides as he past."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where the small band advances in such wise,\nDeserving well eternal praise to gain,\nVouching their deeds, a long-drawn furrow lies,\nA signal record of their might and main.\nHis army's cruel slaughter, with surprise,\nAnger and rage, is viewed by Charlemagne.\nSo he whose shattered walls have felt its force,\nThroughout his mansion tracks the lightning's course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not to the ramparts of the paynim crew\nOf Agramant as yet had pierced this aid,\nWhen, on the further side, these other two,\nRogero and Marphisa, thither made.\nWhen, once or twice, that worthy pair a view\nHave taken of the ground, and have surveyed\nThe readiest way assistance to afford,\nThey swiftly move in succour of their lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As when we spark to loaded mine apply,\nThrough the long furrow, filled with sable grain,\nSo fast the furious wildfire darts, that eye\nPursues the progress of the flash with pain;\nAnd as dire ruin follows, and from high,\nThe loosened rock and solid bastion rain,\nSo bold Rogero and Marphisa rush\nTo battle, so the Christian squadrons crush."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Front and askance, the assailants smote, and low\nOn earth heads, arms, and severed shoulders lay,\nWhere'er the Christian squadrons were too slow\nTo free the path and break their close array.\nWhoe'er has seen the passing tempest blow,\nAnd of the hill or valley, in its way,\nOne portion ravage and another leave,\nMay so their course amid that host conceive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Many who had escaped by quick retreat,\nRodomont and those other furious three,\nThank God that he had given them legs and feet,\nWherewith to fly from that calamity;\nAnd from the Child and damsel new defeat\nEncounter, while with endlong course they flee:\nAs man, no matter if he stands or run,\nSeeks vainly his predestined doom to shun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who 'scape one peril, into other fly,\nAnd pay the penalty of flesh and blood;\nSo, by the teeth of dog, is wont to die\nThe fox, together with her infant brood,\nBy one who dwells her ancient cavern nigh\nUnearthed, and with a thousand blows pursued;\nWhen from some unsuspected place, that foe\nHas filled with fire and smoke the den below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa and the Child, of danger clear,\nEnter the paynim ramparts; and, with eyes\nUpturned, the Saracens, with humble cheer,\nThank Heaven for the success of that emprize:\nThe paladins no longer are their fear;\nThe meanest Moor a hundred Franks defies;\nAnd 'tis resolved, without repose, again\nTo drench with Christian blood the thirsty plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At once a formidable larum rose;\nHorns, drums, and shrilling clarions filled the skies;\nAnd the wind ruffles, as it comes and goes,\nBanner and gonfalon of various dyes.\nThe Germans and the warlike Bretons close;\nRanged on the other part, in martial wise,\nItalians, English, French, were seen, and through\nThose armies furious war blazed forth anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The force of the redoubted Rodomont,\nAnd that of Agrican's infuriate son,\nThat of Rogero, valiant's copious font,\nGradasso's, so renowned for trophies won,\nThe martial maid, Marphisa's fearless front,\nAnd might of Sacripant, excelled by none,\nMade Charles upon Saint John and Denys call,\nAnd fly for shelter to his Paris wall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of fierce Marphisa and her bold allies\nThe unconquered daring and the wondrous might,\nSir, was not of a nature — of a guise —\nTo be conceived, much less described aright:\nThe number slaughtered hence may you surmise!\nWhat cruel blow King Charles sustained in fight!\nAdd to these warriors of illustrious name,\nMore than one Moor, with Ferrau, known to Fame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Many through reckless haste were drowned in Seine,\nFor all too narrow was the bridge's floor,\nAn wished, like Icarus, for wings in vain,\nHaving grim death behind them and before,\nSave Oliver, and Ogier hight the Dane,\nThe paladins are prisoners to the Moor:\nWounded beneath his better shoulder fled\nThe first, that other with a broken head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And. like Orlando and Duke Aymon's son,\nHad faithful Brandimart thrown up the game,\nCharles had from Paris into exile gone,\nIf he had scaped alive so fierce a flame.\nBrandimart does his best, and when 'tis done,\nYields to the storm: Thus Fortune, fickle dame,\nNow smiles upon the paynim monarch, who\nBesieges royal Charlemagne anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From earth beneath the widow's outcry swells,\nMingled with elder's and with orphan's prayer,\nInto the pure serene, where Michael dwells,\nRising above this dim and troubled air;\nAnd to the blest archangel loudly tells,\nHow the devouring wolf and raven tear\nHis faithful English, French, and German train,\nWhose slaughtered bodies overspread the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Red blushed the blessed angel, who believed\nHe ill obedience to his lord had paid;\nAnd, in his anger, deemed himself deceived\nBy the perfidious Discord and betrayed:\nHe his Creator's order had received\nTo stir the Moors to strife, nor had obeyed;\nHad rather in their eyes who marked the event,\nAppeared throughout to thwart his high intent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As servant faithful to his lord, and more\nIn love than memory strong, who finds that he\nHas that forgotten which at his heart-core,\nAs precious as his life and soul should be,\nHastes to repair his error, nor before\nHe mend that fault, again his lord will see,\nSo not to God St. Michael will ascend\nUntil he has achieved his holy end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Again he to that monastery flew,\nWhere whilom he had Discord seen; and there\nSeated in chapter sees her, while anew\nTheir yearly officers elected are,\nShe taking huge delight those friers to view,\nThat at each other hurled their books of prayer.\nHis hand within her locks the archangel twists,\nAnd deals her endless scathe with feet and fists."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On her he next a cross's handle broke;\nWherewith her back, and arms, and head he plies:\nHis mercy with loud voice the wretch bespoke,\nAnd hugged that angel's knees with suppliant cries.\nMichael suspends not the avenging stroke\nTill hunted to the Moorish camp she flies,\nThen thus: \"Believe worse vengeance yet in store,\nIf I beyond these lines behold thee more.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Albeit in back and arms all over shent\nWas Discord by that angel, in her fear\nOf suffering yet again such chastisement,\nSuch horrid fury and such blows severe,\nShe speedily to take her bellows went,\nAnd, adding food to what she lit whilere,\nAnd setting other ready piles afire,\nKindled in many hearts a blaze of ire;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And good Rogero (she inflames them so)\nWith Rodomont and Mandricardo fares\nTo Agramant; and all (since now the foe\nThe paynims pressed no more, the vantage theirs)\nTo him the seed of their dissensions show,\nAnd what the bitter produce which it bears:\nThen to the judgment of the king refer\nWho first in listed field his claim should stir."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As well Marphisa to Troyano's son,\nRelates her case, and will conclude the fray\nWhich with the Tartar king she had begun,\nBecause by him provoked to that assay;\nNor will she yield her place to any one,\nNo, not a single hour, yet less a day;\nBut with loud instances maintains her right\nWith Mandricardo first to wage the fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To have the first possession of the field\nNo less renowned king Rodomont contended,\nWhich he, the African array to shield,\nHad interrupted and till now suspended.\nRogero to King Agramant appealed,\nAs having borne too long, though sore offended,\nThat Rodomont form him detained his horse,\nNor yet would meet him first in martial course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Tartar king, for more perplexity,\nDenied on any ground Rogero's right\nThe bearer of the white-winged bird to be;\nAnd was so passing wood with wrath and spite,\nThat, if to this those others would agree,\nHe would at once those several quarrels fight;\nAnd so those others would as well have done,\nIf Agramant's consent they could have won."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Agramant, with prayer and kingly word,\nHad willingly appeased that jarring crew;\nBut since the foes were deaf to all accord,\nNor would assent to peace or truce anew,\nConsidered how at least he might afford\nThe field of each of them in order due;\nAnd, as the best resolve, at last decreed,\nEach should by lot possess the listed mead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Four lots the monarch bade prepare, which done,\nThis \"Rodomont and Mandricardo\" said;\n\"Rogero and Mandricardo\" were in one;\nIn one, \"Rogero and Rodomont\" were read;\nThat \"Mandricardo and Marphisa\" run:\nNext, as the fickle goddess, Fortune, led,\nThe lots are drawn, and in the first appear\nThe Tartar king and sovereign of Argier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero and Mandricardo for that play\nWere next; Rogero and Rodomont were third;\nMarphisa's lot and Mardricardo's lay\nAt bottom; whence the dame was deeply stirred;\nNor young Rogero seems a whit more gay:\nWho knows the prowess of those two preferred\nWill nothing in the listed combat leave\nFor him or for Marphisa to achieve."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There lies a place, of Paris little wide,\nCovering a mile or somewhat less, and round;\nLike ancient theatre, on every side,\nEncompast by a tall and solid mound;\nWith castle whilom was it fortified,\nWhich sword and fire had levelled with the ground.\nThe Parmesan like circle does survey,\nWhenever he to Borgo wends his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In this place is prepared the listed mead,\nWhich palisades of little height inclose;\nA square, of just proportions for that need,\nWith two capacious gates, as usage goes.\nThe day on which to combat have agreed\nThose valiant knights, who will not balk their foes,\nBeside the palisades, to left and right,\nFacing each entrance, are pavilions pight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In that, which looks towards the western sun,\nIs lodged the giant monarch of Argier;\nAnd him assist his serpent-hide to don\nBold Ferrau and Circassia's cavalier.\nGradasso and the puissant Falsiron,\nIn that which fronts the morning hemisphere,\nClothe with their hands, in Trojan plate and chain,\nThe good successor of King Agricane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "High on a throne of ample state appeared\nAgramant and Marsilius; next in place\nWere Stordilane and all the chiefs, revered\nThroughout the squadrons of the paynim race.\nHappy was he who found himself upreared\nOn mound or tree, above that level space.\nGreat was the throng, and round the palisade\nOn every side the eddying people swayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Were seated with the Queen of fair Castille\nQueens, princesses, and dames of noble strain,\nFrom Arragon, Granada, and Seville,\nAnd Atlas' columns; and amid the train\nAssembled to behold that fierce appeal,\nWas placed the daughter of King Stordilane:\nTwo costly vests — one red, one green — she wore;\nBut ill the first was dyed, and faded sore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In dress succinct Marphisa sate; in plight\nSuch as beseemed a warrior and a maid:\nThermodoon haply witnessed Hippolyte\nAnd her fair squadron in like garb arrayed.\nAfield already, in his livery dight,\nAgramant's herald made proclaim, and said\nIt was forbid to all men, far and wide,\nIn act or word, with either part to side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The frequent crowd expects the double foe;\nAnd often, in impatience, they complain,\nAnd call those famous cavaliers too slow:\nWhen from the Tartar's tent an angry strain\nIs heard, and cries which multiply; sir, know\nIt was the martial king of Sericane,\nAnd puissant Tartar, who that question stirred,\nAnd made the mighty tumult which has heard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sericane's monarch, having with his hand\nEquipt the king of Tartary all o'er,\nApproached to gird him with that sovereign brand,\nWith which Orlando went adorned of yore.\nWhen Durindana on the hilt he scanned,\nGraved with the quartering that Almontes wore;\nWhich from that wretched man, beside a font,\nYouthful Orlando reft in Aspramont."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, seeing this, agnised it for the blade\nSo famous, which Anglantes' warrior bore,\nFor which he had the fairest fleet arrayed\nWhich ever put to sea from eastern shore;\nAnd had Castille's rich kingdom overlaid,\nAnd conquered fruitful France some years before;\nBut cannot now imagine how that sword\nIs in possession of the Tartar lord;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And asks had he by force or treaty won,\nAnd when and where and how, that faulchion bright;\nAnd Mandricardo said that he had done\nFierce battle for that sword with Brava's knight;\nWho feigned himself of sober sense foregone,\nHoping that so he should conceal his fright:\n— \"For I on him would ceaseless war have made,\"\n(He added \"while he kept the goodly blade.\" )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Saying the Count, in yielding to his foe\nThat sword, the Beavers' known device had tried;\nWho. followed closely by the hunter, know\nTheir fell pursuer covers nought beside.\nEre he had heard him out, — \"Nor I forego\nThat sword to thee nor any one,\" (replied\nGradasso, fierce, \"well earned by me, at cost ) \n\nOf treasure, and of pain, and people lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Some other faulchion for thyself purvey;\nThis will I have; nor deem my reasons new;\nWhether Orlando wise or foolish stray,\nI make it mine where'er it meets my view.\nWith none to witness, thou, beside the way\nUsurped that sword; I claim it as my due:\nFor this my scimeter shall reasons yield,\nAnd we will try the cause in listed field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Prepare to win the sword before thou rear\nThat goodly blade against King Rodomont.\nTo win his arms is use of cavalier,\nBefore his foe in duel he affront.\"\n— \"No sweeter music ever soothes my ear\"\n(Replied the Tartar, as he raised his front)\n\"Than voice which champions me to martial field;\nBut see that his consent the Sarzan yield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Be thou the first; and, next on listed ground\nLet Sarza's valiant lord the question try;\nNor doubt but I in readiness be found\nTo thee and every other to reply.\"\n\" — Thou shalt not so the ordered lots confound,\nOr break our compact (was Rogero's cry):\nEither, first Rodomont shall take the field,\nOr shall to me his right of battle yield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"It that be true Gradasso has averred,\nThat knight should win the arms he would assay,\nThou hast no title to my white-winged bird,\nSave this from me thou first shalt bear away.\nBut since, forsooth, whilere I said the word,\nI will not what I once pronounced unsay,\nThat mine shall be the second battle, so\nThat Argier's monarch first affront his foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I will confuse the order of the field,\nThroughout, if partially confused by thee;\nAbandon will I not my blazoned shield,\nUnless thou combat for it now with me.\"\n— \"Were one and the other Mars, for battle steeled,\n(Replies enraged, the king of Tartary)\n\"Nor one nor the other's might should make me waive\nMy title to that shield and goodly glaive\";"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And over mastered by his choler, flies\nWith a clenched fist at him of Sericane,\nAnd smites him with his right-hand in such wise,\nAs makes him quit his hold of Durindane.\nGradasso bold was taken by surprise,\nNot deeming him so furious and insane;\nAnd, while he looked not to the Tartar lord,\nFound himself robbed of good Orlando's sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fury and scorn Gradasso's visage heats,\nWhich seems to flash with fire, at that disgrace;\nAnd with more rage and pain his bosom beats,\nIn that 'twas offered in such public place.\nTo draw his scimeter, the king retreats,\nIntent upon revenge, some little space.\nSo Mandricardo on himself relies\nRogero he to fight, as well defies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Come on in arms against me, both combined,\nAnd be King Rodomont the third!\" (he said)\n\"Come Spain and Afric and all human kind;\nNe'er will I turn.\" And he, at nought dismaid,\nSo saying, in his fury, sawed the wind\nAbout him, with Almontes' noble blade,\nEmbraced his shield, and, full of choler, stood\nAgainst Gradasso and Rogero good."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Leave me the care,\" the fierce Gradasso cried,\n\"The phrensy of this madman to subdue.\"\n— \"Not so, by Heaven!\" Rogero wroth replied,\n\"For I this field claim justly as my due.\"\n— \"Stand back!\" and \"stand thou back!\" on either side\nThey shout; yet neither of the twain withdrew.\nAnd thus among those three began a feud;\nAnd thence some strange result would have ensued,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If many had not interposed, and sought\nWith little wit their fury to restrain;\nWho had well-nigh too dear the experience bought\nOf saving others at their proper pain;\nNor to accord the world had ever brought\nThose knights, but that the worthy king of Spain\nCame thither with renowned Troyano's heir;\nAwed by whose sovereign presence all forbear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant those contending warriors made\nThe cause of their so burning strife display;\nNext earnestly bestirred himself, and prayed\nGradasso that he would, in courteous way,\nConcede the Trojan Hector's goodly blade\nTo Mandricardo, solely for that day,\nUntil the cruel fight was at an end,\nWherein he should with Rodomont contend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While royal Agramant would peace restore,\nAnd now with this and now with that conferred,\nFrom the other tent, between the Sarzan Moor\nAnd Sacripant, another strife was heard.\nValiant King Sacripant (as said before)\nTo equip Sir Rodomont himself bestirred,\nAnd he and Ferrau had that champion drest\nIn his forefather Nimrod's iron vest;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And there had they arrived, where with his spume\nThe horse was making his rich bridle white:\nI of the good Frontino speak, for whom\nRogero urged with yet unfelt despite.\nKing Sacripant, who plays the part of groom,\nAnd has to bring afield the Sarzan knight,\nMarks narrowly the courser's gear and shoes,\nAnd sell and furniture throughout reviews;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And as his points and nimble parts, more near,\nHe, in this view, observes with better heed,\nThe youthful king, beyond all doubt, is clear\nHe sees his Frontilatte in that steed,\nHim he of old had held so passing dear,\nWhilom of such debates the fruitful seed;\nAnd for whose loss, whilere he was so woe,\nHe evermore on foot resolved to go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This from beneath him had Brunello borne\nBefore Albracca, on the very day\nAngelica's rare ring, and Roland's horn,\nAnd Balisarda he conveyed away,\nWith fierce Marphisa's blade, — and on return\nTo Afric — to Rogero, from his prey,\nGave Balisarda and the courser, who\nWas by the Child Frontino named anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Assured 'twas no mistake, Circassia's chief\nTurned him about to Rodomont, and cried:\n\"Reft from me in Albracca, by a thief,\nThis horse is mine; which might be certified\nBy them whose words would warrant well belief:\nBut as my witnesses are distant wide,\nIf it be questioned, I will make it plain,\nAnd will, with sword in hand, the truth maintain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet am I well contented, for that we\nHave for these some few days together gone,\nTo lend him for to-day; since well I see,\nThat not without him could the fight be done;\nBut on condition, that the courser be\nAcknowledged mine, and furnished as a loan:\nOtherwise hope not for that horse, save first\nMe, on this quarrel, thou in combat worst.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The furious king of Argier, that in pride\nSurpassed all knights that ever girt the sword,\nWhose paragon, for heart and prowess tried,\nMeseems no ancient histories record,\nCried: \"Sacripant, if any one beside\nThyself, to me should utter such a word,\nHe should deem quickly, from its bitter fruit,\nHe from his birth would better have been mute."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But, for that fellowship in which we went,\n(As thou hast said together, I to show ) \n\nSuch patience and forbearance am content,\nAs warning thee, thy purpose to forego,\nUntil thou shalt have witnessed the event\nOf strife between me and my Tartar foe:\nWhen him I such example hope to make,\nThat thou shalt humbly say, `The courser take.' \""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fierce and enraged, replied Circassia's peer,\n\"To play the churl with thee is courteous deed,\nBut I to thee repeat more plain and clear,\nThou ill wouldst aught design against that steed,\nFor, while I an avenging sabre rear,\nThis I prohibit thee, and, should it need,\nAnd every better means of battle fail,\nWith thee for this would battle, tooth and nail.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They from dispute proceed to ribaldry,\nFrom words to blows; and through their mickle ire,\nFierce battle was inflamed, and blazed more high\nThan ever lightly-kindled straw took fire.\nKing Rodomont is steeled in panoply;\nSacripant neither plate nor mail attire:\nYet so in fence is skilled that nimble lord,\nHe seems all over sheltered by his sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No greater were the daring and the might\n(Though infinite which Rodomont displaid ) \n\nThan the precaution and the nimble sleight\nWhich the Circassian summoned to his aid:\nNo mill-wheel ever turns with swifter flight\nThe circling stone by which the grain is brayed,\nThan Sacripant at need moves foot or hand,\nAnd shifts now here, now there his restless stand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Serpentine and Ferrau interfere:\nThey with drawn swords the twain asunder bore;\nWith them Grandonio was and Isolier,\nAnd many other leaders of the Moor,\nThis was the tumult which was heard whilere\nIn the other tent, what time they laboured sore,\nRogero vainly to a peace to bring\nWith Tartary's and Sericana's king."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while some voice to Agramant the news\nReports aright, that Ulien's might seed,\nWith Sacripant, Circassia's king, pursues\nA fierce and furious quarrel for the steed.\nAgramant, whom so many jars confuse,\nExclaims to King Marsilius: \"Take thou heed\nThat no worse evil mid these knights betide,\nWhile for this new disorder I provide.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont reined his anger, and retired\nSome deal, at his approaching sovereign's view;\nNor less respect in Sacripant inspired\nThe Moorish monarch; of the furious two,\nHe with grave voice and royal mien inquired\nWhat cause of strife such deadly discord blew;\nAnd having searched their quarrel to the root,\nWould fain accord them; but with little fruit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Circassia's monarch would not, on his side,\nLonger his horse to Argier's lord allow,\nSave humbly Rodomont to him applied,\nThat steed for this occasion to bestow.\nTo him Sir Rodomont, with wonted pride,\nReturned for answer: \"Neither Heaven nor thou\nShall make me recognize as gift or loan\nWhat I with this good hand can make mine own.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king bade Sacripant explain his right,\nAnd how that horse was taken from him sought;\nAnd this from first to last Circassia's knight\nRehearsed, and reddened as the tale he taught,\nRelating to the king the robber's sleight;\nWho had surprised him overwhelmed with thought,\nUpon four spears his courser's saddle stayed,\nAnd from beneath the naked horse conveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa, whom these cries, mid others, bring,\nWhen of the robbery of the horse advised,\nIn visage is disturbed, remembering\nHow on that day her faulchion was surprised;\nAnd when that courser (which equipt with wing\nAppeared when flying her she recognized; ) \n\nAnd recognized as well — at first unknown —\nThe valiant king who filled Circassia's throne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The others who stood round her, wont to hear\nBrunello often boast of the deceit,\n'Gan turn towards that wretch, and made appear\nBy open signs they knew him for the Cheat.\nMarphisa who the subtle knave whilere\nSuspected as the author of that feat,\nNow questions this, now that, who all accord\nIn saying 'twas Brunello stole her sword;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who, well deserving as a fitting pain\nTo dangle from the gallows-tree in air,\nBy Agramant the crown of Tingitane\n(An ill example was preferred to wear. ) \n\nThis fires anew Marphisa's old disdain,\nNor she from instant vengeance will forbear,\nFor this, as well as other shame and scorn\nShe on her road had from that caitiff born."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A squire laced on her helmet, at her hest;\nShe wore the remnant of her armour sheen;\nNor without martial cuirass on her breast,\nFind I, that she ten times was ever seen,\nEven from the day when first that iron vest\nBraced on her limbs the passing-valiant queen:\nWith helm on head, where, mid the highest rows,\nBrunello sits among the first, she goes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him by mid breast Marphisa griped amain,\nAnd lifted up the losel from the ground;\nAs is rapacious eagle wont to strain\nThe pullet, in her talons circled round;\nAnd bore him where the sons of King Troyane\nHeard the two knights their jarring claims propound.\nHe who perceives himself in evil hands,\nAye weeps, and mercy of that maid demands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above the universal noise and shout,\nWhich rose nigh equally on either side,\nBrunello, who from all the crowd about\nFor pity now, and now for succour, cried,\nSo loud was heard, that of that ample rout\nHe gathered round himself the pressing tide.\nArrived before the Moorish army's head,\nTo him with haughty mien Marphisa said:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This thief (said she), thy vassal, will I slay,\nAnd with this hand of mine will knot the cord\nAbout his neck; because the very day\nHe stole this courser, he purloined my sword.\nBut is there any one who deems I say\nAmiss, let him stand forth and speak the word;\nFor I on him will prove, before thine eyes,\nI have done right, and who gainsays me, lies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But because haply some one may pretend\nI have till such a time of strife delayed\nMy vengeance, when such famous knights contend,\nFor three days shall the wretch's doom be stayed;\nIn the mean time let him who would defend\nThat caitiff, come himself, or send him aid.\nFor afterwards, if none the deed prevent,\nHis carcass shall a thousand birds content."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I hence to yonder tower, which distant nigh\nThree leagues, o'erlooks a little copse, repair,\nBut with one varlet in my company,\nAnd with one waiting-maid; if any dare\nRescue the thief, let him come thither; I\nWait the approach of his defenders there.\"\nThus she; and thither quickly wends her ways\nWhither was said, nor any answer stays."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Held on the pommel grappled by his hair,\nBrunello on Marphisa's courser lies:\nThe caitiff weeps, and shrieking in despair,\nOn all in whom he hopes, for succour cries.\nIn such confusion is Troyano's heir,\nHe sees no way through these perplexities;\nAnd, that Marphisa thence Brunello bore\nIn such a guise, yet grieved the monarch more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not that he loved the losel or esteemed,\nRather to him some time had borne despite;\nAnd often had to hand the caitiff schemed,\nSince he had forfeited the ring of might.\nBut here his honour touched the monarch deemed,\nSo that his visage reddened at the slight:\nHe would, in person, follow her at speed,\nAnd to his utmost power avenge the deed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But the wise king, Sobrino, who was by,\nHim from the quest endeavoured to dissuade,\nAnd that with his exalted majesty\nSuch enterprize were ill assorted said:\nAlthough firm hope, nay full security,\nHe had to overcome that martial maid,\nIf he with pain subdued a woman, shame,\nRather than honour, would pursue his name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Small profit and much peril would succeed\nFrom any fight he should with her maintain,\n(And he advised him as the better deed, ) \n\nTo leave that wretched caitiff to his pain;\nAnd albeit but a simple nod should need\nTo free him, from that nod he should refrain.\nIn that the monarch would do ill to force\nEven-handed Justice from her destined course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou to the fierce Marphisa may'st apply\nTo leave his trial (he pursued to thee, ) \n\nWith promise, her in this to satisfy\nAnd to suspend him from the gallows-tree:\nAnd even should the maid thy prayer deny,\nLet her in every wish contented be:\nAnd rather than that she desert thy side,\nLet her hang him and every thief beside.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Right willingly King Agramant gave way\nTo King Sobrino's counsel sage and staid;\nAnd let renowned Marphisa wend her way,\nNor scathed he, nor let scathe, that martial maid,\nNeither endured that any her should pray;\nAnd heaven knows with what courage he obeyed\nThat wise advice, to calm such ruder strife\nAnd quarrel, as throughout his camp were rife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At this mad Discord laughed, no more in fear\nThat any truce or treaty should ensue;\nAnd scowered the place of combat there and here,\nNor could stand still, for pleasure at the view.\nPride gamboled and rejoiced with her compeer,\nAnd on the fire fresh food and fuel threw,\nAnd shouted so that Michael in the sky\nKnew the glad sign of conquest in that cry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Paris-town rocked, and turbid ran the flood\nOf Seine at that loud voice, that horrid roar;\nAnd, so it echo rang in Arden's wood,\nBeasts left their caverns in that forest hoar.\nAlp and Cevenne's mountain-solitude,\nAnd Blois, and Arles, and Rouen's distant shore,\nRhine, Rhone, and Saone, and Garonne, heard the pest;\nScared mothers hugged their children to their breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Five have set up their rest, resolved to be\nThe first their different quarrels to conclude:\nAnd tangled so is one with other plea,\nThat ill Apollo's self could judge the feud.\nTo unravel that first cause of enmity\nThe king began — the strife which had ensued,\nBecause of beauteous Doralice, between\nThe king of Scythia and her Algerine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Agramant oft moved, between the pair,\nNow here now there, to bring them to accord;\nNow there now here, admonishing that pair,\nLike faithful brother and like righteous lord:\nBut when he found that neither would forbear,\nDeaf and rebellious to his royal word,\nNor would consent that lady to forego,\nThe cause of strife, in favour of his foe,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As his best lore, at length the monarch said,\nAnd to obey his sentence both were fain;\nThat he who was by her preferred, should wed\nThe beauteous daughter of King Stordilane:\nAnd that what was established on his head\nShould not be changed, to either's loss or gain.\nThe compromise was liked on either side,\nSince either hoped she would for him decide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The mighty king of Sarza, who long space\nBefore the Tartar, had loved Doralice,\n(Who had preferred that sovereign to such grace\nAs modest lady may, nor do amiss)\nBelieved, when she past sentence on the case,\nShe must pronounce what would ensure his bliss.\nNor thus alone King Rodomont conceived,\nBut all the Moorish host with him believed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All know what exploits wrought by him had been\nFor her in joust and war; they all unsound\nAnd weak King Mandricardo's judgment ween;\nBut he, who oft was with her on their round,\nAnd oftener private with the youthful queen,\nWhat time the tell-tale sun was under ground,\nHe, knowing well how sure he was to speed,\nLaughed at the silly rabble's idle creed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They, after, ratify the king's award,\nBetween his hands, and next the suitors twain\nBefore that damsel go, that on the sward\nFixing her downcast eyes, in modest vein,\nAvows her preference of the Tartar lord;\nAt which sore wondering stand the paynim train;\nAnd Rodomont remains so sore astound,\nHe cannot raise his visage from the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But wonted anger chasing shame which dyed\nThe Sarzan's face all over, he arraigned\nThe damsel's sentence, of the faulchion, tied\nAbout his manly waist, the handle strained,\nAnd in the king's and others' hearing cried:\n\"By this the question shall be lost or gained;\nAnd not by faithless woman's fickle thought,\nWhich thither still inclines, where least it ought.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Kind Mandricardo on his feet once more,\nExclaims, \"And be it as it pleases thee.\"\nSo that ere yet the vessel made the shore\nUnploughed remained a mighty space of sea;\nBut that this king reproved the Sarzan sore,\nRuling that to appeal upon that plea\nNo more with Mandricardo could avail,\nAnd made the moody Sarzan strike his sail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Branded with double scorn, before those peers,\nBy noble Agramant, whose sovereign sway\nHe, as in loyal duty bound, reveres,\nAnd by his lady on the selfsame day,\nThere will no more the monarch of Algiers\nAbide, but of his band — a large array —\nTwo serjeants only for his service takes,\nAnd with that pair the paynim camp forsakes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the afflicted bull who has foregone\nHis heifer, nor can longer warfare wage,\nSeeks out the greenwood-holt and stream most lone,\nOr sands at distance from his pasturage;\nThere ceases not, in sun or shade to moan;\nYet not for that exhales his amorous rage:\nSo parts, constrained his lady to forego,\nThe king of Argier, overwhelmed with woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero moved, his courser to regain,\nAnd had already donned his warlike gear,\nThen recollecting, that on listed plain\nAt Mandricardo he must couch the spear,\nFollowed not Rodomont, but turned his rein,\nTo end his quarrel with the Tartar, ere\nHe met in combat Sericana's lord\nWithin close barriers, for Orlando's sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To have Frontino ravished in his sight,\nAnd be unable to forbid the deed,\nHe sorely grieves; but, when he shall that fight\nHave done, resolves he will regain the steed;\nBut Sacripant, whom, like the youthful knight,\nNo quarrels in the Moor's pursuit impede,\nAnd who was unengaged in other quest,\nUpon the Sarzan's footsteps quickly prest;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And would have quickly joined him that was gone,\nBut for the chance of an adventure rare;\nWhich him detained until the day was done,\nAnd made him lose the track of Ulien's heir:\nA woman who had fallen into the Saone,\nAnd who without his help had perished there,\nThe warrior drowning in that water found,\nAnd stemmed the stream and dragged the dame aground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When afterwards he would remount the sell,\nFrom him his restless charger broke astray,\nWho fled before his lord till evening fell,\nNor lightly did the king that courser stay.\nAt last he caught him; but no more could spell\nWhere he had wandered from the beaten way:\nTwo hundred miles he roved, 'twist hill and plain,\nEre he came up with Rodomont again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How he by Sacripant was overtaken,\nAnd fought by him, to his discomfit sore,\nAnd how he lost his courser, how was taken,\nI say not now, who have to say before,\nWith what disdain and with what anger shaken,\nAgainst his liege and love, the Sarzan Moor\nForth from the Saracen cantonments sped,\nAnd what he of the one and other said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Wherever that afflicted paynim goes,\nHe fills the kindling air with sighs that burn;\nAnd Echo oft, for pity of his woes,\nWith him from hollow rock is heard to mourn:\n\"O female mind!  how lightly ebbs and flows\nYour fickle mood,\" (he cries, \"aye prone to turn! ) \n\nObject most opposite to kindly faith!\nLost, wretched man, who trusts you to his scathe!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Neither my love nor length of servitude,\nThough by a thousand proofs to you made clear,\nHad power even so to fix your faithless mood,\nThat you at least so lightly should not veer:\nNor am I quitted, because less endued\nWith worth than Mandricardo I appear;\nNor for your conduct cause can I declare,\nSave this alone, that you a woman are."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I think that nature and an angry God\nProduced thee to the world, thou wicked sex,\nTo be to man a plague, a chastening rod;\nHappy, wert thou not present to perplex.\nSo serpent creeps along the grassy sod;\nSo bear and ravening wolf the forest vex;\nWasp, fly, and gad-fly buzz in liquid air,\nAnd the rich grain lies tangled with the tare."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Why has not bounteous Nature willed that man\nShould be produced without the aid of thee,\nAs we the pippin, pear, and service can\nEngraft by art on one another's tree?\nBut she directs not all by certain plan;\nRather, upon a nearer view, I see,\nIn naming her, she ill can act aright,\nSince Nature is herself a female hight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet be not therefore proud and full of scorn\nWomen, because man issues from your seed;\nFor roses also blossom on the thorn,\nAnd the fair lily springs from loathsome weed.\nDespiteous, proud, importunate, and lorn\nOf love, of faith, of counsel, rash in deed,\nWith that, ungrateful, cruel and perverse,\nAnd born to be the world's eternal curse!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These plaints and countless others to the wind\nPoured forth the paynim knight, to fury stirred;\nNow easing in low tone his troubled mind,\nAnd now in sounds which were at distance heard,\nIn shame and in reproach of womankind;\nYet certes he from sober reason erred:\nFor we may deem a hundred good abound,\nWhere one or two perchance are evil found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though none for whom I hitherto have sighed\n— Of those so many — have kept faith with me,\nAll with ingratitude, or falsehood dyed\nI deem not, I accuse my destiny.\nMany there are, and have been more beside\nUnmeriting reproach: but if there be,\n'Mid hundreds, one or two of evil way,\nMy fortune wills that I should be their prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet will I make such search before I die,\nRather before my hair shall wax more white,\nThat haply on some future day, even I\nShall say, \"That one has kept her promise plight.\"\nAnd should not the event my trust belie,\n(Nor am I hopeless I with all my might ) \n\nWill with unwearied pain her praise rehearse\nWith pen and ink and voice, in prose and verse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Saracen, whom rage no less profound\nAgainst his sovereign lord than lady swayed,\nAnd who of reason thus o'erpast the bound,\nAnd ill of one and of the other said,\nWould fain behold that monarch's kingdom drowned\nWith such a tempest, with such scathe o'erlaid,\nAs should in Africk every house aggrieve,\nNor one stone standing on another leave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And would that from his realm, in want and woe,\nKing Agramant a mendicant should wend;\nThat through his means the monarch, brought thus low,\nHis fathers' ancient seat might reascend:\nAnd thus he might the fruit of fealty show,\nAnd make his sovereign see, a real friend\nWas aye to be preferred in wrong or right,\nAlthough the world against him should unite;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And thus the Saracen pours forth his moan,\nWith rage against his liege and love possest;\nAnd on his way is by long journeys gone,\nGiving himself and courser little rest.\nThe following day or next, upon the Saone\nHe finds himself, who has his course addrest\nTowards the coast of Provence, with design\nTo his African domain to cross the brine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From bank to bank the stream was covered o'er\nWith boat of little burden, which conveyed,\nFor the supply of the invading Moor,\nVictual, from many places round purveyed:\nSince even from Paris to the pleasant shore\nOf Acquamorta, all his rule obeyed;\nAnd — fronting Spain — whate'er of level land\nWas seen, extending on the better hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The victual, disembarked from loaded barge,\nWas laid on sumpter-horse or ready wain;\nAnd sent, with escort to protect the charge,\nWhere barges could not come; about the plain,\nFat herds were feeding on the double marge,\nBrought thither from the march of either reign;\nAnd, by the river-side, at close of day,\nIn different homesteads lodged, the drovers lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king of Argier (for the dusky air\nOf night began upon the world to close)\nHere listened to a village-landlord's prayer,\nThat in his inn besought him to repose.\n— His courser stalled — the board with plenteous fare\nIs heaped, and Corsic wine and Grecian flows;\nFor, in all else a Moor, the Sarzan drank\nOf the forbidden vintage like a Frank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To warlike Rodomont, with goodly cheer\nAnd kindlier mien, the landlord honour paid;\nFor he the port of an illustrious peer\nIn his guest's lofty presence saw pourtrayed.\nBut, sore beside himself, the cavalier\nHad scarce his heart within him, which had strayed\nTo her — whilere his own — in his despite;\nNor word escaped the melancholy knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Mine host, most diligent in his vocation\nOf all the trade who throughout France were known,\n(In that he had, 'mid strange and hostile nation,\nAnd every chance of warfare, kept his own)\n— Prompt to assist him in his occupation,\nSome of his kin had called; whereof was none\nWho dared before the warrior speak of aught,\nSeeing that paynim mute and lost in thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From thought to thought the Sarzan's fancy flies,\nHimself removed from thence a mighty space,\nWho sits so bent, and with such downcast eyes,\nHe never once looks any in the face.\nNext, after silence long, and many sighs,\nAs if deep slumber had but then given place,\nHis spirits he recalls, his eyelids raises,\nAnd on the family and landlord gazes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then silence broke, and with a milder air,\nAnd visage somewhat less disturbed, applied\nTo him, the host, and those by-standers there,\nTo know if any to a wife were tied;\nAnd landlord and attendants, — that all were,\nTo Sarza's moody cavalier replied:\nHe asked what each conceited of his spouse,\nAnd if he deemed her faithful to her vows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Except mine host, those others were agreed\nThat chaste and good their consorts they believed.\n— \"Think each man as he will, but well I read,\"\n(The landlord said, \"You fondly are deceived: ) \n\nYour rash replies to one conclusion lead,\nThat you are all of common sense bereaved;\nAnd so too must believe this noble knight,\nUnless he would persuade us black is white."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Because, as single is that precious bird\nThe phoenix, and on earth there is but one,\nSo, in this ample world, it is averred,\nOne only can a woman's treason shun.\nEach hopes alike to be that wight preferred,\nThe victor who that single palm has won.\n— How is it possible that what can fall\nTo one alone, should be the lot of all?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Erewhile I made the same mistake as you,\nAnd that more dames than one were virtuous thought,\nUntil a gentleman of Venice, who,\nFor my good fortune, to this inn was brought,\nMy ignorance by his examples true\nSo ably schooled, he better wisdom taught.\nValerio was the name that stranger bore;\nA name I shall remember evermore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of wives and mistresses the treachery\nWas known to him, with all their cunning lore.\nHe, both from old and modern history,\nAnd from his own, was ready with such store,\nAs plainly showed that none to modesty\nCould make pretension, whether rich or poor;\nAnd that, if one appeared of purer strain,\n'Twas that she better hid her wanton vein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He of his many tales, among the rest,\n(Whereof a third is from my memory gone)\nSo well one story in my head imprest,\nIt could not be more firmly graved in stone:\nAnd what I thought and think, would be professed\nFor that ill sex, I ween by every one\nWho heard; and, Sir — if pleased to lend an ear —\nTo their confusion yon that tale shall hear.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What could'st thou offer which could better please\nAt present\" (made reply the paynim knight)\n\"Than sample, chosen from thine histories,\nWhich hits the opinion that I hold, aright?\nThat I may hear thee speak with better ease\nSit so, that I may have thee in my sight.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto I unfold\nWhat to King Rodomont the landlord told.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 28"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To whatsoever evil tongue can tell\nOf womankind King Rodomont gives ear;\nThen journeys homeward; but that infidel\nFinds by the way a place he holds more dear.\nHere him new love inflames for Isabel;\nBut so the wishes of the cavalier\nA friar impedes, who with that damsel wends,\nHim by a cruel death the felon ends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ladies, and all of you that ladies prize,\nAfford not, for the love of heaven, an ear\nTo this, the landlord's tale, replete with lies,\nIn shame and scorn of womankind; though ne'er\nWas praise or fame conveyed in that which flies\nFrom such a caitiff's tongue; and still we hear\nThe sottish rabble all things rashly brand,\nAnd question most what least they understand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Omit this canto, and — the tale untold —\nMy story will as clear and perfect be;\nI tell it, since by Turpin it is told,\nAnd not in malice or in rivalry:\nBesides, that never did my tongue withhold\nYour praises, how you are beloved by me\nTo you I by a thousand proofs have shown,\nVouching I am, and can but be, your own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let him who will, three leaves or four pass-by,\nNor read a line; or let him, who will read,\nAs little of that landlord's history,\nAs of a tale or fiction, make his creed.\nBut to my story: — When his auditory\nHe saw were waiting for him to proceed,\nAnd that a place was yielded him, o'eright\nThe cavalier, he 'gan his tale recite:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Astolpho that the Lombard sceptre swayed,\nWho was King Monacho, his brother's heir,\nBy nature with such graces was purveyed,\nFew e'er with him in beauty could compare:\nSuch scarce Apelles' pencil had pourtrayed,\nZeuxis', or worthier yet, if worthier were:\nBeauteous he was, and so by all was deemed,\nBut far more beauteous he himself esteemed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He not so much rejoiced that he in height\nOf grandeur was exalted o'er the rest,\nAnd that, for riches, subjects, and for might,\nOf all the neighbouring kings he was the best,\nAs that, superior to each other wight,\nHe beauty was throughout the world confest.\nThis pleased the monarch, who the praise conferred,\nAs that wherein he most delighted, heard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Faustus Latinus, one of his array,\nWho pleased the king, a Roman cavalier,\nHearing ofttimes Astolpho now display\nThe beauties of his hand, now of his cheer,\nAnd, questioned by that monarch, on a day,\nIf ever in his lifetime, far or near,\nHe any of such beauty had espied,\nTo him thus unexpectedly replied:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Faustus to him replied: `By what I see,\nAnd what I hear, is said by every one,\nFew are there that in beauty rival thee;\nAnd rather I those few confine to one:\nJocundo is that one, my brother he;\nAnd well I ween that, saving him alone,\nThou leavest all in beauty far behind;\nBut I in him thy peer and better find.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Impossible Astolpho deemed the thing,\nWho hitherto had thought the palm his own;\nAnd such a longing seized the Lombard king\nTo know that youth whose praises so were blown,\nHe prest, till Faustus promised him to bring\nThe brother praised by him, before his throne,\nThough 'twould be much if thither he repaired,\n(The courier added and the cause declared: )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Because the youth had ne'er been known to measure,\nIn all his life, a single pace from Rome;\nBut, on what Fortune gave him, lived at leisure,\nContented in his own paternal dome;\nNor had diminished nor encreased the treasure,\nWherewith his father had endowed that home;\nAnd he more distant would Paris deem\nThan Tanais another would esteem;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And that a greater difficulty were\nTo tear Jocundo from his consort; who\nWas by such love united to that fair,\nNo other will but hers the husband knew:\nYet at his sovereign's hest he would repair\nTo seek the stripling, and his utmost do.\nThe suit with offers and with gifts was crowned,\nWhich for that youth's refusal left no ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Faustus set forth, and, after few days' ride,\nReached Rome, and his paternal mansion gained:\nThere with entreaties so the brother plied,\nHe to that journey his consent obtained;\nAnd wrought so well (though difficult to guide)\nSilent even young Jocundo's wife remained;\nHe showing her what good would thence ensue,\nBesides what gratitude would be her due."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Jocundo names a time to wend his way,\nAnd servingmen meanwhile purveys and steeds;\nAnd a provision makes of fair array;\nFor beauty borrows grace from glorious weeds.\nBeside him or about him, night and day,\nAye weeping, to her lord the lady reads;\nShe knows not how she ever can sustain\nSo long an absence, and not die with pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For the mere thought produced such misery,\nIt seemed from her was ravished her heart's core.\n— `Alas! my love (Jocundo cried let be ) \n\nThy sorrows' — weeping with her evermore —\n`So may this journey prosper!  as to thee\nWill I return ere yet two months are o'er;\nNor by a day o'erpass the term prescribed,\nThough me the king with half his kingdom bribed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This brought his troubled consort small content:\nShe that the period was too distant said,\nAnd that 'twould be a mighty wonderment,\nIf her, at his return, he found not dead.\nThe grief which, day and night, her bosom rent,\nWas such, that lady neither slept nor fed:\nSo that for pity oft the youth repented\nHe to his brother's wishes had consented."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She from her neck unloosed a costly chain\nThat a gemmed cross and holy reliques bore;\nWhich one, a pilgrim of Bohemia's reign,\nHad gathered upon many a distant shore;\nHim did her sire in sickness entertain,\nReturning from Jerusalem of yore;\nAnd hence was made that dying pilgrim's heir:\nThis she undoes, and gives her lord to wear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And round his neck entreats him, for her sake,\nThat chain in memory of herself to wind:\nHer gift the husband is well pleased to take;\nNot that a token needs his love to bind:\nFor neither time, nor absence, e'er will shake,\nNor whatsoever fortune is behind,\nHer memory, which, rooted fast and deep,\nHe still has kept, and after death will keep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The night before that morning streaked the sky,\nFixt for his journey, to his sore dismay,\nHer husband deemed that in his arms would die\nThe wife from whom he was to wend his way.\nShe slumbered not: to her a last goodbye\nHe bade, while yet it lacked an hour of day,\nMounted his nag, and on his journey sped;\nWhile his afflicted spouse returned to bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Jocundo was not two miles on his road,\nWhen he that jewelled cross recalled to mind;\nWhich he beneath his pillow had bestowed,\nAnd, through forgetfulness, had left behind.\n`Alas! (the youth bethought him in what mode ) \n\nShall I excuse for my omission find,\nSo that from this my consort shall not deem\nI little her unbounded love esteem?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He pondered an excuse; then weened' twould be\nOf little value, if it were exprest\nBy page or other — save his embassy\nHe did himself; his brother he addrest;\n` — Now to Baccano ride you leisurely,\nAnd there at the first inn set-up your rest;\nFor I must back to Rome without delay;\nBut trust to overtake you by the way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `No other but myself my need could do.\nDoubt not but I shall speedily be back.'\n— No servant took he, but, with an adieu,\nJocundo, at a trot, wheeled round his hack,\nAnd when that cavalier the stream was through,\nThe rising sun 'gan chase the dusky rack.\nAt home he lighted, sought his bed, and found\nThe consort he had quitted sleeping sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, without saying aught, the curtains drew,\nAnd, what he least believed, within espied;\nFor he beneath the quilt, his consort true\nAnd chaste, saw sleeping at a stripling's side.\nForthwith Jocundo that adulterer knew,\nBy practice, of his features certified,\nIn that he was a footboy in his train,\nNourished by him, and come of humble strain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To imagine his distress and wonderment,\nAnd warrant it, that other may believe,\nIs better than to make the experiment,\nAnd, like this wretch, the cruel proof receive:\nBy anger stirred, it was his first intent\nTo draw his sword, and both of life bereave;\nBut love, which spite himself, he entertained\nFor that ungrateful woman, him restrained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You see if like a vassal he obeyed\nThis ribald Love, who left him not the force\nTo wake her, lest to know her guilt surveyed,\nShould in his consort's bosom move remorse.\nAs best he could, he forth in silence made,\nThe stair descended, and regained his horse.\nGoaded by Love, he goads his steed again,\nAnd ere they reach their inn rejoins his train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His change of mien to all was manifest;\nAll saw his heart was heavy; yet not one,\nMid these, in any sort, the reason guessed,\nNor read the secret woe which caused his moan;\nAll thought he had to Rome his steps addrest,\nWoe to the town, surnamed of horns, had gone.\nThat Love has caused the mischief all surmise,\nThough none of them conjectures in what wise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His brother weened he was in grief immersed\nFor his deserted wife: he, on his side,\nFor other reason, inly chafed and cursed,\n— That she was but too well accompanied.\nMeanwhile, with swelling lips and forehead pursed,\nThe ground that melancholy stripling eyed.\nFaustus, who vainly would apply relief,\nIll cheered him, witless what had caused his grief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He for his sore an evil salve had found,\nAnd, where he should retire, encreased his woes;\nWho, with the mention of his wife, that wound\nInflamed and opened, which he sought to close.\nHe rests not night nor day, in sorrow drowned;\nHis appetite is gone, with his repose,\nNe'er to return; and (whilom of such fame)\nHis lovely visage seems no more the same."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His eye-balls seem deep-buried in his head,\nHis nose seems grown — his cheeks are pined so sore —\nNor even remains (his beauty so is fled)\nEnough to warrant what he was before.\nSuch fever burns him, of his sorrow bred,\nHe halts on Arbia's and on Arno's shore;\nAnd, if a charm is left, 'tis faded soon,\nAnd withered like a rose-bud plucked at noon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Besides that Faustus sorrowed to descry\nHim so bested; worse cause for sorrowing\nWas to that courtier to appear to lie\nBefore Astolpho; he was pledged to bring\nOne that was fairest deemed in every eye,\nWho must appear the foulest to that king;\nYet he continued on his way to wend,\nAnd brought him to Pavia in the end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not that forthwith he lets the youth be seen,\nLest him the king of little wit arraign;\nHe first by his dispatches lets him ween,\nThat thither he Jocundo brings with pain:\nSaying, that of his beauteous air and mien\nSome secret cause of grief had been the bane,\nAccompanied by a distemper sore:\nSo that he seemed not what he was before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Glad was the monarch, of his coming taught,\nAs of a friend's arrival he could be;\nSince in the universal world was nought,\nThat he so much desired as him to see:\nNor was the Lombard's king displeased in ought\nTo mark his guest's inferiority;\nThough, but for his misfortune, it was clear,\nHe his superior would have been or peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lodged by him in his palace, every day\nAnd every hour, the stranger youth he sees,\nStudious to honour him, and bids purvey\nStore of provision for his better ease.\nWhile still his thoughts to his ill consort stray,\nJocundo languishes; nor pastimes please\nThat melancholy man; nor music's strain\nOne jot diminishes his ceaseless pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Above his chambers, on the upper floor,\nNearest the roof, there was an ancient hall:\nThither, in solitary mood, (for sore\nPastime and company, the stripling gall,)\nHe aye betakes himself; while evermore\nSad thoughts some newer cause of grief recall.\nHe here (who would believe the story? found ) \n\nA remedy unhoped, which made him sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"At that hall's farther end, more feebly lighted,\n(For windows ever closed shut out the day)\nWhere one wall with another ill united,\nHe, through the chink, beheld a brighter ray:\nThere laid his eye, and saw, what he had slighted\nAs hard to credit, were it but hearsay:\nHe hears it not, but this himself descries;\nYet hardly can believe his very eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He of the Queen's apartment here was sight,\nHer choicest and her priviest chamber, where\nWas never introduced whatever wight,\nSave he most faithful was esteemed: he there,\nAs he was peeping, saw an uncouth fight;\nA dwarf was wrestling with the royal fair;\nAnd such that champion's skill, though undergrown,\nHe in the strife his opposite had thrown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As in a dream, Jocundo stood, beside\nHimself, awhile of sober sense bereaved;\nNor, but when of the matter certified,\nAnd sure it was no dream, his sight believed.\n— `A scorned and crooked monster,' (then he cried,)\n`Is, as her conqueror, by a dame received,\nWife of the comeliest, of the curtiest wight,\nAnd greatest monarch; Oh!  what appetite!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And he the consort to whom he was wed,\nHer he most used to blame, recalled to mind,\nAnd, for the stripling taken to her bed,\nTo deem the dame less culpable inclined:\nLess of herself than sex the fault he read,\nWhich to one man could never be confined:\nAnd thought, if in one taint all women shared,\nAt least his had not with a monster paired."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To the same place Jocundo made return,\nAt the same hour, upon the following day;\nAnd, putting on the king the self-same scorn,\nAgain beheld that dwarf and dame at play:\nAnd so upon the next and following morn;\nFor — to conclude — they made no holiday:\nWhile she (what most Jocundo's wonder moved)\nThe pigmy for his little love reproved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"One day, amid the rest, the youth surveyed\nThe dame disordered and opprest with gloom;\nHaving twice summoned, by her waiting-maid,\nThe favoured dwarf, who yet delayed to come;\nA third time by the lady sent, she said:\n— `Engaged at play, Madonna, is the groom,\nNor, lest he lose a doit, his paltry stake,\nWill that discourteous churl his game forsake.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"At such strange spectacle, the Roman knight\nCleared up his brow, his visage and his eyes;\nHe jocund, as in name, became in sprite,\nAnd changed his tears for smiles; with altered guise,\nHe waxed ruddy, gay, and plump in plight,\nAnd seems a cherubim of Paradise.\nSo that such change with wonderment all see,\nBrother and king, and royal family."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If from the youth Astolpho wished to know\nFrom whence this sudden light of comfort came,\nNo less Jocundo this desired to show,\nAnd to the king such injury proclaim:\nBut willed that like himself he should forego\nRevenge upon the author of that shame.\nHence, that he might discern her guilt, yet spare,\nHe made him on the Agnus Dei swear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He made him swear that he, for nothing said,\nOr seen, which might to him displeasing be,\n(Though he, in what he should discover, read\nAn outrage offered to his majesty,)\nWould, now or ever, venge him on his head:\nMoreover him he bound to secrecy;\nThat the ill doer ne'er, through deed or word,\nMight guess his injured king that case had heard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The monarch, who to every thing beside\nCould better have given credit, freely swore:\nTo him the cause Jocundo signified,\nWhy he had many days lamenting sore;\n— Because he had his evil wife espied\nIn the embraces of a serjeant poor;\nAnd vowed he should in fine have died of grief,\nIf he for longer time had lacked relief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But that within his highness' palace said,\nHe had witnessed what had much appeased his woe;\nFor, if foul shame had fallen upon his head,\nAt least he was not single; saying so,\nHe to that chink the Lombard monarch led,\nWho spied the mannikin of hideous show.\n(Lines 7 & 8 untranslated by Rose)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You may believe he shameless deemed that act,\nWithout my swearing it; he, at the sight,\nIt seemed, would go distraught, — with fury racked,\nHe against every wall his head would smite —\nWould cry aloud — would break the solemn pact,\nYet kept parforce the promise he had plight;\nAnd gulped his anger down and bitter scorn;\nSince on the holy water he had sworn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then to Jocundo: `What remains to me\nTo do in this misfortune, brother, speak;\nSince vengeance with more noted cruelty\nThou wilt not let me on the sinners wreak.'\n(Jocundo answered `Let these ingrates be; ) \n\nAnd try we if all women are as weak;\nAnd if the wives of others can be won\nTo do what others by our own have done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Both fair and youthful, measured by this scale,\nNor easily our equals shall we find;\nWhat woman but to us shall strike her sail,\nIf even to the ugly these are kind?\nAt least, if neither youth nor grace avail,\nThe money may, with which our bags are lined;\nNor will I that we homeward more return,\nEre the chief spoils we from a thousand earn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Long absence, seeing with a distant part,\nConverse with different women, oft allay,\nAs it would seem, the troubles of a heart,\nWhereof Love's angry passions make their prey.'\nThe king is pleased to hear the youth impart\nThis counsel, nor his journey will delay:\nThence on their road, with but two squires beside,\nHe and the Roman knight together ride."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Disguised they go through France and Italy,\nThey Flanders next and England scower, and where\nA woman they of lovely visage spy,\nAye find the dame complaint with their prayer.\nThey upon some bestow what others buy,\nAnd oft replaced their squandered treasures are.\nOur travellers to the wives of many sued,\nAnd by as many other dames were wooed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"By solid proof those comrades ascertain,\nHere tarrying for a month, and there for two,\nThat their own wives are of no other vein\nThan those of others, and as chast and true.\nAfter some season, wearied are the twain\nWith ever running after something new:\nFor, without risk of death, thus evermore\nThe intruders ill could enter other's door."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"— 'Twere best to find a girl whose natural bent\nAnd face to both of us should pleasing be;\nA girl, that us in common might content,\nNor we in her find cause for jealousy;\nAnd wherefore wouldst thou that I should lament\nMore than with other, to go halves with thee?'\n(Exclaimed Astolpho `well I know is none, ) \n\nOf all the female sex, content with one."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `One damsel that in nought shall us constrain,\n— Then only, when disposed to please the fair —\nWill we in peace and pleasure entertain,\nNor we, about her, have dispute or care.\nNor, deem I, she with reason could complain:\nFor if two fell to every other's share,\nBetter than one might she keep faith with two;\nNor haply we such frequent discord view.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Much seems the king's proposal to content\nThe Roman youth; and thus it is, the twain,\nTo execute Astolpho's project bent,\nJourney by many a hill and many a plain;\nAnd find at last, well fitting their intent,\nThe daughter of a publican of Spain,\nOf presence and of manners framed to win;\nWhose father at Valencia kept his inn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As yet, upon the bloom of spring, the maid\nWas a fresh flower that scarce began to blow:\nHer sire with many children was o'erlaid,\nAnd was to poverty a mortal foe.\nHence 'tis an easy matter to persuade\nMine host his buxom daughter to forego,\nAnd let them, where they will the damsel bear;\nIn that to treat her well the travellers swear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "(Lines 1-6 untranslated by Rose)\nThey to Zattiva come upon the day\nThat from Valencia they had bent their way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The travellers from their inn to street and square\nAnd places, public and divine, resort;\nWho, wheresoever they had made repair,\nThemselves were so accustomed to disport,\nThe girl is with the valets left in care,\nWho make the beds, and wearied hackneys sort:\nWhile others in the hostel-kitchen dight\nThe meal against their lords' return at night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As groom, a stripling in the hostel plied,\nWho in the other landlord's house had been:\nHe, from her childhood at the damsel's side,\nHad joyed her love: they, without change of mien,\nOn meeting, closely one another eyed,\nSince either apprehended to be seen:\nBut when alone — now left together — raised\nTheir eyelids and on one another gazed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The stripling asked her whitherward they sped,\nAnd of the two which claimed her as his right;\nThis, point by point, to him Flammetta read;\nFlammetta she, the Greek that boy was hight.\n` — When I had hoped the time was coming,' said\nThe Greek — `that I should live with thee, my light,\nFlammetta, thou, alas! art lost to me,\nNor know I if I more thy face shall see."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `I to the bitter dregs the cup must drain\nOf promised sweets; since thou art others' prey.\n'Twas my design, having with mickle pain\nAnd labour sore, some money put away,\nWhich I had hoarded out of frequent gain\nFrom parting guests, and from my yearly pay,\nTo seek again Valencia, and demand\nThee from thy sire in lawful wedlock's band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The damsel shrugs her shoulders, and complains;\nAnd — that he is too late — is her reply.\nThe Greek laments and sobs, and partly feigns:\n` — Wilt thou (he answered her thus let me die? ) \n\nLet me, at least, exhale my amorous pains!\nLet me, but once, in thine embrace lie!\nFor every moment in thy presence spent,\nEre thou depart, will make me die content.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To him the damsel, full of pity, cries:\n`Believe, I covet this no less than thee;\nBut here, surrounded by so many eyes,\nIs neither time nor opportunity.'\n` — I feel assured' (to her that youth replied)\n`Were I beloved by you, as you by me,\nThis very night you would find out a place\nWherein to solace us some little space.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "(Stanza LXI untranslated by Rose)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She bade him come — when she awhile had thought —\nWhen he believed that all asleep were laid;\nAnd how by him her chamber should be sought,\nAnd how he should return, at full, displaid.\nThe cautious stripling did as he was taught,\nAnd, when he found all silent, thither made:\nHe pushed, till it gave way, the chamber-door,\nAnd, upon tiptoes, softly paced the floor.\n\nLXIII - LXX\n(Stanzas LXIII - LXX untranslated by Rose)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Gazing on one another, with surprise,\nThe monarch and Jocundo are confused;\nNor even to have heard a case surmise\nOf two, that ever thus had been abused:\nThen laughed so, that they sate with winking eyes,\nAnd open mouth, and lungs which breath refused;\nAnd, wearied with the mirth her tale had bred,\nFell backwards, both, exhausted on the bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When they had laughed so loud a laugh, the dew\nStood in their eyes, and each with aching breast\nRemained, the pair exclaimed: `What shall we do\nIn order not to be a woman's jest?\nSince we, with all our heed, between us two,\nCould not preserve the one by us possest,\nA husband, furnished with more eyes than hair,\nPerforce must be betrayed with all his care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `A thousand, beauteous all, have we found kind,\nNor one of those so many has stood fast.\nIf tried, all women we by proof should find\nLike these; but be the experiment our last.\nThen we may deem our own not worse inclined\nThan are the wives of others, and as chaste:\nAnd, if like others we our own discern,\nI hold it best that we to them return.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When they have come to this resolve, they, through\nFlammetta, call the youth into their bower;\nAnd with the girl her leman, in the view\nOf many, gift, and add a fitting dower.\nThey mount, and to the east their way pursue,\nAccustomed westward hitherto to scower;\nTo their deserted wives again repair,\nNor of their after deeds take farther care.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here paused mine host; to whom on every side\nHis audience had with careful heed attended.\nRodomont listened, nor a word replied,\nUntil the landlord's story was suspended.\nThen — \"Fully I believe,\" that paynim cried,\n\"The tale of women's frauds would ne'er be ended;\nNor could that man in any volume note\nThe thousandth part, who would their treasons quote.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of sounder judgement, 'mid that company,\nThere was an elder, one more wise and bold;\nThat undefended so the sex to see,\nWas inly wroth, and could no longer hold:\nTo the relater of that history\nHe turned; and, \"Many things we have been told\"\n(Exclaimed that ancient \"wherein truth is none, ) \n\nAnd of such matters is thy fable one."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Him I believe not, that told this truth to you,\nThough in all else he gospel-truths exprest;\nAs less by his experience, than untrue\nConceit respecting women prepossest.\nThe malice which he bears to one or two,\nMakes him unjustly hate and blame the rest.\nBut you shall hear him, if his wrath o'erblow,\nYet greater praise than blame on these bestow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And he a larger field for speaking well\nWill find, than blaming womankind withal;\nAnd of a hundred worthy fame may tell,\nFor one whose evil deeds for censure call.\nHe should exalt the many that excel,\nCulled from the multitude, not rail at all,\nIf otherwise your friend Valerio said,\nHe was by wrath, and not by reason, led.\n\nLXXIX - LXXXIII\n(Stanzas LXXIX - LXXXIII untranslated by Rose)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So reasoning, that just elder and sincere,\nWith ready instances, supports his creed;\nShowing there many women are who ne'er\nSinned against chastity, in word or deed:\nBut him with impious visage and severe\nThe paynim scared, ill pleased the truth to read.\nSo that, through fear, he further speech forbore,\nBut changed not therefore aught his former lore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Having stopt further question in this wise,\nThe paynim monarch from the table rose:\nThen lays him on his bed, till from the skies\nThe dusky shades depart, and morning glows:\nBut spends a larger part of night in sighs\nAt his liege-lady's sin, than in repose.\nRodomont thence departs at dawn of day,\nResolved by water to pursue his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For with such care for his good horse's plight,\nAs is becoming a good cavalier,\nThe courser fair and good, made his in spite\nOf young Rogero and Circassia's peer;\nSeeing he, for two days, that horse's might\nHad taxed too hardly in his long career,\n— As well he for his ease embarked the steed,\nAs to pursue his way with better speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He straight makes launch the vessel from the marge,\nAnd bids put forth the oars from either side:\nNor big nor deeply laden, she, at large,\nDescends the Saone, transported by the tide.\nCare never quits him, though the shifting barge\nThe king ascend, or nimble horse bestride:\nThis he encounters aye on prow or poop,\nAnd bears behind him on his courser's croup;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rather within his head or heart always\nCare sits; whence every comfort is o'erthrown:\nNo remedy the wretched man surveys,\nIn that his enemies are in the town.\nFrom others hope is none; since they who raise\nThis fearful war against him, are his own:\nVext by that cruel one, aye night and day,\nWhom he might hope to find his natural stay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont navigates the day and night\nEnsuing, aye by heavy thoughts opprest;\nNor can he ever banish the despite,\nSuffered from King and Lady, from his breast.\nThe self-same grief sate heavy on his sprite\nAboard the bark, as when his steed he prest.\nSuch fire was not by water to be drowned,\nNor he his nature changed by changing ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the sick man who with a fever grows,\nAnd, weak and weary, shifts his place in vain,\nWhether he right or left himself bestows,\nAnd hopes in turning some relief to gain,\nFinds neither on this side nor that repose,\nBut everywhere encounters equal pain;\nThe pagan monarch so found small relief,\nBy land or water, for his secret grief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont brooked no more aboard to stay,\nBut bade them land him, and by Lyons hied;\nBy Vienne and Valence next took his way,\nAnd the rich bridge in Avignon descried.\nFor these and more, which 'twixt the river lay\nAnd Celtiberian hills upon that side,\n(Theirs, from the day they conquered the champaigne)\nObeyed the kings of Afric and of Spain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To pass to Afric straight, the cavalier\nKept to the right, towards Acquamorta's shore,\nAnd lighted on a stream and hamlet, dear\nTo Ceres and to Bacchus, which that Moor\nFound quitted by the peasants, in their fear,\nAs often by the soldier harried sore.\nThe beach upon one side broad ocean laved,\nAnd on the other yellow harvests waved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here, newly built upon a hillock's crest,\nA little church the Saracen espied;\nAbandoned by its priesthood, like the rest,\nFor war was flaming upon every side.\nRodomont of this place himself possest;\nWhich, from its site, as well as lying wide\nOf fields, from whence he tidings loathed to hear,\nSo pleased him, he for it renounced Argier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He changed his scheme of seeking Afric's land,\n(So this fair spot seemed fit for his behoof!)\nAnd here housed carriages, and steed, and band,\nTogether with himself, beneath one roof,\nAt few leagues' distance, did Montpelier stand,\nAnd other wealthy towns, not far aloof.\nThe village was upon a river's side,\nSo that its every need might be supplied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here standing, full of thought, upon a day,\n(Such was his common wont the paynim spied, ) \n\nAdvancing by a narrow path, which lay\nThrough a green meadow, from the adverse side,\nA lovely damsel, that upon her way\nWas by a bearded monk accompanied;\nAnd these behind them led a lusty steed,\nWho bore a burden, trapt with sable weed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who that attendant monk and damsel were,\nAnd what that burden, will to you be clear,\nRemembering Isabella is the fair,\nCharged with the corse of her Zerbino dear:\nI left her, where from Provence, in the care\nOf that good sire, she bowned herself to steer,\nBy whom persuaded, had the lady given\nThe remnant of her virtuous life to heaven."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Although in her pale face and troubled guise,\nThe sorrow of that dame is manifest,\nAlthough two fountains are her streaming eyes,\nAnd sobs aye issue from her burning breast,\nAnd more beside of suffering testifies,\nWith what a load of grief she is opprest,\nYet, in her faded cheek such beauties meet,\nLove and the Graces there might fix their seat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as he of Sarza saw appear\nThe beauteous dame, he laid the thought aside\nOf hatred to that gentle race and dear,\nBy whom alone the world is glorified;\nAnd best by Isabel the cavalier\nBelieved his former love would be supplied,\nAnd one love by another be effaced,\nAs bolt by bolt in timber is displaced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her with the kindest mien and mildest tone\nThat he could fashion, met the Sarzan knight;\nTo whom the dame her every thought made known;\nAnd said, when she was questioned of her plight,\nShe would with holy works — this world forgone —\nSeek favour in her Heavenly Father's sight.\nLoud laughed that godless paynim at the thought,\nWho every faith and worship held at nought;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And said that she from reason wandered wide,\nAnd termed her project sudden and unsound;\nNor deemed her less to blame than those who hide,\nThrough greediness, their treasure under ground,\nAnd keep it from the use of all beside,\nThough hence no profit to themselves redound.\nRightly were prisoned lion, snake, and bear,\nBut ill whate'er is innocent and fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The monk, that to this talk has lent an ear,\nPrompt with advice that mournful dame to stay,\nAnd lest she quit her course, prepared to steer\nHis bark, like practised pilot, on her way,\nA sumptuous table, rich in spiritual cheer,\nHad speedily bestirred him to array;\nBut, born with evil taste, that paynim rude\nNo sooner tasted, than he loathed, the food."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And having interrupted him in vain,\nNor having power to make him stint his lore,\nThat paynim, stirred to fury, broke the rein\nOf patience, and assailed the preacher hoar.\nBut haply wearisome might seem the strain,\nIf I upon this theme dilated more:\nSo here I close, nor words will idly spend,\nAdmonished by that ancient's evil end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 29"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Isabel makes the paynim take her head,\nRather than he his wicked will should gain;\nWho, having his unhappy error read,\nSeeks to appease his wounded spirit in vain.\nHe builds a bridge, and strips those thither led;\nBut falls from it with Roland the insane;\nWho thence, of him regardless, endlong speeds,\nAnd by the road achieves prodigious deeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "O feeble and unstable minds of men!\nHow quickly our intentions fluctuate!\nAll thoughts we lightly change, but mostly when\nThese from some lover's quarrel take their date.\nBut now, so wroth I saw that Saracen\nWith woman, so outrageous in his hate,\nI weened not only he would ill assuage,\nBut never more would calm, his amorous rage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That which he rashly uttered to your blame,\nYe gentle dames, does so my spirit grieve,\nTill I his error teach him, to his shame,\nHe shall no quarter at my hands receive;\nSo him with pen and page will I proclaim,\nThat, whosoever reads me, shall believe\nHe had better held — aye, better bit, his tongue,\nThan ever have your sex with slander stung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But that in this the witless infidel\nSpake as a fool, the event demonstrates clear:\nEven now, with dagger drawn, that paynim fell\nIn fury on all women whomsoe'er.\nNext him so touched one look of Isabel,\nShe quickly made his fickle purpose veer;\nFor her, scarce seen, and to that warrior strange,\nHe would his Doralice already change;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, as new love the king did heat and goad,\nHe moved some arguments of small avail,\nTo shake her stedfast spirit, which abode\nWholly with God; but he, her shield and mail,\nThat hermit, lest she from the better road\nShould wander, and her chaste intention fail,\nWith stronger arguments with him contended,\nAnd still, as best he could, the dame defended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king, who long had taxed himself to bear\nThe monk's bold sermon to his sore displeasure,\nAnd vainly bade him to his cell repair\nAnew, without that damsel, at his leisure,\nYet seeing he would still his patience dare,\nNor peace with him would keep, nor any measure,\nUpon that preacher's chin his right-hand laid,\nAnd whatsoe'er he grasped, as rudely flayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And (so his fury waxed that, as it were ) \n\nWith tongs, he griped his neck, and after he\nHad whirled him once or twice about in air,\nDismist him form his hand towards the sea.\nI say not — know not, what befel him there:\nMany the rumours are, and disagree.\nOne says he burst upon a rock's rude bed,\nAnd lay one shapeless jelly, heels and head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He fell into the sea, by one is said,\nDistant three miles and more; and, in that sound,\nHe having prayer, and Ave vainly made,\nBecause he knew not how to swim, was drowned.\nOthers report a Saint bestowed his aid,\nAnd dragged him with a visible hand aground.\nWhichever be the reading of this mystery,\nOf him I speak no further in mine history."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Cruel King Rodomont, when from his side\nHe had removed the prating eremite,\nWith visage less disturbed, again applied\nTo that sad lady, heartless with affright;\nAnd, in the language used by lovers, cried,\nShe was his very heart, his life, his light,\nShe was his comfort, and his dearest hope;\nWith all such words as have that common scope."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And now, so temperate showed that infidel,\n'Twould seem that he no violence designed,\nThe gentle semblance of fair Isabel,\nEnamoured him, so tamed his haughty mind;\nAnd, though he might that goodly kernel shell,\nThe paynim would not pass beyond the rhind,\nWho that its favour would be lost, believed,\nUnless 'twere as a gift from her received;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And by degrees so thought to mould the dame\nTo his desires.  She in that lone retreat\nAnd savage, open to his evil aim,\nAnd like a mouse, beneath Grimalkin's feet,\nHad liefer found herself i' the midst of flame;\nAnd ever on one thought her fancy beat:\nIf any mode, if any way, remained\nTo scape that wilful man, untouched, unstained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sad Isabella in her mind is bent\nTo slay herself with her own hand, before\nThat fell barbarian compass his intent;\nAnd be the means to make her wrong so sore\nThat cavalier, by cruel Fortune spent,\nWithin her loving arms, to whom she swore\nWith mind to him devoted, his to be,\nVowing to Heaven perpetual chastity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She sees that paynim monarch's passion blind\nIncreasing still, nor what to do she knows;\nWell knows what foul intention is behind,\nWhich she is all too feeble to oppose:\nYet moving many matters in her mind,\nFinds out at last a refuge for her woes,\nAnd means to save her chastity from shame,\n(How I shall say with clear and lasting fame. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She cried unto that paynim, foul to see,\nAlready threatening her with word and act,\nAnd now devoid of all that courtesy,\nWhich he in the beginning did enact,\n\"If thou mine honour wilt ensure to me,\nBeyond suspicion, I, upon this pact,\nWill upon thee bestow what shall o'erpay,\nBy much, that honour thou wouldst take away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For pleasure, which endures so brief a space,\nWherewith this ample world does so o'errun,\nReject not lightly a perpetual grace,\nA real joy, to be postponed to none.\nOf women everywhere of pleasing face\nA hundred and a thousand may be won;\nBut none beside me, or few others, live\nWho can bestow the boon which I can give."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I know, and on my way a herb did view,\nAnd nearly know where I on this could light,\nWhich, being boiled with ivy and with rue,\nOver a fire with wood of cypress dight,\nAnd squeezed, when taken from the caldron, through\nInnocent hands, affords a juice of might,\nWherewith whoever thrice his body laves,\nDestructive steel or fire securely braves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If thrice therewith he bathe himself, I say,\nHis flesh no weapon for a month shall score:\nHe once a month must to his body lay\nMine unction, for its virtue lasts not more:\nThis liquor can I make, and will to-day,\nAnd thou to-day shalt also prove my lore:\nAnd well, I trust, thou shalt more grateful be,\nThan were all Europe won to-day by thee."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In guerdon for this present, I request\nThat thou to me upon thy faith wilt swear,\nThou never wilt my chastity molest\nIn word or deed.\"  So spake that damsel fair;\nAnd Rodomont who heard, again represt\nHis evil will: for so he longed to bear\nA charmed life, that readily he more\nThan Isabel of him demanded swore;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And will maintain his promise, till the fact\nVouched of that wondrous water shall appear;\nAnd force himself, meanwhile, to do no act,\nTo show no sign of violence; but the peer\nResolves he will not after keep the pact,\nAs one who holds not God or saint in fear;\nAnd to that king, regardless of his oath,\nAll lying Afric yields in breach of troth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Argier's perfidious king to Isabel\nMore than a thousand times assurance swore,\nIn case that water rendered him what fell\nAchilles and what Cygnus were of yore.\nShe, aye by beetling cliff and darksome dell,\nAway from city and from farm, a store\nOf herbs collected, nor this while e'er\nAbandoned by the paynim cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When herbs enow by them in many a beat,\nWith or without their roots, collected were,\nAt a late hour, the twain to their retreat\nBetook them; and, throughout night's remnant, there,\nThat paragon of continence did heat\nWhat simples she had culled, with mickle care,\nWhile to those mysteries and her every deed\nThe pagan, present still, gave curious heed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who, wearing out the weary night in sport,\n— He and those followers that with him remained —\nHad suffered thirst in such a grievous sort,\nFrom the fierce fire in that small cave contained,\nThat drinking round, in measure full or short,\nOf Graecian wine two barrels had they drained;\nA booty which those squires who served the Moor,\nFrom travellers seized a day or two before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Argier's warlike king, unused to wine,\n(Cursed, and forbidden by his law, esteemed)\nThe liquor, tasted once, appeared divine,\nSweeter than nectar or than manna seemed:\nHe, quaffing largely, now of Ishmael's line\nThe sober use deserving censure deemed.\nSo fast their cups with that good wine they fill,\nEach reveller's head is whirling like a mill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile that lady from the fire does lift\nThe pot, wherein she cooked those herbs, and cries\nTo Rodomont: \"In proof I not adrift\nHave launched the words I spake, in random guise,\n— By that, which can the truth form falsehood sift,\nExperience, which can make the foolish wise,\nEven now the thing shall to thyself be shown,\nNot on another's body, but my own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I first will trial make\" (that lady said)\n\"Of this choice liquor with rare virtue blest;\nLest haply thou shouldst harbour any dread\nThat mortal poison form these herbs be prest.\nWith this will I anoint myself, from head\nDownwards below the naked neck and breast.\nThen prove on me thy faulchion and thine arm,\nAnd prove if one can smite, the other harm.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She washed, as said, and gladly did decline\nHer neck to that unthinking pagan's brand;\nUnthinking, and perhaps o'ercome by wine,\nWhich neither helm, nor mail, nor shield withstand,\nThat brutish man believed her, and, in sign\nOf faith, so struck with cruel steel and hand,\nThat her fair head, erewhile Love's place of rest,\nHe severed from the snowy neck and breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This made three bounds, and thence in accents clear\nWas heard a voice which spake Zerbino's name,\nTo follow whom, escaping Sarza's peer,\nSo rare a way was taken by the dame.\nSpirit!  which nobly didst esteem more dear\nThy plighted faith, and chaste and holy name,\n(Things hardly known, and foreign to our time)\nThan thine own life and thine own blooming prime!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Depart in peace, O spirit blest and fair!\n— So had my verses power!  as evermore\nI would assay, with all that happy care,\nWhich so adorns and points poetic lore!\nAnd, as renowned should be thy story rare,\nThousands and thousands of long years and more!\n— Depart in peace to radiant realms above,\nAnd leave to earth the example of thy love!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His eyes from heaven did the Creator bend,\nAt the stupendous and unequalled feat,\nAnd said: \"I thee above that dame commend.\nWhose death drove Tarquin from his royal seat;\nAnd I to register a law intend,\n'Mid those which ages change not as they fleet,\nWhich — I attest the inviolable river —\nUnchanged through future times, shall last for ever."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I will that all, in every future age,\nWho bear thy name, be blest with genius high;\nBe courteous, gentle, beautiful, and sage,\nAnd to the real pitch of honour fly.\nThat to their glory the historic page\nThey may with worthy argument supply;\nSo that for aye Parnassus' hill and well\nShall ring with Isabel and Isabel.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So spake the Sire; and cleared the ambient air,\nAnd hushed beyond its wont the heaving main.\nTo the third heaven her chaste soul made repair,\nAnd in Zerbino's arms was locked again.\nOn earth, with shame and sorrow for his share,\nThat second Breuse sans pity did remain;\nWho, when digested was the maddening bowl,\nLamented sore his error, sad at soul."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That placated, or in some content,\nThe sainted soul of Isabel might be;\nThat, if to death that damsel he had shent,\nHe might at least revive her memory,\nHe, as a means to compass his intent,\nWould turn into a tomb that church, where he\nInhabited, and where she buried lies;\nTo you shall be related in what wise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In all parts round about this chosen site,\nFor love or fear, he master-masons found;\nAnd, making full six thousand men unite,\nStript of their heavy stones the mountains round,\nAnd raised a fabric ninety yards in height,\nFrom its extremest summit to the ground;\nAnd he within its walls the church enclosed;\nWherein entombed the lovers twain reposed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This nearly imitates that pile beside\nOld Tyber's stream, by Adrian built; and nigh\nThe sepulchre, will he a tower provide,\nWherein he purposes some time to lie.\nA narrow bridge, and only two yards wide,\nHe flung across the stream which rolled fast by.\nLong, but so scanty is that bridge, with pain\nThe narrow pass two coursers can contain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two coursers, that abreast have thither made,\nOr else, encountering, on that causeway meet:\nNor any where was ledge or barricade,\nTo stay the horses's fall, who lost his feet.\nHe wills that bridge's toll be dearly paid\nBy Christian or by Moor, who pass his seat;\nFor with a thousand trophies, arms, and vest,\nThat damsel's tomb is destined to be drest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within ten days, or shorter time, was placed\nThe bridge, whose arch across the stream was dight;\nBut not that pile and tower with equal haste\nWere so conducted to their destined height.\nYet was the last so high, a sentry paced\nIts top, who, whensoever any knight\nApproached the bridge, was wont his lord to warn,\nSounding a signal on his bugle-horn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whereat he armed, and issued for the stower,\nNow upon one and now the other side:\nFor when a warrior pricked towards the tower,\nHim from the adverse bank that king defied:\nThe bridge affords the field their steeds must scour;\nAnd, should one but a little swerve aside,\n(Peril unparalleled! the horse will go ) \n\nInto the deep and dangerous stream below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The pagan had imagined, as a pain,\nThat, risking oft to tumble in the course,\nHead-first into that stream, where he must drain\nHuge draughts of water in his fall, parforce,\nHe would assoil and cleanse him from that stain,\nWhereof excess in wine had been the source;\nAs if what ill wine prompts to do or say,\nWater, as well as wine, could wash away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Soon thitherward flocked many a cavalier;\nSome who pursued the beaten road and plain;\nSince for way-faring men, who southward steer,\nNo straighter lay for Italy or Spain:\nTheir courage and their honour, held more dear\nThan life, excited others of the train;\nAnd all, where they had hoped the meed of strife,\nHad lost their arms, and many arms and life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If those he conquers are of pagan strain,\nHe is content to take their arms and vest:\nAnd of those first arrived the titles plain\nAre written, and their arms suspended rest.\nBut he in prison pens the christened train,\n('Twould seem to be to Argier's realm addrest. ) \n\nNot yet was brought that building to a head\nWhen thitherward the crazed Orlando sped."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It chanced Orlando, in his furious mood,\nCame thither where that foaming river ran;\nWhere Rodomont beside the mighty flood\nWas hurrying on his work; nor yet were done\nThe tower and tomb, the bridge, scarce finished, stood:\nHere — save his casque was open — Ulien's son\nSteeled cap-a-pee, stood ready armed for fight,\nWhen to the bridge approached Anglantes' knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando running thus his wild career,\nThe barrier tops, and o'er the bridge would fly,\nBut sullen Rodomont, with troubled cheer,\nAfoot, as he that tower is standing nigh,\nFor he disdains to brandish sword or spear,\nShouts to him from afar with threatening cry,\n\"Halt!  thou intrusive churl and indiscreet,\nRash, meddling, saucy villain, stay thy feet!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Only for lord and cavalier was made,\nAnd not for thee, dull slave, that bridge was meant.\"\nTo this no heed insane Orlando paid,\nBut, fixt upon his purpose, forward went.\n\"This madman must I school,\" the paynim said,\nAnd was approaching with the fell intent\nHim into that deep river to dispatch,\nNor deeming in such foe to find his match."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while, a gentle damsel sought the place\nThat towards that bridge across the river rode,\nRichly arraid and beautiful of face,\nWho sage reserve in her demeanor showed.\n'Tis she that, of her Brandimart in chase,\n(If you remember, sir, through every road ) \n\nAnd place her lover seeks in anxious wise,\nExcepting Paris, where the warrior lies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Flordelice that bridge and tower was near,\n(So was by name the wandering damsel hight)\nGrappling with Roland stood the Sarzan peer,\nAnd would into that river pitch the knight.\nShe, conversant with Brava's cavalier,\nThe miserable county knew aright;\nAnd mighty marvel in that dame it raised\nTo see him rove, a naked man and crazed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She stopt, the issue of that strife to know,\nWherein those two so puissant warriors vied.\nHis opposite by might and main to throw,\nInto the stream each doughty champion tried.\n\"How can a fool such mighty prowess show?\"\nBetween his teeth, the furious paynim cried.\nAnd, shifting here and there, was seen to strain,\nBrimfull of pride, and anger, and disdain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This hand and now that other he puts out,\nTo take new hold, where he his vantage spies;\nNow within Roland's legs, and now without,\nLocks his right foot or left, in skilful wise;\nAnd thus resembles, in that wrestling bout,\nThe stupid bear, who in his fury tries\nThe tree, from whence he tumbled, to o'erthrow;\nDeeming it sole occasion of his woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Roland, whose better wit was lost withal,\nI know no where, and who used force alone;\nThat utmost force, to which this earthly ball\nHaply affords few paragons, or none,\nLet himself backwards in that struggle fall,\nEmbracing as he stood with Ulien's son.\nTogether in the foaming stream they sank;\nHigh flashed the wave, and groaned the echoing bank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Quickly the stream asunder bore the pair.\nRoland was naked, and like fish could swim,\nHere shot his feet, his arms extended there,\nAnd gained the bank; nor, when upon the brim,\nHalted to mark if his adventure were\nAchieved with praise or shame: in evil trim,\nThe pagan, by his arms impeded sore,\nWith heavier pain and trouble, toiled ashore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Along the bridge which spanned that foaming tide\nDid Flordelice meantime securely pace,\nAnd, having vainly sought on every side\nBrandimart's bearing, since nor iron case\nNor vest of his she anywhere espied,\nShe hoped to find the knight in other place.\nBut here return we of the count to tell,\nWho left behind him stream, bridge tower, and cell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twere phrensy of his every frantic feat\nTo promise the relation, one by one;\nSo many and many, — should I these repeat,\nI know not when my story would be done.\nYet some of his notorious deeds, and meet\nFor mention in my song, will I make known:\nNor will I not that wondrous one recount,\nNear Thoulouse, on the Pyrenaean Mount."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much country had been traversed by the knight,\nUrged by the furious rage which him misguides:\nAt last he reached the hill whose boundary height\nArragonese and neighbouring Frank divides.\nThither directing aye his course outright,\nWhere the descending sun his visage hides,\nHe reached a path upon the rugged steep,\nWhich overhung a valley dark and deep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here he by chance encountered in mid road\nTwo youths, that wood men were, and drove before\nAn ass along that pathway, with a load\nOf logs; they, marking well what scanty store\nOf brain in poor Orlando's head was stowed,\nCalled to the approaching knight, and threatened sore;\nBidding him stand aside, or else go back,\nNor to their hindrance block the common track."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To this address Orlando answered nought,\nSave that his foot he to their beast applied,\nSmote in mid-breast, which, with that vigour fraught,\n— That force exceeding every force beside —\nTost him so hight, that the beholders thought\nIt was a bird in air which they descried.\nThe ass upon a mountain-summit fell,\nWhich rose above a mile beyond that dell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon those youths next sprang the furious knight.\nWith better luck than wit, one woodman shear\nFrom that tall cliff, twice thirty yards in height,\nCast himself headlong downward in his fear:\nHim a moist patch of brambles, in his flight,\nReceived; and, amid grass and bushes, here,\nFrom other mischief safe, the stripling lit,\nAnd for some scratches in his face was quit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That other to a jutting fragment clung,\nWho so to gain the higher steep would strive;\nBecause he hopes, if once those crags among,\nTo keep him from that fool he may contrive;\nBut by the feet Orlando, ere he sprung,\nSeized him, who will not leave the wretch alive;\nAnd stretching them as wide as he could strain,\nSo stretched his arms, he rent his prey in twain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even in such mode as often we descry\nFalconer by heron or by puller do;\nWhose entrails he plucks out, to satisfy\nMerlin or falcon that the game pursue.\nHow happy was that other not to die!\nWho risqued his neck in that deep bottom, who\nRehearsed the tale so often, Turpin heard,\nAnd handed down to us the wondrous word."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These and more marvels does the count, who bends\nHis steps across that mountain to the plain;\nAnd, seeking long a path, at length descends\nTowards the south, upon the land of Spain.\nHis way along the beach he after wends,\nNear Arragon, beside the rumbling main,\nAnd, ever prompted by his phrensy rank,\nWill make himself a dwelling on the bank,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where he somedeal may shun the noontide ray,\nWith dry and powdery sea-sand covered o'er;\nAnd here, while so employed, upon their way\nArrives Angelica with her Medore,\nWho, as you have been told in former lay,\nHad from the hills descended on that shore.\nWithin a yard or less approached the fair,\nEre yet she of his presence was aware."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So different from himself was he to sight,\nNought of Orlando she in him surveyed:\nFor, from the time that rage possest his sprite,\nHe had gone naked forth in sun and shade.\nHad he been born on hot Syene's site,\nOr sands where worship is to Ammon paid,\nOr nigh those hills, whence Nile's full waters spin,\nOrlando had not borne a dingier skin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nigh buried in their sockets are his eyes,\nSpare in his visage, and as dry as bone:\nDishevelled is his hair in woeful wise,\nWith frightful beard his cheek is overgrown:\nNo sooner is he seen, than backward flies\nAngelica, who, trembling sore, is flown:\nShe shrieking loud, all trembling and dismaid,\nBetakes her to her youthful guide for aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When crazed Orlando was of her aware,\nTo seize the damsel he upsprang in haste;\nSo pleased the wretched count her visage fair,\nSo quickly was his mood inflamed: effaced\nIn him all ancient recollections are,\nHow she by him was whilom served and graced.\nBehind her speech the count and hunts that dame,\nAs questing dog pursues the sylvan game."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The youth, that sees him chase his love who fled,\nHis courser spurs, and in pursuit is gone.\nWith naked faulchion after him he sped,\nAnd cut and thrust at Roland as he run.\nHe from his shoulders hoped to cleave his head,\nBut found the madman's skin as hard as bone;\nYea, harder far than steel, nor to be harmed;\nSo good Orlando at his birth was charmed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When on his back Orlando felt him beat,\nHe turned, and turning on his youthful foe,\nSmote with clenched fist, and force which nought can meet,\n— Smote on his horse's head, a fearful blow;\nAnd, with skull smashed like glass, that courser fleet\nWas by the madman's furious stroke laid low.\nIn the same breath Orlando turned anew,\nAnd chased the damsel that before him flew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At speed Angelica impelled her mare.\nAnd whipt and spurred her evermore; whom slow\nShe would esteem, albeit that palfrey were\nYet faster than a shaft dismist from bow:\nHer ring she thought upon, and this the fair\nPlaced in her mouth; nor failed its virtue now;\nFor putting it between her lips, like light\nExtinguished by a puff, she past from sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Was it through fear, or was she, while she stript\nThis from her finger, shaken in her seat;\nOr was it rather, that her palfrey tript,\n(For neither this nor that I surely weet)\nAngelica, while 'twixt her lips she slipt\nThe virtuous ring, and hid her visage sweet,\nHer stirrups lost; and, tumbling form the sell,\nReversed upon the sand that lady fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If but two inches short had fallen his prey,\nUpon her would have pounced Orlando near;\nWho would have crushed her in his furious way,\nBut that kind Fortune saved her from the peer.\nLet her by other theft herself purvey\nWith other palfrey, as she did whilere;\nFor never will she have this courser more,\nWho chased by swift Orlando scours the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Doubt not that she another will provide;\nAnd follow we in mad Orlando's rear;\nWhose rage and fury nevermore subside,\nWroth that Angelica should disappear:\nAfter that beast along the sands he hied,\nAye gaining on the mare in this career.\nNow, now he touches her, and lo!  The mane\nHe grasps, and now secures her by the rein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando seizes her with that delight\nThat other man might seize a damsel fair;\nThe bit and bridle he adjusts aright,\nSprings on her back, and o'er the sea-beach bare\nFor many miles impels the palfrey's flight,\nWithout repose or pause, now here, now there:\nNor ever sell or bridle be displaced,\nNor let her grass or heartening forage taste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in this course to o'erleap a ditch he sought,\nHead over heels, she with her rider went:\nNor harmed was he, nor felt that tumble aright;\nBut she, with shoulder slipt, lay foully shent.\nLong how to bear her thence Orlando thought,\nAnd in the end upon his shoulders hent.\nHe from the bottom climbed, thus loaded sore,\nAnd carried her three bow-shots' length and more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next, for he felt that weight too irksome grow,\nHe put her down, to lead her by the rein;\nWho followed him with limping gait and slow,\n\"Come on,\" Orlando cried, and cried in vain;\nAnd, could the palfrey at a gallop go,\nThis ill would satisfy his mood insane.\nThe halter from her head he last unloosed,\nWherewith her hind off-foot the madman noosed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis thus he comforts and drags on that mare,\nThat she may follow with more ease, so led;\nWho whiles despoiled of flesh, and whiles of hair,\nIs scathed by stones which that ill road o'erspread.\nAt length the misused beast, with wear and tear\nOf the rude rocks, and suffering sore, lies dead.\nOrlando nought the slaughtered mare regards,\nNor anywise his headlong course retards."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To drag that palfrey ceased he not, though dead,\nContinuing still his course towards the west,\nAnd all this while sacked hamlet, farm, and stead,\nWhenever he by hunger was distrest;\nAnd aye to glut himself with meat, and bread,\nAnd fruit, he every one by force opprest.\nOne by his hand was slain, one foully shent;\nSeldom he stopt, and ever onward went."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As much, or little less, would do the knight\nBy his own love, did not that damsel hide;\nBecause the wretch discerns not black from white,\nAnd harms where he would help.  A curse betide\nThe wonder-working ring, and eke the wight\nWho gave it to that lady, full or pride!\nSince Roland, but for this, would venge the scorn\nHe and a thousand more from her had borne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Would that of her Orlando were possest,\nAnd of all women that are above ground!\nFor one and all are ingrates at the best,\nNor is in all an ounce of goodness found.\nBut it is meet I let my hearer rest\nEre my strained chords return a faltering sound,\nAnd that he may less tedious deem the rhyme,\nDefer my story till another time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 30"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Great feats achieve Orlando by the way.\nThe Tartar king is by Rogero slain:\nFor whom fair Bradamant, his spouse, does stay,\nBut Fate forbade, that he who wounded lay\nTo her his plighted promise should maintain.\nHe after boldly with the brethren made,\nTheir lord Rinaldo in his need to aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Reason, giving way to heat of blood,\nHerself from hasty choler ill defends,\nAnd, hurried on by blind and furious mood,\nWe with the tongue or hand molest our friends,\nThough the offence is, after, wept and rued,\nThe penance which we pay is poor amends.\nAlas!  I sorrow and lament in vain\nFor what I said in other angry strain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But like sick man am I, who, sore bested,\nSuffering with patience many and many a day,\nWhen against pain he can no more make head,\nYields to his rage, and curses; pain give way,\nAnd with it the impetuous wrath is fled,\nWhich moved his ready tongue such ill to say;\nAnd he is left his willful rage to rue,\nBut cannot that which he has done undo."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Well hope I, from your sovereign courtesy,\nYour pardon, since I crave it, ladies bright;\nYou will excuse, if moved by madness, I\nRave in my passion; let your censure light\nOn foe, who treats me so despiteously,\nI could not be reduced to worser plight;\nWho prompts what sore repents me: Heaven above\nKnows how she wrongs me, knows how well I love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No less beside myself than Brava's peer\nAnd I, nor less my pardon should obtain;\nHe, who by mead or mountain, far or near,\nHad scowered large portion of the land of Spain,\nDragging that jennet in his wild career,\nDead as she was, behind him by the rein;\nBut, where a river joined the sea, parforce\nAbandoned on the bank her mangled corse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And he, who could like any otter swim,\nLeapt in and rose upon the further side.\nBehold!  a mounted shepherd at the brim\nArrived, his horse to water in the tide;\nNor when he saw Orlando coming, him\nEschewed, whom naked and alone he spied.\n— \"My jennet for thy hackney were I fain\nTo barter,\" cried the madman to the swain:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her will I show thee, if thou wilt; who dead\nUpon the river's other margin fell;\nAt leisure may'st thou have her cured,\" (he said)\n\"And of no other fault have I to tell.\nGive me thy hackney, with some boot instead:\nPrythee, dismount thee, for he likes me well.\"\nThe peasant, laughing, answered not a word,\nBut left the fool and pricked towards the ford."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hearest thou not?  hola!  I want thy steed,\"\n(Cried Roland and advanced with wrathful cheer. ) \n\nA solid staff and knotted, for his need,\nThat shepherd had, wherewith he smote the peer;\nWhose violence and ire all bounds exceed,\nWho seems withal to wax more fierce than e'er:\nA cuff he levels at that rustic's head,\nAnd splits the solid bone, and lays him dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then leaping on his horse, by different way\nThe country scowers, to make more spoil and wrack:\nThat palfrey never more tastes corn or hay;\nSo that few days exhaust the famished hack.\nBut not afoot does fierce Orlando stray,\nWho will not, while he lives, conveyance lack.\nAs many as he finds, so many steeds\n— Their masters slain — he presses for his needs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He came at last to Malaga, and here\nDid mightier scathe than he had done elsewhere;\nFor now — besides that the infuriate peer\nOf all its people left the country bare,\nNor (such the ravage could another year ) \n\nThe desperate havoc of the fool repair —\nSo many houses burnt he, or cast down,\nSacked was a third of that unhappy town."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Departing thence, insane Orlando flees\nTo Zizera, a seaward town, whose site\nIs in Gibraltar's bay, or (if you please)\nSay Gibletar's; for either way 'tis hight;\nHere, loosening from the land, a boat he sees\nFilled with a party, and for pleasure dight:\nWhich, for their solace, to the morning gale,\nUpon that summer sea, had spread their sail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hoah!  the boat!  put back!\" the count 'gan cry,\nWho was in mind to go aboard their barge:\nBut vainly on their ears his clamours die:\nFor of such freight none willingly take charge.\nAs swiftly as a swallow cleaves the sky,\nFurrowing the foamy wave the boat goes large.\nOrlando urges on, with straightening knee,\nAnd whip and spur, his horse towards the sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He plunged into the waves, at last, parforce;\nFor vainly would he shun the waters green.\nBathed are knees, paunch, and croup, till of that horse\nScarcely the head above the wave is seen:\nLet him not hope to measure back his course,\nWhile smitten with the whip his ears between.\nWoe worth him!  he must founder by the way,\nOr into Africa his load convey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor poops nor prows does Roland more descry,\nFor all have launched their shallops, which are wide\nOf that dry shore; while from his level eye\nTheir hulls the tall and shifting surges hide.\nHe spurs his horse amid the billows high,\nWholly resolved to reach the farther side.\nThe courser ends his swim and life in fine,\nDrained of his strength, and drenched brimfull of brine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He sinks, and would with him draw down his load;\nBut that himself the madman's arms upbear:\nWith sinewy arms and either palm he rowed,\nAnd puffed and blew the brine before; the air\nBreathed softly, and the water gently flowed;\nAnd well was needed weather more than fair:\nFor if the waters yet a little rise,\nWhelmed by the waxing tide Orlando dies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Fortune, that of madmen is the guide,\nHim from the water drew near Ceuta's shore,\nUpon that beach, and of those walls as wide\nAs twice an archer's hand could shoot at score.\nFor many days along the bank he hied,\nAt hazard, ever westward hurrying sore,\nUntil he came where on the sea-beat strand\nEncamped a host of blacks, a countless band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leave we the paladin at will to stray!\nTo speak of him occasion will come round.\n— Sir, what befel the lady of Catay,\nWho scaped, in time, from him of wit unsound,\nAnd afterwards, upon her homeward way,\nWas with good bark and better weather bound;\nAnd how she made Medoro, India's king;\nPerchance some voice in happier verse may sing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To say so many things I am intent,\nI mean not to pursue the cavalier.\nTo Mandricardo my fair argument\nIt now behoves me, in his turn, to veer\nHe happily enjoyed, his rival spent,\nThe beauty, left in Europe without peer,\nSince fair Angelica from hence had wended,\nAnd virtuous Isabel to heaven ascended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Mandricardo, proud that in his right\nHis lady had adjudged the amorous suit,\nEnjoys not her award with full delight;\nSince others with him other points dispute.\nBy young Rogero claimed, that eagle white\nOf one disastrous quarrel is the root;\nAnother moves the king of Sericana\nAgainst the Tartar king, for Durindana."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant and Marsilius strive in vain,\nWith labour sore, this tangle to undo;\nNor only cannot they persuade the twain\nIn peace and concord to unite anew,\nBut cannot make the valiant Child refrain\nFrom claiming Hector's buckler as his due;\nNor yet Gradasso move the sword to lend,\n'Till this, or till that, quarrel have an end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero brooks not that in other fight\nHis shield be braced, nor will Gradasso bear\nThat save against himself the Tartar knight\nShould wield the sword Orlando used to wear\n\"See we, in fine, on whom the chance will light\n(Cries Agramant and further words forbear. ) \n\nHow Fortune rules the matter let us see,\nAnd choose him that of her shall chosen be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And — would ye do what most would me delight,\nAnd be an obligation evermore —\nYou shall by casting lots decide your right:\nPremising, he whose lot is drawn before\nThe other, shall upon two quarrels fight:\nSo he who wins, on his companion's score\nShall win as well as on his own; and who\nLoses the battle lose alike for two."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Between Rogero and Gradasso, we\nDeem there is little difference, rather none;\nAnd wot whichever shall elected be.\nIn arms will make his martial prowess known,\nAs for the rest, let doubtful victory\nDescend on him whom Heaven is pleased to own!\nUpon the vanquished knight no blame shall fall,\nBut we to Fortune will impute it all.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero and Gradasso, at this say\nOf Agramant, stood silent, and agreed,\nThat he whose lot first issued, the assay\nShould undertake for both in listed mead.\nThus in two scrolls, inscribed in the same way,\nTheir names are writ as destined to succeed.\nThese afterwards are cast into an urn,\nWhich much they shake and topsy turvy turn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A seely boy then dipt his hand and drew\nA billet from the vase, and if befel,\nThereon Rogero's name the assistants knew;\n— Gradasso's left behind — I cannot tell\nHow joyed renowned Rogero at the view,\nAnd can as little say what sorrow fell\nUpon Gradasso, on the other side;\nBut he parforce his fortune must abide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gradasso every thought and every deed\nEmploys, Rogero to instruct and aid,\nThat in the strife his champion may succeed;\nAnd teaches every sleight he has assaid:\n— How best to manage sword and shield at need —\n— What strokes are feints, and what with vantage made —\nAnd when he should tempt Fortune, when eschew —\nReminds him, one by one, in long review."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the drawing lots and king's award,\nWhat of the day remained the champions spent\nAs wont, in giving tokens of regard,\nTo this or to that other warrior sent.\nThe people, greedy for the fight, toward\nThe field is gone, and many not content\nWith wending thither ere the dawn of light,\nUpon the place of combat watch all night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The foolish rabble anxiously attends\nThose goodly champions' contest for the prize,\nA crowd which neither sees nor comprehends\nOther than that which is before its eyes.\nBut they who know what boots and what offends,\n— Marsilius and Sobrino, and the wise —\nCensure the fight, and monarch that affords\nA field of combat to those martial lords."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor what a heavy loss he would sustain\n(Cease they to royal Agramant to read)\nWere Mandricardo or Rogero slain;\nA thing by cruel Destiny decreed.\nSince they, to combat against Charlemagne,\nOf one of these alone have greater need\nThan of ten thousand more, amid which crew\nThey scarce would find one champion good and true."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant recognized this truth; but thought\nThat ill his royal word could be repealed;\nYet Mandricardo and the Child besought\nThat they the right, conferred by him, would yield:\nMore; that the question was a thing of nought,\nNor worthy to be tried in martial field;\nAnd prayed them — would they not obey his hest\nAt least somewhile, to let their quarrel rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Five or six months would they the strife delay,\nOr more or less, till Charles defeated were,\nAnd stript of mantle, crown, and royal sway.\nBut each, though he would willingly forbear,\nAnd much desired his sovereign to obey,\nStood out against the Moorish monarch's prayer:\nSince either deemed he would be foully shent\nWho to this treaty first should yield consent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But more than king, than all, who sought in vain\nTo soften Agrican's infuriate son,\nThe beauteous daughter of King Stordilane\nLamented, besought him, woe-begone,\nBesought him he would do what all would fain\nBehold by the relenting warrior done;\n— Lamenting her, as through the cavalier,\nFor ever kept in agony and fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alas!  and what (exclaims she can I find ) \n\nWhich may avail to minister repose,\nIf aye, by this or that desire inclined,\nYou don your harness to affront new foes?\nWhat boots it to restore my harassed mind\nThat I behold one fearful quarrel's close,\nAgainst one champion moved for love of me,\nIf one as fierce already kindled be?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Woe worth me!  I was proud, with little right,\nSo good a king, so stout a cavalier\nFor he should in the fierce and dangerous fight\nPeril his life, who now, I see to clear,\nUpon a ground of strife so passing light,\nWith the same risk prepares to couch the spear.\nYou, more than love for me, to strife impels\nThe natural rage, wherewith your bosom swells."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if the love you force yourself to show,\nBe in good earnest, that which you profess,\nBy this I pray you, by that chastening woe\nWhich does my spirit, does my heart oppress,\nBe not concerned, because the bird of snow\nRogero, pictured on his shield, possess.\nI know not wherefore you should joy or grieve\nThat he the blazoned buckler bear or leave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Much evil may ensue and little gain\nOut of the battle you to wage prepare;\nSmall guerdon will be bought with mickle pain\nIf from Rogero you his eagle bear;\nBut if your fortune shifts on listed plain,\nShe whom you hold not captive by her hair,\nYou cause an evil with such mischief fraught,\nMy heart is broken at the simple thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If of small value life to you appear,\nAnd you esteem a painted bird more high,\nAt least for my life's sake esteem yours dear;\nFor one without the other shall not die.\nWith you to die excites in me no fear;\nWith you, prepared for life or death am I:\nYet would I fain not die so ill content,\nAs I should die if you before me went.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Accompanying words with tears and sighs,\nIn such, or such like speech she him did pray,\nThroughout that livelong night, in piteous wise,\nHoping her lover's anger to allay;\nAnd Mandricardo, sucking from her eyes\nThose sweet tears, glittering in their humid ray,\nAnd that sweet moan, from lips more deeply dyed\nThan crimson rose, himself in tears, replied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alack!  my dearest life!  take thou no dread,\nAlack!  for love of Heaven!  of thing so light:\nFor if (to my sole harm with banners spread, ) \n\nTheir following of the Frank or paynim rite\nKing Agramant and Charles united led,\nThis need not cause you matter for affright.\nWhat poor account you make of me is clear\nIf this one, sole, Rogero breeds such fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And yet should you remember how alone\n(Nor had I scimetar or sword in hand)\nOf knights, with a spear's truncheon overthrown,\nI singly cleared the field, an armed band.\nThough to his shame and sorrow this he own,\nGradasso tells to them who make demand,\nHe was my prisoner in the Syrian tower:\nYet other than Rogero's is his power."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not King Gradasso will the truth deny:\nSacripant knows it and your Isolier:\nI say King Sacripant of Circassy,\nAnd Aquilant, and Gryphon, famous peer;\nWith hundreds — yea and more — from far and nigh\nMade prisoners at that fearful pass whilere,\nBaptized or Infidel; and all by me\nFrom prison on the selfsame day set free."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And even yet they marvel evermore\nAt the great feat which I performed that day;\nGreater than if the squadrons of the Moor\nAnd Frank united I had held at bay;\nAnd shall Rogero, new to martial lore,\nMe, onto to one, with scathe or scorn appay?\nAnd me shall now this young Rogero scare,\nWhen Hector's sword and Hector's arms I wear?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  as I might have won you from my foe,\nWhy did I not for you in arms contend?\nI so had them my valour shown, I know,\nYou would have well foreseen Rogero's end.\nFor heaven's sake dry your tears, nor by such woe\n— An evil omen for my arms — offend;\nAnd learn, 'tis Honour pricks me to the field,\nAnd not an argent bird and blazoned shield.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said he; and with reasons passing good\nTo him that dame replied, with saddest face;\nNor only would have changed his sullen mood,\nBut would have moved a pillar from its place.\nShe would the champion quickly have subdued,\nThough she was gowned, he locked in iron case;\nAnd make him satisfy the Moorish lord,\nIf Agramant spake further of accord;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And had; but that Aurora — on his way\nUshering aye the sun — no sooner stirred,\nThan young Rogero, anxious to display\nThat rightfully he bore Jove's beauteous bird,\nTo cut the quarrel short, and lest delay\nBe further interposed, in act or word,\nWhere round the palisade the people close,\nAppears in armour and his bugle blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When that loud sound is by the Tartar heard,\nWhich the proud warrior to the strife defies,\nNo more of treaty will he hear a word:\nFrom bed upspringing, \"Arms,\" the monarch cries,\nAnd shows a visage with such fury stirred,\nDoralice dares no longer peace advise,\nNor speak of treaty or of truce anew;\nAnd now parforce the battle must ensue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Tartar arms himself in haste; with pain\nThe wonted service of his squires he tarries:\nThis done, he springs upon the steed amain,\nErewhile the champion's who defended Paris;\nAnd him with speed towards the listed plain,\nFixt for that fierce assay, the courser carries.\nEven then the king and barons thither made,\nSo that the strife was little time delaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Put on and laced the shining helmets were,\nAnd given to either champion was the spear:\nQuickly the trumpet's blast was heard in air,\nWhose signal blanched a thousand cheeks with fear.\nLevelled those cavaliers their lances bear,\nSpurring their warlike steeds to the career,\nAnd, in mid champaign, meet with such a shock,\nThat Earth appears to rive and Heaven to rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From this side and from that, the eagle flew,\nWhich Jove in air was wonted to sustain;\nSo hurtled, but with plumes of different hue,\nThose others often on Thessalian plain.\nThe beamy lances, rested by the two,\nWell warranted the warriors' might and main,\nAnd worse than that encounter had withstood:\nSo towers resist the wind, so rocks the flood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As Turpin truly writes, into the sky\nUpwent the splinters, broke in the career;\nFor two or three fell flaming from on high,\nWhich had ascended to the starry sphere.\nThe knights unsheathed their faulchions from the thigh,\nAnd, like those who were little moved by fear,\nFor new encounter wheeled, and, man to man,\nPointing at one another's vizor ran."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They, pointing at the vizors' sight, attacked,\nNor with their faulchions at the steeds took aim,\nEach other to unhorse, unseemly act!\nSince in that quarrel they are nought to blame.\nThose err, nor know the usage, why by pact\nDeem they were bound their horses not to maim:\nWithout pact made, 'twas reckoned a misdeed,\nAnd an eternal blot to smite a steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They level at the vizor, which is double,\nAnd yet resists such mighty blows with pain.\nThe champions evermore their strokes redouble\nFaster than pattering hail, which mars the grain,\nAnd bruises branch and leaf, and stalk and stubble,\nAnd cheats the hopes of the expecting swain.\nTo you is known the force of either brand,\nAnd known the force of either warrior's hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But yet no stroke well worthy of their might\nThose peers have dealt, so cautious are the twain.\nThe Tartar's faulchion was the first to bite,\nBy which was good Rogero well nigh slain.\nBy one of those fell blows which either knight\nSo well could plant, his shield was cleft in twain;\nBeneath, his cuirass opened to the stroke,\nAnd to the quick the cruel weapon broke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The assistants' hearts were frozen at the blow,\nSo did Rogero's danger them appal,\nOn whom the many's favor, well they know,\nAnd wishes rest, if not of one and all.\nAnd then (had Fortune ordered matters so,\nAs the most part desired they should befall)\nTaken had been the Tartar king or slain;\nSo had that blow offended all the train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I think that blow was by some angel stayed,\nTo save Rogero from the mischief near:\nYet at the king (nor answer he delayed)\nHe dealt a stroke more terrible than e'er.\nAs Mandricardo's head he aims his blade,\nBut such the fury of the cavalier,\nAnd such his haste, he less my blame deserves,\nIf slanting from the mark his faulchion swerves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Had Balisarda smote him full, though crowned\nWith Hector's helm, the enchantment had been vain.\nSo reels the Tartar, by that stroke astound,\nHe from the bristle-hand lets go the rein:\nThrice with his head he threats to smite the ground,\nWhile his unguided courser scowers the plain;\nThat Brigliadoro, whom by name you know,\nYet, for his change of master, full of woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Never raged trampled serpent, never so\nRaged wounded lion, as in fell despite\nRaged Mandricardo, rallying from that blow,\nWhich had deprived of sense the astonied knight;\nAnd as his pride and fury waxes, grow\nAs much, yea more, his valour and his might.\nHe at Rogero makes his courser vault,\nWith sword uplifted high for the assault."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Poised in his stirrups stood the Tartar lord,\nAnd aiming at his foeman's casque, believed\nHe with the stroke of his descending sword\nRogero to the bosom should have cleaved;\nBut from that youth, yet quicker in his ward,\nA wound beneath his arm the king received,\nWhich made wide daylight in the stubborn mail,\nThat clothed the better armpit with its scale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero drawing Balisarda back,\nOut sprang the tepid blood of crimson stain;\nHence Mandricardo's arm did vigour lack,\nAnd with less dint descended Durindane:\nYet on the croup the stripling tumbled back,\nClosing his eyelids, through excess of pain;\nAnd memorable aye had been that blow,\nHad a worse helmet clothed the warrior's brow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For this he pauses not, but spurs amain,\nAnd Mandricardo smites in the right side.\nHere little boots the texture of the chain,\nAnd the well wealded metal's temper tried,\nAgainst that sword, which never falls in vain,\nWhich was enchanted to no end beside,\nBut that against it nothing should avail,\nEnchanted corselet or enchanted mail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whate'er that sword takes-in it shears outright,\nAnd in the Tartar's side inflicts a wound:\nHe curses Heaven and raves in such despite,\nLess horribly the boisterous billows sound.\nHe now prepares to put forth all his might:\nThe shield, with argent bird and azure ground,\nHe hurls, with rage transported, from his hand,\nAnd grasps with right and left his trenchant brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Marry,\" (Rogero cried, \"it needs no more ) \n\nTo prove your title to that ensign vain,\nWhich now you cast away, and cleft before;\nNor can you more your right in it maintain.\"\nSo saying, he parforce must prove how sore\nThe danger and the dint of Durindane;\nWhich smites his front, and with such weight withal,\nA mountain lighter than that sword would fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If cleft his vizor through the midst; 'twas well\nThat from the sight diverged the trenchant blade,\nWhich on the saddle's plated pommel fell;\nNor yet its double steel the faulchion stayed:\nIt reached his armour (like soft wax, the shell\nOped, and the skirts wherewith 'twas overlaid)\nAnd trenched upon his thigh a grievous wound;\nSo that 'twas long ere he again waxed sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The spouting blood of either cavalier\nTheir arms had crimsoned in a double drain:\nHence diversly the people guessed, which peer\nWould have the better of the warlike twain:\nBut soon Rogero made the matter clear\nWith that keen sword, so many a champion's bane:\nWith this he at that part in fury past\nWhence Mandricardo had his buckler cast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He the left side of his good cuirass gored,\nAnd found a passage to the heart below;\nWhich a full palm above the flank he bored;\nSo that parforce the Tartar must forego\nHis every title to the famous sword,\nThe blazoned buckler, and its bird of snow,\nAnd yield, together with these seeds of strife,\n— Dearer than sword and shield — his precious life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not unavenged the unhappy monarch dies;\nFor in the very moment he is smit,\nThe sword — for little period his — he plies,\nAnd good Rogero's vizor would have split.\nBut that he stopt the stroke in wary wise,\nAnd broke its force and vigour ere it lit;\nIts force and vigour broke: for he, below\nThe better arm, first smote his Tartar foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Smit was the Child by Mandricardo's hand,\nAt the same moment he that monarch slew:\nHe, albeit thick, divides an iron band\nAnd good steel cap beneath it; inches two,\nLies buried in the head the trenchant brand,\nThe solid bone and sinew severed through.\nAstound Rogero fell, on earth reversed,\nAnd from his head a stream of life-blood burst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero was the first who went to ground,\nAnd so much longer did the king delay,\nNigh every one of those who waited round\nWeened he the prize and vaunt had borne away.\nSo, erred his Doralice, that oft was drowned\nIn tears, and often clad in smiles that day:\nShe thanked her God, with hands to Heaven extended,\nThat in such wise the fearful fight had ended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But when by tokens manifest appear\nThe live man living and the dead man slain,\nThe favourers of those knights, with change of cheer,\nSome weep and some rejoice, an altered train.\nKing, lord, and every worthiest cavalier\nCrowd round Rogero, who has risen with pain.\nHim to embrace and gratulate they wend,\nAnd do him grace and honour without end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Each with Rogero is rejoiced, and feels\nThat which he utters in his heart; among\nThe crowd the Sericane alone conceals\nOther than what he vouches with his tongue.\nHe pleasure in his countenance reveals,\nWith envy at the conquest inly stung;\nAnd — were his destiny or chance to blame —\nCurses whiche'er produced Rogero's name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What of Rogero's favour can be said?\nWhat of caresses, many, true, and kind,\nFrom Agramant?  that not without his aid\nWould have unrolled his ensigns the wind;\nWho had to move from Africk been afraid,\nNor would have trusted in his host combined.\nHe, now King Mandricardo is no more,\nEsteems him the united world before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor to Rogero lean the men alone;\nTo him incline as well the female train,\nWho for the land of France had left their own,\nAmid the troops of Africk or of Spain;\nAnd Doralice, herself, although she moan,\nAnd for her lover, cold and pale, complain,\nSave by the griding curb of shame represt,\nHer voice, perchance, had added to the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say perchance, nor warrant it I dare,\nAlbeit the thing may easily be true;\nFor such his manners, such his merits are,\nSo beauteous is Rogero's form to view,\nShe (from experience we are well aware)\nSo prone to follow whatsoe'er is new,\nThat not to play the widow's lovelorn part,\nShe on Rogero well might set her heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though he did well alive, what could be done\nWith Mandricardo, after he was dead?\n'Tis fitting she provide herself with one\nThat her, by night or day, may bravely stead.\nMeanwhile to young Rogero's succour run\nThe king's physician in his art best read;\nWho, having seen the fruits of that fell strife,\nAlready has ensured Rogero's life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant bids them diligently lay\nThe wounded warrior in his tent, and there\nIs evermore beside him, night and day;\nHim with such love he watches, with such care:\nTo his bed the Tartar's arms and buckler gay,\nSo bade the Moorish king, suspended were;\nSuspended all, save trenchant Durindana,\nRelinquished to the King of Sericana."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With Mandricardo's arms, his other weed\nWas to Rogero given, and given with these\nWas warlike Brigliador, whom on the mead\nOrlando left, distraught with his disease.\nTo Agramant Rogero gave the steed,\nWell knowing how that goodly gift would please.\nNo more of this: parforce my strain returns\nTo her that vainly for Rogero burns."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant's torment have I to recount,\nWhile for the courier damsel she did stay:\nWith tidings of her love to Alban's Mount,\nTo her Hippalca measured back her way:\nShe of Frontino first and Rodomont,\nAnd next of good Rogero had to say;\nHow to the fount anew he had addrest\nHis way, with Richardetto and the rest;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And how the Child, in rescue of the steed,\nHad gone with her to find the paynim rude;\nAnd weened to have chastized his foul misdeed,\nThat from a woman took Frontino good.\nAnd how the youth's design did ill succeed,\nBecause the king had other way pursued.\nThe reason too why to Mount Alban's hold\nRogero had not come, at full she told;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And fully she to Bradamant exprest\nWhat to excuse himself Rogero said:\nShe after drew the letter from her breast,\nWherewith entrusted she had thither sped:\nWith visage which more care than hope confest,\nThe paper Bradamant received and read;\nWhich, but that she expected to have seen\nRogero's self, more welcome would have been."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To find herself with written scroll appaid\nIn good Rogero's place, whom she attends,\nMarred her fair visage; which such fear pourtrayed,\nDespite and sorrow as her bosom rends.\nTen times the page she kisses, while the maid\nAs oft to him who writes her heart commends:\nThe tears alone which trickle from her eyes\nKeep it from kindling at her burning sighs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Four times, nay six, she that epistle read,\nAnd willed moreover that as many more\nThe message by that damsel should be said,\nWho word and letter to Mount Alban bore.\nThis while unceasing tears the lady shed,\nNor, I believe, would ever have given o'er,\nSave by the hope consoled, that she anew\nShould briefly her beloved Rogero view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero's word was pledged for his return\nWhen fifteen days or twenty were gone by:\nSo had he after to Hippalca sworn,\nBidding her boldly on his faith rely.\n\"From accidents that chance at every turn\"\n(Cried Bradamant \"what warranty have I, ) \n\nAlas! — and such are commonest in war —\nThat none the knight's return for ever bar?\n\n`    LXXXII\n\"Alas!  alas!  Rogero, that above\nMyself hast evermore been prized by me,\nWho would have thought thou more than me could'st love\nAny, and most thy mortal enemy?\nAnd harm'st where thou should'st help; nor do I see\nIf thou as worthy praise or blame regard\nSuch tardiness to punish and reward."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I know not if thou knowest — the stones know —\nHow by Troyano was thy father slain;\nAnd yet Troyano's son, against his foe,\nThou would'st defend, and keep from harm or stain\nSuch vengeance upon him do'st thou bestow?\nAnd do his vengers, as their meed obtain,\nThat I, descended of his stock, should be\nThe martyr of the mortal cruelty?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To her Rogero, in his absence, said\nThe lady these sad words, and more beside,\nLamenting aye; while her attendant maid\nNor once alone, but often, certified\nThe stripling would observe his faith, and prayed\nHer — who could do no better — to abide\nThe Child's arrival till the time came round\nWhen he by promise to return was bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The comfort that Hippalca's words convey,\nAnd Hope, companion of the loving train,\nBradamant's fear and sorrow so allay,\nThat she enjoys some respite from her pain:\nThis moves her in Mount Alban's keep to stay;\nNor ever thence that lady stirred again\nUntil the day, that day the youthful knight\nHad fixt, who ill observed his promise plight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But in that he his promise ill maintained,\nNo blame upon Rogero should be cast;\nHim one or other cause so long detained,\nThe appointed time parforce he overpast:\nOn a sick bed, long time, he, sorely pained,\nWas laid, wherein a month or more he past\nIn doubt of death; so deeply him had gored\nErewhile in fight the Tartar monarch's sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him on the day prefixed the maid attended,\nNor other tidings of the youth had read,\nBut those he through Hippalca had commended,\nAnd that which after Richardetto said;\nWho told how him Rogero had defended,\nAnd freed the captive pair to prison led.\nThe tidings, overjoyed, she hears repeat;\nYet blended with some bitter is the sweet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For she had heard as well in that discourse,\nFor might and beauty voiced, Marphisa's praise;\nHeard, how Rogero thither bends his course,\nTogether with that lady, as he says,\nWhere in weak post and with unequal force\nKing Agramant the Christian army stays.\nSuch fair companionship the lady lauds,\nBut neither likes that union nor applauds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor light suspicion has she of that queen:\nFor, were Marphisa beauteous, as was said,\nAnd they together till that time had been,\n'T were marvel but Rogero loved the maid:\nYet would she not believe; but hung between\nHer hopes and fears, and in Mount Alban stayed;\nAnd close and anxious there, until the day\nWhich was to bring her joy or sorrow, lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while Mount Alban's prince and castellain,\nRinaldo, first of that fair brotherhood,\n— I say in honour, not in age, for twain\nIn right of birth before the warrior stood,\nWho — as the sun illumes the starry train —\nHad by his deeds ennobled Aymon's blood,\nOne day at noon, with none beside a page\nTo serve him, reached that famous fortilage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hither had good Rinaldo now repaired;\nBecause returning Paris ward again,\nFrom Brava, (whither had he often fared,\nAs said, to seek Angelica in vain)\nHe of that pair those evil news had heard.\nHis Malagigi and his Viviane,\nHow they were to Maganza to be sent;\nAnd hence to Agrismont his way had bent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There, hearing of the safety of that pair,\nAnd of their enemies' defeat and fall;\nAnd how Rogero and Marphisa were\nThe authors of their ruin; and how all\nHis valiant brethren and his cousins are\nReturned, and harboured in Mount Alban's hall,\nUntil he there embrace the friendly throng\nEach hour appears to him a twelvemonth long."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His course to Mont Albano had he ta'en;\nAnd, there embracing wife and children dear,\nMother and brethren and the cousins twain,\n(They who were captives to their foe whilere)\nA parent swallow seems, amid that train,\nWhich, with full beak, its fasting youth doth cheer.\nWith them a day or more the warrior stayed,\nThen issued forth and others thence conveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guichard, Duke Aymon's eldest born, and they,\nRichard, Alardo, and Richardet' combined,\nVivian and Malagigi, wend their way\nIn arms, the martial paladin behind.\nBradamant, waiting the appointed day,\nWhich she, in her desire, too slow opined,\nFeigned herself ailing to the brethren true,\nNor would she join in arms the banded crew;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, saying that she ailed, most truly said;\nYet 'twas not corporal pain or fever sore,\nIt was Desire that on her spirit preyed,\nDiseased with Love's disastrous fit: no more\nRinaldo in Mount Alban's castle stayed:\nWith him his kinsman's flower the warrior bore.\nHow he for Paris journeyed, and how well"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto tell.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 31"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo and Dudon fight; then friendship make,\nAnd to each other fitting honour pay.\nAgramant's host the united champions break,\nAnd scatter it, like chaff, in disarray.\nBrandimart wages war, for Roland's sake,\nWith Rodomont, and loses in the fray.\nThis while, for good Baiardo, with more pain,\nContend Rinaldo and the Sericane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What sweeter, gladder, state could be possest\nThan falls to the enamoured bosom's share?\nWhat happier mode of life, what lot more blest,\nThan evermore the chains of love to wear?\nWere not the lover, 'mid his joys, distrest\nBy that suspicious fear, that cruel care,\nThat martyrdom, which racks the suffering sprite,\nThat phrensied rage, which jealousy is hight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For by all bitters else which interpose\nBefore enjoyment of this choicest sweet,\nLove is augmented, to perfection grows,\nAnd takes a finer edge; to drink and eat,\nHunger and thirst the palate so dispose,\nAnd flavour more our beverage and our meat.\nFeebly that wight can estimate the charms\nOf peace, who never knew the pain of arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That which the heart aye sees, though undiscerned\nOf human eye, we can support in peace.\nTo him long absent, to his love returned,\nA longer absence is but joy's increase.\nService may be endured, though nought is earned,\nSo that the hope of guerdon does not cease.\nFor worthy service in the end is paid,\nAlbeit its wages should be long delaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scorn, and repulse, and finally each pain\nOf suffering love, his every martyrdom,\nThrough recollection, make us entertain\nDelights with greater rapture, when they come.\nBut if weak mind be poisoned by that bane,\nThat filthy pest, conceived in Stygian home,\nThough joy ensue, with all its festive pleasures,\nThe wretched lover ill his comfort measures."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This is that cruel and envenomed wound\nWhere neither salve nor portion soothes the smart;\nNor figure made by witch, nor murmured sound;\nNor star benign observed in friendly part;\nNor aught beside by Zoroaster found,\nInventor as he was of magic art.\nFell wound, which, more than every other woe,\nMakes wretched man despair, and lays him low!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "O' cruel wound!  incapable of cure,\nInflicted with such ease on lover's breast,\nNo less by false suspicion than by sure!\nO wound!  whose pangs so wofully molest,\nThey reason and our better wit obscure,\nAnd from it natural bent our judgment wrest:\nWound, which against all reason didst destroy\nThe damsel of Dordona's every joy!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I speak not of what fatal mischief wrought\nHippalca's and the brother's bitter blow;\nI speak of fell and cruel tidings brought\nSome few days after; for the former woe,\nWeighed with this other, was a thing of nought:\nThis after some digression will I show:\nBut first Rinaldo's feats I must declare,\nWho with his troop to Paris made repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The following day they met a cavalier,\nTowards evening, with a lady by his side;\nSable his shield, and sable was his gear,\nWhose ground a bar of silver did divide.\nAs foremost, and of seeming force, the peer,\nYoung Richardetto to the joust defend:\nHe, prompt for battle, wheeled his courser round,\nAnd for the tourney took sufficient ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Between those knights no further parley past:\nWithout more question, charged the martial two.\nRinaldo with the friendly troop stood fast,\nAnd looked to see what issue would ensue.\n\"Him from his saddle will I quickly cast,\nIf firm the footing, and mine arm prove true\";\nWithin himself young Richardetto cries:\nBut that encounter ends in other wise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him underneath the vizor's sight offends\nThe stranger champion, of the sable weed,\nWith force so fell, that he the youth extends\nAbove two lances' length beyond his steed.\nQuickly to venge the knight Alardo wends,\nBut falls himself astounded on the mead;\nSore handled, and unhorsed by such a stroke,\nHis buckler in the cruel shock is broke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His lance Guichardo levelled, when he spied\nOutstretched upon the field, the brethren two;\nAlthough \"Halt, halt,\" (renowned Rinaldo cried,)\n\"For this third course to me is justly due\":\nBut he as yet his helmet had not tied;\nSo that Guichardo to the combat flew.\nHe kept his seat no better than the twain;\nForthwith, like them, extended on the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All to be foremost in the joust contend,\nRichardo, Malagigi, Viviane:\nBut to their strife Rinaldo puts an end;\nHe shows himself in arms before the train,\nSaying, \" 'Tis time that we to Paris wend;\nFor us too long the tourney will detain,\nIf I expect till each his course has run,\nAnd ye are all unseated, one by one.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So spake the knight, yet spake not in a tone\nTo be o'erheard in what he inly said;\nWho thus foul scorn would to the rest have done.\nBoth now had wheeled, and fierce encounter made.\nIn the career Rinaldo was not thrown,\nWho all the banded kinsmen much outweighed;\nTheir spears like brittle glass to pieces went,\nBut not an inch the champions backward bent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The chargers such a rough encounter made,\nThat on his crupper sank each staggering horse:\nRinaldo's rose so quick, he might be said\nScarcely to interrupt his rapid course:\nThe stranger's broke his spine and shoulder-blade;\nThat other shocked him with such desperate force.\nWhen his lord sees him slain, he leaves his seat,\nAnd in an instant springs upon his feet;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And to his foe, that having wheeled anew,\nApproached with hand unarmed, the warrior cried:\n\"Sir, to the goodly courser whom ye slew,\nBecause, whenas he lived, he was my pride,\nI deem, I ill should render honour due,\nIf thus unvenged by my good arm he died;\nAnd so fall on, and do as best ye may,\nFor we parforce must meet in new assay.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him Rinaldo, \"If we for thy horse\nHave to contend in fight, and nought beside,\nTake comfort, for I ween that with no worse\nThou, in his place, by me shalt be supplied.\"\n— \"Thou errest if thou deem'st his loss the source\nOf my regret\" (the stranger knight replied);\n\"But I, since thou divinest not my speech,\nTo thee my meaning will more plainly teach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I should esteem it were a foul misdeed,\nUnless I proved thee also with the brand.\nI, if thou in this other dance succeed\nBetter or worse than me, would understand:\nThen, as it please, afoot or on thy steed,\nAttack me, so it be with arms in hand.\nI am content all vantage to afford;\nSuch my desire to try thee with the sword!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not long Rinaldo paused: he cried, \"I plight\nMy promise not to balk thee of the fray;\nAnd, for I deem thou art a valiant knight,\nAnd lest thou umbrage take at mine array,\nThese shall go on before, nor other wight,\nBeside a page, to hold my horse, shall stay.\"\nSo spake Mount Alban's lord; and to his band,\nTo wend their way the warrior gave command."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To that king paladin with praise replied\nThe stranger peer; alighting on the plain,\nRinaldo to the valet, at his side,\nConsigned the goodly steed Baiardo's rein,\nAnd when his banner he no longer spied,\nNow widely distant with the warrior's train,\nHis buckler braced, his biting faulchion drew,\nAnd to the field defied the knight anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And now each other they in fight assail:\nWas never seen a feller strife in show.\nNeither believes his foeman can avail,\nLong, in that fierce debate, against his blow:\nBut when they knew, well neighed in doubtful scale,\nThat they were fitly matched, for weal or woe,\nThey laid their fury and their pride apart,\nAnd for their vantage practised every art."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Their cruel and despiteous blows resound,\nRe-echoing wide, what time the valiant twain\nWith cantlets of their shields now strew the ground,\nNow with their faulchions sever plate and chain.\nYet more behoves to parry than to wound,\nIf either knight his footing would maintain;\nFor the first fault in fence, by either made,\nWill with eternal mischief be appaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One hour and more than half another, stood\nThe knights in battle; and the golden sun\nAlready was beneath the tumbling flood,\nAnd the horizon veiled with darkness dun:\nNor yet had they reposed, nor interlude\nHad been, since that despiteous fight begun,\n'Twixt these, whom neither ire nor rancour warms,\nBut simple thirst of fame excites to arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo in himself revolving weighed\nWho was the stranger knight, so passing stout;\nThat not alone him bravely had gainsaid,\nBut oft endangered in that deadly bout;\nAnd has so harassed with his furious blade,\nHe of its final issue stands in doubt.\n— He that the strife was ended would be fain,\nSo that his knightly honour took no stain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The stranger knight, upon the other side,\nAs little of his valiant foeman knew;\nNor in that lord Mount Alban's chief descried,\nIn warfare so renowned all countries through.\nAnd upon whom, with such small cause defied,\nHis faulchion he in deadly combat drew.\nHe was assured he could not have in fight\nExperience of a more redoubted wight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He gladly would be quit of the emprize\nHe undertook to venge his courser's fall;\nAnd, could he, without blame, a mean devise,\nWould fain withdraw from that disastrous brawl.\nSo overcast already were the skies,\nTheir cruel strokes well nigh fell harmless all.\nBoth blindly strike; more blindly yet those lords\nParry the stroke, who scarce discern their swords."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He of Mount Alban is the first to say,\nThey should not combat darkling, on the plain;\nBut should their duel till such time delay\nAs slow Arcturus should have turned his wain.\n(And adds, as safely as himself might stay ) \n\nThe foe in his pavilion, of his train\nAs duly tended, honoured, and well seen,\nAs he in any place had ever been."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To pray him has Rinaldo little need:\nHe courteously accepts him for his host;\nAnd thither the united warriors speed,\nWhere lies Mount Alban's troop in chosen post.\nFrom his attendant squire a goodly steed,\nWith sumptuous housings gorgeously embossed,\nRinaldo takes, with tempered sword and spear,\nAnd these bestows upon the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For Montalbano's lord the stranger guest,\nThe baron recognised, with whom he came;\nBecause, before they reached their place of rest,\nThe paladin had chanced himself to name;\nAnd (for they brethren were with love opprest, ) \n\nHis tenderness him wholly overcame;\nAnd touched with kind affection, at his heart,\nFrom his full eyes the tears of pleasure start."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guido the savage was that cavalier,\nWho, with Marphisa leagued, the martial maid,\nSansonet, and the sons of Olivier,\nLong sailed the sea, as I erewhile have said;\nFrom earlier meeting with his kindred dear\nBy Pinnabel, the felon knight, delaid;\nSeized by that traitor, and by him detained,\nTo enforce the wicked law he had ordained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sir Guido, when he knew his host to be\nRinaldo, famed above each famous knight,\nWhom he had burned with more desire to see\nThan ever blindman covets the lost light,\nIn rapture cries, \"What fortune tempted me\nWith you, my lord, to strive in deadly fight,\nWhom long I have beloved, and love, whose worth\nI prize above all dwellers' upon earth?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Me on the distant bank of Euxine's flood\n(I Guido am yclept Constantia bare, ) \n\nConceived of the illustrious seed and good\nOf generous Aymon, as ye likewise are.\nTo visit you and my bold brotherhood\nIs the occasion, hither I repair;\nAnd, where to honour you I had in thought,\nI see my coming has but mischief wrought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But that I neither ye nor the others knew,\nMust for so foul a fault be my excuse;\nAnd, if I can amend it, bid me do\nWhate'er thou wilt, nor ought will I refuse.\"\nWhen, on this part and that, between the two,\nOf interchanged embraces there was truce,\n\"Take you no farther thought upon your side\nThe battle to excuse,\" Rinaldo cried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For in complete assurance that you are\nA real offset of our ancient tree,\nYou could no better testimony bear\nThan the tried valour which in you we see;\nIf your demeanour more pacific were,\nWe ill should have believed your ancestry:\nSince neither lion from the doe proceeds,\nNor fearful pigeon, hawk or eagle breeds.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While neither they through talk their journey stay,\nNeither through speed abate their talk, those two\nReached the pavilions where the kinsmen lay:\nThere good Rinaldo, crying to his crew\nThat this was Guido, whom so many a day\nThey had impatiently desired to view,\nMuch pleased the friendly troop; and, at his sight\nAll like his father deemed the stranger knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I will not tell what welcome to the peer\nMade Richardet, Alardo, and those twain;\nWhat Malagigi, what Sir Aldigier,\nAnd gallant Vivian, of that kindred train;\nWhat every captain, every cavalier;\nWhat Guido spake, what they replied again:\nI for conclusion of my tale will say,\nHe was well greeted of the whole array."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ever, I deem, good Guido would have been\nDear to his brethren bold; but welcomed more\nWas now the valiant knight, and better seen\nThat at another time, as needed sore.\nWhen the sun, garlanded with radiance sheen,\nUpraised his visage from the watery floor,\nSir Guido and his kinsmen, in a band,\nBeneath Rinaldo's banner took their stand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So one day and another prick the train,\nThat they to Paris' leaguered gates are nigh,\nScarce ten miles distant, on the banks of Seine;\nWhen, as good Fortune wills it, they descry\nGryphon and Aquilant, the two that stain\nTheir virtuous armour with a different dye;\nSable was Aquilant's, white Gryphon's, weed;\nGood Olivier's and Sigismonda's seed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In parley were they by a damsel stayed,\nNor she of mean condition to behold;\nThat in a snowy samyte was arraid,\nThe vesture edged about with list of gold:\nGraceful and fair; although she was dismaid,\nAnd down her visage tears of sorrow rolled;\nWho with such mien and act her speech enforced,\nIt seemed of some high matter she discoursed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As Guido them, they gallant Guido knew.\nHe with the pair had been few days before;\nAnd to Rinaldo: \"Behold those!  whom few\nIn valour and in prowess go before,\nAnd if they join your banner, against you\nFeebly will stand the squadrons of the Moor.\"\nRinaldo vouched what valiant Guido told,\nHow either champion was a warrior bold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor them he less had recognized at sight;\nBecause (such was the usage of the pair)\nOne by a vest all black, and one all white,\nHe knows, and by the ornaments they wear.\nThe brethren know as well Mount Alban's knight,\nAnd give the warlike kinsmen welcome fair:\nThey both embrace Rinaldo as a friend,\nAnd of their ancient quarrel make an end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They — erst at feud and with sore hate possest,\nThrough Truffaldino — (which were long to say)\nEach other with fraternal love carest,\nNow putting all their enmity away.\nRinaldo next Sir Sansonet addrest,\nWho somewhat later joined that fair array;\nAnd (knowing well his force and mighty thew)\nReceived the cavalier with honour due."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she, that gentle damsel, now more near,\nBeholds renowned Rinaldo, him she knows,\nAcquainted with each paladin and peer.\nShe news which sorely grieve the warrior shows;\nAnd thus begin: \"My lord, your cousin dear,\nTo whom its safety Church and Empire owes,\nRoland, erewhile so honoured and so sage,\nNow roves the world, possest with frantic rage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whence woe, so direful and so strange, ensued\nCannot by me to you be signified:\nI saw on earth his sword and armour strewed,\nDoffed by that peer, and scattered far and wide;\nAnd I a pious knight and courteous viewed\nThose arms collecting upon every side,\nWho, in the guise of trophy, to a tree\nFastened that fair and pompous panoply."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But from the trophied stem the sword withdrew\nThe son of Agrican that very day.\nThou mayst conceive what mischief may ensue\nTo Charles and to the christened host's array,\nFrom loss of Durindana, if anew\nThe infidels that goodly blade should sway.\nGood Brigliador as well, who roved, forsaken,\nAbout those arms, was by the paynim taken."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Few days are past, since I in shameful wise\nSaw Roland, running naked in his mood,\nSending forth piteous shrieks and fearful cries.\nIn fine, that he is frantic I conclude;\nNor this had I believed, save with these eyes\nThat strange and cruel wonder I had viewed.\"\nShe added next, how from the bridge's top,\nEmbraced by Rodomont, she saw him drop."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To whosoe'er I deem not Roland's foe\nI tell my tale,\" (pursued the dame again,)\n\"That, of the crowd who hear this cruel woe\nSome one, in pity to his cruel pain,\nMay strive the peer in Paris to bestow,\nOr other friendly place, to purge his brain.\nWell wot I, if such tidings he receive,\nNought unattempted Brandimart will leave.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fair Flordelice was she, the stranger dame;\nThat his own self to Brandimart more dear:\nWho in pursuit of him to Paris came.\nThat damsel, after, tells the cavalier,\nHow hate and strife were blown into a flame\nBetween Gradasso and the Tartar peer,\nFor Roland's faulchion; fierce Gradasso's prey,\nWhen slain in combat Mandricardo lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By accident, so strange and sad, distrust,\nRinaldo is distraught with ceaseless woe:\nHe feels his heart dissolve within his breast,\nAs in the sun dissolves the flake of snow;\nAnd, with unchanged resolve, upon the quest\nOf good Orlando, every where will go;\nIn hopes, if he discover him, to find\nSome means of cure for his distempered mind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But since his band already had he dight,\n(Did him the hand of Heaven or Fortune sway)\nHe first to put the Saracens to flight,\nAnd raise the siege of Paris, will assay.\nBut (for it promised vantage he till night ) \n\nThe assault of their cantonments will delay,\nTill the third watch or fourth, when heavy sleep\nTheir senses shall in Lethe's water steep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His squadron in the wood he placed, and there,\nAmbushed, he made them lie the daylight through;\nBut when the sun, leaving this nether air\nIn darkness, to his ancient nurse withdrew;\nAnd fangless serpent now, and goat, and bear,\nWith other beasts, adorned the heavens anew,\nWhich by the greater blaze had been concealed,\nRinaldo moved his silent troop afield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A mile an-end with Aquilant he prest,\nGryphon, Alardo, and Vivian of his race,\nGuido and Sansonetto, and the rest,\nWithout word spoken, and with stealthy pace.\nThe Moorish guard they find with sleep opprest:\nThey slaughter all, nor grant one paynim grace;\nAnd, ere they were by others seen or heard,\nInto their midmost camp the squadron spurred."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the first charge on that unchristened band,\nTheir guard and sentries, taken by surprise,\nSo broken are by good Rinaldo's brand,\nNo wight is left, save he who slaughtered lies.\nTheir first post forced, the paynims understand\nNo laughing matter is the lord's emprize;\nFor. sleeping and dismaid, their naked swarms\nMake small resistance to such warriors' arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To strike more dread into the Moorish foe,\nMount Alban's champion, leading the assault,\nBade beat his drums and bade his bugles blow,\nAnd with loud echoing cries his name exalt.\nHe spurs Baiardo, that is nothing slow;\nHe clears the lofty barriers at a vault,\nTrampling down foot, o'erturning cavalier,\nAnd scatters booth and tent in his career."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Is none so bold of all that paynimry\nBut what his stiffened hair stands up on end,\nHearing Mount Alban's and Rinaldo's cry\nFrom earth into the starry vault ascend.\nHim the twin hosts of Spain and Afric fly,\nNor time in loading baggage idly spend;\nWho will not wait that deadly fury more,\nWhich to have proved so deeply irks them sore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guido succeeds; no less their foe pursue,\nThe valiant sons of warlike Olivier,\nAlardo, Richardet, and the other two;\nSansonet's sword and horse a pathway clear;\nAnd well is proved upon that paynim crew\nThe force of Vivian and of Aldigier.\nThus each bestirs himself like valorous knight,\nWho follows Clermont's banner to the fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seven hundred men with good Rinaldo speed,\nDrawn from Mount Alban and the townships nigh\n— No fiercer erst obeyed Achilles' lead —\nEnured to summer and to winter sky:\nSo stout each warrior is, so good at need,\nA hundred would not from a thousand fly;\nAnd, better than some famous cavaliers,\nMany amid that squadron couch their spears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If good Rinaldo gathers small supplies\nFrom rents or cities, which his rule obey,\nSo these he bound by words and courtesies,\nAnd sharing what he had with his array,\nIs none that ever from his service buys\nDeserter by the bribe of better pay.\nOf Montalbano these are left in care,\nSave pressing need demands their aid elsewhere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Them now in succour of King Charles he stirred,\nAnd left with little guard his citadel.\nAmong the Africans that squadron spurred,\nThat squadron, of whose doughty feats I tell,\nDoing by them what wolf on woolly herd\nDoes where Galesus' limpid waters well,\nOr lion by the bearded goat and rank,\nThat feeds on Cinyphus's barbarous bank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Tidings to Charles Rinaldo had conveyed,\nThat he for Paris with his squadron steers,\nTo assail, by night, the paynims ill purveyed;\nAnd ready and in arms the king appears.\nHe, when his help is needed, comes in aid,\nWith all his peerage, and, beside his peers,\nBrings Monodantes' son, amid that crew,\nOf Flordelice the lover chaste and true;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whom by such long and by such tedious way\nShe sought throughout the realm of France in vain;\nHere by the cognizance, his old display,\nAfar, by her distinguished from the train.\nAt the first sight of her he quits the fray,\nAnd wears a semblance loving and humane.\nHe clipt her round with many a fond caress,\nAnd kissed a thousand times, or little less."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To dame and damsel in that ancient age\nThey trusted much, that, in their wandering vein,\nRoved, unescorted, many a weary stage,\nThrough foreign countries and by hill and plain;\nWhom they returning hold for fair and sage,\nNor of their faith suspicion entertain.\nHere Brandimart by Flordelice was taught\nHow Roland wandered, of his wits distraught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Had he such strange and evil tidings heard\nFrom other lips, he scarce had these believed:\nBut credited fair Flordelice's word,\nFrom whom more wondrous things he had received,\nNor this, as told by other, she averred;\nThis had she seen, and ill could be deceived;\nFor well as any she Orlando knows;\nAnd both the when and where that damsel shows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She tells him how the perilous bridge's floor\nFrom cavaliers king Rodomont defends;\nWhere, on a pompous sepulchre, the Moor\nHis prisoners' ravished arms and vest suspends;\nTells how she saw Orlando, raging sore,\nDo fearful deeds, and her relation ends,\nDescribing how the paynim fell reversed,\nTo his great peril, in the stream immersed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Brandimart, who the Country loves as dear\nAs man can love a brother, friend, or son,\nDisposed to seek Orlando, far and near,\nNor pain nor peril in the adventure shun,\nTill something for the comfort of that peer\nBy wizard's or by leech's art be done,\nArmed as he is, leaps lightly on his steed,\nAnd takes his way beneath the lady's lead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thitherward were Orlando she had spied,\nIn company the knight and lady made.\nThey daily post till to that bridge they ride,\nWhich Argier's king maintained, in arms arraid,\nTo him the guard their coming signified;\nCourser and arms his squires as well conveyed;\nAnd Brandimart no sooner is at hand\nThan Rodomont is armed and at his stand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With lofty voice the sovereign of Argier,\nAssorting with his moody rage, 'gan say:\n\" — Whoe'er thou art, sir knight, and whencesoe'er —\nBrought by mistake of purpose or of way,\nLight from thine horse and doff thy warlike gear,\nTo deck this sepulchre, ere thee I slay,\nAn offering to its lovely tenant's spirit;\nAnd thou in thy forced homage have no merit.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Brandimart, at the paynim's proud discourse,\nHis weapon in the rest, for answer, layed;\nHe good Batoldo spurred, his gentle horse,\nAnd at the champion with such fury made,\nAs showed that he, for courage and for force,\nWith any warrior in the world had weighed.\nKing Rodomont as well, with rested spear,\nThundered along the bridge, in fierce career."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The paynim's courser, ever used to go\nUpon that bridge's fearful pass, where one\nFell prone parforce into the stream below,\nSecurely to the fierce encounter run:\nWhile, trembling, and irresolute in show,\nThat other to the unwonted course is gone.\nQuivers the bridge beneath, as it would sink:\nNarrow that passage is, unfenced the brink!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With heavy spears, the growth of forest hoar,\nSaplings rough-hewn, those masters of the just,\nUpon the perilous bridge encountering sore,\nExchange, on either side, no gentle thrust.\nNor much their mighty strength or manege-lore\nAvails the steeds; for, prostrate in the dust,\nCrumbles each knight and charger in mid-course;\nWhelmed in one fate, the rider and his horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When either steed would nimbly spring from ground,\nAs the spur galled and gored his bleeding flank,\nHe on that little bridge no footing found;\nFor all to narrow was the scanty plank.\nHence both fall headlong, and the deafening sound\nRe-echo vaulted skies and grassy bank.\nSo rang our stream, when from the heavenly sphere\nWas hurled the sun's ill-fated charioteer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With all their weight, down hurtled from the steep,\nCoursers and cavaliers, who sate them well;\nAnd dived into the river's darksome deep,\nTo search for beauteous nymph in secret cell.\nNor this the first nor yet the second leap\nWhich from the bridge had made that infidel!\nWho, often floundering in its oozy bed,\nWell in the soundings of that stream was read."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He where 'tis hand and where 'tis softer knows,\nWhere shallow is the water, where profound:\nWith breast and flanks above the waves he rose,\nAnd Brandimart assailed on safer ground.\nBrandimart, whirling with the current, goes,\nWhile his steed's feet the faithless bottom pound.\nHe, with his lord, stands rooted in the mud,\nWith risk to both of drowning in the flood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whelming them upside-down, the waters flow,\nAnd plunge them in the river's deepest bed;\nThe horse is uppermost, the knight below.\nFrom the bridge looks his lady, sore bested,\nAnd tear employs, and prayer, and suppliant vow:\n— \"Ah, Rodomont!  for love of her, whom dead\nYe worship, do not deed of such despite!\nPermit not, sir, the death of such a knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  courteous lord!  if e'er you loved withal,\nHave pity upon me who love this peer;\nLet it suffice that he become thy thrall!\nFor if thou on this stone suspend his gear,\nAmid whatever spoils adorn the wall,\nThe best and worthiest will his spoils appear.\"\nShe ended, and her prayer so well addrest,\nIt touched, though hard to move, the paynim's breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Moved by her words, he lent her lover aid,\nSo by his courser in the stream immersed;\nAnd largely drank, albeit with little thirst.\nBut Rodomont a while his help delayed,\nAnd seized the warrior's sword and helmet first.\nHim half exhausted from the stream he drew,\nAnd prisoned with that other captive crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All happiness was in that damsel spent,\nWhen taken she her Brandimart espied,\nAlthough to see him captive more content,\nThan to behold him perish in the tide.\nNone but herself she blames for the event,\nWho thitherward had been the champion's guide,\nShe having to that faithful warrior shown,\nHow at the bridge Orlando she had known."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She parts, and has anew already planned\nThither with good Rinaldo to resort;\nWith Guido, Sansonet of doughty hand,\nOr other cavalier of Pepin's court;\nSome warrior good by water and by land,\nThat with the Saracen will well assort.\nWho, if no stronger than her baffled knight,\nWith better fortune may maintain the fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For many days the damsel vainly strayed,\nEre she encountered any one who bore\nSemblance of knight, that might afford her aid,\nAnd free her prisoned lover from the Moor;\nAfter she long and fruitless search had made,\nAt length a warrior crost her way, that wore\nA richly ornamented vest, whose ground\nWith trunks of cypresses was broidered round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who was that champion, shall be said elsewhere;\nFor I to Paris must return, and show\nHow Malagigi and Rinaldo are\nVictorious o'er the routed Moorish foe.\nTo count the flyers were a useless care,\nOr many drowned in Stygian streams below.\nThe darkness rendered Turpin's labour vain,\nWho tasked himself to tell the pagans slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Agramant in his pavilion lies,\nFrom his first sleep awakened by a knight:\nHe that the king will be a prisoner cries,\nSave he with speed betake himself to flight,\nThe monarch looks about him and espies\nHis paynim bands dispersed in panic fright.\nNaked, they far and near desert the field;\nNay, never halt to snatch the covering shield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Uncounselled and confused, the king arrayed\nHis naked limbs in knightly plate and chain,\nWhen thither Falsiron, the Spaniard, made\nGrandonio, Balugantes, and their train:\nThey to the Moorish king the risk displayed\nOf being taken in that press, or slain;\nAnd vouched if thence he should in safety fare,\nHe well might thank propitious Fortune's care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marsilius so, Sobrino so, their fear\nExpress; so, one and all, the friendly band;\nThey warn him that Destruction is as near\nAs swift Mount Alban's lord is nigh at hand.\nAnd if against so fierce a cavalier,\nAnd such a troop, he seeks to make a stand,\nHe and his friends in that disastrous strife\nWill surely forfeit liberty or life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But he to Arles and Narbonne may retreat,\nWith such few squadrons as his rule obey:\nSince either is well fortified, and meet\nThe warfare to maintain above one day;\nAnd having saved his person, the defeat\nMay venge upon the foe, by this delay:\nHis troops may rally quickly in that post,\nAnd rout in fine King Charles' conquering host."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant to those lords' opinion bent,\nThough that hard counsel he could ill endure;\nAs if supplied with wings, towards Arles he went,\nBy roads which offered passage most secure.\nBeside safe guides, much favoured his intent\nHis setting out, when all things were obscure.\nScaping the toils by good Rinaldo spread,\nSome twenty thousand of the paynims fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those whom Rinaldo, whom his brethren slew,\nWhom Oliviero's sons, the valiant twain,\nThose who were slaughtered by Mount Alban's crew,\n— The fierce seven hundred, good Rinaldo's train —\nThose whom the valiant Sansonet o'erthrew,\nAnd those that in their flight were drowned in Seine,\nHe who would count, might count as well what flowers\nZephyr and Flora shed, mid April-showers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here one conjectures Malagigi bore\nA part in the alarum of that night:\nNot that he stained the mead with paynim gore,\nNor splintered heads; but that the wizard wight,\nInfernal angels, by his magic lore,\nCalled from Tartarean caverns into light;\nWhose many spears and banners waving wide\nTwo kingdoms such as France had scarce supplied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And with them such sonorous metal brayed,\nSo many drums and martial noises sounded;\nSo many steeds in that encounter neighed;\nSo many cries — with rush of foot confounded —\nRose all about, that hill, dale, wood, and glade,\nFrom distant parts, the deafening din rebounded;\nAnd struck into the Moors such sudden dread,\nThey turned and from the field in panic fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Their king forgets no, how Rogero lay\nSore wounded, and as yet in evil case.\nHim, with what care they could, he made convey\nFrom that dread field, on horse of easy pace.\nBorne to the sea by the securest way,\nThey in a bark the suffering warrior place,\nAnd thence commodiously to Arles transport;\nWhither their wasted squadrons make resort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Chased by Rinaldo and King Charlemagne,\nA hundred thousand, or well nigh, I ween,\nBy wood, by mountain, valley, and by plain,\nFlying the fury of the Franks are seen;\nMore find the passage blocked, and widely stain\nWith crimson what before was white and green.\nNot so Gradasso's puissant troops was spent,\nWho farther from the field had pitched his tent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nay; when he hears it is Mount Alban's knight\nBy whom assailed the paynim quarters are,\nHe in his heart exults, with such delight,\nThat he, for very joy, leaps here and there.\nHe thanks and lauds his God, who him that night\nBlest with so high a fortune and so rare;\nHoping to win the horse without a peer,\nBaiardo, from the Christian cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gradasso had desired long time before\n(I think you will have read the tale elsewhere)\nTo back that courser, which Rinaldo bore,\nAnd Durindana by his side to wear:\nHe with a hundred thousand men and more\nTo France, with this design, had made repair;\nAnd had erewhile to bloody fight defied,\nEven for that good steed, Mount Alban's pride."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hence had that king repaired to the sea-shore,\nThe place assigned to end their discord fell:\nBut all was marred by Malagigi's lore;\nWho, cheating good Rinaldo with a spell,\nTo sea the champion in a pinnace bore.\nToo tedious were the tale at length to tell.\nHence evermore Gradasso had opined,\nThe gentle baron was of craven kind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now that Gradasso learns Mount Alban's peer\nIs he, that storms the camp, in huge delight,\nArmed, on Alfana leaps the cavalier,\nAnd through the pitchy darkness seeks the knight,\nO'erturning all who cross his fierce career,\nHe leaves afflicted and in piteous plight\nThe broken bands of Afric and of France.\nAll, food alike for his wide-wasting lance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He seeks the paladin, now here now there,\nEchoing his name as loud as he can shout;\nAnd thitherward inclines his courser, where\nThe bodies are most thickly strown about.\nAt length encounter, sword to sword, the pair,\nFor broken are alike their lances stout;\nWhich shivering in their hands, had flown upright.\nAnd smote the starry chariot of the Night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When King Gradasso recognized the foe,\nNot by the blazoned bearing of his shield,\nBut by Baiardo — by that horrid blow,\nWhich made him seem sole champion of the field,\nHe to reproach the knight was nothing slow,\nAnd of unworthy action him appealed;\nIn that he had not kept his ground and day,\nErewhile appointed for the fierce assay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Belike thou hoped,\" (said he of Sericane,)\n\"If for that time my vengeance thou couldst fly,\nWe should not meet in this wide world again:\nBut we are met, thou seest, anew; and I,\nBe sure, though thou shouldst seek the Stygian reign,\nOr be from earth translated to the sky,\nWill hunt thee, save that courser thou forego,\nBe it through heaven above or hell below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Dost thou, as matched with me mistrust thy force,\n(And that thou wert ill paired was seen whilere,)\nAnd more esteemest life than fame, a course\nRemains, which thee may from thy peril clear.\nAnd thou, if thou in peace resign the horse,\nMay'st live, if life be deemed so passing dear;\nBut live afoot, unmeriting a steed,\nThat dost by chivalry such foul misdeed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guido the savage, as he spake, was nigh\nWith Richardetto; and the warlike twain\nBrandished alike their trenchant swords on high,\nTo teach more wit to him of Sericane:\nBut them Rinaldo stopt with sudden cry,\nNor brooked that he should injury sustain.\n\"Am I too weak,\" (he cried, \"without your aid, ) \n\nTo answer him that dares my deeds upbraid?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then to the pagan thus: \"Gradasso hear,\nAnd wilt thou listen, thou shalt understand,\nAnd I will prove it manifest and clear,\nI came to seek thee out upon the strand;\nAnd afterwards on thee will made appear\nThe truth of all I say with arms in hand;\nKnow then thou liest, if e'er with slanderous speech\nThou taxest me with aught in knighthood's breach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But warmly I beseech thee, that before\nThe battle be, thou fully comprehend\nMy just excuses, that thou may'st no more\nMe for my failure wrongly reprehend:\nNext for Baiardo, as agreed of yore,\n'Tis my desire that we afoot contend;\nEven as ordained by thee, in desert place,\nAlone in knightly duel, face to face.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Courteous was Sericana's cavalier,\n(For generous bosoms aye such practise use)\nAnd is content to listen to the peer,\nHow he his breach of promise will excuse.\nWith him he seeks the river side, and here\nIn simple words what chanced Rinaldo shews;\nForm the true history removes the veil,\nAnd cites all Heaven to witness to his tale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Next calls upon the son of Buovo, who\nIs of that history informed aright;\nAnd now, from point to point, relates anew\n(Nor more nor less rehearsed the magic sleight. ) \n\nWhen thus Rinaldo: \"What I warrant true\nBy witness, I with arms in single fight,\nFor better proof, will vouch upon thy crest,\nBoth now and ever, as it likes thee best.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king of Sericane, as loath to leave\nThe second quarrel for the former breach,\nThough doubtful how that tale he should receive,\nTakes in good part the bold Rinaldo's speech.\nNot, as upon the former battle's eve,\nThey choose their ground on Barcellona's beach:\nBut on the morn ensuing, and, fast by\nA neighbouring fountain, will the question try."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither Rinaldo will the steed convey,\nThere to be placed in common, 'twixt the two.\nIf good Gradasso take his foe or slay,\nHe wins Baiardo without more ado.\nBut if Gradasso fails in that affray,\n— Should he be slain, or else for mercy sue,\nA prisoner to Mount Alban's valiant lord,\nRinaldo shall possess the virtuous sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With mighty marvel and with greater pain,\nThe paladin from Flordelice (as shown)\nHad heard how troubled was his cousin's brain.\nAnd from the damsel's lips as well had known\nHow he his arms had scattered on the plain;\nAnd heard the quarrel which from thence had grown;\nIn fine, how King Gradasso had the brand,\nWhich won such thousand palms in Roland's hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When they so agreed, Gradasso made\nThither where, camped apart, his servants lay,\nAlbeit warmly by Rinaldo prayed,\nHe would with him in his pavillion stay.\nThe paynim king in armour was arrayed,\nAnd so the paladin, by break of day;\nAnd to the destined fount came either lord,\nThe field of combat for the horse and sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It seemed Rinaldo's friends were all in fear,\nAnd dreaded much, before it was begun,\nThe issue of the fight their cavalier\nShould wage against Gradasso, one to one.\nMuch force, much daring, and much skill appear\nIn that fierce king; and since of Milo's son\nThe goodly sword was to his girdle tied,\nAll cheeks looked pale upon Rinaldo's side;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And Malagigi, more than all the rest,\nSore doubted the event which would ensue,\nHe willingly himself would have addrest\nTo disappoint the destined fight anew;\nBut fears if he that deadly strife arrest,\nRinaldo's utter enmity to rue,\nYet wroth with him upon that other score,\nWhen he conveyed the warrior from the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let others nourish idle grief and fears!\nRinaldo wends afield secure and gay,\nHoping that shame, which to the knight appears\nToo foul to be endured, to wipe away:\nSo that of Altafoglia and Poictiers,\nHe may for ever silence the mis-say.\nBoldly, and in his heart secure to win\nThat battle's honour, wends the paladin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When now from either side those warriors meet,\nNigh at the same time at the fountain-side,\nSo in all points the pair each other greet,\nWith countenance, so kind, so satisfied,\n'Twould seem by kindred and by friendship sweet\nRinaldo and Gradasso were allied.\nBut how they after closed in fierce affray,\nI till another season shall delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 32"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To her that does for her Rogero stay,\nTidings are brought which irk the damsel sore,\nThat fair Marphisa caused the youth's delay;\nShe bent to slay her, grieving evermore,\nDeparts, and overtakes, upon the way,\nUllania with the three kings who rode before.\nThese she o'ercomes, and had o'ercome that maid,\nBut that an evil law she disobeyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I recollect that I was bound to sing\n(I promised so, but it escaped my mind)\nOf a suspicion, fraught with suffering\nTo Bradamant of more displeasing kind,\nAnd made by keener and more venomed sting\nThan caused that other wound, wherewith she pined,\nWhich, hearing Richardet his news impart,\nHad pierced her breast and preyed upon her heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So was I bound to sing, but I begun\nAnother song, Rinaldo crossed my way,\nAnd then those deeds by savage Guido done,\nKept me employed and caused no small delay;\nAnd so from subject I to subject run,\nThat I forgot of Bradamant to say.\nI now remember, and will tell you, ere\nYou of Rinaldo or Gradasso hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But it behoves, ere more of these be said,\nI should awhile of Agramant discourse,\nWho had from that night's raging fire conveyed\nTo Arles, the remnant of his scattered force:\nSince to unite his troops, and furnish aid\nAnd victual, 'twas a place of much resource,\nSeated upon a river, nigh the shore,\nWith Spain in front and Africa before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With horse and foot, of good or evil sort,\nMarsilius throughout Spain their loss repairs;\nAnd each armed back in Barcellona's port,\nFurnished through love or fear, for sea prepares.\nThe Moor to council daily calls his court;\nNor care nor cost the watchful monarch spares:\nMeanwhile sore taxes and repeated cess,\nAll Africa's o'erburdened towns oppress."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He offers Rodomont, if to his side\nHe will return, but offers him in vain,\nRenowned Almontes' daughter, as a bride;\nHis cousin she, her portion Oran's reign.\nHe lures not from his bridge that knight of pride,\nWho has so many sells, such plate and chain\nCollected there, from cavaliers o'erthrown,\nAs serve to hide the monumental stone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa would not such a course pursue:\nNay, the redoubted damsel hearing said\nThat Agramant, subdued by Charles's crew,\n— His choicest warriors taken, chased, or dead —\nIn Arles was sheltered with his broken few,\nThither, unbidden by the monarch, sped,\nPrompt to assist him with her friendly blade;\nAnd proffered purse and person in his aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As a free gift to him the martial fair\nBrunello bore, nor had she done him wrong.\nHe, for ten days and nights, to swing in air,\nHad sorely feared, from lofty gallows hung:\nBut seeing him unhelped by force or prayer\nOf any one amid the paynim throng,\nShe thought foul scorn to stain her generous hands\nWith such base blood, and loosed the losel's bands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She pardoned every ancient injury,\nAnd him to Agramant in Arles conveyed.\nWell may you fancy with what joy and glee\nThe monarch greeted her who brought him aid;\nHe in Brunello's fate wills all shall see\nIn what esteem he holds that warlike maid;\nFor he in earnest does upon her foe\nWhat fierce Marphisa menaced but in show."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The hangman hung his corpse in desert field,\nThe craving vulture and the crow to feed.\nRogero, that erewhile had been his shield,\nAnd from the noose that caitiff would have freed,\nHeaven's justice willed, now lay with wound unhealed,\nNor could assist the craven in his need;\nAnd when the news were known, the knot was tied;\nSo that Brunello, unassisted, died."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while does good duke Aymon's daughter mourn,\nBecause those twenty days so slowly trail:\n— Which term elapsed — Rogero should return,\nAnd be received into her church's pale.\nTime halts not more with him to foreign bourne\nExiled, with prisoner pent in noisome jail,\nPines the poor wretch for liberty and light,\nOr his loved land, desired and gladsome sight!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Aye sick with hope deferred, the expecting maid,\nThat Phoebus' steeds were foundered one while deemed;\nThen that his wheels were out of frame, so stayed,\nBeyond the wonted term, his chariot seemed.\nYet longer than that day when Faith delayed\nThe sun, which on the righteous Hebrew beamed,\nOr than that night Alcides was conceived,\nShe every day and every night believed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How oft of dormouse, badger, or of bear,\nThe heavy slumber would she fain partake!\nFor she that time in sleep would waste and wear;\nNor such prolonged repose desired to break;\nNor wished the damsel any sound to hear,\nUntil Rogero's voice should her awake:\nBut not alone is this beyond her power;\nShe cannot close her eyes one single hour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She here and there, throughout the livelong night,\nTosses and turns, nor ever finds repose;\nAnd still, impatient for the dawn of light,\nFrom time to time she to her window goes,\nTo see if Tithon's spouse the lily white\nYet scatters mingled with the crimson rose.\nNor less desires the damsel, when 'tis morn,\nTo see the golden stars the heaven adorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When, saving some four days, the term was ended,\nAppointed for the youthful warrior's stay,\nShe, full of hope, the messenger attended\nFrom hour to hour, that should arrive, and say,\n\"Behold Rogero comes\"; and oft ascended\nA turret, from whose top she might survey\nGay champaign, wood, and, mid the wide expanse,\nA portion of the road, that led to France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When shining arms at distance she perceives,\nOr any thing that speaks a cavalier,\n'Tis her desired Rogero, she believes;\nAnd her fair eyes and brows are seen to clear.\nIf footman, or unarmed, the maid conceives,\nIt is a courier from the youthful peer;\nAnd, though fallacious every hope she feeds,\nAnother and another aye succeeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And then she arms, and will the warrior meet;\nAnd from the hill descends into the plain:\nShe finds him not, and to Montalban's seat\nHopes he by other road his way has ta'en.\nIn the design, wherewith she moved her feet\nFrom thence, she to her fort returns in vain;\nNor finds him here nor there; meanwhile expired\nThe period whose approach she so desired."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— The period so prefixt o'erpast by one,\nBy two, three, six, by eight, by twenty days —\nShe seeing not her spouse, and tidings none\nReceiving of the youth, laments 'gan raise,\nWhich had from snake-haired Furies pity won,\nIn those dark realms that Rhadamanthus sways.\nShe smote her eyes divine, and bosoms fair;\nShe rent the tresses of her golden hair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Can it be true?\" — (she cried — \"Shall I be fain ) \n\nTo follow one, that strives to hide and fly?\nEsteem a man that has me in disdain?\nPray him that never hears my suppliant cry?\nSuffer who hates me o'er my heart to reign?\nOne that his lofty virtues holds so high,\n'Twere need some heaven-born goddess should descend\nFrom realms above, his stubborn heart to bend?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Proud youth!  he knows my worship and my love,\nNor me will have for lover or for slave.\nThe cruel stripling knows what pangs I prove,\nYet will not aid me till I am in my grave.\nNor let me tell my sorrows, lest they move\nHim his perverse and evil will to wave;\nShunning me like malignant asp, that fears\nTo change his mood, if he the charmer hears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  Love, arrest this wight who runs so free,\nOutstripping my slow feet, or me install\nIn the condition whence thou tookest me,\nSuch as I was, ere thine or other's thrall.\n— Alas!  how vain the hope!  that thou shouldst be\nEver to pity moved by suppliant call,\nWho sport, yea feed and live, in streams that rise\nFrom the distracted lover's brimming eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But, woe is me, alas!  and, what can I\nSave my irrational desire lament?\nWhich makes me soar a pitch so passing high,\nI reach a region, where my plumes are brent;\nThen, unsustained, fall headlong from the sky;\nNor ends my woe; on other flight intent,\nAgain I imp my wings, again I soar;\nTo flame and fall, tormented evermore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yea; rather of myself should I complain,\nThan the desire, to which I bared my breast\nWhereby was Reason hunted from her reign,\nAnd all my powers by stronger force opprest.\nThus borne from bad to worse, without a rein,\nI cannot the unbridled beast arrest;\nWho makes me see I to destruction haste,\nThat I more bitterness in death may taste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet, ah!  why blame myself?  Wherein have I\nEver offended, save in loving thee?\nWhat wonder was it then that suddenly\nA woman's feeble sense opprest should be?\nWhy fence and guard myself, lest bearing high,\nWise words, and beauty rare should pleasure me?\nMost wretched is the mortal that would shun\nTo look upon the visage of the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Besides that me my destiny entrained,\nWords, worthy credence, moved me much, that drew\nA picture of rare happiness, ordained\nAs meed of this fair unless to ensue.\nIf these persuasive words were false and feigned,\nIf famous Merlin's counsel was untrue,\nWrath at the wizard may I well profess;\nBut cannot therefore love Rogero less."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Both Merlin and Melissa have I need\nTo blame, and shall for ever blame the twain,\nThat, to exhibit suckers of my seed,\nConjured up spirits from infernal reign,\nWho with this empty hope my fancy feed,\nMe in perpetual bondage to detain.\nNor other cause for this can I suppose,\nSave that they grudge me safe and sweet repose.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sorrow the maid so wholly occupies,\nRoom has she none for comfort or for rest.\nYet, maugre her affliction, Hope will rise,\nAnd form a lodgement in her harassed breast;\nAnd to the damsel's memory still supplies\nRogero's parting words to her addrest;\nSo makes her, in all seeming facts' despite,\nAwait from hour to hour the youthful knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For a month's space beyond those twenty days\nThis hope affords fair Bradamant content:\nHence sorrow not on her so heavy weighs\nAs it would else her harassed soul have shent.\nShe, one day that along the road she strays,\nBy which she oft to meet Rogero went,\nHears tidings, that of Hope — last comfort left —\n(Like every other good her breast bereft. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bound homeward from the hostile camp, where lay\nKing Agramant, she met a Gascon knight,\nA prisoner to those paynims, from the day,\nThat fought nigh Paris was the famous fight.\nThe damsel prest him all he knew to say:\nThen to the point she covets led the knight:\nAsks of Rogero, on that theme abides,\nListens to that, not aught inquires besides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of him a full account did he afford,\nAs well acquainted with the court; he said\nHow, matched with Mandricardo, strove that lord,\nAnd layed the martial king in combat dead.\nAnd how, sore wounded by the Tartar's sword,\nAbove a month the stripling kept his bed:\nAnd had the stranger here but closed his news,\nWell might his tale the missing knight excuse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But then subjoins the Gascon cavalier\nHow in the Moorish camp a damsel lies,\nBy name Marphisa hight, of beauteous cheer,\nBold and as skilled in arms of every guise,\nWho loves Rogero and to him is dear;\nAnd then the host so rarely sundered spies,\nThat every one, throughout the paynim train,\nDeems that betrothed in wedlock are the twain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And hope, when healed shall be the youthful knight,\nThe marriage of those lovers will succeed;\n(For sure with pleasure and sincere delight, ) \n\nThose tidings paynim prince and monarch read:\nSince, knowing either's superhuman might,\nThey augur, from their loins will spring a breed,\nIn little season, which shall pass in worth\nThe mightiest race that ever was on earth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What he rehearsed, the Gascon knight believed,\nNor without cause believed the news he bore,\nA rumour universally received\nAnd bruited through the squadrons of the Moor;\nWho had that notion of their love conceived\nFrom signs of kindness witnessed evermore.\nFor — good or bad — though from one mouth it flows,\nFame to a boundless torrent quickly grows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That she with him had brought the Paynim aid,\nAnd ne'er was seen without the cavalier,\nThe first foundation of the rumour layed:\nBut what confirmed that fame in every ear,\nWas, that she, having from the camp conveyed\nThe thief Brunello (as I sang whilere)\nAs if alone to see Rogero brought,\nHad to the camp returned, uncalled, unsought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She solely to the camp had ta'en her way,\nTo visit him that on a sick-bed smarted;\nNor once alone; but often all the day\nThere passed that maid, and but at eve departed:\nWho gave yet greater cause of her to say,\nThat — known as one so haughty and hard-hearted,\nWho all the world despised — she now was grown\nBenign and humble to the Child alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Bradamant the Gascon's story heard,\nThat lady suffered such tormenting pain,\nSuch cruel woe her inmost bosom stirred,\nFrom falling she preserved herself with pain.\nShe turned her courser round, without a word,\nInflamed with jealousy and fierce disdain:\nFrom her all hope the wretched damsel spurns,\nAnd to her chamber breathing wrath returns."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Turned on her face, her body on the bed,\nArmed as she is, th4e grieving damsel throws,\nAnd that the sad lament by sorrow bred,\nMay be unheard of any, bites the clothes;\nAnd so, repeating what the stranger said,\nTo such a pitcher her smothered anguish grows,\nHer plaints no longer able to restrain,\nSo vents the maid parforce her piteous pain:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Who ever can be trusted?  woe is me!\nAll false and cruel well may be esteemed,\nIf thou, Rogero, false and cruel be,\nThat I so pious and so faithful deemed.\nWhat foul and felon act, what treachery,\nWas ever yet by tragic poet dreamed,\nBut will fall short of thine, if thou wilt set\nThe sum of my desert, against thy debts?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Wherefore, Rogero, since no cavalier\nMates thee in beauteous form and daring feat,\nSince thou in matchless valour hast no peer,\nAnd none with thee in gentleness compete,\nWhy cannot we, 'mid godlike gifts and clear,\nAllow thee truth, thy graces to complete?\nThe praise of spotless truth to thee allow,\nTo which all other virtues yield and bow?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Knowest thou not, without it, worthless are\nAll gentle bearing and all martial might?\nAs there is nothing, howsoever fair,\nThat can be seen without the aid of light.\nEasily mightest thou a maid ensnare,\nLord as thou was, and idol in her sight.\nHer with thy honied words thou might'st have won,\nTo deem that cold and darksome was the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Cruel, what sin can trouble thee, if thou\nDo'st not her murder who loved thee repent?\nIf held so lightly be a breach of vow —\nBeneath what burden will thy heart be bent?\nWhat treatment will thine adversary know,\nIf one who loves like me thou so torment?\nJustice is none in heaven, I well may say,\nIf Heaven its vengeance for my wrongs delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If of all human sins of deepest dye\nBe fell ingratitude; if doomed to smart\nFor this, the fairest angel of the sky\nWas banished into foul and darksome part;\nIf mighty sins for mighty vengeance cry,\nWhere due atonement cleanses not the heart;\nBeware lest thou beneath such vengeance groan,\nIngrate!  that wouldest not thy sin atone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Cruel Rogero, I of theft, beside\nAll other sins, may justly thee arraign.\nThat thou my heart has ravished form my side,\n— Of this offence I will not, I complain —\nBut, having made it mine, that thou defied\nAll right, and took away thy gift again.\nRestore it; well thou know'st what pains requite\nHis sin, who keeps what is another's right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou hast left me, Rogero; thee to leave,\nAlas!  I neither will nor power possess.\nBut will and power have I my life to reave,\nTo scape from this o'erwhelming wretchedness.\nTo die at strife with thee alone I grieve:\nFor, had the gods so pleased my lot to bless,\nAs to require my life, when loved of thee,\nNever so welcome had been death to me.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Resolved to die, 'twas so the damsel cried;\nAnd starting from her bed, by passion warmed,\nTo her left breast her naked sword applied;\nThen recollected she was wholly armed.\nMeanwhile her better Spirit, at her side,\nWith these persuasive words her fury charmed:\n\"O lady, born to such illustrious name!\nWould'st thou conclude thy life with such foul shame?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Were it not better to the field to go,\nWhere aye thy breath with glory may be spent?\nThere, should Rogero chance to lay thee low,\nHe to have slain thee haply may repent;\nBut, should his faulchion deal the mortal blow,\nWhat death could ever yield thee more content?\nReason it were thou should'st by him be slain,\nWho dooms thee living to such passing pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Haply of that Marphisa, too, before\nThou die, thou yet may deadly vengeance take,\nWho with dishonest love and treacherous lore\nDid thy beloved Rogero's fealty shake.\"\nThis seemed to please the mournful lady more\nThan her first thought; and she forthwith bade make\nA mantle for her arms, which should imply\nHer desperation and desire to die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The vest is of that colour which is spied\nIn leaf, when gray and yellow are at strife;\nWhen it is gathered from the branch, or dried\nIs the green blood, that was it's parent's life.\nEmbroidered is the surcoat's outer side\nWith stems of cypress which disdain the knife;\nWhich shoot not, when by biting steel laid low.\nA habit well according with her woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She took the courser that was wont to bear\nAstolpho, and with him the lance of gold,\nBy whose sole touch unhorsed all champions were.\nNeedless anew I deem it to unfold\nWhy by Astolpho given, and when and where,\nOr how that spear obtained the warrior bold.\nThe lady took the lance, but nothing guessed\nOf the stupendous virtue it possessed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Without attendants, without squire, alone,\nThe hill descending by the nearest way,\nToward Paris is the mournful damsel gone,\nWhere camped erewhile the Moorish forces lay;\nFor yet to her the tidings were unknown,\nThat good Rinaldo and his bold array\nHad raised, with Charles' and Malagigi's aid,\nThe siege the paynims had to Paris laid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— Cadurci, and Cahors city left behind —\nBradamant sees the mountain, far and near,\nWhence Dordogne's waters to the valley wind;\nAnd Montferrant's and Clermont's towers appear:\nWhen she, a lady fair, of semblance kind,\nBeholds, by that same road, towards her steer.\nThree knights were nigh, and — at the pommel hung —\nA buckler from the damsel's saddle swung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Before the lady and behind her ride\nMore squires and maids, a numerous company.\nFair Bradamant of one that past beside\nDemanded who the stranger dame might be?\n\"That lady to the king of France\" (replied\nThe squire \"is sent upon an embassy ) \n\nFrom THE LOST ISLE, which lies mid seas that roll\nTheir restless waves beyond the northern pole."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Some THE LOST ISLE, some Iceland call the reign\nWhereof a royal lady fills the throne;\nWhose charms (before those charms all beauties wane)\nAre such as Heaven had dealt to her alone.\nThe shield you see she sends to Charlemagne,\nBut with the pact and purpose plainly shown,\nHe should confer it on the knight, whose worth\nIs, in his judgment, fairest upon earth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She, as she deems herself (and it is true\nShe is the fairest of all womankind),\nA cavalier, that should in heart and thew\nSurpass all other warriors, fain would find;\nResolved, should her a hundred thousand woo,\nNone shall unfix the purpose of her mind;\n— But he, held worthiest by the world's accord,\nAlone shall be her lover and her lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In France, in royal Charles's famous court,\nThe damsel hopes to find the cavalier,\nWho in a thousand feats of high report\nHas shown that he excels each puissant peer.\nAll three are monarchy who the dame escort,\nAnd what their kingdoms ye as well shall hear.\nOne Sweden rules, one Gothland, Norway one;\nSurpast in martial praise by few or none."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"These three, whose kingdoms at some distance lie,\nYet the least distant lie from the LOST ISLE,\n(Because few mariners its shore descry,\nAs little known, that island so they style),\nWooed and yet woo her for a wife, and vie\nIn valour, and, to win the lady's smile,\nIllustrious deeds have done, which Fame shall sound,\nWhile Heaven shall circle in its wonted round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet she not these will wed, nor cavalier\nThat does not, as she deems, all else excell.\n— `Lightly I hold your proof of valour here,'\n(Those northern monarchs was she wont to tell)\n`And if, like sun amid the stars, one peer\nOutshines his fellows, him I honour well:\nBut therefore hold him not, in fierce alarms,\nOf living men the bravest knight at arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `To Charlemagne, whom I esteem and hold\nAs wisest among reigning kings, by me\nShall be dispatched a costly shield of gold,\nOn pact and on condition, that it be\nBestowed on him, deemed boldest of the bold,\nAmid the martial ranks of chivalry.\nServes the king Charlemagne or other lord,\nI will be governed by that king's award."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `If when King Charles the buckler shall receive\nAnd give to one so stout, that best among\nAll others he that warrior shall believe,\nDo they to his or other court belong.\nFor me the golden buckler shall retrieve\nOne of you three, in his own virtue strong;\nMy every love and thought shall he possess;\nHim for my spouse and lord will I confess.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Moved by these stirring speeches, hither hie\nFrom that wide-distant sea, those monarchs bold,\nResolved to win the buckler, or to die\nBeneath his hand who has that shield of gold.\"\nBradamant ponders much the squire's reply:\nHe give his horse the head — his story told —\nAnd plies him so with restless heel and hand,\nHe overtakes the damsel's distant band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After him gallops not, nor hurries ought,\nBradamant, who pursues her road at ease:\nMuch evermore evolving in her thought\nThings that may chance, she finally foresees\nThat through the buckler by that damsel brought,\nWill follow strife and boundless enmities,\nAmid king Charles's peerage and the rest,\nIf with that shield he shall reward the best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This grieved the damsel's heart, but far above\nThat grief, the former fear her heard did goad;\nThat young Rogero had withdrawn his love\nFrom her, and on the warlike queen bestowed.\nSo buried in the thoughts wherewith she strove,\nWas Bradamant, she heeded nor her road,\nNor took she care where, at the close of light,\nTo find befitting shelter for the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As when from squall, or other chance, a barge\nDrives from the river-side, where late it lay,\nUnder no mariner or pilot's charge,\nThe winds and waves at will transport their prey;\nSo Rabican with Bradamant, at large,\n— She musing on Rogero — wends his way.\nFor thence, by many miles, was distant wide\nThat mind which should her courser's bridle guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She raised her eyes at last, and saw the sun\nHad turned his back on Bocchus' towers and wall;\nThen, like a cormorant, his journey done,\nInto his nurse's lap beheld him fall,\nBeyond Marocco; and for her to run\nTo tree, for shelter from the rising squall,\nHad been a foolish thought; for now 'gan blow\nA blustering wind, which threatened rain or snow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To better speed fair Bradamant aroused\nHer courser, yet but little way did ride,\nWhen with his flock, which on the champaign browsed,\nLeaving the fields, a shepherd she espied.\nTo him where, well or ill, she might be housed,\n— With many instances the maid applied —\nFor never house could such ill shelter yield,\nBut that in rain 'twere worse to lodge afield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To her the shepherd said, \"I know of none\nWhereto I could direct you, near at hand.\nAt least six leagues are distant all, but one,\nNamed TRISTRAM'S TOWER, throughout the neighbouring land.\nBut not to all men is the door undone;\nFor it behoves that they, with lance in hand,\nAchieve their footing first and the defend,\nWho to be lodged within its walls pretend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If there be room within, to stranger knight\nThe castellain gives kindly welcome there:\nBut is a lodging claimed by other wight,\nTo joust with all new comers makes him swear:\nIf none, he need not move; but arms and fight\nHe must what stranger thither shall repair;\nAnd he that worst his warlike arms shall ply,\nMust wander forth beneath the naked sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If two. three, four, or more, seek shelter, they\nThat first arrive, in peace their quarters take.\nWho follows, has a harder game to play;\nFor war upon those many must he make.\nSo, if one only in that mansion stay,\nHe with those two, or more, a lance must break.\nThen with as many others as succeed:\nThus he what strength he has shall sorely need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As well, if wife or maid seek that repair,\n(Is she alone, is she accompanied),\nAnd afterwards another, the most fair\nIs housed; that other must without abide.\"\nBradamant asked the kindly shepherd where\nThat castle stood; and he with signs replied\nAs well as words, and pointed with his hand\nWhere, five or six miles wide, the tower did stand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though Rabican's good paces merit praise,\nTo hurry him the damsel had no skill,\nBy those so passing foul and broken ways,\n(By season somewhat rainy rendered ill)\nSo, as to reach the tower, ere Night o'erlays\nThe world, whose every nook dark shadows fill.\nArrived, that lady finds the portal barred,\nAnd that she seeks a lodging tells the guard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He answers that the place is occupied\nBy dame and knight already housed, who, met\nAbout the fire, in that chill evening-tide,\nWait till their supper be before them set.\nTo him that maid: \"The board is not supplied,\nI deem, for them, unless the meal be eat.\nNow, say I wait their coming.\" (she pursues,)\nWho know and will observe your castle's use.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The guard his message bore, where at their ease\nReposed the weary cavaliers; his tale\nNot overlikely was those kings to please;\nFor cold and peevish blew the wintry gale,\nAnd now fast fell the rain; yet, forced to seize\nTheir arms, they slowly don the martial mail.\nThe rest remain within; while they proceed\nAgainst the damsel, but with little speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Three cavaliers they were, of might so tried,\nFew champions but to them in prowess yield,\nThe same that she that very day, beside\nThe courier maid, encountered in the field,\nThey that in Iceland boasted, in their pride,\nTo bear away from France the golden shield:\nWho (for they had the martial maid outrode)\nArrived before her at that lord's abode."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In feats of arms few warriors were more stout;\nBut she besure will be among those few,\nShe, that on no account will wait without,\nFasting and wet, night's weary watches through.\nWithin from window and from lodge, the rout\nLook forth, and will the joust by moonlight view,\nWhich streams from underneath a covering cloud;\nAlbeit the furious rain beats fast and loud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such transport as the longing gallant cheers,\nAbout to seize the stolen fruits of love,\nWhen, after long delay, the listener hears\nThe bold within its socket softly move,\nSuch transport cheered her, of those cavaliers\nThe prowess and the pith a-fire to prove,\nWhen now the opened portals she descried,\nAnd drawbridge dropt, and issuing knights espied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she beheld, how, of the drawbridge clear\nThose knights, together or scarce sundered, came,\nShe took her ground; and next in fierce career,\nWith flowing bridle, drove the furious dame,\nLevelling against those kings that virtuous spear,\nHer cousin's gift, which never missed its aim;\nWhose touch each warrior must unseat parforce;\nYea Mars, should Mars contend in mortal course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king of Sweden, foremost of those knights,\nIn falling too is foremost of the train;\nWith such surpassing force his helmet smites\nThat spear, which never yet was couched in vain.\nGothland's good king next meets the maid, and lights\nWith feet in air, at distance on the plain.\nThe third (unhorsed by Aymon's beauteous daughter)\nHalf buried lies in mire and marshy water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When at three strokes she had unhorsed them all,\nLighting with head on earth and heels in air,\nRetiring from the field, she sought the Hall,\nIn search of lodging; but, ere harboured there,\nTo issue forth, at whosoever's call,\nIs, by the warder's hest, obliged to swear.\nThat lord who well had weighed her famous feats,\nThe damsel with surpassing honour greets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So does by her the lady, that erewhile\nHad thither journeyed, with those monarchs three,\nAs I related, sent from the LOST ISLE\nTo France's king, upon an embassy.\nKind as she is and affable of style,\nShe renders back the stranger's courtesy;\nRises to welcome her with smiling air,\nAnd to the fire conducts that warlike fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As Bradamant unarms, and first her shield,\nAnd after puts her polished casque away,\nA caul of shining gold, wherein concealed\nAnd clustering close, her prisoned tresses lay,\nShe with the helmet doffs; and now revealed,\n(While the long locks about her shoulders play,)\nA lovely damsel by that band is seen,\nNo fiercer in affray than fair of mien."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As when the stage's curtain is uprolled,\nMid thousand lamps, appears the mimic scene,\nAdorned with arch and palace, pictures, gold,\nAnd statues; or, as limpid and serene\nThe sun his visage, glorious to behold,\nUnveils, emerging from a cloudy screen;\nSo when the lady doffs her iron case,\nAll paradise seems opened in her face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already so well-grown and widely spread\nWere the bright tresses which the hermit shore,\nThese, gathered in a knot, behind her head,\nThough shorter than their wont, the damsel wore;\nAnd he, that castle's master, plainly read,\n(Who often had beheld her face before)\nThat this was Bradamant; and now he paid\nYet higher honours to the martial maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With modest and with mirthful talk this while,\nSeated about the fire, they feed the ear;\nAnd in this way the weary time beguile\nTill they are heartened with more solid cheer.\nIf new or ancient were his castle's style,\n(Bradamant asks the courteous cavalier)\nBy whom begun, and how it took its rise?\nAnd thus that castellain to her replies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When Pharamond of France possessed the throne,\nHis son, prince Clodion, had a mistress rare;\nAnd damsel in that ancient age was none\nMore graceful, beauteous, or more debonair;\nSo loved of Pharamond's enamoured son,\nThat he lost sight no oftener of the fair\nThan Io's shepherd of his charge whilere:\nFor jealous as enamoured was the peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her in this mansion, which his sire bestowed,\nHe kept, and rarely issued from his rest:\nWith him were lodged ten cavaliers, allowed\nThrough France to be the boldest and the best.\nHither, while in this castle he abode,\nSir Tristram and a dame their course addrest:\nWhom from a furious giant, in her need,\nShort time before that gentle knight had freed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sir Tristram and his lady reached the Hall,\nWhen now the sun had Seville left behind.\nThey for admission on the porter call,\nSince they for ten miles round no shelter find,\nBut Clodion, that loved much, and was withal\nSore jealous, was determined in his mind\nNo stranger in his keep should ever inn,\nSo long as that fair lady lodged therein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When, after long entreaties made in vain,\nThe castellain refused to house the knight,\nHe said, `What supplication cannot gain,\nI hope to make thee do in they despite';\nAnd loudly challenged him, with all his train,\nThose ten which he maintained, to bloody fight;\nOffering, with levelled lance and lifted glaive,\nTo prove Sir Clodion a discourteous knave;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"On pact, if he sate fast, and overthrown\nShould be the warder, and his warlike rout,\nHe in that castle should be lodged alone,\nAnd Clodion with his knights remain without.\nAgainst him goes the king of France's son,\nAt risque of death, to venge that galling flout;\nBut falls astound; the rest partake his fate,\nAnd on the losers Tristram bars the gate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Entering the tower, he finds her harboured there\nWhereof I spake, so dear in Clodion's eyes;\nWhom SHE had equalled with the loveliest fair,\nNature, so niggard of such courtesies.\nWith her Sir Tristram talks, while fell despair\nAye racks the houseless prince in horrid wise.\nWho prays the conquering knight, with suppliant cry,\nNot to his arms the damsel to deny."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Though she small worth in Tristram's sight possess,\nNor any, saving Yseult, please his sight,\nNor other dame to love or to caress,\nThe philtre, drunk erewhile, allows the knight;\nYet, for he would that foul discourteousness\nOf Clodion with a fit revenge requite,\nHe cries, `I deem it were foul wrong and sore,\nIf so such beauty I should shut the door."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And, should Sir Clodion grieve beneath the tree\nTo lodge alone, and company demand;\nAlthough less beautiful, I have with me\nA fair and youthful damsel, here at hand,\nWho, I am well content, his mate shall be,\nAnd do in all things, as he shall command.\nBut she that is most fair to the most strong,\nMeseemeth, in all justice should belong.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Shut out all night, the moody Clodion strayed,\nPuffing and pacing round his lofty tower,\nAs if that prince the sentinel had played\nOn them, that slept at ease in lordly bower:\nHim, sorer far than wind and cold dismayed\nThat lovely lady's loss in Tristram's power:\nBut he, with pity touched, upon the morrow,\nRendered her back, and so relieved his sorrow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Because, he said, and made it plain appear,\nSuch as he found her, he returned the fair;\nAnd though for his discourtesy whilere,\nClodion had every scorn deserved to bear,\nHe was content with having made the peer\nOutwatch the weary night in open air.\nAccepting not that cavalier's excuse,\nWho would have thrown on Love his castle's use."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For Love should make a churlish nature kind,\nAnd not transform to rude a gentle breast.\nWhen Tristram hence was gone, not long behind\nRemained the enamoured prince who changed his rest:\nBut first he to a cavalier consigned\nThe tower; whereof that baron he possest,\nOn pact, that he and his in the domain\nHenceforth this usage ever should maintain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That cavalier of greater heart and power\nShould in this hall be harboured without fail:\nThey that less worthy were should void the tower,\nAnd seek another inn, by hill or dale.\nIn fine, that law was fixt, which to this hour\nEndures, as you have seen\"; while so his tale\nTo Bradamant recounts that castle's lord,\nThe sewer with savoury meats has heaped the board."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the great hall that plenteous board was laid,\n(None fairer was in all the world beside)\nThen came where those beauteous ladies stayed,\nAnd them, with torches lit, did thither guide.\nOn entering, Bradamant the room surveyed,\nAnd she, that other fair, on every side;\nWho as they gaze about the gorgeous hall\nFilled full of picture, mark each storied wall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So beauteous are the figures, that instead\nOf eating, on the painted walls they stare;\nAlbeit of meat they have no little need,\nWho wearied sore with that day's labour are.\nWith grief the sewer, with grief the cook takes heed,\nHow on the table cools the untasted fare.\nNay, there is one amid the crowd, who cries,\n\"First fill your bellies, and then feast your eyes.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The guests were placed, and now about to eat,\nWhen suddenly bethought that castellain,\nTo house two damsels were a thing unmeet;\nOne lady must dislodge, and one remain;\nThe fairest stay, and she least fair retreat.\nWhere howls the wind, where beats the pattering rain.\nBecause they separate came, 'tis ordered so:\nOne lady must remain, one lady go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lord some matrons of his household crew\nCalls, with two elders, in such judgments wise;\nHe marks the dames, and bids them of the two\nDeclare which is most beauteous in their eyes;\nAnd all, upon examination due,\nCry, Aymon's daughter best deserves the prize,\nAnd vouch as she in might those kings outweighed,\nNo less in beauty she surpassed the maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warder cries to that Islandic dame,\nWho of her sentence has a shrewd suspicion,\n\"O lady, let it be no cause of blame,\nThat we observe our usage and condition;\nTo seek some other rest must be thine aim,\nSince, by our universal band's admission,\nThough unadorned that martial maid be seen,\nThou canst not match her charms and lovely mien.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in a moment's time a cloud obscure\nSteams from the bottom of some marshy dale,\nWhich the sun's visage, late so bright and pure,\nMantles all over with its dingy veil;\nSo that poor damsel, sentenced to endure,\nWithout, the pelting shower and blustering gale,\nIs seen to change her cheer, and is no more\nThe fair and mirthful maid she was before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The maid turns pale, and all her colour flies,\nWho dreads so stern a sentence to obey:\nBut generous Bradamant, in prudent guise,\nWho could not bear to see her turned away,\nCried to that baron, \"Partial and unwise\nYour judgment seems, as well all judgments may,\nWherein the losing party has not room\nTo plead before the judge pronounces doom."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I, who this cause take on me to defend,\nSay (whether fairer or less fair I be)\nI came not as a woman, nor intend\nThat now mine actions shall be womanly.\nBut, saving I undress, who shall pretend\nTo say I am or am not such as she?\nNeither should aught be said but what we know,\nAnd least of all what works another woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Many, as well as I, long tresses wear,\nYet are not therefore women; if, as guest,\nI have admittance gained to your repair,\nLike woman or like man, is manifest:\nThen why should I the name of woman bear,\nThat in my actions stand a man confest?\n'Tis ruled that woman should a woman chase;\nNor that a knight a woman should displace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Grant we (what I confess not howsoe'er)\nThat you the woman in my visage read;\nBut that in beauty I am not her peer:\nNot therefore, deem I, of my valour's meed\nYe would deprive me, though in beauteous cheer\nThe palm I to that damsel should concede\n'Twere hard, before I yield to her in charms,\nThat I should forfeit what I won in arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if it be your usage, that the dame\nWho yields in beauty, from your tower must wend,\nHere to remain I my design to proclaim,\nShould my resolve have good or evil game,\nHence I infer, unequal were the game,\nIf she and I in beauty should contend:\nFor if such strife 'twixt her and me ensues,\nNought can the damsel gain, and much may lose;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And save the gain and loss well balanced be\nIn every match, the contest is unfair.\nSo that by right, no less than courtesy,\nMay she a shelter claim in you repair.\nBut are there any here that disagree,\nAnd to impugn my equal sentence dare,\nBehold my prompt, at such gainsayer's will,\nTo prove my judgment right, his judgment ill!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant — grieved that maid of gentle kind\nShould from that castle wrongfully be sped,\nTo bide the raging of the rain and wind,\nWhere sheltering house was none, nor even shed —\nWith reasons good, in wary speech combined,\nPersuades that lord; but mostly what she said\nOn ending silences the knight; and he\nAllows the justice of that damsel's plea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As when hot summer sun the soil has rived,\nAnd most the thirsty plant of moisture drains,\nThe weak and wasting flower, well nigh deprived\nOf that quick sap which circled in its veins,\nSucks in the welcome rain, and is revived;\nSo, when bold Bradamant so well maintains\nThe courier maid's defence, her beauteous cheer\nAnd mirth revive, and brighten as whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At length the supper, which had long been dight,\nNor yet was touched, enjoys each hungry guest;\nNor any further news of errant knight\nThem, seated at the festive board, molest;\nAll, saving Bradamant, enjoy, whose sprite,\nAs wont, is still afflicted and opprest.\nFor that suspicious fear, that doubt unjust,\nWhich racked her bosom, marred the damsel's gust."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The supper done — brought sooner to a close\nHaply from their desire to feast their eyes —\nFirst of the set, Duke Aymon's daughter rose,\nAnd next the courier maid is seen to rise.\nWith that the warder signs to one, that goes\nAnd many torches fires in nimble wise;\nWhose light on storied wall and ceiling fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto tell.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 33"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant sees in picture future fight\nThere, where she gained admission by the spear.\nFrom combat cease, upon Baiardo's flight,\nGradasso and Montalban's cavalier.\nWhile soaring through the world, the English knight\nArrives in Nubia's distant realm, and here\nDriving the Harpies from the royal board,\nHunts to the mouth of hell that impious horde."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Timagoras, Parrhasius, Polygnote,\nProtogenes, renowned Apollodore,\nTimanthes, and Apelles, first of note,\nZeuxis and others, famed heretofore,\nWhose memory down the stream of Time will float,\nWhile we their wreck and labours lost deplore,\nWhose fame will flourish still in Fate's despite,\n(Grammercy authors! while men read and write. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And those, yet living or of earlier day,\nMantegna, Leonardo, Gian Belline,\nThe Dossi, and, skilled to carve or to pourtray,\nMichael, less man than angel and divine,\nBastiano, Raphael, Titian, who (as they\nUrbino and Venice makes Cadoro shine; ) \n\nWith more, whose works resemble what he hear\nAnd credit of those spirits, famed whilere;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The painters we have seen, and others, who\nThousands of years ago in honour stood,\nThings which had been with matchless pencil drew,\nSome working upon wall, and some on wood.\nBut never, amid masters old or new,\nHave ye of pictures heard or pictures viewed\nOf things to come; yet such have been pourtrayed\nBefore the deeds were done which they displayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet let not artist whether new or old,\nBoast of his skill such wondrous works to make;\nBut leave this feat to spell, wherewith controlled\nThe spirits of the infernal bottom quake.\nThe hall, whereof in other strain I told,\nWith volume sacred to Avernus' lake,\nOr Norsine grot, throught subject Demons' might,\nWas made by Merlin in a single night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That art, whereby those ancient erst pourtrayed\nSuch wonders, is extinguished in our day.\nBut to the troop, by whom will be surveyed\nThe painted chamber, I return, and say;\nA squire attendant on a signal made,\nBore thither lighted torches, by whose ray\nWere scattered from that hall the shades of night,\nNor this in open day had shown more bright."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When thus the castle's lord addressed that crew:\n\"Know, of adventures in this chamber wrought,\nUp to our days, have yet been witnessed few;\nA warfare storied, but its fields unfought.\nWho limned the battles, these as well foreknew.\nHere of defeats to come and victories taught,\nWhate'er in Italy our host befalls\nYou may discern as painted on these walls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The wars, wherein French armies should appear,\nBeyond the Alps, of foul event or fair,\nEven from his days until the thousandth year,\nBy the prophetic Merlin painted were.\nHither Great Britain's monarch sent the seer,\nTo him, that of King Marcomir was heir:\nWhy hither sent, and why this hall was made,\nAt the same time to you shall be displayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"King Pharamond, the first of those that passed\nThe Rhine, amid his Franks' victorious train,\nWhen Gaul was won, bethought him how to cast\nOn restive Italy the curbing rein;\nAnd this; that evermore he wasting fast\nBeheld the Roman empire's feeble reign;\nAnd (for both reigned at once would make accord, ) \n\nTo compass his design, with Britain's lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The royal Arthur, by whom nought was done\nWithout the ripe advice of Merlin sage,\n(Merlin, I say, the Devils mighty son,\nWell versed in what should chance in future age,)\nKnowing through him, to Pharamond made known,\nHe would in many woes his host engage,\nEntering that region, which, with rugged mound,\nApennine parts, and Alp and sea surround."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To him sage Merlin shows, that well nigh all\nThose other monarchs that in France will reign,\nBy murderous steel will see their people fall,\nConsumed by famine, or by fever slain;\nAnd that short joy, long sorrow, profit small,\nAnd boundless ill shall recompense their pain;\nSince vainly will the lily seek to shoot\nIn the Italian fields its withered root."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"King Pharamond so trusted to the seer\nThat he resolved to turn his arms elsewhere;\nAnd Merlin, who beheld with sight as clear\nThe things to be, as things that whilom were,\n'Tis said, was brought by magic art to rear\nThe painted chamber at the monarch's prayer;\nWherein whatever deeds the Franks shall do,\nAs if already done, are plain to view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That king who should succeed, might comprehend,\nAs he renown and victory would obtain,\nWhene'er his friendly squadrons should defend\nFrom all barbarians else the Italian reign;\nSo, if to damage her he should descend,\nThinking to bind her with the griding chain,\n— Might comprehend, I say, and read his doom —\nHow he beyond these hills should find a tomb.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said, he leads the listening ladies where\nThose pictured histories begin; to show\nHow Sigisbert his arms will southward bear\nFor what imperial Maurice shall bestow.\n\"Behold him from the Mount of Jove repair\nThither where Ambra and Ticino flow!\nEutar behold, who not alone repels,\nBut puts the foe to flight, and routs and quells."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Where they with Clovis tread the mountain way,\nMore than a hundred thousand warriors trace;\nSee Benevento's duke the monarch stay,\nWhose thinner files his hostile army face.\nLo!  these who feign retreat an ambush lay.\nLo!  where through danger, havoc, and disgrace,\nThe Franks, who to the Lombard wine-fat hie,\nDrugged by the bait, like poisoned mullets die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Where Childibert the boundary hills has crost,\nHeading what bands of France and captains, see;\nYet shall no more than baffled Clovis boast\nThe conquest or the spoil of Lombardy.\nHeaven's sword descends so heavy on his host.\nChoked with their bodies every road shall be;\nSo pined with watery flux and withering sun,\nThat, out of ten, unharmed returns not one.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He shows King Pepin, shows King Charlemagne;\nHow into Italy their march they bend;\nAnd one and the other fair success obtain,\nBecause her land they came not to offend.\nBut Stephen one, the other Adriane,\nAnd, after, injured Leo, would defend.\nThis quells Astolpho, and that takes his heir,\nAnd re-establishes the papal chair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A youthful Pepin of the royal line\nHe after shows; who seemed to spread his host,\nEven from THE KILNS to the Isle of Palestine;\nAnd with a bridge, achieved at mighty cost,\nAt Malamocco, to bestride the brine,\nAnd on Rialto's shore his battle post.\nThen fly and leave his drowning bands behind,\nHis bridge destroyed by wasting waves and wind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Burgundian Lewis ye behold descend\nThither with his invading squadrons, where,\nVanquishing and taken, nevermore to offend\nWith hostile arms, he is compelled to swear.\nBehold!  he slights his solemn oath — to wend,\nAnew, with reckless steps, into the snare.\nLo!  there he leaves his eyes; and his array,\nBlind as the moldwarp, hence their lord convey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You see him named from Arles, victorious Hugh,\nFrom Italy the Berengari chase!\nWhom, quelled and broken twice and thrice, anew\nNow the Bavarians, now the Huns, replace.\nO'ermatched, he then for peace is fain to sue;\nNor long survives, nor he who fills his place;\nTo Berengarius yielding his domains,\nWho, repossest of all his kingdom, reigns."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You see, her goodly pastor to sustain,\nAnother Charles set fire to Italy;\nWho has two kings in two fierce battles slain,\nManfred and Conradine, and after see\nHis bands, who seem to vex the new-won reign\nWith many wrongs, and who dispersedly\n— Some here, some there — in different cities dwell.\nSlain on the rolling of the vesper-bell.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He shows them next (but after interval,\n'Twould seem, of many and many an age, not years)\nHow through the Alps, a captain out of Gaul,\nTo war upon the great Viscontis, steers;\nAnd seems to straiten Alexandria's wall,\nGirt with his forces, foot and cavaliers:\nA garrison within, an ambuscade\nWithout the works, the warlike duke has laid;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And the French host, decoyed in cunning wise\nThither where the surrounding toils are spread,\nConducted on that evil enterprise\nBy Armagnac, the Gallic squadron's head,\nSlaughtered throughout the spacious champaign lies,\nOr is to Alexandria captive led:\nWhile, swoln not more with water than with blood,\nTanarus purples wide Po's ample flood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Successively that castellain displayed\nOne hight of Marca, of the Anjouites three.\nHow \"Marsi, Daunians, Salentines,\" (he said)\n\"And Bruci, these shall oft molest, you see:\nYet not by Frank or Latian's friendly aid\nShall one delivered from destruction be.\nLo!  from the realm, as oft as they attack,\nAlphonso and Gonsalvo beat them back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You see the eighth Charles, amid his martial train,\nThe flower of France, through Alpine pass has pressed.\nWho Liris fords, and takes all Naples' reign,\nYet draws not sword nor lays a lance in rest:\nAll, save that rock which — Typheus' endless pain —\nLies on the giant's belly, arms, and breast:\nBy Inigo del Guasto here withstood,\nDerived from Avalo's illustrious blood.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warder of the castle, who makes clear\nTo beauteous Bradamant that history,\nSays, having shown her Ischia's island, \"Ere\nI lead you further other things to see,\nI'll tell what my great-grandfather whilere\n— I then a child — was wont to tell to me.\nWhich in like manner (that great-grandsire said),\nAs well to him his father whilome read;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And his from sire or grandsire heard recite;\nSo son from sire; even to that baron, who\nHeard it related by the very wight,\nThat these fair pictures without pencil drew,\nWhich you see painted azure, red, and white.\nHe when to Pharamond (as now to you)\nWas shown the castle on the rocky mount,\nHeard him relate the things I now recount."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Heard him relate, how in that fortilage\nFrom that good knight should spring, who, 'twould appear,\nGuards it so well, he scorns the fires that rage,\nEven to the Pharo, flaming far and near,\nThen, or within short space, and in that age,\n(And named the week and day, as well as year,)\nA noble warrior, unexcelled in worth\nBy other, that has yet appeared on earth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nereus less fair, Achilles was less strong,\nLess was Ulysses famed for daring feat;\nNestor, that knew so much and lived so long,\nLess prudent; nimble Ladas was less fleet;\nLess liberal and less prompt to pardon wrong,\nCaesar, whose praises ancient tales repeat.\nSo that, compared with him, in Ischia born,\nEach might appear of vaunted virtues shorn;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if illustrious Crete rejoiced of old\nIn giving birth to Coelus' godlike heir;\nIf Thebes in Hercules and Bacchus bold,\nIf Delos boasted of her heavenly pair,\nNought should as well this happy isle withhold\nFrom lifting high her glorious head in air,\nWhen that great Marquis shall in her be born,\nWhom with its every grace shall Heaven adorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sage Merlin said — and oft renewed that say —\nHe was reserved to flourish in an age,\nWhen most opprest the Roman empire lay,\nThat he might free that holy heritage:\nBut as some deeds of his I must display\nHereafter, these I will not now presage.\nSo spake that wizard, and renewed the story,\nWhich told of Charlemagne's predestined glory."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lewis, (so learned Merlin said, is woe ) \n\nTo have brought to Italy King Charlemagne,\nWhom he called in to harass, not o'erthrow\nThat ancient rival of his goodly reign;\nAt his return declares himself his foe,\nAnd, leagued with Venice, would the king detain.\nBehold that valiant monarch couch his spear,\nAnd in his foes' despite a passage clear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But his new kingdom leaving to his band,\nFar other destiny awaits that throng:\nFor, with the Mantuan's friendly succour manned,\nGonsalvo to the war returns so strong,\nHe leaves not in few months, by sea or land,\nOne living head, his slaughtered troops among.\nBut then, because of one by treason spent,\nIn him appears the joy of triumph shent.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, to his guests the cavalier\nAlphonso, of Pescara hight, displayed:\n\"Who in a thousand feats will shine more clear\nThan the resplendent carbuncle,\" he said.\n\"Behold, deceived by faithless treaty, here,\nMid snares by the malignant Aethiop laid,\nTransfixt with deadly dart the warrior lies,\nIn whom the age's worthiest champion dies.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Under Italian escort next they see\nWhere the twelfth Lewis o'er the hills is gone;\nHas by its roots uptorn the mulberry,\nAnd in Viscontis' land the lilies sown:\n\"Treading in Charles's steps, by him shall be\nBridges athwart the Garigliano thrown.\nYet after shall he mourn his army's slaughter,\nDispersed and drowning in that fatal water.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "(The lord pursues \"with no less overthrow, ) \n\nBroken in Puglia, see the Gallic train.\nIn him who twice entraps the routed foe,\nGonslavo you behold, the pride of Spain.\nFortune to Lewis a fair face shall show,\nAs late a troubled mien, upon that plain,\nWhich even to where vext Adria pours her tides,\nPo, between Alp and Apennine, divides.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The host reproved himself, while so he said,\nAnd pieced his tale, as having left untold\nThings first in order; next to them displayed\nA royal castle by its warder sold.\nA prisoner by the faithless Switzer made,\nHe shows the lord who hired him with his gold:\nWhich double treason, without couching lance,\nHas given the victory to the king of France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That warder then shows Caesar Borgia, grown\nPuissant in Italy, through this king's grace;\nFor all Rome's peerage, and all lords that own\nHer sway, he into exile seems to chase:\nThen shows the king, that will the saw take down,\nAnd papal acorns in Bologna place:\nThen Genoa's burghers, by this monarch broke,\nAnd rebel city stooping to his yoke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You see,\" (pursued that warder, \"how with dead ) \n\nCovered is Ghiaradada's green champaign.\nIt seems each city opes her gates through dread;\nAnd Venice scarce her freedom can maintain.\nYou see he suffers not the Church's head,\nPassing the narrow confines of Romagne,\nModena from Ferrara's duke to reave;\nWho would not to that prince a remnant leave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nay he Bologna rescues from his sway;\nWhither the Bentivogli them betake.\nYou next see Lewis siege to Brescia lay,\nAnd the close-straitened city storm and take;\nFelsina almost at the same time stay\nWith succour, and the papal army break;\nAnd next, 'twoud seem, that either hostile band\nLies tented upon Chassis' level strand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"On this side France, upon the other Spain,\nExtend their files, and battle rages high;\nFast fall the men at arms in either train,\nAnd the green earth is tinged with crimson dye.\nFlooded with human gore seems every drain;\nMars doubts to whom to give the victory;\nWhen through Alphonso's worth the Spaniards yield,\nAnd the victorious Franks maintain the field;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, for Ravenna sacked and ravaged lies,\nThe Roman pastor bites his lips through woe;\nCalled by him, from the hills, in tempest's guise,\nSwoop the fierce Germans on the fields below.\nIt seems each Frenchman unresisting flies,\nChased by their bands beyond the mountain snow,\nAnd that they set the mulberry's thriving shoot\nThere, whence they plucked the golden lily's root."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Behold the Frank returns, and here behold\nIs broken, by the faithless Swiss betrayed,\nHe, that his royal father seized and sold,\nWhose succour dearly by the youth is paid.\nThose over whom false Fortune's wheel had rolled,\nErewhile, beneath another king arraid,\nYou here behold, preparing to efface\nWith vengeful deed Novara's late disgrace;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And see with better auspices return\nThe valiant Francis, foremost of his train,\nWho so shall break the haughty Switzer's horn,\nThat little short of spent their bands remain;\nAnd them shall nevermore the style adorn,\nUsurped by that foul troop of churlish vein,\nOf scourge of princes, and the faith's defence,\nTo which those rustics rude shall make pretence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  he takes Milan, in the league's despite:\nLo!  with the youthful Sforza makes accord:\nLo!  Bourbon the fair city keeps, in right\nOf Francis, from the furious German horde:\nLo!  while in other high emprize and fight\nElsewhere is occupied his royal lord,\nNor knows the pride and license of his host,\nThrough these the city shall anew be lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  other French who his grandsire's vein\nInherits, not his generous name alone!\nWho by the Church's favour will regain\n— The Gaul expelled — a land which was his own.\nFrance too returns, but keeps a tighter rein,\nNor over Italy, as wont, has flown:\nFor Mantua's noble duke the foe shall stay,\nAnd, at Ticino's passage, bar his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Though on his cheek youth's blossoms scarce appear,\nWorthy immortal glory, Frederick shines;\nAnd well that praise deserves, since by his spear,\nBut more by care and skill, Pavia's lines\nAgainst the French defends that cavalier,\nAnd frustrates the sea-lion's bold designs.\nYou see two marquises, Italia's boast,\nAnd both, alike the terror of our host."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Both of one blood and of one nest they are;\nThe foremost is the bold Alphonso's seed,\nWhom, led by that false black into the snare,\nYou late beheld in purple torrent bleed.\nYou see defeated by his counsel ware,\nHow oft the Franks from Italy recede.\nThe next, of visage so benign and bright,\nIs lord of Guasto and Alphonso hight;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This is that goodly knight, whose praise you heard\nWhen rugged Ischia's island I displayed,\nOf whom sage Merlin, with prophetic word,\nTo Pharamond such mighty matters said;\nWhose birth should to that season be deferred,\nWhen more than ever such a champion's aid,\nAgainst the barbarous enemy's attack,\nVext Italy, and Church, and Empire lack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He in his cousin of Pescara's rear,\n— Prosper Colonna, chief of that emprize —\nMakes the rude Switzer pay Bicocca dear,\nPaid by the Frenchman in yet dearer wise.\nBehold where France prepares for fresh career,\nAnd to repair her many losses tries\nBehold one host on Lombardy descend!\nBehold that other against Naples wend!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Bust she, that moves us like the dust which flies\nBefore the restless wind, which whirls it round,\nLifts if aloft awhile, and from the skies\nBlows back anew the rising cloud to ground,\nTo a hundred thousand swells, in Francis' eyes,\nThe soldiers who Pavia's walls surround.\nThe monarch sees but that which he commands,\nNor marks how wax or waste his leaguering bands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Tis thus that, through the greedy servant's sin,\nAnd easy sovereign's goodness, on his side,\nThe files beneath his banners muster thin,\nWhen in his midnight camp, `to arms,' is cried,\nFor by the wary Spaniards charged within\nHis ramparts is he; foes that with the guide\nOf Avalo's fair lineage, would assay\nTo make to heaven or hell their desperate way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You see the best of the nobility\nOf all fair France extinguished on the field;\nHow many swords, how many lances, see\nThe Spaniards round the valiant monarch wield.\nBehold!  his horse falls under him; yet he\nWill neither own himself subdued, or yield;\nThough to assault him from all sides is run\nBy wrathful bands, and succour there is none."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The monarch well defends him from the foe,\nAll over bathed with blood of hostile vein.\nBut valour stoops at last to numbers; lo!\nThe king is taken, is conveyed to Spain;\nAnd all upon Pescara's lord bestow\nAnd him of that inseparable twain —\nOf Guasto hight — the praise and prime renown\nFor that great king captived and host o'erthrown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This host o'erthrown upon Pavia's plains,\nThat, bound for Naples, halts upon its way:\nAs an ill-nourished lamp or taper wanes,\nFor want of wax or oil, with flickering ray.\nLo!  the king leaves his sons in Spanish chains,\nAnd home returns, his own domain to sway.\nLo!  while in Italy he leads his band,\nAnother wars upon his native land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In every part you see how Rome is woe,\nMid ruthless rapine, murder, fire, and rape.\nSee all to wasting rack and ruin go,\nAnd nothing human or divine escape.\nThe league's men hear the shrieks, behold the glow\nOf hostile fires, and lo! they backward shape\nTheir course, where they should hurry on their way,\nAnd leave the pontiff to his foes a prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lautrec the monarch sends with other bands;\nYet not anew to war on Lombardy;\nBut to deliver from rapacious hands\nThe Church's head and limbs, already free,\nSo slowly he performs the king's commands.\nNext, overrun by him the kingdom see,\nAnd his strong arms against the city turned,\nWherein the Syren's body lies inurned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lo!  the imperial squadrons thither steer,\nAid to the leaguered city to convey;\nAnd lo!  burnt, sunk, destroyed, they disappear,\nEncountered by the Doria in mid-way.\nBehold!  how Fortune light does shift and veer,\nSo friendly to the Frenchman till this day!\nWho slays their host with fever, not with lance;\nNor of a thousand one returns to France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These histories and more the pictures shew,\n(For to tell all would ask too long a strain)\nIn beauteous colours and of different hue;\nSince such that hall, it these could well contain.\nThe painting twice and thrice those guests review,\nNor how to leave them knows the lingering train,\n'Twould seem; perusing oft what they behold\nInscribed below the beauteous work in gold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When with these pictures they their sight had fed,\nAnd talked long while — these ladies and the rest —\nThey to their chambers by that Lord were led,\nWont much to worship every worthy guest.\nAlready all were sleeping, when her bed\nAt last Duke Aymon's beauteous daughter prest.\nShe here, she there, her restless body throws,\nNow right, now left, but vainly seeks repose:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet slumber toward dawn, and in a dream\nThe form of her Rogero seems to view.\nThe vision cries: \"Why vex yourself, and deem\nThings real which are hollow and untrue?\nBackwards shall sooner flow the mountainstream\nThan I to other turn my thought from you.\nWhen you I love not, then unloved by me\nThis heart, these apples of mine eyes, will be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hither have I repaired (it seemed he said)\nTo be baptized and do as I professed.\nIf I have lingered, I have been delaid,\nBy other wound than that of Love opprest.\"\nWith that he vanished from the martial maid,\nAnd with the vision broken was her rest.\nNew floods of tears the awakened damsel shed,\nAnd to herself in this sad fashion said:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What pleased was but a dream; alas!  a sheer\nReality is this my waking bane;\nMy joy a dream and prompt to disappear,\nNo dream my cruel and tormenting pain.\nAh!  wherefore what I seemed to see and hear,\nCannot I, waking, see and hear again?\nWhat ails ye, wretched eyes, that closed ye show\nUnreal good, and open but on woe?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sweet sleep with promised peace my soul did buoy,\nBut I to bitter warfare wake anew;\nSweet sleep but brought with it fallacious joy,\nBut — sure and bitter — waking ills ensue.\nIf falsehood so delight and truth annoy,\nNever more may I see or hear what's true!\nIf sleeping brings me weal, and watching woe,\nThe pains of waking may I never know!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Blest animals that sleep through half the year,\nNor ope your heavy eyelids, night nor day!\nFor if such tedious sleep like death appear,\nSuch watching is like life, I will not say,\nSince — such my lot, beyond all wont, severe —\nI death in watching, life in sleep assay.\nBut oh!  if death such sleep resemble, Death,\nEven now I pray three stop my fleeting breath!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The clouds were gone, the horizon overspread\nWith glowing crimson by the new-born sun,\nAnd in these signs, unlike the past, was read\nA better promise of the day begun:\nWhen Bradamant upstarted from her bed,\nAnd armed her for the journey to be done,\nHer thanks first rendered to the courteous lord,\nFor his kind of cheer and hospitable board."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And found, the lady messenger, with maid\nAnd squire, had issued from the castled hold,\nAnd was a-field, where her arrival stayed\nThose three good warriors, those the damsel bold\nThe eve before had on the champaign laid,\nCast from their horses by her lance of gold;\nAnd who had suffered, to their mighty pain,\nAll night, the freezing wind and pattering rain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Add to such ill, that, hungering sore for food,\nThey and their horses, through the livelong night,\nTrampling the mire, with chattering teeth, had stood:\nBut (what well-nigh engendered more despite\n— Say not well nigh — more moved the warrior's mood)\nWas that they knew the damsel would recite\nHow they had been unhorsed by hostile lance\nIn the first course which they had run in France;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And — each resolved to die or else his name\nForthwith in new encounter to retrieve —\nThat Ulany, the message-bearing dame,\n(Whose style no longer I unmentioned leave),\nA fairer notion of their knightly fame\nThan heretofore, might haply now conceive,\nBold Bradamant anew to fight defied,\nWhen of the drawbridge clear they her descried;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not thinking, howsoe'er, she was a maid,\nWho in no look or act the maid confest;\nDuke Aymon's daughter, loth to be delaid,\nRefuses, as a traveller that is pressed.\nBut they so often and so sorely prayed,\nThat she could ill refuse the kings' request.\nHer lance she levels, at three strokes extends\nAll three on earth, and thus the warfare ends:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For Bradamant no more her courser wheeled,\nBut turned her back upon the foes o'erthrown.\nThey, that intent to gain the golden shield,\nHad sought a land so distant from their own,\nRising in sullen silence from the field\n(For speech with all their hardihood was gone)\nAppeared as stupefied by their surprise,\nNor to Ulania dared to lift their eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For they, as thither they their course addrest,\nHad vaunted to the maid in boasting vein,\nNo paladin or knight with lance in rest,\nAgainst the worst his saddle could maintain.\nTo make them vail yet more their haughty crest,\nAnd look upon the world with less disdain,\nShe tells them, by no paladin or peer\nWere they unhorsed, but by a woman's spear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Now what of Roland's and Rinaldo's might,\nNot without reason held in such renown,\nOught you to think (she said when thus in fight ) \n\nYe by a female hand are overthrown?\nSay, if the buckler one of these requite,\n— Better than by a woman ye have done,\nWill ye by those redoubted warriors do?\nSo think not I, nor haply think so you."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This may suffice you all; and need in none\nA clearer proof of prowess to display;\nAnd who desires, if rashly any one\nDesires, again his valour to assay,\nWould add but scathe to shame, now made his own;\nNow; and the same to-day as yesterday.\nUnless perchance he thinks it praise and gain,\nBy such illustrious warriors to be slain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When they by Ulany were certified\nA woman's hand had caused their overthrow,\nWho with a deeper black than pitch had dyed\nTheir honour, heretofore so fair of show;\nAnd more than ten her story testified,\nWhere one sufficed — with such o'erwhelming woe\nWere they possest, they with such fury burned,\nThey well nigh on themselves their weapons turned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What arms they had upon them, they unbound,\nAnd cast them, strung by rage and fury sore,\nInto the moat which girt that castle round,\nNor even kept the faulchions which they wore;\nAnd, since a woman them had cast to ground,\nO'erwhelmed with rage and shame, the warriors swore,\nThemselves of such a crying shame to clear,\nThey, without bearing arms, would pass a year;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And that they evermore afoot would fare\nUp hill or down, by mountain or by plain,\nNor, when the year was ended, would they wear\nThe knightly mail or climb the steed again;\nSave that from other they by force should bear,\nIn battle, other steeds and other chain.\nSo, without arms, to punish their misdeeds,\nThese wend a-foot, those others on their steeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lodged in a township at the fall of night,\nDuke Aymon's daughter, journeying Paris-ward,\nHears how King Agramant was foiled in fight.\nGood harbourage withal of bed and board,\nShe in her hostel found; but small delight\nThis and all comforts else to her afford.\nFor the sad damsel meat and sleep foregoes,\nNor finds a resting place; far less repose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But so I will not on her story dwell,\nAs not to seek anew the valiant twain;\nWho, by consent, beside a lonely well,\nHad tied their goodly coursers by the rein.\nI of their war to you somedeal will tell,\nA war not waged for empire or domain,\nBut that the best should buckle to his side\nGood Durindana, and Baiardo ride."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No signal they, no trumpet they attend,\nTo blow them to the lists, no master who\nShould teach them when to foin and when to fend,\nOr wake their sleeping wrath; their swords they drew:\nThen, one against the other, boldly wend,\nWith lifted blades, the quick and dextrous two.\nAlready 'gan the champions' fury heat,\nAnd fast and hard their swords were heard to beat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "None e'er by proof two other faulchions chose\nFor sound and solid, able to endure\nThree strokes alone of such conflicting foes,\nPassing all means and measure; but so pure,\nSo perfect was their temper, from all blows\nBy such repeated trial so secure,\nThey in a thousand strokes might clash on high,\n— Nay more, nor yet the solid metal fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With mickle industry, with mighty pain\nAnd art, Rinaldo, shifting here and there,\nAvoids the deadly dint of Durindane,\nWell knowing how 'tis wont to cleave and tear.\nGradasso struck with greater might and main,\nBut well nigh all his strokes were spent in air;\nOf, if he sometimes smote, he smote on part,\nWhere Durindana wrought less harm than smart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo with more skill his blade inclined,\nAnd stunned the arm of Sericana's lord.\nHim oft he reached where casque and coat confined,\nAnd often raked his haunches with the sword:\nBut adamantine was his corslet's rind,\nNor link the restless faulchion broke or bored.\nIf so impassive was the paynim's scale,\nKnow, charmed by magic was the stubborn mail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Without reposing they long time had been,\nUpon their deadly battle so intent,\nThat, save on one another's troubled mien,\nTheir angry eyes the warriors had not bent.\nWhen such despiteous war and deadly spleen,\nDiverted by another strife, were spent,\nHearing a mighty noise, both champions turn,\nAnd good Baiardo, sore bested, discern."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They good Baiardo by a monster view,\n— A bird, and bigger than that courser — prest.\nAbove three yards in length appeared to view\nThe monster's beak; a bat in all the rest.\nEquipt with feathers, black as ink in hue,\nAnd piercing talons was the winged pest;\nAn eye of fire it had, a cruel look,\nAnd, like ship-sails, two spreading pinions shook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Perhaps it was a bird; but when or where\nAnother bird resembling this was seen\nI know not, I, nor have I any where,\nExcept in Turpin, heard that such has been.\nHence that it was a fiend, to upper air\nEvoked from depths of nether hell I ween;\nWhich Malagigi raised by magic sleight,\nThat so he might disturb the champions' fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So deemed Rinaldo too: and contest sore\n'Twixt him and Malagigi hence begun;\nBut he would not confess the charge; nay swore,\nEven by the light which lights the glorious sun,\nThat he might clear him of the blame he bore,\nHe had not that which was imputed done.\nWhether a fiend or fowl, the pest descends,\nAnd good Baiardo with his talons rends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Quickly the steed, possessed of mickle might,\nBreaks loose, and, in his fury and despair,\nAgainst the monster strives with kick and bite;\nBut swiftly he retires and soars in air:\nHe thence returning, prompt to wheel and smite,\nCircles and beats the courser, here and there.\nWholly unskilled in fence, and sore bested,\nBaiardo swiftly from the monster fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Baiardo to the neighbouring forest flies,\nSeeking the closest shade and thickest spray;\nAbove the feathered monster flaps, with eyes\nIntent to mark where widest is the way.\nBut that good horse the greenwood threads, and lies\nAt last within a grot, concealed from day.\nWhen the winged beast has lost Baiardo's traces.\nHe soars aloft, and other quarry chases."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo and Gradasso, who descried\nBaiardo's flight, the conqueror's destined meed,\nThe battle to suspend, on either side,\nTill they regained the goodly horse, agreed,\nSaved from that fowl which chased him, far and wide;\nConditioning whichever found the steed,\nWith him anew should to that fountain wend,\nBeside whose brim their battle they should end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Quitting the fount, they follow, where they view\nNew prints upon the forest greensward made:\nBy much Baiardo distances the two,\nWhose tardy feet their wishes ill obeyed.\nHimself the king on his Alfana threw,\nThat near at hand was tethered in the glade,\nLeaving his foe behind in evil plight;\n— Never more malcontent and vext in sprite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo ceased in little time to spy\nBaiardo's traces, who strange course had run;\nAnd made for thorny thicket, wet or dry,\nTree, rock, or river, with design to shun\nThose cruel claws, which, pouncing from the sky,\nTo him such outrage and such scathe had done.\nRinaldo, after labour vain and sore\nTo await him at the fount returned once more;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In case, as erst concerted by the twain,\nThe king should thither with the steed resort;\nBut having sought him there with little gain,\nFared to his camp afoot, with piteous port.\nReturn we now to him of Sericane,\nHe that had sped withal in other sort,\nWho, not by judgement, guided to his prey,\nBut his rare fortune, heard Baiardo neigh;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And found him shrowded in his caverned lair,\nSo sore moreover by his fright opprest,\nHe feared to issue into open air.\nThus of that horse himself the king possest.\nWell he remembered their conditions were\nTo bring him to the fount; but little pressed\nNow was that knight to keep the promise made,\nAnd thus within himself in secret said:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Win him who will, in war and strife, I more\nDesire in peace to make the steed my own:\nFrom the world's further side, did I of yore\nWend hitherward, and for this end alone.\nHaving the courser, he mistakes me sore,\nThat thinks the prize by me will be foregone.\nHim would Rinaldo conquer, let him fare\nTo Ind, as I to France have made repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For him no less secure is Sericane,\nThan twice for me has been his France,\" he said,\nAnd pricked for Arles, along the road most plain,\nAnd in its haven found the fleet arrayed.\nFreighted with him, the steed and Durindane,\nA well-rigged galley from that harbour weighed.\nOf these hereafter! — I, at other call,\nNow quit Rinaldo, king, and France, and all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho in his flight will I pursue,\nThat made his hippogryph like palfrey flee,\nWith reins and sell, so quick the welkin through;\nThat hawk and eagle soar a course less free.\nO'er the wide land of Gaul the warrior flew\nFrom Pyrenees to Rhine, from sea to sea.\nHe westward to the mountains turned aside,\nWhich France's fertile land from Spain divide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Arragon he past out of Navarre,\n— They who beheld, sore wondering at the sight —\nThen, leaves he Tarragon behind him far,\nUpon his left, Biscay upon his right:\nTraversed Castile, Gallicia, Lisbon, are\nSeville and Cordova, with rapid flight;\nNor city on sea-shore, nor inland plain,\nIs unexplored throughout the realm of Spain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beneath him Cadiz and the strait he spied,\nWhere whilom good Alcides closed the way;\nFrom the Atlantic to the further side\nOf Egypt, bent o'er Africa, to stray;\nThe famous Balearic isles descried,\nAnd Ivica, that in his passage lay;\nToward Arzilla then he turned the rein,\nAbove the sea that severs it from Spain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Morocco, Fez, and Oran, looking down,\nHippona, Argier, he, and Bugia told,\nWhich from all cities bear away the crown,\nNo palm or parsley wreath, but crown of gold;\nNoble Biserta next and Tunis-town,\nCapys, Alzerba's isle, the warrior bold,\nTripoli, Berniche, Ptolomitta viewed,\nAnd into Asia's land the Nile pursued."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twixt Atlas' shaggy ridges and the shore,\nHe viewed each regions in his spacious round;\nHe turned his back upon Carena hoar,\nAnd skimmed above the Cyrenaean ground;\nPassing the sandy desert of the Moor,\nIn Albajada, reached the Nubian's bound;\nLeft Battus' tomb behind him on the plain,\nAnd Ammon's, now dilapidated, fane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To other Tremizen he posts, where bred\nAs well the people are in Mahound's style;\nFor other Aethiops then his pinions spread,\nWhich face the first, and lie beyond the Nile.\nBetween Coallee and Dobada sped,\nBound for the Nubian city's royal pile;\nThreading the two, where, ranged on either land,\nMoslems and Christians watch, with arms in hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In Aethiopia's realm Senapus reigns,\nWhose sceptre is the cross; of cities brave,\nOf men, of gold possest, and broad domains,\nWhich the Red Sea's extremest waters lave.\nA faith well nigh like ours that king maintains,\nWhich man from his primaeval doom may save.\nHere, save I err in what their rites require,\nThe swarthy people are baptized with fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho lighted in the spacious court,\nIntending on the Nubian king to wait.\nLess strong than sumptuous is the wealthy fort,\nWherein the royal Aethiop keeps his state,\nThe chains that serve the drawbridge to support,\nThe bolts, the bars, the hinges of the gate,\nAnd finally whatever we behold\nHerewrought in iron, there is wrought in gold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "High prized withal, albeit it so abound,\nIs that best metal; lodges built in air\nWhich on all sides the wealthy pile surround,\nClear colonnades with crystal shafts upbear.\nOf green, white, crimson, blue and yellow ground,\nA frieze extends below those galleries fair.\nHere at due intervals rich gems combine,\nAnd topaz, sapphire, emerald, ruby shine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In wall and roof and pavement scattered are\nFull many a pearl, full many a costly stone.\nHere thrives the balm; the plants were ever rare,\nCompared with these, which were in Jewry grown,\nThe musk which we possess from thence we bear,\nIn fine those products from this clime are brought,\nWhich in our regions are so prized and sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The soldan, king of the Egyptian land,\nPays tribute to this sovereign, as his head,\nThey say, since having Nile at his command\nHe may divert the stream to other bed.\nHence, with its district upon either hand,\nForthwith might Cairo lack its daily bread.\nSenapus him his Nubian tribes proclaim;\nWe Priest and Prester John the sovereign name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of all those Aethiop monarchs, beyond measure,\nThe first was this, for riches and for might;\nBut he with all his puissance, all his treasure,\nAlas!  had miserably lost his sight.\nAnd yet was this the monarch's least displeasure;\nVexed by a direr and a worse despite;\nHarassed, though richest of those Nubian kings,\nBy a perpetual hunger's cruel stings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whene'er to eat or drink the wretched man\nPrepared, by that resistless need pursued,\nForthwith — infernal and avenging clan —\nAppeared the monstrous Harpies' craving brood;\nWhich, armed with beak and talons, overran\nVessel and board, and preyed upon the food;\nAnd what their wombs suffice not to receive\nFoul and defiled the loathsome monsters leave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this, because upborn by such a tide\nOf full blown honours, in his unripe age,\nFor he excelled in heart and nerve, beside\nThe riches of his royal heritage,\nLike Lucifer, the monarch waxed in pride,\nAnd war upon his maker thought to wage.\nHe with his host against the mountain went,\nWhere Egypt's mighty river finds a vent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon this hill which well-nigh kissed the skies,\nPiercing the clouds, the king had heard recite,\nWas seated the terrestrial paradise,\nWhere our first parents flourished in delight.\nWith camels, elephants, and footmen hies\nThither that king, confiding in his might;\nWith huge desire if peopled be the land\nTo bring its nations under his command."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "God marred the rash emprise, and from on high\nSent down an angel, whose destroying sword\nA hundred thousand of that chivalry\nSlew, and to endless night condemned their lord.\nEmerging, next, from hellish caverns, fly\nThese horrid harpies and assault his board;\nWhich still pollute or waste the royal meat,\nNor leave the monarch aught to drink or eat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And him had plunged in uttermost despair\nOne that to him erewhile had prophesied\nThe loathsome Harpies should his daily fare\nLeave unpolluted only, when astride\nOf winged horse, arriving through the air,\nAn armed cavalier should be descried.\nAnd, for impossible appears the thing,\nDevoid of hope remains the mournful king."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now that with wonderment his followers spy\nThe English cavalier so make his way,\nO'er every wall, o'er every turret high,\nSome swiftly to the king the news convey.\nWho calls to mind that ancient prophecy,\nAnd heedless of the staff, his wonted stay,\nThrough joy, with outstretched arms and tottering feet,\nComes forth, the flying cavalier to meet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within the castle court Astolpho flew,\nAnd there, with spacious wheels, on earth descended;\nThe king, conducted by his courtly crew,\nBefore the warrior knelt, with arms extended,\nAnd cried: \"Thou angel send of God, thou new\nMessiah, if too sore I have offended,\nFor mercy, yet, bethink thee, 'tis our bent\nTo sin, and thine to pardon who repent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Knowing my sin, I ask not, I, to be\n— Such grace I dare not ask — restored to light;\nFor well I ween such power resides in thee,\nAs Being accepted in thy Maker's sight.\nLet it suffice, that I no longer see,\nNor let me with perpetual hunger fight.\nAt least, expel the harpies' loathsome horde,\nNor let them more pollute my ravaged board;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And I to build thee, in my royal hold,\nA holy temple, made of marble, swear,\nWith all its portals and its roof of gold,\nAnd decked, within and out, with jewels rare.\nHere shall thy mighty miracle be told\nIn sculpture, and thy name the dome shall bear.\"\nSo spake the sightless king of Nubia's reign,\nAnd sought to kiss the stranger's feet in vain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor angel\" — good Astolpho made reply —\n\"Nor new Messiah, I from heaven descend;\nNo less a mortal and a sinner I,\nTo such high grace unworthy to pretend.\nTo slay the monsters I all means will try,\nOr drive them from the realm which they offend.\nIf I shall prosper, be thy praises paid\nTo God alone, who sent me to thine aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Offer these vows to God, to him well due;\nTo him thy churches build, thine altars rear.\"\nDiscoursing so, together wend the two,\n'Mid barons bold, that king and cavalier.\nThe Nubian prince commands the menial crew\nForthwith to bring the hospitable cheer;\nAnd hopes that now the foul, rapacious band,\nWill not dare snatch the victual from his hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Forthwith a solemn banquet they prepare\nWithin the gorgeous palace of the king.\nSeated alone here guest and sovereign are,\nAnd the attendant troop the viands bring.\nBehold!  a whizzing sound is heard in air,\nWhich echoes with the beat of savage wing.\nBehold!  the band of harpies thither flies,\nLured by the scent of victual from the skies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All bear a female face of pallid dye,\nAnd seven in number are the horrid band;\nEmaciated with hunger, lean, and dry;\nFouler than death; the pinions they expand\nRagged, and huge, and shapeless to the eye;\nThe talon crook'd; rapacious is the hand;\nFetid and large the paunch; in many a fold,\nLike snake's, their long and knotted tails are rolled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The fowls are heard in air; then swoops amain\nThe covey well nigh in that instant, rends\nThe food, o'erturns the vessels, and a rain\nOf noisome ordure on the board descends.\nTo stop their nostrils king and duke are fain;\nSuch an insufferable stench offends.\nAgainst the greedy birds, as wrath excites,\nAstolpho with his brandished faulchion smites."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At croup or collar now he aims his blow,\nNow strikes at neck or pinion; but on all,\nAs if he smote upon a bag of tow,\nThe strokes without effect and languid fall.\nThis while nor dish nor goblet they forego;\nNor void those ravening fowls the regal hall,\nTill they have feasted full, and left the food\nWaste or polluted by their rapine rude."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That king had firmly hoped the cavalier\nWould from his royal seat the harpies scare.\nHe now, that hope foregone, with nought to cheer,\nLaments, and sighs, and groans in his despair.\nOf his good horn remembers him the peer,\nWhose clangours helpful aye in peril are,\nAnd deems his bugle were the fittest mean\nTo free the monarch from those birds unclean;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And first to fill their ears, to king and train,\nWith melted wax, Astolpho gives command;\nThat every one who hears the deafening strain\nMay not in panic terror fly the land.\nHe takes the reins, his courser backs again,\nGrasps the enchanted bugle in his hand;\nAnd to the sewer next signs to have the board\nAnew with hospitable victual stored."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The meats he to an open galley bears,\nAnd other banquet spreads on other ground.\nBehold, as wont, the harpy-squad appears;\nAstolpho quickly lifts the bugle's round;\nAnd (for unguarded are their harassed ears)\nThe harpies are not proof against the sound;\nIn terror form the royal dome they speed,\nNor meat nor aught beside the monsters heed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After them spurs in haste the valiant peer:\nAnd on the winged courser forth is flown,\nLeaving beneath him, in his swift career,\nThe royal castle and the crowded town;\nThe bugle ever pealing, far and near.\nThe harpies fly toward the torrid zone;\nNor light until they reach that loftiest mountain\nWhere springs, if anywhere, Nile's secret fountain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Almost at that aerial mountain's feet,\nDeep under earth, extends a gloomy cell.\nThe surest pass for him, as they repeat,\nThat would at any time descend to hell.\nHither the predatory troop retreat,\nAs a safe refuge from the deafening yell.\nAs far, and farther than Cocytus' shore\nDescending, till that horn is heard no more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At that dark hellish inlet, which a way\nOpens to him who would abandon light,\nThe terrifying bugle ceased to bray;\n— The courser furled his wings and stopt his flight.\nBut, ere Astolpho further I convey,\n— Not to depart from my accustomed rite —\nSince on all sides the paper overflows,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto and repose.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 34"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the infernal pit Astolpho hears\nOf Lydia's woe, by smoke well-nigh opprest.\nHe mounts anew, and him his courser bears\nTo the terrestrial paradise addrest.\nBy John advised in all, to heaven he steers;\nOf some of his lost sense here repossest,\nOrlando's wasted wit as well he takes,\nSees the Fates spin their threads, and earthward makes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "O fierce and hungry harpies, that on blind\nAnd erring Italy so full have fed!\nWhom, for the scourge of ancient sins designed,\nHaply just Heaven to every board has sped.\nInnocent children, pious mothers, pined\nWith hunger, die, and see their daily bread,\n— The orphan's and the widow's scanty food —\nFeed for a single feast that filthy brood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Too foul a fault was his, who did unclose\nThat cave long shut, and made the passage free,\nFrom whence that greediness, that filth arose,\nOur Italy's infection doomed to be.\nThen was good life extinguished, and repose\nSo banished, that with strife and poverty,\nWith fear and trouble, is she still perplext,\nAnd shall for many a future year be vext:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Till she her sons has shaken by the hair,\nAnd from Lethaean sloth to life restored;\nExclaiming, \"Will none imitate that pair,\nZethes and Calais, with avenging sword\nRescue from claws and stench our goodly fare,\nAnd cleanse and glad anew the genial board.\nAs they king Phineus from those fowls released,\nAnd England's peer restored the Nubian's feast?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hunting those hideous birds, that cavalier\nAye scared them with the bugle's horrid sound;\nTill at the mountain-cave his long career\nHe closed, and ran the monstrous troop to ground:\nAttentive to the vent he held his ear,\nAnd in that troubled cavern heard rebound,\nWeeping and wailing, and eternal yell;\nProof certain that its entrance led to hell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho doubts if he within shall wend,\nAnd see those wretched ones expelled from day;\nInto the central pit of earth descend,\nAnd the infernal gulfs around survey.\n\"Why should I fear, that on my horn depend\nFor certain succour?\" (did the warrior say)\n\"Satan and Pluto so will I confound,\nAnd drive before me their three-headed hound.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He speedily his winged horse forsook;\n(Him to a sapling near at hand he ties)\nThe cavern entered next; but first he took\nHis horn, whereon the knight in all relies.\nNot far has he advanced before a smoke,\nObscure and foul, offends his nose and eyes.\nRanker than pitch and sulphur is the stench,\nYet not thereat does good Astolpho blench."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But as he more descends into that lair,\nSo much he finds the smoke and vapour worse;\nAnd it appears he can no further fare;\nNay, backward must retrace his way parforce.\nLo!  something (what he knows not he in air ) \n\nEspies, that seems in motion, like a corse,\nUpon whose wasted form long time had beat\nThe winter's rain and summers scorching heat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In that dim cavern was so little light,\n— Yea, well-nigh might be said that light was none —\nNought sees or comprehends the English knight\nWhat wavers so, above that vapour dun:\nFor surer proof, a stroke or two would smite\nWith his good faulchion Otho's valiant son:\nThen deemed that duke it was a spirit, whom\nHe seemed to strike amid the misty gloom."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When him a melancholy voice addressed;\n\"Ah! without harming other, downward wend.\nMe but too sore the sable fumes molest,\nWhich hither form the hellish fires ascend.\"\nThereat the duke, amazed, his steps represt,\nAnd to the spirit cried: \"So may Heaven send\nA respite from the vapours that exhale,\nAs thou shalt deign to tell thy mournful tale!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And to be known on earth shouldst thou be fain,\nThee will I satisfy.\"  To him the sprite:\nSo sweet it seems to me, in fame again\nThus to return into the glorious light,\nMy huge desire such favour to obtain,\nForces my words from me in my despite,\nConstraining me to tell the things ye seek;\nThough 'tis annoyance and fatigue to speak."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Lydia, the child of Lydia's king, am I,\nTo proud estate and princely honours born,\nCondemned by righteous doom of God on high\nIn murky smoke eternally to mourn:\nBecause a kindly lover's constancy\nI, while I lived, repaid with spite and scorn.\nWith countless others swarm these grots below,\nFor the same sin, condemned to the same woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet lower down, harsh Anaxarete\nSuffers worse pain where thicker fumes arise;\nHeaven changed her flesh to stone, and here to be\nTormented, her afflicted spirit sties:\nIn that unmoved she, hung in air, could see\nA lover vest by her barbarities.\nHere Daphne learns how rashly she had done\nIn having given Apollo such a run.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of hosts of ingrate women in this cell\nConfined, it would be tedious to recite,\nIf, one by one, I upon these should dwell;\nSo many, their amount is infinite.\n'Twould be more tedious of the men to tell,\nWhose base ingratitude due pains requite;\nAnd whom, in a more dismal prison pent,\nSmoke blinds, and everlasting fires torment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Since to belief soft woman is more prone,\nHe that deceives her, merits heavier pain;\nTo Theseus and to Jason this is known,\nAnd him that vexed of old the Latian reign,\nAnd him that of his brother Absalon\nErewhile provoked the pestilent disdain,\nBecause of Thamar; countless is the horde\nOf those who left a wife or wedded lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But, rather of my state than theirs to shew,\nAnd sin which brought me hither: — I was fair,\nBut so much haughtier was than fair of hue,\nI know not if I ever equalled were:\nNor which was most excessive of the two,\nMy pride of beauty, could to thee declare.\nThough it is certain, Pride but took its rise\nIn that rare loveliness which pleased all eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"There lived a Thracian knight, for warlike skill\nAnd prowess, upon earth without a peer;\nWho, voiced by many a worthy witness still,\nThe praises of my matchless charms did hear.\nSo that, of forethought and his own free will,\nFixed all his love on me that cavalier;\nWeening this wife that I, upon my part,\nShould for his valour duly prize his heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He came to Lydia, and by faster tie\nWas fettered at my sight; and there enrolled\nAmid my royal father's chivalry,\nIn mickle fame increased that baron bold.\nHis feats of many a sort, and valour high\nWould make a tale too tedious to be told;\nWith what his boundless merit had deserved,\nIf a more grateful master he had served."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Pamphylia, Caria, and Cilicia's reign,\nThrough him, my father brought beneath his sway,\nWho never moved a-field his martial train,\nBut when that warrior pointed out the way:\nHe, when he deemed he had deserved such gain,\nPressed close the Lydian king, upon a day,\nAnd craved me from the monarch as his wife,\nAs meed of all that booty made in strife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Rejected of the monarch was the peer,\nWho was resolved his child should highly wed;\nNot him who was a simple cavalier;\nWho, saving valour, was with nought bested.\nFor on my father, bent on gain and gear\nAnd avarice, of all vice the fountain-head,\nManners and merit for as little pass,\nAs the lute's music on the lumpish ass."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alcestes, he of whom I speak (so hight\nThat warrior), when he sees his suit denied,\nRepulsed by one, by whom he had most right\nTo think that he should most be gratified,\nCraves his discharge, and threatens he this slight\nWill make the Lydian monarch dear abide.\nThe Armenian, an old rival of my sire,\nAnd mortal for, he sought with this desire;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And so the monarch urged, he made him rear\nHis banner, and attack my sire; and, through\nHis famous feats, that Thracian cavalier\nWas named the captain of the invading crew.\nFor the Armenian sovereign, far and near,\nAll things (so said the knight he would subdue; ) \n\nBut claiming as his share, when all was won,\nMy sovereign beauties for the service done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I ill to you the mischief could express\nAlcestes did us in that war; o'erthrown\nBy him four armies were, and he in less\nThan one short twelvemonth left us neither town,\nNot tower, save one, where cliffs forbade access:\n'Twas here my sire, amid those of his own\nWhom most he loved, took refuge, in his need,\nWith all the wealth he could collect with speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Us in this fortilage the knight attacked,\nAnd shortly to such desperation drave,\nThat gladly would the king have made a pact,\nTo yield me for his consort, yea his slave,\nWith half our realm, if certain by that act\nHimself from every other loss to save;\nRight sure he otherwise should forfeit all,\nAnd, after, die in bonds, a captive thrall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Before this happened, to try every way\nOf remedy the Lydian king was bent;\nAnd thither, where Alcestes' army lay,\nMe, the first cause of all the mischief, sent.\nTo yield my person to him as a prey\nI with intention to Alcestes went;\nTo bid him take what portion of our reign\nHe pleased, and pacify his fierce disdain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When of my coming that good knight does know,\nMe he encounters pale and trembling sore:\n'Twould seem a vanquished man's a prisoner's brow,\nHe, rather than a victor's semblance, bore.\nI who perceive he loves, address not now\nThe warrior as I was resolved before.\nMy vantage I descry, and shift my ground,\nTo fit the state wherein that knight was found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To curse the warrior's passion I begun,\nAnd of his crying cruelty complained,\nSince foully by my father had he done,\nAnd me would have by violence constrained;\nWho with more grace my person would have won,\nNor waited many days, had he maintained\nHis course of courtship, as begun whilere.\nTo king and all of us so passing dear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if the honest suit he hoped to gain\nHad been at first rejected by my sire,\n'Twas, he was somedeal of a churlish vein,\nNor ever yielded to a first desire;\nHe should not therefore, restive to the rein,\nHave left his goodly task, so prompt to ire;\nSure, passing aye from good to better deed,\nIn little time to win the wished-for meed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if my father would not have been won,\nTo him I would so earnestly have prayed,\nThat he my lover should have made his son;\nNay, had my royal sire my suit gainsayed,\nFor him in secret that I would have done,\nWherewith he should have deemed himself appaid:\nBut since, it seemed, he other means designed,\nNever to love him had I fixed my mind;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, though I sought him, at my father's hest,\nAnd pious love for him had been my guide,\nHe might be sure, not long should be possest\nThe bliss that I, in my despite, supplied;\nFor the red blood should issue from my breast\nAs soon as his ill will was satisfied\nOn this my wretched person, which alone\nHe so by brutal force should make his own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With these, and words like these, I moved the peer,\nWhen I such puissance in myself espied;\nAnd him so contrite made, in desert drear,\nWas never seen a saint more mortified.\nBefore my feet the doleful cavalier\nFell down, and snatched a poniard from his side;\nWhich, he protested, I parforce should take,\nAnd for so foul a sin my vengeance slake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To push my mighty victory to an end\nI scheme, when him I see in such distress,\nAnd give him hopes he may even yet pretend\nThat I deservedly his love should bless,\nIf he his ancient error will amend,\nWill of his realm my father repossess,\nAnd will in future time deserve my charms\nBy love and service, not by force of arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So promised he to do; and set me free,\nAnd let me, as I came, untouched, depart;\nNor even to kiss my lips he ventured; see\nIf he is yoked securely, if his heart\nLove has well touched with the desire of me,\nIf he for him need feather other dart!\nHe seeks the Armenian, why by pact should take\nWhatever spoil the conquering armies make;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And him, as best he might, would fain persuade\nTo leave to Lydia's monarch his domain,\nUpon whose wasted lands his host had preyed,\nAnd rest content with his Armenian reign.\n— He would not hear of this (the monarch said,\nWith cheers with fury swolen nor would refrain ) \n\nFrom pressing Lydia's king with armed band,\nSo long as he possessed a palm of land;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if the knight, when a vile woman sues,\nHis purpose shift, let him the evil bear:\nHe will not, for the warrior's asking, lose\nWhat he has hardly conquered in a year.\nAlcestes to the king his suit renews,\nAnd next complains, that he rejects his prayer.\nAt length the Thracian fires, and threatens high,\nBy love or force the monarch shall comply."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So kindling anger waxed between the two,\nIt urged them from ill words to worser deed:\nUpon the king his sword Alcestes drew;\nThough thousands aid the monarch in his need,\nAnd, in despite of all, their sovereign slew;\nAnd made that day as well the Armenian bleed,\nBacked by the Thracians' and Cilicians' aid\nAnd other followers, by the warrior paid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His conquest he pursued, and, at his cost,\nWithout expense to us, in less than one\nShort month, the kingdom by my father lost\nRestored; and, to repair the mischief done,\n(Beside spoil given he conquered with his host, ) \n\n— Taxing or taking what his arms had won —\nArmenia and Cappadocia which confine;\nAnd scowered Hyrcania to the distant brine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Him not to greet with triumphs, but to slay,\nReturning from that warfare, we intend;\nBut, fearing failure, our design delay\nIn that we find too many him befriend.\nFeeding him aye with hope from day to day,\nI for the Thracian warrior love pretend:\nBut first declare my will that he oppose\nAnd prove his valour on our other foes;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And him, now sole, now ill accompanied,\nOn strange and perilous emprize I speed;\nWherein a thousand knights might well have died;\nBut all things happily with him succeed:\nFor Victory was ever on his side;\nAnd oft with horrid foes of monstrous breed,\nWith Giants and with Lestrigons, who brought\nDamage in our domains, the warrior fought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor Juno, nor Eurystheus, in such chase\nEver renowned Alcides vext so sore,\nIn Erymanth, Nemaea, Lerna, Thrace,\nAetolia, Africa, by Tyber's shore,\nBy Ebro's sunny bank, or other place,\nAs (hiding murderous hate, while I implore)\nI exercise my lover still in strife,\nWith the same fell design upon his life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Unable to achieve my first intent,\nI on a scheme of no less mischief fall:\nThrough me, all deemed his friends by him are shent,\nWho thus bring down on him the hate of all.\nThe Thracian leader never more content\nThan to obey, whatever be the call,\nIs at my bidding ever prompt to smite,\nWithout regarding who or what the wight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When I perceive that, through the warrior's mean,\nExtinguished is my father's every foe;\nAnd, conquered by himself, that knight is seen\n— Friendless, through us — I now the masque forego;\nWhat I, from him, beneath a flattering mien,\nHad hitherto concealed, I plainly show;\n— What deep and deadly hate by bosom fired,\nAnd that I but to work his death desired."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then, thinking if such course I should pursue,\nThat public shame would still the deed attend,\n(For men too well my obligations knew,\nAnd would be prompt my cruelty to shend.)\nMeseemed enough to drive him from my view,\nSo that he should no more my eyes offend:\nNor would I more address or see the peer,\nNor letter would receive or message hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This my ingratitude in him such pain\nAt length produced, that mastered by his woe,\nAfter entreating mercy long in vain,\nHe sickened sore and sank beneath the blow.\nFor pain which fits my sin, dark fumes now stain\nMy cheek, and with salt rheum mine eyes o'erflow.\nThus in eternal torment shall I dwell;\nFor saving mercy helpeth not in hell.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since wretched Lydia spake no more, the peer\nWould fain discern if more in torment lay;\nBut, those false ingrates' curse, the darkness drear\nSo waxed before him, and obscured the way,\nThat not one inch advanced the cavalier;\nNay, back parforce returns that warrior; nay,\nHimself from that increasing smoke to save,\nMakes for the mouth of the disastrous cave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The motion of his quickly shifting feet\nMore savours of a run than walk or trot.\nThus mounting the ascent in swift retreat,\nAstolpho sees the outlet of the grot;\nWhere, through the darkness of that dismal seat\nAnd those foul fumes, a dawn of daylight shot;\nHe from the cavern, sorely pained and pined,\nIssues at last, and leaves the smoke behind;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And next to bar the way against that band,\nWhose greedy bellies so for victual crave,\nPicks stones, and trees lays level with his brand,\nWhich charged with pepper or amomum wave;\nAnd what might seem a hedge, with busy hand,\nAs best he can, constructs before the cave;\nAnd so succeeds in blocking that repair,\nThe harpies shall no more revisit air."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While in that cave Astolpho did remain,\nThe fumes that from the sable pitch arose,\nNot only what appeared to sight did stain;\nBut even so searched the flesh beneath his clothes,\nHe sought some cleansing stream, long sought in vain;\nBut found at length a limpid till, which rose\nOut of a living rock, within that wood,\nAnd bathed himself all over in the flood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then backed the griffin-horse, and soared a flight\nWhereby to reach that mountain's top he schemes,\nWhich little distant, with its haughty height,\nFrom the moon's circle good Astolpho deems;\nAnd, such desire to see it warms the knight,\nThat he aspires to heaven, nor earth esteems.\nThrough air so more and more the warrior strains,\nThat he at last the mountain-summit gains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here sapphire, ruby, gold, and topaz glow,\nPearl, jacinth, chrysolite and diamond lie,\nWhich well might pass for natural flowers which blow,\nCatching their colour from that kindly sky.\nSo green the grass!  could we have such below,\nWe should prefer it to our emerald's dye.\nAs fair the foliage of those pleasant bowers!\nWhose trees are ever filled with fruit and flowers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Warble the wanton birds in verdant brake,\nAzure, and red, and yellow, green and white.\nThe quavering rivulet and quiet lake\nIn limpid hue surpass the crystal bright.\nA breeze, which with one breath appears to shake,\nAye, without fill or fall, the foliage light,\nTo the quick air such lively motion lends,\nThat Day's oppressive noon in nought offends;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this, mid fruit and flower and verdure there,\nEvermore stealing divers odours, went;\nAnd made of those mixt sweets a medley rare,\nWhich filled the spirit with a calm content.\nIn the mid plain arose a palace fair,\nWhich seemed as if with living flames it brent.\nSuch passing splendour and such glorious light\nShot from those walls, beyond all usage bright."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither where those transparent walls appear,\nWhich cover more than thirty miles in measure,\nAt ease and slowly moved the cavalier,\nAnd viewed the lovely region at his leisure;\nAnd deemed — compared with this — that sad and drear,\nAnd seen by heaven and nature with displeasure,\nWas the foul world, wherein we dwell below:\nSo jocund this, so sweet and fair in show!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astound with wonder, paused the adventurous knight,\nWhen to that shining palace he was nigh,\nFor, than the carbuncle more crimson bright,\nIt seemed one polished stone of sanguine dye.\nO mighty wonder!  O Daedalian sleight!\nWhat fabric upon earth with this can vie?\nLet them henceforth be silent, that in story\nExalt the world's seven wonders to such glory!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "An elder, in the shining entrance-hall\nOf that glad house, towards Astolpho prest;\nCrimson his waistcoat was, and white his pall;\nVermillion seemed the mantle, milk the vest:\nWhite was that ancient's hair, and white withal\nThe bushy beard descending to his breast;\nAnd from his reverend face such glory beamed,\nOf the elect of Paradise he seemed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, with glad visage, to the paladin,\nWho humbly, from his sell had lighted, cries:\n\"O gentle baron, that by will divine\nHave soared to this terrestrial paradise!\nAlbeit nor you the cause of your design,\nNor you the scope of your desire surmise,\nBelieve, you not without high mystery steer\nHitherward, from your arctic hemisphere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You for instruction, how to furnish aid\nTo Charles and to the Church in utmost need,\nWith me to counsel, hither are conveyed,\nWho without counsel from such distance speed.\nBut, son, ascribe not you the journey made\nTo wit or worth; nor through your winged steed,\nNor through your virtuous bugle had ye thriven,\nBut that such helping grace from God was given."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"We will discourse at better leisure more,\nAnd you what must be done shall after hear;\nBut you that, through long fast, must hunger sore,\nFirst brace your strength with us, with genial cheer.\"\nContinuing his discourse, that elder hoar\nRaised mighty wonder in the cavalier,\nWhen he avouched, as he his name disclosed,\nThat he THE HOLY GOSPEL, had composed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He of our Lord so loved, the blessed John;\nOf whom a speech among the brethren went,\nHe never should see death, and hence the Son\nOf God with this rebuke St. Peter shent;\nIn saying, \"What is it to thee, if one\nTarry on earth, till I anew be sent?\"\nAlbeit he said not that he should not die,\nThat so he meant to say we plain descry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Translated thither, he found company,\nThe patriarch Enoch, and the mighty seer\nElias; nor as yet those sainted three\nHave seen corruption, but in garden, clear\nOf earth's foul air, will joy eternity\nOf spring, till they angelic trumpets hear,\nSounding through heaven and earth, proclaim aloud\nChrist's second advent on the silvery cloud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The holy ancients to a chamber lead,\nWith welcome kind, the adventurous cavalier;\nAnd in another then his flying steed\nSufficiently with goodly forage cheer.\nAstolpho they with fruits of Eden feed,\nSo rich, that in his judgment 'twould appear,\nIn some sort might our parents be excused\nIf, for such fruits, obedience they refused."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When with that daily payment which man owes,\nNature had been contented by the peer,\nAs well of due refreshment as repose,\n(For all and every comfort found he here)\nAnd now Aurora left her ancient spouse,\nNot for his many years to her less dear,\nRising from bed, Astolpho at his side\nThe apostle, so beloved of God, espied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much that not lawfully could here be shown,\nTaking him by the hand, to him he read.\n\"To you, though come from France, may be unknown\nWhat there hath happened,\" next the apostle said;\n\"Learn, your Orlando, for he hath foregone\nThe way wherein he was enjoined to tread,\nIs visited of God, that ever shends\nHim whom he loveth best, when he offends:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, your Orlando, at his birth endowed\nWith sovereign daring and with sovereign might,\nOn whom, beyond all usage, God bestowed\nThe grace, that weapon him should vainly smite,\nBecause he was selected from the crowd\nTo be defender of his Church's right.\nAs he elected Sampson, called whilere\nThe Jew against the Philistine to cheer;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He, your Orlando, for such gifts has made\nUnto his heavenly Lord an ill return:\nWho left his people, when most needing aid,\nThen most abandoned to the heathens' scorn.\nIncestuous love for a fair paynim maid\nHad blinded so that knight, of grace forlorn,\nThat twice and more in fell and impious strife\nThe count has sought his faithful cousin's life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hence God hath made him mad, and, in this vein,\nBelly, and breast, and naked flesh expose;\nAnd so diseased and troubled is his brain,\nThat none, and least himself, the champion knows,\nNebuchadnezzar whilom to such pain\nGod in his vengeance doomed, as story shows;\nSent, for seven years, of savage fury full,\nTo feed on grass and hay, like slavering bull."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But yet, because the Christian paladine\nHas sinned against his heavenly Maker less,\nHe only for three months, by will divine,\nIs doomed to cleanse himself of his excess.\nNor yet with other scope did your design\nOf wending hither the Redeemer bless,\nBut that through us the mode you should explore,\nOrlando's missing senses to restore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Tis true to journey further ye will need,\nAnd wholly must you leave this nether sphere;\nTo the moon's circle you I have to lead,\nOf all the planets to our world most near,\nBecause the medicine, that is fit to speed\nInsane Orlando's cure, is treasured here.\nThis night will we away, when over head\nHer downward rays the silver moon shall shed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In talk the blest apostle is diffuse\nOn this and that, until the day is worn:\nBut when the sun is sunk i' the salt sea ooze,\nAnd overhead the moon uplifts her horn,\nA chariot is prepared, erewhile in use\nTo scower the heavens, wherein of old was borne\nFrom Jewry's misty mountains to the sky,\nSainted Elias, rapt from mortal eye."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Four goodly coursers next, and redder far\nThan flame, to that fair chariot yokes the sire;\nWho, when the knight and he well seated are,\nCollects the reins; and heavenward they aspire.\nIn airy circles swiftly rose the car,\nAnd reached the region of eternal fire;\nWhose heat the saint by miracle suspends,\nWhile through the parted air the pair ascends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The chariot, towering, threads the fiery sphere,\nAnd rises thence into the lunar reign.\nThis, in its larger part they find as clear\nAs polished steel, when undefiled by stain;\nAnd such it seems, or little less, when near,\nAs what the limits of our earth contain:\nSuch as our earth, the last of globes below,\nIncluding seas, which round about it flow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here doubly waxed the paladin's surprize,\nTo see that place so large, when viewed at hand;\nResembling that a little hoop in size,\nWhen from the globe surveyed whereon we stand,\nAnd that he both his eyes behoved to strain,\nIf he would view Earth's circling seas and land;\nIn that, by reason of the lack of light,\nTheir images attained to little height."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here other river, lake, and rich champaign\nAre seen, than those which are below descried;\nHere other valley, other hill and plain,\nWith towns and cities of their own supplied;\nWhich mansions of such mighty size contain,\nSuch never he before of after spied.\nHere spacious hold and lonely forest lay,\nWhere nymphs for ever chased the panting prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, that with other scope had thither soared,\nPauses not all these wonder to peruse:\nBut led by the disciple of our Lord,\nHis way towards a spacious vale pursues;\nA place wherein is wonderfully stored\nWhatever on our earth below we lose.\nCollected there are all things whatsoe'er,\nLost through time, chance, or our own folly, here."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor here alone of realm and wealthy dower,\nO'er which aye turns the restless wheel, I say:\nI speak of what it is not in the power\nOf Fortune to bestow, or take away.\nMuch fame is here, whereon Time and the Hour,\nLike wasting moth, in this our planet prey.\nHere countless vows, here prayers unnumbered lie,\nMade by us sinful men to God on high:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The lover's tears and sighs; what time in pleasure\nAnd play we here unprofitably spend;\nTo this, of ignorant men the eternal leisure,\nAnd vain designs, aye frustrate of their end.\nEmpty desires so far exceed all measure,\nThey o'er that valley's better part extend.\nThere wilt thou find, if thou wilt thither post,\nWhatever thou on earth beneath hast lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, passing by those heaps, on either hand,\nOf this and now of that the meaning sought;\nFormed of swollen bladders here a hill did stand,\nWhence he heard cries and tumults, as he thought.\nThese were old crowns of the Assyrian land\nAnd Lydian — as that paladin was taught —\nGrecian and Persian, all of ancient fame;\nAnd now, alas!  well-nigh without a name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Golden and silver hooks to sight succeed,\nHeaped in a mass, the gifts which courtiers bear,\n— Hoping thereby to purchase future meed —\nTo greedy prince and patron; many a snare,\nConcealed in garlands, did the warrior heed,\nWho heard, these signs of adulation were;\nAnd in cicalas, which their lungs had burst,\nSaw fulsome lays by venal poets versed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Loves of unhappy end in imagery\nOf gold or jewelled bands he saw exprest;\nThen eagles' talons, the authority\nWith which great lords their delegates invest:\nBellows filled every nook, the fume and fee\nWherein the favourites of kings are blest:\nGiven to those Ganymedes that have their hour,\nAnd reft, when faded is their vernal flower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "O'erturned, here ruined town and castle lies,\nWith all their wealth: \"The symbols\" (said his guide)\n\"Of treaties and of those conspiracies,\nWhich their conductors seemed so ill to hide.\"\nSerpents with female faces, felonies\nOf coiners and of robbers, he descried;\nNext broken bottles saw of many sorts,\nThe types of servitude in sorry courts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He marks mighty pool of porridge spilled,\nAnd asks what in that symbol should be read,\nAnd hears 'twas charity, by sick men willed\nFor distribution, after they were dead.\nHe passed a heap of flowers, that erst distilled\nSweet savours, and now noisome odours shed;\nThe gift (if it may lawfully be said)\nWhich Constantine to good Sylvester made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A large provision, next, of twigs and lime\n— Your witcheries, O women! — he explored.\nThe things he witnessed, to recount in rhyme\nToo tedious were; were myriads on record,\nTo sum the remnant ill should I have time.\n'Tis here that all infirmities are stored,\nSave only Madness, seen not here at all,\nWhich dwells below, nor leaves this earthly ball."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He turns him back, upon some days and deeds\nTo look again, which he had lost of yore;\nBut, save the interpreter the lesson reads,\nWould know them not, such different form they wore.\nHe next saw that which man so little needs,\n— As it appears — none pray to Heaven for more;\nI speak of sense, whereof a lofty mount\nAlone surpast all else which I recount."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It was as 'twere a liquor soft and thin,\nWhich, save well corked, would from the vase have drained;\nLaid up, and treasured various flasks within,\nLarger or lesser, to that use ordained.\nThat largest was which of the paladin,\nAnglantes' lord, the mighty sense contained;\nAnd from those others was discerned, since writ\nUpon the vessel was ORLANDO'S WIT."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The names of those whose wits therein were pent\nHe thus on all those other flasks espied.\nMuch of his own, but with more wonderment,\nThe sense of many others he descried,\nWho, he believed, no dram of theirs had spent;\nBut here, by tokens clear was satisfied,\nThat scantily therewith were they purveyed;\nSo large the quantity he here surveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Some waste on love, some seeking honour, lose\nTheir wits, some, scowering seas, for merchandise,\nSome, that on wealthy lords their hope repose,\nAnd some, befooled by silly sorceries;\nThese upon pictures, upon jewels those;\nThese on whatever else they highest prize.\nAstrologers' and sophists' wits mid these,\nAnd many a poet's too, Astolpho sees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since his consent the apostle signified\nWho wrote the obscure Apocalypse, his own\nHe took, and only to his nose applied,\nWhen (it appeared it to its place was gone; ) \n\nAnd henceforth, has Sir Turpin certified,\nThat long time sagely lived king Otho's son;\nTill other error (as he says again ) \n\nDeprived the gentle baron of his brain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The fullest vessel and of amplest round\nWhich held the wit Orlando erst possessed,\nAstolpho took; nor this so light he found,\nAs it appeared, when piled among the rest.\nBefore, from those bright spheres, now earthward bound,\nHis course is to our lower orb addressed,\nHim to a spacious palace, by whose side\nA river ran, conducts his holy guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Filled full of fleeces all its chambers were,\nOf wool, silk, linen, cotton, in their hue,\nOf diverse dyes and colours, foul and fair.\nYarns to her reel from all those fleeces drew,\nIn the outer porch, a dame of hoary hair.\nOn summer-day thus village wife we view,\nWhen the new silk is reeled, its filmy twine\nWind from the worm, and soak the slender line."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A second dame replaced the work when done\nWith other; and one bore it off elsewhere;\nA third selected from the fleeces spun,\nAnd mingled by that second, foul from fair.\n\"What is this labour?\" said the peer to John;\nAnd the disciple answered Otho's heir,\n\"Know that the Parcae are those ancient wives,\nThat in this fashion spin your feeble lives."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As long as one fleece lasts, life in such wise\nEndureth, nor outlasts it by a thought.\nFor Death and Nature have their watchful eyes\nOn the hour when each should to his end be brought.\nThe choicest threads are culled for Paradise,\nAnd, after, for its ornaments are wrought;\nAnd fashioned from the strands of foulest show\nAre galling fetters for the damned below.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On all the fleeces that erewhile were laid\nUpon the reel, and culled for other care,\nThe names were graved on little plates, which made\nOf silver, or of gold, or iron, were,\nThese piled in many heaps he next surveyed;\nWhence an old man some skins was seen to bear,\nWho, seemingly unwearied, hurried sore,\nHis restless way retracing evermore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That elder is so nimble and so prest,\nThat he seems born to run; he bears away\nOut of those heaps by lapfulls in his vest\nThe tickets that the different names display.\nWherefore and whither he his steps addrest,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto say,\nIf you, in sign of pleasure, will attend,\nWith that kind audience ye are wont to lend.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 35"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The apostle praises authors to the peer.\nDuke Aymon's martial daughter in affray,\nConquers the giant monarch of Argier,\nAnd of the good Frontino makes a prey.\nShe next from Arles defies her cavalier,\nAnd, while he marvels who would him assay,\nGrandonio and Ferrau she with her hand\nAnd Serpentine unhorses on the strand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Madonna, who will scale the high ascent\nOf heaven, to me my judgment to restore,\nWhich, since from your bright eyes the weapon went,\nThat pierced my heart, is wasting evermore?\nYet will not I such mighty loss lament,\nSo that it drain no faster than before;\nBut — ebbing further — I should fear to be\nSuch as Orlando is described by me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To have anew that judgment, through the skies,\nI deem there is no need for me to fly\nTo the moon's circle, or to Paradise;\nFor, I believe, mine is not lodged so high.\nOn your bright visage, on your beauteous eyes,\nAlabastrine neck, and paps of ivory,\nWander my wits, and I with busy lip,\nIf I may have them back, these fain would sip."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho wandered through that palace wide,\nObserving al the future lives around:\nWhen those already woven he had spied\nUpon the fatal wheel for finish wound,\nHe a fair fleece discerned that far outvied\nFine gold, whose wondrous lustre jewels ground,\nCould these into a thread be drawn by art,\nWould never equal by the thousandth part."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The beauteous fleece he saw with wondrous glee\nEqualled by none amid that countless store;\nAnd when and whose such glorious life should be,\nLonged sore to know.  \"This,\" (said the apostle hoar,\nConcealing nothing of its history,)\n\"Shall have existence twenty years before,\nDating from THE INCARNATE WORD, the year\nShall marked my men with M and D appear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, as for splendor and for substance fair,\nThis fleece shall have no like or equal, so\nShall the blest age wherein it shall appear\nBe singular in this our world below;\nBecause all graces, excellent and rare,\nWhich Nature or which Study can bestow,\nOr bounteous Fortune upon men can shower,\nShall be its certain and eternal dower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Between the king of rivers' horns,\" (he cries,)\n\"Stands what is now a small and humble town.\nBefore it runs the Po, behind it lies\nA misty pool of marsh; this — looking down\nThe stream of future years — I recognize\nFirst of Italian cities of renown;\nNot only famed for wall and palace rare,\nBut noble ways of life and studies fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Such exaltation, reached so suddenly,\nIs not fortuitous nor wrought in vain;\nBut that is may his worthy cradle be,\nWhereof I speak, shall so the heaven ordain.\nFor where men look for fruit they graff the tree,\nAnd study still the rising plant to train;\nAnd artist uses to refine the gold\nDesigned by him the precious gem to hold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor ever, in terrestrial realm, so fine\nAnd fair a raiment spirit did invest,\nAnd rarely soul so great from realms divine\nHas been, or will be, thitherward addrest,\nAs that whereof THE ETERNAL had design\nTo fashion good Hippolytus of Este:\nHippolytus of Este shall he be hight,\nOn whom so rich a gift of God shall light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"All those fair graces, that, on many spent,\nWould have served many wholly to array,\nAre all united for his ornament,\nOf whom thou hast entreated me to say.\nTo prop the arts, the virtues is he sent;\nAnd should I seek his merits to display,\nSo long a time would last my tedious strain,\nOrlando might expect his wits in vain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas so Christ's servant with the cavalier\nDiscoursed; they having satisfied their view\nWith sight of that fair mansion, far and near,\nThat whence conveyed were human lives, the two\nIssued upon the stream, whose waves appear\nTurbid with sand and of discoloured hue;\nAnd found that ancient man upon the shore,\nWho names, engraved on metal, thither bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I know not if you recollect; of him\nI speak, whose story I erewhile suspended,\nAncient of visage, and so swift of limb,\nThat faster far than forest stag he wended.\nWith names he filled his mantle to the brim,\nAye thinned the pile, but ne'er his labour ended;\nAnd in that stream, hight Lethe, next bestowed,\nYea, rather cast away, his costly load."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say, that when upon the river side\nArrives that ancient, of his store profuse,\nHe all those names into the turbid tide\nDischarges, as he shakes his mantle loose.\nA countless shoal, they in the stream subside;\nNor henceforth are they fit for any use;\nAnd, out of mighty myriads, hardly one\nIs saved of those which waves and sand o'errun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Along that river and around it fly\nVile crows and ravening vultures, and a crew\nOf choughs, and more, that with discordant cry\nAnd deafening din their airy flight pursue;\nAnd to the prey all hurry, when from high\nThose ample riches they so scattered view;\nAnd with their beak or talon seize the prey:\nYet little distance they their prize convey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When they would raise themselves in upward flight,\nThey have not strength the burden to sustain;\nSo that parforce in Lethe's water light\nThe worthy names, which lasting praise should gain.\nTwo swans there are amid those birds, as white,\nMy lord, as is your banner's snowy grain;\nWho catch what names they can, and evermore\nWith these return securely to the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus, counter to that ancient's will malign,\nWho them to the devouring river dooms,\nSome names are rescued by the birds benign;\nWasteful Oblivion all the rest consumes.\nNow swim about the stream those swans divine,\nNow beat the buxom air with nimble plumes,\nTill, near that impious river's bank, they gain\nA hill, and on that hill a hallowed fane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Immortality 'tis sacred; there\nA lovely nymph, that from the hill descends,\nTo the Lethean river makes repair;\nTakes from those swans their burden, and suspends\nThe names about an image, raised in air\nUpon a shaft, which in mid fane ascends;\nThere consecrates and fixes them so fast,\nThat all throughout eternity shall last."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of that old sire, and why he would dispense\nIdly, all those fair names, as 'twould appear,\nAnd of the birds and holy place, from whence\nThe nymph was to the river seen to steer,\nThe solemn mystery, and the secret sense,\nAstolpho, marvelling, desired to hear;\nAnd prayed the man of God would these unfold,\nWho to the warrior thus their meaning told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"There moves no leaf beneath, thou hast to know,\nBut here above some sign thereof we trace;\nSince all, in Heaven above or Earth below,\nMust correspond, though with a different face.\nThat ancient, with his sweeping beard of snow,\nBy nought impeded and so swift of pace,\nWorks the same end and purpose in our clime,\nAs are on earth below performed by Time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The life of man its final close attains,\nWhen on the wheel is wound the fatal twine;\nThere fame, and here above the mark remains;\nFor both would be immortal and divine,\nBut for that bearded sire's unwearied pains,\nAnd his below, that for their wreck combine.\nOne drowns them, as thou seest, mid sand and surges.\nAnd one in long forgetfulness immerges."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And even, as here above, the raven, daw,\nVulture, and divers other birds of air,\nAll from the turbid water seek to draw\nThe names, which in their sight appear most fair;\nEven thus below, pimps, flatterers, men of straw,\nBuffoons, informers, minions, all who there\nFlourish in courts, and in far better guise\nAnd better odour, than the good and wise;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And by the crowd are gentle courtiers hight,\nBecause they imitate the ass and swine:\nWhen the just Parcae or (to speak aright)\nVenus and Bacchus cut their master's twine,\n— These base and sluggish dullards, whom I cite —\nBorn but to blow themselves with bread and wine,\nIn their vile mouths awhile such names convey,\nThen drop the load, which is Oblivion's prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But as the joyful swans, that, singing sweet,\nConvey the medals safely to the fane,\nSo they whose praises poets well repeat,\nAre rescued from oblivion, direr pain\nThan death.  O Princes, wary and discreet,\nThat wisely tread in Caesar's steps, and gain\nAuthors for friends!  They, doubt it not, shall save\nYour noble names from Lethe's laxy wave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Rare as those gentle swans are poets too,\nThat well the poet's name have merited,\nAs well because it is Heaven's will, that few\nGreat rulers should the paths of glory tread,\nAs through foul fault of sordid lordlings, who\nLet sacred Genius beg his daily bread;\nWho putting down the Virtues, raise the tribe\nOf Vices, and the liberal arts proscribe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Believe it, that these ignorant men should be\nBlind and deprived of judgment, is God's doom;\nWho makes them loathe the light of poetry,\nThat envious Death may wholly them consume.\nBesides that Song can quicken and set free\nHim that is prisoned in the darkness tomb,\nThough foul his name, if Cirrha him befriend.\nIts savour myrrh and spikenard shall transcend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Aeneas not so pious, nor of arm\nSo strong Achilles, Hector not so bold,\nWas, as 'tis famed; and mid the nameless swarm,\nThousands and thousands higher rank might hold:\nBut gift of palace and of plenteous farm,\nBestowed by heirs of them, whose deeds they told,\nHave moved the poet with his honoured hand,\nTo place them upon Glory's highest stand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Augustus not so holy and benign\nWas as great Virgil's trumpet sounds his name,\nBecause he savoured the harmonious line.\nHis foul proscription passes without blame.\nThat Nero was unjust would none divine,\nNor haply would he suffer in his fame,\nThough Heaven and Earth were hostile, had he known\nThe means to make the tuneful tribe his own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Homer a conqueror Agamemnon shows,\nAnd makes the Trojan seem of coward vein,\nAnd from the suitors, faithful to her vows,\nPenelope a thousand wrongs sustain:\nYet — would'st thou I the secret should expose? —\nBy contraries throughout the tale explain:\nThat from the Trojan bands the Grecian ran;\nAnd deem Penelope a courtezan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What fame Eliza, she so chaste of sprite,\nOn the other hand, has left behind her, hear!\nWho widely is a wanton baggage hight,\nSolely that she to Maro was not dear,\nMarvel not this should cause me sore despite,\nAnd if my speech diffusive should appear.\nAuthors I love, and pay the debt I owe,\nSpeaking their praise; an author I below!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"There earned I, above all men, what no more\nTime nor yet Death from me shall take away;\nAnd it behoved our Lord, of whom I bore\nSuch testimony, so my paints to pay.\nIt grieves me much for them, on whom her door\nCourtesy closes on a stormy day;\nWho meagre, pale, and worn with hopeless suit,\nKnock night and day, and ever without fruit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Henceforth with that apostle let the peer\nRemain; for I have now to make a spring\nAs far as 'tis from heaven to earth; for here\nI cannot hang for ever on the wing.\nI to the dame return, who was whilere\nWounded by jealousy with cruel sting.\nI left her where, successively o'erthrown,\nThree kings she quickly upon earth had strown;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And afterwards arriving in a town,\nAt eve, which on the road to Paris lay,\nHeard tidings of Rinaldo's victory blown;\nAnd how in Arles the vanquished paynim lay.\n— Sure, her Rogero with the king is gone —\nAs soon as reappears the dawning day,\nTowards fair Provence, whither (as she hears)\nKing Charlemagne pursues, her way she steers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She towards Provence, by the nearest road,\nSo journeying, met a maid of mournful air;\nWho, though her cheeks with tears were overflowed,\nWas yet of visage and of manners fair.\nShe was it, so transfixed with Love's keen goad,\nWho sighed for Monodante's valiant heir,\nWho at the bridge had left her lord a thrall,\nWhen with King Rodomont he tried a fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She sought one of an otter's nimbleness,\nBy water and by land, a cavalier\nSo fierce, that she that champion — to redress\nHer wrongs — might match against the paynim peer.\nWhen good Rogero's lady, comfortless,\nTo that fair dame, as comfortless, drew near,\nHer she saluted courteously, and next\nDemanded by what sorrow she was vext."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Flordelice marked the maid, that, in her sight,\nAppeared a warrior fitted for her needs;\nAnd of the bridge and river 'gan recite,\nWhere Argier's mighty king the road impedes;\nAnd how he had gone nigh to slay her knight;\nNot that more doughty were the monarch's deeds;\nBut that the wily paynim vantage-ground\nIn that streight bridge and foaming river found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Are you (she said so daring and so kind, ) \n\nAs kind and daring you appear in show,\nVenge me of him that has my lord confined,\nAnd makes me wander thus, opprest with woe,\nFor love of Heaven; or teach me where to find\nAt least a knight who can resist the foe,\nAnd of such skill that little boot shall bring\nHis bridge and river to the pagan king."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Besides that so you shall achieve an end,\nBefitting courteous man and cavalier,\nYou will employ your valour to befriend\nThe faithfullest of lovers far and near.\nHis other virtues I should ill commend,\nSo many and so many, that whoe'er\nKnoweth not these, may well be said to be\nOne without ears to hear or eyes to see.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The high-minded maid, to whom aye welcome are\nAll noble quests, by which she worthily\nMay hope a great and glorious name to bear,\nStraight to the paynim's bridge resolves to hie;\nAnd now so much the more — as in despair —\nWends willingly, although it were to die:\nIn that she, ever with herself at strife,\nDeeming Rogero lost, detested life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O loving damsel (she made answer), I\nOffer mine aid, for such as 'tis, to do\nThe hard and dread adventure, passing by\nCauses beside that move me, most that you\nA matter of your lover testify,\nWhich I, in sooth, hear warranted of few;\nThat he is constant; for i'faith I swear,\nI well believed all lovers perjured were.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With these last words a sigh that damsel drew,\nA sigh which issued from her heart; then said:\n\"Go we\"; and, with the following sun, those two\nAt the deep stream arrived and bridge of dread:\n— Seen of the guard, that on his bugle blew\nA warning blast, when strangers thither sped —\nThe pagan arms him, girds his goodly brand,\nAnd takes upon the bridge his wonted stand;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And as the maid appears in martial scale,\nThe moody monarch threatens her to slay,\nUnless her goodly courser and her mail,\nAs an oblation to the tomb she pay.\nFair Bradamant who knew the piteous tale,\nHow murdered by him Isabella lay,\nThe story gentle Flordelice had taught;\nReplied in answer to that paynim haught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Wherefore, O brutish man, for your misdeed\nShould penance by the innocent be done?\n'Tis fitting to appease her you should bleed;\nYou killed her, and to all the deed is known.\nSo that, of trophied armour or of weed\nOf those so many, by your lance o'erthrown,\nYour armour should the blest oblation be,\nAnd you the choicest victim, slain by me;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And dearer shall the gift be from my hand;\nSince I a woman am, as she whilere;\nNor save to venge her have I sought this strand;\nIn this desire alone I hither steer:\nBut first, 'tis good some pact we understand,\nBefore we prove our prowess with the spear:\nYou shall do by me, if o'erthrown, what you\nBy other prisoners have been wont to do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if, as I believe and trust, you fall,\nI will your horse and armour have (she cried),\nAnd taking down all others from the wall,\nHang on the tomb alone those arms of pride;\nAnd will that you release each warlike thrall.\"\n— \"The pact is just (King Rodomont replied),\nBut those, my prisoners, are not here confined,\nAnd therefore cannot be to you consigned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"These have I sent into mine Africk reign;\nBut this I promise thee, and pledge my fay;\nIf, by strange fortune, thou thy seat maintain,\nAnd I shall be dismounted in the fray;\nDelivered, all, shall be the captive train,\nWithin what time suffices to convey\nAn order thither, that they our of hand\n'Should do what thou, if conqueror, may'st command."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But art thou undermost, as fitter were,\nAnd, as thou surely wilt be, I from thee\nNot therefore will thy forfeit armour tear,\nNor shall thy name inscribed, as vanquished, be.\nTo thy bright face, bright eyes, and beauteous hair,\nAll breathing love and grace, the victory\nWill I resign; let it suffice that thou\nThen stoop to love me, as thou hatest now."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To fall by me thou needest not disdain;\nI with such strength, such nerve am fortified.\"\nSomedeal she smiled; but smiled in bitter vein;\nSavouring of anger more than aught beside.\nShe spake not to that haughty man again,\nTo the bridge-end returned the damsel, plied\nHer courser with the rowels, couched her spear,\nAnd rode to meet the furious cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Rodomont prepares his course to run;\nComes on at speed; and with such mighty sound\nEchoes that bridge, the thundering noise might stun\nThe ears of many distant from the ground.\nThe golden lance its wonted work has done;\nFor that fierce Moor, in tourney so renowned,\nThis from the saddle lifts, in air suspends,\nThen headlong on the narrow bridge extends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scarce for her horse the martial damsel can\nFind space to pass, when she has thrown her foe;\nAnd little lacked, and mighty risque she ran\nOf falling into that deep stream below:\nBut, born of wind and flame, good Rabican\nSo dextrous was, and could so lightly go,\nHe picked a path along the outer ledge,\nAnd could have paced upon a faulchion's edge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The damsel wheeled, towards the cavalier\nReturned, and him bespoke in sportive way;\n\"Who is the loser now to thee is clear,\nAnd who is undermost in this assay.\"\nSilent remained the monarch of Argier,\nAmazed, that woman him on earth should lay.\nHe cannot, or he will not speak; and lies\nOn earth, like one astound, in idiot guise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Silent and sad, he raised himself from ground,\nAnd when he some few paces thence had gone,\nHis shield unbraced and helm and mail unbound,\nHe flung against the tomb; and thence, alone,\nAfoot the moody monarch left that ground:\nYet not till he had given command to one\n(Of his four squires was he to do his hest ) \n\nRelating to those captives, as exprest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He parts; and save that in a caverned cell\nHe dwelt, no further news of him were known:\nMeanwhile the harness of that infidel\nBradamant hung upon the lofty stone;\nAnd having thence removed all plate and shell\nWherewith (as by the writing it was shown)\nThe cavaliers of Charles their limbs had drest,\nShe moved not, nor let other move, the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Besides the arms of Monodantes' heir\nWere those of Sansonet and Olivier,\nWho, bound in search of good Orlando, were\nThither conducted by the road most near.\nThe day before here taken was the pair,\nAnd sent by that proud paynim to Argier:\nThese warriors' arms the martial maid bade lower\nFrom that fair tomb, and stored them in the tower."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All others, taken from the paynim train,\nBradamant left suspended from the stone;\nMid these a king's, that idly and in vain,\nHad thither, seeking Frontalatte, gone:\nI say his arms, that ruled Circassia's reign;\nWho, after wandering long, by date and down,\nHere to his grief another courser left,\nAnd lightly went his way, of arms bereft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stript of his armour and afoot, did part\nThat paynim monarch from the bridge of dread;\nAs Rodomont permitted to depart\nThose other knights that in his faith were bred:\nBut to his camp to wend he had no heart,\nFor there he was ashamed to show his head:\nSince, in such fashion, thither to return\nAfter his boasts, had been too foul a scorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet still with new desire the warrior burned\nTo seek her, fixed alone in his heart's core;\nAnd such the monarch's chance, he quickly learned\n(I cannot tell you who the tidings bore)\nShe was towards her native land returned.\nHence, as Love spurs and goads him evermore,\nHe bowns him straight her footsteps to pursue:\nBut I to Bradamant return anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When she in other writing had displaid\nHow she had freed that passage from the foe,\nTo mournful Flordelice the martial maid,\nShe that still held her weeping visage low,\nTurned her, and courteously that lady prayed\nTo tell her whither she designed to go.\nTo her afflicted Flordelice replied:\n\"To Arles, where camp the paynims, would I ride."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Which bark (I hope and fitting company, ) \n\nTo carry me to Africk may afford;\nNor will I halt upon my way, till I\nOnce more rejoin my husband and my lord;\nAll means and measures there resolved to try,\nThat may release him from his jailer's ward;\nAnd should the Saracen deceitful prove,\nOthers, and others yet, I mean to move.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My company (replied the martial fair)\nFor some part of the road, I offer thee,\nTill we have sight of Arles; then to repair\nThither, will pray you, for the love of me,\nTo find King Agramant's Rogero there,\nWhose glorious name is spread o'er land and sea,\nAnd render to that knight this goodly horse,\nWhence the proud Moor was flung in martial course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Say thus, from point to point, `A cavalier\nThat would in combat prove his chivalry,\nAnd to the world at large would fain make clear\nThy breach of faith with him, that thou may'st be\nReady and well prepared for the career,\nGave me this horse, that I might give it thee.\nHe bids thee promptly mail and corslet dight,\nAnd wait him, who with thee will wage the fight.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Say this and nought beside, and would he hear\nMy name, declare that 'tis to thee unknown.\"\nWith wonted kindness cried that dame, \"I ne'er\nIn spending life itself, not words alone,\nShould weary in your service; since whilere\nYou would in my behalf as much have done.\"\nHer Aymon's daughter thanked in courteous strain,\nAnd to her hand consigned Frontino's rein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through long days' journey, by that river-shore,\nTogether go the lovely pilgrim pair,\nTill they see Arles, and hear the hollow roar.\nOf billows breaking on the sea-beach bare.\nAlmost without the suburbs, and before\nThe furthest barrier, stops the martial fair;\nTo furnish Flordelice what time might need\nFor the conveyance of Rogero's steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She forward rode, within the enclosure sped,\nAnd o'er the bridge and through the gateway wended,\nAnd (furnished with a guide, who thither led)\nTo young Rogero's inn; and there descended.\nShe to the Child, as bid, her message said,\nAnd gave the courser, to her care commended:\nThen (for she waits not for an answer speeds ) \n\nIn haste to execute her proper needs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero stands confused; he finds no end\nTo his perplexing thoughts, and cannot see\nWho should defy him, who that message send,\nTo speak him ill, and do him courtesy.\nWho thus as faithless him should reprehend,\nOr any reprehend, whoe'er it be,\nNor knows he nor imagines; least of all\nOn Bradamant the knight's suspicions fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To think 'twas Rodomont the youthful peer\nWas more inclined than any other wight;\nAnd wherefore even from him he this should hear,\nMuses, nor can the cause divine aright;\nSave him, in all the world the cavalier\nKnows not of one, that has him at despite.\nMeanwhile Dordona's lady craved the field;\nAnd loud that martial damsel's bugle pealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Agramant and King Marsilius flew\nThe news, that one craved battle on the plain.\nSerpentine stood by chance before the two,\nAnd gained their leave to don his plate and chain,\nAnd vowed to take that haughty man; the crew\nOf people over wall and rampart strain;\nNor child nor elder was there, but he pressed\nTo see which champion should bestir him best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In beauteous arms and costly surcoat drest,\nSerpentine of the star to combat sped;\nThe ground he at the first encounter prest;\nAs if equipt with wings, his courser fled.\nThe damsel flew his charger to arrest,\nAnd by the bride to that paynim led,\nExclaiming: \"Mount, and bid your monarch send\nA knight that better can with me contend.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Moorish king, that on the rampart's height\nStood, with a mighty following, next the plain,\nMarking the joust, much marvelled at the sight\nOf the foe's courtesy to him of Spain.\n\"He takes him not, although he may of right,\"\nHe cries i' the hearing of the paynim train.\nSerpentine comes, and, as the maid commands,\nA better warrior of that king demands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Grandonio de Volterna, fierce of mood,\nAnd in all Spain the proudest cavalier,\nThe second for that fell encounter stood,\nSuch favour had his suit obtained whilere.\n\"To thee thy courtesy shall do no good,\"\nHe threats, \"for if unhorsed in the career\nA prisoner to my lord shalt thou be led:\nBut, if I fight as wonted, thou art dead.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She cries, \"I would not thy discourtesy\nShould make me so forget my courteous vein,\nBut that aforehand I should caution thee\nBack to thy fortress to return again,\nEre on hard earth thy bones shall battered be.\nGo tell thy king no champion of thy grain\nI seek, but hither come to crave the fight\nWith warrior that is worthy of my might.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant's sharp and stinging answer stirred\nThe paynim's fury to a mighty flame;\nSo that, without the power to speak a word,\nHe wheeled his courser, filled with rage and shame;\nWheeling as well, at that proud paynim spurred\nHer horse with levelled lance the warlike dame.\nAs the charmed weapon smites Grandonio's shield,\nWith heels in air, he tumbles on the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him the high-minded damsel gave his horse,\nAnd said, \"Yet was this fate to thee foreshown,\nInstead of craving thus the knightly course,\nBetter mine embassy wouldst thou have done.\nSome other knight, that equals me in force,\nI pray thee bid the Moorish king send down,\nNor weary me, by forcing me to meet\nChampions like thee, untried in martial feat.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They on the walls, that know not who the peer\nThat in the joust so well maintains his seat,\nName many a warrior, famous in career,\nThat often make them shake in fiercest heat.\nBrandimart many deem the cavalier;\nMore guesses in renowned Rinaldo meet;\nMany would deem Orlando was the knight,\nBut that they knew his pitiable plight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The third encounter craved Lanfusa's son,\nAnd cried, \"Not that I better hope to fare,\nBut that to warriors who this course have run,\nMy fall may furnish an excuse more fair.\"\nNext, with all arms that martial jousters don,\nClothed him, and of a hundred steeds that were\nReady for service, kept in lordly stall,\nFor speed and action chose the best of all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He bowned him for the tournay, on his side\nBut first saluted her and she the knight.\n\"If 'tis allowed to ask,\" (the lady cried,)\n\"Tell me in courtesy how ye are hight.\"\nIn this Ferrau the damsel satisfied,\nWho rarely hid himself form living wight.\n\"Ye will I not refuse,\" (subjoined the dame)\n\"Albeit I to meet another came.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— \"And who?\" the Spaniard said; — the maid replied,\n\"Rogero\"; and pronounced the word with pain.\nAnd, in so saying, her fair face was dyed\nAll over with the rose's crimson grain.\nShe after added, \"Hither have I hied,\nTo prove how justly famed his might and main.\nNo other care have I, no other call,\nBut with that gentle youth to try a fall.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She spoke the word in all simplicity,\nWhich some already may in malice wrest.\nFerrau replied, \"Assured I first must be\nWhich of us two is schooled in warfare best,\nIf what has chanced to many, falls on me,\nHither, when I return, shall be addrest,\nTo mend my fault, that gentle cavalier,\nWith whom you so desire to break a spear.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Discoursing all this while, the martial maid\nSpake with her beavor up, without disguise:\nFerrau, as that fair visage he surveyed,\nPerceived he was half vanquished by its eyes.\nAnd to himself, in under tone, he said,\n\"He seems an angel sent from Paradise;\nAnd, though he should not harm me with his lance,\nI am already quelled by that sweet glance.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They take their ground, and to the encounter ride,\nAnd, like those others, Ferrau goes to ground;\nHis courser Bradamant retained, and cried,\n\"Return, and keep thy word with me as bound.\"\nShamed, he returned, and by his monarch's side,\nAmong his peers, the young Rogero found;\nAnd let the stripling know the stranger knight,\nWithout the walls, defied him to the fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero (for not yet that warrior knows\nWhat champion him in duel would assail)\nNigh sure of victory, with transport glows,\nAnd bids his followers bring his plate and mail;\nNor having seen beneath those heavy blows\nThe rest dismounted, makes his spirit quail.\nBut how he armed, how sallied, what befell"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto will I tell.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 36"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While with the fierce Marphisa at despite\nDuke Aymon's daughter wages fierce affray,\nOne and the other host engage in fight.\nWith Bradamant Rogero wends his way.\nWith other war disturbs their great delight\nMarphisa bold; but when that martial may\nHas for her brother recognized the peer,\nThey end their every strife with joyous cheer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where'er they be, all hearts of gentle strain\nStill cannot choose but courtesy pursue;\nFor they from nature and from habit gain\nWhat they henceforth can never more undo.\nAlike the heart that is of churlish vein,\nWhere'er it be, its evil kind will shew.\nNature inclines to ill, through all her range,\nAnd use is second nature, hard to change."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Among the warriors of antiquity\nMuch gentleness and courtesy appear,\nVirtues but seldom seen with us; while we\nOf evil ways, on all sides, see and hear.\nHippolytus, when you, with ensignry\nWon from the foe, and with his captive gear\nAdorned our temples; and his galleys bore,\nLaden with prey, to your paternal shore;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All the inhuman deeds which wrought by hand\nOf Moor, or Turk, or Tartar ever were,\n(Yet not by the Venetians' ill command,\nThat evermore the praise of justice bear,)\nWere practised by that foul and evil band\nOf soldiers, who their mercenaries are.\nOf those so many fires not now I tell\nWhich on our farms and pleasant places fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though a foul vengeance in that blow was meant\nMainly at you, who being at Caesar's side,\nWhen Padua by his leaguering host was pent,\n'Twas known, that oft, through you, was turned aside\nMore than one ravening flame, and oft was spent\nThe fire, in fane and village blazing wide:\nWhat time the destined mischief ye withstood,\nAs to your inborn courtesy seemed good."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This will I pass, nor their so many more\nDiscourteous and despiteous doings tell,\nSave one alone, whereat from rock-stone hoar\nWhene'er the tale is told warm tears might well.\nThat day you sent your family before,\nThither, my lord, where, under omens fell,\nYour foes into a well protected seat,\nAbandoning their barks, had made retreat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As Hector and Aeneas, mid the flood,\nFire to the banded fleet of Greece applied,\nI Hercules and Alexander viewed,\nUrged by too sovereign ardour, side by side,\nSpurring before all others in their mood,\nEven within the hostile ramparts ride;\nAnd prick so far, the second 'scaped with pain,\nAnd on the foremost closed the opposing train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Feruffine 'scaped, the good Cantelmo left,\nWhat counsel, Sora's duke, was thine, what heart,\nWhen thy bold son thou saw'st, of helm bereft,\nAmid a thousand swords, when — dragged apart —\nThou saw'st his young head from his shoulders cleft,\nA shipboard, on a plank?  I, on my part,\nMarvel, that seeing but the murder done,\nSlew thee not, as the faulchion slew thy son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Cruel Sclavonian!  say, whence hast thou brought\nThy ways of warfare?  By what Scythian rite\nTo slay the helpless prisoner is it taught,\nWho yields his arms, nor fends himself in fight?\nWas it a crime he for his country fought?\nIll upon thee the sun bestows his light.\nRemorseless aera, which hast filled the page\nWith Atreus', Tantalus', Thyestes' rage!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Barbarian!  thou madest shorter by the head\nThe boldest of his age, on whom did beam\nThe sun 'twixt pole and pole, 'twixt Indus' bed\nAnd where he sinks in Ocean's western stream;\nWhose years and beauty might have pity bred\nIn Anthropophagus, in Polypheme;\nNot thee; that art in wickedness outdone\nBy any Cyclops, any Lestrigon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I ween, mid warriors in the days of yore,\nNo such example was; they all, in field,\nWere full of gentleness and courteous lore,\nNor against conquered foe their bosom steeled.\nNot only gentle Bradamant forbore\nTo harm the knights whom, smitten on the shield,\nHer lance unhorsed; but for the vanquished crew\nDetained their steeds, that they might mount anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I of that lady fair, of mickle might,\nTold you above, how she had overthrown\nSerpentine of the Star in single fight,\nGrandonio and Ferrau, and then upon\nTheir coursers had replaced each baffled knight.\nI told moreover how the third was gone\nRogero to defy to the career,\nUpon her call, who seemed a cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero heard the call in joyous vein,\nAnd bade his arms be brought; now while in view\nOf Agramant he donned the plate and chain,\nThose lords the former question moved anew;\nWho was the knight, that on the martial plain\nThe manage of the lance so quaintly knew?\nAnd of Ferrau, who spake with him whilere,\nCraved, if to him was known that cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Be ye assured,\" to them Ferrau replied,\n\"He is not one of those I hear you cite\nTo me (for I his open face descried).\nRinaldo's youthful brother seemed the knight.\nBut since his doughty valour I have tried,\nAnd wot not such is Richardetto's might,\nI ween it is his sister, who, I hear,\nResembles much in mien that martial peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The damsel equals well, so Rumour tells,\nRinaldo, and every paladin in fray.\nBut brother she and cousin both excels,\nMeasured by that which I have seen to-day.\"\nHearing him, while upon her praise he dwells,\nAs the sky reddens with the morning ray,\nRogero's face is flushed with crimson hue,\nAnd his heart throbs, nor knows he what to do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stung, at these tidings, by the amorous dart —\nWithin, new fire inflames the cavalier;\nAnd strait, together with the burning smart,\nShoots through his bones a chill, produced by fear;\nFear, that new wrath had stifled in her heart\nThat mighty love, wherewith she burned whilere.\nConfused he stands, irresolute and slow,\nAnd undecided if to stay or go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now fierce Marphisa, who was there, and prest\nBy huge desire to meet the stranger wight,\nAnd armed withal (for, save in iron vest,\nHer seldom would you find by day or night).\nHearing Rogero is in armour drest,\nFearing to lose the honour of the fight,\nIf first that champion with the stranger vies;\nThinks to prevent the youth and win the prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She leapt upon her horse, and thither hied\nWhere Aymon's daughter on the listed plain,\nWith palpitating heart, upon her side,\nWaited Rogero; whom the damsel fain\nWould make her prisoner, and but schemed to guide\nHer lance in mode the stripling least to pain.\nMarphisa from the city portal fares,\nAnd on her gallant helm a phoenix wears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether the maid would publish, in her pride,\nThat she was single in the world, for might;\nOr whether by that symbol signified,\nThat she would live, exempt from bridal rite.\nHer closely Aymon's martial daughter eyed;\nWhen seeing not those features, her delight,\nShe craves the damsel's name before they move,\nAnd hears that it is she who joys her love:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Or rather she, that gentle lady thought,\nHad joyed her love; and whom she hated so,\nHer to Death's door her anger would have brought,\nUnless she venged her sorrow on the foe.\nShe wheeled her courser round, with fury fraught,\nLess with desire to lay her rival low,\nThan with the lance to pierce her in mid breast,\nAnd put her every jealousy at rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Parforce to ground must go the royal maid,\nTo prove it hard or soft the listed plain,\nAnd be with such unwonted scorn appaid,\nThat she is nearly maddened by disdain.\nScarce was she thrown, before her trenchant blade\nShe bared, and hurried to avenge the stain.\nCried Aymon's daughter, no less proud of heart,\n\"What art thou doing?  Thou my prisoner art.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Though I have courtesy for others, none\"\n(She said \"from me, Marphisa, shalt thou find. ) \n\nSince evermore I hear of thee, as one\nTo pride and every churlishness inclined.\"\nMarphisa, at these words, was heard to groan,\nAs roars in some sea-rock the prisoned wind.\nShe screamed an answer; but its sense was drowned\n(Such rage confused that damsel in the sound. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She whirls this while her faulchion, and would fain\nWound horse or rider in the paunch or breast;\nBut Aymon's watchful daughter turns the rein;\nAnd on one side her courser leaps; possest\nWith furious anger and with fierce disdain,\nShe at her opposite her lance addrest;\nAnd hardly touched the damsel, ere, astound,\nMarphisa fell, reversed upon the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scarce down, Marphisa started from the plain,\nIntent fell mischief with her sword to do,\nBradamant couched her golden spear again,\nAnd yet again the damsel overthrew.\nYet Bradamant, though blest with might and main,\nWas not so much the stronger of the two\nAs to have flung the maid in every just,\nBut that such power was in the lance's thrust."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This while some knights (some knights upon our side,\nI say forth issuing from the city, go ) \n\nTowards the field of strife, which did divide\nThe squadrons, here and there, of either foe\n— Not half a league of one another wide —\nSeeing their knight such mighty prowess show;\nTheir knight, but whom no otherwise they knew\nThan as a warrior of the Christian crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Troyano's generous son, who had espied\nThis band approaching to the city-wall,\nFor due defence would every means provide,\nAnd every peril, every case forestall:\nAnd orders many to take arms, who ride\nForth from the ramparts, at the monarch's call.\nWith them Rogero goes, in armour cased,\nBalked of the battle by Marphisa's haste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The enamoured youth, with beating heart, intent,\nStood by, the issue of the just to view.\nFor his dear cousin fearing the event,\nIn that he well Marphisa's valour knew;\n— At the beginning I would say — when, bent\nOn mischief, fiercely closed the furious two:\nBut when that duel's turn the stripling eyes,\nHe stands amazed and stupid with surprize;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And when he saw unfinished was the fight,\nAt the first onset, like the justs whilere,\nMisdoubting some strange accident, in sprite,\nSore vexed, this while remained the cavalier.\nTo either maid wished well that youthful knight;\nFor both were loved, but not alike were dear.\nFor this the stripling's love was fury, fire;\nFor that 'twas rather fondness than desire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If so Rogero could with honour do,\nHe willingly the warriors would divide;\nBut his companions, in the fear to view\nVictory with King Charles's knight abide,\nEsteeming him the better of the two,\nBreak in between and turn their arms aside;\nUpon the other part, the Christian foes\nAdvance, and both divisions come to blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On this side and that other, rings the alarm,\nWhich in those camps is sounded every day,\nBidding the unmounted mount, the unarmed arm,\nAnd all their standards seek, without delay,\nWhere, under separate flags, the squadrons swarm,\nMore than one shrilling trump is heard to bray;\nAnd as their rattling notes the riders call,\nRousing the foot, beat drum and ataball."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As fierce as thought could think, 'twixt either host\nKindled the fell and sanguinary fray.\nThe daring damsel, fair Dordona's boast,\nSore vexed and troubled, that in the affray\nShe cannot compass what she covets most,\n— Marphisa with avenging steel to slay, —\nNow here, not there, amid the medley flies,\nHoping to see the youth for whom she sighs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By the eagle argent on the shield of blue\nShe recognized Rogero, mid the rest.\nWith eyes and thought intent, she stops to view\nThe warrior's manly shoulders and his breast,\nFair face and movements full of graceful shew;\nAnd then the maid, with mickle spite possest,\nThinking another joys the stripling's love,\nThus speaks, as sovereign rage and fury move."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Shall then another kiss those lips so bright\nAnd sweet, if those fair lips are lost to me?\nAh!  never other shall in thee delight;\nFor it not mine, no other's shalt thou be.\nRather than die alone and of despite,\nI with this hand will slay myself and thee,\nThat if I lose thee here, at least in hell\nWith thee I to eternity may dwell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If thou slay'st me, there is good reason, I\nThe comfort too of vengeance should obtain;\nIn that all edicts and all equity\nThe death of him that causes death ordain;\nNor, since you justly, I unjustly, die,\nDeem I that thine is equal to my pain.\nI him who seeks my life, alas!  shall spill,\nThou her that loves and worships thee wouldst kill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My hand, why hast thou not the hardiment\nTo rive with steel the bosom of my foe,\nThat me so many times to death has shent,\nUnder the faith of love, in peaceful show;\nHim, who to take my life can now consent,\nNor even have pity of my cruel woe?\nDare, valiant heart, this impious man to slay,\nAnd let his death my thousand deaths appay!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said, she spurred at him amid the throng;\nBut, first — \"Defend thee, false Rogero!\" — cried.\n\"No more, if I have power, in spoil and wrong,\nDone to a virgin heart, shalt thou take pride.\"\nHearing that voice the hostile ranks among,\nHe deems — and truly deems — he hears his bride;\nWhose voice the youth remembers in such wise,\nThat mid a thousand would he recognize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her further meaning well did he divine,\nWeening that him she in that speech would blame,\nFor having broke their pact; and — with design,\nThe occasion of his failure to proclaim, —\nOf his desire for parley made a sign:\nBut she, with vizor closed, already came,\nRaging and grieved, intent, with vengeful hand,\nTo fling the youth; nor haply upon sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, when he saw her so offended,\nFixed himself firmly in his arms and seat,\nHe rests his lance, but holds the stave suspended,\nSo that it shall not harm her when they meet,\nShe that to smite and pierce the Child intended,\nPitiless, and inflamed with furious heat,\nHas not the courage, when she sees him near,\nTo fling, or do him outrage with the spear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Void of effect, 'tis thus their lances go;\nAnd it is well; since Love with burning dart,\nTilting this while at one and the other foe,\nHas lanced the enamoured warriors in mid-heart.\nUnable at the Child to aim her blow,\nThe lady spent her rage in other part,\nAnd mighty deeds achieved, which fame will earn,\nWhile overhead the circling heavens shall turn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above three hundred men in that affray\nIn little space by her dismounted lie,\nAlone that warlike damsel wins the day;\nFrom her alone the Moorish people fly.\nTo her Rogero, circling, threads his way,\nAnd says: \"Unless I speak with you I die.\nHear me, for love of heaven! — what done I done,\nAlas!  that ever mine approach ye shun?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As when soft southern breezes are unpent,\nWhich with a tepid breath from seaward blow,\nThe snows dissolve, and torrents find a vent,\nAnd ice, so hard erewhile, is seen to flow;\nAt those entreaties, at that brief lament,\nRinaldo's sister's heart is softened so;\nForthwith compassionate and pious grown;\nWhich anger fain had made more hard than stone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Would she not, could she not, she nought replied,\nBut spurred aslant the ready Rabicane,\nAnd, signing to Rogero, rode as wide\nAs she could wend from that embattled train;\nThen to a sheltered valley turned aside,\nWherein embosomed was a little plain.\nIn the mid lawn a wood of cypress grew,\nWhose saplings of one stamp appeared to view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within that thicket, of white marble wrought,\nIs a proud monument, and newly made;\nAnd he that makes enquiry, here is taught\nIn few brief verses who therein is laid.\nBut of those lines, methinks, took little thought,\nFair Bradamant, arriving in that glade.\nRogero spurred his courser, and pursued\nAnd overtook that damsel in the wood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But turn we to Marphisa, that anew\nDuring this space was seated on her steed,\nAnd sought again the valiant champion, who\nAt the first onset cast her on the mead;\nAnd saw, how from the mingling host withdrew\nRogero, after that strange knight to speed;\nNor deemed the youth pursued in love; she thought\nHe but to end their strife and quarrel sought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She pricks her horse behind the two, and gains,\nWell nigh as soon as they, that valley; how\nHer coming thither either lover pains,\nWho lives and loves, untaught by me, may know:\nBut sorest vext sad Bradamant remains;\nBeholding her whence all her sorrows flow.\nWho shall persuade the damsel but that love\nFor young Rogero brings her to that grove?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And him perfidious she anew did name.\n— \"Perfidious, was it not enough (she said)\nThat I should know thy perfidy from fame,\nBut must the witness of thy guilt be made?\nI wot, to drive me from thee is thine aim;\nAnd I, that thy desires may be appaid,\nWill die; but strive, in yielding up my breath,\nShe too shall die, the occasion of my death.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Angrier than venomed viper, with a bound,\nSo saying, she upon Marphisa flies;\nAnd plants so well the spear, that she, astound,\nFell backward on the champaigne in such guise,\nNigh half her helm was buried in the ground:\nNor was the damsel taken by surprise:\nNay, did her best the encounter to withstand;\nYet with her helmed head she smote the sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant who will die, or in that just\nWill put to death Marphisa, rages so,\nShe has no mind again with lance to thrust,\nAgain that martial maid to overthrow:\nBut thinks her head to sever from the bust,\nWhere it half buried lies, with murderous blow:\nAway the enchanted lance that damsel flings,\nUnsheathes the sword, and from her courser springs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But is too slow withal; for on her feet\nShe finds Marphisa, with such fierce disdain\nInflamed, at being in that second heat\nSo easily reversed upon the plain,\nShe hears in vain exclaim, in vain entreat,\nRogero, who beholds their strife with pain.\nSo blinded are the pair with spite and rage,\nThat they with desperate fury battle wage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At half-sword's engage the struggling foes;\nAnd — such their stubborn mood — with shortened brand\nThey still approach, and now so fiercely close,\nThey cannot choose but grapple, hand to hand.\nHer sword, no longer needful, each foregoes;\nAnd either now new means of mischief planned.\nRogero both implores with earnest suit:\nBut supplicates the twain with little fruit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When he entreaties unavailing found,\nThe youth prepared by force to part the two;\nTheir poniards snatched away, and on the ground,\nBeneath a cypress-tree, the daggers threw.\nWhen they no weapons have wherewith to wound,\nWith prayer and threat, he interferes anew:\nBut vainly; for, since better weapons lack,\nEach other they with fists and feet attack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero ceased not from his task; he caught,\nBy hand or arm, the fiercely struggling pair,\nTill to the utmost pitch of fury wrought\nThe fell Marphisa's angry passions were.\nShe, that this ample world esteemed at nought,\nOf the Child's friendship had no further care.\nPlucked from the foe, she ran to seize her sword,\nAnd fastened next upon that youthful lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Like a discourteous man and churl ye do,\nRogero, to disturb another's fight;\nA deed (she cried this hand shall make ye rue, ) \n\nWhich I intend, shall vanquished both.\"  The knight\nSought fierce Marphisa's fury to subdue\nWith gentle speech; but full of such despite\nHe found her, and inflamed with such disdain,\nAll parley was a waste of time and pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At last his faulchion young Rogero drew;\nFor ire as well had flushed that cavalier:\nNor is it my belief, that ever shew\nAthens or Rome, or city whatsoe'er\nWitnessed, which ever so rejoiced the view,\nAs this rejoices, as this sight is dear\nTo Bradamant, when, through their strife displaced,\nEvery suspicion from her breast is chased."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant took her sword, and to descry\nThe duel of those champions stood apart.\nThe god of war, descended from the sky,\nShe deemed Rogero, for his strength and art:\nIf he seemed Mars, Marphisa to the eye\nSeemed an infernal Fury, on her part.\n'Tis true, that for a while the youthful knight\nAgainst that damsel put not forth his might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He knew the virtues of that weapon well,\nSuch proof thereof the knight erewhile had made.\nWhere'er it falls parforce is every spell\nAnnulled, or by its stronger virtue stayed.\nHence so Rogero smote, it never fell\nUpon its edge or point, but still the blade\nDescended flat: he long this rule observes;\nYet once he from his patient purpose swerves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In that, a mighty stroke Marphisa sped,\nMeaning to cleave the brainpan of her foe:\nHe raised the buckler to defend his head,\nAnd the sword smote upon its bird of snow,\nNor broke nor bruised the shield, by spell bested;\nBut his arm rang astounded by the blow;\nNor aught but Hector's mail the sword had stopt,\nWhose furious blow would his left arm have lopt;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And had upon his head descended shear,\nWhereat designed to strike the savage fair.\nScarce his left arm can good Rogero rear;\nCan scarce the shield and blazoned bird upbear.\nAll pity he casts off, and 'twould appear\nAs in his eyes a lighted torch did glare.\nAs hard as he can smite, he smites; and woe\nTo thee, Marphisa, if he plants the blow!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I cannot tell you truly in what wise,\nThat faulchion swerves against a cypress-stock,\nIn such close-serried ranks the saplings rise,\nBuried above a palm within the block.\nAs this the mountain and the plain that lies\nBeneath it, with a furious earthquake rock;\nAnd from that marble monument proceeds\nA voice, that every mortal voice exceeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The horrid voice exclaims, \"Your quarrel leave;\nFor 'twere a deed unjust and inhumane,\nThat brother should of life his sister reave,\nOr sister by her brother's hand be slain.\nRogero and Marphisa mine, believe!\nThe tale which I deliver is not vain.\nSeed of one father, on one womb ye lay;\nAnd first together saw the light of day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Galaciella's children are ye, whom\nShe to Rogero, hight the second, bare.\nWhose brothers, having, by unrighteous doom,\nOf your unhappy sire deprived that fair,\nNot heeding that she carried in her womb\nYe, who yet suckers of their lineage are,\nHer in a rotten carcase of a boat,\nTo founder in mid ocean, set afloat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But Fortune, that had destined you whilere,\nAnd yet unborn, to many a fair emprize,\nYour mother to that lonely shore did steer,\nWhich overright the sandy Syrtes lies.\nWhere, having given you birth, that spirit dear\nForthwith ascended into Paradise.\nA witness of the piteous case was I,\nSo Heaven had willed, and such your destiny!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I to the dame as descent burial gave\nAs could be given upon that desert sand.\nYe, well enveloped in my vest, I save,\nAnd bear to Mount Carena from the strand;\nAnd make a lioness leave whelps and cave,\nAnd issue from the wood, with semblance bland.\nYe, twice ten months, with mickle fondness bred,\nAnd from her paps the milky mother fed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Needing to quit my home upon a day,\nAnd journey through the country, (as you can\nHaply remember ye we are on our way, ) \n\nWere overtaken by an Arab clan.\nThose robbers thee, Marphisa, bore away:\nWhile young Rogero 'scaped, who better ran.\nBereaved of thee, they woful loss I wept,\nAnd with more watchful care thy brother kept."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Rogero, if Atlantes watched thee well,\nWhile yet he was alive, thou best dost know.\nI the fixed stars had heard of thee foretell,\nThat thou shouldst perish by a treacherous foe\nIn Christian land; and still their influence fell\nWas ended, laboured to avert the blow;\nNor having power in fine thy will to guide,\nI sickened sore, and of my sorrow died."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But here, before my death, for in this glade\nI knew thou should'st with bold Marphisa fight,\nI with huge stones, amassed by hellish aid,\nHad this fair monument of marble dight;\nAnd I to Charon with loud outcries said;\nI would not he should hence convey my sprite,\nTill here, prepared in deadly fray to strive,\nRogero and his sister should arrive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thus has my spirit for this many a day\nWaited thy coming in these beauteous groves;\nSo be no more to jealous fears a prey,\nO Bradamant, because Rogero loves.\nBut me to quit the cheerful realms of day,\nAnd seek the darksome cloisters it behoves.\"\nHere ceased the voice; which in the Child amazed\nAnd those two damsels mighty marvel raised."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gladly a sister in the martial queen\nRogero, she in him a brother knows;\nWho now embrace, nor move her jealous spleen,\nThat with the love of young Rogero glows;\nAnd citing what, and when, and where had been\nTheir childish deeds, as they to memory rose,\nIn summing up past times, more sure they hold\nThe things whereof the wizard's spirit told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero from Marphisa does not hide,\nHow Bradamant to him at heart is dear;\nAnd by what obligations he is tied\nIn moving words relates the cavalier;\nNor ceases till he has, on either side,\nTurned to firm love the hate they bore whilere.\nWhen, as a sign of peace, and discord chased,\nThey, at his bidding, tenderly embraced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa to Rogero makes request\nTo say what sire was theirs, and what their strain;\nAnd how he died; by banded foes opprest,\nOr at close barriers, was the warrior slain?\nAnd who it was had issued the behest\nTo drown their mother in the stormy main?\nFor of the tale, if ever heard before,\nLittle or nothing she in memory bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of Trojan ancestors are we the seed,\nThrough famous Hector's line,\" (Rogero said,)\n\"For after young Astyanax was freed,\nFrom fierce Ulysses and the toils he spread,\nLeaving another stripling in his stead,\nOf his own age, he out of Phrygia fled.\nWho, after long and wide sea-wandering, gained\nSicily's shore, and in Messina reigned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Part of Calabria within Faro held\nThe warrior's heirs, who after a long run\nOf successors, departed thence and dwelled\nIn Mars' imperial city: more than one\nFamed king and emperor, who that list have swelled,\nIn Rome and other part has filled the throne;\nAnd from Constantius and good Constantine,\nStretched to the son of Pepin, is their line."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Rogero, Gambaron, Buovo hence succeed;\nAnd that Rogero, second of the name,\nWho filled our fruitful mother with his seed;\nAs thou Atlantes may'st have heard proclaim.\nOf our fair lineage many a noble deed\nShalt thou hear blazed abroad by sounding Fame.\"\nOf Agolant's inroad next the stripling told,\nWith Agramant and with Almontes bold;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And how a lovely daughter, who excelled\nIn feats of arms, that king accompanied;\nSo stout she many paladins had quelled;\nAnd how, in fine, she for Rogero sighed;\nAnd for his love against her sire rebelled;\nAnd was baptized, and was Rogero's bride;\nAnd how a traitor loved (him Bertram name)\nHis brother's wife with an incestuous flame;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And country, sire, and brethren two betrayed,\nHoping he so the lady should have won;\nHow Risa open to the foe he laid,\nBy whom all scathe was on those kinsmen done;\nHow Agolant's two furious sons conveyed\nTheir mother, great with child, and six months gone,\nAboard a helmless boat, and with its charge,\nIn wildest winter, turned adrift the barge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Valiant Marphisa, with a tranquil face,\nHeard young Rogero thus his tale pursue,\nAnd joyed to be descended of a race\nWhich from so fair a font its waters drew:\nWhence Clermont, whence renowned Mongrana trace\nTheir noble line, the martial damsel knew;\nBlazoned through years and centuries by Fame,\nUnrivalled, both, in arms of mighty name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When afterwards she from her brother knew\nAgramant's uncle, sire, and grandsire fell,\nIn treacherous wise, the first Rogero slew\nAnd brought to cruel pass Galacielle,\nMarphisa could not hear the story through:\nTo him she cries, \"With pardon, what you tell,\nBrother, convicts you of too foul a wrong,\nIn leaving thus our sire unvenged so long."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Could'st thou not in Almontes and Troyane,\nAs dead whilere, your thirsty faulchion plant,\nBy you those monarch's children might be slain.\nAre you alive, and lives King Agramant?\nNever will you efface the shameful stain,\nThat ye, so often wronged, not only grant\nLife to that king, but as your lord obey;\nLodge in his court, and serve him for his pay?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Here heartily in face of Heaven I vow,\nThat Christ my father worshipped, to adore;\nAnd till I venge my parents on the foe\nTo wear this armour, and I will deplore\nYour deed, Rogero, and deplore even now,\nThat you should swell the squadrons of the Moor,\nOr other follower of the Moslem faith,\nSave sword in hand, and to the paynim's scathe.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ah!  how fair Bradamant uplifts again\nHer visage at that speech, rejoiced in sprite!\nRogero she exhorts in earnest vein\nTo do as his Marphisa counsels right;\nAnd bids him seek the camp of Charlemagne,\nAnd have himself acknowledged in his sight,\nWho so reveres and lauds his father's worth,\nHe even deems him one unmatched on earth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the beginning so he should have done,\n(Warily young Rogero answer made,)\nBut, for the tale was not so fully known,\nAs since, the deed had been too long delaid.\nNow, seeing it was fierce Troyano's son\nThat had begirt him with the knightly blade,\nHe, as a traitor, well might be abhorred,\nIf he slew one, accepted as his lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But, as to Bradamant whilere, he cries,\nHe will all measures and all means assay,\nWhereby some fair occasion may arise\nTo leave the king; and had there been delay,\nAnd he whilere had done in otherwise,\nShe on the Tartar king the fault must lay:\nHow sorely handled that redoubted foe\nHad left him in their battle, she must know;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And she, that every day had sought his bed,\nMust of this truth the fittest witness be.\nMuch upon this was answered, much was said,\nBetween those damsels, who at last agree;\nAnd as their last resolve, last counsel read,\nHe should rejoin the paynim's ensignry,\nTill he found fair occasion to resort\nFrom Agramant's to Charles's royal court."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Bradamant the bold Marphisa cries:\n\"Let him begone, nor doubt am I, before\nMany days pass, will manage in such wise,\nThat Agramant shall be his lord no more.\"\nSo says the martial damsel, nor implies\nThe secret purpose which she has in store.\nMaking his congees to the friendly twain,\nTo join his king Rogero turns the rein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When a complaint is heard from valley near:\nAll now stand listening, to the noise attent;\nAnd to that plaintive voice incline their ear,\nA woman's (as 'twould seem that makes lament. ) \n\nBut I this strain would gladly finish here,\nAnd, that I finish it, be ye content:\nFor better things I promise to report,\nIf ye to hear another strain resort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 37"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lament and outcry loud of some that mourn,\nAttract Rogero and the damsels two.\nThey find Ulania, with her mantle shorn\nBy Marganor, amid her moaning crew.\nUpon that felon knight, for his foul scorn,\nA fierce revenge Marphisa takes: a new\nStatute that maid does in the town obtain,\nAnd Marganor is by Ulania slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If, as in seeking other gift to gain,\n(For Nature, without study, yieldeth nought)\nWith mighty diligence, and mickle pain,\nIllustrious women day and night have wrought;\nAnd if with good success the female train\nTo a fair end no homely task have brought,\nSo — did they for such other studies wake —\nAs mortal attributes immortal make;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, if they of themselves sufficient were\nTheir praises to posterity to show,\nNor borrowed authors' aid, whose bosoms are\nWith envy and with hate corroded so,\nThat oft they hide the good they might declare,\nAnd tell in every place what ill they know,\nTo such a pitch would mount the female name,\nAs haply ne'er was reached by manly fame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To furnish mutual aid is not enow,\nFor many who would lend each other light.\nMen do their best, that womankind should show\nWhatever faults they have in open sight;\nWould hinder them of rising from below,\nAnd sink them to the bottom, if they might;\nI say the ancients; as if glory, won\nBy woman, dimmed their own, as mist the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But hands or tongue ne'er had, nor has, the skill,\nDoes voice or lettered page the thought impart,\nThough each, with all its power, increase the ill,\nDiminishing the good with all its art,\nSo female fame to stifle, but that still\nThe honour of the sex survives in part:\nYet reacheth not its pitch, nor such its flight,\nBut that 'tis far below its natural height."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not only Thomyris and Harpalice,\nAnd who brought Hector, who brought Turnus aid,\nAnd who, to build in Lybia crost the sea,\nBy Tyrian and Sidonian band obeyed;\nNot only famed Zenobia, only she\nWho Persian, Indian, and Assyrian frayed;\nNot only these and some few others merit\nTheir glory, that eternal fame inherit:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Faithful, chaste, and bold, the world hath seen\nIn Greece and Rome not only, but where'er\nThe Sun unfolds his flowing locks, between\nThe Hesperides and Indian hemisphere;\nWhose gifts and praise have so extinguished been,\nWe scarce of one amid a thousand hear;\nAnd this because they in their days have had\nFor chroniclers, men envious, false, and bad."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But ye that prosper in the exercise\nOf goodly labours, aye your way pursue;\nNor halt, O women, in your high emprise,\nFor fear of not receiving honour due:\nFor, as nought good endures beneath the skies,\nSo ill endures no more; if hitherto\nUnfriendly by the poet's pen and page,\nThey now befriend you in our better age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Erewhile Marullo and Pontante for you\nDeclared, and — sire and son — the Strozzi twain;\nCapello, Bembo, and that writer, who\nHas fashioned like himself the courtier train;\nWith Lewis Alamanni, and those two,\nBeloved of Mars and Muses, of their strain\nDescended, who the mighty city rule,\nWhich Mincius parts, and moats with marshy pool."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One of this pair (besides that, of his will,\nHe honours you, and does you courtesies;\nAnd makes Parnassus and high Cynthus' hill\nResound your praise, and lift it to the skies)\nThe love, the faith, and mind, unconquered still,\nMid threats of ruin, which in stedfast wise\nTo him his constant Isabel hath shown,\nRender yet more your champion than his own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So that he never more will wearied be\nWith quickening in his verse your high renown;\nAnd, if another censures you, than he\nPrompter to arm in your defence is none;\nNor knight, in this wide world, more willingly\nLife in the cause of virtue would lay down:\nMatter as well for other's pen he gives,\nAs in his own another's glory lives;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And well he merits, that a dame so blest,\n(Blest with all worth, which in this earthly round\nIs seen in them who don the female vest,)\nTo him hath evermore been faithful found;\nOf a sure pillar of pure truth possest\nIn her, despising Fortune's every wound.\nWorthy of one another are the twain;\nNor better ere were paired in wedlock's chain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "New trophies he on Oglio's bank has shown;\nFor he, mid bark and car, amid the gleam\nOf fire and sword, such goodly rhymes hath strown,\nAs may with envy swell the neighbouring stream.\nBy Hercules Bentivoglio next is blown\nThe noble strain, your honour's noble theme;\nReynet Trivulzio and Guidetti mine,\nAnd Molza, called of Phoebus and the Nine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There's Hercules of the Carnuti, son\nOf my own duke, who spreads his every plume\nSoaring and singing, like harmonious swan,\nAnd even to heaven uplifts your name; with whom\nThere is my lord of Guasto, not alone\nA theme for many an Athens, many a Rome;\nIn his high strain he promises as well,\nYour praise to all posterity to tell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And beside these and others of our day,\nWho gave you once, or give you now renown,\nThis for yourselves ye may yourselves purvey:\nFor many, laying silk and sampler down,\nWith the melodious Muses, to allay\nTheir thirst at Aganippe's well, have gone,\nAnd still are going; who so fairly speed,\nThat we more theirs than they our labour need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If I of these would separately tell,\nAnd render good account and honour due,\nMore than one page I with their praise should swell,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto shew;\nAnd if on five or six alone I dwell,\nI may offend and anger all the crew.\nWhat then shall I resolve? to pass all by?\nOr choose but one from such a company?</p>\n<pre></pre>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One will I choose, and such will choose, that she\nAll envy shall so well have overthrown,\nNo other woman can offend be,\nIf, passing others, her I praise alone:\nNor joys this one but immortality,\nThrough her sweet style (and better know I none):\nBut who is honoured in her speech and page,\nShall burst the tomb, and live through every age."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As Phoebus to his silvery sister shows\nHis visage more, and lends her brighter fires,\nThan Venus, Maja, or to star that glows\nAlone, or circles with the heavenly quires;\nSo he with sweeter eloquence than flows\nFrom other lips, that gentle dame inspires;\nAnd gives her word such force, a second sun\nSeems in our days its glorious course to run."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Mid victories born, Victoria is her name,\nWell named; and whom (does she advance or stay)\nTriumphs and trophies evermore proclaim,\nWhile Victory heads or follows her array.\nAnother Artemisia is the dame,\nRenowned for love of her Mausolus, yea\nBy so much greater, as it is more brave\nTo raise the dead, than lay them in the grave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If chaste Laodamia, Portia true,\nEvadne, Argia, Arria, and many more\nMerited praise, because that glorious crew\nCoveted burial with their lords of yore,\nHow much more fame is to Victoria due?\nThat from dull Lethe, and the river's shore,\nWhich nine times hems the ghosts, to upper light\nHas dragged her lord, in death and fate's despite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If that loud-voiced Maeonian trump whilere\nThe Macedonian grudged Achilles, how,\nFrancis Pescara, O unconquered peer,\nWould he begrudge thee, were he living now,\nThat wife, so virtuous and to thee so dear,\nThy well-earned glory through the world should blow;\nAnd that thy name through her should so rebound,\nThou needst not crave a clearer trumpet's sound!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If all that is to tell, and all I fain\nWould of that lady tell, I wished to unfold,\nThough long, yet not so long, would be the stain,\nBut that large portion would be left untold,\nWhile at a stand the story would remain\nOf fierce Marphisa and her comrades bold;\nTo follow whom I promised erst, if you\nWould but return to hear my song anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now, being here to listen to my say,\nBecause I would not break my promise, I\nUntil my better leisure, will delay\nHer every praise at length to certify.\nNot that I think she needs my humble lay,\nWho with such treasure can herself supply:\nBut simply to appay my single end,\nThat gentle dame to honour and commend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ladies, in fine I say, that every age\nWorthy of story, many a dame supplies;\nBut that, through jealous authors' envious rage,\nUnchronicled by fame, each matron dies;\nBut will no more; since in the historic page\nYour virtues ye, yourselves, immortalize.\nHad those two damsels in this art been read,\nTheir every warlike deed had wider spread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant and Marphisa would I say,\nWhose bold, victorious deeds, in battle done,\nI strive to bring into the light of day;\nBut nine in ten remain to me unknown.\nI what I know right willingly display;\nAs well, that all fair actions should be shown,\nAs well that, gentle ladies, I am bent\nYe whom I love and honour, to content."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As said, in act to go Rogero stood;\nAnd, having taken leave, the cavalier\nWithdraws his trenchant faulchion from the wood,\nWhich holds no more the weapon, as whilere.\nWhen, sounding loud amid that solitude,\nA cry, not distant far, arrests the peer.\nThen thitherward he with those damsels made,\nPrompt, if 'twere needed, to bestow his aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They rode an-end; and louder waxed the sound,\nAnd plainer were the plaintive words they heard:\nWhen in a valley they three women found\nMaking that plaint, who in strange garb appeared:\nFor to the navel were those three ungowned,\n— Their coats by some uncourteous varlet sheared —\nAnd knowing not how better to disguise\nTheir shame, they sate on earth, and dared not rise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As Vulcan's son, that sprang (as it is versed)\nOut of the dust, without a mother made,\nWhom — so Minerva bade — Aglauros nursed\nWith sovereign care, too bold and curious maid,\nSeated in car, by him constructed first\nTo hide his hideous feet, was erst conveyed;\nSo that which never is to sight revealed,\nSitting, those mournful damsels kept concealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At that dishonest sight and shameful, glows\nEach martial damsel's visage, overspread\nWith the rich dyes of Paestum's crimson rose,\nWhen vernal airs their gentle influence shed.\nBradamant marked them; and that one of those\nWas Ulany, the damsel quickly read;\nUlany, that was sent with solemn train\nFrom the LOST ISLE to royal Charlemagne;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And recognised the other two no less;\nFrom them she saw, when she saw Ulany;\nBut now to her directed her address.\nAs the most honoured of those ladies three,\nDemanding, who so full of wickedness,\nSo lawless was and so unmannerly,\nThat he those secrets to the sight revealed,\nWhich Nature, as she could, 'twould seem, concealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ulany, that in Bradamant descried,\n— Known both by voice and ensignry — the maid,\nWho some few days before those knights of pride\nWith her victorious lance on earth had laid,\nHow, in a town not far remote — replied —\nAn evil race, by pity never swayed,\nBesides that they their raiment thus had shorn,\nHad beat them, and had done them other scorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What of the shield became, she cannot say,\nNor knows she those three monarchs' destiny,\nWho guided her so long upon her way;\nIf killed, or led into captivity;\nAnd says that she herself has ta'en her way,\nAlbeit to fare a-foot sore irksome be,\nTo appeal to royal Charlemagne, assured\nBy him such outrage will not be endured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To hear, yet more to see, so foul a wrong,\nDisturbed the Child and damsels' placid air\nAnd beauteous visage, whose bold hearts and strong\nNo less compassionate than valiant were.\nThey now, all else forgetting, ere the tongue\nOf Ulany prefers demand, or prayer,\nThat they would venge them on their cruel foe,\nIn haste towards the felon's castle go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With one constant, the maids and cavalier,\nBy their great goodness moved, from plate and mail\nHad stript their upper vests, well fitting gear\nThose miserable ladies' shame to veil.\nBradamant suffers not, that, as whilere,\nSad Ulany shall tramp by hill and dale;\nBut seats her on her horse's croup; so do\nHer comrades by those other damsels two."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To gentle Bradamant Ulania showed\nThe nearest way to reach the castle height;\nWhile comfort Bradamant on her bestowed,\nPromising vengeance for that foul despite.\nThey leave the vale, and by a crooked road\nAnd long ascend, now wheeling left, now right:\nNor till the sun is hidden in the sea,\nUpon their weary way repose the three."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They to a hamlet on the summit wound,\nScaling the mountain's steep and rugged side;\nAnd such good shelter and good supper found,\nAs could by such rude quarters be supplied.\nArriving there, they turned their eyes around,\nAnd full of women every place espied,\nSome old, some young; nor, mid so large a clan,\nAppeared the visage of a single man."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not more bold Jason wondered, and the train\nWhich sailed with him, that Argonautic crew,\nSeeing those dames that had their husbands slain,\nFathers and sons and brethren, — so that through\nAll Lemnos' pleasant isle, by hill or plain,\nOf manly visage they beheld not two —\nThan here Rogero, and the rest who go\nWith good Rogero, wonder at this show."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The martial damsels bid for Ulany,\nAnd those who came with her, provide attire;\nAnd gowns that eve are furnished for the three,\nIf meaner than their own, at least entire.\nTo him a woman of that villagery\nValiant Rogero summons, to inquire\nWhere are the men; in that he none descries;\nAnd thus to him that village wife replies:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What haply is to you a wonderment,\nThis crowd of womankind, where man is none,\nTo us is grave and grievous punishment,\nWho, banished here, live wofully alone;\nAnd, that such exile us may more torment,\nFrom those so loved, as brother, father, son,\nA long divorce and cruel we sustain,\nAs our fell tyrant pleases to ordain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sent to these confines from his land, which lies\nBut two leagues distant thence, where we were born,\nUs in this place the fell barbarian sties,\nHaving first done us many a brutal scorn;\nAnd has with death and all extremities\nThreatened our kinsmen and ourselves forlorn,\nIf they come hither, or he hears report\nWe harbour them, when hither they resort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He to our name is such a deadly foe,\nHe will not have us nearer than I shewed,\nNow have us of our kin approached, as though\nInfection from the female sex ensued.\nAlready have the greenwood trees laid low\nTheir leafy honours twice, and twice renewed,\nSince our lord's fury to such pitch arose,\nNow is there one his phrensy to oppose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For he has spread such passing fear among\nThe people, death can cause no worse affright;\nIn that, beside his natural love of wrong,\nHe is endowed with more than human might.\nHe than a hundred other men more strong,\nIn body is of a gigantic height:\nNor us his vassals he molests alone;\nBut worse by him to stranger dame is done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If your own honour, sir, and of those three,\nBeneath your charge, to you in aught is dear,\n'Twill safer, usefuller, and better be\nTo leave this road, and by another steer.\nThis leads you to his tower, described by me,\nTo prove the savage use that cruel peer\nHas there established, to the shame and woe\nOf dame or cavalier, who thither go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This castellain or tyrant, Marganor\n(So name the felon knight than whom more fell ) \n\nNero was not, nor other heretofore,\nIf other be, whose actions Fame doth swell,\nThirsts for man's blood, but thirsts for woman's more\nThan wolf for blood of lambs; and bids expel\nWith shame all females, that, in evil hour,\nTheir fortune has conducted to his tower.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "How in that impious man such fury grew,\nAsked young Rogero and those damsels twain,\nAnd prayed she would in courtesy pursue,\nYea, rather from the first her tale explain.\n\"That castle's lord, fierce, and inhumane,\nYet for a while his wicked heart concealed,\nNor what he was so suddenly revealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For in the lifetime of his sons, a pair\nThat differed much from the paternal style,\n(Since they the stranger loved; and loathers were\nOf cruelty and other actions vile)\nFlourished the courtesies and good customs there,\nAnd there were gentle deeds performed this while:\nFor. albeit avaricious was the sire,\nHe never crossed the youths in their desire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The cavaliers and dames who journeyed by\nThat castle, there so well were entertained,\nThat they departed, by the courtesy\nOf those two kindly brothers wholly gained.\nIn the holy orders of fair chivalry\nAlike the youthful pair had been ordained.\nCylander one, Tanacro hight the other;\nBold, and of royal mien each martial brother;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And truly were, and would have been alway\nWorthy of every praise and fame, withal\nHad they not yielded up themselves a prey\nTo that uncurbed desire, which Love we call;\nBy which they were seduced from the right way\nInto foul Error's crooked maze; and all\nThe good that by those brethren had been wrought,\nWaxed, in a moment, rank, corrupt and naught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"It chanced, that in their father's fortilage,\nA knight of the Greek emperor's court did lie;\nWith him his lady was; of manners sage;\nNor fairer could be craved by wishful eye:\nFor her Cylander felt such amorous rage,\nHe deemed, save he enjoyed her, he should die;\nHe deemed that, when the lady should depart,\nHis soul as well would from his body part:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, for he knew 'twas useless to entreat,\nDevised to make her his by force of hand;\nArmed, and in silence, near his father's seat,\nWhere must pass knight and lady, took his stand.\nThrough natural daring and through amorous heat,\nHe with too little thought the matter planned;\nSo that, when he beheld the knight advance,\nHe issued, to assail him, lance to lance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To overthrow him, at first shock he thought,\nAnd to win dame and palm in the career;\nBut that Greek knight, in warlike strife well-taught,\nShivered, like glass, his breastplate with the spear.\nThe bitter tidings to the sire were brought,\nWho bade bear home the stripling on a bier:\nHe, finding he was dead, loud mourning made,\nAnd him in earth, beside his fathers, layed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet harbourage and welcome as before\nHad he who sought it; neither more nor less:\nBecause Tanacro in his courteous lore\nEqualled his brother as in gentleness.\nThither that very year, from foreign shore,\nA baron and his wife their steps address:\nA marvel he of valour, and as fair\nAs could be said, is she, and debonnair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No fairer was the dame than chaste and right,\nAnd well deserving every praise; the peer\nDerived of generous stock, and bold in fight,\nAs ever champion, of whose fame we hear;\nAnd 'tis well fitting, that such valiant wight\nShould joy a thing so excellent and dear,\nOlindro he, the lord of Lungavilla,\nAnd she, his lady wife, yclept Drusilla."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"No less for her the young Tanacro glows,\nThan for that other burned Cylander sore;\nWho brought erewhile to sad and bitter close\nThe wicked love he to that lady bore.\nThe holy, hospitable laws he chose\nTo violate no less than he, before\nHe would endure, that him, with venomed sting,\nHis new desire to cruel death should bring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But he, because he has before his eyes\nThe example of his elder brother slain,\nThinks to bear off the lady in such wise,\nThat bold Olindro cannot venge the stain.\nStraight spent in him, not simply weakened, lies\nThe virtue, wont Tancaro to sustain\nAbove that flood of vice, in whose profound\nAnd miry waters Marganor lay drowned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That night, he in deep silence bade array\nA score of armed men; and next conveyed\nInto some caverns, bordering on the way,\nAnd distant from the tower, his ambuscade.\nThe roads were broken, and the following day\nOlindro from all sides was overlaid;\nAnd, though he made a brave defence and long,\nOf wife and life was plundered by that throng."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Olindro slain, they led his lady fair\nA captive thence, o'erwhelmed with sorrow so,\nThat she refused to live, and made her prayer,\nTanacro, as a grace, would death bestow:\nResolved to die, she leapt, in her despair,\nFrom a high bank into a vale below;\nBut death was to the wretched dame refused;\nWho lay with shattered head and sorely bruised."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She could not to the castle be conveyed\nIn other guise than borne upon a bier:\nHer (so Tanacro bids prompt leeches aid; ) \n\nBecause he will not lose a prey so dear;\nAnd while to cure Drusilla they essayed,\nBusied about their spousals was the peer:\nIn that so chaste a lady and so fair,\nA wife's and not a leman's name should wear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He had no other thought, no other aim,\nNo other care, nor spake beside of ought;\nSaw he had wronged her, and took all the blame,\nAnd, as he could, to amend his error wrought:\nBut all was vain; the more he loved the dame,\nThe more be to appease her anger sought,\nSo much more was her hate; so much more will,\nSo much more thirst had she that youth to kill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet hatred blinded not her judgment so,\nBut what the dame could clearly comprehend,\nThat she, if she would strike the purposed blow,\nMust feign, and secret snares for him extend.\nAnd her desire beneath another show\n(Which is but how Tanacro to offend)\nMust mask; and make him think, that overblown\nIs her first love, and turned to him alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her face speaks peace; while vengeance inwardly\nHer heart demands, and but to this attends:\nShe many things revolves, accepts, puts by;\nOr, as of doubtful issue, some suspends.\nDeeming she can, if she resolves to die,\nCompass her scheme, with this resolve she ends;\nAnd better how can she expend her breath\nThan in avenging dear Olindro's death?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She showed herself all joyful, on her part,\nAnd feigned that she desired those nuptials sore;\nNor only showed an unreluctant heart;\nBut all delay and hindrance overbore.\nPainted and tired above the rest with art,\n'Twould seem, she of her husband thinks no more:\nBut 'tis her will, that in her country's wise\nTanacro shall their wedding solemnize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The custom howsoever was not true,\nWhich as her country's use she certified;\nBut, because never thought within her grew\nWhich she could spend on any thing beside,\nA falsehood she devised, whence hope she drew\nOf killing him by whom her husband died;\nAnd told Tanacro — and the manner said —\nHow in her country's fashion she would wed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `The widow that a husband's bed ascends,\nEre she approach the bridegroom (said that fair)\nThe spirit of the dead, whom she offends,\nMust soothe with solemn office, mass and prayer;\nIn the holy temple making her amends,\nWhere her first husband's bones entombed are.\n— That sacrifice performed — to bind their vows\nThe nuptial ring the bridegroom gives the spouse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `But the holy priest, while this shall be about,\nUpon wine, thither for that purpose sped,\nHis orisons, appropriate and devout,\nBlessing withal the liquor, shall have said;\nThen from the flask into a cup pour out,\nAnd give the blessed wine to them that wed.\nBut 'tis the spouse's part to take the cup;\nAnd first that vessel's cordial beverage sup.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The unsuspecting youth, who takes no heed\nWhat nuptials, ordered in her wise, import,\nAt her own pleasure bids the dame proceed,\nSo that she cut his terms of waiting short;\nNor does the miserable stripling read\nShe would avenge Olindro in that sort;\nAnd on one object is so sore intent,\nHe sees but that, on that alone is bent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"An ancient woman, seized with her whilere,\nAnd left, withal, obeyed Drusilla, who\nThat beldam called and whispered in her ear,\nSo as that none beside could hear the two —\nA poison of quick power for me prepare,\nSuch as, I know, thou knowest how to brew;\nAnd bottle it; for I have found a way\nThe traitorous son of Marganor to slay;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And me and thee no less can save,' (she said,)\n`And this at better leisure will explain.'\nThe woman went her ways, the potion made,\nAnd to the palace bent her steps again:\nA flask of Candian sweet wine she purveyed,\nWherewith Drusilla sheathed that deadly bane;\nAnd kept the beverage for the nuptial day;\nFor now had ceased all hindrance and delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"On the fixt day she seeks the temple, dight\nWith precious jewels and with goodly gear;\nWhere her lord's tomb, befitting such a knight,\nBuilt by her order, two fair pillars rear.\nThe holy office there, with solemn rite,\nIs sung, which men and women troop to hear;\nAnd — gay, beyond his usage — with his heir,\nBegirt by friends, Sir Marganor is there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When the holy obsequies at last were o'er,\nAnd by the priest was blest the poisoned draught,\nHe into a fair golden cup did pour\nThe wine, as by Drusilla had been taught,\nShe drank what sorted with her sex; nor more\nThan would effect the purpose which she sought:\nThen to the bridegroom, with a jocund eye,\nHanded the draught, who drained the goblet dry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The cup returned — Tanacro, blithe and gay,\nOpened his arms Drusilla to embrace.\nThen altered was her sweet and winning way,\nAnd to a tempest that long calm gave place.\nShe thrust him back, she motioned him away;\nShe seemed to kindle in her eyes and face;\nAnd to the youth, with broken voice and dread,\n— `Traitor, stand off,' — the furious lady said; —"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Shalt thou then joy and solace have from me,\nI tears from thee, and punishment and woe?\nNow these mine hands shall make an end of thee.\nThis, if thou know'st it not, for poison know.\nMuch grieve I that thou should'st too honoured be\nBy the executioner who deals the blow;\nShould'st die a death too easy: since I wot,\nFor thee too shameful hand or pain is not."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `In seeing this thy death, it gives me pain,\nMy sacrifice should be completed ill;\nFor could I do by thee as I were fain,\nNothing should lack that purpose to fulfill.\nMay my sweet consort not the work disdain,\nAnd for the imperfect deed accept the will!\nThat, without power to compass what I would,\nI have been fain to slay thee as I could!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And that deserved punishment, which I\nCannot, as I desire, on thee bestow,\nI hope thy soul shall have; hope to be nigh,\nTo see thee suffer, in the realms of woe.'\nHer turbid eyes then raising to the sky,\nWith joyous face all over in a glow,\n(She cried `Olindro, take this victim's life, ) \n\nWith the good will of thine avenging wife;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And of our lord for me the grace obtain,\nTo be this day in paradise with thee,\nIf he reply, none cometh to your reign,\nWithout desert; say such I bring with me,\nWho this fell impious monster, in his fane,\nOffer, as my first-fruits; and what can be\nA greater merit than to have supprest\nSuch loathsome and abominable pest?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her life, together with her speech, was spent;\nAnd, even dead, her face appeared to glow\nWith joy, at having dealt such punishment\nTo him, that laid her cherished husband low.\nIf fierce Tanacro's spirit did prevent,\nOf follow hers, I wiss not; but, I trow,\nPrevented, for on him that venom rank\nYet faster wrought, because he deeper drank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Marganor, who beheld his only son\nFall and expire, his outstretched arms between,\nWell nigh had with Tanacro died, o'erthrown\nBy that so sudden grief and unforeseen.\nTwo sons he had, and now was left alone;\nBrought to that pass he by two wives had been;\nThis was the cause one spent his vital breath\nWith her own hand, that dealt the other death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Love, pity, sorrow, anger, and desire\nOf death and vengeance, all together rend\nAnd rack the childless and unhappy sire,\nWho groans like sea, when wind and waves contend:\nTowards the dame, with vengeful thoughts afire,\nHe goes, but sees that life is at an end;\nAnd, goaded by his rage and hatred hot,\nSeeks to offend her corse that feels it not."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As serpent, by the pointed spear pinned down,\nFixes his teeth in it, with fruitless spire;\nOr as the mastiff runs towards a stone,\nWhich has been flung by some wayfaring wight,\nAnd gnaws it in his rage, nor will be gone\nUntil he venge himself; 'tis so the knight,\nThan any mastiff, any serpent, worse\nOffends Drusilla's cold and lifeless corse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, for he venteth not, nor slakes his mood,\nBy foul abuse upon the carcase done,\nAmong the women, a large multitude,\nHe springs, and there shows mercy unto none.\nMown are we with his impious sword, as strewed\nIs grass with scythe, when dried by summer sun.\nThere is no 'scape; for straightways of our train\nAre full a hundred maimed, and thirty slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He of his vassals is so held in dread,\nThere is no man who dares to lift his eyes:\nThe women with the meaner sort are fled,\nAnd whosoever can, the temple flies.\nHis friends against the furious fit make head,\nAt last, with kind constraint and suppliant cries;\nAnd, leaving every thing in tears below,\nHim in his castle on the rock bestow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"His wrath enduring still, to send away\nThe wretch determines all the female band:\nIn that, his will us utterly to slay\nHis people and his friends, with prayer, withstand;\nAnd he bids punish, on that very day,\nAn order for us all to leave his land;\nPlaced such his pleasures on these confines: woe\nTo them that nearer to his castle go!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thus husbands from their wives divided are,\nMothers from sons: if hither to resort,\nDespite that order, any one should dare,\nLet none know this, who might the deed report!\nFor sorely mulcted for the transgression were\nMany, and many slain in cruel sort.\nA statute for his town next made the peer:\nOf fouler law we neither read nor hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"It wills, all women found within the vale,\n(For thither even yet will some descend,)\nHis men with rods shall on the shoulders whale,\nAnd into exile from those countries send;\nBut first their gowns shall clip, and parts unveil\nThat decency and natural shame offend;\nAnd if with escort of an armed knight\nAny wend thither, they are slain outright."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Those that an armed warrior's escort have,\nBy this ill man, to piety a foe,\nAre dragged as victims to his children's grave,\nWhere his own hand inflicts the murderous blow.\nStript ignominiously of armour, glaive,\nAnd steed, their champions to his prisons go;\nAnd this can he compel; for, night and day,\nA thousand men the tyrant's hest obey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And I will add, moreover, 'tis his will,\nDoes he free any one, he first shall swear\nUpon the holy wafer, that he still\nTo woman, while he lives, will hatred bear.\nIf then these ladies and yourself to spill\nSeem good to you, to yonder walls repair;\nAnd put to proof withal, if prowess more\nOr cruelty prevails in Marganor.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, in those maids of martial might\nFirst she such pity moved and then disdain,\nThat they (had it been day instead of night)\nWould then have gone against that castellain.\nThere rest the troop; and when Aurora's light\nServes as a signal to the starry train,\nThat they should all before the sun recede,\nThey don the cuirass and remount the steed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And now, in act to go, that company\nBehind them hear the stony road resound\nWith a long trample, when those warlike three\nLook down the vale and roll their eyes around;\nAnd they from thence, a stone's-throw distant, see\nA troop, which through a narrow pathway wound:\nA score they are perhaps in number, who\nOn horseback, or on foot, their way pursue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They with them on a horse a woman haul,\n(Whom stricken sore in years her visage shows,)\nIn guise wherein some doleful criminal\nCondemned to gallows, fire, or prison goes;\nWho, notwithstanding that wide interval,\nIs by her features known, as well as clothes:\nThey of the village, mid the cavalcade,\nKnow her for fair Drusilla's chamber maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The chamber wench, made prisoner with his prize,\nBy the rapacious stripling, as I shewed,\nWho being trusted with that ill emprize,\nThe poisoned draught of foul effect had brewed.\nFrom the others she and those solemnites\nHad kept away, suspecting what ensued:\nYea, this while, from that lordship had she fled,\nWhere she in safety hoped to hide her head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "News being after to her foeman brought,\nThat she retired in Ostericche lay,\nHe, with intent to burn the woman, sought\nTo have her in his power by every way;\nAnd finally unhappy Avarice, bought\nBy costly presents, and by proffered pay,\nWrought on a lord, assured upon whose lands\nThe beldam lived, to put her in his hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He on a sumpter horse the prisoner sent\nTo Constance-town, like merchandise addrest;\nFastened and bound in manner to prevent\nThe use of speech, and prisoned in a chest.\nFrom whence that rabble, his ill instrument,\nWho has all pity banished from his breast,\nHad hither brought her, that his impious rage\nThat cruel man might on the hag assuage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the flood, swoln with Vesulo's thick snows,\nThe farther that it foams upon its way,\nAnd, with Ticino and Lambra, seaward goes,\nAda, and other streams that tribute pay,\nSo much more haughty and impetuous flows;\nRogero so, the more he hears display\nMarganor's guilt, and so that gentle pair\nOf damsels filled with fiercer choler are."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Them with such hatred, them with such disdain\nAgainst the wretch so many crimes incense,\nThat they will punish him, despite the train\nOr armed men arraid in his defence:\nBut speedy death appears too kind a pain,\nAnd insufficient for such foul offence.\nBetter they deem, mid pangs prolonged and slow,\nHe all the bitterness of death should know."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But first 'tis right that woman to unchain,\nShe whom the hangman-crew to death escort;\nAnd the quick rowel and the loosened rein\nMade the quick coursers make that labour short.\nNever had those assaulted to sustain\nEncounter of so fell and fierce a sort;\nWho held it for a grace, with loss of shield,\nHarness and captive dame, to quit the field;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even as the wolf, who, laden with his prey,\nIs homeward to his secret cavern bound,\nAnd, when he deems that safest is the way,\nBeholds it crost by hunter and by hound,\nFlings down his load, and swiftly darts away,\nWhere most o'ergrown with brushwood is the ground.\nNor quicker are that band to void the vale,\nThan those bold three are quicker to assail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not only they the dame and martial gear,\nBut many horses they as well forsook;\nAnd, as the surest refuge in their fear,\nCast themselves down from bank and caverned nook:\nWhich pleased the damsels and the youthful peer;\nWho three of those forsaken horses took,\nTo mount those three, whom, through the day before,\nUpon their croups the three good coursers bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thence, lightened thus, their way they thither bend,\nWhere that despiteous, shameful, lordship lies;\nResolved the beldam in their band shall wend,\nTo see Drusilla venged; in vain denies\nThat woman, who misdoubts the adventure's end,\nAnd grieves, and shrieks, and weeps in piteous wise:\nFor flinging her upon Frontino's croup,\nRogero bears her off amid the troop."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They reached a summit, and from thence espied\nA town with many houses, large and rich;\nWith nought to stop the way on any side,\nAs neither compassed round by wall or ditch.\nA rock was in the middle, fortified\nWith a tall tower, upon its topmost pitch.\nFearlessly thither pricked the warriors, who\nMarganor's mansion in that fortress knew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as in the town that cavalcade\nArrived, some footmen, who kept watch and ward,\nBehind those warriors closed a barricade;\nWhile that, before, they found already barred.\nAnd lo!  Sir Marganor, with men arraid,\nSome foot, some horsemen!  armed was all the guard;\nWho to the strangers, in few words, but bold,\nThe wicked custom of his lordship told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa, who had planned the thing whilere\nWith Aymon's daughter and the youthful knight,\nFor answer, spurred against the cavalier;\nAnd, valiant as she was and full of might,\nNot putting in the rest her puissant spear,\nOr baring that good sword, so famed in fight,\nSo smote him with her fist upon the head,\nThat on his horse's neck he fell half dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The maid of France is with Marphisa gone,\nNor in the rear it seen Rogero's crest;\nWho with those two his course so bravely run,\nThat, though his lance he raised not from the rest,\nSix men he slew; transfixed the paunch of one,\nAnother's head, of four the neck or breast;\nI' the sixth he broke it, whom in flight he speared:\nIt pierced his spine and at his paps appeared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As many as are touched, so many lie\nOn earth, by Bradamant's gold lance o'erthrown;\nShe seems a bolt, dismist form burning sky,\nWhich, in its fury, shivers and beats down\nWhatever it encounters, far and nigh.\nSome fly to plain, or castle from the town,\nOthers to sheltering church and house repair;\nAnd none, save dead, are seen in street or square."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile the hands of Marganor, behind\nHis back, the fierce Marphisa had made fast,\nAnd to Drusilla's maid the wretch consigned,\nWell pleased that such a care on her was cast.\nTo burn the town 'twas afterwards designed,\nSave it repented of its errors past,\nRepealed the statute Marganor had made,\nAnd a new law, imposed by her, obeyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such end to compass is no hard assay;\nFor, besides fearing lest Marphisa yearn\nTo execute more vengeance, — lest she say,\n— She one and all will slaughter and will burn, —\nThe townsmen all were advised to the sway\nAnd cruel statute of that tyrant stern;\nBut did, as others mostly do, that best\nObey the master whom they most detest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since none dares trust another, nor his will,\n— Out of suspicion — to his comrades break,\nThey let him banish one, another kill,\nFrom this his substance, that his honour take.\nBut the heart cries to Heaven, that here is still,\nTill God and saints at length to vengeance wake:\nWho, albeit they due punishment suspend,\nBy mighty pain the long delay amend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The rabble, full of rage and enmity,\nNow seeks the wretch with word and deed to grieve;\nAs, it is said, all strip the fallen tree,\nWhich from its roots and wintry winds upheave:\nLet rulers in his sad example see,\nIll doers in the end shall ill receive.\nTo view fell Marganor's disastrous fall,\nFit penance for his sins, pleased great and small."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Many, of whom the sister had been slain,\nThe mother, or the daughter, or the wife,\nSeeking no more their rebel wrath to rein,\nHurry, with their own hands to take his life;\nAnd young Rogero and the damsels twain\nCan scarce defend the felon in that strife;\nWhom those illustrious three had doomed to die,\nMid trouble, fear, and lengthened agony."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To the hag, who bore such hatred to that wight,\nAs woman to an enemy can bear,\nThey give their prisoner naked, bound so tight,\nHe will not at one shake the cordage tear;\nAnd she, her pains and sorrow to requite,\nCrimsons the wretch's body, here and there,\nWith a sharp goad, which, mid that village band,\nA peasant churl had put into her hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor she the courier maid, nor they that ride\nWith her, aye mindful how they had been shent,\nNow let their hands hang idle by their side;\nNo less than that old crone on vengeance bent:\nSuch was their fierce desire, it nullified\nThe power to harm; but rage must have its vent.,\nHim one with stones, another with her nails,\nThis with her teeth, with needles that, assails."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As torrent one while foams in haughty tide,\nWhen fed with mighty rain or melted snow;\nAnd, rending form the mountain's rugged side\nTree, rock, and crop and field, the waters go:\nThen comes a season when its crested pride\nIs vanished, and its vigour wasted so,\nA child, a woman, everywhere may tread,\nAnd often dry-shod cross, its rugged bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So Marganor whilere each bound and bourn\nMade tremble, whereso'er his name was heard:\nNow one is come to bruise the tyrant's horn;\nAnd now his prowess is so little feared,\nThat even the little children work him scorn:\nSome pluck his hair and others pluck his beard.\nThence young Rogero and the damsels twain\nTowards his rock-built castle turn the rein."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This without contest its possessors yield,\nAnd the rich goods preserved in that repair.\nThese the friends partly spoiled, and partly dealed\nTo Ulany and that attendant pair.\nWith them, recovered was the golden shield,\nAnd those three monarchs that were prisoned there;\nWho, without arms, afoot, towards that hold\nHad wended, as meseems whilere was told."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For from the day that they were overthrown\nBy Bradamant, afoot, they evermore,\nUnarmed, in company with her had gone,\nThat hither came from her so distant shore.\nI know not, I, if it was better done\nOr worse, by her, that they their arms forbore;\nWorse, touching her defence; but better far,\nIf they were losers in the doubtful war."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For she would have been dragged, — like others, whom\nArmed men had thither brought beneath their guide,\n(Unhappy women to the brothers' tomb, — ) \n\nAnd by the sacrifice knife have died.\nDeath, sure, is worse, and more disastrous doom\nThan showing that which modesty would hide;\nAnd they who can to force ascribe the blame,\nExtinguish this and every other shame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Before they hence depart, the martial twain\nAssemble the inhabitants, to swear,\nThey to their wives the rule of that domain\nWill leave, as well as every other care;\nAnd that they will chastise, with heavy pain,\nWhoever to oppose this law shall dare.\n— In fine, man's privileges, whatsoe'er,\nThey swear, shall be conferred on woman here:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then make them promise never to bestow\nHarbourage on whosoever thither sped,\nFootman or cavalier, nor even allow\nAny beneath a roof to hide his head,\nUnless he swore by God and saints, or vow\nYet stronger made — if stronger could be said —\nThat he the sex's cause would aye defend,\nFoe to their foes, and woman's faithful friend;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, if he then were wived, or ever were\n— Sooner or later — linked in nuptial noose,\nStill to his wife he would allegiance bear,\nNor e'er compliance with her will refuse.\nMarphisa says, within the year, she there\nWill be, and ere the trees their foliage lose;\nAnd, save she find her statute in effect,\nThat borough fire and ruin may expect."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor hence they part ill from the filthy place,\nWherein it lay, Drusilla's corse is borne;\nHer with her lord they in a tomb encase,\nAnd, with what means the town supplies, adorn.\nDrusilla's ancient woman, in this space,\nMarganor's body with her goad has torn.\nWho only grieves she has not wind enow,\nNo respite to his torture to allow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beside a church, the martial damsels twain\nBehold a pillar, standing in the square;\nWhereon the wicked lord of the domain\nHad graved that mad and cruel law; the pair,\nIn imitation, his helm, plate, and chain,\nAnd shield, in guise of trophy fasten there;\nAnd afterwards upon the pillar trace\nThat law they had enacted for the place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within the town the troop set up their rest,\nUntil the law is graved, of different frame\nFrom that before upon the stone imprest,\nWhich every woman doom'd to death and shame.\nWith the intention to replace her vest,\nHere from that band divides the Islandick dame;\nWho deems, at court 'twere shameful to appear,\nUnless adorned and mantled as whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here Ulany remained, and in her power\nRemained the wicked tyrant Marganor:\nShe, lest he any how, in evil hour,\nShould break his bonds and injure damsel more,\nMade him, one day, leap headlong from a tower,\nWho never took so still a leap before.\nNo more of her and hers!  I of the crew\nThat journey toward Arles, the tale pursue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Throughout all that and the succeeding day,\nTill the forenoon, proceed those banded friends;\nAnd, where the main-road branches, and one way\nTowards the camp, to Arles the other tends,\nAgain embrace the lovers, and oft say\nA last farewell, which evermore offends.\nThe damsels seek the camp; to Arles is gone"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto I have done.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 38"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Arles the Child, to Charles Marphisa wends,\nTo be baptized, with Bradamant for guide.\nAstolpho from the holy realm descends;\nThrough whom with sight the Nubian is supplied:\nAgramant's land he with his troop offends;\nBut he is of his Africk realm so wide,\nWith Charles he bargains, that, on either side,\nTwo knights by strife their quarrel should decide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ye courteous ladies, who unto my strain\nKind audience lend — I read it in your cheer —\nThat good Rogero should depart again\nSo suddenly, from her that held him dear,\nDispleases ye, and scarce inflicts less pain\nThan that which Bradamant endured whilere:\nI read you also argue, to his shame,\nThat feebly burned in him the amorous flame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If from her side for other cause had gone,\nAgainst that lady's will, the youthful lord;\nThough in the hope more treasure to have won\nThan swelled rich Croesus' or rich Crassus' hoard,\nI too should deem the dart, by Cupid thrown,\nHad not the heart-core of Rogero gored.\nFor such a sovereign joy, a prize so high\nNo silver and no gold could ever buy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet to preserve our honour not alone\nDeserves excuse, it also merits praise:\nThis to preserve, I say, when to have done\nIn other wise, might shame and scandal raise;\nAnd had fair Bradamant reluctance shown,\nAnd obstinately interposed delays,\nThis, as a certain sign, had served to prove\nThat lady's little wit or little love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For if his life, whom gentle woman loves,\nAs her own life she values, or before;\n(I speak of one at whom young Cupid roves\nWith arrows which beneath the mantle gore)\nHis honour to his pleasure it behoves\nThat woman to prefer, by so much more,\nAs man beyond his life his honour treasures,\nEsteemed by him above all other pleasures."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His duty good Rogero satisfied,\nFollowing the royal lord with whom he came;\nFor having no fair cause to quit his side,\nHe could not leave the Paynim without shame;\nAnd, if his sire had by Almontes died,\nIn this, King Agramant was not to blame;\nWho for his parents' every past offence\nHad made Rogero mighty recompense."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He will perform his duty to repair\nTo his liege-lord; so did that martial maid;\nWho had not with reiterated prayer\n(As so she might have done Rogero stayed. ) \n\nThe stripling may appay the warlike fair\nIn other season, if not now appaid;\nBut twice two hundred years will not atone\nThe crying sin of honour once foregone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Arles-town whither had his king conveyed\nHis remnant of a host, he pricked anew;\nWhile they that, since their kindred was displayed,\nHad a close friendship formed — the damsels two —\nThither together go where Charles had made\nHis mightiest effort, with the Christian crew;\nHoping by siege or fight to break the foe,\nAnd free his kingdom form so long a woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant, when she in the camp appeared,\nWas greeted with a welcome warm and kind.\nOn all sides was she hailed, by all was cheered;\nAnd she in this or that her head inclined.\nRinaldo, when he of her coming heard,\nMet her; nor young Richardo stayed behind;\nNor Richardet; nor others of her race;\nAnd all received the maid with joyful face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When next 'tis known, the second of the twain\nIs that Marphisa, so in arms renowned,\nWho from Catay unto the bounds of Spain\nHad journeyed, with a thousand laurels crowned,\nNor rich nor poor within their tents remain:\nThe curious crowd, encompassing them round,\nPress, harm, and heave each other here and there,\nIn the sole wish to see so bright a pair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By them was Charles saluted reverently,\nAnd the first day was this (has Turpin shown)\nMarphisa had been seen to bend her knee:\nFor Pepin's royal son to her, alone,\nDeserving of such duty seemed to be,\nMid emperors or kings that filled a throne,\nBaptized or infidel, of all those named\nFor mighty riches, or for valour famed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Her kindly Charlemagne received, and wide\nOf the pavilions met, in open view;\nAnd, above king, and prince, and peer, beside\nHimself the monarch placed that damsel true.\nWho go not, are dismist; so none abide\nIn little time, except the good and few.\nThe Paladins and lords remain; without,\nIs left the unrespected rabble-rout."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa first began in grateful strain:\n\"Unconquered Caesar, glorious and august,\nWho, to Alcides' strait from Indian main,\nMak'st Scythian's pale and Aethiop's race adust\nRevere thy Christian cross of snowy grain,\n— Of earthly monarchs thou most sage and just —\nHither thy glory, which no limits bound,\nHas brought me from the world's extremest ground;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And (to avow the truth in jealous mood ) \n\nAlone I came, alone with thee to fight;\nBecause I grudged that king so puissant shou'd\nExist on earth, save he observed my rite.\nHence reek they ravaged fields with Christian blood;\nAnd yet with greater rancour and despite,\nLike cruel foe, I purposed to offend,\nBut that it chanced, one changed me to a friend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When to worst harm and scaith thy bands I doom,\nI find (as at my leisure I will show)\nRogero of Risa was my father, whom\nAn evil brother traitorously laid low.\nMe my sad mother carried in her womb\nBeyond the sea, and bore in want and woe.\nTill my seventh year by wizard nourished, I\nWas stolen from him by thieves of Araby."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"They to a king in Persia vended me,\nThat after died beneath my faulchion, who\nWould fain have taken my virginity.\nWhen grown, that king and all his court I slew;\nChased his ill race, and seized his royalty;\nAnd — such my fortune — by a month or two,\nI eithteen years had not o'erpast, before\nI added to my realm six kingdoms more;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, moved by envy of thy glorious fame\nI in my heart resolved (as thou hast heard)\nTo abate the grandeur of they mighty name:\nI haply so had done; I haply erred.\nBut now a chance has served that will to tame,\nAnd clip my fury's wings; the having heard\nSince I arrived in Christendom, how we\nAre bound by ties of consanguinity;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And, for my father thee, as kinsman, served,\nSo thou a kin and servant hast in me;\nAnd I that envy, that fierce hate, which nerved\nMine arm whilere, now blot from memory.\nNay, these for evil Agramant reserved,\nAnd for his sire's and uncle's kin shall be;\nThey who were whilom guilty of the death\nOf that unhappy pair, who gave me breath.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She adds, the Christian faith she will receive,\nAnd, after having spent king Agramant,\nWill home return, with royal Charles's leave,\nHer kingdom to baptize in the Levant,\nAnd war upon whatever nation cleave\nTo cheating Mahound or to Termagant;\nPromising that whate'er her arms obtain\nShall be the Christian faith's and empire's gain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Charles, no less eloquent upon his side,\nThan bold in deed and prudent in design,\nMuch that illustrious lady magnified,\nAnd much her father, much her noble line:\nHe courteously to every point replied;\nAnd of his heart his open front was sign.\nAs his last words, that he received the maid\nAs kinswoman and child, the monarch said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then rose and locked her in a new embrace,\nAnd kissed her, like a daughter, on the brow.\nMorgana and Clermont's kin, with joyful face,\nAll thither troop; 'twere tedious to tell how\nRinaldo did the gentle damsel grace;\nFor he had oftentimes espied ere now\nHer martial prowess, tried by goodly test,\nWhen they with girding siege Albracca pressed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twere long to tell how, with those worthies met,\nGuido rejoiced to see Marphisa there;\nGryphon and Aquilant, and Sansonet,\nThat with her in the cruel city were;\nVivian, and Malagigi, and Richardet;\nWho, when Maganza's traitors made repair,\nWith those ill purchasers of Spain to trade,\nFound such a faithful comrade in the maid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They deck the ground for the ensuing day;\nAnd Charlemagne takes care himself to see\nThat they the place shall sumptuously array,\nWherein Marphisa's baptism is to be.\nBishops are gathered, learned clerks, and they\nWho ken the laws of Christianity;\nThat taught in all its doctrine by their care\nAnd holy skill may be that martial fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In sacred stole, pontifical, arraid,\nHer the archbishop Turpin did baptize;\nCharlemagne from the healthful font the maid\nUplifted with befitting ceremonies.\nBut it is time the witless head to aid\nWith that, which treasured in the phial lies,\nWherewith Astolpho, from the lowest star,\nDescended in Elias' fiery car."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke descended from the lucid round,\nOn this our earthly planet's loftiest height.\nWither he with that blessed vase was bound,\nWhich was the mighty champion's brain to right.\nA herb of sovereign virtue on that ground\nThe apostle shows, and with it bids the knight\nThe Nubian's eyeballs touch, when him anew\nHe visits, and restore that sovereign's view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That he, for this and for his first desert,\nMay give him bands, Biserta to assail;\nAnd shows him how that people inexpert\nHe may to battle train, in plate and mail;\nAnd how to pass the deserts, without hurt,\nWhere men are dazzled by the sandy gale.\nThe order that throughout should be maintained\nFrom point to point, the sainted sire explained;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then made him that plumed beast again bestride,\nRogero's and Atlantes' steed whilere.\nBy sainted John dismist, his reverend guide,\nThose holy regions left the cavalier;\nAnd coasting Nile, on one or the other side,\nSaw Nubia's realm before him soon appear;\nAnd there, in its chief city, to the ground\nDescended, and anew Senapus found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Great was the joy, and great was the delight,\nWherewith that king received the English lord;\nWho well remembered how the gentle knight\nHad from the loathsome harpies freed his board.\nBut when the humour, that obscured his sight,\nValiant Astolpho scaled, and now restored\nWas the blind sovereign's eyesight as before,\nHe would that warrior as a god adore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So that not only those whom he demands\nFor the Bisertine war, he gives in aid;\nBut adds a hundred thousand from his bands,\nAnd offer of his royal person made.\nScarce on the open plain embattled stands,\n— All foot — the Nubian host, for war arraid.\nFor few the horses which that region bore;\nOf elephants and camels a large store."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The night before the day, when on its road\nThe Nubian force should march, Astolpho rose,\nAnd his winged hippogryph again bestrode:\nThen, hurrying ever south, in fury goes\nTo a high hill, the southern wind's abode;\nWhence he towards the Bears in fury blows:\nThere finds a cave, through whose strait entrance breaks\nThe fell and furious Auster, when he wakes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, as his master erst instruction gave,\nWith him an empty bladder had conveyed;\nWhich, at the vent of that dim Alpine cave,\nWherein reposed the wearied wind, was laid\nQuaintly and softly by the baron brave;\nAnd so unlooked for was the ambuscade,\nThat, issuing forth at morn, to sweep the plains,\nAuster imprisoned in the skin remains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Nubia he, rejoicing in his prey,\nReturns; and with that very light the peer,\nWith the black host, sets out upon his way,\nAnd lets the victual follow in his rear.\nTowards Mount Atlas with his whole array\nIn safety goes the glorious cavalier.\nThrough shifting plains of powdery sand he past,\nNor dreaded danger from the sultry blast;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And having gained the mountain's hither side,\nWhence are discerned the plain, and distant brine,\nHe chooses from the swarm he has to guide\nThe noblest and most fit for discipline;\nAnd makes them, here and there, in troops divide,\nAt a hill's foot, wherewith the plains confine;\nThen leaves his host and climbs the hill's ascent,\nLike one that is on lofty thoughts intent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After he, lowly kneeling in the dust,\nHis holy master had implored, in true\nAssurance he was heard, he downward thrust\nA heap of stones.  O what things may he do\nThat in the Saviour wholly puts his trust!\nThe stones beyond the use of nature grew;\nWhich rolling to the sandy plain below,\nNext, neck and muzzle, legs and belly show."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They, neighing shrill, down narrow paths repair,\nWith lusty leaps; and lighting on the plain,\nUplift the croup, like coursers as they are,\nSome bay, some roan, and some of dapple stain.\nThe crowds that waiting in the valleys were,\nLayed hands on them, and seized them by the rein.\nThus in a thought each soldier had his horse,\nBorn ready reined and saddled for the course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He fourscore thousand of his Nubian power,\nOne hundred and two footmen, in a day\nTo horsemen changes, who wide Afric scour,\nAnd, upon every side, sack, burn, and slay.\nAgramant had intrusted town and tower,\nTill his return, to king Branzardo's sway,\nTo Fersa's king, and him of the Algaziers;\nAnd these against Astolpho lead their spears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Erewhile a nimble bark, with sail and oar,\nThey had dispatched, which, stirring feet and wings,\nNews of the Nubian monarch's outrage bore\nTo Agramant from his vicegerent kings,\nThat rests not, night nor day, till to the shore\nOf Provence she her doleful tiding brings;\nAnd finds her monarch half subdued in Arles,\nFor camped within a mile was conquering Charles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant, hearing in what peril lies\nHis realm, through his attack on Pepin's reign,\nHim in this pressing peril to advise,\nCalls kings and princes of the paynim train;\nAnd when he once or twice has turned his eyes\nOn sage Sobrino and the king of Spain,\n— Eldest and wisest they those lords among —\nThe monarch so bespeaks the assembled throng:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Albeit if fits not captain, as I know,\nTo say, `on this I thought not,' this I say;\nBecause when from a quarter comes the blow,\nFrom every human forethought far away,\n'Tis for such fault a fair excuse, I trow;\nAnd here all hinges; I did ill to lay\nUnfurnished Africk open to attack,\nIf there was ground to fear the Nubian sack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But who could think, save only God on high\nPrescient of all which is to be below,\nThat, from land, beneath such distant sky,\nSuch mighty host would come, to work us woe?\n'Twixt shifting sands, which restless whirlwinds blow:\nYet they their camp have round Biserta placed,\nAnd laid the better part of Africk waste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I now on this, O peers!  your counsel crave.\nIf, bootless, homeward I should wend my way,\nOr should not such a fair adventure wave,\nTill Charles with me a prisoner I convey;\nOr how I may as well our Africk save,\nAnd ruin this redoubted empire, say.\nWho can advise, is prayed his lore to shew,\nThat we may learn the best, and that pursue.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He said; and on Marsilius seated nigh\nNext turned his eyes, who in the signal read,\nThat it belonged to him to make reply\nTo what the king of Africa had said.\nThe Spaniard rose, and bending reverently\nTo Agramant the knee as well as head,\nAgain his honoured seat in council prest,\nAnd in these words the Moorish king addrest:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My liege, does Rumour good or ill report,\nIt still increases them; hence shall I ne'er,\nUnder despondence, lack for due support,\nNor bolder course than is befitting steer,\nFor what may chance, of good or evil sort;\nWeighing in even balance hope and fear,\nO'errated still; and which we should not mete\nBy what I hear so many tongues repeat;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Which should so much more doubtfully be viewed,\nAs it seems less with likelihood to stand.\nNow it is seen, if there be likelihood,\nThat king who reigns in so remote a land,\nFollowed by such a mighty multitude,\nShould set his foot on warlike Africk's strand;\nTraversing sands, to which in evil hour\nCambyses trusted his ill-omened power."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I well believe, that from some neighbouring hill\nThe Arabs have poured down, to waste the plain;\nWho, for the country was defended ill,\nHave taken, burnt, destroyed and sacked and slain;\nAnd that Branzardo, who your place doth fill,\nAs viceroy and lieutenant of the reign,\nHas set down thousands, where he tens should write;\nThe better to excuse him in your sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The Nubian squadrons, I will even yield,\nHave been rained down on Africk from the skies;\nOr haply they have come, in clouds concealed,\nIn that their march was hidden from all eyes:\nThink you, because unaided in the field,\nYour Africk from such host in peril lies?\nYour garrisons were sure of coward vein,\nIf they were scared by such a craven train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But will you send some frigates, albeit few,\n(Provided that unfurled your standards be)\nNo sooner shall they loose from hence, that crew\nOf spoilers shall within their confines flee;\n— Nubians are they, or idle Arabs — who,\nKnowing that you are severed by the sea\nFrom your own realm, and warring with our band,\nHave taken courage to assail your land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Now take your time for vengeance, when the son\nOf Pepin is without his nephew's aid.\nSince bold Orlando is away, by none\nOf the hostile sect resistance can be made.\nIf, through neglect or blindness, be foregone\nThe glorious Fortune, which for you has stayed,\nShe her bald front, as now her hair, will show,\nTo our long infamy and mighty woe.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus warily the Spanish king replied,\nProving by this and other argument,\nThe Moorish squadrons should in France abide,\nTill Charlemagne was into exile sent.\nBut King Sobrino, he that plainly spied\nThe scope whereon Marsilius was intent,\nTo public good preferring private gain,\nSo spake in answer to the king of Spain:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My liege, when I to peace exhorted you,\nWould that my prophecy had proved less just!\nOf, if I was to prove a prophet true,\nYe in Sobrino had reposed more trust,\nThan in King Rodomont and in that crew,\nAlzirdo, Martasine and Marbalust!\nWhom I would here see gladly, front to front;\nBut see most gladly boastful Rodomont."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To twit that warrior with his threat to do\nBy France, what by the brittle glass is done;\nAnd throughout heaven and hell your course pursue,\nYea (as the monarch said your course outrun. ) \n\nYet lapt in foul and loathsome ease, while you\nSo need his help, lies Ulien's lazy son;\nAnd I, that as a coward was decried\nFor my true prophecy, am at your side;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And ever will be while this life I bear;\nWhich, albeit 'tis with yours sore laden, still\nDaily for you is risked with them that are\nThe best of France; and — be he who he will —\nThere is not mortal living, who will dare\nTo say Sobrino's deeds were ever ill:\nYea, many who vaunt more, amid your host,\nHave not so much, nay lighter, cause for boast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I speak, these words to show that what whilere\nI said and say again, has neither sprung\nFrom evil heart, nor is the fruit of fear;\nBut that true love and duty move my tongue.\nYou homeward with what haste you may to steer,\nI counsel, your assembled bands among;\nFor little is the wisdom of that wight,\nWho risks his own to gain another's right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If there be gain, ye know, Late thirty-two,\nYour vassal kings, with you our sails we spread;\nNow, if we pause to sum the account anew,\nHardly a third survives; the rest are dead.\nMay it please Heaven no further loss ensue!\nBut if you will pursue your quest, I dread\nLest not a fourth nor fifth will soon remain;\nAnd wholly spent will be your wretched train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Orlando's absence so far aids, that where\nOur troops are few, there haply none would be;\nBut not through this removed our perils are,\nThough it prolongs our evil destiny.\nBehold Rinaldo!  whom his deeds declare\nNo less than bold Orlando; of his tree\nThere are the shoots; with paladin and peer,\nOur baffled Saracens' eternal fear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And the other Mars (albeit against my heart\nIt goes to waste my praise upon a foe);\nI speak of the redoubted Brandimart,\nWhose feats no less than fierce Orlando's show;\nWhose mighty prowess I have proved in part,\nIn part, at others' cost I see and know.\nThen many days Orlando has been gone;\nYet we have lost more fields than we have won."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I fear, if heretofore our band has lost,\nA heavier forfeit will henceforth be paid.\nBlotted is Mandricardo from our host;\nMartial Gradasso hath withdrawn his aid;\nMarphisa, at our worst, has left her post;\nSo Argier's lord; of whom it may be said,\nWhere he as true as strong, we should not need\nGradasso and the Tartar king, to speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"While aids like these are lost to our array,\nWhile on our side such slaughtered thousands lie,\nThose looked-for are arrived, nor on her way\nIs any vessel fraught with new supply —\nCharles has been joined by four, that, as they say,\nMight with Orlando or Rinaldo vie;\nWith reasons, for from hence to Bactrian shore,\nIll would you hope to find such other four."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I know not if you know who Guido are,\nSansonet, and the sons of Olivier.\nFor these I more respect, more fear I bear,\nThan any warlike duke or cavalier,\nOf Almayn's or of other lineage fair,\nWho for the Roman empire rests the spear,\nThough I misrate not those of newer stamp,\nThat, to our scathe, are gathered in their camp."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As often as ye issue on the plain,\nWorsted so oft, or broken, shall you be.\nIf oft united Africa and Spain\nWere losers, when sixteen to eight were we,\nWhat will ensue, when banded with Almayn\nAre England, Scotland, France, and Italy?\nWhen with our six twice six their weapons cross,\nWhat else can we expect but shame and loss?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"You lose your people here, and there your reign,\nIf you in this emprize are obstinate;\n— Returning — us, the remnant of your train,\nYou save, together with your royal state.\nIt were ill done to leave the king of Spain,\nSince all for this would hold you sore ingrate;\nYet there's a remedy in peace; which, so\nIt pleases but yourself, will please the foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But, if, as first defeated, on your part\nIt seems a shame to offer peace, and ye\nHave war and wasteful battle more at heart,\nWaged hitherto with what success you see,\nAt least to gain the victory use art,\nWhich may be yours, if you are ruled by me.\nLay all our quarrel's trial on one peer,\nAnd let Rogero be that cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Such our Rogero is, ye know and I,\nThat — pitted one to one in listed fight —\nNot Roland, not Rinaldo stands more high,\nNor whatsoever other Christian knight.\nBut would ye kindle warfare far and nigh,\nThough superhuman be that champion's might,\nThe warrior is but one mid many spears,\nMatched singly with a host of martial peers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Meseemeth, if to you it seemeth good,\nYe should propose to Charles the war to end;\nAnd that, to spare the constant waste of blood,\nWhich his, and countless of your warriors spend,\nHe — by a knight of yours to be withstood —\nA champion, chosen from his best should send;\nAnd those two all the warfare wage alone,\nTill one prevails, and one is overthrown;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"On pact the king, whose champion in the just\nIs loser, tribute to that other pay.\nNor will this pact displease King Charles, I trust,\nThough his was the advantage in the fray.\nThen of his arms Rogero so robust\nI deem, that he will surely win the day;\nWho would prevail (so certain is our right)\nThough Mars himself should be his opposite.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With these and other sayings yet more sound,\nSo wrought Sobrino, he his end obtained;\nAnd on that day interpreters were found,\nAnd they that day to Charles their charge explained.\nCharles, whom such matchless cavaliers surround.\nBelieves the battle is already gained;\nAnd chooses good Rinaldo for the just,\nNext to Orlando in his sovereign's trust."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In this accord like cause for pleasure find,\nAs well the Christian as the paynim foe:\nFor, harassed sore in body and in mind,\nThose warriors all were weary, all were woe.\nEach in repose and quietude designed\nTo pass what time remained to him below:\nEach cursed the senseless anger and the hate\nWhich stirred their hearts to discord and debate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo felt himself much magnified,\nThat Charles, for what in him so strong weighed,\nMore trusted him than all his court beside,\nAnd glad the honoured enterprise assayed:\nRogero he esteemed not in his pride,\nAnd thought he ill could keep him from his blade.\nNor deemed the Child could equal him in fight,\nAlbeit he slew in strife the Tartar knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, though much honoured, on his part,\nThat him his king has chosen from the rest,\nTo whom a trust so weighty to impart,\nAs of his many martial lords the best,\nYet shows a troubled face; not that the heart\nOf that good knight unworthy fears molest;\nNot only none Rinaldo would have bred;\nHim, with Orlando leagued, he would not dread —"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But because sister of the Christian knight\n(He knows is she, his consort true and dear; ) \n\nThat to the stripling evermore did write,\nAs one sore injured by that cavalier.\nNow, if to ancient sins he should unite\nA mortal combat with Montalban's peer,\nHer, although loving, will he anger so,\nNot lightly she her hatred will forego."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If silently Rogero made lament\nThat he in his despite must battle do;\nIn sobs his consort dear to hers gave vent,\nWhen shortly to her ears the tidings flew.\nShe beat her breast, her golden tresses rent:\nFast, scalding tears her innocent cheeks bedew:\nShe taxes young Rogero as ingrate,\nAnd aye cries out upon her cruel fate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nought can result to Bradamant but pain,\nWhatever is the doubtful combat's end.\nShe will not think Rogero can be slain;\nFor this, 'twould seem, her very heart would rend;\nAnd should our Lord the fall of France ordain,\nThat kingdom for more sins than one to amend,\nThe gentle maid, beside a brother's loss,\nWould have to weep a worse and bitterer cross."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For, without shame and scorn, she never may,\nNot without hatred of her kin combined,\nTo her loved lord return in such a way\nAs that it may be known of all mankind;\nAs, thinking upon this by night and day,\nShe oftentimes had purposed in her mind;\nAnd so by promise both were tied withal,\nRoom for repentance and retreat was small."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But she, that ever, when things adverse were,\nWith faithful succour Bradamant had stayed,\nI say the weird Melissa, could not bear\nTo hear the wailings of the woeful maid;\nShe hurried to console her in her care,\nAnd proffered succour in due time and said,\nShe would disturb that duel 'twixt the twain,\nThe occasion of such grief and cruel pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile their weapons for the future fray\nRogero and Duke Aymon's son prepared;\nThe choice whereof with that good warrior lay,\nThe Roman empire's knight by Charles declared;\nAnd he, like one that ever from the day\nHe lost his goodly steed afoot had fared,\nMade choice, afoot and fenced with plate and mail,\nHis foe with axe and dagger to assail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether Chance moved Mountalban's martial lord,\nOr Malagigi, provident and sage,\nThat knew how young Rogero's charmed sword\nCleft helm and hauberk in its greedy rage,\nOne and the other warrior made accord,\n(As said without their faulchions to engage. ) \n\nThe place of combat chosen by that twain\nWas near old Arles, upon a spacious plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Watchful Aurora hardly from the bower\nOf old Tithonus hath put forth her head,\nTo give beginning to the day and hour\nPrefixed and ordered for that duel dread,\nWhen deputies from either hostile power,\nOn this side and on that forth issuing, spread\nTents at each entrance of the lists; and near\nThe two pavillions, both, an altar rear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After short pause, was seen upon the plain\nThe paynim host in different squadrons dight.\nRich in barbarick pomp, amid that train,\nRode Africk's monarch, ready armed for fight:\nBay was the steed he backed, with sable mane;\nTwo of his legs were pied, his forehead white\nFast beside Agramant, Rogero came,\nAnd him to serve Marsilius thought no shame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The casque that he from Mandricardo wrung\nIn single combat with such travel sore,\nThe casque that (as in loftier strain is sung)\nCased Hector's head, a thousand years before,\nMarsilius carried, by his side, among\nPrinces and lords, that severally bore\nThe other harness of Rogero bold,\nEnriched with precious pearls and rough with gold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the other part, without his camp appears\nCharles, with his men at arms in squadrons dight;\nWho in such order led his cavaliers,\nAs they would keep, if marshalled for the fight.\nFenced is the monarch with his famous peers,\nAnd with him wends, all armed, Montalban's knight,\nArmed, save his helmet, erst Mambrino's casque;\nTo carry which is Danish Ogier's task;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, of two axes, hath Duke Namus one,\nKing Salamon the other: Charlemagne\nIs to this side, with all his following, gone,\nTo that wend those of Africk and of Spain.\nIn the mid space between the hosts is none;\nEmpty remains large portion of the plain;\nFor he is doomed to death who thither goes,\nBy joint proclaim, except the chosen foes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After the second choice of arms was made\nBy him, the champion of the paynim clan,\nThither two priests of either sect conveyed\nTwo books; that, carried by one holy man,\n— Him of our law — Christ's perfect life displayed;\nThose others' volume was their Alcoran.\nThe emperor in his hands the Gospel took,\nThe king of Africa that other book."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Charlemagne, at his altar, to the sky\nLifted his hands, \"O God, that for our sake\"\n(Exclaimed the monarch \"wast content to die, ) \n\nThyself a ransom for our sins to make;\n— O thou that found such favour in his eye,\nThat God from thee the flesh of man did take,\nBorne for nine months within thy holy womb,\nWhile aye thy virgin flower preserved its bloom,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Hear, and be witnesses of what I say,\nFor me and those that after me shall reign,\nTo Agramant and those that heir his sway,\nI twenty loads of gold of perfect grain\nWill every year deliver, if to-day\nMy champion vanquished in the lists remain;\nAnd vow I will straightway from warfare cease,\nAnd from henceforth maintain perpetual peace;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And may your joint and fearful wrath descend\nOn me forthwith, if I my word forego!\nAnd may it me and mine alone offend,\nAnd none beside, amid this numerous show!\nThat all in briefest time may comprehend,\nMy breach of promise has brought down the woe.\"\nSo saying, in his hand the holy book\nCharles held, and fixed on heaven his earnest look."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This done, they seek that altar, sumptuously\nDecked for the purpose, by the pagan train;\nWhere their king swears, that he will pass the sea,\nWith all his army, to his Moorish reign,\nAnd to King Charles will tributary be;\nIf vanquished, young Rogero shall remain;\nAnd will observe the truce for evermore\nUpon the pact declared by Charles before;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And like him, nor in under tone, he swears,\nCalling on Mahound to attest his oath;\nAnd on the volume which his pontiff bears,\nTo observe what he has promised plights his troth.\nThen to his side each hastily repairs;\nAnd mid their several powers are harboured both.\nNext these, to swear arrive the champions twain;\nAnd this the promise which their oaths contain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero pledges first his knightly word,\nShould his king mar, or send to mar, the fray,\nHe him no more as leader or as lord\nWill serve, but wholly Charlemagne obey.\n— Rinaldo — if in breach of their accord,\nHim from the field King Charles would bear away,\nTill one or the other is subdued in fight,\nThat he will be the Moorish monarch's knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When ended are the ceremonies, here\nAnd there, to seek their camps the two divide.\nNor long, therein delayed; when trumpets clear\nThe time for their encounter signified:\nNow to the charge advanced each cavalier,\nMeasuring with cautious care his every stride.\nLo!  the assault begins; now low, now high,\nThat pair the sounding steel in circles ply."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now with the axe's blade, now with its heel\nTheir strokes they at the head or foot address;\nAnd these so skilfully and nimbly deal,\nAs needs must shock all credence to express.\nThe Child, that at her brother aims the steel,\nWho doth his miserable soul possess,\nEvermore with such caution strikes his blow,\nThat he is deemed less vigorous than his foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rather to parry then to smite intent,\nHe know not what to wish; that low should lie\nRinaldo, would Rogero ill content,\nNor willingly the Child by him would die.\nBut here I am at my full line's extent,\nWhere I must needs defer my history."
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto shall the rest appear,\nCanto please to hear.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 39"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant breaks the pact, is overthrown,\nAnd forced fair France for Afric to forego.\nMeanwhile Astolpho in Biserta's town\nHaving with numerous host besieged the foe,\nBy hazard there arrives bold Milo's son,\nTo whom the duke, instructed how to do,\nRestores his wits.  At sea does Dudon meet\nKing Agramant, and sore annoys his fleet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Than that fell woe which on Rogero weighs\nHarder, and bitterer pain forsooth is none,\nWhich upon flesh and more on spirit preys:\nFor of two deaths there is no scaping one.\nHim, if in strife o'erlaid, Rinaldo slays,\nBradamant, if Rinaldo is outdone:\nFor if he killed her brother, well he knew\nHer hate, than death more hateful, would ensue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo, unimpeded by such thought,\nStrove in all ways Rogero to o'erthrow;\nFierce and despiteous whirled his axe, and sought\nNow in the arms, now head, to wound the foe.\nRogero circled here and there, and caught\nUpon his weapon's shaft the coming blow;\nAnd, if ever smote, aye strove to smite\nWhere he should injure least Montalban's knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To most of them that led the paynim bands,\nBut too unequal seemed the fierce assay.\nToo slowly young Rogero plied his hands;\nToo well Rinaldo kept the Child at bay.\nWith troubled face the king of Afric stands:\nHe sighed, and breathless gazed upon the fray;\nAnd all the blame of that ill counsel flung\nOn King Sobrino's head, from whom it sprung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile the weird Melissa, she — the font\nOf all that wizards or enchanters know —\nHad by her art transformed her female front,\nAnd taken Argier's mighty shape; in show\nAnd gesture she appeared as Rodomont,\nAnd seemed, like him, in dragon's hide to go:\nSuch was her belied sword and such her shield;\nNor aught was wanting which he wore afield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She towards Troyano's mournful son did guide,\nIn form of courser, a familiar sprite,\nAnd with a troubled visage loudly cried,\n\"My liege, this is too foul an oversight,\nA stripling boy in peril yet untried,\nAgainst a Gaul, so stout and famed in fight,\nYour champion in so fierce a strife to make;\nWhere Afric's realm and honour are at stake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Let not this battle be pursued, my lord,\nIn that 'twould cost our Moorish cause too dear.\nLet sin of broken faith and forfeit word\nFall upon Rodomont!  take thou no fear!\nLet each now show the metal of his sword,\nEach for a hundred stands when I am here.\"\nSo upon Agramant this counsel wrought,\nThat king pressed forward without further thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, thinking that the monarch of Algiers\nIs with him, of the pact has little care;\nAnd would not rate a thousand cavaliers\nSo high, if handed in his aid they were.\nHence steeds reined-in and spurred, hence levelled spears\nAre seen in one short instant here and there.\nMelissa, when the hosts are mixed in fight\nBy her false phantoms, vanishes from sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The champions two, that, against all accord,\nAgainst all faith, disturbed their duel see,\nNo longer strive in fight, but pledge their word\n— Yea, put aside all hostile injury —\nThat they, on neither part, will draw the sword,\nUntil they better certified shall be\nWho broke the pact, established by that twain,\nYoung Agramant, or aged Charlemagne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They sweat anew, the king who had o'erthrown\nThat truce, and broken faith, as foe to treat.\nThe field of combat is turned upside down;\nSome hurry to the charge, and some retreat.\nWho most deserved disgrace, who most renown,\nWas seen, on both hands, in the selfsame feat;\nAll ran alike: but, 'mid that wild affray,\nThese ran to meet the foe, those ran away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As greyhound in the slip, that the fleet hare\nScowering about and circling him discerns,\nNor with the other dogs a part can bear\n(For him the hunter holds), with anger burns;\nTorments himself and mourns in his despair,\nAnd whines, and strives against the leash, by turns;\nSuch till that moment had the fury been\nOf Aymon's daughter and the martial queen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They till that hour upon the spacious plain,\nHad watched so rich a prize throughout the day;\nAnd, as obliged by treaty to refrain\nFrom laying hands upon the costly prey,\nHad sore lamented and had grieved in vain,\nGazing with longing eyes on that array.\nNow seeing truce and treaty broke, among\nThe Moorish squadrons they rejoicing sprung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa piercing her first victim's breast,\n(Two yards beyond his back the lance did pass)\nIn briefer time than 'tis by me exprest,\nBroke with her sword four helms which flew like glass;\nNo less did Bradamant upon the rest;\nBut them her spear reduced to other pass.\nAll touched by that gold lance she overthrew;\nDoubling Marphisa's score; yet none she slew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They witness to each others' exploits are,\n(Those maids to one another are so near)\nThen, whither fury drives, the martial pair,\nDividing, through the Moorish ranks career.\nWho could each several warrior's name declare,\nStretched on the champaign by that golden spear?\nOr reckon every head Marphisa left\nDivided by her horrid sword, or cleft?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As when benigner winds more swiftly blow,\nAnd Apennine his shaggy back lays bare,\nTwo turbid torrents with like fury flow,\nWhich, in their fall, two separate channels wear,\nUproot hard rocks, and mighty trees which grow\nOn their steep banks, and field and harvest bear\nInto the vale, and seem as if they vied\nWhich should do mightiest damage on its side:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So those high-minded virgin warriors two,\nScowering the field in separate courses, made\nHuge havock of the Moors; whom they pursue\nOne with couched lance, and one with lifted blade.\nHardly King Agramant his Africk crew\nFrom flight, beneath his royal banners stayed:\nIn search of Rodomont, he vainly turned;\nNor tidings of the missing warrior learned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He at his exhortation (so he trowed)\nHad broke the treaty made in solemn wise,\nTo witness which the gods were called aloud;\nWho then so quick vanished from his eyes:\nNor sees he King Sobrino; disavowed\nBy King Sobrino is the deed, who flies\nTo Arles, and deems that day some vengeance dread\nWill fall on Agramant's devoted head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marsilius too is fled into the town:\nSo has that monarch holy faith at heart.\n'Tis hence, that feebly King Troyano's son\nResists the crew, that war on Charles's part,\nItalians, English, Germans; of renown\nAre all; and, scattered upon every part,\nAre mixed the paladins, those barons bold,\nGlittering like jewels on a cloth of gold;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, with those peers, is more than one confest\nAs perfect as is earthly cavalier,\nGuide the savage, that intrepid breast,\nAnd those two famous sons of Olivier.\nI will not now repeat what I exprest\nOf that fierce, daring female twain whilere;\nWho on the field so many Moors extend,\nNo number is there to the slain or end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But, putting this affray some while aside,\nWithout a pinnace will I pass the sea.\nTo them of France so fast I am not tied,\nBut that Astolpho should remembered be:\nOf the grace given him by his holy guide\nI told erewhile, and told (it seems to me)\nBranzardo and the king of Algaziers\nAgainst the duke had mustered all their spears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such as the monarchs could in haste engage,\nRaked from all Africa, that host contained;\nWhether of fitting or of feeble age:\nScarce from impressing women they refrained,\nResolved his thirst of vengeance to assuage,\nAgramant twice his Africa had drained.\nFew people in the land were left, and they\nA feeble and dispirited array."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So proved they; for the foe was scarce in view,\nBefore that levy broke in panic dread:\nLike sheep, their quailing bands Astolpho slew,\nCharging at his more martial squadrons' head;\nAnd with the slain filled all that champaign; few\nInto Biserta from the carnage fled.\nA prisoner valiant Bucifar remained;\nThe town in safety King Branzardo gained;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "More grieved as Bucifaro's loss alone,\nThan had he lost the rest in arms arrayed.\nWide and in want of ramparts is the town;\nAnd these could ill be raised without his aid.\nWhile fain to ransom him, he thinks upon\nThe means, and stands afflicted and dismayed,\nHe recollects him how the paladin,\nDudon, has many a month his prisoner been."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him under Monaco, upon the shore,\nIn his first passage, Sarza's monarch took.\nThenceforth had been a prisoner evermore\nDudon, who was derived of Danish stock.\nThe paladin against the royal Moor\nBranzardo thought, in this distress, to truck;\nAnd knowing through sure spy, Astolpho led\nThe Nubians, to that chief the offer sped."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A paladin himself, Astolpho knows\nHe gladly ought a paladin to free;\nAnd when that case the Moorish envoy shows,\nTo King Branzardo's offer does agree.\nDudon from prison loosed, his thanks bestows;\nAnd whatsoe'er pertains to land or sea,\nBestirs him to accomplish, in accord\nWith his illustrious chief, the English lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho leading such a countless band\nAs might have well seven Africas opprest,\nAnd recollecting 'twas the saint's command,\nWho upon him whilere imposed the quest,\nThat fair Provence and Aquamorta's strand\nHe from the reaving Saracen should wrest,\nMade through his numerous host a second draught\nOf such as least inapt for sea he thought;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And filling next as full as they could be\nHis hands with many different sorts of leaves,\nPlucked from palm, olive, bay and cedar tree,\nApproached the shore, and cast them on the waves.\nOh blessed souls!  Oh great felicity!\nO grace!  which rarely man from God receives;\nO strange and wondrous miracle, which sprung\nOut of those leaves upon the waters flung!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They wax in number beyond all esteem;\nBecoming crooked and heavy, long, and wide.\nInto hard timber turn and solid beam,\nThe slender veins that branch on either side:\nTaper the masts; and, moored in the salt stream,\nAll in a thought transformed to vessels, ride;\nAnd of as diverse qualities appear,\nAs are the plants, whereon they grew whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It was a miracle to see them grown\nTo galliot, galley, frigate ship, and boat;\nWondrous, that they with tackling of their own,\nAre found as well as any barks afloat.\nNor lack there men to govern them, when blown\nBy blustering winds — from islands not remote —\nSardinia or Corsica, of every rate,\nPilot and patron, mariner and mate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Twenty-six thousand were the troop that manned\nThose ready barks of every sort and kind.\nTo Dudon's government, by sea or land\nA leader sage, the navy was consigned;\nWhich yet lay anchored off the Moorish strand,\nExpecting a more favourable wind,\nTo put to sea; when, freighted with a load\nOf prisoners, lo!  a vessel made the road."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She carried those, whom at the bridge of dread,\n— On that so narrow place of battle met —\nRodomont took, as often has been said.\nThe valiant Olivier was of the set,\nOrlando's kin, and, with them, prisoners led,\nWere faithful Brandimart and Sansonet,\nWith more; to tell whereof there is no need;\nOf German, Gascon, or Italian seed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The patron, yet unweeting he should find\nFoes in the port, here entered to unload;\nHaving left Argier many miles behind,\nWhere he was minded to have made abode;\nBecause a boisterous, overblowing, wind\nHad driven his bark beyond her destined road;\nDeeming himself as safe and welcome guest,\nAs Progne, when she seeks her noisy nest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But when, arrived, the imperial eagle spread,\nAnd pards and golden lilies he descries,\nWith countenance as sicklied o'er by dread,\nHe stands, as one that in unwary guise,\nHas chanced on fell and poisonous snake to tread,\nWhich, in the grass, opprest with slumber lies;\nAnd, pale and startled, hastens to retire\nFrom that ill reptile, swoln with bane and ire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But no retreat from peril is there here,\nNor can the patron keep his prisoners down:\nHim thither Brandimart and Olivier,\nSansonet and those others drag, where known\nAnd greeted are the friends with joyful cheer,\nBy England's duke and Danish Ogier's son;\nWho read that he who brought them to that shore\nShould for his pains be sentenced to the oar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Otho's son kind welcome did afford\nUnto those Christian cavaliers, as said:\nWho — honoured at his hospitable board —\nWith arms and all things needful were purveyed.\nHis going, for their sake, the Danish lord\nDeferred, who deemed his voyage well delayed,\nTo parley with those peers, though at the cost\nOf one or two good days, in harbour lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of Charles, and in what state, what order are\nThe affairs of France they gave advices true;\nTold where he best could disembark, and where\nTo most advantage of the Christian crew.\nWhile so the cavaliers their news declare,\nA noise is heard; which ever louder grew,\nFollowed by such a fierce alarm withal,\nAs to more fears than one gave rise in all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The duke Astolpho and the goodly throng,\nThat in discourse with him were occupied,\nArmed in a moment, on their coursers sprung,\nAnd hurried where the Nubians loudest cried;\nAnd seeking wherefore that wide larum rung,\nNow here, now there — those warlike lords espied\nA savage man, and one so strong of hand,\nNaked and sole he troubled all that band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The naked savage whirled a sapling round,\nSo hard, so heavy, and so strong of grain,\nThat every time the weapon went to ground,\nSome warrior, more than maimed, opprest the plain.\nAbove a hundred dead are strewed around;\nNor more defence the routed hands maintain;\nSave that a war of distant parts they try;\nFor there is none will wait the champion nigh."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Astolpho, Brandimart, the Danish knight,\nHastening towards that noise with Olivier,\nRemain astounded at the wondrous might\nAnd courage, which in that wild man appear.\nWhen, posting thither on a palfry light,\nIs seen a damsel, clad in sable gear.\nTo Brandimart in haste that lady goes,\nAnd both her arms about the warrior throws."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This was fair Flordelice, whose bosom so\nBurned with the love of Monodantes' son,\nShe, when she left him prisoner to his foe\nAt that streight bridge, had nigh distracted gone.\nFrom France had she past hither — given to know —\nBy that proud paynim, who the deed had done,\nHow Brandimart, with many cavaliers,\nWas prisoner in the city of Algiers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When now she for that harbour would have weighed,\nAn eastern vessel in Marseilles she found,\nWhich thither had an ancient knight conveyed:\nOf Monodantes' household; a long round\nTo seek his Brandimart that lord had made,\nBy sea, and upon many a distant ground.\nFor he, upon his way, had heard it told,\nHow he in France should find the warrior bold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She knowing old Bardino in that wight,\nBardino who from Monodantes' court\nWith little Brandimart had taken flight,\nAnd reared his nursling in THE SYLVAN FORT;\nThen hearing what had thither brought the knight,\nWith her had made him loosen from the port;\nRelating to that elder, by what chance\nBrandimart had to Africk passed from France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as landed, that Biserta lies\nBesieged by good Astolpho's band, they hear;\nThat Brandimart is with him in the emprize,\nThey learn, but learn not as a matter clear.\nNow in such haste to him the damsel flies,\nWhen she beholds her faithful cavalier,\nAs plainly shows her joy; which woes o'erblown\nHad made the mightiest she had ever known."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The gentle baron no less gladly eyed\nHis faithful and beloved consort's face;\nHer whom he prized above all things beside;\nAnd clipt and welcomed her with loving grace;\nNor his warm wishes would have satisfied\nA first, a second, or a third embrace,\nBut that he spied Bardino, he that came\nFrom France, together with that faithful dame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He stretched his arms, and would embrace the knight;\nAnd — wherefore he was come — would bid him say:\nBut was prevented by the sudden flight\nOf the sacred host, which fled in disarray,\nBefore the club of that mad, naked wight,\nWho with the brandished sapling cleared his way.\nFlordelice viewed the furious man in front;\nAnd cried to Brandimart, \"Behold the count!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the same time, withal, Astolpho bold\nThat this was good Orlando plainly knew,\nBy signs, whereof those ancient saints had told,\nIn the earthly paradise, as tokens true.\nNone of those others, who the knight behold,\nThe courteous baron in the madman view;\nThat from long self-neglect, while wild he ran,\nHad in his visage more of beast than man."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With breast and heart transfixed with pity, cried\nValiant Astolpho — bathed with many a tear —\nTurning to Danish Dudon, at this side,\nAnd afterwards to valiant Olivier;\n\"Behold Orlando!\"  Him awhile they eyed,\nStraining their eyes and lids; then knew the peer;\nAnd, seeing him in such a piteous plight,\nWere filled with grief and wonder at the sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So grieve and so lament the greater part\nOf those good warriors, that their eyes o'erflow.\n\" `Tis time\" (Astolpho cried \"to find some art ) \n\nTo heal him, not indulge in useless woe\";\nAnd from his courser sprang: bold Brandimart,\nOlivier, Sansonet and Dudon so\nAll leap to ground, and all together make\nAt Roland, whom the warriors fain would take."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seeing the circle round about him grow,\nLevels his club that furious paladin,\nAnd makes fierce Dudon feel (who — couched below\nHis buckler — on the madman would break in)\nHow grievous is that staff's descending blow;\nAnd but that Olivier, Orlando's kin,\nBroke in some sort its force, that stake accurst\nHad shield and helmet, head and body burst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It only burst the shield, and in such thunder\nBroke on the casque, that Dudon prest the shore:\nWith that, Sir Sansonet cut clean asunder\nThe sapling, shorn of two cloth-yards and more,\nSo vigorous was that warrior's stroke, while under\nHis bosom, Brandimart girt Roland sore\nWith sinewy arms about his body flung;\nAnd to the champion's legs Astolpho clung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando shook himself, and England's knight,\nTen paces off, reversed upon the ground;\nYet loosed not Brandimart, who with more might\nAnd better hold had clasped the madman round.\nTo Olivier, too forward in that fight,\nHe dealt so furious and so fell a wound,\nWith his clenched fist, that pale the marquis fell;\nAnd purple streams from eyes and nostrils well;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And save his morion had been more than good,\nBold Olivier had breathed his last, who lies,\nSo battered with his fall, it seemed he wou'd\nBequeath his parting soul to paradise.\nAstolpho and Dudon, that again upstood\n(Albeit swoln were Dudon's face and eyes)\nAnd Sansonet, who plied so well his sword,\nAll made together at Anglantes' lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dudon Orlando from behind embraced,\nAnd with his foot the furious peer would throw:\nAstolpho and others seize his arms; but waste\nTheir strength in all attempts to hold the foe.\nHe who has seen a bull, by mastiffs chased\nThat gore his bleeding ears, in fury lowe,\nDragging the dogs that bait him there and here,\nYet from their tusks unable to get clear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Let him imagine, so Orlando drew\nAstolpho and those banded knights along.\nMeanwhile upstarted Oliviero, who\nBy that fell fistycuff on earth was flung;\nAnd, seeing they could ill by Roland do\nThat sought by good Astolpho and his throng,\nHe meditates, and compasses, a way\nThe frantic paladin on earth to lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He many a hawser made them thither bring,\nAnd running knots in them he quickly tied;\nWhich on the count's waist, arms, and legs, they fling;\nAnd then, among themselves, the ends divide,\nConveyed to this or that amid the ring,\nCompassing Roland upon every side.\nThe warriors thus Orlando flung parforce,\nAs farrier throws the struggling ox or horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as down, they all upon him are,\nAnd hands and feet more tightly they constrain:\nHe shakes himself, and plunges here and there;\nBut all his efforts for relief are vain.\nAstolpho bade them hence the prisoner bear;\nFor he would heal (he said the warrior's brain. ) \n\nShouldered by sturdy Dudon is the load,\nAnd on the beach's furthest brink bestowed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seven times Astolpho makes them wash the knight;\nAnd seven times plunged beneath the brine he goes.\nSo that they cleanse away the scurf and blight,\nWhich to his stupid limbs and visage grows.\nThis done, with herbs, for that occasion dight,\nThey stop his mouth, wherewith he puffs and blows.\nFor, save his nostrils, would Astolpho leave\nNo passage whence the count might air receive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Valiant Astolpho had prepared the vase,\nWherein Orlando's senses were contained,\nAnd to his nostrils in such mode conveys,\nThat, drawing-in his breath, the county drained\nThe mystic cup withal.  Oh wondrous case!\nThe unsettled mind its ancient seat regained;\nAnd, in its glorious reasonings, yet more clear\nAnd lucid waxed his wisdom than whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As one, that seems in troubled sleep to see\nAbominable shapes, a horrid crew;\nMonsters which are not, and which cannot be;\nOr seems some strange, unlawful thing to do,\nYet marvels at himself, from slumber free.\nWhen his recovered senses play him true;\nSo good Orlando, when he is made sound,\nRemains yet full of wonder, and astound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Aldabelle's brother, Monodantes' son,\nAnd him that on his brain such cure had wrought,\nHe wondering marked, but word he spake to none;\nAnd when and how he was brought thither, thought.\nHe turned his restless eyes now up now down,\nNor where he was withal, imagined aught,\nMarvelling why he there was naked cast,\nAnd wherefore tethered, neck and heels, so fast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then said, as erst Silenus said — when seen,\nAnd taken sleeping the cave of yore —\nSOLVITE ME, with visage so serene,\nWith look so much less wayward than before,\nThat him they from his bonds delivered clean,\nAnd raiment to the naked warrior bore;\nAll comforting their friend, with grief opprest\nFor that delusion which had him possest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When to his former self he was recovered,\nOf wiser and of manlier mind than e'er,\nFrom love as well was freed the enamoured lord;\nAnd she, so gentle deemed, so fair whilere,\nAnd by renowned Orlando so adored,\nDid but to him a worthless thing appear.\nWhat he through love had lost, to reacquire\nWas his whole study, was his whole desire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile Bardino told to Brandimart,\nHow Monodantes, his good sire, was dead,\nAnd, on his brother, Gigliantes' part,\nTo call him to his kingdom had he sped,\nAs well as from those isles, which most apart\nFrom other lands, in eastern seas are spread,\nThat prince's fair inheritance; than which\nWas none more pleasant, populous, or rich."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He said, mid many reasons which he prest,\nThat home was sweet, and — were the warrior fain\nTo taste that sweet — he ever would detest\nA wandering life; and Brandimart again\nReplies, through all that war, he will not rest\nFrom serving Roland and King Charlemagne;\nAnd after, if he lives to see its end,\nTo his own matters better will attend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the following day, for Provence steer\nThe shipping under Danish Dudon's care;\nWhen with the duke retired Anglantes' peer,\nAnd heard that lord the warfare's state declare:\nThen prest with siege Biserta, far and near,\nBut let good England's knight the honour wear\nOf every vantage; while Astolpho still\nIn all was guided by Orlando's will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The order taken to attack the town\nOf huge Biserta, when, and on what side;\nHow, at the first assault, the walls are won,\nAnd with Orlando who the palm divide,\nLament not that I now shall leave unshown,\nSince for short time I lay my tale aside.\nIn the meanwhile, how fierce an overthrow\nThe Moors received in France, be pleased to know."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Well nigh abandoned was their royal lord\nIn his worst peril; for to Arles again\nHad gone, with many of the paynim horde,\nThe sage Sobrino and the king of Spain;\nWho, for the deemed the land unsafe, aboard\nTheir barks sought refuge, with a numerous train,\nBarons and cavaliers, that served the Moor;\nWho moved by their example put from shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet royal Agramant the fight maintains;\nBut when he can no longer make a stand,\nTurns from the combat, and directly strains\nFor Arles, not far remote, upon the strand.\nHim Rabican pursues, with flowing reins,\nWhom Aymon's daughter drives with heel and hand.\nHim would she slay, through whom so often crost,\nThat martial maid had her Rogero lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa by the same desire was stirred,\nWho had her thoughts on tardy vengeance placed,\nFor her dead sire; and as she fiercely spurred,\nMade her hot courser feel his rider's haste.\nBut neither martial maid, amid that herd\nOf flying Moors, so well the monarch chased,\nAs to o'ertake him in his swift retreat,\nFirst into Arles, and then aboard his fleet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As two fair generous pards, that from some crag\nTogether dart, and stretch across the plain;\nWhen they perceive that vigorous goat or stag,\nTheir nimble quarry, is pursued in vain,\nAs if ashamed they in that chase did lag,\nReturn repentant and in high disdain:\nSo, with a sigh, return those damsels two,\nWhen they the paynim king in safety view:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet therefore halt not, but in fury go\nAmid that crowd, which flies, possest with dread;\nFeeling, now here, now there, at every blow,\nMany that never more uprear their head.\nTo evil pass was brought the broken foe;\nFor safety was not even for them that fled:\nSince Agramant, a sure retreat to gain,\nBade shut the city-gate which faced the plain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And bade on Rhone break all the bridges down.\nUnhappy people, ever held as cheap\n— Weighed with the tyrant's want who wears a crown —\nAs worthless herd of goats or silly sheep!\nThese in the sea, those in the river drown;\nAnd those with blood the thirsty fallows steep.\nThe Franks few prisoners made, and many slew;\nFor ransom in that battle was for few."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of the great multitude of either train,\nChristened or paynim, killed in that last fight,\nThough in unequal parts (for, of the slain,\nBy far more Saracens were killed in flight,\nBy hands of those redoubted damsels twain),\nSigns even to this day remain in sight:\nFor, hard by Arles, where sleeps the lazy Rhone,\nThe plain with rising sepulchres is strown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile his heavy ships of deepest draught\nKing Agramant had made put forth to sea,\nLeaving some barks in port — his lightest craft —\nFor them that would aboard his navy flee:\nHe stays two days, while they the stragglers waft,\nAnd, for the winds are wild and contrary,\nOn the third day, to sail he give command,\nIn trust to make return to Africk's land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Royal Marsilius, in that fatal hour,\nFearing the costs will fall upon his Spain,\nAnd that the clouds, which big with tempest lower,\nIn the end will burst upon his fields and grain,\nMakes for Valentia; where he town and tower\nBegins to fortify with mickle pain;\nAnd for that war prepares, which after ends\nIn the destruction of himself and friends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Agramant his sails for Africk bent:\nHis barks ill-armed and almost empty go;\nEmpty of men, but full of discontent,\nIn that three-fourths had perished by the foe.\nAs cruel some, as weak and proud some shent\nTheir king, and (as still happens in like woe)\nAll hate him privily; but, for they fear\nHis fury, in his presence mute appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet sometimes two or three their lips unclose,\n— Some knot of friends, where each on each relies —\nAnd their pent choler and their rage expose:\nYet Agramant beneath the illusion lies,\nThat each will love and pity overflows;\nAnd this befalls, because he still espies\nFalse faces, hears but voices that applaud,\nAnd nought but adulation, lies and fraud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not in Biserta's port his host to land\nWas the sage king of Africa's intent,\nWho had sure news that shore by Nubia's band\nWas held, but he so far above it meant\nTo steer his Moorish squadron, that the strand\nShould not be steep or rugged for descent:\nThere would he disembark, and thence would aid\nForthwith his people, broken and dismaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But favoured not by his foul destiny\nWas that intention, provident and wise;\nWhich willed the fleet, from leaves of greenwood tree,\nProduced upon the beach in wondrous guise,\nThat, bound for France, now ploughed the foaming sea,\nShould meet the king at night; that from surprise\nIn that dark, dismal hour, amid his crew\nWorse panic and disorder might ensue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not yet to him have tidings been conveyed,\nThat squadrons of such force the billows plow:\nNor would he have believed in him who said,\nA hundred barks had sprung from one small bough;\nAnd hence for Africa the king had weighed,\nNot fearing to encounter hostile prow;\nNor has he watchmen in his tops to spy,\nAnd make report of what they hence descry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "`Twas so those ships, by England's peer supplied\nTo Dudon, manned with good and armed crew,\nWhich see that Moorish fleet at eventide,\nAnd that strange armament forthwith pursue,\nAssailed them unawares, and, far, and wide,\nAmong those barks their grappling-irons threw,\nAnd linked by chains, to their opponents clung,\nWhen known for Moors and foemen by their tongue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In bearing down, impelled by winds that blow\nPropitious to the Danish chief's intent,\nThose weighty ships so shocked the paynim foe,\nThat many vessels to the bottom went;\nThen, taxing wits and hands, to work them woe,\nThem with fire, sword, and stones the Christians shent;\nWhich on their ships in such wide ruin pour,\nLike tempest never vext the sea before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bold Dudon's men, to whom unwonted might\nAnd daring was imparted from on high,\n(Since the hour was come the paynims to requite\nFor more than one ill deed, from far and nigh, ) \n\nThe Moors so pestilently gall and smite,\nAgramant finds no shelter; from the sky\nAbove, thick clouds of whistling arrows strike;\nAround gleam hook and hatchet, sword and pike."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The king hears huge and heavy stones descend,\nFrom charged machine or thundering engine sent,\nWhich, falling, poop and prow and broadside rend,\nOpening to ravening seas a mighty vent;\nAnd more than all the furious fires offend,\nFires that are quickly kindled, slowly spent,\nThe wretched crews would fain that danger shun,\nAnd ever into direr peril run."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One headlong plunged, pursued by fire and sword,\nAnd perished mid the waters, one who wrought\nFaster with arms and feet, his passage oared\nTo other barque, already overfraught:\nBut she repulsed the wretch that fain would board;\nWhose hand, which too importunately sought\nTo clamber, grasped the side, while his lopt arm\nAnd body stained the wave with life-blood warm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him, that to save his life i' the waters thought,\nOr, at the worst, to perish with less pain,\n(Since swimming profited the caitiff nought,\nAnd he perceived his strength and courage drain)\nTo the hungry fires from which the refuge sought,\nThe fear of drowning hurries back again:\nHe grasps a burning plank, and in the dread\nOf dying either death, by both is sped."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This vainly to the sea resorts, whom spear\nOr hatchet, brandished close at hand, dismay;\nFor stone or arrow following in his rear,\nPermit the craven to make little way.\nBut haply, while it yet delights your ear,\n'Twere well and wisely done to end my lay,\nRather than harp upon the theme so long\nAs to annoy you with a tedious song."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 40"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To fly the royal Agramant is fain,\nAnd sees Biserta burning far away;\nBut landing finds the royal Sericane,\nWho of his faith gives goodly warrant; they\nDefy Orlando, backed by champions twain;\nWhom bold Gradasso firmly trusts to slay.\nFor seven kings' sake, fast prisoners to their foes,\nRogero and the Dane exchange rude blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The diverse chances of that sea-fight dread,\nHere to rehearse would take a weary while;\nAnd to discourse to you upon this head,\nGreat son of Hercules, were to Samos' isle\nTo carry earthen vessels, as 'tis said,\nTo Athens owls, and crocodiles the Nile.\nIn that, my lord, by what is vouched to me,\nSuch things you saw, such things made others see."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Your faithful people gazed on a long show,\nThat night and day, wherein they crowded stood,\nAs in a theatre, and hemmed on Po\nTwixt fire and sword, the hostile navies viewed.\nWhat outcries may be heard, what sounds of woe,\nHow rivers may run red with human blood,\nIn suchlike combat, in how many a mode\nMen die, you saw, and you to many showed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I saw not, I, who was compelled to course,\nEvermore changing nags, six days before,\nTo Rome, in heat and haste, some helpful force\nOf him our mighty pastor to implore.\nBut, after, need was none of foot or horse,\nFor so the lion's beak and claws you tore,\nFrom that day unto this I hear not said\nThat he more trouble in your land has bread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Trotto, present at this victory,\nAfranio, Moro, Albert, Hannibal,\nZerbinat, Bagno, the Ariostos three,\nAssured me of the mighty feat withal,\nCertified after by that ensignry,\nSuspended from the holy temple's wall,\nAnd fifteen galleys at our river-side,\nWhich with a thousand captive barks I spied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He that those wrecks and blazing fires discerned,\nAnd such sore slaughter, under different shows,\nWhich — venging us for hall and palace burned —\nWhile bark remained, raged wide among the foes,\nMight also deem how Africk's people mourned,\nWith Agramant, mid diverse deaths and woes,\nOn that dark night, when the redouted Dane\nAssaulted in mid sea the Moorish train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas night, nor gleam was anywhere descried,\nWhen first the fleets in furious strife were blended;\nBut when lit sulphur, pitch and tar from side\nAnd poop and prow into the sky ascended,\nAnd the destructive wild-fire, scattered wide,\nFed upon ship and shallop ill defended,\nThe things about them all descried so clear\nThat night was changed to day, as 'twould appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hence Agramant, that by the dark deceived,\nHad rated not so high the foes' array,\nNor to encounter such a force believed,\nBut would, if 'twere opposed, at last give way,\nWhen that wide darkness cleared, and he perceived\n(What least he weened upon the first affray)\nThat twice as many were the ships he fought,\nAs his own Moorish barks, took other thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Into a boat he with some few descends,\nBrigliador and some precious things, to flee;\nAnd so, twixt ship and ship, in silence wends,\nUntil he finds himself in safer sea,\nFar from his own; whom fiery Dudon shends,\nReduced to sad and sore extremity;\nThem steel destroys, fires burn, and waters drown;\nWhile he, that mighty slaughter's cause, is flown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant flies, and with him old Sobrine,\nAgramant grieving he had not believed,\nWhat time that sage foresaw with eye divine,\nAnd told the woe wherewith he is aggrieved.\nBut turn me to the valiant paladine,\nWho, before other aid can be received,\nCounsels the duke Biserta to destroy;\nThat it no more may Christian France annoy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And hence in public order was it said,\nThe camp should to its arms the third day stand;\nFor this, it was with many barks bested;\nFor all were placed not at the Dane's command.\nThat fleet the worthy Sansonetto led,\n(As good a warrior he by sea as land)\nWhich a mile off the port, and overight\nBiserta, now was anchored by the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando and the duke, like Christians true,\nWhich dare no danger without God for guide,\nThat fast and prayer be made their army through,\nOrdain by proclamation to be cried;\nAnd that upon the third day, when they view\nThe signal, all shall bown them, far and wide,\nBiserta's royal city to attack,\nWhich they, when taken, doom to fire and sack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And so, when now devoutly have been done\nVigil and vow, and holy prayer and fast,\nKin, friends, and those to one another known,\nTogether feast; who, when with glad repast\nTheir wasted bodies were refreshed, begun\nTo embrace and weep; and acts and speeches past,\nUpon the banquet's close, amid those crews\nSuch as best friends, about to sever, use."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The holy priests within Biserta's wall,\nPray with their grieving people, and in tears,\nAye beat their bosoms, and for succour call\nUpon their Mahomet, who nothing hears.\nWhat vigils, offerings, and what gifts withal\nWere promised silently, amid their fears!\nWhat temples, statues, images were vowed,\nIn memory of their bitter woes, aloud!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, when the cadi hath his blessing said,\nThe people arms and to the rampart hies.\nAs yet reposing in her Tithon's bed\nAurora was, and dusky were the skies;\nWhen to their posts, their several troops to head,\nHere Sansonetto, there Astolpho flies.\nAnd when they hear Orlando's signal blown\nAssault with furious force Biserta's town."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Washed by the sea, upon two quarters, were\nThe city walls, two stood on the dry shore,\nOf a construction excellent and rare,\nWherein was seen the work of days of yore:\nOf other bulwarks was the town nigh bare;\nFor since Branzardo there the sceptre bore;\nFew masons at command, and little space\nThat monarch had to fortify the place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Nubian king is charged by England's peer,\nWith sling and arrow so the Moors to gall,\nThat none upon the works shall dare appear;\nAnd that, protected by the ceaseless fall\nOf stone and dart, in safety cavalier\nAnd footman may approach the very wall;\nWho loaded, some with plank, with rock-stone some,\nAnd some with beam, or weightier burden, come."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This and that other thing the Nubians bore,\nAnd by degrees filled-up that channel wide,\nWhose waters were cut off the day before,\nSo that in many parts the ooze was spied.\nFilled is the ditch in haste from shore to shore,\nAnd forms a level to the further side.\nCheering the footmen on the works to mount,\nStand Olivier, Astolpho, and the Count."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Nubian upon hope of gain intent,\nImpatient of delay, nor heeding how\nWith pressing perils they were compassed, went\nProtected by the sheltering boar and sow.\nWith battering ram, and other instrument,\nTo break the gate and make the turret bow,\nSpeedily to the city wall they post,\nNor unprovided find the paynim host."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For steel, and fire, and roof, and turret there,\nIn guise of tempest on the Nubians fell,\nWhich plank and beam from those dread engines tear,\nMade for annoyance of the infidel.\nIn the ill beginning, and while dim the air,\nMuch injury the christened host befell;\nBut when the sun from his rich mansion breaks,\nFortune the faction of the Moor forsakes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The assault is reinforced on every side,\nBy Count Orlando, both by sea and land:\nThe fleet, with Sansonetto for its guide,\nEntered the harbour, and approached the strand;\nAnd sorely they with various engines plied,\nWith arrows and with slings, the paynim band;\nAnd sent the assailants scaling-ladder, spear,\nAnd naval stores, and every needful gear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando, Oliviero, Brandimart,\nAnd he, in air so daring heretofore,\nDo fierce and furious battle on that part,\nWhich lies the furthest inland from the shore:\nEach leads a portion of those Aethiops swart,\nOrdered in equal bands beneath the four,\nWho at the walls, the gateways, or elsewhere,\nAll give of prowess shining proofs and rare."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So better could be seen each warrior's claim,\nThat in confused in combat there and here.\nWho of reward is worthy, who of shame,\nTo a thousand and to watchful eyes is clear.\nDragged upon wheels are towers of wooden frame,\nAnd others well-trained elephants uprear,\nWhich so o'ertop the turrets of the foe,\nThose bulwarks stand a mighty space below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Brandimart to the walls a ladder brought,\nClimbed, and to climb withal to others cried:\nMany succeed, with bold assurance fraught,\nFor none can fear beneath so good a guide:\nNor was there one who marked, nor one who thought\nOf marking, if such weight it would abide.\nBrandimart only, on the foes intent,\nClambered and fought, and grasped a battlement."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here clang with hand and foot the daring knight,\nSprang on the embattled wall, and whirled his sword;\nAnd, showing mickle tokens of his might,\nThe paynims charged, o'erthrew, hewed down and gored:\nBut all at once, o'erburthened with that weight,\nThe ladder breaks beneath the assailing horde;\nAnd, saving Brandimart, the Christians all\nInto the ditch with headlong ruin fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not therefore blenched the valiant cavalier,\nNor thought he of retreat, albeit was none\nOf his own band that followed in his rear;\nAlthough he was a mark for all the town.\nOf many prayed, the warrior would not hear\nThe prayer to turn; but mid the foes leapt down;\nI say, into the city took a leap,\nWhere the town-wall was thirty cubits deep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, without any harm on the hard ground,\nAs if on feathers or on straw, did light;\nAnd, like cloth shred and shorn, the paynims round\nIn fury shreds and shears the valiant knight.\nNow springs on these, now those, with vigorous bound;\nAnd these and those betake themselves to flight.\nThey that without have seen the leap he made,\nToo late to save him deem all human aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Throughout the squadrons a deep rumour flew,\nA murmur and a whisper, there and here,\nFrom mouth to mouth, the Fame by motion grew,\nAnd told and magnified the tale of fear:\nFor upon many quarters stormed that crew,\nWhere good Orlando was, where Olivier,\nWhere Otho's son, she flew on pinions light,\nNor ever paused upon her nimble flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those warriors, and Orlando most of all,\nWho love and prize the gentle Brandimart,\nHearing, should they defy upon that call,\nThey would from so renowned a comrade part,\nTheir scaling-ladders plant, and mount the wall\nWith rivalry, which shows the kingly heart;\nWho carry all such terror in their look,\nThat, at the very sight, their foemen shook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As on loud ocean, lashed by boisterous gale\nThe billows the rash bark assault, and still —\nNow threatening poop, now threatening prow — assail,\nAnd, in their rage and fury, fain would fill;\nThe pilot sighs and groans, dismaid and pale,\n— He that should aid, and has not heart or skill —\nAt length a surge the pinnace sweeps and swallows,\nAnd wave on wave in long succession follows;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus when those win the wall, they leave a space\nSo wide, that who beneath their conduct go,\nSafely may follow them; for at its base,\nA thousand ladders have been reared below.\nMeanwhile the battering rams, in many a place,\nHave breached that wall, and with such mighty blow,\nThe bold assailant can, from many a part,\nBear succour to the gallant Brandimart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even with that rage wherewith the stream that reigns,\nThe king of rivers — when he breaks his mound,\nAnd makes himself a way through Mantuan plains —\nThe greasy furrows and glad harvests, round,\nAnd, with the sheepcotes, flock, and dogs and swains\nBears off, in his o'erwhelming waters drowned;\nOver the elm's high top the fishes glide,\nWhere fowls erewhile their nimble pinions plied;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Even with that rage rushed in the impetuous band,\nWhere many breaches in the wall were wrought,\nTo slay with burning torch and trenchant brand,\nThat people, which to evil pass were brought.\nMurder and rapine there, and violent hand\nDipt deep in blood and plunder, in a thought,\nDestroy that sumptuous and triumphant town,\nWhich of all Africk wore the royal crown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Filled with dead bodies of the paynim horde,\nBlood issued from so many a gaping wound,\nA fouler fosse was formed and worse to ford\nThan girdles the infernal city round.\nFrom house to house the fire in fury poured;\nMosque, portico, and palace, went to ground;\nAnd spoiled and empty mansions with the clang,\nOf beaten breast, and groan and outcry rang."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The victors, laden with their mighty prey,\nFrom that unhappy city's gates are gone,\nOne with fair vase, and one with rich array,\nOr silver plate from ancient altar won.\nThe mother this, that bore the child away;\nRapes and a thousand evil things were done.\nOf much, and what they cannot hinder, hear\nRenowned Orlando and fair England's peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By Olivier, amid that slaughter wide,\nFell Bucifaro of the paynim band;\nAnd — every hope and comfort cast aside —\nBranzardo slew himself with his own brand;\nPierced with three wounds whereof he shortly died,\nFolvo was taken by Astolpho's hand;\nThe monarchs three, intrusted to whose care\nAgramant's African dominions were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Agramant, who had left without a guide\nHis fleet this while, and with Sobrino fled,\nWept over his Biserta when he spied\nThose fires that on the royal city fed.\nWhen nearer now the king was certified,\nHow in that cruel strife his town had sped,\nHe thought of dying, and himself had slain,\nBut that Sobrino's words his arm restrain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What victory, my lord,\" (Sobrino cries)\n\"Could better than thy death the Christian cheer,\nWhence he might hope to joy in quiet wise\nFair Africa, from all annoyance clear?\nThy being yet alive this hope denies;\nHence shall he evermore have cause for fear.\nFor well the foeman knows, save thou art gone,\nHe for short time will fill thine Africk throne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thy subjects by thy death deprived will be\nOf hope, the only good they have in store,\nThou, if thou liv'st, I trust, shalt set us free,\nRedeem from trouble, and to joy restore.\nCaptives for ever, if thou diest, are we;\nAfrick is tributary evermore.\nAlthough not for thyself, yet not to give\nMy liege, annoyance to thy followers, live."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The soldan, he thy neighbour, will be won,\nSurely with men and money thee to aid:\nBy him with evil eye King Pepin's son,\nSo strong in Africa, will be surveyed.\nAll efforts to restore thee to thy throne\nBy Norandine, thy kinsman, will be made.\nTurk, Persian and Armenian, Arab, Mede,\nIf prayed, will all assist thee in thy need.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In such and such like words, with wary art,\nWith hope of quickly winning back his reign,\nSobrino soothed the king, while in his heart\nHe other thought perchance did entertain.\nWell knows he to what pass, what evil mart\nThat lord is brought; how often sighs in vain,\nWhoe'er foregoes the sceptre which he swayed,\nAnd to barbarians hath recourse for aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Jugurtha, martial Hannibal, and more\nIn ancient times, good proof of this afford:\nIn our own era, Lewis, hight the Moor,\nDelivered into other Lewis' ward.\nYour brother, Duke Alphonso, wiser lore\nLearned from their fate; — I speak to you, my lord —\nWont them as very madmen to decry,\nThat more on others than themselves rely;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And therefore aye, throughout that warfare drear\nWaged by the pontiff, in his fierce disdain,\nAlbeit upon his feeble powers the peer\nCould ill depend, though from Italian plain\nWas driven the friend that aided him whilere,\nAnd by the foe possessed was Naples' reign,\nHe against menace, against promise steeled,\nNe'er to another would his dukedom yield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Eastward King Agramant had turned his prow;\nAnd seaward steered his bark, of Africk wide;\nWhen from the land a wicked wind 'gan blow,\nAnd took the reeling vessel on one side:\nThe master, seated at the helm, his brow\nRaised towards heaven, and to the monarch cried:\n\"I see so fell and fierce a tempest form,\nOur pinnace cannot face the pelting storm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If you, my lords, will listen to my lore,\nAn isle is on our left-hand; and to me\nIt seems that it were well to make that shore\nTill overblown the tempest's fury be.\"\nTo his advice assents the royal Moor,\nAnd makes the larboard land, from peril free;\nWhich, for the sailor's weal, when tempests rise,\n'Twixt Vulcan's lofty forge and Africk lies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With juniper and myrtle overgrown,\nOf habitations is that islet bare;\nA pleasing solitude; and where alone\nHarbour wild stag and roebuck, deer and hare;\nAnd, save to fishermen, is little known,\nThat oftentimes on the shorn brambles there\nHang their moist nets; meanwhile, untroubled sleep\nThe scaly fishes in their quiet deep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here other vessel, sheltered from the main,\nThey found, by tempest tost upon that land,\nWhich had conveyed the king of Sericane\nErewhile from Arles; on one and the other hand,\nIn reverent wise and worthy of the twain,\nThose valiant kings embraced upon the strand:\nFor friends the monarchs were, and late before\nThe walls of Paris, arms together bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With much displeasure Sericana's knight\nHeard by King Agramant his griefs displaid;\nThen him consoled, and in his cause to fight,\nLike courteous king, the kindly offer made:\nBut brooked nat, that to Egypt's people, light\nAnd lacking faith, he should resort for aid.\n\"That thither it is perilous to wend,\nExiles (he said are warned by Pompey's end. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And for Senapus' Aethiopian crew\nHave come beneath Astolpho, as ye show,\nTo wrest your fruitful Africa from you,\nAnd burnt and laid her chiefest city low.\nAnd with their squadrons is Orlando, who\nWas wandering void of wit, short while ago,\nThe fittest cure for all, whereby to scape\nOut of this trouble I, meseems, can shape."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I, for your love, will undertake the quest,\nThe Count in single combat to appear;\nHe vainly would, I wot, with me contest,\nIf wholly made of copper or of steel.\nI rate the Christian church, were he at rest,\nAs wolf rates lambs, when hungering for his meal.\nNext have I thought how of the Nubian band\n— A brief and easy task — to free your land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I will make other Nubians, they that hold\nAnother faith, divided by Nile's course,\nAnd Arabs and Macrobians (rich in gold\nAnd men are these, and those in herds of horse),\nChaldaean, Perse, and many more, controlled\nBy my good sceptre, in such mighty force,\nWill make them war upon the Nubians' reign,\nThose reavers shall not in your land remain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gradasso's second offer seemed to be\nMost opportune to King Troyano's son;\nAnd much he blest the chances of the sea,\nWhich him upon that desert isle had thrown:\nYet would not upon any pact agree,\n— Nay, not to repossess Biserta's town —\nGradasso should for him in fight contend;\nDeeming too sore his honour 'twoud offend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If Roland is to be defied, more due\nThe battle is to me (that king replies)\nI am prepared for it; and let God do\nHis will by me, in good or evil wise.\"\n\" — Follow my mode; another mode and new,\nWhich comes into my mind\" (Gradasso cries),\n\"Let both of us together wage this fight\nAgainst Orlando and another knight.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So not left out, I care not, if I be\nThe first or last (said Agramant): I know\nIn arms no better can I find than thee,\nThough I should seek a comrade, high or low,\nAnd what (Sobrino cried becomes of me? ) \n\nI should be more expert if old in show;\nAnd evermore in peril it is good,\nForce should have Counsel in his neighbourhood.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stricken in years, yet vigorous was the sage,\nAnd well had proved himself with sword and spear;\nAnd said, he found himself in gray old age,\nSuch as in green and supple youth whilere.\nThey own his claim, and for an embassage\nForthwith a courier find, then bid him steer\nFor Africa, where camped the Christians lie,\nAnd Count Orlando on their part defy;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With equal number of armed knights to be,\nMatching his foes, on Lampedosa's shore;\nWhere on all quarters that circumfluent sea,\nBy which they are inisled, is heard to roar.\nThe paynim messenger unceasingly,\nLike one in needful haste, used sail and oar,\nTill he found Roland in Biserta, where\nThe host beneath his eye their plunder share."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From those three monarchs to the cavalier\nThe invitation was in public told;\nSo pleasing to Anglante's valiant peer,\nTo the herald he was liberal of his gold:\nFrom his companions had he heard whilere\nThat Durindane was in Gradasso's hold:\nHence, to retrieve that faulchion from the foe,\nTo India had the Count resolved to go:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Deeming he should not find that king elsewhere,\nWho, so he heard, had sailed from the French shore.\nA nearer place is offered now; and there\nHe hopes Gradasso shall his prize restore;\nMoved also by Almontes' bugle rare,\nTo accept the challenge which the herald bore;\nNor less by Brigliadoro; since he knew\nIn Agramant's possession were the two."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He chose for his companions in the fight\nThe faithful Brandimart and Olivier:\nWell has he proved the one and the other's might;\nKnows he alike to both is passing dear.\nGood horses and good armour seeks the knight\nAnd goodly swords and lances, far and near,\nFor him and his; meseems to you is known\nHow none of those three warriors had his own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando (as I oft have certified)\nIn fury, his had scattered wide and far;\nRodomont took the others', which beside\nThe river, locked in that high turret are.\nFew throughout Africa could they provide;\nAs well because to France, in that long war,\nKing Agramant had born away the best,\nAs because Africa but few possest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What could be had of armour, rusted o'er\nAnd brown with age, Orlando bids unite;\nMeanwhile with his companions on the shore,\nHe walks, discoursing on the future fight.\nSo wandering from their camp three miles and more,\nIt chanced that, turning towards the sea their sight,\nUnder full sail approaching, they descried\nA helmless barque, with nought her course to guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, without pilot, without crew, alone,\nAs wind and fortune ordered it, was bound:\nThe vessel neared the shore, with sails full-blown,\nFurrowing the waves, until she took the ground.\nBut ere of these three warriors more be shown,\nThe love wherewith I to the Child am bound,\nTo his story brings me back, and bids record\nWhat past 'twixt him and Clermont's warlike lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I spake of that good pair of warriors, who\nHad both retreated from the martial fray,\nBeholding pact and treaty broken through,\nAnd every troop and band in disarray.\nWhich leader to his oath was first untrue,\nAnd was occasion of such evil, they\nStudy to learn of all the passing train;\nKing Agramant or the Emperor Charlemagne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile a servant of the Child's, at hand,\n— Faithful, expert and wary was the wight,\nNor in the shock of either furious band,\nHad ever of his warlike lord lost sight —\nTo bold Rogero bore his horse and brand,\nThat he might aid his comrades now in flight.\nRogero backed the steed and grasped the sword;\nBut not in battle mixed that martial lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thence he departed; but he first renewed\nHis compact with Montalban's knight — that so\nHis Agramant convinced of perjury stood —\nHim and his evil sect he would forego.\nThat day no further feats of hardihood\nRogero will perform against the foe:\nHe but demands of all that make for Arles,\nWho first broke faith, King Agramant or Charles?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From all he hears repeated, far and near,\nThat Agramant had broke the promise plight:\nHe loves that king, and from his side to veer,\nFor this, believes would be no error light.\nThe Moors were broke and scattered (this whilere\nHas been rehearsed and from the giddy height ) \n\nOf HER revolving wheel were downward hurled,\nWho at her pleasure rolls this nether world."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero ponders if he should remain,\nOr rather should his sovereign lord attend:\nLove for his lady fits him with a rein\nAnd bit, which lets him not to Africk wend;\nWheels him, and to a counter course again\nSpurs him, and threats his restive mood to shend,\nSave he maintains the treaty, and the troth\nPledged to the paladin with solemn oath."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A wakeful, stinging care, on the other side\nScourges and goads no less the cavalier;\nLest, if he now from Agramant divide,\nHe should be taxed with baseness or with fear.\nIf many deem it well he should abide,\nTo many and many it would ill appear:\nMany would say, that oaths unbinding are,\nWhich 'tis unlawful and unjust to swear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He all that day and the ensuing night\nRemains alone, and so the following day;\nForever sifting in his doubtful sprite,\nIf it be better to depart or stay:\nLastly for Agramant decides the knight;\nTo him in Africk will he wend his way:\nMoved by his love for his liege-lady sore,\nBut moved by honour and by duty more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He made for Arles, where yet he hoped would ride\nThe fleet which him to Africa might bear;\nNor in the port nor offing ships espied,\nNor Saracens save dead beheld he there.\nFor Agramant had swept the roadstead wide,\nAnd burnt what vessels in the haven were.\nRogero takes the road, when his hope fails,\nAlong the sea-beat shore toward Marseilles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon some boat he hoped to lay his hand,\nWhich him for love or force should thence convey.\nAlready Ogier's son had made the land,\nWith the barbarians' fleet, his captive prey.\nYou could not there have cast a grain of sand\nBetween those vessels; moored closely lay\nThe mighty squadrons to that harbour brought,\nWith conquerors these, and those with prisoners fraught."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The vessels of the Moor that were not made\nThe food of fire and water on that night\n(Saving some few that fled were all conveyed ) \n\nSafe to Marseilles by the victorious knight\nSeven of those kings, that Moorish sceptres swayed,\nWho, having seen their squadron put to flight,\nWith their seven ships had yielded to the foe,\nStood mute and weeping, overwhelmed with woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dudon had issued forth upon dry land,\nBent to find Charlemagne that very day;\nAnd of the Moorish spoil and captive band\nMade in triumphal pomp a long display.\nThe prisoners all were ranged upon the strand,\nAnd round them stood their Nubian victors gay;\nWho, shouting in his praise, with loud acclaim,\nMade all that region ring with Dudon's name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, when from far the ships he spied,\nBelieved they were the fleet of Agramant,\nAnd, to know further, pricked his courser's side;\nThen, nearer, mid those knights of mickle vaunt,\nNasamon's king a prisoner he desired,\nAgricalt, Bambirago, Farurant,\nBalastro, Manilardo, and Rimedont;\nWho stood with weeping eyes and drooping front."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In their unhappy state to leave that crew\nThe Child, who loved those monarchs, cannot bear;\nThat useless is the empty hand he knew;\nThat where force is not, little profits prayer.\nHe couched his lance, their keeper overthrew,\nThen proved his wonted might with faulchion bare;\nAnd in a moment stretched upon the strand\nAbove a hundred of the Nubian band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The noise Sir Dudon hears, the slaughter spies,\nBut knows not who the stranger cavalier:\nHe marks how, put to rout, his people flies;\nWith anguish, with lament and mighty fear;\nQuickly for courser, shield, and helmet cries,\n(Bosom, and arms, and thighs, were mailed whilere)\nLeaps on his horse, nor — having seized his lance —\nForgets he is a paladin of France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He called on every one to stand aside,\nAnd with the galling spur his courser prest;\nMeanwhile a hundred other foes have died,\nAnd filled with hope was every prisoner's breast;\nAnd as Rogero holy Dudon spied\nApproach on horseback, (footmen were the rest,)\nEsteeming him their head, he charged the knight,\nImpelled by huge desire to prove his might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Already, on his part, had moved the Dane;\nBut when he saw the Child without a spear,\nHe flang is own far from him, in disdain\nTo take such vantage of the cavalier.\nAdmiring at Sir Dudon's courteous vein,\n\"Belie himself he cannot,\" said the peer,\n\"And of those perfect warriors must be one\nThat as the paladins of France are known."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If I my will can compass, he shall shew\nHis name, to me, ere further deed be done.\"\nHe made demand; and in the stranger knew\nDudon, the Danish Ogier's valiant son:\nHe from Rogero claimed an equal due,\nAnd from the Child as courteous answer won.\n— Their names on either side announced — the foes\nA bold defiance speak, and come to blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bold Dudon had with him that iron mace,\nWhich won him deathless fame in many a fight:\nWherewith he proved him fully of the race\nOf that good Danish warrior, famed for might.\nThat best of faulchions, which through iron case\nOf cuirass or of casque was wont to bite,\nYouthful Rogero from the scabbard snatched,\nAnd with the martial Dane his valour matched."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But for the gentle youth was ever willed\nTo offend his lady-love the least he could,\nAnd knew he should offend her, if he spilled,\nIn that disastrous battle, Dudon's blood\n(Well in the lineage of French houses skilled\nHe wist of Beatrice's sisterhood,\n— Bradamant's mother she — with Armelline,\nThe mother of the Danish paladine)."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He therefore never thrust in that affray,\nAnd rarely smote an edge on plate and chain.\nNow warding off the mace, now giving way,\nBefore the fall of that descending bane.\nTurpin believes it in Rogero lay\nSir Dudon in few sword-strokes to have slain.\nYet never when the Dane his guard foregoes,\nSave on the faulchion's flat descend the blows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The flat as featly as the edge he plies,\nOf that good faulchion forged of stubborn grain;\nAnd, at strange blindman's bluff, in weary wise,\nHammers on Dudon with such might and main,\nHe often dazzles so the warrior's eyes,\nThat hardly he his saddle can maintain.\nBut to win better audience for my rhyme,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>Canto I defer to other time.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 41"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His prisoners to the Child the Danish peer\nConsigns, who, homeward bound, are wrecked at sea;\nBy swimming he escapes, and a sincere\nAnd faithful servant now of Christ is he.\nMeanwhile bold Brandimart, and Olivier,\nAnd Roland fiercely charge the hostile three.\nSobrino is left wounded in the strife;\nGradasso and Agramant deprived of life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The odour which well-fashioned bear or hair,\nOf that which find and dainty raiment steeps\nOf gentle stripling, or of damsel fair,\n— Who often love awakens, as she weeps —\nIf it ooze forth and scent the ambient air,\nAnd which for many a day its virtue keeps,\nWell shows, by manifest effects and sure,\nHow perfect was its first perfume and pure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The drink that to his cost good Icarus drew\nOf yore his sun-burned sicklemen to cheer,\nAnd which ('tis said lured Celts and Boi through ) \n\nOur Alpine hills, untouched by toil whilere,\nWell shows that cordial was the draught, when new;\nSince it preserves its virtue through the year.\nThe tree to which its wintry foliage cleaves,\nWell shows that verdant were its spring tide leaves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The famous lineage, for so many years\nOf courtesy the great and lasting light,\nWhich ever, brightening as it burns, appears\nTo shine and flame more clearly to the sight,\nWell proves the sire of Este's noble peers\nMust, amid mortals, have shone forth as bright\nIn all fair gifts which raise men to the sky,\nAs the glad sun mid glittering orbs on high."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in his every other feat exprest,\nRogero's valiant mind and courteous lore\nWere showed by tokens clear and manifest,\nAnd his high mindedness shone more and more;\n— So toward the Dane those virtues stood confest,\nWith whom (as I rehearsed to you before)\nHe had belied his mighty strength and breath;\nFor pity loth to put that lord to death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Danish warrior was well certified,\nNo wish to slay him had the youthful knight,\nWho spared him now, when open was his side;\nNow, when so wearied he no more could smite.\nWhen finally he knew, and plain descried\nRogero scrupled to put forth his might,\nIf with less vigour and less prowess steeled,\nAt least in courtesy he would not yield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Pardi, sir, make we peace;\" (he said \"success ) \n\nIn this contention cannot fall to me —\nCannot be mine; for I myself confess\nConquered and captive to thy courtesy.\"\nTo him Rogero answered, \"And no less\nI covet peace, than 'tis desired by thee.\nBut this upon condition, that those seven\nAre freed from bondage, and to me are given.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With that he showed those seven whereof I spake,\nBound and with drooping heads, a sad array;\nAdding, he must to him no hindrance make,\nWho would those kings to Africa convey.\nAnd Dudon thus allowed the Child to take\nThose seven, and him allowed to bear away\nA bark as well; what likes him best he chooses,\nAmid those vessels, and for Africk looses."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He looses bark and sail; and in bold wise\nTrusting the fickle wind, to seaward stood.\nAt first on her due course the vessel flies,\nAnd fills the pilot full of hardihood.\nThe beach retreats, and from the sailors' eyes\nSo fades, the sea appears a shoreless flood.\nUpon the darkening of the day, the wind\nDisplays its fickle and perfidious kind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It shifts from poop to beam, from beam to prow,\nAnd even there short season doth remain:\nThe reeling ship confounds the pilot; now\nStruck fore, now aft, now on her beam again.\nThreatening the billows rise, with haughty brow,\nAnd Neptune's white herd lows above the main.\nAs many deaths appear to daunt that rout,\nAs waves which beat their troubled bark about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now blows the wind in front, and now in rear,\nAnd drives this wave an-end, that other back;\nOthers the reeling vessel's side o'erpeer;\nAnd every billow threatens equal wrack.\nThe pilot sighs, confused and pale with fear;\nVainly he calls aloud to shift the tack,\nTo strike or jibe the yard; and with his hand,\nSigns to the crew the thing he would command."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But sound or signal little boots; the eye\nSees not amid the dim and rainy night;\nThe voice unheard ascends into the sky, —\nThe sky, which with a louder larum smite\nThe troubled sailors' universal cry,\nAnd roar of waters, which together fight.\nUnheard is every hest, above, below,\nStarboard or larboard, upon poop or prow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the strained tackle sounds a hollow roar,\nWherein the struggling wind its fury breaks;\nThe forked lightning flashes evermore,\nWith fearful thunder heaven's wide concave shakes.\nOne to the rudder runs, one grasps an oar;\nEach to his several office him betakes.\nOne will make fast, another will let go;\nWater into the water others throw."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lo! howling horribly, the sounding blast,\nWhich Boreas in his sudden fury blows,\nScourges with tattered sail the reeling mast:\nAlmost as high as heaven the water flows:\nThe oars are broken; and so fell and fast\nThat tempest pelts, the prow to leeward goes;\nAnd the ungoverned vessel's battered side\nIs undefended from the foaming tide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fallen on her starboard side, on her beam ends,\nAbout to turn keel uppermost, she lies.\nMeanwhile, his soul to Heaven each recommends,\nSurer than sure to sink, with piteous cries.\nScathe upon scathe malicious Fortune sends,\nAnd when one woe is weathered, others rise.\nO'erstrained, the vessel splits; and through her seams\nIn many a part the hostile water streams."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A fierce assault and cruel coil doth keep\nUpon all sides that wintry tempest fell.\nNow to their sight so high the billows leap,\nIt seems that these to heaven above would swell;\nNow, plunging with the wave, they sink so deep,\nThat they appear to spy the gulfs of hell.\nSmall hope there is or none: with faultering breath\nThey gaze upon inevitable death."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On a despiteous sea, that livelong night,\nThey drifted, as the wind in fury blew.\nThe furious wind that with the dawning light\nShould have abated, gathered force anew.\nLo!  a bare rock, ahead, appears in sight,\nWhich vainly would the wretched band eschew;\nWhom towards that cliff, in their despite, impel\nThe raging tempest and the roaring swell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Three times and four the pale-faced pilot wrought\nThe tiller with a vigorous push to sway;\nAnd for the bark a surer passage sought:\nBut the waves snapt and bore the helm away.\nTo lower, or ease the bellying canvas aught\nThe sailors had no power; nor time had they\nTo mend that ill, or counsel what was best;\nFor them too hard the mortal peril prest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Perceiving now that nothing can defend\nTheir bark from wreck on that rude rock and bare,\nAll to their private aims alone attend,\nAnd only to preserve their life have care.\nWho quickest can, into the skiff descend;\nBut in a thought so overcrowded are,\nThrough those so many who invade the boat,\nThat, gunwale-deep, she scarce remains afloat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, on beholding master, mate,\nAnd men abandoning the ship with speed,\nIn doublet, as he is, sans mail and plate,\nHopes in the skiff, a refuge in that need:\nBut finds her overcharged with such a weight,\nAnd afterwards so many more succeed,\nThat the o'erwhelming wave the pinnace drown,\nAnd she with all her wretched freight goes down;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Goes down, and, foundering, drags with her whoe'er\nLeaving the larger bark, on her relies.\nThen doleful shrieks are heard, 'mid sob and tear,\nCalling for succour on unpitying skies:\nBut for short space that shrilling cry they rear;\nFor, swoln with rage and scorn, the waters rise,\nAnd in a moment wholly stop the vent\nWhence issues that sad clamour and lament."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One sinks outright, no more to reappear;\nSome rise, and bounding with the billows go:\nTheir course, with head uplifted, others steer;\nAn arm, an unshod leg, those others show:\nRogero, who the tempest will not fear,\nSprings upward to the surface from below;\nAnd little distant sees that rock, in vain\nEschewed by him and his attendant train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Himself with hands and feet the warrior rows,\nHoping by force thereof to win the shore;\nBreast boldly the importunate flood, and blows\nWith his unwearied breath the foam before.\nWaxing meanwhile, the troubled water rose,\nAnd from the rock the abandoned vessel bore;\nQuitted of those unhappy men, who die\n(So curst their lot the death from which they fly. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Alas!  for man's deceitful thoughts and blind!\nThe ship escaped from wreck, where hope was none;\nWhen master and when men their charge resigned,\nAnd let the vessel without guidance run.\nIt would appear the wind has changed its mind,\nOn seeing all that sailed in her are gone;\nAnd blows the vessel from those shallows free,\nThrough better course, into a safer sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, having drifted wildly with her guide,\nWithout him, made directly Africk's strand,\nTwo or three miles of waste Biserta wide,\nUpon the quarter facing Egypt's land;\nAnd, as the sea went down and the wind died,\nStood bedded in that weary waste of sand.\nNow thither Roland roved, who paced the shore;\nAs I in other strain rehearsed before;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And willing to discover if alone,\nLaden, or light, the stranded vessel were,\nHe, Olivier, and Monodantes' son,\nAboard her in a shallow bark repair:\nBeneath the hatchways they descend, but none\nOf human kind they see; and only there\nFind good Frontino, with the trenchant sword\nAnd gallant armour of his youthful lord;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who was so hurried in his hasty flight\nHe had not even time to take his sword;\nTo Orlando known; which, Balisardo hight,\nWas his erewhile; the tale's upon record,\nAnd ye have read it all, as well I wite;\nHow Falerina lost it to that lord,\nWhen waste as well her beauteous bowers he laid;\nAnd how from him Brunello stole the blade;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And how beneath Carena, on the plain\nBrunello on Rogero this bestowed.\nHow matchless was that faulchion's edge and grain,\nTo him experience had already showed;\nI say, Orlando; who was therefore fain,\nAnd to heaven's king with grateful thanks o'erflowed;\nAnd deemed, and often afterwards so said,\nHeaven for such pressing need had sent the blade:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such pressing need, in that he had to fight\nWith the redoubted king of Sericane;\nAnd knew that he, besides his fearful might,\nWas lord of Bayard and of Durindane.\nNot knowing them, Anglantes' valiant knight\nSo highly rated not the plate and chain\nAs he that these had proved: they valour were,\nBut valued less as good than rich and fair;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, for of harness he had little need,\nCharmed, and against all weapons fortified,\nTo Olivier he left the warlike weed:\nNot so the sword; which to his waist he tied:\nTo Brandimart Orlando gave the steed:\nThus equally that spoil would he divide\nWith his companions twain, in equal share,\nWho partners in that rich discovery were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Against the day of fight, in goodly gear\nAnd new, those warriors seek their limbs to deck.\nBlazoned upon Orlando's shield appear\nThe burning bold and lofty Babel's wreck.\nA lyme-dog argent bears Sir Olivier,\nCouchant, and with the leash upon his neck:\nThe motto; TILL HE COMES: In gilded vest\nAnd worthy of himself he will be drest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bold Brandimart designed upon the day\nOf battle, for his royal father's sake,\nAnd his own honour, no device more gay\nThan a dim surcoat to the field to take.\nBy gentle Flordelice for that dark array,\nWas wrought the fairest facing she could make.\nWith costly jewels was the border sown;\nSable the vest, and of one piece alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With her own hand the lady wrought that vest,\nBecoming well the finest plate and chain,\nWherein the valiant warrior should be drest,\nAnd cloak his courser's croup and chest and mane:\nBut, from that day when she herself addrest\nUnto this task, till ended was her pain,\nShe showed no sign of gladness; nor this while,\nNor after, was she ever seen to smile."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The heartfelt fear, the torment evermore\nOf losing Brandimart the dame pursued.\nShe him whilere a hundred times and more\nEngaged in fierce and fearful fight had viewed;\nNor ever suchlike terror heretofore\nHad blanched her cheek and froze her youthful blood;\nAnd this new sense of fear increased her trouble,\nAnd made the trembling lady's heart beat double."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The warriors to the wind their canvas rear,\nWhen point device the three accoutred are.\nBold Sansonet is left, with England's peer,\nIntrusted with the faithful army's care.\nFlordelice, pricked at heart with cruel fear,\nFilling the heavens with vow, lament and prayer,\nAs far as they by sight can followed be,\nFollows their sails upon the foaming sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scarce, with much labour, the two captains led\nHer, gazing on the waters, from the shore,\nAnd to the palace drew, where on her bed\nThey left the lady, grieved and trembling sore.\nMeanwhile upon their quest those others sped,\nWhom mercy wind and weather seaward bore.\nTheir vessel made that island on the right;\nThe field appointed for so fell a fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando disembarks, with his array,\nHis kinsman Olivier and Brandimart;\nWho on the side which fronts the eastern ray,\nEncamp them, and not haply without art.\nKing Agramant arrives that very day,\nAnd tents him on the contrary part.\nBut for the sun is sinking fast, forborne\nIs their encounter till the following morn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Until the skies the dawning light receive,\nArmed servants keep their watch both there and here.\nThe valiant Brandimart resorts that eve\nThitherward, where their tents the paynims rear;\nAnd parleys, by this noble leader's leave,\nWith Agramant; for they were friends whilere;\nAnd, underneath the banner of the Moor,\nHe into France had passed from Africk's shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After salutes, and joining hand with hand,\nFair reasons, as a friend, the faithful knight\nPressed on the leader of the paynim band\nWhy he should not the appointed battle fight;\nAnd every town — restored to his command —\nLaying  'twixt Nile and Calpe's rocky height,\nVowed he, with Roland's license, should receive,\nIf upon Mary's Son he would believe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He said: \"For loved you were, and are by me,\nThis counsel give I; that I deem it sane,\nSince I pursue it, you assured must be:\nMahound I hold but as an idol vain;\nIn Jesus Christ, the living God I see,\nAnd to conduct you in my way were fain;\nI' the way of safety fain would have you move\nWith me and all those others that I love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In this consists your welfare; counsel none\nSave this, in your disaster, can avail;\nAnd, of all counsels least, good Milo's son\nTo meet in combat, clad in plate and mail;\nIn that the profit, if the field be won,\nWeighs not against the loss, in equal scale.\nIf you be conqueror, little gain ensues,\nYet little loss results not, if you lose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Were good Orlando and we others slain,\nBanded with him to conquer or to die;\nWherefore, through this, ye should your lost domain\nAcquire anew, forsooth, I see not, I;\nNor is there reason hope to entertain\nThat, if we lifeless on the champaigne lie,\nMen should be wanting in King Charles's host\nTo guard in Africa his paltriest post.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thus Brandimart to Afick's cavalier;\nAnd much would have subjoined; but, on his side,\nThat knight, with angry voice and haughty cheer,\nThe pagan interrupted, and replied:\n\" `Tis sure temerity and madness sheer\nMoves you and whatsoever wight beside,\nThat counsels matter, be it good or ill,\nUncalled a counsellor's duty to fulfil;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And how to think, from love those counsels flow\nWhich once you bore and bear me, as you say,\n(To speak the very truth I do not know, ) \n\nWho with Orlando see you here, this day.\nI ween that, knowing you are doomed to woe,\nAnd marked for the devouring dragon's prey,\nYe all mankind would drag to nether hell,\nIn your eternity of pains to dwell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If I shall win or lose, remount my throne,\nOr pass my future days in exile drear,\nGod only knows, whose purpose is unknown\nTo me, in turn, or to Anglantes' peer.\nBefall what may, by me shall nought be done\nUnworthy of a king, through shameful fear.\nIf death must be my certain portion, I,\nRather than wrong my princely blood, will die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ye may depart, who, save ye better play\nThe warrior, in to-morrow's listed fight,\nThen ye have plaid the embassador to-day,\nIn arms will second ill Anglantes' knight.\"\nAgramant ended so his furious say;\n— His angry bosom boiling with despite.\nSo said — the warriors parted, to repose,\nTill from the neighbouring sea the day arose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the first whitening of the dawn was seen,\nArmed, in a moment leapt on horseback all;\nShort parley past the puissant foes between.\nThere was no stop; there was no interval;\nFor they have laid in rest their lances keen:\nBut I into too foul a fault should fall\nMeseems, my lord, if, while their deeds I tell\nI let Rogero perish in the swell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Cleaving the flood with nimble hands and feet\nHe swims, amid the horrid surges' roar,\nOn him the threatening wind and tempest beat,\nBut him his harassed conscience vexes more.\nChrist's wrath he fears; and, since in waters sweet\n(When time and fair occasion served of yore)\nHe, in his folly, baptism little prized,\nFears in these bitter waves to be baptized."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those many promises remembered are\nWhereby he to his lady-love was tied,\nThose oaths which sworn to good Rinaldo were,\nAnd were in nought fulfilled upon his side.\nTo God, in hope that he would hear and spare,\nThat he repented, oftentimes he cried,\nAnd, should he land, and scape that mortal scaith,\nTo be a Christian, vowed in heart and faith;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And ne'er, in succour of the Moorish train,\nWith sword or lance, the faithful to offend;\nAnd into France, where he to Charlemagne\nWould render honour due, forthwith to wend;\nNor Bradamant with idle words again\nTo cheat, but bring his love to honest end.\nA miracle it is that, as he vows,\nHe swims more lightly and his vigour grows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His vigour grows; unwearied is his mind;\nAnd still his arms from him the billow throw,\nThis billow followed fast by that behind;\nWhereof one lifts him high, one sinks him low.\nRising and falling, vext by wave and wind,\nSo gains the Child that shore with labour slow;\nAnd where the rocky hill slopes seaward most,\nAll drenched and dropping, climbs the rugged coast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All the others that had plunged into the flood\nIn the end, o'erwhelmed by those wild waters died.\nRogero, as to Providence seemed good,\nMounted the solitary islet's side.\nWhen safe upon the barren rock he stood,\nA new alarm the stripling terrified;\nTo be within those narrow bounds confined,\nAnd die, with hardship and with hunger pined."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet he with an unconquered heart, intent\nTo suffer what the heavens for him ordained,\nO'er those hard stones, against that steep ascent,\nTowards the top with feet intrepid strained;\nAnd not a hundred yards had gone, when, bent\nWith years, and with long fast and vigil stained,\nHe worthy of much worship one espied,\nIn hermit's weed, descend the mountain's side;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who cries, on his approaching him, \"Saul, Saul,\nWhy persecutest thou my faithful seed?\"\nAs whilom said the Saviour to Saint Paul,\nWhen (blessed stroke! he smote him from his steed. ) \n\n\"Thou thought'st to pass the sea, nor pay withal;\nThought'st to defraud the pilot of his meed.\nThou seest that God has arms to reach and smite,\nWhen farthest off thou deem'st that God of might.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And he, that holiest anchoret, pursued,\nTo whom the night foregoing God did send\nA vision, as he slumbered, and foreshewed\nHow, thither by his aid the Child should wend;\nWherein his past and future life, reviewed,\nWere seen, as well as his unhappy end;\nAnd sons, and grandsons, and his every heir,\nFully revealed to that good hermit were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That anchoret pursues, and does upbraid\nRogero first, and comforts finally:\nUpbraideth him, because he had delaid\nBeneath that easy yoke to bend the knee;\nAnd what he should have done, when whilom prayed\nAnd called of Christ — then uncompelled and free —\nHad done with little grace; nor turned to God\nUntil he saw him threatening with the rod."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then comforts him — that Christ aye heaven allows\nTo them, that late or early heaven desire;\nAnd all those labourers of the Gospel shows,\nPaid by the vineyard's lord with equal hire.\nWith charity and warm devotion glows,\nAnd him instructs the venerable sire,\nAs toward the rocky cell where he resides\nHe with weak steps and slow Rogero guides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above that hallowed cell, on the hill's brow,\nA little church receives the rising day;\nCommodious is the fane and fair enow;\nThence to the beach descends a thicket gray,\nWhere fertile and fruit-bearing palm-trees blow,\nMyrtle, and lowly juniper, and bay,\nEvermore threaded by a limpid fountain,\nWhich falls with ceaseless murmur from the mountain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twas well nigh forty years, since on that stone\nThe goodly friar had fixed his quiet seat;\nWhich, there to live a holy life, alone,\nFor him the Saviour chose, as harbourage meet.\nPure water was his drink, and, plucked from one,\nOr the other plant, wild berries were his meat;\nAnd hearty and robust, of ailments clear,\nThe holy man had reached his eightieth year."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That hermit lit a fire, and heaped the board\nWith different fruits, within his small repair;\nWherewith the Child somedeal his strength restored,\nWhen he had dried his clothes and dripping hair.\nAfter, at better ease, to him God's word\nAnd mysteries of our faith expounded were;\nAnd the day following, in his fountain clear,\nThat anchoret baptized the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There dwells the young Rogero, well content\nWith what the rugged sojourn does allow;\nIn that the friar showed shortly his intent\nTo send him where he fain would turn his prow.\nMeanwhile with him he many an argument\nHandles and often; of God's kingdom now;\nNow of things appertaining to his case;\nNow to Rogero's blood, a future race."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Lord, that every thing doth see and hear,\nHad to that holiest anchoret bewrayed,\nHow he should not exceed the seventh year,\nDating from when he was a Christian made;\nWho for the death of Pinabel whilere,\n(His lady's deed, but on Rogero laid)\nAs well as Bertolagi's, should be slain\nBy false Maganza's ill and impious train;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, how that treason should be smothered so,\nNo sign thereof should outwardly appear;\nFor where that evil people dealt the blow,\nThey should entomb the youthful cavalier.\nFor this should vengeance follow, albeit slow,\nDealt by his consort and his sister dear;\nAnd how he by his wife should long be sought,\nWith weary womb, with heavy burden fraught,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Twixt Brenta and Athesis, beneath those hills\n(Which erst the good Antenor so contented,\nWith their sulphureous veins and liquid rills,\nAnd mead, and field, with furrows glad indented,\nThat he for these left pools which Xanthus fills;\nAnd Ida, and Ascanius long lamented,)\nTill she a child should in the forests bear,\nWhich little distant from Ateste are;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And how the Child, in might and beauty grown,\nThat, like his sire, Rogero shall be hight,\nThose Trojans, as of Trojan lineage known,\nShall for their lord elect with solemn rite;\nWho next by Charles (in succour of whose crown\nAgainst the Lombards shall the stripling fight)\nOf that fair land dominion shall obtain,\nAnd the honoured title of a marquis gain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And because Charles shall say in Latin `Este',\n(That is — be lords of the dominion round!)\nEntitled in a future season Este\nShall with good omen be that beauteous ground;\nAnd thus its ancient title of Ateste\nShall of its two first letters lose the sound.\nGod also to his servant had foresaid\nThe vengeance taken for Rogero's dead;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who shall, in vision, to his consort true\nAppear somedeal before the dawn of day;\nAnd shall relate how him the traitor slew,\nAnd where his body lies to her shall say.\nShe and Marphisa hence, those valiant two,\nWith fire and sword on earth shall Poictiers lay;\nNor shall his son, when of befitting age,\nLess harm Maganza in his mighty rage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On Azos, Alberts, Obysons, did dwell\nThat hermit hoar, and on their offspring bright;\nOr Borso, Nicholas, and Leonel,\nAlphonso, Hercules, and Hippolyte,\nAnd. last of those, the gentle Isabel;\nThen curbs his tongue and will no more recite.\nHe to Rogero what is fit reveals,\nAnd what is fitting to conceal, conceals."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile Orlando and bold Brandimart,\nWith that good knight, the Marquis Olivier,\nAgainst the paynim Mars together start;\n(Name well befitting Sericana's peer)\nAnd the other two — that from the adverse part,\nAt more than a foot-pace their coursers steer;\nI say King Agramant and King Sobrine:\nThe pebbly beach resounds, and rolling brine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When they encounter in mid field, pell-mell,\nAnd to the sky flew every shivered lance,\nAt that loud noise, the sea was seen to swell,\nAt that loud noise, which echoed even to France.\nGradasso and Roland met as it befel;\nAnd fairly balanced might appear the chance,\nBut for the vantage of Rinaldo's horse;\nWhich made Gradasso seem of greater force."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Baiardo shocked the steed of lesser might,\nBacked by Orlando, with such might and main,\nHe made that courser stagger, left and right,\nAnd measure next his length upon the plain:\nVainly to raise him strove Anglantes' knight,\nThrice, nay four times, with rowels and with rein;\nBalked of his end, he lights upon the field,\nDraws Balisarda, and uplifts his shield."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With Agramant encounters Olivier,\nWho, fitly matched, their foaming coursers gall.\nBold Brandimart unhorsed in the career\nSobrino; but it was not plain withal\nIf 'twas the fault of horse or cavalier;\nFor seldom good Sobrino used to fall.\nWas it his courser's or his own misdeed,\nSobrino found himself without a steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now Brandimart, that upon earth descried\nThe king Sobrine, assailed no more his man;\nBut at Gradasso, who Anglantes' pride\nHad equally unhorsed, in fury ran.\nOn Agramant and Oliviero's side,\nMeanwhile the warfare stood as it began:\nWhen broken on their bucklers were the spears,\nWith swords encountered the returning peers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Roland who saw Gradasso in such guise,\nAs showed that to return he little cared,\n— Nor can return; so Brandimart aye plies,\nAnd presses Sericana's monarch hard,\nTurns round, and, like himself, afoot descries\nSobrino, in the doubtful strife unpaired:\nAt him he sprang; and, at his haughty look,\nHeaven, as the warrior trod, in terror shook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Foreseeing the assault with wary eye,\nPrepared, and at close ward, behold the Moor!\nAs pilot against whom, now cresting nigh,\nThe threatening billow comes with hollow roar,\nTowards it turns his prow, and, when so high\nHe views the sea, would gladly be ashore.\nSobrino rears his buckler, to withstand\nThe furious fall of Falerina's brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of such fine steel was Balisarda's blade,\nThat arms against it little shelter were;\nAnd by a person of such puissance swayed,\nBy Roland, singe in the world or rare,\nIt splits the shield, and is in nowise stayed,\nThough bound about with steel the edges are:\nIt splits the shield, and to the bottom rends,\nAnd on the shoulder underneath descends."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the shoulder; nor, though twisted chain\nAnd double plates encase the paynim foe,\nThese hinder much that sword of stubborn grain\nFrom opening wide the parted flesh below.\nSobrino at Orlando smites; but vain\nAgainst the valiant count is every blow;\nTo whom, for special grace, the King of heaven\nA body charmed against all arms had given."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The valorous count, redoubling still his blows,\nThought from the trunk the monarch's head to smite.\nSobrino, who the strength of Clermont knows,\nAnd how the shield ill boots, retired from fight,\nYet not so far, but that upon his brows\nFell the dread faulchion of Anglantes' knight:\n'Twas on its flat, but such his might and main,\nIt crushed the helm and stupefied the brain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Stunned by that furious stroke, he pressed the shore,\nAnd it was long ere he again did rise.\nThe paladin believes the warfare o'er,\nAnd that deprived of life Sobrino lies;\nAnd, lest Gradasso to ill pass and sore\nShould bring Sir Brandimart, at him he flies:\nFor him the paynim overmatched in horse,\nIn arms and faulchion, and perhaps in force."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bold Brandimart, who guides Frontino's rein,\nThe goodly courser, erst Rogero's steed,\nSo well contends with him of Sericane,\nThe king yet little seems his foe to exceed;\nWho, if he had as tempered plate and chain\nAs that bold paynim lord, would better speed;\nBut (for he felt himself ill-armed the knight ) \n\nOften gave ground, and traversed left and right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Better than good Frontino horse is none\nTo obey upon a sign the cavalier;\n'Twould seem that courser had the sense to shun\nSharp Durindana's fall, now there now here.\nMeanwhile elsewhere is horrid battle done\nBy royal Agramant and Olivier;\nWho may be deemed well matched in warlike sleight,\nNor champions differing much in martial might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando had left Sobrino (as I said)\nOn earth, and against Sericana's pride,\nDesirous valiant Brandimart to aid,\nEven as he was, afoot, in fury hied:\nWhen, prompt to assail Gradasso with the blade,\nHe, loose and walking in mid field, espied\nThe goodly horse, which had Sobrino thrown;\nAnd bowned him straight to make the steed his own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He seized the horse (for none the deed gainsaid)\nAnd took a leap, and vaulted on his prize.\nThis hand the bridle grasped, and that the blade.\nOrlando's motions good Gradasso spies;\nNor at his coming is the king dismaid;\nWho by his name the paladin defies:\nWith him, and both his partners in the fight,\nHe hopes to make it dark before 'tis night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leaving his foe, he, facing Brava's lord,\nThrust at the collar of his shirt of mail,\nAll else beside the flesh the faulchion bored;\nTo pierce through which would every labour fail.\nAt the same time descends Orlando's sword,\n(Where Balisarda bites no spells avail)\nShears helmet, cuirass, shield, and all below,\nAnd cleaves whate'er it rakes with headlong blow;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And in face, bosom, and in thigh it seamed,\nBeneath his mail, the king of Sericane.\nFrom whom his blood till how had never streamed\nSince he that armour wore; new rage and pain\nThereat the warrior felt, and strange it seemed\nSword cut so now, nor yet was Durindane.\nHad Roland struck more home, or nearer been,\nFrom head to belly he had cleft him clean."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No more in arms can trust the cavalier\nAs heretofore; for proved those arms have been:\nHe with more care, more caution than whilere,\nPrepares to parry with the faulchion keen.\nWhen entered Brandimart sees Brava's peer,\nWho snatched that battle from him, he between\nThose other conflicts placed himself, that where\nIt most was needed, he might succour bear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While so the fight is balanced 'mid those foes,\nSobrino, that on earth long time had lain,\nWhen to himself he was returned, uprose,\nIn face and shoulder suffering grievous pain.\nHe lifts his face, his eyes about him throws;\nAnd thither, where more distant on the plain\nHe sees his leader, with long paces steers\nSo stealthily, that none his coming hears;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He on the Marquis came, who had but eyes\nFor Agramant, and in the warrior's rear,\nWounded upon the hocks in such fierce wise\nThe courser of unheeding Olivier,\nThat he falls headlong; and beneath him lies\nHis valiant master, nor his foot can clear;\nHis left foot, which in that unthought for woe,\nWas in the stirrup jammed, his steed below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sorbine pursued, and with back-handed blow\nThought he his head should from his neck have shorn;\nBut this forbids that armour, bright of show,\nBy Vulcan hammered, and by Hector worn.\nBrandimart sees his risque, and at the foe\nIs by his steed, with flowing bridle, borne.\nSobrino on the head he smote and flung;\nBut straight from earth that fierce old man upsprung;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And turned anew to Olivier, to speed\nThe warrior's soul more promptly on its way;\nOr at the least that baron to impede.\nAnd him beneath his courser keep at bay:\nBold Olivier, whose better arm was freed,\nAnd with his sword could fend him as he lay,\nMeanwhile so smites and longes, there and here,\nThat at sword's length he holds the ancient peer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He hopes, if him but little he withstood,\nHe shall be straight delivered from that pain:\nHe sees him wholly strained and wet with blood,\nAnd that he spills so much from open vein,\n'Twould seem he speedily must be subdued,\nSo weak he hardly can himself sustain.\nOften and oft to rise the Marquis strove,\nYet could not from beneath his courser move."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Brandimart has found out the royal Moor,\nAnd storms about that paynim cavalier;\nUpon Frontino, like a lathe, before,\nBeside, or whirling in the warrior's rear.\nA goodly horse the Christian champion bore;\nNor worse the southern king's in the career:\nThat Brigliador, Rogero's gift he crost,\nErewhile, by haughty Mandricardo lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Great vantage has he, on another part:\nOf proof and perfect is his iron weed.\nHis at a venture took Sir Brandimart,\nAs he could have in haste in suchlike need;\nBut hopes (his anger puts him so in heart)\nTo change it for a better coat with speech;\nAlbeit the Moorish king, with bitter blow,\nHas made the blood from his right should flow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him in the flank Gradasso too had gored;\n(Nor this was laughing matter so had scanned ) \n\nHis vantage that redoubted paynim lord,\nHe found a place wherein to plant his brand;\nHe broke the warrior's shield, his left arm bored,\nAnd touched him slightly in the better hand.\nBut this was play, was pastime (might be said),\nWith Roland's and Gradasso's battle weighed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gradasso has Orlando half disarmed;\nAtop and on both sides his helm has broke:\nFallen is his shield, his cuirass split; but harmed\nThe warrior is not by the furious stroke,\nWhich opened plate and mail; for he is charmed;\nAnd worser vengeance on the king has wroke,\nIn face, throat, breast has gored that cavalier,\nBeside the wounds whereof I spake whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gradasso, desperate when he descried\nHimself all wet, and smeared with sanguine dye,\nAnd Roland, all from head to foot espied,\nAfter such mighty strokes unstained and dry,\nThinking head, breast, and belly to divide,\nWith both his hands upheaved his sword on high;\nAnd, even as he devised, upon the front,\nSmote with mid blade Anglantes' haughty count."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And would by any other so have done;\n— Would to the saddle-tree have cleft him clean:\nBut the good sword, as if it fell upon\nIts flat, rebounds again, unstained and sheen.\nThe furious stroke astounded Milo's son\nBy whom some scattered stars on earth were seen.\nHe drops the bridle and would drop the brand,\nBut that a chain secures it to his hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So by the noise was scared the horse that bore\nUpon his back Anglantes' cavalier.\nThe courser scowered about the powdery shore,\nShowing how good his speed in the career:\nThe County by that stroke astounded sore,\nHas not the power the frightened horse to steer.\nGradasso follows and will reach him, so\nThat he but little more pursues the foe;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But turning round, beholds the royal Moor\nTo the utmost peril in that battle brought;\nFor by the shining helmet which he wore,\nWith the left hand, him Brandimart had caught;\nAlready had unlaced the casque before,\nAnd with his dagger would new ill have wrought:\nNor much defence could make the Moorish lord;\nFor Brandimart as well had reft his sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Gradasso turned, nor more Orlando sought,\nBut hastened where he Agramant espied:\nThe incautious Brandimart, suspecting nought\nOrlando would have let him turn aside,\nHad not Gradasso in his eyes or thought,\nAnd to the paynim's throat his knife applied.\nGradasso came, and at his helmet layed,\nWielding with either hand his trenchant blade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Father of heaven!  'mid spirits chosen by thee,\nTo him thy martyr true, a place accord;\nWho, having traversed his tempestuous sea,\nNow furls his sails in port.  Ah!  ruthless sword,\nSo cruel, Durindana, can'st thou be,\nTo good Orlando, to thine ancient lord,\nThat thou can'st slaughter, in the warrior's view,\nOf all his friends the dearest and most true?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "An iron ring that girt his helmet round,\nTwo inches thick, was broke by that fell blow\nAnd cleft; and with the solid iron bound,\nWas parted the good cap of steel below,\nBold Brandimart, reversed upon the ground,\nWith haggard face beside his horse lies low;\nAnd issuing widely from the warrior's head\nA stream of life-blood dyes the shingle red."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Come to himself, the County turns his eye\nAnd sees his Brandimart upon the plain,\nAnd in such act Gradasso standing by\nAs clearly shows by whom the knight was slain.\nIf he most raged or grieved I know not, I,\nBut such short time is left him to complain,\nHis hasty wrath breaks forth, his grief gives way;\nBut now 'tis time that I suspend my lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 42"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The victory with Count Orlando lies;\nBut good Rinaldo and Bradamant at heart,\n(One for Angelica, the other sighs\nFor young Rogero suffer cruel smart. ) \n\nHim that in chase of the Indian damsel hies\nDisdain preserves; from thence does he depart\nTowards Italy, and is with courteous cheer\nAnd welcome guested by a cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What bit, what iron curb is to be found,\nOr (could it be what adamantine rein, ) \n\nThat can make wrath keep order and due bound,\nAnd within lawful limits him contain?\nWhen one, to whom the constant heart is bound\nAnd linked by Love with solid bolt and chain,\nWe see, through violence or through foul deceit,\nWith mortal damage or dishonour meet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And is the mind sometimes, if so possest,\nTo ill and savage action led astray,\nIt may deserve excuse; in that the breast\nNo more is under Reason's sovereign sway.\nAchilles, when, beneath his borrowed crest,\nHe saw Patroclus crimsoning the way,\nWas with his murderer's slaughter ill content,\nTill he his mangled corse had dragged and shent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Unconquered Duke Alphonso, anger so\nInflamed thy host the day that weighty stone\nWounded thy forehead with such grievous blow,\nThat all believed it to its rest was gone;\n— Inflamed them with such fury, for the foe\nIn rampart, fosse, or wall, defence was none,\nWho, one and all, within their works lay dead,\nNor wight was left the woeful news to spread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Seeing thy fall caused thine such mighty pain,\nThey were to fury moved; hadst thou, my lord,\nMaintained thy footing, haply might thy train\nHave with less licence plied the murderous sword.\nEnough for thee thy Bastia to regain!\nIn fewer hours replaced beneath thy ward,\nThen Cordova's and fierce Granada's band\nTook days erewhile, to wrest it from thy hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Haply Heaven's vengeance ordered what befel,\nAnd in that case thy wound so hindered thee\nTo the end, the cruel outrage, foul and fell,\nDone by that band before, should punished be.\nFor after the unhappy Vestidel,\nWearied and hurt, had sought their clemency,\nAmong them (mostly an unchristened train)\nHe, mid a hundred swords, unarmed, was slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To end; I say that other rage is none\nWhich can be weighed with that in equal wise,\nWhich kindles, when an injury is done\nTo kinsman, friend or lord before our eyes.\nThen justly in Orlando's heart, for one\nSo dear to him, might sudden fury rise;\nWhen him he saw, extended on the sand,\nSlain by the stroke of fierce Gradasso's brand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As nomade swain, who darting on its way\nIn slippery line the horrid snake has seen,\nThat his young son, amid the sands at play,\nHas killed with venomed tooth, enflamed with spleen,\nGrasps his batoon, the poisonous worm to slay;\nHis sword, than every other sword more keen,\nSo, in his fury grasped Anglantes' knight,\nAnd wreaked on Agramant his first despite,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Scaped, bleeding, with helm loosened form his head,\nWith half a shield and swordless, through his mail,\nSore wounded in more places than is said;\nAs from the dull or envious falcon's nail,\nEscapes the unhappy sparrowhawk, half dead,\nWith ruffled plumage and with loss of tail.\nOn him Orlando came and smote him just\nWhere with the helmed head confined the bust."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Loosed was the helm, the neck without its band:\nSo, like a rush, was severed by the sword.\nDown-fell, and shook its last upon the sand\nThe heavy trunk of Libya's mighty lord.\nHis spirit, which flitted to the Stygian strand,\nCharon with crooked boat-hook dragged aboard.\nOn him Orlando wastes no further pain,\nBut, sword in hand, seeks him of Sericane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As the headless trunk of Africk's cavalier\nExtended on the shore Gradasso's viewed,\n(What never had befallen him whilere)\nHe shook at heart, a troubled visage shewed,\nAnd, at the coming of Anglantes' peer,\nPresageful of his fate, appears subdued:\nNor seeks he means of fence against his foe,\nWhen fierce Orlando deals the fatal blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando levels at his better side,\nBeneath the lowest rib, his faulchion bright;\nAnd crimsoned to the hilt, a hand's breadth wide\nOf the other flank, the sword appears in sight;\nAnd well his mighty puissance testified,\nAnd spoke him as the strongest living knight\nThat stroke, by which a warrior was undone,\nBetter than whom in Paynimry was none."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Little his victory good Orlando cheers:\nHimself he quickly from his saddle throws;\nAnd, with a face disturbed, and wet with tears,\nTo his Brandimart in haste the warrior goes;\nThe field about him red with blood appears,\nHis helmet cleft as by a hatchet's blows;\nAnd, had it been than spungy rind more frail,\nWould have defended him no worse than mail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando lifts the helmet, and descries\nBrandimart's head by that destructive brand\nCleft even to his nose, between the eyes;\nYet so the wounded knight his spirits manned,\nThat pardon of the king of Paradise\nHe, before death, was able to demand,\nAnd to exhort to patience Brava's peer,\nWhose manly cheeks were wet with many a tear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And — \"Roland, in thy helping orisons, I\nBeseech thee to remember me,\" he cried,\n\"Nor recommend to thee less warmly my —\"\n— Flordelice would, but could not, say — and died;\nAnd sounds and songs of angels in the sky,\nAs the soul parts, are heard on every side;\nWhich from its prison freed, mid hymns of love,\nAscends into the blissful realms above."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Orlando, albeit he should joy in heart\nAt death so holy, and is certified\nThat called to bliss above is Brandimart;\nFor he heaven opened to the knight described;\nThrough human wilfulness — which aye takes part\nWith our weak senses — hardly can abide\nThe loss of one, above a brother dear,\nNor can refrain from many a scalding tear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Warlike Sobrino, of much blood bereaved,\nWhich from his flank and wounded visage rained,\nLong since had fallen, reversed and sore aggrieved,\nAnd had by now his vessels well nigh drained.\nOlivier too lies stretched; nor has retrieved,\nNor can retrieve, his crippled foot, save sprained,\nAnd almost crushed; so long between the plain,\nAnd his stout courser jammed, the limb has lain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And but Orlando helped (so woe begone\nWas weeping Olivier, and brought so low)\nHe could not have released his limb alone;\nAnd, when released, endures such pain, such woe,\nThe helpless warrior cannot stand upon,\nOr shift withal his wounded foot, and so\nBenumbed and crippled is the leg above,\nThat he without assistance cannot move."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The victory brought Orlando small delight;\nOn whom too heavily and hardly weighed\nOf slaughtered Brandimart the piteous sight;\nNor sure of Oliviero's life he made.\nSobrino yet survived; but little light\nThe wounded monarch had, amid much shade:\nFor almost spend his ebbing life remained\nSo fast from him the crimson blood had drained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The County has him taken, bleeding sore;\nThither, where he is saved with sovereign care;\nAnd he as if a kinsman of the Moor,\nBenignly comforts him and speaks him fair:\nFor in Orlando, when the strife was o'er,\nWas nothing evil; ever prompt to spare.\nHe from the dead their arms and coursers reft,\nThe rest he to their knives' disposal left."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here as my story stood not on good ground,\nFrederick Fulgoso doubtful does appear;\nWho, searching Barbary's every shore and sound\nErewhile on board a squadron, landed here;\nAnd the isle so rugged and so rocky found,\nIn all its parts so mountainous and drear,\nThere is not (through the land a level space ) \n\n(He says whereon a single boot to place. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor deems he likely, that six cavaliers,\nThe wide world's flower, on Alpine rock should vye,\nIn that equestrian fight, with levelled spears.\nTo whose objection thus I make reply:\nErewhile a place, well fit for such careers,\nStretched at the bottom of the hills did lie;\nBut afterwards, o'erthrown by earthquake's shock,\nA cliff o'erspread the plain with broken rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So, of Fulgoso's race thou shining ray,\nClear, lasting light, if, questioning my word,\nThou on this point hast ever said me nay,\nAnd haply too, before the unconquered lord,\nThrough whom thy land, reposing, casts away\nAll haste, and wholly leans to kind accord,\nPrythee delay not to declare, that I\nIn this my story haply tell no lie."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile his eyes the good Orlando reared,\nAnd saw, on turning them to seaward, where\nUnder full sail a nimble bark appeared,\nAs if she to that island would repair.\nI will not now rehearse who thither steered;\nFor more than one awaiteth me elsewhere.\nWend me to France and see if they be glad\nAt having chased the Saracens, or sad;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "See what she does withal, the lady true,\nThat sees her knight content to wend so wide;\nOf the afflicted Bradamant I shew;\nAfter she saw the oath was nullified,\nMade in the hearing of those armies two,\nUpon the Christian and the paynim side;\nSince he again had failed her, there was nought\nWherein she could confide, the damsel thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And now her too accustomed plaint and wail\nRepeating, of Rogero's cruelty\nFair Bradamant renewed the wonted tale;\nShe cursed her hard and evil destiny;\nThen loosening to tempestuous grief the sail,\nHeaven that consented to such perjury,\n— And did not yet by some plain token speak —\nShe, in her passion, called unjust and weak."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The sage Melissa she accused, and cursed\nThe oracle of the cavern, through whose lie\nShe in that sea of love herself immersed,\nUpon whose waters she embarked to die.\nShe to Marphisa afterwards rehearsed\nHer woes, and told her brother's perfidy;\nShe chides, pours forth her sorrows, and demands,\nWith tears and outcries, succour at her hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa shrugs her shoulders; what alone\nShe can, she offers — comfort to the fair;\nNor thinks Rogero her has so foregone\nBut what to her he shortly will repair.\nAnd, should he not, such outrage to be done,\nThe damsel plights her promise not to bear;\nTwixt her and him shall deadly war be waged,\nOr he shall keep the word, which he engaged."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She makes her somewhat thus her grief restrain;\nWhich having vent in some sort spend its gall,\nNow we have seen the damsel in her pain\nRogero impious, proud, and perjured call,\nSee we, if in a happier state remain\nThe brother of that gentle maid withal;\nWhose flesh, bones, nerves, and sinews are a prey\nTo burning love; Rinaldo I would say."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say Rinaldo that (as known to you)\nAngelica the beauteous loved so well:\nNor him into the amorous fillets drew\nSo much her beauty as the magic spell.\nIn peace reposed those other barons true;\nFor wholly broken was the infidel:\nAlone amid the victors, he, of all\nThe paladins, remained Love's captive thrall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To seek her he a hundred couriers sent,\nAnd sought as well,  himself, the missing maid:\nHe in the end to Malagigi went,\nWho in his need had often given him aid:\nTo him he told his love, with eyelids bent\nOn earth, and visage crimsoned o'er; and prayed\nThat sage magicians to instruct him, where\nHe in the world might find the long-sought fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A case, so strange and wondrous, marvel sore\nIn friendly Malagigi's bosom bred:\nThe wizard knew, a hundred times and more,\nHe might have had the damsel in his bed;\nAnd he himself, to move the knight or yore,\nIn her behalf, enough had done and said:\nHad him by prayer and menace sought to bend,\nYet ne'er was able to obtain his end;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And so much more, that out of prison ward\nHe then would Malagigi so have brought.\nNow will he seek her, of his own accord,\nOn less occasion, when it profits nought.\nNext that magician Montalbano's lord\nTo mark how sorely do had erred, besought:\nSince little lacked, but through the boon denied,\nErewhile he had in gloomy dungeon died."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But how much more Rinaldo's strange demand\nSounded importunately in his ear,\nSo by sure index Malagigi scanned,\nThat so much was Angelica more dear.\nRinaldo prayer unable to withstand,\nIn ocean sunk the wizard cavalier\nAll memory of old injury assaid,\nAnd bowned himself to give the warrior aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For his reply he craved some small delay,\nAnd with fair hope consoled Mount Alban's knight,\nHe should be able of the road to say\nBy which Angelica had sped her flight,\nIn France or wheresoe'er; then wends his way\nThither where he is wont his imps to cite;\nA grot impervious and with mountains walled:\nHis book he opened and the spirits called."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then one he chooses, in love-cases read,\nWhom Malagigi to declare requires,\nHow good Rinaldo's heart, before so died,\nWas now so quickly moved by soft desires;\nAnd of those fountains twain (the demon said)\nWhereof one lights, one quenches amorous fires;\nAnd how nought cures the mischief caused by one\nBut that whose streams in counter current run;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And says, Rinaldo, having drunk whilere\nFrom the love-chasing fountain's mossy urn,\nTo Angelica, that long had wooed the peer,\nHad shown himself so obstinate and stern;\nAnd he, whom after his ill star did steer\nTo drink of that which makes the bosom burn,\nHer whom but just before he loathed above\nAll reason, by that draught was forced to love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him his ill star and cruel fate conveyed\nTo swallow fire and flame i' the frozen lake:\nFor nigh at the same time the Indian maid\nIn the other bitter stream her thirst did slake;\nWhich in her bosom so all love allayed,\nHenceforth she loathed him more than noisome snake;\nHe loved her, and such love was his, as late\nRinaldo bore her enmity and hate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of this strange story fully certified\nWas Malagigi by the demon's lore;\nWho news as well of Angelique supplied;\nHow yielding up herself to a young Moor,\nWith him embarking on the unstable tide,\nShe had abandoned Europe's every shore;\nAnd hoisting her bold canvas to the wind,\nIn Catalonian galley loosed for Ind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo seeking out the sage anew\nFor his reply — he would dissuade the knight\nFrom loving more that Indian lady, who\nNow waited on a vile barbarian wight;\nAnd was so distant he could ill pursue;\nIf he would chase the damsel on her flight,\nWho must have measured than half her way\nHomeward, with young Medoro to Catay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In that bold lover no displeasure deep\nThe journey of Angelica would move;\nNor yet would mar or break the warrior's sleep\nTo think that he again must eastward rove:\nBut that a stripling Saracen should reap\nThe first fruits of that faithless lady's love\nIn him such passion bred, such heart-ache sore,\nHe never in his life so grieved before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No power hath he to make one sole reply;\nHis heart, his lip, is quivering with disdain;\nHis tongue no word is able to untie;\nHis mouth is bitter, and 'twould seem with bane.\nHe flung from the magician suddenly,\nAnd, as by fury stirred and jealous pain,\nHe after mighty plaint and mighty woe\nResolved anew to eastern realms to go."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Licence he asks of Pepin's royal son,\nUpon the ground, since with his courser dear\nTo Sericane is King Gradasso gone,\nAgainst the use of gallant cavalier,\nHim honour moves the selfsame course to run,\nIn the end he may prevent the paynim peer\nFrom ever vaunting, that with sword or lance\nHe took him from a Paladin of France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Charles gives him leave to go; though, far and nigh,\nWith him all France laments he thence should wend;\nBut he in fine that prayer can ill deny,\nSo honest seems the worthy warrior's end.\nHim Dudon, Guido, would accompany;\nBut he refuses either valiant friend:\nFrom Paris he departs, and wends alone,\nPlunged in his grief and heaving many a groan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ever in memory dwells the restless thought,\nHe might a thousand times have had the fair;\nAnd — mad and obstinate — had, when besought,\nA thousand times refused such beauty rare;\nAnd such sweet joy was whilom set at nought,\nSuch bright, such blessed moments wasted were;\nAnd now he life would gladly give away\nTo have that damsel but for one short day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The thought will never from his mind depart,\nHow for a sorry footpage she could slight,\n— Flinging their merit and their love apart —\nThe service of each former loving wight.\nVext by such thought, which racked and rent his heart,\nRinaldo wends towards the rising light:\nHe the straight road to Rhine and Basle pursued,\nTill he arrived in Arden's mighty wood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When within that adventurous wood has hied\nFor many a mile Montalban's cavalier,\nOf lonely farm or lordly castle wide,\nWhere the rude place was roughest and most drear,\nThe sky disturbed he suddenly descried,\nHe saw the sun's dimmed visage disappear,\nAnd spied forth issuing from a cavern hoar\nA monster, which a woman's likeness wore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A thousand lidless eyes are in her head:\nShe cannot close them, nor, I think, doth sleep:\nShe listens with as many ears, and spread\nLike hair, about her forehead serpents creep.\nForth issued into day that figure dread\nFrom devilish darkness and the caverned deep.\nFor tail, a fierce and bigger serpent wound\nAbout her breast, and girt the monster round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What in a thousand, thousand quests had ne'er\nBefal'n Rinaldo, here befel the knight;\nWho, when he sees the horrid form appear,\nComing to seek him and prepared for fight,\nFeels in his inmost veins such freezing fear,\nAs haply never fell on other wight;\nYet wonted daring counterfeits and feigns,\nAnd with a trembling hand the faulchion strains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The monster so the fierce assault did make\nTherein her master was well descried,\nIt might be said; she shook a poisonous snake,\nAnd now on this, now on the other side,\nLeapt at the knight; at her Rinaldo strake\nEver meanwhile with random blows and wide;\nWith forestroke, backstroke, he assails the foe;\nHe often smites, but never plants a blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The monster threw a serpent at his breast,\nThat froze his heart beneath its iron case:\nNow through the vizor flung the poisonous pest,\nWhich crept about his collar and his face.\nDismaid, Rinaldo fled the field, and prest\nWith all his spurs his courser through the chase:\nBut not behind the hellish monster halts,\nWho in a thought upon the crupper vaults."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Wend where the warrior will, an-end or wide,\nEver with him is that accursed Pest:\nNor knows he how from her to be untied,\nAlbeit his courser plunges without rest.\nLike a leaf quakes his heart within his side,\nNot that the snakes in other mode molest,\nBut they such horror and such loathing bred,\nHe shrieks, he groans, and gladly would be dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By gloomiest track and blindest path he still\nThreaded the tangled forest here and there;\nBy thorniest valley and by roughest hill,\nAnd wheresoever darkest was the air;\nThus hoping to have rid him of that ill,\nHideous, abominable, poisonous Care;\nBeneath whose gripe he foully might have fared,\nBut that one quickly to his aid repaired."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But aid, and in good time, a horseman bore,\nEquipt with arms of beauteous steel and clear:\nFor crest, a broken yoke the stranger wore;\nRed flames upon his yellow shield appear:\nSo was the courser's housing broidered o'er,\nAs the proud surcoat of the cavalier.\nHis lance he grasped, his sword was in its place,\nAnd at his saddle hung a burning mace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That warrior's mace a fire eternal fills,\nWhose lasting fuel ever blazes bright;\nAnd goodly buckler, tempered corslet thrills,\nAnd solid helm; then needs the approaching knight\nMust make him way, wherever 'tis his will\nTo turn his inextinguishable light.\nNor of less help in need Rinaldo stands,\nTo save him from the cruel monster's hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The stranger horseman, like a warrior bold,\nWhere he that hubbub hears, doth thither swoop,\nUntil he sees the beast, whose snakes enfold\nRinaldo, linked in many a loathsome loop,\nWho sweats at once with heat and quakes with cold,\nNor can he thrust the monster from his croup.\nArrived the stranger smote her in the flank,\nWho on the near side of the courser sank:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But scarcely was on earth extended, ere\nShe rose and shook her snakes in volumed spire.\nThe knight no more assails her with the spear;\nBut is resolved to plague the foe with fire:\nHe gripes the mace and thunders in her rear\nWith frequent blows, like tempest in its ire;\nNor leaves a moment to that monster fell\nTo strike one stroke in answer, ill or well;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, while he chases her or holds at bay,\nSmites her and venges many a foul affront,\nCounsels the paladin, without delay,\nTo take the road which scales the neighbouring mount:\nHe took that proffered counsel and that way,\nAnd without stop, or turning back his front,\nPricked furiously till he was out of sight;\nThough hard to clamber was the rugged height."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The stranger, when he to her dark retreat\nHad driven from upper light that beast of hell\n(Where she herself doth ever gnaw and eat,\nWhile from her thousand eyes tears ceaseless well)\nFollowed the knight, to guide his wandering feet;\nAnd overtook him on the highest swell;\nThen placed himself beside the cavalier\nHim from those dark and gloomy parts to steer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When him returned beheld Montalban's knight,\nThat countless thanks were due to him, he said,\nAnd that at all times, as a debt of right,\nHis life should be for his advantage paid.\nOf him he next demands, how he is hight,\nThat he may know and tell who brought him aid;\nAnd among worthy warriors, and before\nKing Charles, exalt his prowess evermore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The stranger answered: \"Let it irk not thee\nThat I not now my name to thee display;\nEre longer by a yard the shadows be,\nThis will I signify; a short delay.\"\nWending together, they a river see\nWhose murmurs woo the traveller from his way,\nAnd shepherd-swain, by whiles, to their green brink;\nThere an oblivion of their love to drink."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "My lord, that fountain's chilling stream and clear\nExtinguished love; Angelica of yore\nDrinking thereof, for good Montalban's peer\nConceived that hate she nourished evermore;\nAnd if she once displeased the cavalier,\nAnd he to her such passing hatred bore,\nFor this no other cause occasion gave,\nMy lord, save drinking of this chilly wave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Arriving at that limpid river's side,\nThe cavalier that with Rinaldo goes,\nReined-in his courser, how with toil, and cried,\n\"Here 'twere not ill, meseemeth, to repose.\"\n— \"It cannot but be well\" (the peer replied),\n\"Because, beside that mid-day fiercely glows,\nI have so suffered from that hideous Pest,\nAs sweet and needful shall I welcome rest.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the green sward lit the martial two,\nWhile their loose horses through the forest fed;\nAnd from their brows the burnished helmets threw\nOn that flowered herbage, yellow, green, and red.\nRinaldo to the liquid crystal flew,\nBy heat and thirst unto the river sped;\nAnd with one draught of that cold liquid drove\nOut of his burning bosom thirst and love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whenas Rinaldo, sated with the draught,\nRaising his head the stranger knight espied,\nAnd saw that he, repentant, every thought\nOf that so frantic love had put aside,\nHe reared himself, and said with semblance haught\nThat which he would not say before, and cried:\n\"Rinaldo, know that I am hight Disdain,\nBound hither but to break thy worthless chain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, suddenly he passed from sight;\nWith him his horse: this in Rinaldo bred\nMuch wonderment; and the astonished knight,\n\"Where is he?\" gazing round about him, said.\nHe cannot guess if 'twere a magic sprite,\nA fiend by Malagigi thither sped,\nFrom those his ministers, to break the chain,\nFettered whereby he lived so long in pain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of if an angel from the heavenly sphere\nIn his ineffable goodness by the Lord,\nDispatched, as to Tobias's aid whilere,\nA medicine for his blindness to afford.\nBut good or evil angel — whatsoe'er\nHe was that him to liberty restored —\nHim thanked and praised Rinaldo, for a heart\nHealed only by his help of amorous smart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Old hate revived upon Rinaldo's side;\nNor he alone unworthy to be wooed,\nThe damsel deemed by pilgrimage so wide\nHer half a league he would not have pursued.\nNathless anew Baiardo to bestride\nTo Sericane would go that warrior good:\nAs well because his honour him compelled,\nAs for the talk which he with Charles had held."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He pricked to Basle upon the following day,\nWhither the tidings had arrived before:\nThat Count Orlando was, in martial fray,\nTo meet Gradasso and the royal Moor:\nNor through Orlando was divulged that say:\nBut one, who crost from the Sicilian shore,\nAnd thither had, in haste, the journey made,\nAs certain news, the tidings had conveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo had gladly been at Roland's side,\nAnd from that battle far himself doth see:\nEvery ten miles he changes horse and guide,\nAnd whips and spurs, and makes his courser flee.\nHe crost the Rhine at Constance, forward hied,\nHe traversed Alp, arrived in Italy,\nHe left Verona, Mantua, in his rear,\nAnd reached and past the Po, with swift career."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much towards eve already sloped the sun,\nAnd the first star was glimmering in the sky,\nWhen, doubting on the bank if he shall run\nAnother course, or in some hostel lie\nUntil the shades of night and vapours dun\nBefore Aurora's beauteous visage fly,\nA cavalier approaching him he viewed,\nWho courtesy in face and semblance shewed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, after greeting him, if he were tied\nIn wedlock, made in gentle wise demand.\nRinaldo, wondering what the quest implied,\nMade answer: \"I am bound in nuptial band.\"\n— \"I joy thereat,\" the cavalier replied;\nThen, that he might this saying understand,\nAdded, \"I pray that you, sir knight, within\nMy mansion will this eve be pleased to inn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For I will make you see what must please\nA wight\" (pursued the stranger \"that is wed.\" ) \n\nRinaldo, as well that he would take his ease,\n— But this, with so long posting sore bested —\nAs that to see and hear strange novelties\nBy natural desire he still was led,\nHis offer takes, and enters a new road,\nFollowing that cavalier to his abode."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A bowshot from the way diverged the two,\nAnd a great palace fronting them descried:\nWhence squires with blazing lights (a numerous crew)\nIssued, and chased the darkness far and wide.\nEntering, his eyes around Rinaldo threw,\nAnd saw a place, whose like is seldom spied,\nOf beauteous fabric, and well ordered plan;\nNor such huge cost befitted private man."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of serpentine and of hard porphyry are\nThe stones which form the gateway's arch above.\nOf bronze the portal leaves, which figures bear,\nWhose lively features seem to breathe and move.\nBeneath the vaulted entry, colours rare\nCheating the eye, in mixt mosaic strove,\nThe quadrangle within was galleried,\nAnd of a hundred yards, on every side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A gateway is there to each galleried row,\nAnd, twixt it and that gate, an arch is bent;\nOf equal breadth, but different in their show,\nFor the architect had spared not ornament.\nEach arch an entrance was; up which might go\nA laden horse; so easy the ascent.\nTo arch above leads every stair withal,\nAnd every arch is entrance to a hall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above, project the arches in such sort,\nThey for the spacious portals form a shade;\nAnd each two pillars has for its support:\nOf bronze are some, and some of marble made.\nThe ornamented chambers of the court\nToo many are to be at length displayed;\nWith easements, which (beside what is in sight)\nThe skilful master underground had dight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Tall columns, with their capitals of gold,\nWhich gemmed entablatures support in air;\nExotic marbles engraved with figures fair;\nPicture and cast, and works so manifold,\nAlbeit by night they mostly hidden were,\nShowed that two kings' united treasure ne'er\nWould have sufficed such gorgeous pile to rear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Above the beauteous ornaments and rich\nThat mingled in that gay quadrangle meet,\nThere is a fresh and plenteous fountain, which\nScatters in many threads its watery sheet,\n'Tis here that youths at equal distance pitch,\nI' the middle, tables for the festive treat.\nWhence they four gates of that rich mansion see,\nAnd seen from those four gates as well may be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By cunning master, diligent and wise,\nWith much and subtle toil, the fount was made:\nIn open gallery or pavilion's guise;\nWhich from eight separate fronts, projects a shade.\nA gilded roof, which with enamelled dyes\nWas stained below, the building overlayed.\nEight marble statues (snowy was the grain),\nWith the left arm that gilded roof sustain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fair Amalthaea's horn in the right hand\nHad quaintly sculptured the ingenious master,\nWhence water, trickling forth with murmur bland,\nDescends into a vase of alabaster;\nAnd he, in likeness of a lady grand,\nWith sovereign art had fashioned each pilaster.\nVarious they were in visage and in vest,\nBut all of equal charms and grace possest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon two beauteous images below\nEach of these female statues fix their feet.\nThe lower seem with open mouth to show\nThat song and harmony to them are sweet;\nAnd, by their attitude, 'twould seem, as though\nTheir every work and every study meet\nIn praising them, they on their shoulders bear,\nAs they would those whose likenesses they wear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The images below them in their hand\nLong scrolls and of an ample size contain,\nWhich of the worthiest figures of that band\nThe several names with mickle praise explain\nAs well their own at little distance stand,\nInscribed upon that scroll, in letters plain,\nRinaldo, by the help of blazing lights,\nMarked, one by one, the ladies and their knights."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The first inscription there which meets the eye\nRecites at length Lucretia Borgia's fame,\nWhom Rome should place, for charms and chastity,\nAbove that wife who whilom bore her name.\nStrozza and Tebaldeo — Anthony\nAnd Hercules — support the honoured dame:\n(So says the scroll): for tuneful strain, the pair\nA very Linus and an Orpheus are."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A statue no less jocund, no less bright,\nSucceeds, and on the writing is impressed;\nLo!  Hercules' daughter, Isabella hight,\nIn whom Ferrara deems her city blest,\nMuch more because she first shall see the light\nWithin its circuit, than for all the rest\nWhich kind and favouring Fortune in the flow\nOf rolling years, shall on that town bestow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The pair that such desirous ardour shew\nThat aye her praises should be widely blown:\nJohn James alike are named: of those fair two,\nOne is Calandra, one is Bardelon.\nIn the third place, and fourth, where trickling through\nSmall rills, the water quits that octagon,\nTwo ladies are there, equal in their birth,\nEqual in country, honour, charms and worth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One was Elizabeth, one Eleanor,\nAnd if we credit what that marble said,\nManto's so glorious city which such store\nSets my melodious Maro, whom she bred,\nMore vaunts not him, nor reverences more,\nThan these fair dames her poet's honoured head.\nThe first of these her hallowed feet had set\nOn Peter Bembo and James Sadolet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Arelio and Castiglion, a polished pair,\nThat other lady, in mid air, sustain.\nTheir names were carved upon the marble fair,\nThen both unknown, and now so fames a twain.\nNext was a lady, that from Heaven shall heir\nAs mighty virtue as on earth doth reign,\nOr ever yet hath reigned, in any age,\nWell proved by Fortune in her love or rage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Inscribed in characters of gold is here\nLucretia Bentivoglia, and among\nHer praises, 'tis declared Ferrara's peer\nJoys that such daughter doth to him belong.\nHer shall Camillus voice, and far and near\nReno and Felsina shall hear his song,\nWrapt in as mighty wonder at the strain\nAs that wherewith Amphrysus heard his swain;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And one, through whom that city's name (where sweet\nIsaurus salts his wave in larger vase)\nFame shall from Africa to Ind repeat,\nFrom southern tracts to Hyperborean ways,\nMore than because Rome's gold in that famed seat\nWas weighed, whereof perpetual record says\nGuy Posthumus — about whose honoured brow\nPhoebus and Pallas bind a double bough."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dian is next in order of that train.\n\"Regard not (said the marble is she wear ) \n\nA haughty port; for in her heart, humane\nThe matron is, as in her visage, fair.\nLearned Celio Calcagnine in lofty strain\nHer glories and fair name abroad shall bear,\nAnd Juba's and Moneses' kingdom hear,\nAnd Spain and farthest Ind, his trumpet clear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And a Cavallo shall make such a font\nOf poetry in famed Ancona run,\nAs that winged courser on Parnassus' mount;\nOr was it on the hill of Helicon?\n'Tis Beatrice, who next uprears her front,\nWhereof so speaks the writing on the stone:\n\"Her consort Beatrice, while she has breath,\nBlesses, and leaves unhappy at her death;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yea, Italy; that with her triumphs bright,\nWithout that lady fair shall captive be.\"\nA lofty song appears of her to indite\nA lord of the Correggio's noble tree;\nAnd, Benedeo's pride, Timotheus hight.\nBetween his banks, descending to the sea,\nBy their joint music shall the stream be stopt,\nWhose trees erewhile the liquid amber dropt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Between this and that lofty column's place\nInto fair Borgia fashioned (as was said)\nOf aspect so distinguished, of such grace,\nA lady was, of alabaster made,\nThat, hiding in a simple veil her face,\nIn sable, without gems or gold arraid,\nShe, 'mid the brightest, flung her light as far,\nAs amid lesser fires the Cyprian star."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "None knows, observing her with steadfast view,\nIf she of charms or grace have fuller store,\nWhether her visage most majestic shew,\nOr beam with genius or with beauty more.\n\"He that would speak — would speak her praises true —\n(Declares in fine the sculptured marble's lore)\nThe fairest of emprizes would intend,\nBut never bring his noble task to end.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Albeit such grace and passing sweetness shewed\nHer fair and well wrought image, she disdain\nAppeared to nurse, that one of wit so rude\nShould dare to sing her praise in humble strain,\nAs he that only without comrade stood,\nI know not why, her statue to sustain,\nThe marble all those other names revealed.\nThat pair's alone the artist had concealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The statues in the middle form a round,\nThe floor whereof dry stalks of coral pave;\nMost pleasant, cool, and grateful, is that ground;\nSo rendered by the pure and crystal wave.\nWhich vent without in other channel found;\nAnd issued forth in many a stream, to lave\nA mead of azure, white, and yellow hue;\nGladdening the plants that on their margins grew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Conversing with his courteous host, the peer\nSate at the board, and oft and often prayed,\nThat without more delay the cavalier\nWould keep the promise he whilere had made;\nAnd marking, ever and anon, his cheer,\nObserves his heart with some deep woe downweighed.\nFor not a moment 'mid their converse slips,\nBut what a burning sigh is on his lips."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oft with desire was good Rinaldo stung\nTo ask that sorrow's cause, and the request\nWas almost on the gentle warrior's tongue,\nAnd there by courteous modesty represt.\nNow at their banquet's close a youth, among\nThe menial crew, on whom that charge did rest,\nPlaced a gold cup before the paladin,\nFilled full of gems without, of wine within."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The host then somedeal smiling, from the board\nLooked up at Aymon's son; but who this while\nWell marked him, as he eyed Montalban's lord,\nHad deemed him more disposed to weep than smile.\n\"So oft reminded, to maintain my word,\n'Tis time meseems (said he, that owned the pile)\nTo shew the touchstone for a woman's love,\nWhich needs to wedded man must welcome prove."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ne'er, in my judgment, should the married dame\nBe from espial by her lord released;\nThus shall he know if honour or if blame\nHis portion is; if he is man or beast.\nThe weight of horns, though coupled with such shame,\nIs of all burdens upon the earth the least.\nWhile well-nigh all behold his antlers spread,\nHe feels them not who has them on his head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If certain of thy wife's fidelity,\nThou hast more ground to prize and hold her dear\nThan one, whose wife is evil known to be,\nOr husband that is still in doubt and fear.\nFull many husbands live in jealousy,\nAnd groundlessly, of women chaste and clear.\nOn many women many men rely\nMeanwhile, who bear their branching antlers high."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If thou would'st be assured thy wife is true\n(As sure methinks thou thinkest and must think)\nFor it is hard that notion to undo,\nUnless thy trust before sure tokens sink,\n— No hearsay matter this — thyself shalt view\nThe truth, if thou in this fair vessel drink,\nPlaced solely on the supper-board, that thou\nMay'st see the marvel promised thee but now."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Drink, and a mighty marvel shall be seen;\nFor if thou wearest Cornwall's lofty crest,\nNo drop of wine shall pass thy lips between,\nAnd all the draught be spilt upon thy breast.\nIf faithful is thy wife, thou shalt drink clean.\nAnd now — to try thy fortune — to the test!\"\nHe said, and with fixt eyes the sign explored;\nIf on his breast the wine Rinaldo poured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo was nigh moved the cup to raise,\nAnd seek what he would haply wish unsought:\nForward he reached his hand and took the vase,\nAbout to prove his fortune in the draught.\nThen of the passing peril of the case,\nBefore it touched his lips, the warrior thought.\nBut let me, sir, repose myself, and I\nWill then relate the Paladin's reply."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 43"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo from his courteous landlord hears\nWhat folly had destroyed his every good;\nNext learns another story, as he steers\nToward Ravenna with the falling flood:\nThen last arrives where, conqueror o'er his foes\nOrlando was, but in no joyful mood.\nHe, that the Child a Christian made whilere,\nChristens Sobrino, and heals Olivier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "O Execrable avarice!  O vile thirst\nOf sordid gold!  it doth not me astound\nSo easily thou seizest soul, immersed\nIn baseness, or with other taint unsound;\nBut that thy chain should bind, amid the worst,\nAnd that thy talon should strike down and wound\nOne that for loftiness of mind would be\nWorthy all praise, if he avoided thee."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Some earth and sea and heaven above us square,\nKnow Nature's causes, works, and properties;\nWhat her beginnings, what her endings are;\nAnd soar till Heaven is open to their eyes:\nYet have no steadier aim, no better care,\nStung by thy venom, than, in sordid wise,\nTo gather treasure: such their single scope,\nTheir every comfort, and their every hope."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Armies by him are broken in his pride,\nAnd gates of warlike towns in triumph past:\nThe foremost he to breast the furious tide\nOf fearful battle; to retire the last;\nYet cannot save himself from being stied\nTill death, in thy dark dungeon prisoned fast.\nOf others that would shine thou dimm'st the praise;\nWhom other studies, other arts would raise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What shall of high and beauteous dames be said?\nWho (from their lovers' worth and charms secure)\nAgainst long service, I behold, more staid,\nMore motionless, than marble shafts, endure:\nThen Avarice comes, who so her spells hath laid,\nI see them stoop directly to her lure.\n— Who could believe? — unloving, in a day\nThey fall some elder's, fall some monster's prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Not without reason here I raise this cry:\n— Read me who can, I read myself — nor so\nI from the beaten pathway tread awry,\nNor thus the matter of my song forego.\nNot more to what is shown do I apply\nMy saying, than to what I have to show.\nBut now return we to the paladine,\nWho was about to taste the enchanted wine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Fain would he think awhile, of whom I speak,\n(As said ere to his lips the vase he bore; ) \n\nHe thought; then thus: \"When finding what we seek\nDispleases, this 'tis folly to explore,\nMy wife's a woman; every woman's weak.\nThen let me hold the faith I held before.\nFaith still has brought, and yet contentment brings.\nFrom proof itself what better profit springs?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"From this small good, much evil I foresee:\nFor tempting God moves sometimes his disdain.\nI know not if it wise or foolish be,\nBut to know more than needs, I am not fain.\nNow put away the enchanted cup from me;\nI neither will, nor would, the goblet drain;\nWhich is with Heaven's command as much at strife,\nAs Adam's deed who robbed the tree of life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For as our sire who tasted of that tree,\nAnd God's own word, by eating, disobeyed,\nFell into sorrow from felicity,\nAnd was by misery evermore o'erlaid;\nThe husband so, that all would know and see;\nWhatever by his wife is done and said;\nPasses from happiness to grief and pain,\nNor ever can uplift his head again.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile the good Rinaldo saying so,\nAnd pushing from himself the cup abhorred,\nBeheld of tears a plenteous fountain flow\nFrom the full eyes of that fair mansion's lord;\nWho cried, now having somewhat calmed his woe,\n\"Accursed be he, persuaded by whose word,\nAlas!  I of the fortune made assay,\nWhereby my cherished wife was reft away!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Wherefore ten years ago wast thou not known,\nSo that I counselled might have been of thee?\nBefore the sorrows and the grief begun,\nThat have nigh quenched my eyes; but raised shall be\nThe curtain from the scene, that thou upon\nMy pain mayst look, and mayst lament with me;\nAnd I to thee of mine unheard-of woe\nThe argument and very head will show."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Above, was left a neighbouring city, pent\nWithin a limpid stream that forms a lake;\nWhich widens, and wherein Po finds a vent.\nTheir way the waters from Benacus take.\nBuilt was the city, when to ruin went\nWalls founded by the Agenorean snake.\nHere me of gentle line my mother bore,\nBut of small means, in humble home and poor."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If Fortune's care I was not, who denied\nTo me upon my birth a wealthy boon,\nNature that went with graceful form supplied;\nSo that in beauty rival had I none.\nEnamoured of me in youth's early tide\nErewhile was dame and damsel more than one:\nFor I with beauty coupled winning ways;\nThough it becomes not man himself to praise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A sage within our city dwelled, a wight,\nBeyond belief, in every science great;\nWho, when he closed his eyes on Phoebus' light,\nNumbered one hundred years, one score and eight:\nA savage life he led and out of sight,\nUntil impelled by love, the senior late\nBy dint of gifts obtained a matron fair,\nWho secretly to him a daughter bare;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And to prevent the child from being won,\nAs was erewhile the mother, that for gain\nBartered her chastity, whose worth alone\nExcels what gold earth's ample veins contain,\nWith her he from the ways of man is gone,\nAnd where he spies the loneliest place, his train\nOf demons forces, in enchantment skilled,\nThis dome so spacious, fair, and rich, to build."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"By ancient and chaste dames he there made rear\nThis daughter, that in sovereign beauty grew;\nNor suffered her to see or even hear\nA man beside himself; and, for her view,\n— Lest lights should lack, whereby her course to steer —\nThe senior every modest lady, who\nE'er on unlawful love the barrier shut,\nMade limn in picture, or in sculpture cut."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor he alone those virtuous dames, who, sage\nAnd chaste, had so adorned antiquity,\nWhose fame, preserved by the historic page,\nIs never doomed its dying day to see;\nBut those as well that will in future age\nEverywhere beautify fair Italy,\nMade fashion in their well-known form and mien;\nAs eight that round this fount by thee are seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What time the damsel ripe for husband shows,\nSo that the fruit may now be gathered, I\n(Did chance or my misfortune so dispose?)\nAm worthiest found; and those broad lands that lie\nWithout the walls which that fair town enclose,\n— The fishy flat no less than upland dry —\nExtending twenty miles about that water,\nHe gives me for a dowry, with his daughter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She was so mannered, was so fair of hue,\nNone could desire she other gifts should bring;\nSo well to broider was she taught, and sew,\nMinerva knew not better; did she sing,\nOr play, or walk, to those that hear and view,\nShe seems a heavenly, and no mortal thing;\nAnd in the liberal arts was skilled as well\nAs her own sire, or scarce behind him fell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With genius high and beauty no less bright,\nWhich might have served the very stones to move,\nSuch love, such sweetness did the maid unite,\nThinking thereof meseems my heart is clove.\nShe had no greater pleasure or delight\nThan being with me, did I rest or rove.\nTwas long ere we had any strife; in fine\nWe quarrelled; and the fault, alas!  was mine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Five years my consort's father had been dead,\nSince to that yoke I stooped, and pledged my vow;\nWhen in short time (the manner shall be said)\nBegan the sorrows that I feel even now.\nWhile me with all his pinions overspread\nLove of the dame, whose praises thus I blow,\nA noble townswoman with love of me\nWas smit; more sorely smitten none could be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She, in all magic versed, was of such skill\nAs never was enchantress; by her say\nMoved solid earth, and made the sun stand still,\nIllumined gloomy night and darkened day:\nYet never could she work upon my will,\nWith salve I could not give, except with scathe\nOf her to whom erewhile I pledged my faith."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not because she right gentle was and bright,\nNor because I believed her love so true,\nNor for large gift, nor promise often plight,\nNor yet because she never ceased to sue,\nCould she from me obtain one spark of light\nFrom that first flame my gentle consort blew:\nSo mates and masters every will in me\nThe knowledge of my wife's fidelity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I in the hope, belief, and certitude\nMy wife to me was faithful evermore,\nShould with contempt the beauty have eschewed\nOf that famed daughter which fair Leda bore;\nAnd all the wit and wealth wherewith was wooed\nThe illustrious shepherd upon Ida hoar.\nBut no repulse withal with her avails,\nWho me, for ever at my side, assails."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"One day that me beyond my palace sees\nThat weird enchantress, who Melissa hight,\nAnd where she can discourse with me at ease,\nShe finds a way whereby my peace to blight;\nAnd, goading me with evil jealousies,\nThe faith I nursed at heart, she puts to flight.\nShe 'gan commending my intent to be\nFaithful to her who faithful was to me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `But that she faithful is, ye cannot say,\nSave of her faith ye have assurance true;\nIf she fails not withal, where fail she may,\nShe faithful, modest may be deemed by you:\nBut is she never from your side away,\nIs not permitted other man to view,\nHow does this boldness come, that you would be\nThe warrant of her untried modesty?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Go forth awhile; go forth come from home alone;\nAnd be the bruit in town and village spread\nThat she remains behind, and you are gone;\nLet lovers and let couriers have their head:\nIf, unpersuaded still by prayer and boon,\nShe does no outrage to the marriage bed;\nThough doing so she deem herself unseen,\nThen faithful you the dame may justly ween.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I with such words and such-like words was plied,\nTill so on me the shrewd enchantress wrought,\nI wished to see my consort's virtue tried\nBy certain proof, and to the touchstone brought.\n— `Now grant we (I to that witch-lady cried)\nShe prove what cannot by myself be thought,\nHow by some certain token can I read\nIf she will merit punishment or meed?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `A drinking-cup will I for that assay\nGive you (she said of virtue strange and rare: ) \n\nSuch was for Arthur made by Morgue the fay,\nTo make him of Genevra's fault aware.\nThe chaste wife's lord thereof may drink; but they\nDrink not, whose wedded partners wanton are:\nFor, when they would the cordial beverage sup,\nInto their bosom overflows the cup."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Below departing, you the test shall try,\nAnd, to my thinking, now shall you drink clean;\nFor clean as yet I think your consort, I:\nThe event however shall by you be seen.\nYet will I warrant not your bosom dry,\nShould you repeat the proof; for if, between\nThe cup and lip, the liquor be not shed,\nYou are the happiest wight that ever wed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The offer I accept, the vase to me\nIs given, and trial made with full success;\nFor hitherto (as hoped confirmed I see ) \n\nMy gentle consort's worth and faithfulness.\n'Leave her awhile (Melissa said), and be\nA month or twain a truant, more or less:\nThen homeward wend; again the goblet fill;\nAnd prove if you the beverage drink or spill.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I thought it hard to leave my consort's side;\nNot as so much about her truth in pain,\nAs that I could nor for two days abide,\nNay, not an hour without her could remain.\n`— You in another way (Melissa cried)\nGuided by me, the truth shall ascertain;\nVoice, vesture shall you change; and to her sight\nPresent yourself, disguised like other wight.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sir, a fair city nigh at hand, defends\nTwixt fierce and threatening horns the foaming Po;\nWhose jurisdiction to the shore extends,\nWhere the sea's briny waters come and go:\nThis yields in ancientry, but well contends\nWith neighbouring towns in rich and gorgeous show:\nA Trojan remnant its foundations placed,\nWhich scaped from Attila's destructive waste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"A rich, a youthful, and a handsome knight\nBridles this city with his sovereign sway;\nWho, following a lost falcon in its flight,\nEntering by chance my dwelling on a day,\nBeheld my wife, who pleased him so at sight,\nHe bore her impress in his heart away;\nNor ceased to practise on her, with intent\nTo incline the matron to his evil bent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So often she repels the cavalier\nThat finally his courtship is foregone;\nBut her fair image graved by Love will ne'er\nBe razed from memory; me Melissa won\n(So well she soothed and flattered of that peer ) \n\nThe face and figure to the sight to don;\nAnd changed me — nor well how can I declare —\nIn voice and visage and in eyes and hair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I, having to my lady made a show\nAs eastward bound and gone, — like him that wooed,\nHer rich and youthful lover, altered so,\nHis semblance, attended by Melissa, go,\nInto a page upon her side transmewed;\nWho the most costly jewels with her bore\nE'er brought form Ind, or Erithraean shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I enter safely, that my palace knew,\nAnd with me wends Melissa; and there I\nSo wholly at her ease Madonna view,\nNo woman or attendant squire is by.\nTo her with suppliant prayer forthwith I sue,\nAnd next those goads to evil deed apply;\nShow emerald, ruby, diamond, that might serve;\nTo make the firmest heart from honour swerve;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And I declare to her the gift is small\nTo that, which she may hope to make her own;\nThen of the vantage speak, that from his hall\nHer husband at the present time is gone;\nAnd I how long it was to her recall,\nSince, as she knew, to her my love was shown;\nAnd that my loving with such faith, in the end\nMight worthily to some reward pretend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"At first she was somedeal disturbed; became\nLike scarlet; nor would listen to my say;\nBut seeing those bright jewels flash like flame,\nHer stubborn heart was softened, and gave way;\nAnd in brief speech and feeble said the dame\nWhat to remember takes my life away:\nShe with my wishes, said, she would comply,\nIf sure to be unseen of watchful eye."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Me my wife's words like poisoned weapon thrill,\nAnd pierce my suffering spirit through and through:\nThrough bones and veins there went a deadly chill;\nMy tongue clave to my throat: The witch withdrew\nWith that the magic mantle, and at will\nTransformed me to mine ancient shape anew.\n— Bethink thee of what hue my wife became,\nTaken by me in such notorious shame!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Of deadly hue we both of us remain;\nWe both stand silent; both with downcast eye.\nSo feeble is my tongue, that I with pain,\nSo faint my voice, that I with pain can cry;\n'Thou wouldst betray me then, O wife, for gain,\nIf there was one that would my honour buy!'\nShe nought replies; nor save by tears she speaks,\nWhich furrow, as they fall, her woeful cheeks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Shame stings her sore, but yet in sorer wise\nWrath at the outrage I to her had done;\nAnd so without restraint it multiplies,\nAnd into rage and cruel hate is run,\nTo fly from me forthwith does she devise;\nAnd, what time from his car dismounts the sun,\nRuns to the shore, aboard her pinnace wends,\nAnd all that night the stream in haste descends;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And she at morn presents herself before\nHim that had loved her once, the cavalier,\nWhose semblance and whose borrowed face I wore\nWhen, to my shame, I tempted her whilere.\nTo him that loved, and loves her evermore,\nHer coming, it may be believed, is dear.\nFrom thence she bade me never entertain\nThe hope she'd love me or be mine again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alas!  with him she swells in mickle glee\nEven from that day, and makes of me a jest;\nAnd of that evil which I brought on me\nI languish yet, and find no place of rest.\nJustly this growing ill my death will be,\nOf little remnant now of life possest.\nI well believe I in a year had died,\nBut that a single comfort aid supplied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That comfort was; of all which harboured were\nHere for ten years (for still to every guest\nBeneath my roof I bade the vessel bear)\nWas none but with the wine had bathed his breast.\nTo have so many comrades in my care,\nSome little soothes the griefs that so molest.\nThou only of so many hast been wise,\nWho wouldst forbear the perilous emprize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My wish, o'erpassing every fitting bound,\nTo know what husband of his wife should know,\nIs cause, by me no quiet will be found,\nWhether my death be speedy of be slow.\nThereat at first Melissa joys; but drowned\nForthwith is her light mirth; for of my woe\nEsteeming her the cause, that dame so sore\nI hated, I would not behold her more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Impatient to be treated with disdain\nBy me, — of her more loved than life, she said -\nWhere she forthwith as mistress to remain\nHad hoped, when thence the other was conveyed,\n— Not to behold such present, cause of pain,\nHer own departure little she delayed;\nAnd went so far away, no further word\nBy me was ever of that woman heard.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His tale the mournful cavalier so taught;\nAnd when he now had closed his history,\nWith pity touched, somewhile immersed in thought\nRinaldo mused, and after made reply:\n\"Right ill advice to thee Melissa brought,\nWho moved three thus to anger wasps; and I\nPerceive in thee small wisdom, that wouldst sound\nA thing which thou wouldst gladly not have found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If she, thy wife, by avarice was inclined\nTo break her faith and be to thee untrue,\nMuse not: nor first nor last of womankind,\nShe, worsted, from such cruel war withdrew;\nAnd by a meaner bribe yet firmer mind\nIs even tempted fouler deed to do.\nOf men, of how many we hear, that sold\nTheir patrons and their friends for sordid gold?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With such fierce arms thou ill didst her assail,\nIf to behold a brave defence thou sought.\nKnowst thou not, against gold of no avail\nIs stone, or steel to hardest temper wrought?\nMeseems that thou in tempting her didst fail\nMore than herself, that was so quickly caught.\nI know not, had she tempted thee as much,\nIf thou, thyself, hadst better stood the touch.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here ends Rinaldo, and — the parley done —\nRises and to his rest desires to go:\nAwhile will he repose; and then be gone,\nAn hour or two before the daylight show.\nBut little time has Aymon's warlike son;\nNor idly will that little time bestow.\nTo him the mansion's master made reply,\nHe in his house might at his pleasure lie."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For bed and bower, within, were ready dight;\nBut — would he take his counsel for his guide —\nIn comfort might he sleep throughout the night.\nAnd yet advance some miles; \"For thou,\" he cried,\n\"Shalt have a pinnace, that with rapid flight\nAnd without risque shall with the current glide.\nTherein shalt thou all night pursue thy way,\nAnd on thy journey gain withal a day.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Good seemed that proffer in Rinaldo's eyes,\nAnd to the courteous host large thanks he paid;\nThen for the pinnace which that lord supplies,\nThat waits him with her crew, the warrior made.\nHere, at full ease reclined, Rinaldo lies,\nWhile with the stream his frigate is conveyed;\nWhich, by six oars impelled, flies fast and fair,\nAnd cleaves the water, as a bird the air."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as he reclines his weary head,\nAsleep is Mount Albano's cavalier;\nHaving erewhile that they shall wake him, said,\nAs soon as they Ferrara's city near.\nMelara lies left of that river's bed,\nSermide to the right; they in their rear\nNext leave Stellata and Figarolo,\nWhere his two horns are lowered by angry Po."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of those two horns that which t'ward Venice goes\nRinaldo's pilot left, and took the right;\nThen the Bodeno past.  Already shows\nFaintly the eastern blue, and fades from sight;\nFor now Aurora from her basket throws\nAll her rich flowers, and paints it red and white;\nWhen viewing the two castles of Tealdo,\nAgain his head uplifts the good Rinaldo."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O happy town!  whereof\" (the warrior cried)\n\"Spake Malagigi, having, far and near,\nThe fixt and wandering fires of heaven espied,\nAnd forced some subject spirit to appear,\nTo me foretelling that in future tide,\n— What time with him I took his way whilere —\nEven to such pitch thy glorious fame should rise,\nThou from all Italy wouldst bear the prize.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, in his barge he all this while\nHurries, as if the bark with pinions flew,\nScowering the king of rivers, to that isle\nNearest the town; and, though it not to view\n(Deserted and neglected then doth smile, ) \n\nThis yet rejoices to behold anew;\nNor makes small mirth thereat; because aware\nHereafter how adorned 'twill be and fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Before when he with him that way had gone,\nFrom Malagigi, his cousin, did he hear\nThat when seven hundred times his course had run,\nCircling the heaven in Aries, the fourth sphere,\nOf islands this should be the fairest one\nIn sea, or pool, or river, far and near,\nSo that who this beheld, would brook no more\nTo hear that praised which fair Nausicaa bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He heard, it in fair mansions would outdo\nThat island which Tiberius held so dear;\nAnd trees that in Hesperian gardens grew\nWould yield to what this beauteous place should bear;\n— So rare its race of beasts — no fairer shew\nHerded or housed erewhile by Circe were;\nVenus with Loves and Graces there should sport,\nNor more in Gnide and Cyprus keep her court;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And so would flourish through his study and care,\nWho will with knowledge and with power should blend;\nAnd who so safely should that bright repair\nWith circling wall and sheltering dyke defend,\nThe united world's assault it well might dare,\nNor call on foreign power its aid to lend;\nAnd that Duke Hercules' sire and Hercules' son\nWas he by whom this marvel should be done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So wends the warrior summing in his mind\nWhat erst to him had told his cousin wise;\nWhat time the sage of future things divined,\nWhereof with him he often wont devize;\nAnd aye contemplating that city blind,\n\"How can it ever be,\" Rinaldo cries,\n\"That in all liberal and all worthy arts\nShall flourish so these waste and watery parts?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And that to city of such amplitude\nAnd beauty such a petty burgh should grow,\nAnd where but marsh and miry pool is viewed,\nHenceforth should full and fruitful harvests glow?\nEven now I rise, to hail the gentle blood,\nThe love, the courtesy thy lords shall show,\nO thou fair city, in succeeding years;\nThy burghers' honours and thy cavaliers'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The grace ineffable of powers above,\nThy princes' wisdom and their love of right,\nShall with perpetual peace, perpetual love\nPreserve thee in abundance and delight;\nAnd a defence from all the fury prove\nOf such as hate thee; and unmask their spite.\nBe thy content thy neighbours' wide annoy,\nRather than thou shouldst envy other's joy!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "While thus Rinaldo speaks, so swiftly borne\nBy the quick current flies that nimble yawl;\nNot to the lure more swiftly makes return\nThe falcon, hurrying at his lord's recall.\nThenceforth the right-hand branch of the right horn\nRinaldo takes; and hid are roof and wall:\nSt. George recedes; recede from that swift boat\nThe turrets OF GAIBANA and OF THE MOAT."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Montalban's martial lord (as it befell,\nThat thought moved thought, which others moved again)\nIn memory chances on the knight to dwell,\nThat him at supper late did entertain;\nThat, through this city's cause, the truth to tell,\nHath reason evermore to be in pain;\nAnd of the magic vessel him bethinks\nWhich shows his consort's guilt to him that drinks;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And him bethinks therewith of what the knight\nRelated; how of all that he had tried,\nWho of his goblet drank, there was no wight\nBut split the wine he to his lips would guide.\nNow he repents him; now, \"'Tis my delight,\"\n(Mutters \"that I the proof would not abide: ) \n\nSucceeding I should prove but what I thought;\nAnd not succeeding, to what pass am brought!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This my belief I deem a certainty;\nAnd faith could have but small increase in me:\nSo, if I this should by the touchstone try,\nMy present good would little bettered be:\nBut small the evil would not prove, if I\nSaw of my Clarice what I would not see.\nThis were a thousand against one to stake;\nTo hazard much where I could nothing take.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The knight of Clermont buried in this mood,\nWho lifted not his visage from the floor,\nA mariner with much attention viewed,\nThat overright was seated at his oar;\nAnd, for he deemed he fully understood\nThe thought that prest the cavalier so sore,\nMade him (well-spoken was the man and bold)\nWake from his muse, some talk with him to hold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The substance of the talk between the two\nWas, that the husband little wit possest,\nWho, wishing to assay if she was true,\nHad tried his wife by too severe a test:\nFor woman, proof to gold and silver, who,\nArmed but with modesty, defends her breast,\nThis from a thousand faulchions will defend\nMore surely, and through burning fires will wend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The mariner subjoined: \"Thou saidest well;\nWith gifts so rich he should not her have prest;\nFor, these assaults, these charges, to repel,\nNot good alike is every human breast.\nI know not if of wife thou has heard tell\n(For haply not with us the tale may rest)\nThat in the very sin her husband spied,\nFor which she by his sentence should have died."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My lord should have remembered, gold and meed\nHave upon every hardest matter wrought:\nBut he forgot this truth in time of need;\nAnd so upon his head this ruin brought,\nAh!  would that he in proof, like me, a deed\nDone in this neighbouring city had been taught,\nHis country and mine own; which lake and fen,\nBrimming with Mincius' prisoned waters, pen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I of Adonio speak, that in a hound\nA treasure on the judge's wife conferred.\"\n\"Thereof,\" replied the paladin, \"the sound\nHath not o'erpast the Alps; for never word\nOf this neighbouring France, nor in my round\nThrough far and foreign countries have I heard:\nSo tell, if telling irks not,\" said the peer,\n\"What willingly I bown myself to hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The boatman then: \"Erewhile was of this town\nOne Anselm, that of worthy lineage came;\nA wight that spent his youth in flowing gown,\nStudying his Ulpian: he of honest fame,\nBeauty, and state assorting with his own,\nA consort sought, and one of noble name:\nNor vainly; in a neighbouring city, crowned\nWith superhuman beauty, one he found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She such fair manners and so graceful shows,\nShe seems all love and beauty; and much more\nPerchance than maketh for her lord's repose;\nThen well befits the reverend charge he bore.\nHe, wedded, strait in jealousy outgoes\nAll jealous men that ever were before:\nYet she affords not other cause for care\nBut that she is too witty and too fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"In the same city dwelt a cavalier,\nNumbered that old and honoured race among,\nSprung from the haughty lineage, which whilere\nOut of the jaw-bone of a serpent sprung:\nWhence Manto, doomed my native walls to rear,\nDescended, and with her a kindred throng.\nThe cavalier (Adonio was he named)\nWas with the beauties of the dame inflamed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And for the furtherance of his amorous quest,\nTo grace himself, began his wealth to spend,\nWithout restraint, in banquet and in vest,\nAnd what might most a cavalier commend:\nIf he Tiberius' treasure had possest,\nHe of his riches would have made an end.\nI well believe two winters were not done,\nEre his paternal fortune was outrun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The house erewhile, frequented by a horde\n— Morning and evening — of so many friends,\nIs solitary; since no more his board\nBeneath the partridge, quail, and pheasant bends.\nOf that once noble troop upon the lord,\nSave beggars, hardly any one attends.\nRuined, at length he thinks he will begone\nTo other country, where he is unknown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He leaves his native land with this intent,\nNor letteth any his departure know;\nAnd coasts, in tears and making sad lament,\nThe marshes that about his city go:\nHe his heart's queen, amid his discontent,\nMeanwhile forgets not, for this second woe.\nLo!  him another accident that falls,\nFrom sovereign woe to sovereign bliss recalls!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He saw a peasant who with heavy stake\nSmote mid some sapling trunks on every side:\nAdonio stopt, and wherefore so he strake,\nAsked of the rustic, that in answer cried,\nWithin that clump a passing ancient snake,\nAmid the tangled stems he had espied:\nA longer serpent and more thick to view\nHe never saw, nor thought to see anew;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And that from thence he would not wend his way\nUntil the reptile he had found and slain,\nWhen so Adonio heard the peasant say,\nHe scarce his speech with patience could sustain,\nAye reverence to the serpent wont to pay,\nThe honoured ensign of his ancient strain;\nIn memory that their primal race had grown\nErewhile from serpent's teeth by Cadmus sown;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And by the churl the offended knight so said,\nAnd did withal, he made him quit the emprize;\nLeaving the hunted serpent neither dead,\nNor injured, nor pursued in further wise.\nThither, where he believes would least have spread\nThe story of his woe, Adonio hies;\nAnd in discomfort and in sorrow wears,\nFar from his native land, seven weary years."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Neither for distance nor for straitened cheer,\nWhich will not let Thought run its restless round,\nCeased Love, so wont to rein the cavalier,\nAye to inflame his heart, aye vex his wound:\nAt length those beauties, to his eyes so dear,\nParforce must he revisit, homeward bound.\nUnshorn, afflicted, he, in poor array,\nThither returns, from whence he went his way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My city, at the time whereof I tell,\nTo Rome was fain to send an embassy;\nThat sometime near his holiness should dwell;\nAnd for how long a time could none foresee.\nUpon our judge the lot of envoy fell:\nO day, that ever wept by him will be!\nTo be excused, Anselmo promised, prayed,\nAnd bribed; but at the last parforce obeyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As no less cruel and less hard to abide\nHe deemed a woe which caused such piteous smart,\nThan had he seen a hostile hand his side\nLay bare, and from his bosom pluck his heart:\nDead-white with jealous fear his cheek is dyed,\nThrough doubt of his fair consort while apart;\nAnd in the mode he deems may best avail,\nHe supplicates her not in faith to fail,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor beauty, to his wife the husband cries,\nNor noble blood, nor fortune, are enow\nTo make a woman to true honour rise,\nSave chaste in name and deed; subjoining how\nThe virtue that mankind most highly prize\nIs that which triumphs after strife; and now\nThrough his long absense, a fair field and wide\nIs opened where that virtue may be tried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"With such persuasions, and with many more\nAnselm exhorts the lady to be true.\nHis going doth his woful wife deplore.\nO heaven, what tears, what loud complaints ensue!\nImmersed in her despair, that lady swore,\nSooner the sun bedimmed the world should view\nThan she would break her faith; she would expire\nSooner than she would cherish such desire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Though to the lady's promise and protest\nHe lent belief, and somewhat calmed his fears,\nUntil he further hear he will not rest;\nAnd till he can find matter for his tears,\nA soothsayer he among his friends possest,\nPrized for his knowledge, as the first of seers;\nWho of all witchery and of magic art\nHad read the whole, or read the greater part."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To him before departing does he pray,\nTo take the charge upon himself to see\nIf true would be Argia while away\n(So name his consort), or the contrary.\nWon by his prayers, he takes the time o' the day;\nFigures the heavens as they appear to be.\nAnselmo left him at his work, and came\nHis answer on the following day to claim."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The astrologer is silent, loath to expose\nA matter that will work the doctor woe;\nAnd would excuse himself with many a gloze:\nBut when he sees, he would the evil know,\nArgia will break faith with him, he shows,\nAs soon as he shall from his threshold go.\nNor prayer shall soften her, nor beauty fire:\nCorrupted will she be by gain and hire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"When to Anselmo's early doubt and fear\nAre joined the threatnings of the signs above,\nHow stands his heart may well to thee appear,\nIf thou hast known the accidents of love;\nAnd worse than every woe, wherewith whilere\nThe afflicted spirits of that husband strove,\nIs that it by the prophet is foretold,\nArgais' honour will be bought and sold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Now to support his wife, as best he may,\nFrom falling into such an evil deed.\nFor man, alas, will sometimes disarray\nThe altar, when he finds himself in need,\nWhat gold and gems the judge had put away,\n(A plenteous store he leaves; and field and mead, ) \n\nRents, fruits, and all possessions whatsoe'er\nLeaves to his consort; all his worldly gear:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `With power,' he said, `not only without measure,\nThese, as thou needest, to enjoy and spend,\nBut do with them according to thy pleasure,\nConsume and fling away, and give and vend:\nOther account I ask not of my treasure,\nIf such as now I find thee in the end;\nBut such as now remain; — at thy command\n(Even shouldst thou squander both are house and land.' )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Unless she heard he thither made repair,\nHe prayed that she would dwell not in the town;\nBut would a farm of his inhabit, where\nShe might with all convenience live alone.\nAnd this besought he of his consort fair,\nAs thinking, that the rustics, which on down\nPasture their flocks, or fruitful fallows till,\nCould ne'er contaminate her honest will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Her fearful husband still embracing close,\nHer arms about his neck Argia threw:\nA burst of tears her visage overflows:\nFor from her eyes two streams their way pursue.\nShe grieves, he guilty should his wife suppose;\nAs if she hath already been untrue:\nFor his suspicion to its source she traced;\nThat in her faith no faith Anselmo placed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Citing their long farewell, I should exceed.\n`— To thee at length,' he so the dame addrest,\n`I recommend my honour'; — and indeed\nTook leave, and on his road in earnest prest;\nAnd truly felt, on wheeling round his steed,\nAs if his heart was issuing from his breast.\nShe follows him as long as she can follow\nWith eyes whose tears her furrowed visage hollow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Poor, pale, unshorn, and wretched (as whilere\nTo you in former strain by me was said),\nHomeward meanwhile the wandering cavalier,\nHoping he there should be unknown, had made.\nBeside the lake that pilgrim journeyed, near\nThe city, where he gave the serpent aid,\nIn that thick brake besieged by village swain,\nWho with his staff the reptile would have slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Arriving here, upon the dawn of light,\nFor yet some stars were glimmering in the skies,\nApproaching him, in foreign vesture dight,\nAlong the shore, a damsel he espies.\nThough neither squire nor waiting wench in sight\nAppears, yet noble is the lady's guise.\nWith pleasing visage she Adonio boards,\nAnd then breaks silence in the following words."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Albeit thou know'st me not, O cavalier\nI am thy kin, and greatly bound to thee:\nI am thy kin; for of the lineage clear\nDerived of haughty Cadmus' seed are we.\nI am the fairy Manto, that whilere\nLaid the first stone of this rude villagery;\nAnd (as thou haply mayst have heard it famed)\nMantua from me the rising town was named."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `O' the fairies am I one: with that to show\nOur fatal state, and what it doth import;\nWe to all other kinds of ill below\nAre subject by our natal influence, short\nOf death; but with immortal being such woe\nIs coupled, death is not of direr sort.\nFor every seventh day we all must take\nBy certain law, the form of spotted snake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `So sad it is that loathsome coil to fill,\nAnd prone, at length, upon the ground to crawl;\nEqual to this here is no worldly ill;\nSo that immortal life is cursed by all.\nAnd thou the debt I owe thee (for my will\nIs to inform thee of its cause withal)\nShalt know as well; how on that fatal day\nOf change we are to countless ills a prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `So hated as the serpent beast is none;\nAnd we that wear its evil form, alarm,\nOutrage, and war endure from every one:\nFor all that see us, hunt and do us harm:\nUnless we can to ground for shelter run,\nWe feel how heavy falls man's furious arm.\nHappier it were to die, than languish — broke,\nBattered, and crippled by the cruel stroke."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `My mighty obligation due to thee\nIs that, when once thou didst this greenwood thread,\nThou from a rustic's fury rescuedst me,\nBy whose ill handling was I sore bested.\nBut for thine aid, I should not have got free,\nWithout a broken spine or battered head:\nWith body crooked and crushed I should have lain,\nAlbeit I could not by his arm be slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Because thou hast to know upon the day\nWe sprang from earth with scales of dragon dight,\n— Subject to us at other times — to obey\nThe heavens refuse; and we are void of might:\nAt other seasons, at our simple say\nThe circling sun stands still, and dims its light:\nFixt earth is moved, and in a circle wheels:\nIce at our word takes fire, and fire congeals."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Now here, prepared to render thee the meed\nOf benefit then done to me, I stand;\nFor now, dismantled of my dragon weed,\nVainly no grace of me wilt thou demand.\nEven now, thrice richer art thou by my deed,\nThan when thou heirdst erewhile thy father's land:\nNow will I that henceforth thou shalt be poor;\nBut wealth, the more 'tis spent, augment the more:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And because with that ancient knot thou still,\nI know, art tangled, which by Love was tied,\nThe mode and order, how thou mayst fulfil\nThy wishes, shall by me be signified.\nNow that her lord is absent, 'tis my will\nMy scheme without delay by thee be tried;\nGo forth the lady at her farm to find,\nWithout the town; nor will I say behind.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She her discourse continuing, 'gan advise\nWhat form he to that lady's eyes should take:\nI say, what vesture wear, and in what wise\nShould speak, how tempt her; what entreaties make:\nAnd said, how she her figure would disguise;\nFor, save the day wherein she was a snake,\nUpon all others went the fairy drest\nIn whatsoever figure pleased her best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"She in a pilgrim's habit clothed the knight,\nSuch as from door to door our alms entreat:\nInto a dog she changed herself to sight;\nThe smallest ever seen, of aspect sweet,\nLong hair, than ermine's fur more snowy white;\nAnd skilled withal in many a wondrous feat.\nTowards Agria's villa, so transmewed,\nThe fairy and the knight their way pursued;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And at the labourer's cabins in his round\nThe stripling halts, before he stops elsewhere;\nAnd certain rustic reeds begins to sound;\nHis dog is up, and dances to the air.\nThe dame, that hears the voice and cry rebound,\nIs by the rumour moved to see the pair.\nInto her court she has the pilgrim brought,\nAs Anselm's evil destiny had wrought:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And here Adonio gives the dog command;\nAnd here by that obedient dog is shown\nDance of our country and of foreign land,\nWith paces, graces, fashions of his own;\nAnd finally he does, amid that band,\nWith winning ways what else is to be done,\nWith such attention of the admiring crew,\nNone winked their eyes, their breath they scarcely drew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Great marvel in the dame, then longing, bred\nThat gentle dog: she one that her had nursed\nWith no mean offer to his master sped.\n— `If all the riches for which women thirst'\n(To her embassadress in answer said\nThe wary pilgrim `in my bags were pursued, ) \n\nThere is not in that treasure what would boot\nTo purchase of my dog one single foot':"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And he, the truth of his discourse to show,\nInto a corner took the beldam old,\nAnd bade the dog in courtesy bestow\nUpon that messanger a mark of gold.\nThe dog obeyed, and shook himself; and lo!\nThe treasure!  which he bade her have and hold:\nThereto he added, `Thinkest thou by ought\nA dog so fair and useful can be bought?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `For whatsoever I of him demand,\nI empty-handed never go away;\nNow pearl, now ring will he shake from him, and\nNow gift me with some rich and fair array.\nYet tell madonna he is at her command;\nBut not for gold; for him no gold can pay;\nBut if I for one night her arms may fill,\nHim may she take and do with him her will.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"So said, a gem, new-dropt, on her he prest,\nAnd bade her to the lady bear the boon.\nThat in the costly produce she possest\nTen, twenty ducats' value deemed the crone.\nShe bore the message to the dame addressed,\nAnd after wrought on her till she was won\nTo buy the beauteous dog, who might be bought\nBy payment of a prize which costeth nought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Argia somewhat coy at first appears;\nPartly that she her faith will not forego;\nPartly that she believes not all she hears\nThat beldam of the dog and pilgrim show.\nThe nurse insists, and dins into her ears,\nThat seldom such a chance occurs below;\nAnd makes her fix another day to see\nThat dog, when fewer eyes on her shall be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The next appearance which Adonio made\nWas ruin to the doctor; for the hound\nDoubloons, by dozens and by dozens, braid\nOf pearl, and costly jewels scattered round.\nSo that Argia's pride of heart was laid;\nAnd so much less the dame maintained her ground,\nWhen she in him, who made the proffer, viewed\nThe Mantuan cavalier that whilom wooed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The harlot nurse's evil oratory,\nThe prayer and presence of the suitor lord,\nThe occasion to acquire that mighty fee,\nWhich wretched Anselm's absence would afford,\nThe hope that none would her accuser be,\nSo vanquish her chaste thoughts, she makes the accord —\nAccepts the wondrous dog; and, as his pay,\nTo her leman yields herself a willing prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The fruits of love long culled that cavalier\nWith his lady fair; unto whom the fay\nTook such affection, whom she held so dear,\nThat she obliged herself with her to stay.\nThrough all the signs the sun had travelled, ere\nThe judge had leave to wend his homeward way.\nHe finally returned; but sore afraid\nThrough what the astrologer erewhile had said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Arrived, his first employment is to run\nTo that astrologer's abode, and crave,\nIf shame and evil to his wife be done;\nOf if she yet her faith and honor save.\nThe heavens he figured; and to every one\nOf the seven planets its due station gave;\nThen to the judge replied that it had been\nEven as he feared, and as it was foreseen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"By richest presents tempted to forego\nHer faith, a prey was she to other wight.\nThis to the doctor's heart was such a blow;\nNor lance, nor spear, I deem, so sorely smite.\nTo be more certified he wends (although\nHe is too well assured the seer is right)\nTo that old nurse; and, drawing her apart,\nTo learn the truth employs his every art."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He in wide circles doth about her wind,\nHoping now here, now there, to spy some trace:\nBut nought in the beginning can he find,\nWith whatsoever care he sifts the case.\nFor she, as not unpractised in that kind,\nDenies, and fronts him with untroubled face;\nAnd, as well taught, above a month stands out,\nHolding the judge 'twixt certainty and doubt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"How blest would doubt appear, had he that wound\nForeseen, which would be given by certainty!\nWhen out of that false nurse at last he found\nHe could not fish the truth by prayer or fee,\nTouching no chord but yielded a false sound,\nHe shrewdly waits his time till there should be\nDiscord between the beldam and his wife:\nFor whereso women are, is stir and strife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And even that Anselmo waited, so\nBefell; since, angered by the first despite,\nUnsought of him, to him that nurse did go,\nTo tell the whole; and nothing hid from sight.\nHow sank his heart beneath that cruel blow,\n'Twere long to say; how prostrate lay his sprite.\nSo was the wretched judge with grief opprest,\nHe of his wits well-nigh was dispossest;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And finally resolved to die, so burned\nHis rage, but first would kill the faithless dame;\nAnd he with one destructive faulchion yearned\nTo free himself from woe and her from shame.\nStung by such blind and furious thoughts, returned\nAnselmo to the city, in a flame;\nAnd to the farm despatched a follower true,\nCharged with the bidding he was bound to do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He bids the servant to the villa go,\nAnd to Argia in his name pretend,\nHe by a fever is reduced so low,\nShe hardly can arrive before his end.\nHence without waiting escort — would she show\nHer love — she with his man must backward wend,\n(Wend with him will she surely, nor delay)\nAnd bids him cut her throat upon the way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The serving man to call his lady went\nPrepared his lord's command on her to do.\nHaving her little dog at starting hent,\nShe mounted and began her journey, through\nThe dog advised of Anselm's ill intent,\nBut bid no less her purpose to pursue;\nFor he had taken thought for her; and aid\nShould in the time of peril be purveyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The servant from his pathway turns aside,\nAnd through bye-roads and solitary goes;\nPurposely lighting on a stream, whose tide\nFrom Apennine into our river flows;\nWhere, both of farm and busy city wide,\nA holt, and dark and dismal greenwood grows.\nSilent appeared the gloomy place, and one\nFitting the cruel deed which should be done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He drew his sword on her, and signified\nThe mandate by her angry husband given;\nThat so she might entreat, before she died,\nForgiveness of her every sin from Heaven.\nI know not how; she vanished from his side,\nWhen through her flank the blade he would have driven.\nVainly long time he seeks her, then remains\nFoiled and outscorned, for guerdon of his pains."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He all astound and with bewildered face,\nAnd full of shame, to seek his lord returns;\nWho from the servant that unwonted case,\nUnweeting how the thing had happened, learns;\nNor knows the fairy Manto fills a place\nAbout Argia, prompt to serve her turns.\nBecause the nurse, that all the rest revealed\n(I know not wherefore, I), had this concealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He knows not what to do: the outrage sore\nAvenged he has not, nor his pain allaid:\nWhat was a mote is now a beam; so sore\nIt prest him; on his heart so heavy weighed.\nSo plain is what was little known before,\nHe fears that it will shortly be displaid.\nAt first, he haply might have hid his woe;\nWhich Rumour now throughout the world will blow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Full well he wots, that since his evil vein\nHe to his wife, unhappy wretch!  hath shown,\nNot to be subject to his yoke again,\nShe to some strong protector will have flown;\nWho to his ignominy will maintain,\nAnd utter scorn, the lady as his own:\nAnd haply may she to some losel flee,\nWho will her paramour and pander be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For remedy, he sends in haste a band\nOf messengers, with letters far and nigh.\nSome of Argia here, some there demand;\nNor town unsearched is left in Lombardy.\nNext he in person goes; nor any land\nLeaves unexamined by himself or spy.\nYet cannot he discover means or way\nFor learning where concealed his consort lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The servant last he called on whom was laid\nThe ill hest, but who had served not his despite;\nAnd thither by his guidance was conveyed,\nWhere (as 'twas said she vanished from his sight; ) \n\nWho haply lurked by day in greenwood-shade,\nAnd to some friendly roof retired at night.\nHe thither guided, where but forest-trees\nHe thinks to find, a sumptuous palace sees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"This while for bright Argia in that part\nThe fay had made with speedy toil prepare\nAn alabaster palace by her art,\nGilded within, without, and everywhere.\nSo wonderful, no tongue could tell, no heart\nConceive, how rich within, without how fair:\nThat, which thou deemed so fair, my master's home,\nIs but a cottage to that costly dome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Curtain and cloth of arras deck the wall,\nSumptuously woven and in different wise,\nIn vaulted cellar and in littered stall;\nNot only spread in latticed galleries,\nNot only spread in lordly bower and hall.\nVase, gold and silver, gems of many dyes,\nCarved into cup and charger, blue, red, green,\nAnd countless cloths of silk and gold are seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"He chanced upon the costly dome (as I\nTo you was in my story making known)\nWhen he expected not a hut to spy,\nAnd but a weary waste of woodland lone.\nAs he beheld the dome with wondering eye,\nAnselmo thought his intellects were gone:\nThat he was drunk, or dreamed that wondrous sight\nHe weened, of that his wits had taken flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"An Aethiop woman posted at the door,\nWith blubber lip and nostril, he descries.\nNor will he see again, nor e'er before\nHad seen a visage of such loathsome guise:\nIll-favoured — such was Aesop feigned of yore:\nIf there, she would have saddened Paradise.\nGreasy and foul and beggarly her vest;\nNor half her hideousness have I exprest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Anselm, who saw no other wight beside\nTo tell who was that mansion's lord, drew nigh\nTo the Aethiopian, and to her applied;\nAnd she: `The owner of this house am I.'\nThe judge was well assured the negress lied,\nAnd made that answer but in mockery:\nBut with repeated oaths the negress swears;\n'Tis hers, and none with her the mansions shares;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And would he see the palace, him invites\nTo view it at his ease; and recommends\nIf there be ought within which him delights,\nTo take it for himself or for his friends.\nAnselmo hears, and from his horse alights,\nGives it his man; and o'er the threshold wends;\nAnd by the hag conducted, mounts from hall\nBelow to bower above, admiring all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Form, site, and sumptuous work doth he behold,\nAnd royal ornament and fair device;\nAnd oft repeats, not all this wide world's gold\nTo buy the egregious mansion wound suffice.\nTo him in answer said that negress old:\n'And yet this dome, like others, hath its prize;\nIf not in gold and silver, price less high\nThan gold and silver will the palace buy':"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And she to him prefers the same request,\nWhich erst Adonio to Argia made.\nA fool he deemed the woman and possest,\nWho for a boon so foul and filthy prayed.\nYet ceased she not, though more than thrice represt;\nAnd strove so well Anselmo to persuade,\nProffering, for his reward, the palace still,\nShe wrought on him to do her evil will."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The wife Argia, that is hid fast by,\nWhen in such sin her husband she descries,\nOf doctor, that was deemed so passing wise,\nSprings forth and saith: `Ah!  worthy deed!  which I\nFound in such foul and filthy work, espy!'\nBethink thee, if his kindling blushes rise;\nIf he stands mute!  why opens not thy hollow\nAnd central womb, O earth, the wretch to swallow?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"To clear herself and shame him, doth she stun\nAnselmo, never ceasing to upbraid.\n`What pain should by thyself be undergone\nFor this so filthy deed, (Argia said)\nIf thou would'st take my life for having done\nWhat Nature prompted and a lover prayed;\nOne that was fair and gentle, and who brought\nA gift, compared wherewith, this dome is nought?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `If worthy of one death thou deemest me,\nWorthy art thou a hundred deaths to die:\nAnd, though my pleasure might I do on thee,\nSo passing puissant in this place am I,\nNo other or worse vengeance done shall be\nUpon my side, on thy delinquency.\nThe give against the take, O husband, place;\nAnd, as 'twas granted thee, so grant me grace:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `And be there peace between us, and accord\nThat all be to forgetfulness consigned;\nNor thee I of thy fault by deed or word,\nNor me of mine, henceforward thou remind!'\nThis seemed a goodly bargain to her lord;\nNor to such pardon was he disinclined.\nThus peace and concord they at home restore,\nAnd love each other dearly evermore.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So said the mariner, and some brief fit\nOf laughter in Montalban's master stirred;\nAnd made his visage burn, as if 'twas lit\nWith fire, when of Anselmo's shame he heard.\nRinaldo greatly praised Argia's wit,\nWho by such quaint device had trapped that bird;\nWho fell into the net wherein the dame\nHerself erewhile had fallen, but with less shame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When the sun climbed a steeper road, the knight\nOrdered the board with food to be supplied,\nWhich the good Mantuan landlord overnight\nTook care with largest plenty to provide;\nWhile the fair town, upon the left, from sight\nRetired, and on the right that marish wide.\nArgenta is come and gone, with circling walls\nAnd stream into whose bed Santerno falls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then was not fair Bastia built, deem I,\nWhich little cause of boast affords to Spain\n(That there her banner has been raised on high),\nAnd causes deeper sorrow to Romagne.\nThence in strait line their bark, that seems to fly,\nTo the right shore the boatmen drive amain:\nNext through a stagnant channel make, that near\nRavenna brings by noon the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though oft of money he had small supply,\nThen was the knight so well bested, he made\nThe weary rowers, in his courtesy,\nA parting present, ere farewell was said.\nHere changing horse and guide, to Rimini\nRinaldo rode that very eye, nor stayed\nIn Montefiore till the night was done;\nAnd well nigh reached Urbino with the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Then Frederick was not there of gentle lore,\nNor was Elizabeth nor Guido good;\nFrancis Maria nor sage Leonore;\nWho would in courteous, not in haughty mood,\nHave forced so famed a paladin for more\nThan one short eye, with them to make abode;\nAs they long did, and do unto this day,\nBy dames and cavaliers who pass that way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since here none takes his rein, Rinaldo bends\nHis course an-end to Cagli; o'er the height,\nRifted by Gaurus and Metaurus, wends\nPast Apennine, no longer on his right,\nUmbri and Tuscans; and at Rome descends.\nFrom Rome to Ostia goes Montalban's knight:\nThence to the city sails; wherein a grave\nHis pious son to old Anchises gave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There changes back; and thence in haste he goes\nBound towards Lampedosa's island-shore,\nThat place of combat chosen by the foes,\nAnd where they had encountered Frank and Moor.\nRinaldo grants his boatmen no repose;\nThat do what can be done by sail and oar.\nBut with ill wind and strong the warrior strives;\nAnd, though by little, there too late arrives."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither he came what time Anglante's peer\nThe useful and the glorious deed had done;\nHad slain those paynim kings in the career,\nBut had a hard and bloody conquest won:\nDead was Sir Brandimart; and Olivier,\nDangerously hurt and sore, sate woe-begone,\nSomedeal apart, upon the sandy ground,\nMartyred and crippled by his cruel wound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From tears could not the mournful Count refrain,\nWhen brave Rinaldo he embraced, and said,\nHow in the battle Brandimart was slain.\nSuch love, such faith endeared the warrior dead.\nNor less Rinaldo's tears his visage stain\nWhen he so cleft beholds their comrade's head.\nThence to embrace bold Oliviero, where\nHe sits with wounded foot, he makes repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All comfort that he could he gave; though none\nCould good Rinaldo to himself afford;\nBecause he came but when the feast was done;\nYea after the removal of the board.\nThe servants wend to the demolished town,\nThere hide the bones of either paynim lord\nBeneath Biserta's ruined domes, and nigh\nAnd far, the fearful tidings certify."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the fair conquest won by Roland's blade,\nSansonet and Astolpho make great cheer;\nYet other mirth those warriors would have made\nHad Brandimart not perished; when they hear\nThat he is dead, their joy is so allayed\nThey can no more the troubled visage clear.\nWhich of them now the tidings of such woe\nTo the unhappy Flordelice shall show?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The night preceding that ill-omened day\nFlordelice dreamed the vest of sable grain\nThat she had made, her husband to array,\nAnd woven with her hand and worked with pain,\nBefore her eyes all sprinkled-over lay\nWith ruddy drops, in guise of pattering rain.\nThat she had worked it so the lady thought;\nAnd then was grieved at seeing what was wrought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And seemed to say, \"Yet from my lord have I\nCommand to make it all of sable hue;\nNow wherefore it is stained with other dye\nAgainst his will, in mode so strange to view?\"\nShe from that dream draws evil augury;\nAnd thither on that eve the tidings flew:\nBut these concealed Astolpho from the dame\nTill he to her with Sansonetto came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When they are entered, and she sees no show\nOf joyful triumphs, she, without a word,\nWithout a hint to indicate that woe,\nKnows that no longer living is her lord.\nWith that her gentle heart was riven so,\nAnd so her harassed eyes the light abhorred,\nAnd so was every other sense astound,\nThat, like one dead, she sank upon the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She in her hair, when life returns again,\nFastens her hand; and on her lovely cheeks,\nRepeating the beloved name in vain,\nWith all her force her scorn and fury wreaks;\nUproots and tears, her locks, and in her pain\nLike woman, smit by evil demon, shrieks,\nOr, as Bacchante at the horn's rude sound,\nErewhile was seen to run her restless round."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now to the one, to the other now her prayer\nShe made for knife, wherewith her heart to smite;\nNow she aboard the pinnace would repair\nThat brought the corse of either paynim knight,\nAnd would on either, lifeless as they were,\nDo cruel scathe, and vent her fierce despite.\nNow would she seek her lord, till at his side\nShe rested from her weary search, and died."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  wherefore, Brandimart, did I let thee\nWithout me wend on such a dire emprize?\nShe ne'er before did thy departure see,\nBut Flordelice aye followed thee,\" she cries:\n\"Well aided mightest thou have been by me;\nFor I on thee should still have kept my eyes;\nAnd when Gradasso came behind thee, I\nThee might have succoured with a single cry;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And haply I so nimbly might have made\nBetween you, that the stroke I might have caught,\nAnd with my head, as with a buckler, stayed:\nFor little ill my dying would have wrought.\nAnyhow I shall die; and — that debt paid —\nMy melancholy death will profit nought:\nWhen, had I died, defending thee in strife,\nI could not better have bestowed my life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Even is averse had been hard Destiny,\nAnd all heaven's host, when thee I sought to aid,\nAt least my tears had bathed thy visage, I\nShould the last kiss thereon, at least, have laid;\nAnd, ere amid the blessed hierarchy\nThy spirit mixt, `Depart' — I should have said —\n`In peace, and wait me in thy rest; for there,\nWhere'er thou art, I swiftly shall repair.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Is this, O Brandimart, is this the reign,\nWhose honoured sceptre thou wast now to take?\nWith thee to Dommogire, thy fair domain,\nThus went I; me thus welcome dost thou make?\nAlas!  what hope to-day thou renderest vain!\nAh!  what designs, fell Fortune, dost thou break!\nAh!  wherefore fear I, since a lot so blest,\nIs lost, to lose as well the worthless rest?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Repeating this and other plaint, so spite\nAnd fury waxed, that she in her despair\nMade new assault upon her tresses bright,\nAs if the fault was wholly in her hair:\nWildly her hands together doth she smite,\nAnd gnaw; with nails her lip and bosom tear.\nBut I return to Roland and his peers;\nWhile she bemoans herself and melts in tears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Roland with Olivier, who much requires\nSuch leech's care, his anguish to allay;\nAnd who, himself, some worthy place desires\nAs much, wherein Sir Brandimart to lay,\nSteers for the lofty mountain, that with fires\nBrightens the night, with smoke obscures the day.\nThe wind blows fair, and on the starboard hand,\nNot widely distant from them, lies that land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With a fresh wind, that in their favour blows,\nThey loose their hawser at the close of day:\nIn heaven above the silent goddess shows\nHer shining horn, to guide them on their way;\nAnd on the following morn before them rose\nThe pleasant shores that round Girgenti lay.\nHere Roland orders for the ensuing night\nAll that is needful for the funeral rite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He, when he saw his order duly done,\nAnd now the westering sun's fair light was spent.\nWith many nobles, who from neighbouring town,\nAt his invital, to Girgenti went,\n— The shore with torches blazing up and down,\nAnd sounding wide with cries and loud lament, —\nThither returned where late, of life bereft,\nHis friends, beloved in life and death, was left."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There stands Bardino, weeping o'er the bier,\nWho under Age's heavy burden bows;\nWho, in the tears on shipboard shed whilere.\nMight well have wept away his eyes and brows:\nUpbraiding skies and stars, the cavalier,\nLike lion, in whose veins a fever glows,\nRoars as he wreathes his wayward hands within\nHis hoary hair, and rends his wrinkled skin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon the paladin's return the cry\nRedoubled, and the mourning louder grew\nOrlando to the corse approached more nigh,\nAnd speechless stood awhile, his friends to view,\nPale, as at eve is the acanthus' dye\nOr lily's, which were plucked at morn: he drew\nA heavy sigh, and on the warrior dead\nFixing his stedfast eyes, the County said:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"O comrade bold and true, there here liest slain,\nAnd who dost live in heaven above, I know,\nRewarded with a life, thy glorious gain,\nWhich neither heat nor cold can take, my woe\nForgive, if thou beholdest me complain:\nBecause I sorrow to remain below,\nAnd not to share in such delights with thee;\nNot that thou art not left behind with me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alone, without thee, there is nought I may\nEver possess, without thee, that can please.\nIf still with thee in tempest and affray,\nAh wherefore not with thee in calm and ease?\nRight sore must be my trespass, since this clay\nWill not to follow thee my soul release.\nIf in thy troubles still I bore a burden,\nWhy am I not a partner of thy guerdon?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thine is the guerdon; mine the loss; thy gain\nIs single; but not single is my woe:\nPartners with me in sorrow are Almayne,\nAnd grieving France and Italy; and oh!\nHow will my lord and uncle, Charlemagne,\nHow will his paladins lament the blow!\nHow will the Christian church and empire moan,\nWhose best defence in thee is overthrown!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Oh!  how thy foes will by the death of thee\nBe freed henceforward from alarm and fear!\nAlas!  how strengthened paynimry will be!\nWhat hardiment will now be theirs!  what cheer!\nWhat of thy consort will become?  I see\nEven here her mourning, and her outcries hear.\nMe she accuses, haply hates, I know;\nIn that, through me, her every hope lies low."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet by one comfort, Flordelice, is followed\nHis loss, for us that reft of him remain:\nHis death, with such surpassing glory hallowed,\nTo die all living warriors should be fain.\nThose Decii; Curtius, in Rome's forum swallowed;\nCordus, so vaunted by the Grecian train;\nNot with more honour to themselves, with more\nProfit to others, went to death of yore.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These sad laments and more Orlando made;\nAnd all this while white friars, and black, and gray,\nWith other clerks, by two and two arrayed,\nBehind in long procession took their way;\nAnd they to God for the departed prayed,\nThat he would to his rest his soul convey.\nBefore and all about were torches reared,\nAnd changed to day the sable night appeared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They raise the warrior's bier, and ranged to bear\nBy turns that honoured weight were earl and knight.\nThe pall was purple silk, with broidery rare\nOf gold, and pearls in costly circles dight.\nThereon, of lordly work and no less fair,\nCushions were laid, with jewels shining bright.\nOn which was stretched the lifeless knight in view,\nArrayed in vest of like device and hue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A hundred men had past before the rest,\nAll taken from the poorest of the town;\nAnd in one fashion equally were drest\nThose beadsmen all, in black and trailing gown.\nA hundred pages followed them, who prest\nA hundred puissant steeds, for warfare bown;\nAnd by those pages backed, the portly steeds\nWent, sweeping wide the ground with sable weeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Banners in front and banners borne in rear,\nWhose fields with diverse ensignry is stained,\nUnfurled accompany the funeral bier;\nWhich from a thousand vanquished bands were gained,\nFor Caesar and for Peter's church whilere,\nBy that rare force, which now extinct remained.\nBucklers by other followers carried are,\nWon from good warriors, whose device they bear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By hundreds and by hundreds followed more,\nOrdained for different tasks, the steps of those;\nWho burning torches like those others bore.\nMantled, say rather closely muffled, goes\nRoland in sables next, and evermore\nHis eyes suffused and red with weeping shows.\nNor wears a gladder face Montalban's peer.\nAt home his wound detains Sir Olivier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The ceremonies would be long to say\nIn verse, wherewith Sir Brandimart was mourned;\nThe mantles, black or purple, given away;\nThe many torches which that eve were burned.\nWending to the cathedral, where the array\nPast on its road, were no dry eyes discerned:\nAll sexes, ages, ranks, in pitying mood\nGazed upon him so youthful, fair, and good."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He in the church was placed; and, when with vain\nLament the women had bemoaned the dead,\nAnd Kyrie Eleison, by the priestly train,\nAnd other holy orisons were said,\nIn a fair ark, upraised on columns twain,\nWas reared, with sumptuous cloth of gold o'erspread.\nSo willed Orlando; till he could be laid\nIn sepulchre of costlier matter made:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor out of Sicily the Count departs,\nTill porphyries he procures and alabasters,\nAnd fair designs; and in their several arts\nHas with large hire engaged the primest masters.\nNext Flordelice, arriving in those parts,\nRaises the quarried slabs and rich pilasters;\nWho, good Orlando being gone before,\nIs hither wafted from the Africk shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She, seeing that her tears unceasing flow,\nAnd that of long lament she never tires;\nNor she, for mass or service said, her woe\nCan ease, or satisfy her sad desires,\nVows in her heart she thence will never go\nTill from the wearied corse her soul expires;\nAnd builds in that fair sepulchre a cell;\nThere shuts herself; therein for life will dwell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither in person, having courier sent\nAnd letter, Roland goes, her thence to take;\nHer, would she wend to France, with goodly rent\nWould gift, and Galerana's inmate make;\nAs far as Lizza convoy her, if bent\nOn journeying to her father; for her sake\nIf wholly she to serve her God was willed,\nA monastery would the warrior build."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Still in that sepulchre she dwelt, and worn\nBy weary penance, praying night and day,\nIt was not long, ere by the Parcae shorn\nWas her life's thread: already on their way\nWere the three Christian warriors, homeward borne,\nSorrowing and afflicted sore in mind\nFor their fourth comrade who remained behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They would not go without a leech, whose skill\nMight ease the wound of warlike Olivier;\nWhich, as in the beginning it could ill\nBe salved, is hard to heal.  Meanwhile they hear\nThe champion so complain, his outcries fill\nOrlando and all that company with fear.\nWhile they discoursed thereon, the skipper, moved\nBy a new notion, said what all approved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A hermit not far distance hence, he said\nA lonely rock inhabits in this sea;\nWhose isle none, seeking succour, vainly tread,\nWhether for counsel or for aid it be:\nWho hath done superhuman deeds; the dead\nRestores to life; and makes the blind to see;\nHushes the winds; and with a sign o' the cross\nLulls the loud billows when they highest toss;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And adds they need not doubt, if they will go\nTo seek that holy man to God so dear,\nBut he on Olivier will health bestow;\nHaving his virtue proved by signs more clear.\nThis counsel pleases good Orlando so,\nThat for the holy place he bids him steer;\nWho never swerving from his course, espies\nThe lonely rock, upon Aurora's rise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CLXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Worked by good mariners, the bark was laid\nSafely beside the rugged rock and fell:\nThe marquis there, with crew and servants' aid,\nThey lowered into their boat; and through the swell\nAnd foaming waters in that shallop made\nFor the rude isle; thence sought the holy cell;\nThe holy cell of that same hermit hoar,\nBy whom Rogero was baptized before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The servant of the Lord of Paradise\nReceives Orlando and the rest on land;\nBlesses the company in cheerful wise;\nAnd after of their errand makes demand;\nThough he already had received advice\nFrom angels of the coming of that band.\nThat they were thither bound in search of aid\nFor Oliviero's hurt, Orlando said;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who, warring for the Christian faith, in fight\nTo perilous pass was brought by evil wound.\nAll dismal fear relieved that eremite,\nAnd promised he would make him wholly sound.\nIn that no unguents hath the holy wight,\nNor is in other human medicine found,\nHis church he seeks, his knee to Jesus bows,\nAnd issues from the fane with cheerful brows;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And in the name of those eternal Three,\nThe Father, and the Son, and Holy Ghost,\nOn Oliviero bade his blessing be.\nOh!  grace vouchsafed to faith!  his sainted host\nFrom every pain the paladin did free;\nAnd to his foot restored its vigour lost.\nHe moved more nimble than before, and sure;\nAnd present was Sobrino at the cure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sobrino, so diseased that he described\nHow worse with each succeeding day he grew,\nAs soon as he that holy monk espied\nThe manifest and mighty marvel do,\nDisposed himself to cast Mahound aside,\nAnd own in Christ a living God and true.\nHe, full of faith, with contrite heart demands\nOur holy rite of baptism at his hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So him baptized the hermit; and as well\nThat monarch made as vigorous as whilere.\nAt this conversion no less gladness fell\nOn Roland and each Christian cavalier,\nThan when, restored from deadly wound, and well\nThe friendly troop beheld Sir Olivier.\nRogero more rejoiced than all that crew;\nAnd still in faith and grace the warrior grew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero from the day he swam ashore\nUpon that islet, there had ever been.\nThat band is counselled by the hermit hoar,\nWho stands, benign, those warlike knights between,\nEschewing in their passage mire and moor,\nTo wade withal through that dead water, clean,\nWhich men call life; wherein so fools delight;\nAnd evermore on heaven to fix their sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Roland on shipboard sends one from his throng,\nWho fetches hence good wine, hams, cheese, and bread;\nAnd makes the sage, who had forgotten long\nAll taste of partridge since on fruits he fed,\nEven do for love, what others did, among\nThose social guests for whom the board was spread.\nThey, when their strength by food was reinforced,\nOf many things amid themselves discoursed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And as in talk it often doth befall\nThat one thing from another takes its rise,\nRoland and Olivier Rogero call\nTo mind for that Rogero, in such wise\nRenowned in arms; whose valour is of all\nLauded and echoed with accordant cries.\nNot even had Rinaldo known the knight\nFor him whose prowess he had proved in fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him well Sobrino recognized whilere,\nAs soon as with that aged man espied;\nBut he at first kept silence; for in fear\nOf some mistake the monarch's tongue was tied.\nBut when those others knew the cavalier\nFor that Rogero, famous far and wide,\nWhose courtesy, whose might and daring through\nThe universal world loud Rumor blew,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All, for they know he is a Christian, stand\nAbout him with serene and joyful face:\nAll press upon the knight; one grasps his hand;\nAnother locks him fast in his embrace:\nYet more than all the others of that band\nHim would Montalban's lord caress and grace:\nWhy more than all the others will appear\nIn other strain, if you that strain will hear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 44"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo his sister to the Child hath plight,\nAnd to Marseilles is with the warrior gone:\nAnd having crimsoned wide the field in fight,\nTherein arrives King Otho's valiant son.\nTo Paris thence: where to that squadron bright\nIs mighty grace and wonderous honour done.\nThe Child departs, resolved on Leo's slaughter,\nTo whom Duke Aymon had betrothed his daughter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In poor abode, mid paltry walls and bare,\nAmid discomforts and calamities,\nOften in friendship heart united are,\nBetter than under roof of lordly guise,\nOr in some royal court, beset with snare,\nMid envious wealth, and ease, and luxuries;\nWhere charity is spent on every side,\nNor friendship, unless counterfeit, is spied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hence it ensues that peace and pact between\nPrinces and peers are of such short-lived wear.\nTo-day king, pope, and emperor leagued are seen,\nAnd on the marrow deadly foemen are.\nBecause such is not as their outward mien\nThe heart, the spirit, that those sovereigns bear.\nSince, wholly careless as to right or wrong,\nBut to their profit look the faithless throng."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though little prone to friendship is that sort,\nBecause with those she loveth not to dwell,\nWho, be their talk in earnest or in sport,\nSpeak not, except some cozening tale to tell;\nYet if together in some poor resort\nThey prisoned are by Fortune false and fell,\nWhat friendship is they speedily discern;\nThough years had past, and this was yet to learn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In his retreat that ancient eremite\nCould bind his inmates with a faster noose,\nAnd in true love more firmly them unite,\nThan other could in domes where courtiers use;\nAnd so enduring was the knot and tight,\nThat nothing short of death the tie could loose.\nBenignant all the hermit found that crew;\nWhiter at heart than swans in outward hue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "All kind he found them, and of courteous lore;\nUntainted with iniquity, in wise\nOf them I painted, and who nevermore\nGo forth, unless concealed in some disguise.\nOf injuries among them done before\nAll memory, by those comrades buried lies:\nNor could they better love, if from one womb\nAnd from one seed that warlike band had come."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo more than all that lordly train\nRogero graced and lovingly caressed;\nAs well because be on the listed plain\nHad proved the peer so strong in martial gest,\nAs that he was more courteous and humane\nThan any knight that e'er laid lance in rest:\nBut much more; that to him on many a ground\nBy mighty obligation was he bound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The fearful risk by Richardetto run\nHe knew, and how Rogero him bested;\nWhat time the Spanish monarch's hest was done,\nAnd with his daughter he was seized in bed;\nAnd how he had delivered either son\nOf good Duke Buovo (as erewhile was said)\nFrom Bertolagi of Maganza's hand,\nHis evil followers, and the paynim band."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To honour and to hold Rogero dear,\nHim, Sir Rinaldo thought, this debt constrained;\nAnd that he could not so have done whilere,\nThe warlike lord was sorely grieved and pained;\nWhen one for Africk's monarch couched the spear,\nAnd one the cause of royal Charles maintained:\nNow he Rogero for a Christian knew,\nWhat could not then be done he now would do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Welcome, with endless proffers, on his side,\nAnd honour he to good Rogero paid.\nThe prudent sire that in such kindness spied\nAn opening made for more, the pass assayed:\n\"And nothing else remains,\" that hermit cried,\n\"Nor will, I trust, my counsel be gainsaid)\nBut that, conjoined by friendship, you shall be\nYet faster coupled by affinity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That from the two bright progenies, which none\nWill equal in illustrious blood below,\nA race may spring, that brighter than the sun\nWill shine, wherever that bright sun may glow;\nAnd which, when years and ages will have run\nTheir course, will yet endure and fairer show,\nWhile in their orbits burn the heavenly fires:\nSo me, for your instruction, God inspires.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And his discourse pursuing still, the seer\nSo spake, he moves Rinaldo by his rede\nTo give his sister to the cavalier;\nAlbeit with either small entreaties need.\nTogether with Orlando, Olivier\nThe counsel lauds, and would that union speed:\nKing Charles and Aymon will, he hopes, approve,\nAnd France will welcome wide their wedded love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So spake together peer and paladine:\nNor knew that Aymon, with King Charles' consent,\nUnto the Grecian emperor Constantine\nTo give his gentle daughter had intent;\nWho for young Leo, of his lofty line\nThe heir and hope, to crave the maid had sent.\nSuch warmth the praises of her worth inspired,\nWith love of her unseen was Leo fired."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him hath Aymon answered: he, alone,\nCannot conclude thereon in other sort,\nUntil he first hath spoken with his son,\nRinaldo, absent then from Charles's court;\nWho with winged haste, he deems, will thither run,\nAnd joy in kinsman of such high report;\nBut from the high regard he bears his heir,\nCan nought resolve till thither he repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now good Rinaldo, of his father wide,\nAnd of the imperial practice knowing nought,\nPromised his beauteous sister as a bride,\nUpon his own, as well as Roland's thought\nAnd the others, harboured in that cell beside;\nBut most of all on him the hermit wrought;\nAnd by such marriage, 'twas the peer's belief,\nHe could not choose but pleasure Clermont's chief."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That day and night, and of the following day\nGreat part, with that sage monk the warriors spent;\nScarce mindful that the crew their coming stay,\nAlbeit the wind blew fair for their intent,\nBut these, impatient at their long delay,\nMore than one message to the warriors sent;\nAnd to return those barons urged so sore,\nParforce they parted from the hermit hoar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Child who, so long banished, had not stayed\nFrom the lone rock, whereon the waters roared,\nHis farewell to that holy master made,\nWho taught him the true faith: anew with sword\nOrlando girt his side, and with the blade,\nFrontino and martial Hector's arms restored;\nAs knowing horse and arms were his whilere,\nAs well as out of kindness to the peer;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, though the enchanted sword with better right\nWould have been worn by good Anglantes' chief,\nWho from the fearful garden by his might\nHad won the blade with mickle toil and grief,\nThan by Rogero, who that faulchion bright\nReceived with good Frontino, from the thief,\nHe willingly thereof, as with the rest,\nAs soon as asked, the warrior repossest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The hermit blessings on the band implores:\nThey to their bark in fine return; their sails\nGive to the winds, and to the waves their oars;\nAnd such clear skies they have and gentle gales,\nNor vow nor prayer the patron makes; and moors\nHis pinnace in the haven of Marseilles.\nThere, safely harboured, let the chiefs remain,\nTill I conduct Astolpho to that train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When of that bloody, dear-brought victory\nThe scarcely joyful tale Astolpho knew,\nHe, seeing evermore fair France would be\nSecure from mischief from the Moorish crew,\nHomeward to send the king of Aethiopy\nDevised, together with his army, through\nThe sandy desert, by the self-same track,\nThrough which he led them to Biserta's sack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Erewhile restored, in Afric waters ride\nSir Dudon's ships which did the paynims rout;\nWhose prows (new miracle! and poop, and side, ) \n\nAs soon as all their sable crews are out,\nAre changed anew to leaves; which far and wide,\nRaised by a sudden breeze, are blown about;\nAnd scattered in mid-air, like such light gear,\nGo eddying with the wind, and disappear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Home, horse and foot, the Nubian host arraid\nBy squadrons, all, from wasted Africk go;\nBut to their king, first, thanks Astolpho paid,\nAnd said, he an eternal debt should owe;\nIn that he had in person given him aid\nWith all his might and main against the foe.\nThe skins Astolpho gave them, which confined\nThe turbid and tempestuous southern wind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I say, enclosed in skins that wind he gave,\nWhich in such fury blows at noon, on high\nI moves the shifting plain in many a wave,\nAnd fills the eddying sand the troubled sky,\nTo carry with them, and from scathe to save\nTheir squadrons, lest the dusty whirlwind fly;\nAnd bids them, when arrived at home, unnoose\nThe bladder's vent, and let their prisoners loose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When they have lofty Atlas passes won,\nThe horses that the Nubian riders bear,\nTurpin relates, are changed at once to stone;\nSo that the steeds return to what they were.\nBut it is time the Duke to France was gone;\nWho having thus provided, in his care,\nFor the main places in the Moorish land,\nMade the hippogryph anew his wings expand;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He reached Sardinia at one flight and shear,\nCorsica from Sardinia; and then o'er\nThe foaming sea his venturous course did steer,\nInclining somewhat left the griffin's soar.\nIn the sea-marshes last his light career\nHe stopt, on rich Provence's pleasant shore:\nWhere to the hyppogryph by him is done\nWhat was erewhile enjoined by sainted John."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To him the charge did sainted John commit,\nWhen to Provence by that winged courser borne,\nHim nevermore with saddle or with bit\nTo gall, but let him to his lair return.\nAlready had the planet, whither flit\nThings lost on earth, of sound deprived his horn:\nFor this not only hoarse but mute remained,\nAs soon as the holy place Astolpho gained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thence to Marseilles he came; and came the day\nOrlando, and Rinaldo, and Olivier\nArrived therein, upon their homeward way,\nWith good Sobrino, and the better peer,\nRogero: not so triumphs that array,\nTouched by the death of him, their comrade dear,\nAs they for such a glorious victory won\n— But for that sad disaster — would have done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of the kings slain upon the paynim part,\nThe news from Sicily to Charles were blown,\nSobrino's fate, and death of Brandimart;\nNor less of good Rogero had been shown.\nCharles stood with jocund fate and gladsome heart,\nRejoicing he had from his shoulders thrown\nThe intolerable load whereof the weight\nWill for long time prevent his standing straight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To honour those fair pillars that sustain\nThe state — the holy empire's corner-stone —\nThe nobles of his kingdom Charlemagne\nDispatched, to meet the knights, as far as Saone;\nAnd from his city with his worthiest train,\nKing, duke, and her, the partner of his throne,\nIssued amid a fair and gorgeous band\nOf noble damsels, upon either hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The emperor Charles with bright and cheerful brow,\nLords, paladins and people, kinsmen, friends,\nFair love to Roland and the others show.\nMongrana and Clermont's cry the welkin rends.\nNo sooner, mid that kind and festal show,\nThe interchange of fond embracements ends,\nThan Roland and his friends Rogero bring,\nAnd mid those lords present him to the king;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And him Rogero of Risa's son declare,\nAnd vouch in valour as his father's peer,\n\"Witnesses of his worth our squadrons are,\nThey best can tell his prowess with the spear.\"\nMeanwhile, the noble and the lovely pair,\nMarphisa and gentle Bradamant appear.\nThis runs to fold Rogero to her heart;\nMore coy, that other stands somedeal apart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The emperor bids Rogero mount again,\nWho from his horse had lit, in reverence due;\nAnd, side by side, with him his courser rein;\nNor aught omits that monarch which may do\nThe warrior honour, mid his martial train:\nHow the true faith he had embraced he knew;\nOf all instructed by that band before;\nWhen first those paladins set foot ashore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With pomp triumphal and with festive cheer\nThe troop returns within the city-walls:\nWith leaves and garlands green the streets appear,\nAnd tapestried all about with gorgeous palls.\nOf herbs and flowers a mingled rain, where'er\nThey wend, upon the conquering squadron falls,\nWhich with full hands from stand and window throw\nDamsel and dame upon the knights below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At every turn, in various places are,\nOf sudden structure arch and trophy high,\nWhereon Biserta's sack is painted fair,\nRuin and fire, and feat of chivalry:\nScaffolds, upraised for different sports elsewhere\nAnd merrimake and stage-play meet the eye;\nAnd, writ with truth, above, below, between,\nTo THE EMPIRE'S SAVIOURS, everywhere is seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With sound of shrilling pipe and trumpet proud,\nAnd other festive music, laughter light,\nApplause and favour of the following crowd,\nWhich scarce found room, begirt with dames and knight,\nThe mighty emperor, mid those greetings loud.\nBefore the royal palace did alight:\nWhere many days he feasted high in hall\nHis lords, mid tourney, mummery, mask and ball."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His son to Aymon on a day made known\nHis sister he would make Rogero's bride;\nAnd, before Olivier and Milo's son,\nHer to the Child by promise had affied;\nWho think with him that kindred is there none\nWherewith to league themselves, on any side,\nFor valour or nobility of blood,\nBetter than his; nay, none so passing good."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Duke Aymon heard his heir with some disdain;\nThat, without concert with him, and alone\nHe dared to plight his daughter, whom he fain\nWould marry to the Grecian emperor's son;\nAnd not to him that has no kingly reign,\nNay has not ought that he can call his own;\nAnd should not know, how little nobleness\nIs valued without wealth; how virtue less."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But Beatrice, his wife, with more despite\nArraigns her son, and calls him arrogant;\nAnd moves each open way and hidden sleight\nTo break Rogero's match with Bradamant;\nResolved to tax her every means and might\nTo make her empress of the wide Levant.\nFirm in his purpose is Montalban's lord,\nNor will in ought forego his plighted word."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beatrice who believes the highminded fair\nIs at her hest, exhorts her to reply,\nRather than she will be constrained to pair\nWith a poor knight, she is resolved to die;\nNor, if this wrong she from Rinaldo bear\nWill she regard her with a mother's eye:\nLet her refuse and keep her stedfast course;\nFor her free will Rinaldo cannot force."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Silent stands mournful Bradamant, nor dares\nMeanwhile her lady-mother's speech gainsay;\nTo whom such reverence, and respect, she bears,\nShe thinks no choice is left but to obey.\nYet a foul fault it in her eyes appears,\nIf what she will not do, she falsely say:\nShe will not, for she cannot; since above\nAll guidance, great or small, is mighty Love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Deny she dared not, nor yet seem content;\nSo, sighed and spake not; but — when uncontrolled\nShe could — she gave her secret sorrow vent,\nWhile from her eyes the tears like billows rolled;\nA portion of the pains that her torment,\nInflicting on her breast and locks of gold:\nFor this she beat, and those uptore and brake;\nAnd thus she made lament, and thus she spake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  shall I will what she wills not, by right\nMore sovereign mistress of my will than I?\nHers shall I hold so cheaply, so to slight\nA mother's will, my own to satisfy?\nAlas!  what blemish is so foul to sight\nIn damsel?  What so ill, as to affy\nMyself to husband, reckless of her will,\nWhich 'tis my duty ever to fulfil?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Wo worth the while!  and shall I then to thee\nBy filial love be forced to be untrue,\nO my Rogero, and surrender me\nTo a new hope, a new love, and a new\nDesire; or rather from those ties break free,\nFrom all good children to good parents due;\nObservance, reverence cast aside; and measure\nMy duty by my happiness, my pleasure?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I know, alas!  what I should do; I know\nThat which a duteous daughter doth behove;\nI know; but what avails it, if not so\nMy reason moves me as my senses move;\nIf she retires before a stronger foe;\nNor can I of myself dispose, for Love;\nNor think how to dispose; so strict his sway;\nNor, saving as he dictates, do and say?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Aymon and Beatrice's child, the slave\nOf Love am I; ah!  miserable me!\nI from my parents am in hope to have\nPardon and pity, if in fault I be:\nBut, if I anger Love, whose prayer shall save\nMe from his fury, till one only plea,\nOf mine the Godhead shall vouchsafe to hear;\nNor doom me dead as soon as I appear?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Alas!  with long and obstinate pursuit,\nTo our faith to draw Rogero have I wrought;\nAnd finally have drawn; but with what boot,\nIf my fair deed for other's good be wrought?\nSo yearly by the bee, whose labour's fruit\nIs lost for her, is hive with honey fraught.\nBut I will die ere I the Child forsake,\nAnd other husband than Rogero take."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If I shall not obey my father's hest,\nNor mothers, I my brother's shall obey,\nOf greater wisdom far than them possest;\nNor Time hath made that warrior's wit his prey;\nAnd what he wills by Roland is profest;\nAnd, one and the other, on my side are they;\nA pair more feared and honoured far and wide\nThan all the members of my house beside."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If them the flower of Clermont's noble tree,\nThe glory and the splendor all account;\nIf all believe our other chivalry\nThey, more than head o'ertops the foot, surmount;\nWhy would I Aymon should dispose of me,\nRather than good Rinaldo and the Count?\nI should not; so much less, as not affied\nTo Leo, and Rogero's promised bride.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If cruel thoughts the afflicted maid torment,\nRogero's mind enjoys not more repose;\nFor albeit those sad tidings have not vent\nYet in the city, he the secret knows.\nHe o'er his humble fortunes makes lament\nWhich his enjoying such a good oppose;\nAs unendowed with riches or with reign,\nDispensed so widely to a worthless train."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of other goods which Nature's hand supplies,\nOr which acquired by man's own study are,\nHe such a portion in himself espies,\nSuch and so large was never other's share:\nIn that, no beauty with his beauty vies;\nIn that, resistance to his might is rare.\nThe palm by none from him can challenged be,\nIn regal splendour, magnanimity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But they at whose disposal honours lie,\nWho give at will, and take away renown;\nThe vulgar herd; and from the vulgar I,\nExcept the prudent man, distinguished none;\nNor emperor, pope, nor king, is raised more high\nThan these by sceptre, mitre, or by crown,\nNor save by prudence; save by judgement, given\nBut to the favoured few by partial Heaven;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This vulgar (to say out what I would say)\nWhich only honours wealth, therewith more smit\nThan any worldly thing beside, nor they\nAught heed or aught esteem, ungraced with it,\nBe beauty or be daring what it may,\nDexterity or prowess, worth, or wit,\nOr goodness — yet more vulgar stands confest\nIn that whereof I speak than in the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero said: \"If Aymon is disposed\nAn empress in his Bradamant to see,\nLet not his treaty be so quickly closed\nWith Leo; let a year be granted me:\nIn that, meanwhile, I hope, by me deposed\nShall Leo with his royal father be,\nAnd I, encircled with their forfeit crown,\nShall be for Aymon no unworthy son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if he give without delay, as said,\nHis daughter to the son of Constantine,\nIf to that promise no regard be paid,\nWhich good Rinaldo and the paladine,\nHis cousin, erst before the hermit made,\nThe Marquis Olivier and King Sobrine,\nWhat shall I do?  such grievous wrong shall I\nEndure, or, rather than endure it, die?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What shall I do?  her father then pursue,\nOn whom for vengeance this grave outrage cries?\nI heed not that the deed is hard to do,\nOr if the attempt in me is weak or wise: —\nBut presuppose that, with his kindred crew\nSlain by my hand that unjust elder dies;\nThis will in nothing further my content;\nNay it will wholly frustrate my intent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\" `Twas ever my intent, and still 'tis so\nTo have the love, not hatred, of that fair;\nBut should I Aymon slay, or bring some woe\nBy plot or practice, on his house or heir,\nWill she not justly hold me as her foe,\nAnd me, that foeman, as her lord forswear?\nWhat shall I do, endure such injury?\nAh!  no, by Heaven!  far rather I will die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nay die I will not; but with better right\nShall Leo die, who so disturbs my joy;\nHe and his unjust sire; less dear his flight\nWith Helen paid her paramour of Troy;\nNor yet in older time that foul despite,\nDone to Proserpina, cost such annoy\nTo bold Pirithous, as for her I've lost\nMy grief of heart shall son and father cost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Can it be true, my life, that to forsake\nThy champion for this Greek should grieve not thee?\nAnd could thy father force thee him to take,\nThough joined thy brethren with thy sire should be?\nBut 'tis my fear that thou would'st rather make\nAccord withal with Aymon than with me;\nAnd that it seemeth better in thy sight\nTo wed with Caesar than with simple wight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Can it be true that royal name should blind,\nImperial title, pomp and majesty,\nAnd taint my Bradamant's egregious mind,\nHer mighty valour and her virtue high,\nSo that, as cheaper, she should cast behind\nHer plighted faith, and from her promise fly?\nNor sooner she a foe to Love be made,\nThan she no longer say, what once she said?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These things Rogero said, and more beside,\nDiscoursing with himself, and in such strain\nOftentimes the afflicted warrior cried,\nThat stander-by o'erheard the knight complain,\nAnd more than once his grief was signified\nTo her that was the occasion of his pain;\nWho no less for his cruel woe, when known,\nLamented than for sorrows of her own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But most, of all the sorrows that were said\nTo vex Rogero, most it works her woe\nTo hear that he afflicts himself, in dread\nLest for the Grecian prince she him forego.\nHence this belief, this error, from his head\nTo drive, comfort on the knight bestow,\nThe trustiest of her bower-women, one day,\nShe to Rogero bade these words convey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Rogero, I what I was till death will be;\nAnd be more faithful, if I can be more:\nDeals Love in kindness or in scorn with me;\nHath doubtful Fortune good or ill in store;\nI am a very rock of faith, by sea\nAnd winds unmoved, which round about it roar\nNor I have changed for calm or storm, nor I\nWill ever change to all eternity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Sooner shall file or chisel made of lead\nTo the rough diamond various forms impart,\nThan any stroke, by fickle Fortune sped,\nOr Love's keen anger, break my constant heart:\nSooner return, to Alp, their fountain-head,\nThe troubled streams that from its summit part,\nThan e'er, for change or chances, good or nought,\nShall wander from its way my stedfast thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"All power o'er me have I bestowed on you,\nRogero; and more than others may divine:\nI know that to a prince whose throne is new\nWas never fealty sworn more true than mine;\nNor ever surer state, this wide world through,\nBy king or keysar was possest than thine.\nThou need'st not dig a ditch nor build a tower,\nIn fear lest any rob thee of that power."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For if thou hire no aids, assault is none,\nBut what thereon shall aye be made in vain;\nNor shall it be by any riches won:\nSo vile a price no gentle heart can gain:\nNor by nobility, nor kingly crown,\nThat dazzle so the silly vulgar train;\nNor beauty, puissant with the weak and light,\nShall ever make me thee for other slight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou hast no cause, amid thy griefs, to fear\nMy heart should ever bear new impress more:\nSo deeply is thine image graven here,\nIt cannot be removed: that my heart's core\nIs not of wax is proved; for Love whilere\nSmote it a hundred times, not once, before\nHe by his blows a single scale displaced,\nWhat time therein his hand thine image traced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ivory, gem, and every hard-grained stone\nThat best resists the griding tool, may break:\nBut, save the form it once hath taken, none\nWill ever from the graver's iron take.\nMy heart like marble is, or thing least prone\nBeneath the chisel's trenchant edge to flake:\nLove this may wholly splinter, ere he may\nAnother's beauty in its core enlay.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Other and many words with comfort rife,\nAnd full of love and faith, she said beside;\nWhich might a thousand times have given him life,\nAlbeit a thousand times the knight had died:\nBut, when most clear of the tempestuous strife,\nIn friendly port these hopes appeared to ride,\nThese hopes a foul and furious wind anew\nFar from the sheltering land to seaward blew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In that the gentle Bradamant, who fain\nWould do far more than she hath signified,\nWith wonted daring armed her heart again;\nAnd boldly casting all respect aside,\nOne day stood up before King Charlemagne;\nAnd, \"Sire, if ever yet,\" the damsel cried,\n\"I have found favour in your eyes for deed\nDone heretofore, deny me not its meed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And I entreat, before I claim my fee,\nThat you to me your royal promise plight,\nTo grant my prayer; and fain would have you see\nThat what I shall demand is just and right.\"\n\"Thy valour, damsel dear, deserves from me\nThe boon wherewith thy worth I should requite\"\n(Charles answered), \"and I to content thee swear,\nThough of my kingdom thou should'st claim a share.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The boon for which I to your highness sue,\nIs not to let my parents me accord\n(Pursued the martial damsel save he shew ) \n\nMore prowess than myself, to any lord.\nLet him contend with me in tourney, who\nWould have me, or assay me with the sword.\nMe as his wife let him that wins me, wear;\nLet him that loses me, with other pair.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With cheerful face the emperor made reply,\nThe entreaty was well worthy of the maid;\nAnd that with tranquil mind she might rely,\nHe would accord the boon for which she prayed.\nThis audience was not given so secretly,\nBut that the news to others were conveyed;\nWhich on that very day withal were told\nIn the ears of Beatrice and Aymon old;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who against Bradamant with fury flame,\nAnd both alike, with sudden anger fraught,\n(For plainly they perceive, that in her claim\nShe for Rogero more than Leo wrought)\nAnd active to prevent the damsel's aim\nFrom being to a safe conclusion brought,\nPrivily take her from King Charles's court,\nAnd thence to Rocca Forte's tower transport."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A castle this, which royal Charlemagne\nHad given to Aymon some few days before,\nBuilt between Carcasson and Perpignan,\nOn a commanding point upon the shore.\nResolved to send her eastward, there the twain\nAs in a prison kept her evermore.\nWilling or nilling, so must she forsake\nRogero, and for lord must Leo take."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The martial maid of no less modest vein\nThan bold and full of fire before the foe,\nAlbeit no guard on her the castellain\nHath set, and she is free to come or go,\nObservant of her sire, obeys the rein:\nYet prison, death, and every pain and woe\nTo suffer is resolved that constant maid\nBefore by her Rogero be betrayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rinaldo, who thus ravished from his hand,\nBy ancient Aymon's craft his sister spied,\nAnd saw he could no more in wedlock's band\nDispose of her, by him in vain affied,\nOf his old sire complains, and him doth brand,\nLaying his filial love and fear aside:\nBut little him Rinaldo's words molest;\nWho by the maid will do as likes him best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, bearing this and sore afraid\nThat he shall lose his bride; and Leo take,\nIf left alive, by force or love the maid,\nResolved within himself (but nothing spake)\nConstantine's heir should perish by his blade;\nAnd of Augustus him a god would make.\nHe, save his hope deceived him and was vain,\nWould sire and son deprive of life and reign."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His limbs in arms, which Trojan Hector's were,\nAnd afterwards the Tartar king's, he steeled;\nBade rein Frontino, and his wonted wear\nExchanged, crest, surcoat and emblazoned shield.\nOn that emprize it pleased him not to bear\nHis argent eagle on its azure field.\nWhite as a lily, was a unicorn\nBy him upon a field of crimson worn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He chose from his attendant squires the best,\nAnd willed none else should him accompany;\nAnd gave him charge, that ne'er by him exprest\nRogero's name in any place should be;\nCrost Meuse and Rhine, and pricked upon his quest\nThrough the Austrian countries into Hungary;\nAlong the right bank of the Danube made,\nAnd rode an-end until he reached Belgrade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where Save into dark Danube makes descent,\nAnd to the sea, increased by him, doth flow,\nHe saw the imperial ensigns spread, and tent\nAnd white pavilion, thronged with troops below.\nFor Constantine to have that town was bent\nAnew, late won by the Bulgarian foe.\nIn person, with his son, is Constantine,\nWith all the empire's force his host to line."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Within Belgrade, and through the neighbouring peak,\nEven to its bottom which the waters lave,\nThe Bulgar fronts him; and both armies seek\nA watering-place in the intermediate Save.\nA bridge across that rapid stream the Greek\nWould fling; the Bulgar would defend the wave;\nWhen thither came Rogero; and engaged\nBeheld the hosts in fight, which hotly raged."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Greeks in that affray were four to one,\nAnd with pontoons to bridge the stream supplied;\nAnd a bold semblance through their host put on\nOf crossing to the river's further side.\nLeo meanwhile was from the river gone\nWith covert guile; he took a circuit wide,\nThen thither made return; his bridges placed\nFrom bank to bank, and past the stream in haste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With many horse and foot in battle dight,\nWho nothing under twenty thousand rank,\nAlong the river rode the Grecian knight;\nAnd fiercely charged his enemies in flank.\nThe emperor, when his son appeared in sight.\nLeading his squadrons on the farther bank,\nUniting bridge and bark together, crost\nUpon his part the stream with all his host."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Vatran, chief of the Bulgarian band,\nWise, bold, withal a warrior, here and there\nLaboured in vain such onset to withstand,\nAnd the disorder of his host repair;\nWhen Leo prest him sore, and with strong hand\nThe king to earth beneath his courser bare;\nWhom at the prince's hest, for all to fierce\nIs he to yield, a thousand faulchions pierce."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The Bulgar host hath hitherto made head;\nBut when they see their sovereign is laid low,\nAnd everywhere that tempest wax and spread,\nThey turn their backs where erst they faced the foe.\nThe Child, who mid the Greeks, from whom they fled,\nWas borne along, beheld that overthrow,\nAnd bowned himself their battle to restore,\nAs hating Constantine and Leo more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He spurs Frontino, that in his career\nIs like the wind, and passes every steed;\nHe overtakes the troop, that in their fear\nFly to the mountain and desert the mead.\nMany he stops and turns; then rests his spear;\nAnd, as he puts his courser to his speed,\nSo fearful is his look, even Mars and Jove\nAre frighted in their azure realms above."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Advanced before the others, he descried\nA cavalier, in crimson vest, whereon\nWith all its stalk in silk and gold was spied\nA pod, like millet, in embroidery done:\nConstantine's nephew, by the sister's side,\nHe was, but was no less beloved than son:\nHe split like glass his shield and scaly rind;\nAnd the long lance appeared a palm behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He left the dead, and drew his shining blade\nUpon a squadron, whom he saw most nigh;\nAnd now at once, and now at other made;\nCleft bodies, and made hearts from shoulders fly.\nAt throat, at breast and flank the warrior laid;\nSmote hand, and arm, and shoulder, bust, and thigh;\nAnd through that champaign ran the reeking blood,\nAs to the valley foams the mountain-flood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "None that behold those strokes maintain their place;\nSo are they all bewildered by their fear.\nThus suddenly the battle changed its face:\nFor, catching courage from the cavalier,\nThe Bulgar squadrons rally, turn, and chase\nThe Grecian troops that fled from them whilere.\nLost was all order in a thought, and they\nWith all their banners fled in disarray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leo Augustus on a swelling height,\nSeeing his followers fly, hath taken post;\nWhere woeful and bewildered (for to sight\nNothing in all the country round is lost)\nHe from his lofty station eyes the knight,\nWho with his single arm destroys that host;\nAnd cannot choose, though so his prowess harms,\nBut praise that peer and own his worth in arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He knew full well by ensignry displaid,\nBy surcoat and by gilded panoply,\nThat albeit to the foe he furnished aid,\nThat champion was not of his chivalry;\nWondering his superhuman deeds surveyed;\nAnd now an angel seemed in him to see,\nTo scourge the Greeks from quires above descended,\nWhose sins so oft and oft had heaven offended;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, as a man of great and noble heart,\n(Where many others would have hatred sworn)\nEnamoured of such valour, on his part,\nWould not desire to see him suffer scorn:\nFor one that died, six Grecians' death less smart\nWould cause that prince; and better had he borne\nTo lose as well a portion of his reign,\nThan to behold so good a warrior slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As baby, albeit its fond mother beat\nAnd drive it forth in anger, in its fear\nNeither to sire nor sister makes retreat;\nBut to her arms returns with fondling cheer:\nSo Leo, though Rogero in his heat\nSlaughters his routed van and threats his rear,\nCannot that champion hate; because above\nHis anger is the admiring prince's love."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But if young Leo loved him and admired,\nMeseems that he an ill exchange hath made;\nFor him Rogero loathed; nor aught desired\nMore than to lay him lifeless with his blade:\nHim with his eyes he sought; for him inquired;\nBut Leo's fortune his desire gainsayed;\nWhich with the prudence of the practised Greek,\nMade him in vain his hated rival seek."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leo, for fear his bands be wholly spent,\nBids sound the assembly his Greek squadrons through:\nHe to his father a quick courier sent,\nTo pray that he would pass the stream anew;\nWho, if the way was open, well content\nMight with his bargain he; and with a few\nWhom he collects, the Grecian cavalier\nRecrost the bridge by which he past whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Into the power o' the Bulgars many fall,\nStalin from the hill-top to the river-side;\nAnd they into their hands had fallen all,\nBut for the river's intervening tide.\nFrom the bridge many drop, and drown withal;\nAnd many that ne'er turned their heads aside,\nThence to a distant ford for safety made;\nAnd many were dragged prisoners to Belgrade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When done was that day's fight, wherein (since borne\nTo ground the Bulgar king his life did yield)\nHis squadrons would have suffered scathe and scorn,\nHad not for them the warrior won the field,\nThe warrior, that the snowy unicorn\nWore for his blazon on a crimson shield,\nTo him all flock, in him with joy and glee\nThe winner of that glorious battle see."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Some bow and some salute him; of the rest\nSome kist the warrior's feet, and some his hand.\nRound him as closely as they could they prest,\nAnd happy those are deemed, that nearest stand;\nMore those that touch him; for to touch a blest\nAnd supernatural thing believes the band.\nOn him with shouts that rent the heavens they cried,\nTo be their king, their captain, and their guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As king or captain them will he command\nAs liked them best, he said, but will not lay\nOn sceptre or on leading-staff his hand;\nNor yet Belgrade will enter on that day:\nFor first, ere farther flies young Leo's band,\nAnd they across the river make their way,\nHim will he follow, nor forego, until\nThat Grecian leader he o'ertake and kill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A thousand miles and more for this alone\nHe thither measured, and for nought beside.\nHe saith; and from the multitude is gone,\nAnd by a road that's shown to him doth ride.\nFor towards the bridge is royal Leo flown;\nHaply lest him from this the foe divide:\nBehind him pricks Rogero with such fire,\nThe warrior calls not, nor awaits, his squire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such vantage Leo has in flight (to flee\nHe rather may be said than to retreat)\nThe passage open hath he found and free;\nAnd then destroys the bridge and burns his fleet.\nRogero arrived not, till beneath the sea\nThe sun was hid; nor lodging found; his beat\nHe still pursued; and now shone forth the moon:\nBut town or village found the warrior none."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Because he wots not where to lodge, he goes\nAll night, nor from his load Frontino frees.\nWhen the new sun his early radiance shows,\nA city to the left Rogero sees;\nAnd there all day determines to repose,\nAs where he may his wearied courser ease,\nWhom he so far that livelong night had pressed;\nNor had he drawn his bit, nor given him rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ungiardo had that city in his guard,\nConstantine's liegeman, and to him right dear;\nWho, since upon the Bulgars he had warred,\nMuch horse and foot had sent that emperor; here\nNow entered (for the entrance was not barred)\nRogero, and found such hospitable cheer,\nHe to fare further had no need, in trace\nOf better or of more abundant place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the same hostelry with him a guest\nWas lodged that evening a Romanian knight;\nPresent what time the Child with lance in rest\nSuccoured the Bulgars in that cruel fight;\nWho hardly had escaped his hand, sore prest\nAnd scared as never yet was living wight;\nSo that he trembled still, disturbed in mind,\nAnd deemed the knight of the unicorn behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He by the buckler knew as soon as spied\nThe cavalier, whose arms that blazon bear,\nFor him that routed the Byzantine side;\nBy hand of whom so many slaughtered were.\nHe hurried to the palace, and applied\nFor audience, weighty tidings to declare;\nAnd, to Ungiardo led forthwith, rehearsed\nWhat shall by men in other strain be versed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 45"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Young Leo doth from death Rogero free;\nFor him Rogero Bradamant hath won,\nMaking that maid appear less strong to be,\nDisguised in fight like Leo; and, that done,\nStraight in despite would slay himself; so he\nBy sorrow, so by anguish is foredone.\nTo hinder Leo of his destined wife\nMarphisa works, and kindles mighty strife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By how much higher we see poor mortal go\nOn Fortune's wheel, which runs a restless round,\nWe so much sooner see his head below\nHis heels; and he is prostrate on the ground.\nThe Lydian, Syracusan, Samian show\nThis truth, and more whose names I shall not sound;\nAll into deepest dolour in one day\nHurled headlong from the height of sovereign sway."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By how much more deprest on the other side,\nBy how much more the wretch is downwards hurled,\nHe so much sooner mounts, where he shall ride,\nIf the revolving wheel again be twirled.\nSome on the murderous block have well-nigh died,\nThat on the following day have ruled the world.\nVentidius, Servius, Marius this have shown\nIn ancient days; King Lewis in our own;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Lewis, stepfather of my duke's son;\nWho, when his host at Santalbino fled,\nLeft in his clutch by whom that field was won,\nWas nigh remaining shorter by the head.\nNor long before the great Corvinus run\nA yet more fearful peril, worse bested:\nBoth throned, when overblown was their mischance,\nOne king of Hungary, one king of France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "'Tis plain to sight, through instances that fill\nThe page of ancient and of modern story,\nThat ill succeeds to good, and good to ill;\nThat glory ends in shame, and shame in glory;\nAnd that man should not trust, deluded still,\nIn riches, realm, or field of battle, gory\nWith hostile blood, nor yet despair, for spurns\nOf Fortune; since her wheel for ever turns."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through that fair victory, when overthrown\nWere Leo and his royal sire, the knight\nWho won that battle to such trust is grown,\nIn his good fortune and his peerless might,\nHe, without following, without aid, alone\n(So is he prompted by his daring sprite)\nThinks, mid a thousand squadrons in array,\n— Footmen and horsemen — sire and son to slay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But she, that wills no trust shall e'er be placed\nIn her by man, to him doth shortly show,\nHow wight by her is raised, and how abased;\nHow soon she is a friend, how soon a foe;\nShe makes him know Rogero, that in haste\nIs gone to work that warrior shame and woe;\nThe cavalier, which in that battle dread\nWith much ado had from his faulchion fled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He to Ungiardo hastens to declare\nThe Child who put the imperial host to flight,\nWhose carnage many years will not repair,\nHere past the day and was to pass the night;\nAnd saith, that Fortune, taken by the hair,\nWithout more trouble, and without more fight,\nWill, if he prisons him, the Bulgars bring\nBeneath the yoke and lordship of his king."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ungiardo from the crowd, which had pursued\nThither their flight from the ensanguined plain,\nFor, troop by troop, a countless multitude\n(Arrived, because not all the bridge could gain)\nKnew what a cruel slaughter had ensued:\nFor there the moiety of the Greeks was slain;\nAnd knew that by a cavalier alone\nOne host was saved, and one was overthrown;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And that undriven he should have made his way\nInto the net, and of his own accord,\nWondered, and showed his pleasure, at the say\nIn visage, gesture, and in joyful word.\nHe waited till Rogero sleeping lay;\nThen softly sent his guard to take that lord;\nAnd made the valiant Child, who had no dread\nOf such a danger, prisoner in his bed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By his own shield accused, that witness true,\nThe Child is captive in Novogorood,\nTo Ungiardo, worst among the cruel, who\nMarvellous mirth to have that prisoner shewed.\nAnd what, since he was naked, could he do,\nBound, while his eyes were yet by slumber glued?\nA courier, who the news should quickly bear,\nUngiardo bids to Constantine repair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Constantine on that night with all his host,\nRaising his camp, from Save's green shore had gone:\nWith this in Beleticche he takes post,\nAndrophilus', his sister's husband's town,\nFather of him, whose arms in their first joust\n(As if of wax had been his habergeon)\nHad pierced and carved the puissant cavalier,\nNow by Ungiardo pent in dungeon drear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here from attack the emperor makes assure\nThe city walls and gates on every side;\nLest, from the Bulgar squadrons ill secure,\nHaving so good a warrior for their guide,\nHis broken Grecians worse than fear endure;\nDeeming the rest would by his hand have died.\nNow he is taken, these breed no alarms;\nNor would he fear the banded world in arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The emperor, swimming in a summer sea,\nKnows not for very pleasure what to do:\n\"Truly the Bulgars may be said to be\nVanquished,\" he cries, with bold and cheerful brow.\nAs he would feel assured of victory,\nThat had of either arm deprived his foe;\nSo the emperor was assured, and so rejoiced,\nWhen good Rogero's fate the warrior voiced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No less occasion has the emperor's son\nFor joying; for besides that he anew\nTrusts to acquire Belgrade, and tower and town\nThroughout the Bulgars' country to subdue,\nHe would by favours make the knight his own,\nAnd hopes to rank him in his warlike crew:\nNor need he envy, guarded by his blade,\nKing Charles', Orlando's, or Rinaldo's aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Theodora was by other thoughts possest,\nWhose son was killed by young Rogero's spear;\nWhich through his shoulders, entering at his breast,\nIssued a palm's breadth in the stripling's rear;\nConstantine's sister she, by grief opprest,\nFell down before him; and with many a tear\nThat dropt into her bosom, while she sued,\nHis heart with pity softened and subdued."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I still before these feet will bow my knee,\nSave on this felon, good my lord,\" (she cried)\n\"Who killed my son, to venge me thou agree,\nNow that we have him in our hold; beside\nThat he thy nephew was, thou seest how thee\nHe loved; thou seest what feats upon thy side\nThat warrior wrought; thou seest if thou wilt blot\nThine own good name, if thou avenge him not."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Thou seest how righteous Heaven by pity stirred\nFrom the wide champaign, red with Grecian gore,\nBears that fell man; and like a reckless bird\nInto the fowler's net hath made him soar;\nThat for short season, for revenge deferred,\nMy son may mourn upon the Stygian shore.\nGive me, my lord, I pray, this cruel foe,\nThat by his torment I may soothe my woe.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So well she mourns; and in such moving wise\nAnd efficacious doth she make lament;\n(Nor from before the emperor will arise,\nThough he three times and four the dame has hent,\nAnd to uplift by word and action tries)\nThat he is forced her wishes to content;\nAnd thus, according to her prayer, commands\nThe Child to be delivered to her hands;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And, not therein his orders to delay,\nThey take the warrior of the unicorn\nTo cruel Theodora; but one day\nOf respite has the knight: to have him torn\nIn quarters, yet alive; to rend and slay\nHer prisoners publicly with shame and scorn,\nSeems a poor pain; and he must undergo\nOther unwonted and unmeasured woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "At the commandment of that woman dread,\nChains on his neck and hands and feet they don;\nAnd put him in a dungeon-cell, where thread\nOf light was never by Apollo thrown:\nHe has a scanty mess of mouldy bread;\nAnd sometimes is he left two days with none;\nAnd one that doth the place of jailer fill\nIs prompter than herself to work him ill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh!  if Duke Aymon's daughter brave and fair,\nOf if Marphisa of exalted mind\nHad heard Rogero's sad estate declare,\nAnd how he in this guise in prison pined,\nTo his rescue either would have made repair,\nAnd would have flung the fear of death behind:\nNor had bold Bradamant, intent to aid,\nRespect to Beatrice or Aymon paid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile King Charlemagne upon his side,\nHeeding his promise made in solemn sort,\nThat none should have the damsel for his bride,\nThat of her prowess in the field fell short;\nNot only had his sovereign pleasure cried\nWith sound of trumpet in his royal court,\nBut in each city subject to his crown.\nHence quickly through the world the bruit was blown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such the condition which he bids proclaim:\nHe that would with Duke Aymon's daughter wed\nMust with the sword contend against that dame\nFrom the suns rise until he seeks his bed;\nAnd if he for that time maintains the game,\nAnd is not overcome, without more said,\nThe lady is adjudged to have lost the stake;\nNor him for husband can refuse to take."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The choice of arms must be by her foregone,\nNo matter who may claim it in the course:\nAnd by the damsel this may well be done,\nGood at all arms alike, on foot or horse.\nAymon, who cannot strive against the crown,\n— Cannot and will not — yields at length parforce.\nHe much the matter sifts, and in the end\nResolves to court with Bradamant to wend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though for the daughter choler and disdain\nThe mother nursed, yet that she honour due\nMight have, she garments, dyed in different grain,\nHad wrought for her, of various form and hue.\nBradamant for the court of Charlemagne\nDeparts, and finding not her love, to her view\nHis noble court appears like that no more,\nWhich had appeared to her so fair before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As he that hath beheld a garden, bright\nWith flowers and leaves in April or in May,\nAnd next beholds it, when the sun his light\nHath sloped toward the north, and shortened day,\nFinds it a desert horrid to the sight;\nSo, now that her Rogero is away,\nTo Bradamant, who thither made resort,\nNo longer what it was appeared that court."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What is become of him she doth not dare\nDemand, lest more suspicion thence be bred;\nBut listens still, and searches here and there;\nThat this by some, unquestioned, may be said;\nKnows he is gone, but has no notion where\nThe warrior, when he went, his steps had sped;\nBecause, departing thence, he spake no word\nSave to the squire who journeyed with his lord."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh!  how she sighs!  how fears the gentle maid,\nHearing Rogero, as it were, was flown!\nOh!  how above all other terrors, weighed\nThe fear, that to forget her he was gone!\nThat, seeing Aymon still his wish gainsayed,\nAnd that to wed the damsel hope was none,\nHe fled, perchance, so hoping to be loosed\nFrom toils wherein he by her love was noosed;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And that with further end the youthful lord\nHer from his heart more speedily to chase,\nWill rove from realm to realm, till one afford\nSome dame, that may his former love efface;\nEven, as the proverb says, that in a board\nOne nail drives out another from its place.\nA second thought succeeds, and paints the youth\nArraigned of fickleness, as full of truth;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And her reproves for having lent an ear\nTo a suspicion so unjust and blind;\nAnd so, this thought absolves the cavalier;\nAnd that accuses; and both audience find;\nAnd now this way, now that, she seemed to veer;\nNor this, nor that — irresolute of mind —\nPreferred: yet still to what gave most delight\nMost promptly leaned, and loathed its opposite;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And thinking, ever and anon, anew\nOn that so oft repeated by the knight,\nAs for grave sin, remorse and sorrow grew\nThat she had nursed suspicion and affright;\nAnd she, as her Rogero were in view,\nWould blame herself, and would her bosom smite;\nAnd say: \"I see 'twas ill such thoughts to nurse,\nBut he, the cause, is even cause of worse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Love is the cause; that in my heart inlaid\nThy form, so graceful and so fair to see;\nAnd so thy darling and thy wit pourtrayed,\nAnd worth, of all so bruited, that to me\nIt seems impossible that wife or maid,\nBlest with thy sight, should not be fired by thee;\nAnd that she should not all her art apply\nTo unbind, and fasten thee with other tie."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Ah!  wellaway!  if in my thought Love so\nThy thought, as thy fair visage, had designed,\nThis — am I well assured — in open show,\nAs I unseen believe it, should I find;\nAnd be so quit of Jealousy, that foe\nWould not still harass my suspicious mind;\nAnd, where she is by me repulsed with pain,\nNot quelled and routed would she be, but slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I am like miser, so intent on gear,\nAnd who hath this so buried in his heart,\nThat he, for hoarded treasure still in fear,\nCannot live gladly from his wealth apart.\nSince I Rogero neither see nor hear,\nMore puissant far than Hope, O Fear!  thou art;\nTo thee, though false and idle I give way;\nAnd cannot choose but yield myself thy prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But I, Rogero, shall no sooner spy\nThe light of thy glad countenance appear,\nAgainst mine every credence, from mine eye\nConcealed (and woe is me), I know not where, —\nOh!  how true Hope false Fear shall from on high\nDepose withal, and to the bottom bear!\nAh!  turn to me, Rogero!  turn again,\nAnd comfort Hope, whom Fear hath almost slain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As when the sun withdraws his glittering head,\nThe shadows lengthen, causing vain affright;\nAnd as the shadows, when he leaves his bed,\nVanish, and reassure the timid wight:\nWithout Rogero so I suffer dread;\nDread lasts not, if Rogero is in sight.\nReturn to me, return, Rogero, lest\nMy hope by fear should wholly be opprest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"As every spark is in the night alive,\nAnd suddenly extinguished when 'tis morn;\nWhen me my sun doth of his rays deprive,\nAgainst me felon Fear uplifts his horn:\nBut they the shades of night no sooner drive,\nThan Fears are past and gone, and Hopes return.\nReturn, alas!  return, O radiance dear!\nAnd drive from me that foul, consuming Fear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If the sun turn from us and shorten day,\nEarth all its beauties from the sight doth hide;\nThe wild winds howl, and snows and ice convey;\nBird sings not; nor is leaf or flower espied.\nSo, whensoever thou thy gladsome ray,\nO my fair sun, from me dost turn aside,\nA thousand, and all evil, dreads, make drear\nWinter within me many times a year."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Return, my sun, return!  and springtide sweet,\nWhich evermore I long to see, bring back;\nDislodge the snows and ice with genial hear;\nAnd clear my mind, so clouded o'er and black.\"\nAs Philomel, or Progne, with the meat\nReturning, which her famished younglings lack,\nMourns o'er an empty nest, or as the dove\nLaments himself at having lost is love;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The unhappy Bradamant laments her so,\nFearing the Child is reft from her and gone;\nWhile often tears her visage overflow:\nBut she, as best she can, conceals her moan.\nOh!  how — oh!  how much worse would be her woe,\nIf what she knew not to the maid were known!\nThat, prisoned and with pain and pine consumed,\nHer consort to a cruel death was doomed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The cruelty which by that beldam ill\nWas practised on the prisoned cavalier,\nAnd who prepared the wretched Child to kill,\nBy torture new and pains unused whilere,\nWhile so Rogero pined, the gracious will\nOf Heaven conveyed to gentle Leo's ear;\nAnd put into his heart the means to aid,\nAnd not to let such worth be overlaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The courteous Leo that Rogero loved,\nNot that the Grecian knew howe'er that he\nRogero was, but by that valour moved\nWhich sole and superhuman seemed to be,\nThought much, and mused, and planned, how it behoved\n— And found at last a way — to set him free;\nSo that his cruel aunt should have no right\nTo grieve or say he did her a despite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In secret, Leo with the man that bore\nThe prison-keys a parley had, and said,\nHe wished to see that cavalier, before\nUpon the wretch was done a doom so dread.\nWhen it was night, one, faithful found of yore,\nBold, strong, and good in brawl, he thither led;\nAnd — by the silent warder taught that none\nMust know 'twas Leo — was the door undone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leo, escorted by none else beside,\nWas led by the compliant castellain,\nWith his companion, to the tower, where stied\nWas he, reserved for nature's latest pain.\nThere round the neck of their unwary guide,\nWho turns his back the wicket to unchain,\nA slip-knot Leo and his follower cast;\nAnd, throttled by the noose, he breathes his last."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "— The trap upraised, by rope from thence suspended\nFor such a need — the Grecian cavalier,\nWith lighted flambeau in his hand, descended,\nWhere, straitly bound, and without sun to cheer,\nRogero lay, upon a grate extended,\nLess than a palm's breadth of the water clear:\nTo kill him in a month, or briefer space,\nNothing was needed but that deadly place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lovingly Leo clipt the Child, and, \"Me,\nO cavalier!  thy matchless valour,\" cried,\n\"Hath in indissoluble bands to thee,\nIn willing and eternal service, tried;\nAnd wills thy good to mine preferred should be,\nAnd I for thine my safety set aside,\nAnd weigh thy friendship more than sire, and all\nWhom I throughout the world my kindred call."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"I Leo am, that thou what fits mayst know,\nCome to thy succour, the Greek emperor's son:\nIf ever Constantine, my father, trow\nThat I have aided thee, I danger run\nTo be exiled, or aye with troubled brow\nRegarded for the deed that I have done;\nFor thee he hates because of those thy blade\nPut to the rout and slaughtered near Belgrade.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He his discourse with more beside pursues,\nThat might from death to life the Child recall;\nAnd all this while Rogero's hands doth loose.\n\"Infinite thanks I owe you,\" cries the thrall,\n\"And I the life you gave me, for your use\nWill ever render back, upon your call;\nAnd still, at all your need, I for your sake,\nAnd at all times, that life will promptly stake.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero is rescued; and the gaoler slain\nIs left in that dark dungeon in his place;\nNor is Rogero known, nor are the twain:\nLeo the warrior, free from bondage base,\nBrings home, and there in safety to remain\nPersuades, in secret, four or six days' space:\nMeanwhile for him will he retrieve the gear\nAnd courser, by Ungiardo reft whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Open the gaol is found at dawn of light,\nThe gaoler strangled, and Rogero gone.\nSome think that these or those had helped his flight:\nAll talk; and yet the truth is guessed by none.\nWell may they think by any other wight\nRather than Leo had the deed been done;\nFor many deemed he had cause to have repaid\nThe Child with scathe, and none to give him aid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So wildered by such kindness, so immersed\nIn wonder, is the rescued cavalier,\nSo from those thoughts is he estranged, that erst\nSo many weary miles had made him steer,\nHis second thoughts confronting with his first,\nNor these like those, nor those like these appear.\nHe first with hatred, rage, and venom burned;\nWith pity and with love then wholly yearned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much muses he by night and much by day;\n— Nor cares for ought, nor ought desires beside —\nBy equal or more courtesy to pay\nThe mighty debt that him to Leo tied.\nBe his life long or short, or what it may,\nAlbeit to Leo's service all applied,\nDies he a thousand deaths, he can do nought,\nBut more will be deserved, Rogero thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Thither meanwhile had tidings been conveyed\nOf Charles' decree: that who in nuptial tye\nWould yoke with Bradamant, with trenchant blade\nOr lance must with the maid his prowess try.\nThese news the Grecian prince so ill appaid,\nHis cheek was seen to blanch with sickly dye;\nBecause, as one that measured well his might,\nHe knew he was no match for her in fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Communing with himself, he can supply\n(He sees the valour wanting with his wit; ) \n\nAnd the strange knight with his own ensignry,\nWhose name is yet unknown to him, will fit:\nHim he against Frank champion, far and nigh,\nBelieves he may for force and daring pit;\nAnd if the knight to that emprize agree,\nVanquished and taken Bradamant will be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But two things must he do; must, first, dispose\nThat cavalier to undertake the emprize;\nThen send afield the champion, whom he chose,\nIn mode, that none suspect the youth's disguise:\nTo him the matter Leo doth disclose;\nAnd after prays in efficacious wise,\nThat he the combat with the maid will claim,\nUnder false colours and in other's name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much weighs the Grecian's eloquence; but more\nThan eloquence with good Rogero weighed\nThe mighty obligation which he bore;\nThat debt which cannot ever be repaid.\nSo, albeit it appeared a hardship sore\nAnd thing well-nigh impossible, he said,\nWith blither face than heart, that Leo's will\nIn all that he commands he would fulfil."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Albeit no sooner he the intent exprest,\nThan with sore grief Rogero's heart was shent;\nWhich, night and day, and ever, doth molest,\nEver afflict him, evermore torment:\nAnd though he sees his death is manifest,\nNever will he confess he doth repent:\nRather than not with Leo's prayer comply,\nA thousand deaths, not one, the Child will die."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Right sure he is to die; if he forego\nThe lady, he foregoes his life no less.\nHis heart will break through his distress and woe,\nOr, breaking not with woe and with distress,\nHe will, himself, the bands of life undo,\nAnd of its clay the spirit dispossess.\nFor all things can he better bear than one;\nThan see that gentle damsel not his own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To die is he disposed; but how to die\nCannot as yet the sorrowing lord decide:\nSometimes he thinks his prowess to belie,\nAnd offer to her sword his naked side:\nFor never death can come more happily\nThan if her hand the fatal faulchion guide:\nThen sees, except he wins the martial maid\nFor that Greek prince, the debt remains unpaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For he with Bradamant, as with a foe,\nPromised to do, not feign, a fight in mail,\nAnd not to make of arms a seeming show;\nSo that his sword should Leo ill avail.\nThen by his word will he abide; and though\nHis breast now these now other thoughts assail,\nAll from his bosom chased the generous youth,\nSave that which moved him to maintain his truth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With the emperor's licence, armour to prepare,\nAnd steeds meanwhile had wrought his youthful son;\nWho with such goodly following as might square\nWith his degree, upon his way was gone:\nWith him Rogero rides, through Leo's care,\nEquipt with horse and arms, that were his own.\nDay after day the squadron pricks; nor tarries\nUntil arrived in France; arrived at Paris."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leo will enter not the town; but nigh\nPitches his broad pavilions on the plain;\nAnd his arrival by an embassy\nMakes known that day to royal Charlemagne.\nWell pleased is he; and visits testify\nAnd many gifts the monarch's courteous vein.\nHis journey's cause the Grecian prince displayed,\nAnd to dispatch his suit the sovereign prayed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To send afield the damsel, who denied\nEver to take in wedlock any lord\nWeaker than her: for she should be his bride,\nOr he would perish by the lady's sword.\nCharles undertook for this; and, on her side,\nThe following day upon the listed sward\nBefore the walls, in haste, enclosed that night,\nAppeared the martial maid, equipt for fight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero past the night before the day\nWherein by him the battle should be done,\nLike that which felon spends, condemning to pay\nLife's forfeit with the next succeeding sun:\nHe made his choice to combat in the fray\nAll armed; because he would discovery shun:\nNor barded steed he backed, nor lance he shook;\nNor other weapon than his faulchion took."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "No lance he took: yet was it not through fear\nOf that which Argalia whilom swayed;\nAstolpho's next; then hers, that in career\nHer foemen ever upon earth had laid:\nBecause none weened such force was in the spear,\nNor that it was by necromancy made;\nExcepting royal Galaphron alone;\nWho had it forged, and gave it to his son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nay, bold Astolpho, and the lady who\nAfterwards bore it, deemed that not to spell,\nBut simply to their proper force, was due\nThe praise that they in knightly joust excel;\nAnd with whatever spear they fought, those two\nBelieved that they should have performed as well.\nWhat only makes that knight the joust forego\nIs that he would not his Frontino show."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For easily that steed of generous kind\nShe might have known, if him she had espied;\nWhom in Montalban, long to her consigned,\nThe gentle damsel had been wont to ride.\nRogero, that but schemes, but hath in mind\nHow he from Brandamant himself shall hide,\nNeither Frontino nor yet other thing.\nWhereby he may be known, afield will bring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With a new sword will he the maid await;\nFor well he knew against the enchanted blade\nAs soft as paste would prove all mail and plate;\nFor never any steel its fury stayed;\nAnd heavily with hammer, to rebate\nIts edge, as well he on this faulchion layed.\nSo armed, Rogero in the lists appeared,\nWhen the first dawn of day the horizon cheered."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To look like Leo, o'er his breast is spread\nThe surcoat that the prince is wont to wear;\nAnd the gold eagle with its double head\nHe blazoned on the crimson shield doth bear;\nAnd (what the Child's disguisement well may stead)\nOf equal size and stature are the pair.\nIn the other's form presents himself the one;\nThat other lets himself be seen of none."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Dordona's martial maid is of a vein\nRight different from the gentle youth's, who sore\nHammers and blunts the faulchion's tempered grain,\nLest it his opposite should cleave or bore.\nShe whets her steel, and into it would fain\nEnter, that stripling to the quick to gore:\nYea, would such fury to her strokes impart,\nThat each should go directly to his heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As on the start the generous barb in spied,\nWhen he the signal full of fire attends;\nAnd paws now here now there; and opens wide\nHis nostrils, and his pointed ears extends;\nSo the bold damsel, to the lists defied,\nWho knows not with Rogero she contends,\nSeemed to have fire within her veins, nor found\nResting-place, waiting for the trumpet's sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As sometimes after thunder sudden wind\nTurns the sea upside down; and far and nigh\nDim clouds of dust the cheerful daylight blind,\nRaised in a thought from earth, and whirled heaven-high;\nScud beasts and herd together with the hind;\nAnd into hail and rain dissolves the sky;\nSo she upon the signal bared her brand,\nAnd fell on her Rogero, sword in hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But well-built wall, strong tower, or aged oak,\nNo more are moved by blasts that round them rave,\nNo more by furious sea is moved the rock,\nSmote day and night by the tempestuous wave,\nThan in those arms, secure from hostile stroke,\nWhich erst to Trojan Hector Vulcan gave,\nMoved was he by that ire and hatred rank\nWhich stormed about his head, and breast, and flank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now aims that martial maid a trenchant blow,\nAnd now gives point; and wholly is intent\n'Twixt plate and plate to reach her hated foe;\nSo that her stifled fury she may vent:\nNow on this side, now that, now high, now low\nShe strikes, and circles him, on mischief bent;\nAnd evermore she rages and repines;\nAs balked of every purpose she designs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As he that layeth siege to well-walled town,\nAnd flanked about with solid bulwarks, still\nRenews the assault; now fain would batter down\nGateway or tower; now gaping fosse would fill;\nYet vainly toils (for entrance is there none)\nAnd wastes his host, aye frustrate of his will;\nSo sorely toils and strives without avail\nThe damsel, nor can open plate or mail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sparks now his shield, now helm, now cuirass scatter,\nWhile straight and back strokes, aimed now low, now high,\nWhich good Rogero's head and bosom batter,\nAnd arms, by thousands and by thousands fly\nFaster than on the sounding farm-roof patter\nHailstones descending from a troubled sky.\nRogero, at his ward, with dexterous care,\nDefends himself, and ne'er offends the fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now stopt, now circled, now retired the knight,\nAnd oft his hand his foot accompanied;\nAnd lifted shield, and shifted sword in fight,\nWhere shifting he the hostile hand espied.\nEither he smote her not, or — die he smite —\nSmote, where he deemed least evil would betide.\nThe lady, ere the westering sun descend,\nDesires to bring that duel to an end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of the edict she remembered her, and knew\nHer peril, save the foe was quickly sped:\nFor if she took not in one day nor slew\nHer claimant, she was taken; and his head\nPhoebus was now about to hide from view,\nNigh Hercules' pillars, in his watery bed,\nWhen first she 'gan misdoubt her power to cope\nWith the strong foe, and to abandon hope."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "By how much more hope fails the damsel, so\nMuch more her anger waxes; she her blows\nRedoubling, yet the harness of her foe\nWill break, which through that day unbroken shows;\nAs he, that at his daily drudgery slow,\nSees night on his unfinished labour close,\nHurries and toils and moils without avail,\nTill wearied strength and light together fail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Didst thou, O miserable damsel, trow\nWhom thou wouldst kill, if in that cavalier\nMatched against thee thou didst Rogero know,\nOn whom depend thy very life-threads, ere\nThou killed him thou wouldst kill thyself; for thou,\nI know, dost hold him than thyself more dear;\nAnd when he for Rogero shall be known,\nI know these very strokes thou wilt bemoan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Charles and peers him  sheathed in plate and shell\nDeem not Rogero, but the emperor's son;\nAnd viewing in that combat fierce and fell\nSuch force and quickness by the stripling shown;\nAnd, without e'er offending her, how well\nThat knight defends himself, now change their tone;\nEsteem both well assorted; and declare\nThe champions worthy of each other are."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Phoebus wholly under water goes,\nCharlemagne bids the warring pair divide;\nAnd Bradamant (nor boots it to oppose)\nAllots to youthful Leo as a bride.\nNot there Rogero tarried to repose;\nNor loosed his armour, nor his helm untied:\nOn a small hackney, hurrying sore, he went\nWhere Leo him awaited in his tent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Twice in fraternal guise and oftener threw\nLeo his arms about the cavalier;\nAnd next his helmet from his head withdrew,\nAnd kiss'd him on both cheeks with loving cheer.\n\"I would,\" he cried, \"that thou wouldst ever do\nBy me what pleaseth thee; for thou wilt ne'er\nWeary my love: at any call I lend\nTo thee myself and state; these friendly spend;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor see I recompense, which can repay\nThe mighty obligation that I owe;\nThough of the garland I should disarray\nMy brows, and upon thee that gift bestow.\"\nRogero, on whom his sorrows press and prey,\nWho loathes his life, immersed in that deep woe,\nLittle replies; the ensigns he had worn\nReturns, and takes again his unicorn;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And showing himself spiritless and spent,\nFrom thence as quickly as he could withdrew,\nAnd from young Leo's to his lodgings went;\nWhen it was midnight, armed himself anew,\nSaddled his horse, and sallied from his tent;\n(He takes no leave, and none his going view;)\nAnd his Frontino to that road addrest,\nWhich seemed to please the goodly courser best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Now by straight way and now by crooked wound\nFrontino, now by wood and wide champaign;\nAnd all night with his rider paced that round,\nWho never ceased a moment to complain:\nHe called on Death, and therein comfort found;\nSince broke by him alone is stubborn pain;\nNor saw, save Death, what other power could close\nThe account of his insufferable woes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Whereof should I complain,\" he said, \"wo is me!\nSo of my every good at once forlorn?\nAh!  if I will not bear this injury\nWithout revenge, against whom shall I turn?\nFor I, besides myself, none other see\nThat hath inflicted on me scathe and scorn.\nThen I to take revenge for all the harm\nDone to myself, against myself must arm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Yet was but to myself this injury done,\nMyself to spare (because this touched but me)\nI haply could, yet hardly could, be won;\nNay, I will say outright, I could not be.\nLess can I be, since not to me alone,\nBut Bradamant, is done this injury;\nEven if I could consent myself to spare,\nIt fits me not unvenged to leave that fair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Then I the damsel will avenge, and die,\n(Nor this disturbs me whatsoe'er betide; ) \n\nFor, bating death, I know not aught, whereby\nDefence against my grief can be supplied.\nBut I lament myself alone, that I\nBefore offending her, should not have died.\nO happier Fortune!  had I breathed my last\nIn Theodora's dungeon prisoned fast!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Though she had slain, had tortured me before\nShe slew, as prompted by her cruelty,\nAt least the hope would have remained in store\nThat I by Bradamant should pitied be:\nBut when she knows that I loved Leo more\nThan her, that, of my own accord and free,\nMyself of her, I for his good, deprive,\nDead will she rightly hate me or alive.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These words he said and many more, with sigh\nAnd heavy sob withal accompanied,\nAnd, when another sun illumed the sky,\nMid strange and gloomy woods himself espied;\nAnd, for he desperate was and bent to die,\nAnd he, as best he could, his death would hide;\nThis place to him seemed far removed from view,\nAnd fitted for the deed that he would do."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He entered into that dark woodland, where\nHe thickest trees and most entangled spied:\nBut first Frontino was the warrior's care,\nWhom he unharnessed wholly, and untied.\n\"O my Frontino, if thy merits rare\nI could reward, thou little cause\" (he cried)\n\"Shouldst have to envy him, so highly graced,\nWho soared to heaven, and mid the stars was placed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor Cillarus, nor Arion, was whilere\nWorthier than thee, nor merited more praise;\nNor any other steed, whose name we hear\nSounded in Grecian or in Latin lays.\nWas any such in other points thy peer,\nNone of them, well I know, the vaunt can raise;\nThat such high honour and such courtesy\nWere upon him bestowed, as were on thee."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Since to the gentlest maid, of fairest dye,\nAnd boldest that hath been, or evermore\nWill be, thou wast so dear, she used to tie\nThy trappings, and to thee thy forage bore:\nDear wast thou to my lady-love: Ah!  why\nCall I her mine, since she is mine no more?\nIf I have given her to another lord,\nWhy turn I not upon myself this sword?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If him these thoughts so harass and torment,\nThat bird and beast are softened by his cries;\n(For, saving these, none hears the sad lament,\nNor sees the flood that trickles form his eyes)\nYou are not to believe that more content\nThe Lady Bradamant in Paris lies;\nWho can no longer her delay excuse,\nNor Leo for her wedded lord refuse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Ere she herself to any consort tie,\nBeside her own Rogero, she will fain\nDo what so can be done; her word belie;\nAnger friends, kindred, court, and Charlemagne;\nAnd if she nothing else can do, will die,\nBy poison or her own good faulchion slain:\nFor not to live appears far lesser woe,\nThan, living, her Rogero to forego."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Rogero mine, ah!  wonder gone\" (she cried)\n\"Art thou; and canst thou so far distant be,\nThou heardest not this royal edict cried,\nA thing concealed from none, expecting thee?\nFaster than thee would none have hither hied,\nI wot, hadst thou known this; ah!  wretched me!\nHow can I e'er in future think of aught,\nSaving the worst that can by me be thought?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"How can it be, Rogero, thou alone\nHast read not what by all the world is read?\nIf thou hast read it not, nor hither flown,\nHow canst thou but a prisoner be, or dead?\nBut well I wot, that if the truth were known,\nThis Leo will for thee some snare have spread:\nThe traitor will have barred thy way, intent\nThou shouldst not him by better speed prevent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"From Charles I gained the promise, that to none\nLess puissant than myself should I be given;\nIn the reliance thou wouldst be that one,\nWith whom I should in arms have vainly striven.\nNone I esteemed, excepting thee alone:\nBut well my rashness is rebuked by Heaven:\nSince I by one am taken in this wise\nUnfamed through life for any fair emprize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If I am held as taken, since the knight\nI had not force to take nor yet to slay;\nA thing that is not, in my judgment, right;\nNor I to Charles's sentence will give way,\nI know that I shall be esteemed as light,\nIf what I lately said, I now unsay;\nBut of those many ladies that have past\nFor light, I am not, I, the first or last."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Enough I to my lover faith maintain,\nAnd, firmer than a rock, am still found true!\nAnd far herein surpass the female train,\nThat were in olden days, or are in new!\nNor, if they me as fickle shall arraign,\nCare I, so good from fickleness ensue;\nThough I am lighter than a leaf be said,\nSo I be forced not with that Greek no wed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These things and more beside the damsel bright\n('Twixt which oft sobs and tears were interposed),\nCeased not to utter through the livelong night\nWhich upon that unhappy day had closed.\nBut, when within Cimmeria's caverned height\nNocturnus with his troops of shades reposed,\nHeaven, which eternally had willed the maid\nShould be Rogero's consort, brought him aid:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This moves the haught Marphisa, when 'tis morn,\nTo appear before the king; to whom that maid\nSaith, to the Child, her brother, mighty scorn\nWas done; nor should he be so ill appaid,\nThat from him should his plighted wife be torn;\nAnd nought thereof unto the warrior said;\nAnd on whoever lists she will in strife\nProve Bradamant to be Rogero's wife;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And this, before all others, will prove true\nOn her, if to deny it she will dare;\nFor she had to Rogero, in her view,\nSpoken those words, which they that marry swear;\nAnd with all ceremony wont and due\nSo was the contract sealed between the pair,\nThey were no longer free; nor could forsake\nThe one the other, other spouse to take."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Whether Marphisa true or falsely spake,\nI well believe that, rather with intent\nYoung Leo's purpose, right or wrong, to break,\nThan tell the truth, she speaks; and with consent\nOf Bradamant doth that avowal make:\nFor to exclude the hated Leo bent,\nAnd of Rogero to be repossest,\nThis she believes her shortest way and best."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Sorely by this disturbed, King Charlemagne\nBade Bradamant be called, and to her told\nThat which the proud Marphisa would maintain;\nAnd Aymon present in the press behold!\n— Bradamant drops her head, nor treats as vain,\nNor vouches what avows that virgin bold,\nIn such confusion, they may well believe\nThat fierce Marphisa speaks not to deceive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Joy good Orlando and joy Rinaldo show,\nWho view in valorous Marphisa's plea\nA cause the alliance shall no further go,\nWhich sealed already Leo deemed to be;\nAnd yet, in spite of stubborn Aymon's no,\nBradamant shall Rogero's consort be;\nAnd they may, without strife, without despite\nDone to Duke Aymon's, give her to the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "For if such words have pass'd between the twain,\nFast is the knot and cannot be untied;\nThey what they vowed more fairly will obtain,\nAnd without further strife are these affied.\n\"This is a plot, a plot devised in vain;\nAnd ye deceive yourselves (Duke Aymon cried)\nFor, were the story true which ye have feigned,\nBelieve not therefore that your cause is gained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"For granting what I will not yet allow,\nAnd what I to believe as yet demur;\nThat weakly to Rogero so her vow\nWas plighted, as Rogero's was to her;\nWhere was the contract made, and when and how?\nMore clearly this to me must ye aver.\nEither it was not so, I am advised;\nOr was before Rogero was baptized."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"But if it were before the youthful knight\nA Christian was, I will not heed it, I;\nFor 'twixt a faithful and a paynim wight,\nI deem that nought avails the marriage-tie.\nFor this not vainly in the doubtful fight\nShould Constantine's fair son have risked to die;\nNor Charlemagne for this, our sovereign lord\nWill forfeit, I believe, his plighted word."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What now you say you should before have said,\nWhile yet the matter was unbroke, and ere\nCharles at my daughter's prayer that edict made\nWhich has drawn Leo to the combat here.\"\nOrlando and Rinaldo were gainsayed\nSo before royal Charles by Clermont's peer;\nAnd equal Charlemagne heard either side,\nBut neither would for this nor that decide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As in the southern or the northern breeze\nThe greenwood murmurs; and as on the shore,\nWhen Aeolus with the god that rules the seas\nIs wroth, the hoarse and hollow breakers roar,\nSo a loud rumour of this strife, that flees\nThrough France, and spreads and circles evermore,\nAffords such matter to rehearse and hear,\nThat nought beside is bruised far or near."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These with Rogero, those with Leo side;\nBut the most numerous are Rogero's friends,\nWho against Aymon, ten to one, divide.\nGood Charlemagne to neither party bends;\nBut wills that cause shall be by justice tried,\nAnd to his parliament the matter sends.\nMarphisa, now the bridal was deferred,\nAppeared anew, and other question stirred;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And said, \"In that anther cannot have\nBradamant, while my brother is alive,\nLet Leo, if the gentle maid he crave,\nHis foe in listed fight of life deprive;\nAnd he, that sends the other to his grave,\nFreed from his rival, with the lady wive.\"\nForthwith this challenge, as erewhile the rest,\nTo Leo was declared at Charles' behest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leo who if he had the cavalier\nOf the unicorn, believed he from his foe\nWas safe; and thought no peril would appear\nToo hard a feat for him; and knew not how\nThence into solitary woods and drear\nThat warrior had been hurried by his woe;\nHim gone for little time and for disport\nBelieved, and took his line in evil sort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "This shortly Leo was condemned to rue:\nFor he, on whom too fondly he relied,\nNor on that day nor on the following two\nAppeared, nor news of him were signified;\nAnd combat with Rogero was, he knew,\nUnsafe, unless that knight was on his side:\nSo sent, to eschew the threatened scathe and scorn,\nTo seek the warrior of the unicorn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through city, and through hamlet, and through town,\nHe sends to seek Rogero, far and near:\nAnd not content with this, himself is gone\nIn person, on his steed, to find the peer.\nBut of the missing warrior tidings none\nNor he nor any of the Court would hear\nBut for Melissa: I for other verse\nReserve myself, her doings to rehearse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Canto 46"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>ARGUMENT</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "After long search for good Rogero made,\nHim Leon finds, and yields to him his prize:\nInformed of all — already with that maid\nHe wives; already in her bosom lies:\nWhen thither he that Sarza's sceptre swayed\nTo infect such bliss with impious venom hies,\nBut falls in combat; and, blaspheming loud,\nTo Acheron descends his spirit proud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "I"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "I, if my chart deceives me not, shall now\nIn little time behold the neighbouring shore;\nSo hope withal to pay my promised vow\nTo one, so long my guide through that wide roar\nOf waters, where I feared, with troubled brow,\nTo scathe my bark or wander evermore.\nBut now, methinks — yea, now I see the land;\nI see the friendly port its arms expand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "II"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A burst of joy, like thunder to my ear,\nRumbles along the sea and rends the sky.\nI chiming bells, I shrilling trumpets hear,\nConfounded with the people's cheerful cry;\nAnd now their forms, that swarm on either pier\nOf the thick-crowded harbour, I descry.\nAll seem rejoiced my task is smoothly done,\nAnd I so long a course have safely run."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "III"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "What beauteous dames and sage, here welcome me!\nWith them what cavaliers the shore adorn!\nWhat friends!  to whom I owe eternity\nOf thanks for their delight at my return.\nMamma, Ginevra, with the rest I see,\nCorreggio's seed, on the harbour's furthest horn.\nVeronica de Gambara is here,\nTo Phoebus and the Aonian choir so dear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With Julia, a new Ginevra is in sight,\nAnother offset from the selfsame tree;\nHippolita Sforza, and Trivultia bright,\nBred in the sacred cavern, I with thee\nEmilia Pia, and thee, Margherite,\nAngela Borgia, Graziosa, see,\nAnd fair Richarda d'Este, Lo!  the twain,\nBlanche and Diana, with their sister train!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "V"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Beauteous, but wiser and more chaste than fair,\nI Barbara Turca, linked with Laura, know:\nNor beams the sun upon a better pair\n'Twixt Ind and where the Moorish waters flow.\nBehold Ginevra!  that rich gem and rare\nWhich gilds the house of Malatesta so,\nThat never worthier or more honoured thing\nAdorned the dome of Keysar or of king."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "If she had dwelt in Rimini of yore,\nWhat time, from conquered Gaul returning home,\nJulius stood fearing on the river-shore,\nTo ford the stream and make a foe of Rome,\nHe every banner would have bowed before\nThat dame, discharged his trophies, and such doom,\nSuch pact would have received as liked her best;\nAnd haply ne'er had Freedom been opprest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The consort of my lord of Bozzolo\nBehold!  the mother, sisters, cousinhood;\nThem of Torello, Bentivoglio,\nPallavigini's and Visconti's brood!\nLo!  she to whom all living dames forego\nThe palm, and all of Grecian, Latin blood,\nOr barbarous, all that ever were, whose name\nFor grace and beauty most is noised by Fame;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "VIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Julia Gonzaga, she that wheresoe'er\nShe moves, where'er she turns her lucid eyes,\nNot only is in charms without a peer,\nBut seems a goddess lighted from the skies:\nWith her is paired her brother's wife, who ne'er\nSwerved from her plighted faith — aye good and wise —\nBecause ill Fortune bore her long despite;\nLo!  Arragonian Anna, Vasto's light!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "IX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Anne gentle, courteous, and as sage as fair,\nTemple of Love and Truth and Chastity:\nWith her, her sister dims all beauty, where\nHer radiance shines.  Lo!  one that hath set free\nHer conquering lord from Orcus' dark repair,\nAnd him in spite of death and destiny\n(Beyond all modern instance raised on high, ) \n\nTo shine with endless glory in the sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "X"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "My ladies of Ferrara, those of gay\nUrbino's court are here; and I descry\nMantua's dames, and all that fair array\nWhich Lombardy and Tuscan town supply.\nThe cavalier amid that band, whom they\nSo honour, unless dazzled is mine eye\nBy those fair faces, is the shining light\nOf his Arezzo, and Accolti hight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Adorned with scarlet hat, and scarlet pall,\nHis nephew Benedict, lo!  there I see;\nWith him Campeggio and Mantua's cardinal;\nGlory and light of the consistory;\nAnd (if I dote not mark how one and all ) \n\nIn face and gesture show such mighty glee\nAt my return, no easy task 'twould seem\nSo vast an obligation to redeem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With them Lactantius is, Claude Ptolemy,\nTrissino, Pansa, and Capilupi mine,\nLatino Giovenal, it seems to me;\nSasso, and Molza, and Florian hight Montine;\nWith him, by whom through shorter pathway we\nAre led to the Ascraean font divine,\nJulio Camillo; and meseems that I\nBerna, and Sanga, and Flaminio spy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lo!  Alexander of Farnese, and O\nLearned company that follows in his train!\nPhaedro, Cappella, Maddalen', Portio,\nSurnamed the Bolognese, the Volterrane.\nBlosio, Pierio, Vida, famed for flow\nOf lofty eloquence of exhaustless vein;\nMussuro, Lascari, and Navagero,\nAnd Andrew Maro, and the monk Severo."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Lo!  two more Alexanders!  of the tree\nOf the Orologi one, and one Guarino:\nMario d' Olvito, and of royalty\nThat scourge, divine Pietro Aretino.\nI two Girolamos amid them see,\nOf Veritade and the Cittadino;\nSee the Mainardo, the Leoniceno,\nPanizzato, Celio, and Teocreno."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bernardo Capel, Peter Bembo here\nI see, through whom our pure, sweet idiom rose,\nAnd who, of vulgar usage winnowed clear,\nIts genuine form in his example shows.\nBehold an Obyson, that in his rear\nAdmires the pains which he so well bestows.\nI Fracastoro, Bevezzano note,\nAnd Tryphon Gabriel, Tasso more remote."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon me Nicholas Tiepoli\nAnd Nicholas Ammanio fix their eyes;\nWith Anthony Fulgoso, who to spy\nMy boat near land shows pleasure and surprise.\nThere, from those dames apart, my Valery\nStands with Barignan, haply to devise\nWith him how, evermore by woman harmed,\nBy her he shall not evermore be charmed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of high and superhuman genius, tied\nBy love and blood, lo!  Pico and Pio true;\nHe that approaches at the kinsmen's side,\n— So honoured by the best — I never knew;\nBut, if by certain tokens signified,\nHe is the man I so desire to view,\nThat Sannazaro, who persuades the nine\nTo leave their fountain for the foaming brine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Diligent, faithful secretary, lo!\nThe learned Pistophilus, mine Angiar here,\nAnd the Acciajuoli their joint pleasure show\nThat for my bark there is no further fear.\nThere I my kinsman Malaguzzo know;\nAnd mighty hope from Adoardo hear,\nThat these my nest-notes shall by friendly wind\nBe blown from Calpe's rock to furthest Ind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Joys Victor Fausto; Tancred joys to view\nMy sail; and with them joy a hundred more.\nWomen and men I see, a mingled crew,\nAt my return rejoicing, crowd the shore.\nThen, since the wind blows fair, nor much to do\nRemains, let me my course delay no more;\nAnd turning to Melissa, in what way\nShe rescued good Rogero let me say."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Much bent was this Melissa (as I know\nI many times have said to you whilere)\nThat Bradamant in wedlock should bestow\nHer hand upon the youthful cavalier;\nAnd so at heart had either's weal and woe,\nThat she from hour to hour of them would hear:\nHence ever on that quest she spirits sent,\nOne still returning as the other went."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A prey to deep and stubborn grief, reclined\nMid gloomy shades Rogero they descried;\nFirm not to swallow food of any kind,\nNor from that purpose to be turned aside;\nAnd so to die of hunger he designed:\nBut weird Melissa speedy aid supplied;\nWho took a road, from home forth issuing, where\nShe met the Grecian emperor's youthful heir;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leo that, one by one, dispatched his train\nOf followers, far and wide, through every bourn,\nAnd afterwards, in person went in vain,\nTo find the warrior of the unicorn.\nThe wise enchantress, that will sell and rein,\nHad on that day equipt a demon, borne\nBy him, in likeness of a hackney horse,\nConstantine's son encountered in her course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"If such as your ingenuous mien\" (she cried\nTo Leo \"is your soul's nobility, ) \n\nAnd corresponding with your fair outside\nYour inward goodness and your courtesy,\nSome help, some comfort, sir, for one provide\nIn whom the best of living knights we see;\nWho, save ye help and comfort quickly lend,\nIs little distant from his latter end."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The best of knights will die of all, who don,\nOr e'er donned sword and buckler, the most fair\nAnd gentle of all warriors that are gone,\nOr who throughout the world yet living are,\nAnd simply for a courteous deed, if none\nShall comfort to the youthful sufferer bear.\nThen come, sir, for the love of Heaven, and try\nIf any counsel succour may supply.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "It suddenly came into Leo's mind\nThe knight of whom she parlayed was that same,\nWhom throughout all the land he sought to find,\nAnd seeking whom, he now in person came.\nSo that obeying her that would persuade\nSuch pious work, he spurred behind the dame;\nWho thither led (nor tedious was the way)\nWhere nigh reduced to death the stripling lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They found Rogero fasting from all food\nFor three long days, so broken down; with pain\nThe knight could but upon his feet have stood,\nTo fall, albeit unpushed, to ground again.\nWith helm on head, and with his faulchion good\nBegirt, he lay reclined in plate and chain.\nA pillow of his buckler had he made,\nWhere the white unicorn was seen pourtraid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There thinking what an injury he had done\nTo his lady love — how ingrate, how untrue\nTo her had been — not simple grief alone\nO'erwhelmed him, to such height his fury grew,\nHe bit his hands and lips; while pouring down\nHis cheeks, the tears unceasing ran, and through\nThe passion that so wrapt his troubled sprite,\nNor Leo nor Melissa heard the knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor therefore interrupts he his lament,\nNor checks his sighs, nor checks his trickling tears.\nYoung Leo halts, to hear his speech intent;\nLights from his courser, and towards him steers:\nHe knows that of the sorrows which torment\nLove is the cause; but yet from nought appears\nWho is the person that such grief hath bred;\nFor by Rogero this remains unsaid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Approaching nearer and yet nearer, now\nHe fronts the weeping warrior, face to face,\nGreets with a brother's love, and stooping low,\nHis neck encircles with a fast embrace.\nBy the lamenting Child I know not how\nIs liked his sudden presence in that place;\nWho fears annoy or trouble at his hand;\nAnd lest he should his wish for death withstand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him with the sweetest words young Leo plied,\nAnd with the warmest love that he could show,\n\"Let it not irk thee,\" to the Child he cried,\n\"To tell the cause from whence thy sorrows flow;\nFor few such desperate evils man betide,\nBut that there is deliverance from his woe,\nSo that the cause be known; nor he bereft\nOf hope should ever be, so life be left."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Much grieve I thou wouldst hide thyself from me,\nThat known me for thy faithful friend and true;\nNot only now I am so bound to thee,\nThat I the knot can never more undo;\nBut even from the beginning, when to be\nThy deadly foeman I had reason due.\nHope then that I will succour thee with pelf,\nWith friends, with following, and with life itself."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Nor shun to me thy sorrow to explain,\nAnd I beseech thee leave to me to try\nIf wealth avail to free thee from thy pain,\nArt, cunning, open force, or flattery,\nIf my assistance is employed in vain,\nThe last relief remains to thee to die:\nBut be content awhile this deed to shun\nTill all that thou canst do shall first be done.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He said; and with such forceful prayer appealed;\nSo gently and benignly soothed his moan;\nThat good Rogero could not choose but yield,\nWhose heart was not of iron or of stone;\nWho deemed, unless he now his lips unsealed,\nHe should a foul discourteous deed have done.\nHe fain would have replied, but made assay\nYet twice or thrice, ere words could find their way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"My lord, when known for what I am (and me\nNow shalt thou know),\" he made at last reply,\n\"I wot thou, like myself, content wilt be,\nAnd haply more content, that I should die.\nKnow me for him so hated once by thee;\nRogero who repaid that hate am I;\nAnd now 'tis many days since with intent\nOf putting thee to death from court I went."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Because I would not see my promised bride\nBorne off by thee; in that Duke Aymon's love\nAnd favour was engaged upon thy side.\nBut, for man purposes, and God above\nDisposes, thy great courtesy, well tried\nIn a sore need, my fixt resolve did move.\nNor only I renounced the hate I bore,\nBut purposed to be thine for evermore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"What time I as Rogero was unknown,\nThou madest suit I would obtain for thee\nThe Lady Bradamant; which was all one\nAs to demand my heart and soul from me.\nWhether thy wish I rather than mine own\nSought to content, thou hast been made to see.\nThine is the lady; her in peace possess;\nFar more than mine I prize thy happiness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Content thee, that deprived of her, as well\nI should myself of worthless life deprive;\nFor better I without a soul could dwell\nThan without Bradamant remain alive.\nAnd never while these veins with life-blood swell\nCanst thou with her legitimately wive:\nFor vows erewhile have been between us said;\nNor she at once can with two husbands wed.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So filled is gentle Leo with amaze\nWhen he the stranger for Rogero knows,\nWith lips and brow unmoved, with stedfast gaze\nAnd rooted feet, he like a statue shows;\nLike statue more than man, which votaries raise\nIn churches, for acquittance of their vows.\nHe deems that courtesy of so high a strain\nWas never done nor will be done again;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And that he him doth for Rogero know\nNot only that goodwill he bore whilere\nAbates not, but augments his kindness so,\nThat no less grieves the Grecian cavalier\nThan good Rogero for Rogero's woe.\nFor this, as well as that he will appear\nDeservedly an emperor's son — although\nIn other things outdone — he will not be\nDefeated in the race of courtesy;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And says, \"That day my host was overthrown,\nRogero, by thy wond'rous valour, though\nI had thee at despite, if I had known\nThou was Rogero, as I know it now,\nSo me thy virtue would have made thine own,\nAs then it made me, knowing not my foe;\nSo hatred from my bosom would have chased,\nAnd with my present love have straight replaced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"That I Rogero hated, ere I knew\nThou was Rogero, will I not deny.\nBut think not that I further would pursue\nThe hatred that I bore thee; and had I,\nWhen thee I from thy darksome dungeon drew,\nDescried the truth, as this I now descry,\nSuch treatment shouldst thou then have had, as thou\nShalt have from me, to thine advantage, now;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"And if I willingly had done so then,\nWhen not, as I am now, obliged to thee;\nHow much more gladly should I now; and when,\nNot doing so, I should with reason be\nDeemed most ungrateful amid ingrate men;\nSince thou foregoest thine every good for me!\nBut I to thee restore thy gift, and, more\nGlady than I received it, this restore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"The damsel more to thee than me is due;\nAnd though for her deserts I hold her dear,\nIf that fair prize some happier mortal drew,\nI think not I my vital thread should shear:\nNor would I by thy death be free to woo:\nThat from the hallowed bands of wedlock clear\nWherein the lady hath to thee been tied,\nI might possess her as my lawful bride."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Not only Bradamant would I forego,\nBut whatsoe'er I in the world possess;\nAnd rather forfeit life than ever know\nThat grief, through me, should such a knight oppress.\nTo me is thy distrust great cause of woe,\nThat since thou couldst dispose of me no less\nThan of thyself, thou — rather than apply\nTo me for succour — wouldst of sorrow die.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "These words he spake, and more to that intent,\nToo tedious in these verses to recite;\nRefuting evermore such argument\nAs might be used in answer by the knight:\nWho said, at last, \"I yield, and am content\nTo live; but how can I ever requite\nThe obligation, which by me is owed\nTo thee that twice hast life on me bestowed?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Melissa generous wine and goodly cheer\nThither bade carry, in a thought obeyed;\nAnd comforted the mourning cavalier,\nWho would have sunk without her friendly aid.\nMeanwhile the sound of steeds Frontino's ear\nHad reached, and thither had he quickly made:\nHim Leo's squires at his commandment caught,\nAnd saddled, and to good Rogero brought;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who, though by Leo helped, with much ado\nAnd labour sore the gentle courser scaled.\nSo wasted was the vigour which some few\nShort days before, in fighting field, availed\nTo overthrow a banded host, and do\nThe deeds he did, in cheating armour mailed.\nDeparting thence, ere they had measured more\nThan half a league, they reached an abbey hoar:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Wherein what of that day was yet unworn\nThey past, the morrow, and succeeding day;\nUntil the warrior of the unicorn\nHis vigour had recruited by the stay.\nHe, Leo, and Melissa then return\nTo Charles's royal residence; where lay\nAn embassy, arrived the eve before,\nWhich from the Bulgars' land a message bore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XLIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Since they that had for king proclaimed the knight\nBesought Rogero thither to repair\nThrough these their envoys deeming they would light\nOn him in Charles's court, where they should swear\nFidelity, and yield to him his right;\nAnd he from them the crown receive and wear.\nRogero's squire who served this band to steer\nHas published tidings of the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "L"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He of the fight has told which at Belgrade\nErewhile Rogero for the Bulgars won;\nHow Leo and his sire were overlaid,\nAnd all their army slaughtered and undone;\nWherefore the Bulgars him their king had made;\nTheir royal line excluding from the throne:\nThen how Ungiardo took the warrior brave,\nAnd him to cruel Theodora gave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He speaks with that of certain news, which say\nHow good Rogero's jailer was found dead,\nThe prison broke and prisoner away:\nOf what became of him was nothing said.\n— Towards the city by a secret way\n(Nor was his visage seen Rogero sped. ) \n\nHe, on the following morning, and his friend,\nLeo, to Charles's court together wend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Charles' court he wends; the bird he bore\nOf gold with its two heads — of crimson hue\nIts field — and that same vest and ensigns wore,\nAs was erewhile devised between the two;\nAnd such as in the listed fight before\nHis bruised and battered armour was in shew.\nSo that they quickly knew the cavalier\nFrom him that strove with Bradamant whilere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In royal ornaments and costly gown,\nUnarmed, beside him doth young Leo fare.\nA worthy following and of high renown\nBefore, behind him, and about him are.\nHe bowed to Charlemagne, who from his throne\nHad risen to do honour to the pair:\nThen holding still Rogero by the hand,\nSo spake, while all that warrior closely scanned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Behold the champion good, that did maintain\nFrom dawn till fall of day the furious fight;\nAnd since by Bradamant nor taken, slain,\nNor forced beyond the barriers was the knight,\nHe is assured his victory is plain,\nDread sir, if he your edict reads aright;\nAnd he hath won the lady for his wife:\nSo comes to claim the guerdon of the strife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Besides that by your edict's tenor none\nBut him can to the damsel lift his eyes,\n— Is she deserved by deeds of valour done,\nWhat other is so worthy of the prize?\n— Should she by him that loves her best be won,\nNone passes him, nor with the warrior vies;\nAnd he is here to fight against all foes\nThat would in arms his right in her oppose.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "King Charlemagne and all his peerage stand\nAmazed, who well believed the Grecian peer\nWith Bradamant had striven with lifted brand\nIn fight, and not that unknown cavalier.\nMarphisa, thither borne amid the band,\nThat crowded round the royal chair to hear,\nHardly till Leo made an ending staid;\nThen prest before the listening troop, and said:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Since here Rogero is not, to contest\nThe bride's possession with the stranger knight,\nLest he, as undefended, be opprest,\nAnd forfeit so without dispute his right,\nOn his behalf I undertake this quest,\n— His sister I — against whatever wight\nShall here assert a claim to Bradamant,\nOr more desert than good Rogero vaunt.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She spake this with such anger and disdain,\nMany surmised amid the assistant crew,\nThat, without waiting leave from Charlemagne,\nWhat she had threatened she forthwith would do.\nNo longer Leo deemed it time to feign;\nAnd from Rogero's head the helm withdrew;\nAnd to Marphisa, \"For himself to speak,\nBehold him here and ready!\" cried the Greek."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As looked old Aegeus at the accursed board,\nSeeing it was his son to whom — so willed\nHis wicked consort — that Athenian lord\nHad given the juice from deadly drugs distilled;\nWhom he, if he had recognized his sword\nThough but a little later, would have killed;\nSo looked Marphisa when, disclosed to view,\nShe in the stranger knight Rogero knew;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And ran forthwith to clip the cavalier;\nNor could unclasp her arms: with loving show\nCharlemagne, Roland, and Rinaldo, here\nAnd there, fix friendly kisses on his brow.\nNor him Sir Dudon, nor Sir Olivier,\nNor King Sobrino can caress enow:\nNor paladin nor peer, amid the crew,\nWearies of welcoming that warrior true."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Leo, who well can play the spokesman, now\nThat warlike band hath ceased to clip the knight,\nTells before Charles and all that audience, how\nRogero's daring, how Rogero's might,\n— Albeit to his good squadron's scathe and woe —\nWhich at Belgrade he witnessed in that fight,\nSo moved him that they overweighed all harms\nInflicted on him by the warrior's arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So that to her Rogero being brought,\nWho would all havoc of the youth have made,\nHe setting all his family at nought,\nHad out of durance vile the knight conveyed;\nAnd how Rogero, that the rescue wrought\nBy Leo might be worthily repaid,\nDid that high courtesy; which can by none,\nThat ever were or e'er will be, outdone;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And he from point to point continuing, said\nThat which Rogero had for him achieved;\nAnd after, how by sorrow sore bested,\nIn that to leave his cherished wife he grieved,\nHe had resolved to die, and, almost dead,\nWas only by his timely aid relieved;\nAnd this he told so movingly, no eye\nRemained, amid those martial many, dry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So efficaciously he after prayed\nTo the obstinate Duke Aymon, not alone\nThe stubborn sire of Bradamant he swayed,\nAnd to forego his settled purpose won;\nBut that proud lord in person did persuade\nTo beg Rogero's pardon, and his son\nAnd son-in-law to be beseech the knight;\nAnd thus to him his Bradamant was plight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To her, where, of her feeble life in doubt,\nShe in a secret chamber made lament,\nThrough many a messenger, with joyful shout\nAnd mickle haste, the happy tidings went.\nHence the warm blood, that stagnated about\nHer heart, by her first sorrow thither sent,\nEbbed at this notice in so full a tide,\nWell nigh for sudden joy the damsel died."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Of all her vigour is she so foregone,\nShe cannot on her feeble feet rely:\nYet what her force must needs to you be known,\nAnd what the damsel's magnanimity.\nNone doomed to prison, wheel or halter, none\nCondemned some other evil death to die,\nAbout whose brows the sable band is tied,\nRejoices more to hear his pardon cried."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Joys Clermont's, joys Mongrana's noble house,\nThose kindred branches that fresh know to view.\nWith equal grief Count Anselm overflows,\nGan, Falcon, Gini and Ginami's crew:\nYet they meanwhile beneath contented brows\nConceal the dark and envious thoughts they brew.\nAs the fox waits the motions of the hare,\nThey wait their time for vengeance, and forbear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Besides that oftentimes before the rage\nOf Roland and Rinaldo on them fell,\nThough they were calmed by Charles's counsel sage,\nAnd common danger from the infidel,\nThey had new cause for grief in Bertolage\nSlain by their foemen and Sir Pinnabel:\nBut they concealed their hatred, and endured\nThose griefs, as of the matter ill assured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Those envoys of the Bulgars that had made\nFor Charles's court (as hath erewhile been shown),\nHoping to find the knight, whose shield pourtrayed\nThe unicorn, elected to their throne,\nBless the good fortune which their hope repayed,\nSeeing that valiant warrior, and fall down\nBefore his feet, and him in humble speech\nAgain to seek their Bulgary beseech;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Where kept for him in Adrianople are\nThe sceptre and the crown, his royal due:\nBut let him succour to his kingdom bear;\nFor — to their further scathe — advices shew\nConstantine doth a mighty host prepare,\nAnd thitherward in person moves anew;\nAnd they — of their elected king possest —\nHope the Greek empire from his hands to wrest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He accepts the realm, by their entreaties won;\nAnd, to afford them aid against their foes,\nWill went to Bulgary when three months are done;\nSave Fortune otherwise of him dispose.\nWhen this is heard by that Greek emperor's son,\nHe bids Rogero on his faith repose;\nFor since by him the Bulgar's realm is swayed,\nPeace between them and Constantine is made;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Nor needeth he depart in haste, to guide\nHis Bulgar bands against the Grecian foe;\nFor all that he had conquered far and wide,\nHe will persuade his father to forego.\nNone of the virtues, in Rogero spied,\nMoved Bradamant's ambitious mother so,\nOr so to endear her son-in-law availed,\nAs hearing now that son a sovereign hailed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The rich and royal nuptials they prepare\nAs well befits him, by whose care 'tis done,\n'Tis done by Charles; and with such cost and care\nAs if 'twere for a daughter of his own.\nFor such the merits of the damsel are,\nAnd such had all her martial kindred shown,\nCharles would not think he should exceed due measure\nIf spent for her was half his kingdom's treasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He a free court bids cry; whither his way\nSecurely every one that wills may wend;\nAnd offers open lists till the ninth day\nTo whosoever would in arms contend;\nAnd bids build bowers afield, and interlay\nGreen boughs therein, and flowers and foliage blend;\nAnd make those bowers so gay with silk and gold,\nNo fairer place this ample world doth hold."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Guested within fair Paris cannot be\nThe countless foreign bands that thither fare;\nWho, rich and poor, of high and low degree,\nAnd Greeks and Latins and Barbarians are.\nThere is no end of lord and embassy\nThat thither from all ends of earth repair;\nAll lodged conveniently, to their content,\nBeneath pavilion, booth, and bower and tent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The weird Melissa against the coming night\nWith singular and matchless ornament\nHad for that pair the nuptial chamber dight;\nWhereon long time before she had been bent:\nLong time before desirous of the rite\nHad been that dame, presageful of the event;\nPresageful of futurity, she knew\nWhat goodly fruit should from their stems ensue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She had prepared the genial, fruitful bed,\nUnder a broad pavilion; one more rich,\nAdorned, and jocund, never overhead\n(Did this for peace or war its master pitch)\nWas in the world, before or after, spread;\nAnd this from Thracian strand had borne the witch.\nThe costly prize from Constantine she bore,\nWho for disport was tented on that shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She with young Leo's leave, or rather so\nThe Grecian's admiration to obtain,\nAnd a rare token of that art to show,\nWhich on Hell's mighty dragon puts the rein,\nAnd at her pleasure rules that impious foe\nOf Heaven, together with his evil train,\nBade demons the pavilion through mid air\nTo Paris from Constantinople bear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "From Constantine that lay therein, who swayed\nThe Grecian empire's sceptre, at mid-day\nThis with its cordage, shaft whereby 'twas stayed,\nAnd all within and out, she bore away;\nAnd of the costly tent, through air conveyed,\nFor young Rogero made a lodging gay.\nThe bridal ended, this her demon crew\nThither, from whence 'twas brought, conveyed anew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Two thousand tedious years were nigh complete,\nSince this fair work was fashioned by the lore\nOf Trojan maid, warmed with prophetic heat;\nWho, 'mid long labour and 'mid vigil sore,\nWith her own fingers all the storied sheet\nOf the pavilion had embroidered o'er;\nCassandra hight; that maid to Hector brave\n(Her brother he this costly present gave. )"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The curtiest cavalier, the kindliest shoot\nThat ever from her brother's stock should grow\n(Albeit she knew far distant from its root,\nWith many a branch between, should be that bough)\nIn silk and gold upon the gorgeous suit\nOf hangings had she wrought in goodly show.\nMuch prized that gift, while living, Priam's son,\nFor its rare work and her by whom 'twas done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But when by treachery perished Priam's heir,\nAnd Greeks the Trojans scathed in cruel sort,\nWhen her gates opened by false Sinon were,\nAnd direr ill was done than tales report,\nThis plunder fell to Menelaus' share,\nWherewith to Egypt's land he made resort;\nThere left it to King Proteus, Egypt's lord,\nIn ransom for his prisoned wife restored;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "She Helen hight: her Menelaus to free,\nTo Proteus the pavilion gave away;\nWhich, passing through the line of Ptolemy,\nTo Cleopatra fell; from her in fray\nAgrippa's band on the Leucadian sea\nBore off the treasure, amid other prey.\nAugustus and Tiberius heired the loom,\nKept till the time of Constantine in Rome:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That Constantine, whom thou shall ever rue\nFair Italy, while the heavens above are rolled.\nConstantine to Byzantium, when he grew\nWeary of Tyber, bore the tent of old.\nMelissa from his namesake this withdrew,\nIts pole of ivory and its cord of gold,\nAnd all its cloth with beauteous figures fraught;\nFairer Apelles' pencil never wrought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Here the three Graces in gay vesture gowned\nAssisted the delivery of a queen.\nNot in four ages in this earthly round\nWas ever born a boy so fair of mien.\nJove, Venus, Mars, and Mercury renowned\nFor fluent speech, about the child are seen:\nHim have they strewed, and stew with heaven's perfume,\nAmbrosial odours and aetherial bloom."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Hippolytus a little label said,\nInscribed upon the baby's swaddling clothes.\nBy the hand him Fortune leads in age more staid;\nAnd Valour as a guide before him goes.\nAn unknown band in sweeping vest arraid,\nWith long descending locks, the tapestry shows,\nDeputed by Corvinus to desire\nThe tender infant from his princely sire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He reverently parts from Hercules' side,\nFrom her, his lady mother, Eleanor;\nAnd to the Danube wends; where far and wide\nThey meet the boy, and as a god adore.\nThe prudent king of Hungary is descried,\nWho does due honour to his ripened lore,\nIn yet unripe, yea, raw and tender years,\nAnd ranks the stripling above all his peers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "One is there that in his green age and new\nPlaces Strigonia's crozier in his hand.\nHim ever at Corvinus' side we view;\nWhether he doth in court or camp command,\nWhether against the Turk, or German crew\nThe puissant monarch leads his martial band,\nWatchful Hippolytus is at his side,\nAnd gathers virtue from his generous guide."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "LXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "There is it seen, how he his blooming age\nDivides mid arts and wholesome discipline:\nThe secret spirit of the ancient page\nThere Fuscus well instructs him to divine:\n\"This must thou shun, that follow\" — seems the sage\nTo say — \"if thou immortally wouldst shine.\"\nFashioned withal with so much skill and care\nBy her who wrought that work, their gestures were."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XC"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "A cardinal he next is seen, though young\nIn years, at council in the Vatican;\nWhere for deep wisdom graced by eloquent tongue,\nWith wonder him the assembled conclave scan.\n\"What will he be\" — they seem to say among\nThemselves — \"when he is ripened into man?\nOh!  if on him St. Peter's mantle fall,\nWhat a blest aera!  what a happy call!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "That brave youth's liberal pastimes are designed\nIn other place; on Alpine mountain hoar\nHere he affronts the bear of rugged kind;\nAnd there in rushy bottom bays the boar:\nNow on his jennet he outgoes the wind,\nAnd drives some goat or gallant hind before;\nWhich falls o'ertaken on the dusty plain,\nBy his descending faulchion cleft in twain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He is descried, amid a fair array\nOf poets and philosophers elsewhere\nThis pricks for him the wandering planets' way;\nThese earth, these heaven for his instruction square.\nSome chant sad elegies, some verses gay\nLays lyric or heroic; singers there\nHe with rich music hears; nor moves a pace\nBut what in every step is sovereign grace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The first part of the storied walls pourtraied\nThat noble prince's gentle infancy.\nCassandra all beside had overlaid\nWith fears of justice, prudence, modesty,\nValour, and that fifty virtue, which hath made\nWith those fair sisters closest amity;\nI speak of her that gives and that bestows.\nWith all these virtues gilt, the stripling glows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In this part is the princely youth espied\nWith that unhappy duke, the Insubri's head;\nIn peace they sit in council at his side,\nTogether armed, the serpent-banner spread.\nThe youth by one unchanging faith is tied\nTo him for ever, well or ill bested;\nHis followers still in flight before the foe,\nHis guide in peril, his support in woe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Him in another quarter you descry,\nFor his Ferrara and her duke in fear,\nWho by strange proofs doth sift, and certify\nTo his just brother, vouched by tokens clear,\nThe close device of that ill treachery,\nHatched by those kinsmen whom he held most dear;\nHence justly he becomes that title's heir,\nWhich Rome yet free bade righteous Tully bear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Elsewhere in martial panoply he shone,\nHasting to help the church with lifted blade;\nWith scanty and tumultuous levy gone\nAgainst well-ordered host in arms arraid:\nAnd lo!  the coming of that chief alone\nAffords the priestly band such present aid,\nExtinguished are the fires before they spread.\nHe came, he saw, he conquered, may be said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Elsewhere he stands upon his native strand,\nFighting against the mightiest armament,\nThat whensoever against Argive land,\nOr Turkish, from Venetian harbour went;\nScatters and overthrows the hostile band,\nAnd — spoil and prisoners to his brother sent —\nNothing reserves save that unfading bay;\nThe only prize he cannot give away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Upon those figures gazed the courtly crew,\nBut read no meaning in the storied wall:\nBecause there was not any one to shew\nThat these were things hereafter to befall.\nThose fair and quaintly fashioned forms they view\nWith pleasure, and peruse the scrolls withal:\nBut Bradamant, to whom the whole was known,\nBy wise Melissa taught, rejoiced alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "XCIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Though not instructed in that history\nLike gentle Bradamant, the affianced knight\nRemembers how amid his progeny\nAtlantes often praised this Hippolyte.\n— Who faithfully could verse such courtesy,\nAs Charlemagne vouchsafed to every wight?\nWith various games that solemn feast was cheered,\nAnd charged with viands aye the board appeared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "C"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Who is a valiant knight, is here descried;\nFor daily broke a thousand lances lay:\nSingly to combat or in troops they ride;\nOn horseback or afoot, they mix in fray.\nWorthiest of all Rogero is espied,\nWho always conquers, jousting night and day;\nAnd so, in wrestling, dance, and every deed,\nStill from its rivals bears away the meed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "On the last day, when at their festive cheer\nWas seated solemnly the assembled band,\nWhere at Charles' left was placed the wedded peer,\nAnd Bradamant upon his better hand,\nAcross the fields an armed cavalier,\nOf semblance haughty, and of stature grand,\nWas seen to ride towards the royal table;\nHimself and courser wholly clothed in sable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The King of Argier he; that for the scorn\nReceived from her, when on the bridge he fell,\nNever to clothe himself in arms had sworn,\nNor draw the faulchion nor bestride the sell,\nTill he had like an anchoret outworn\nA year and month and day in lowly cell.\nSo to chastise themselves for such like crimes\nWere cavaliers accustomed in those times."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Albeit of Charles and Agramant the Moor\nHad heard the several fortunes while away,\nNot to foreswear himself, he armed no more\nThan if in nought concerned in that affray:\nBut when the year and month were wholly o'er,\nAnd wholly past was the succeeding day,\nWith other courser, harness, sword, and lance,\nThe king betook him to the court of France."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He neither lighted from his horse, nor bowed\nHis head; and, without sign of reverence due,\nHis scorn for Charlemagne by gestures showed,\nAnd the high presence of so fair a crew.\nAstound and full of wonder stood the crowd,\nSuch license in that haughty man to view.\nAll leave their meat, all leave their talk, to hear\nThe purpose of the stranger cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "To Charles and to Rogero opposite,\nWith a loud voice, and in proud accent, \"I\nAm Rodomont of Sarza,\" said the knight,\n\"Who thee, Rogero, to the field defy;\nAnd here, before the sun withdraws his light,\nWill prove on thee thine infidelity;\nAnd that thou, as a traitor to thy lord,\nDeserv'st not any honour at this board."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "\"Albeit thy felony be plain and clear,\nWhich thou, as christened, canst not disavow;\nNathless to make it yet more plain appear,\nThis will I prove upon thee; and, if thou\nCanst find a knight to combat for thee here,\nHim will accept; — if one be not enow —\nWill four, nay six accept; and will maintain\nMy words against them all in listed plain.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero, with the leave of Pepin's son,\nUprose at that appeal, and thus replied:\nThat he — nor he alone — but every one,\nWho thus impeached him as a traitor, lied;\nThat so he by his king had ever done,\nHim none could justly blame; and on his side,\nHe was prepared in listed field to shew\nHe evermore by him had done his due."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He can defend himself; nor need he crave\nAnother warrior's help that course to run;\nAnd 'tis his hope to show him he would have\nEnough, perhaps would have too much, of one.\nThither Orlando and Rinaldo, brave\nOlivier, and his white and sable son,\nThither good Dudon and Marphisa wend;\nWho fain with that fierce paynim will contend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "They tell Rogero that, as newly wed\nThe combat he in person should refuse.\n\"Take ye no further pains,\" the warrior said,\n\"For such would be for me a foul excuse.\"\nThe Tartar's arms were brought, which cut the thread\nOf more delay and of all further truce:\nWith spurs Orlando deck'd the youthful lord,\nKing Charlemagne begirt him with the sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Marphisa and Bradamant in corslet case\nHis breast, and clothe him in his other gear.\nAstolpho led his horse of noble race:\nSir Dudon held his stirrup: far and near\nRinaldo and Namus made the mob give place,\nAssisted by the Marquis Olivier.\nAll from the crowded lists they drive with speed,\nEvermore kept in order for such need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "The pale-faced dames and damsels troop, in guise\nOf pigeons round the lists, a timid show;\nWhen, homeward bound, from fruitful field they rise,\nScared by wide-sweeping winds, which loudly blow,\nMid flash and clap; and when the sable skies\nThreat hail and rain, the harvest's waste and woe:\nA timid troop, they for Rogero fear,\nIll matched they deem with that fierce cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So him deemed all the rabble; and so most\nOf those bold cavalier and barons thought;\nIn that they had not yet the memory lost\nOf what that paynim had in Paris wrought,\nWhen singly fire and sword the warrior tost,\nAnd much of that fair town to ruin brought;\nWhose signs remained, and yet will long remain:\nNor ever greater havoc plagued that reign."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Bradamant's heart above those others' beat:\nNot that she deemed the Saracen in might,\nOr valour which in the heart-core hath its seat,\nWas of more prowess than the youthful knight;\nNor (what oft gives success in martial feat\nThat with the paynim was the better right.\nYet cannot she her some ill misgivings quell.\nBut upon those that love such fear sits well."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Oh!  in her fear for him, how willingly\nShe battle for Rogero would have done!\nIf lifeless on the listed field to lie\nSurer than sure, — in fight with Ulien's son.\nMore than one death would she consent to die,\nIf she withal could suffer more than one,\nRather than she in that unhappy strife\nWould see her cherished consort risk his life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But prayer availed not on the damsel's part\nTo make Rogero leave to her the quest:\nShe then with mournful face and beating heart\nStood by to view that pair to fight addrest.\nFrom right and left the peer and paynim start,\nAnd at each other run with lance in rest.\nThe spears seem ice, as they in shivers fly.\nThe fragments birds, that mount through middle sky."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont's lance which smote in the career\nUpon mid-shield, yet harmed it little; so\nPerfect was famous Hector's iron gear,\nHardened by Vulcan's hand, and safe from blow.\nAs well against the shield his levelled spear\nRogero guides, and that good buckler — though\nWell steeled within and out, with bone between,\nAnd nigh a palm in thickness — pierces clean;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And — but his lance resists not that fierce shock,\nAnd at the first assault its splinters fly,\nAnd bits and fragments of the shivered stock\nSeem fledged with feathers they ascend so high;\nWere his arms hewn from adamantine rock,\nThe spear would pierce the paynim's panoply;\nAnd end that battle: but it breaks withal,\nAnd on their croups both staggering coursers fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With bridle and with spur the martial pair\nRaise their proud horses nimbly from the ground;\nAnd having broke their spears, with faulchions bare\nReturn, to bandy fierce and cruel wound.\nWheeling with wondrous mastery, here and there,\nThe bold and ready coursers in a round,\nThe warriors with their biting swords begin\nTo try where either's armour is most thin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont had not that hard dragon-hide\nWhich heretofore had cased the warrior's breast;\nNor Nimrod's trenchant sword was at his side;\nNor the accustomed helm his temples prest.\nFor on that bridge which spanned the narrow tide,\nA loser to Dordona's lady, vest\nAnd arms suspended from the votive stone\nHe left; as I, meseems, erewhile have shown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Clad was the king in other goodly mail;\nYet not like that first panoply secure:\nBut neither this, nor that, nor harder scale\nCould Balisarda's deadly dint endure;\nAgainst which neither workmanship avail,\nEnchantment, temper, nor prime steel and pure.\nSo here so there Rogero plied his sword,\nHe more than once the paynim's armour bored."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "When Rodomont beholds in that fierce close\nHis widely crimsoned arms, nor can restrain\nThe greater portion of those griding blows\nFrom biting to the quick, through plate and chain,\nHe with more fury, with more rage o'erflows,\nThan in mid winter the tempestrous main\nFlings down his shield, and with both hands outright\nLays at Rogero's helm with all his might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "With that excessive force, wherewith the gin,\nErected in two barges upon Po,\nAnd raised by men and wheels, with deafening din\nDescends upon the sharpened piles below,\nWith all his might he smote the paladin\nWith either hand; was never direr blow:\nHim the charmed helmet helped, or — such its force —\nThe stroke would have divided man and horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As if about to fall, the youthful lord\nTwice nodded, opening legs and arms; anew\nRodomont smote, in that he would afford\nHis foe no time his spirits to renew:\nThen threatened other stroke; but that fine sword\nBore not such hammering, and in shivers flew;\nAnd the bold Saracen, bereft of brand\nWas in the combat left with unarmed hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "But not for this doth Rodomont refrain:\nHe swoops upon the Child, unheeding aught:\nSo sore astounded is Rogero's brain;\nSo wholly overclouded is his thought.\nBut him the paynim well awakes again,\nWhom by the neck he with strong arm has caught,\nAnd gripes and grapples with such mighty force,\nHe falls on earth, pulled headlong from his horse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet leaps from earth as nimbly, moved by spleen\nFar less than shame; for on his gentle bride\nHe turned his eyes, and that fair face serene\nNow troubled the disdainful warrior spied.\nShe in sore doubt her champion's fall had seen;\nAnd well nigh at that sight the lady died.\nRogero, quickly to revenge the affront,\nClutches his sword and faces Rodomont."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "He at Rogero rode, who that rude shock\nShunned warily, retiring from his ground,\nAnd, as he past, the paynim's bridle took\nWith his left had, and turned his courser round;\nWhile with his right he at his rider struck,\nWhom he in belly, flank and breast would wound;\nAnd twice sore anguish felt the monarch, gored\nIn flank and thigh, by good Rogero's sword."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont, grasping still in that close fight\nThe hilt and pommel of his broken blade,\nLayed at Rogero's helmet with such might,\nThat him another stroke might have dismaid:\nBut good Rogero, who should win of right,\nSeizing his arm, the king so rudely swayed,\nBringing his left his better hand to speed,\nThat he pulled down the paynim from his steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Through force or skill, so fell the Moorish lord,\nHe stood his match, I rather ought to say\nFell on his feet; because Rogero's sword\nGave him, 'twas deemed, advantage in the fray.\nRogero stands aloof, with wary ward\nAs fain to keep the paynim king at bay.\nFor the wise champion will not let a wight\nSo talk and bulky close with him in fight;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero flank and thigh dyed red beheld,\nAnd other wounds; and hoped he would have failed\nBy little and by little, as it welled;\nSo that he finally should have prevailed.\nHis hilt and pommel in his fist yet held\nThe paynim, which with all his might he scaled\nAt young Rogero; whom he smote so sore,\nThe stripling never was so stunned before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "In the helmet-cheek and shoulder-bone below\nThe Child was smit, and left so sore astound,\nHe, tripping still and staggering to and fro,\nScarce kept himself from falling to the ground.\nRodomont fain would close upon his foe;\nBut his foot fails him, weakened by the wound,\nWhich pierced his thigh: he overtasked his might;\nAnd on his kneepan fell the paynim knight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero lost no time, and with fierce blows\nSmote him in face and bosom with his brand;\nHammered, and held the Saracen so close,\nTo ground he bore that champion with his hand.\nBut he so stirred himself, again he rose:\nHe gripes Rogero so, fast locked they stand.\nSeconding their huge vigour by address,\nThey circle one another, shake, and press."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "His wounded thigh and gaping flank had sore\nWeakened the vigour of the Moorish king:\nRogero had address; had mickle lore;\nWas greatly practised in the wrestlers' ring:\nHe marked his vantage, nor from strife forbore;\nAnd, where he saw the blood most freely spring,\nAnd where most wounded was the warrior, prest\nThe paynim with his feet, his arms, and breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rodomont filled with spite and rage, his foe\nTakes by the neck and shoulders, and now bends\nTowards him, and now pushes from him; now\nRaises from earth, and on his chest suspends;\nWhirls here and there and grapples; and to throw\nThe stripling sorely in that strife contends.\nCollected in himself, Rogero wrought,\nTo keep his vantage taxing strength and thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "So shifting oft his hold, about the Moor\nHis arms the good and bold Rogero wound;\nAgainst his left flank shoved his breast, and sore\nStrained him with all his strength engirdled round.\nAt once he past his better leg before\nRodomont's knees and pushed, and from the ground\nUplifted high in air the Moorish lord;\nThen hurled him down head foremost on the sward."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXV"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Such was the shock wherewith King Rodomont\nWith battered head and spine the champion smote,\nThat, issuing from his wounds as from a font,\nStreams of red blood the crimsoned herbage float.\nRogero, holding Fortune by the front,\nLest he should rise, with one hand griped his throat,\nWith one a dagger at his eyes addrest;\nAnd with his knees the paynim's belly prest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXVI"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As sometimes where they work the golden vein\nWithin Pannonian or Iberian cave,\nIn unexpected ruin whelm the train\nBy impious avarice there condemned to slave,\nSo with the load they lie opprest, with pain\nA passage can their prisoned spirit have:\nNo less opprest the doughty paynim lay,\nPinned to the ground in that disastrous fray."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Rogero at his vizor doth present\nHis naked poniard's point, with threatening cry,\nThat he will slay him, save he yields, content\nTo let him live, if he for grace apply.\nBut Rodomont, who rather than be shent\nFor the least deed of shame, preferred to die,\nWrithed, struggled, and with all his vigour tried\nTo pull Rogero down, and nought replied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXVIII"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "As mastiff that below the deer-hound lies,\nFixed by the gullet fast, with holding bite,\nSorely bestirs himself and vainly tries,\nWith lips besmeared with foam and eyes alight,\nAnd cannot from beneath the conqueror rise,\nWho foils his foe by force, and not despite;\nSo vainly strives the monarch of Argier\nTo rise from underneath the cavalier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXXXIX"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "Yet Rodomont so twists and strives, he gains\nThe freedom of his better arm anew;\nAnd with the right hand, which his poniard strains,\nFor he had drawn his deadly dagger too,\nWould wound Rogero underneath the reins:\nBut now the wary youth the error knew\nThrough which he might have died, by his delay\nThat impious Saracen forthwith to slay;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h5",
    "innerHtml": "CXL"
  },
  {
    "tag": "pre",
    "innerHtml": "And smiting twice or thrice his horrid front,\nRaising as high as he could raise in air\nHis dagger, buried it in Rodomont;\nAnd freed himself withal from further care.\nLoosed from the more than icy corse, to font\nOf fetid Acheron, and hell's foul repair,\nThe indignant spirit fled, blaspheming loud;\nErewhile on earth so haughty and so proud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  }
]